<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FETAL-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ON A DANGEROUS PATH TO FETAL RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 14:
</P>
<P>
   Congressional opponents of abortion rights have come up with yet
another scheme to advance their agenda. Called the ``Unborn Victims
of Violence Act,'' and scheduled for action today by the House
Judiciary Committee, the measure aims to chip away at women's
reproductive freedom by granting new legal status to ``unborn
children'' _ under the deceptively benign guise of fighting crime.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would add to the federal criminal code a separate new
offense to punish individuals who injure or cause the death of a
``child'' who is ``in utero'' _ regardless of the stage of
gestation or whether the perpetrator knew of the pregnancy. Under
the measure, a prosecutor could choose to pursue a defendant for
harming a fetus independent of whether he prosecuted the defendant
for harming the mother.
</P>
<P>
   No one would quarrel that an attack on a pregnant woman that
results in a miscarriage or prevents normal fetal development is a
tragedy. Extra severe penalties in such cases may be appropriate.
But that can be done by prosecuting a defendant for assaulting the
pregnant woman. The pending bill, however, treats the woman as a
different entity from the fetus _ in essence raising the status of
a fetus to that of a person for law enforcement purposes _ a
longtime goal of the right-to-life movement.
</P>
<P>
   The bill contains exceptions for medical treatment and legal
abortions. That has allowed the bill's sponsors to assert that the
measure has nothing to do with the abortion issue. But that view is
disingenuous. By creating a separate legal status for fetuses, the
bill's supporters are plainly hoping to build a foundation for a
fresh legal assault on the constitutional underpinnings of the
Supreme Court's ruling in Roe vs. Wade. Sending the nation down a
legal path that could undermine the privacy rights of women is not
a reasonable way to protect women or deter crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
