<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSPLANTED PALFFY GLAD TO BE A KING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Ziggy Palffy didn't hesitate Monday when
asked which arena is his favorite to play in.
</P>
<P>
   ``MSG,'' Palffy said, referring to Madison Square Garden, home
of the New York Rangers. ``It's a lot of fun and they always have a
big crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   MSG almost was his home, too, but instead of trading him to the
Rangers this summer, the New York Islanders dealt Palffy to the
Kings. And tonight at the Forum, he will make his first Los
Angeles-area appearance as a King, in an exhibition game against
the Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to come here,'' Palffy said. ``What happened,
happened. I'm very glad to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Kings are happy to have added their most dynamic
offensive threat since the Wayne Gretzky era. Coach Andy Murray
said he's been especially pleased that the slightly built Palffy
(who is 5-foot-10, 183 pounds) has shown a willingness to battle
for the puck, which belies his smallish stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I've really noticed is he's really feisty,'' Murray
said. ``He's not big, but when he battles for the puck, he's very
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Palffy said, ``You have to fight for the puck. If you have the
puck, you can score goals or pass the puck to someone who is
(open). If you don't have the puck, you can't score.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Sixty-minute men:During the exhibition season, many coaches
will play one goalie for the first 30 minutes of a game, the other
goalie for the last 30. Not Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday in Las Vegas, Murray used Stephane Fiset for 60
minutes, and the Kings' No. 1 goalie responded with a 19-save
shutout of the Phoenix Coyotes. Tonight, Murray said he is planning
to use Jamie Storr for the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you're helping your goalies by splitting
games,'' Murray said. ``Part of it is the physical side, giving
them the chance to play 60 minutes. But it's also the mental side,
having them have to focus for the whole game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
