</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUN-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GUN-CONTROL SHOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 14:
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations in Congress over the fate of the modest menu of gun
control measures the Senate approved last spring may finally be
coming to a head. The House-Senate conference committee dealing
with the issue is expected to meet later this week to decide what,
if any, new restrictions on firearms will be included in the
juvenile justice measure being readied for a vote by the full House
and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   A major logjam has developed over extending the Brady law's
background check requirement to all gun-show sales. There is talk
of a possible compromise that would require background checks, but
allow the government well under the three business days that are
the minimum needed to track down criminal and mental health
records. It is unclear whether the GOP might now be amenable to
stronger record-keeping requirements, so that weapons bought at gun
shows and used later in crime are easily traceable.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as a study released last week by the Justice Department
underscored, the only reason to limit the time for background
checks is to make it easier for prohibited purchasers to obtain
weapons _ hardly a worthy goal for the nation's top lawmakers. Most
gun purchasers sail through the process. The study showed that
almost three-quarters of the people buying guns from federally
licensed dealers received a response through the new instant check
system in about 30 seconds, and that 95 percent have their checks
completed within two hours. But other cases take longer, for very
good reasons _ typically because a preliminary check turned up a
felony arrest, a domestic-violence restraining order or some other
potentially disqualifying factor.
</P>
<P>
   After all the violence, and with Americans looking to Congress
for strong steps on gun control that go well beyond the meager
items under consideration, Republicans should accept the need for a
record-keeping system that makes all guns traceable. They should
also be willing to extend to gun shows the Brady law's existing
limit of three business days on background checks. Pressing a
watered-down version destined to put deadly firepower in the hands
of felons, fugitives and other prohibited buyers is not the way to
save lives or win votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
