<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TENNIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: OF TIME AND TENNIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 14:
</P>
<P>
   Before this year's U.S. Open even started, Steffi Graf retired
from professional tennis and Pete Sampras withdrew from the
competition with an injury. Yet despite these prominent no-shows _
and the early, injury-related default of the 1998 champion, Patrick
Rafter _ the last Grand Slam tournament of the 20th century was a
dandy, providing two weeks of compelling tennis, heartening
comeback stories and, in Serena Williams, the first
African-American women's champion since Althea Gibson in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   The results confirmed a generational shift in the women's game.
Jana Novotna, the former Wimbledon champion, will soon follow Graf
into retirement, leaving the top of the women's field to a handful
of supercharged teen-agers. Serena is just 17, Martina Hingis, whom
she defeated in the finals, is 18, and Serena's sister Venus is 19.
All three hit their ground strokes with incredible power, and the
Williams sisters serve as hard as many of the men.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest comeback story belongs to Andre Agassi. Just two
years ago Agassi was ranked 141st in the world. His thrilling
five-set victory in the final against Todd Martin gave him his
second Grand Slam title of the year and at least temporary claim to
the number-one ranking in the world.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult for anyone who remembers the long hair and punk
outfits of 10 years ago to grasp the fact that, at 29, Agassi is
now an elder statesman. But the men's division is dominated by
veterans. Martin is 29, Sampras is 28. The women have had their
revolution. The men are holding the insurgents at bay. In fact, it
is hard to find any insurgents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
