<SLUG> BC-MRI-COLUMBINE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRM ESTABLISHES SCHOLARSHIP FOR COLUMBINE HIGH STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT BOCZKIEWICZ  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLDEN, Colo. _ Midwest Research Institute and its partners at
an energy laboratory have donated $25,000 to endow a scholarship in
memory of victims of the massacre at nearby Columbine High School. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Midwest Research Institute, based in Kansas City, Mo., is the
lead partner of a consortium that operates the National Renewable
Energy Laboratory under contract for the U.S. Department of
Energy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In April, two Columbine students shot and killed 12 of their
classmates and a teacher before taking their own lives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Columbine tragedy struck me and NREL's (1,000) employees
deeply,'' lab director Richard H. Truly said in a news release.
``We all wanted to do something that would capture the spirit of
our community by making a lasting investment in science
education.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The scholarship will be at the Colorado School of Mines. That
school, the lab and Columbine High School are in Jefferson County,
Colo., a Denver suburb. The lab and the mining school have a
collaborative research relationship. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Recipients will be chosen from Columbine and other Jefferson
County schools by the School of Mines Foundation from among
students in disciplines related to the National Renewable Energy
Laboratory's research and development. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The other energy lab partners are Battelle Memorial Institute of
Columbus, Ohio, and Bechtel Corp. of San Francisco. No federal
money was used for the endowment, the energy lab said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
