<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENBERG-HONOR-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Parkinson's association to honor Wall Street executive  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Parkinson Association of Greater Kansas
City will recognize a Wall Street executive and a doctor at its
annual gala next month.
</P>
<P>
   Alan C. Greenberg, chairman of the investment firm Bear Stearns
&AMP; Cos. Inc., will receive the Shirley and Barnett Helzberg
Philanthropic and Humanitarian Award. Greenberg, a Wichita, Kan.,
native, became chief executive officer of Bear Stearns in 1978. He
also became chairman when the investment firm went public in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg has been a major contributor to the Oklahoma Hospital
for Parkinson's research.
</P>
<P>
   After growing up in Oklahoma, Greenberg went to the University
of Missouri and earned his business degree in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Also being honored is William C. Koller, a neurologist prominent
in advancing research and treatment for Parkinson's disease. Koller
will receive the Lee Kirkland Award at the event.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Koller was named to a list of the best doctors in
America.
</P>
<P>
   The event will be Oct. 2 in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The honorary chairmen of the event are Shirley and Barnett
Helzberg. The event chairmen are Arlene Jacobs and Zelda Cohen.
</P>
</TEXT>
