<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MGE-HEDGING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI GAS ENERGY CUSTOMERS LOSE HEDGING PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Missouri Gas Energy customers may be far more
vulnerable this winter to the sort of spikes in natural-gas prices
that caused heating bills to soar three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the last two years, Missouri Gas Energy customers are
headed into a winter not protected by a program to guard against
sky-high prices for natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   After the winter of 1996-97, when natural-gas prices more than
doubled in one month, the utility began to hedge the prices it paid
for gas. For a few dollars a month, customers were cushioned
against such price spikes if they occurred again.
</P>
<P>
   But when the hedging program lapsed earlier this year, Missouri
Gas Energy didn't ask regulators for permission to renew it. Now
the utility is entering the winter without the program and with
prices for natural gas already as much as 50 percent higher than a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   An official with the Missouri Public Service Commission said
regulators could not force Missouri Gas Energy to hedge prices. But
the utility will face extra scrutiny over the decision not to hedge
if customers pay sharply higher prices this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The staff view is that MGE is accountable for the decision,''
said David Sommerer, manager of the Public Service Commission's gas
procurement division.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gas Energy, which has about 471,000 customers, said
Monday that a utility executive was not comfortable discussing the
decision until a proposal was filed with Missouri regulators on
Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the utility probably will submit an incentive
program. Such programs can benefit consumers when Missouri Gas
Energy spends less than it expected to buy gas for its customers.
The utility has used the incentives the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as though we've been operating in a vacuum,'' said
Kevin Crockett, a spokesman for Missouri Gas Energy. Details of the
incentive plan were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The utility is exploring options, including hedging, that it
might include in its request to Missouri regulators, Crockett said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are now questions whether any plan would be too late
to benefit customers this winter. Kevin Kelly, a spokesman for the
Missouri Public Service Commission, said the soonest a decision
could be made on a Missouri Gas Energy proposal would be 30 days
after it was submitted, and that's only if no questions arose. That
would push any approval to Nov. 1 at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Even now is too late to effectively hedge gas prices, in the
view of many observers. Because of the recent increases in prices,
hedging would be far more expensive, or price caps would have to be
set much higher than they could have been a few months ago.
Typically, the programs are more effective when done in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally you want to hedge when prices are lower,'' said Chris
Ellsworth, manager of natural gas for Energy Security Analysis Inc.
in Washington, which conducts research on energy issues.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri regulators in June renewed the hedging program for
Laclede Gas, the gas utility serving St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   After the price spikes of three years ago, utilities were
criticized for not doing enough to protect consumers. One problem
was that any price increases for natural gas could be passed
directly on to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Although utilities could traditionally put gas in storage or
contract to buy some gas at fixed-rate prices to lend stability to
prices, Missouri regulators decided utilities could do more. They
gave the OK to hedging for any gas utilities that wanted to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The hedge works something like an insurance policy. A financial
institution for a premium will guarantee that a utility will pay
only a specified amount for gas. If the price goes above that
amount, the institution pays the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Missouri Gas Energy paid $3 million _ about $7 a
customer _ to hedge its gas costs. Those costs were paid by its
customers. Because gas prices were low last year _ usually below $2
a thousand cubic feet _ the hedges didn't pay off.
</P>
<P>
   So far prices have already edged above $3. On Monday they were
at about $2.80, according to one price index. In January 1997, gas
prices topped $4 a thousand cubic feet. A typical household in the
Kansas City area uses 120,000 cubic feet of natural gas a year.
</P>
<P>
   At Kansas Gas Service, a majority of the gas it expects to sell
this winter has been hedged. This year that means that if gas
prices go above $3.05 a thousand cubic feet, then the utility's
customers will get some relief, said Steve Johnson, a spokesman for
Kansas Gas Service.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the utility asked some customers in focus groups if
the cost of the program _ about $5 a customer _ was worth it. The
results were encouraging, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people said yes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure how much natural gas will end up costing this
winter. The threat of hurricanes and what that could do to some
natural-gas wells was being blamed by traders Monday for some of
the recent increases.
</P>
<P>
   John Zekoll, a deputy director of the New York State Public
Service Commission, said that whatever the reason, this serves as
another wake-up call for utilities to manage their gas costs,
including the use of hedges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't, they will after this winter,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
