u i BC-TIMOR-U.N.-1STLD-WRIT     09-14 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-U.N.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. MOVING AHEAD TO ORGANIZE FORCE FOR EAST TIMOR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout)   (See also TIMOR-RDP, TIMOR-U.S.) 
(sw) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Security Council members worked late Monday
night on a draft resolution to authorize the use of force in East
Timor, and some members assembled troops, ships, advisers and
aircraft in preparation to move quickly into the territory to end
the violence there.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's foreign minister, Ali A. Alatas, told Secretary
General Kofi Annan and the Security Council on Monday that his
government would welcome speedy deployment of a multinational force
but had some questions about the nationalities of its commander and
the troops.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council was refining a draft from Britain that
would mandate troops to control militias that have been terrorizing
the East Timorese and driving them from their land. The draft,
which the council is expected to act on in a day or two, indicates
that the commander would be an Australian, a decision strongly
backed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Although Alatas said Indonesia would place no conditions on the
force, he said it would prefer soldiers from members of the
Association of South East Asian Nations. Some of those nations,
including Thailand, Malaysia, Singapore and the Philippines, have
said they will take part. British Gurkha troops based in Brunei are
also on call.
</P>
<P>
   For many Indonesians, however, Australia is a provocative and
politically explosive choice to lead the troops because it has been
a strong supporter of East Timorese independence leaders in the
past and the two countries had very rocky relations until
relatively recently. Some council members also have qualms about
the choice, a diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   In Darwin, an Australian port 250 miles from East Timor,
preparations for action already have begun, with the Australians
apparently confident they will lead the force.
</P>
<P>
   Australia has appointed a commander, Maj. Gen. Peter Cosgrove, a
Vietnam War veteran, and is assembling ships, helicopters and a
high-speed catamaran capable of carrying more than 500 troops.
France has sent four military officers to advise the Australians,
and 10 American military experts are in Darwin to help draw up
plans.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon spokesman, Rear Adm. Craig R. Quigley, said the
United States is preparing to use cargo planes to transport troops
and equipment, but had not selected ships or soldiers for duty.
</P>
<P>
   The council appears united on the need for a quick deployment to
restore order in East Timor; on Tuesday in Dili, the United Nations
closed its besieged compound there and, with Jakarta's permission,
began evacuating 1,300 refugees hiding there to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   After selecting a commander, the council is unlikely to specify
the number or nationalities of soldiers in the force, leaving those
decisions to the countries contributing troops.
</P>
<P>
   In Jakarta, nationalists are demanding that no Americans, New
Zealanders or Portuguese take part. Portugal was the former
colonial power in East Timor, and Americans, New Zealanders and
other non-Asians are apparently viewed as prejudiced against
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   One diplomat suggested that Indonesia's long years under often
harsh Dutch rule left a legacy of revulsion against European
domination that explains the persistent racial subtext in the
debate about peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Annan told the council on Monday that Indonesian
``sensitivities'' had to be taken into account, diplomats said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We didn't come here to prevent any country from
participating,'' Alatas said, but he hinted broadly that the issue
should be weighed. ``It is up to the countries themselves to
consider whether it is appropriate, whether their presence would or
would not exacerbate the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobs in Indonesia have been attacking Australian diplomatic and
trade missions during the last week, including an attack Monday on
the office of the representative of Western Australia in Surabaya.
Alatas called the demonstrations responses to protests at
Indonesian consulates and its Embassy in Australia, which he said
cannot get basic supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the outside chance that mounting political pressures
will cause Habibie to balk, diplomats here were relieved to hear
Alatas' message on Monday and are more or less optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if I'm optimistic or pessimistic,'' Richard C.
Holbrooke, the U.S. representative to the United Nations, said in
an interview after the council meeting. But he said he saw no real
opposition to quick action, and he marveled at the speed with which
the situation had turned around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty-eight hours ago we were looking at the worst,'' he said.
``Twenty-four hours ago we were trying to parse the meaning of
Habibie. Now we're working on implementation. That's a pretty
impressive record for the Security Council and for Kofi. So far,
even if we got there too slowly, the last 48 hours have been a
major step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's envoy, Antonio Monteiro, said he welcomed Alatas'
assurances that he would not set conditions. ``We are very
encouraged,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Jeremy Greenstock, Britain's representative and one of five
envoys sent to Indonesia last week to urge the government to accept
outside help in East Timor, said Monday on his return that he
thought government officials had underestimated the scale of the
crisis. The week of violence by pro-Indonesian forces was set off
by a vote for independence by the territory's population.
</P>
<P>
   Alatas told reporters on Monday that while he would like more
discussion on the composition of the force, ``what is important is
that Indonesia would like to see this security cooperation, the
sending of a force, as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   He said an international peacekeeping force had been authorized
under a May 5 agreement on the future of East Timor, but only in
the third phase of the process, after the Indonesian Parliament had
ratified the referendum results, probably in November, and the
United Nations took over administration of East Timor until the new
country's first elections. Until the parliamentary ratification,
Indonesian troops were supposed to be responsible for law and
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, however, the situation is different,'' Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up a multinational force with Security Council backing
rather than an full-dress U.N. peacekeeping operation is essential
to the Clinton administration because of congressional restraints
on any American role in the latter type operation and on payments
for such operations. A Security Council force does not require
congressional notification and the bills for it go to the countries
involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 0027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1119 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-JOB-HUNT-3TAKES-KAN &LR;      09-14 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOB-HUNT-3TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN'S PERSISTENT JOB HUNT FINALLY PAYS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In January, ``Z'' became a trailing spouse. His wife's company
promoted her and moved her from one Midwest city to another _
Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had to look for a job in 10 years,'' Z said earlier
this year. ``I've forgotten what it's like.''
</P>
<P>
   Z, sharp, experienced and in his mid-30s, worried, too, about
job-hunting in a city where he knew no one. He didn't necessarily
think, though, that the search would take eight months.
</P>
<P>
   He now has a job that fits his professional goals. And something
else: a job hunter's diary that he agreed to keep and share.
</P>
<P>
   To give readers candid and free-flowing insights into one
applicant's job-hunting odyssey, Z's identity was protected. In the
interest of fairness, none of the companies he named in his diary
are identified. Z's previous employment has been verified.
</P>
<P>
   Z's job hunter's diary is being shared because his experiences
mirror those of many other unemployed midcareer professionals. They
wonder why the statistics say it's a time of ``full employment''
and news stories talk of a ``job hunter's market.'' How can this
be, they wonder, when they are having trouble finding work.
</P>
<P>
   His story shows that help-wanted signs may be plentiful, but
there often are imbalances between the jobs offered and the jobs
sought.
January
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Day, still living in his former city, Z searched
on the Internet. He was concerned about job hunting in a strange
location.
</P>
<P>
   ``My career has been based upon networking in my community, and
I really have not had to look for a position,'' Z wrote. ``They
came looking for me. Welcome to my dose of KC reality!''
</P>
<P>
   Z's resume showed a strong career progression in the financial
services industry. From an assistant branch manager and loan
officer in 1990, he'd moved on and up to be an investment
consultant for a securities corporation, then an assistant vice
president and trust officer at a large bank. A year ago, he
transferred his financial skills to a health-care management
company where he would have liked to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Z accessed the KCJobhunter and Headhunter Web sites for leads.
He posted his resume. He tried two other job posting sites, too,
but found them ``to be very slow and loaded with tech positions''
that didn't fit him.
</P>
<P>
   He also contacted an executive recruiter, and ``after an
in-depth discussion of my skills, he requested my references and
stated that he would call me tomorrow to discuss the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   The recruiter, who works to fill positions for corporate
clients, did call the next day. The day after that, Z was on a
plane to Kansas City, airfare and car rental paid for by the
recruiter. He had interviews with the president and trust
department head of a bank on the Kansas side of the metropolitan
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my interview,'' Z wrote, ``I went for psychological
testing. I sat across from a nice, if not stone-faced person, who
for the next four hours gave me timed tests that would compare my
skills to the best bank sales and management people in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first test, I felt as if I should be working the
window somewhere (May I super size that for you?), and Stoneface
was not giving me any hints on how I was doing. By the end of the
testing I was a mess. My shirt was soaked with sweat and I was
telling him about my childhood ...
</P>
<P>
   ``After an eternity, he came out of his office smiling. He said
I ranked in the upper 10 percent of my peers. Yeah, Baby!''
</P>
<P>
   The recruiter called Z at the hotel that night. The bank wanted
someone who had more local contacts.
</P>
<P>
   But the recruiter said he'd keep Z's resume. He thought another
corporate client might be interested in about a month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Z also found on the Internet and contacted:
</P>
<P>
   - A medical center, which advertised for a business director. Z
received no response, even after sending three letters by an
express mail service.
</P>
<P>
   - A financial services company, which acknowledged receipt of
his e-mail within a day, but offered no immediate follow-up.
</P>
<P>
   - A national bank, which wanted a trust officer. No response.
</P>
<P>
   - A state credit association, which wanted a consultant. No
response.
</P>
<P>
   - A regional bank, which advertised for a portfolio manager. Z
e-mailed, faxed, called its job hot line and met representatives at
two job fairs before getting an interview scheduled for February.
</P>
<P>
   - A telecommunications corporation, for a business manager's
post. No response.
</P>
<P>
   - A health maintenance organization, which wanted a medical
manager. It acknowledged receipt of his resume within a week but
didn't offer an interview.
</P>
<P>
   - Another regional bank, for a portfolio manager. No response.
</P>
<P>
   - A credit union, for vice president of member services. No
response.
</P>
<P>
   - Two local executive job recruiters. One seemed ``terribly
annoyed with my call, but she did put my name into her junk e-mail
file, so I get way too many `do you know someone?' e-mails. The
other one ``was wonderful and took the time to talk, in great
detail, with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``annoyed'' recruiter told Z his salary expectations were
out of line for the Kansas City market. He shared comparable income
and expenses statistics he'd researched on the Wall Street Journal
Web site, but she rejected the comparison.
</P>
<P>
   The ``wonderful'' recruiter said Z's expectations were ``right
in line with the local marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Z also put his name in with a national recruiter specializing in
financial institutions.
- MORE -
</P>
<P>
   in financial institutions.
February
</P>
<P>
   In the first week of February, Z checked into an area hotel. It
would be his home base for a couple of days of house and job
hunting.
</P>
<P>
   He also sent an e-mail to the careers columnist at The Kansas
City Star, asking whether it would be valuable to attend a
Star-sponsored job fair advertised for Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Career Expo ad piqued my interest, but my peers have
stated that Expos are for rookies and a total waste of time for
someone with experience,'' Z wrote.
</P>
<P>
   At the job fair, Z approached. He was well-dressed,
well-groomed, carrying a nice briefcase. His handshake was firm.
His voice confident, brash even _ except for one thing:
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I'm talking to are young,'' he said at the job
fair. ``I feel old. I'm asking them more questions than they're
asking me.''
</P>
<P>
   Z wrote later: ``It's scary. I'm seeing lots of middle-aged,
middle-level management people wandering around, looking out of
place here. I.T. (information technology) rules, and if you're not
I.T. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   All told, he admitted, it was a depressing day.
</P>
<P>
   He tried two other job fairs while in Kansas City. At one, Z had
a pleasant 20-minute conversation with a bank recruiter. She said,
though, that she didn't recruit at his level; her boss did that,
and her boss wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   At the other fair, the hiring department head was there and
seemed to be impressed with Z, but his openings were all more than
an hour commute from where he'd be living.
</P>
<P>
   Z also made a side trip to the medical center where he'd sent an
e-mail. Its advertised financial position sounded perfect for his
skills and experience.
</P>
<P>
   He said a rude receptionist said the employment ad was in error
and that hospital experience was required. He couldn't get past the
receptionist to plead his case.
</P>
<P>
   On the way out of town, Z said he embarrassed his wife by
handing his business card to a bookstore clerk. He had learned in
casual conversation that the clerk's mother was in human resources
at the telecommunications company he'd contacted.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-February, Z had sent 16 resumes to 16 companies. He got
one immediate response _ not from the resumes, but from the mother
of the bookstore clerk.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was in compensation, not HR ... and could not help me
directly, but she would pass along my resume and would welcome my
telephone call,'' Z wrote. ``I called.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still some nice people in the world, and she is one
of them. She told me about the area and where to look for homes and
where not to, as well.''
March
</P>
<P>
   Z flew back to Kansas City for interviews with two regional
banks and with the bank client that the executive recruiter had
said might be looking for someone within the month.
</P>
<P>
   The interview with one bank's department head went well. Z then
was led into a conference room and found five persons seated around
a table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ambushed! The questions started with `tell us about yourself'
and got worse,'' Z wrote. ``The group did not really seem prepared
to ask questions. So I asked them questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Z received a call the next day. The bank wanted a candidate who
had better local contacts. Z was somewhat disappointed; he thought
it could have been a decent fit.
</P>
<P>
   Z's next interview was with the bank referred by the executive
recruiter. He described a long, ``rambling'' interview with two
bank executives. One questioned Z's sales skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stated that I was a great salesman with a great closing
rate, but I also knew when to walk away from a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank executive said he'd never walked away from a deal, and
no sales person on his staff would ever walk away from a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The interview deteriorated. Z felt insulted. He left convinced
he wouldn't get an offer and didn't want to work there anyway. He
took his anger out on the executive recruiter, complaining about
being exposed to such a bad fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I burned a bridge.'' It was his last contact with the
executive recruiter, whom Z otherwise thought was a terrific
professional.
</P>
<P>
   An hourlong interview with an HR official at the other regional
bank was promising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interview questions were obviously well thought out and
put my mind to work,'' Z wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He was told to expect a call the following week.
- MORE -
</P>
<P>
   the following week.
April
</P>
<P>
   Z moved to a Kansas City suburb. His wife was nine months
pregnant, so the bulk of the physical work fell to him. His job
hunt waned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a follow-up call from the bank where I thought the HR
interview went so well. They basically said there's nothing to
offer you right now, but we'll keep you in a decent file. Really, a
decent file.''
</P>
<P>
   Z took time out from moving to read the newspaper religiously.
He paid close attention to lists of professional meetings and
breakfast clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just started showing up at the door and filling out a name
tag. `Hi. I'm new in town. Tell me about your group.' I sat down
next to strangers and started talking.''
</P>
<P>
   He went to sales groups, finance groups, banking groups,
anything that looked like it might provide a job-referral link. At
one breakfast he met a commercial loan officer who promised to pass
along his resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just happened to have some along,'' Z joked.
May
</P>
<P>
   Z took the month off.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife spent days and nights with an extra-fussy new
baby. Thoughts of job-hunting paled in comparison to the desire for
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew job hunting could be ugly, that it could take time. I'd
put away some nuts for the winter,'' Z said. ``My wife had
disability income from the maternity leave. We weren't in financial
trouble, so we could just take time to focus on family.''
</P>
<P>
   May memories blur. Once, unshaven, he took his newborn daughter
to the doctor's office and ran into someone he'd met while
interviewing. The woman, watching him slick down his disheveled
hair with water from a drinking fountain, laughed.
June
</P>
<P>
   Z took more time off _ partly on purpose, partly not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am beginning to get irritated because no one is calling
back. They said they would,'' Z said. ``I couldn't believe the lack
of courtesy, the lack of professionalism. I couldn't believe
businesses operated that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Z also admitted he'd made some poor decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd put my professional future in the hands of others. I'd put
too much stock in the recruiters. I'd never tied my fate to
headhunters before.''
</P>
<P>
   Z's irritation turned on himself. He had stopped doing the
networking that he knew he needed to do.
July
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the saddle. I went to networking breakfasts again. I
started a series of interviews.''
</P>
<P>
   The first interview was rocky. In the cash management department
at a telecommunications company, the interviewer described himself
``as a den mother to a bunch of kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Z didn't like that, and liked it less as the interview
progressed. Repeatedly, the interviewer ``hollered at his assistant
with language that would have gotten my mouth washed out by Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   The next interview was great. At an energy company, Z's
interviewer was ``intelligent, thought-provoking and had a genuine
interest in what I had to say. I could work there in a heartbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Z heard back within two weeks: The spot had gone to someone
promoted internally, but the company was holding on to his resume.
</P>
<P>
   Z's third July interview was with the regional bank holding
company where he'd made promising HR contacts in March. This time
he met with members of the senior management team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well-thought-out questions, and they actually shared their
vision of the future for the organization with me ... the first
company to do so. I could work there.''
</P>
<P>
   Z believes he got the follow-up call because of the resume he
handed the commercial loan officer he met at a breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Z's fourth July interview was with another regional bank. Z was
surprised that the HR interviewer took two personal calls during
the interview. From hearing half the conversation, Z thought one
call was about an oil change and the other was about a tee time.
</P>
<P>
   He continued to talk with the bank but was disturbed to learn
about the possible pay offer: Because of his earlier contact with a
headhunter that had a contract with the bank, his placement would
cost the bank $12,000. To pay the headhunter, the bank essentially
would offer him $12,000 less.
</P>
<P>
   Z's fifth July interview was with a national bank undergoing a
big transition. The interview and pay were great, but Z learned
that crucial stock research and investment decisions were handled
out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to just babysit accounts while someone else
picked every investment for their clients,'' Z wrote. ``I could
work for the people, but not the company.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the month, Z had three bank-related offers and a
promise of continued interest from the energy company.
</P>
<P>
   He took the bank holding company job ``that, in the end, seemed
to be the only one that was right for me _ moneywise, visionwise,
careerwise. It was truly the best fit.''
</P>
<P>
   The job he took paid about $8,000 less than one of his other
offers, but the tradeoffs seemed worth it.
August
</P>
<P>
   Z is working. He likes his job. He even liked part of the hunt.
Looking back, he has two overriding thoughts:
</P>
<P>
   ``Network. I can't believe I'd forgotten that. I'd forgotten to
shake hands. I got lulled into thinking I need headhunter help
because I was new in the city. I forgot to use my own sales
skills.''
</P>
<P>
   And this:
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder how many CEOs actually know what their HR departments
are doing and saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Z said the failure of HR representatives to follow up on
applications or to call back when they said they would paints a
rude and uninviting picture of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   He's also afraid that HR generalists don't have the specific
knowledge or experiences needed to evaluate applicants for skilled
positions in the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I question the screening abilities of many I met.''
</P>
<P>
   Z is careful to add that he excludes his new employer from the
criticism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
