<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1123 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     09-14 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO DECISION GIVES ONE PAUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bob Toledo could have dumped the season off to
Drew Bennett. To pass the torch, that would have been the quaint,
conservative play. After all, the UCLA redshirt junior has more
exposure to the offense, fewer interceptions and a better
completion rate after two games than redshirt freshman Cory Paus.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Bruins' fourth-year head coach checked off on the
easy call and looked way downfield.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday the onus is on Paus, the Bruins' starting
quarterback from here to maturity, to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo picked Paus, on the basis of his promise, to be Cade
McNown's successor and then got down to nit-picking.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the honeymoon. If this is going to be a happy
marriage, Toledo intoned, Paus is going to have to find his wide
receivers. Preferably as soon as Saturday, when the Bruins host
Fresno State at the Rose Bowl in a final tuneup before tackling
their Pacific-10 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to to get the ball down the field to the guys who
are our playmakers,'' Toledo said during his weekly press
conference. ``That's got to be a point of emphasis.''
</P>
<P>
   If the offense hasn't exactly been purring like a Porsche, it's
because neither Paus nor Bennett has shifted Freddie Mitchell or
Brian Poli-Dixon out of first gear. Too, Danny Farmer has been
clunking along on one bad tire.
</P>
<P>
   So far the Rolls-Royce of receiving corps has a total of 17
catches. The Bruins' tight ends and running backs have combined for
20 receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, a marvelous playmaker, has as many completed passes
(one) as he does receptions.
</P>
<P>
   In their hunger to succeed, Paus and Bennett have been settling
for hamburger instead of holding out for prime rib. They've been
choosing the expedient option over the excellent one. It doesn't
take a football connoisseur to understand why. That which is
well-done takes time to perfect. It's no easy thing to remain
patient when opposing linebackers are coming at you as though you
were a T-bone steak.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just a new quarterback the Bruins have thrown on the
barbecue; they have three new offensive linemen, too. Until
everybody gets his directions straight, the veteran receivers are
apt to feel disconnected. They're out there and open, yet out of
reach, like remote islands in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, for one, is far too hale and hyper to live in such
isolation. He has only one reception in two games, and no amount of
trick plays _ in which he seemingly pulls the football out of the
quarterback or running back's ear _ can make him forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it was frustrating,'' Mitchell said. ``It hurts, but
you just have to go with the flow. The first year, I remember I had
jitters too. It's especially hard for Drew and Cory, trying to fill
Cade's shoes. It took Cade until his junior and senior seasons to
get as good as he was. That's why I don't feel it's in my best
interests to say to them, `You need to get me the ball.' They're
trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying is one thing, succeeding something else. During the loss
at Ohio State Mitchell had so much space around him it looked like
he was flying first class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was open,'' he sighed.
</P>
<P>
   But not many balls came close to penetrating his air space.
After the game someone asked Mitchell who he would pick to start at
quarterback. The redshirt sophomore demurred. He was not the best
judge of passers, he explained, given how few passes he has seen.
</P>
<P>
   His words read all wrong in the papers the next morning.
Mitchell was so mortified he has been bending over backward to make
amends. Who would have thought his apologies could be as acrobatic
as one of his signature catches?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mean to sound like I was whining,'' Mitchell said
Monday in an unsolicited soliloquy. ``I don't think I'm a selfish
player. It really kills me that people might be thinking that.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo didn't take offense. In fact, he considered it a grand,
grown-up gesture when Mitchell came knocking on his office door
first thing Monday morning, groveling for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, Freddie's right,'' Toledo said. ``I respect that
he wants the ball. He should get the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo allowed himself a chuckle. ``He just shouldn't be telling
anybody he should.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, selfish is an ill-fitting adjective for Mitchell,
who fractured his right leg last year while returning a kickoff in
the first quarter of the Bruins' second game. If he was looking out
for No. 1, would Mitchell have been so eager to grace special teams
or get back in the lineup to play in UCLA's Rose Bowl loss to
Wisconsin?
</P>
<P>
   We think not.
</P>
<P>
   Forget for a moment what's best for Mitchell _ even if friends
can't seem to; they keep telling him HE ought to be the next UCLA
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The honest truth is it's in the best interest of the Bruins to
get Mitchell, Poli-Dixon and Farmer the football.
</P>
<P>
   With Cory, Toledo obviously feels it's Paus-ible. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1126 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-BLUEJAYS-NY     09-14 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BLUEJAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE JAYS NIP YANKEES, 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Mirror-shaking loud music had not been heard in the
New York Yankees' clubhouse since the departure of David Wells, but
on Monday afternoon, one of the Yankees turned up the stereo to
play ``Let's Go Crazy,'' a song built on the screams of an electric
guitar, the lyrics and beat meant to increase adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   It just so happened that Wells pitched against the Yankees on
Monday night, and assuming he could have heard the tunes, they
inspired him a lot more than the Yankees, who may soon need an
adrenaline injection. Wells held the Yankees to four hits and the
Blue Jays hung on to win, 2-1, the fourth consecutive defeat for
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, coming off its three-game sweep at Yankee Stadium, lost
to Cleveland on Monday night and the Yankees' lead in the American
League East remains at three and a half games, but far more
alarming is the diminishing gap between the Yankees and Oakland,
the team with the fifth-best record in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics (80-64) are five and a half games behind the
Yankees (85-58), and there is a remote danger that the Yankees will
be knocked out of the playoffs altogether _ especially because the
Yankees must play the Blue Jays twice more here before facing the
Indians in a four-game series that begins Thursday in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees Manager Joe Torre remained as calm as usual after Monday
night's loss, deflecting a question about his team's spiraling
fortunes by saying that it would not be right to overlook Wells'
stunning outing; the larger-than-life left-hander, who is even
larger now, walked two, struck out two and dominated the Yankees
with a mixture of fastballs and off-speed pitches. ``Let's not take
any credit away from the Boomer,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees, the patient and calm machine that dismantled
opponents last season with a wrecking-ball impact, are coming
undone in bits and strands. Paul O'Neill and Tino Martinez, who
usually make up two-thirds of the middle of the Yankees' lineup,
were out of the batting order on Monday night because they have not
hit left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   The middle of the order has not generated consistent run
production, so in recent days the swing of the leadoff batter,
Chuck Knoblauch, has got much longer; he is back to hitting fly
balls, a bad habit for someone who thrives on line drives. Chili
Davis, the Yankees' designated hitter, felt compelled to swing at a
3-ball, 0-strike pitch in Sunday's game, even though he was leading
off an inning.
</P>
<P>
   No one is struggling more than Bernie Williams, who went 0 for 4
on Monday night, hitting into a double play in the ninth inning.
Williams has just three extra-base hits in his last 25 games, and
his swing these days is terrible, perhaps a result of his sore left
shoulder. ``There's no question that he's fighting it right now,''
Torre said. ``He feels like he's letting people down.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' feelings are common in the Yankees' clubhouse these
days. Players are sensing that there is more of a load to be
shared, so they try to do more and ultimately wind up contributing
less. During batting practice on Monday, Torre strolled around the
field, chatting with Martinez and others, trading idle laughs.
Torre wants the players to feel confident and make them understand
he has confidence in them. He has not changed the lineup
dramatically; he has not benched anybody or changed his approach or
handling of them.
</P>
<P>
   Such faith is a good thing, David Cone said before the game. But
the Yankees must do a better job of executing, he continued. They
must advance runners, perform better at those crossroads each game
presents, such as first and second and nobody out in the sixth
inning, with the score tied.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees didn't really have a chance to execute offensively
on Monday night. Wells held them to a single hit over the first
seven innings, and while Orlando Hernandez pitched an ``inspiring''
game, to use Torre's word, the Yankees just never hit.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto took a 1-0 lead in the second inning and added a run on
Vernon Wells' first career home run in the sixth. Chad Curtis
singled home Jorge Posada in the top of the eighth, but Wells
closed out the Yankees in the ninth, Davis grounding to third for
the final out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
