<HEADLINE>
MESA MISFIRE CAPS COMEDY OF ERRORS FOR MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ For a series that was truly a comedy of errors,
Mariners manager Lou Piniella had an appropriate punch line after
Monday night's 5-4, 10-inning loss to the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a one-hopper,'' Piniella said of Jeff Conine's decisive
comebacker. ``When he hit it, I thought we were out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were.''
</P>
<P>
   They were, but not the way Piniella or any of the fans at Camden
Yards expected. Closer Jose Mesa gathered the ball, took a moment
to gather himself, then attempted a throw to second to start an
inning-ending double play. But the throw had all the precision of
an alley-oop pass tossed over the backboard, and it landed in
center field as B.J. Surhoff raced home from second with the
winning run.
</P>
<P>
   The error capped a series in which the also-ran Orioles, playing
their best baseball of the season, allowed the Mariners no room for
mistakes. Seattle needed that room, making crucial errors in the
first two games and losing a ball in the sun in the third game even
before Mesa's miscue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give 'em breaks and make mistakes and lose,'' said Piniella,
who missed Sunday's game to attend the funeral of former teammate
Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter. ``I didn't see yesterday's game, but the
three I saw were all carbon copies.''
</P>
<P>
   An off day and three losses meant Mesa (2-6) was fresh Monday.
He worked the eighth inning with the Mariners trailing, 4-2, and
after David Bell's two-run homer in the ninth tied the score, Mesa
stayed in and worked another scoreless inning.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff started the tenth with a single, and Albert Belle nearly
ended the game on a deep fly that Raul Ibanez caught at the wall in
right-center. An intentional walk to Cal Ripken set up a
double-play situation with Conine hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa fielded the grounder cleanly but, throwing from the slope
on the front of the mound, lobbed his toss over the head of second
baseman David Bell. Game over.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tougher play than most people think,'' Bell said.
``For a closer, that's probably the first time he's had to make a
play like that all year. I remember four or five comebackers to
him, and he's gone to the plate on every one because the bases were
loaded. It's not as easy as it looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's throwing 95 (miles per hour) to the plate, and then to
get a ball with his arm speed at that rate, it's tough to slow
yourself down. There's no way to simulate a play like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was a game like so many the Mariners have played this
year, in which they came back on offense but were not rewarded with
a victory. The M's had trailed since the second inning until Bell
connected with one out in the ninth, tying the score 4-4 and giving
former Mariner Mike Timlin his ninth blown save of the year. The
home run was Bell's 19th, extending his career high.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Wilson gave the M's their first run with a single in the
second, and Russ Davis ripped his career-high 21st home run in the
seventh, a solo shot that was one of three hits on the night. The
homer brought the Mariners within a run at 3-2, but Charles Johnson
doubled in a run in the bottom of the inning to give Baltimore a
4-2 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's double drove Gil Meche from the game after 61/3
innings. Meche allowed four runs on five hits, walking four and
striking out one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had good stuff tonight, but, again, I wasn't
throwing my off-speed pitches for strikes,'' the rookie
right-hander said. ``Any major league team, once they realize that,
they're going to sit on your fastball. That's why I wasn't putting
people away _ I had a real good fastball tonight but I couldn't use
it to my advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The times when I really needed to get an out, it seemed like I
walked a guy or lost focus a little bit. With the stuff I had
tonight, there's no reason to walk four guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of Meche's walks scored, and at least one of the Orioles'
could have. Ibanez walked to lead off the Mariner eighth, and a
walk and a single loaded the bases with two outs for pinch-hitter
Tom Lampkin. Facing Scott Kamieniecki, Lampkin took a 3-and-2 pitch
that seemed high and outside. But umpire Bill Welke _ who two
batters earlier had inexplicably called a foul ball on a pitch that
was nowhere near Edgar Martinez's bat _ called the pitch strike
three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the world knows I'm up there swinging the bat,''
Lampkin said. ``It's not like we're tricking anybody by sending me
up there. It was a ball. There's nothing else to say about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's nothing else to say about this lost, long weekend in
Baltimore, except that it's over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy,'' Piniella sighed. ``Let's hope things are better in
Tampa.''
</P>
<P>
   They can't get much worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
