<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLAQB-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S PAUS OVER BENNETT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA's quarterback platoon is dead and the Cory
Paus era has begun. It looks a lot like the start of the Cade
McNown era.
</P>
<P>
   Paus, a redshirt freshman, was named the Bruins' starting
quarterback Monday by coach Bob Toledo after a two-game competition
with junior Drew Bennett. Paus will take 80 percent of the snaps in
practice and he will start the Fresno State game Saturday and every
game beyond _ unless he gets hurt or fails miserably.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly nine months after it began, UCLA's quarterback quandary
has been cleared up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it's best to go with Cory,'' Toledo said. ``If he
makes mistakes, it's not over. I'm not going to have a quick
trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus and Bennett were disappointed with their performances at
Ohio State and awoke Monday figuring the platoon would last another
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we'd have at least another game to square off,''
Bennett said. ``I'm very disappointed and a little embarrassed. It
was mine to lose and I lost it. It's nobody's fault but mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus, from New Lenox, Ill., took the news with mixed emotions.
He and Bennett have become close friends in recent months and they
are roommates on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it hadn't come down to deciding between myself and
Drew,'' Paus said. ``I wanted to do backflips, but I felt bad. He
told me, `Congratulations.' He handled it awesome. I was worried
how he was going to react and he's been great.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo often has compared Paus to a young McNown, who outplayed
several veterans to win the starting job early in his freshman
season.
</P>
<P>
   Like McNown, Paus has natural leadership qualities, a knack for
big plays and plenty to learn. Just as McNown struggled as a
freshman and sophomore, the Bruins expect Paus to make mistakes. He
made a slew of them Saturday, completing just 8 of 20 passes and
throwing an interception. But because he redshirted last season,
Paus is more advanced at this stage than McNown, who played three
months after graduating from high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cory's a lot like Cade, in my opinion,'' Toledo said. ``He's
going to make some mistakes. He just needs to settle down. Also,
eventually he'll give us some leadership and the players respect
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus won the job because he throws better than Bennett. His
spiral is tighter. His passes are crisper, easier to catch and more
accurate. (He had a higher completion percentage in training camp.)
Bennett's passes tend to flutter, sometimes wildly, and his arm
isn't as strong.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's performance against Ohio State was also a factor. The
bizarre first-quarter touchdown to Matt Stanley was a bad pass that
should have been intercepted. He threw an interception and lost a
fumble in the third quarter when UCLA had a chance to reclaim the
lead. He also missed several open receivers, and completing passes
to Freddie Mitchell, Danny Farmer and Brian Poli-Dixon is crucial
to UCLA's aerial attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Drew helped his cause much,'' Toledo said of the
Ohio State game.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches spent several hours on Sunday reviewing game film
and discussing the quarterback situation. Monday morning, Toledo
and offensive coordinator Al Borges agreed on Paus and presented
their plan to the offensive staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unanimous,'' Toledo said. ``Cory throws the ball real
well. He throws it better than Cade did at this stage. He just has
to learn, but he can make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett is one of UCLA's best athletes and asked about moving to
receiver or playing defensive back _ anything to get on the field.
But Toledo wants a well-prepared backup and declined Bennett's
offer, at least for this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little confused right now,'' Bennett said. ``Coach
Toledo told me to stay ready. I'm still one ankle (injury) away
(from playing). But I'm really embarrassed. I didn't even let this
be an option in my head and here it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
