<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-LEAKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEAK FROM STARR'S OFFICE WAS NOT ILLEGAL, COURT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 2nd and 3rd grafs to specify nature of charges against
Starr's office) (ms) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court ruled Monday that there was
nothing illegal in discussions by Kenneth Starr, the independent
counsel, or his aides with reporters about deliberations over
whether to indict President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous three-judge panel reversed a ruling by U.S.
District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson that the independent
counsel's office had leaked secret grand jury information. The
judges told her to rescind her order directing the Justice
Department to investigate Starr's office and his former spokesman
on possible criminal contempt charges over an article that appeared
in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling disclosed that Johnson had, last July, secretly
ordered the department to conduct what would have been the first
criminal investigation of the Office of the Independent Counsel and
its former spokesman, Charles Bakaly, who was forced to resign last
March over his role in the Times article.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals panel said Johnson erred by adopting an overly broad
definition of the kind of grand jury information that prosecutors
may not discuss with reporters. The judges said that any leaks by
Starr's office or Bakaly that may have contributed to the article
were not illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The Times reported in January that Starr had concluded that he
had the constitutional authority to seek a grand jury indictment of
Clinton before he leaves office in January 2001. The article said
Starr had not made a final decision to do so but his conclusion
that he had the authority to indict a sitting president followed an
intense discussion in the office of the independent counsel. The
article's assertions were attributed to ``several associates of Mr.
Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling provides what appears to be a fresh and
expansive definition of what prosecutors may discuss publicly and
with reporters. It came in response to an appeal of Johnson's order
that was brought not only by Starr and Bakaly but also by the
Justice Department itself. The department was concerned that its
hundreds of federal prosecutors could be liable for their regular
discussions with reporters about criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a law that prohibits prosecutors from publicly
discussing ``matters occurring before the grand jury,'' a phrase
contained in Rule 6(e) of the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeals court ruled Monday that ``internal deliberations
of prosecutors that do not directly reveal grand jury proceedings
are not Rule 6(e) material.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his lawyer, David Kendall, had argued before Johnson
that Starr and his associates were engaging in a purposeful and
illegal campaign to leak damaging information about the president
to aid their investigation. Starr had responded that any
discussions he and his aides held with reporters did not disclose
6(e) material and were therefore permissible.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said Monday he strongly disagreed with the appeals court
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the decision of the panel is inconsistent with
the precedents of the Court of Appeals,'' he said. Kendall said
that he will seek to have Monday's ruling reconsidered by the full
appeals court, a procedure the court employs in a small number of
extraordinary cases.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, a setback for the president, was a victory for Starr
and a more limited one for Bakaly. According to the opinion, Bakaly
filed a declaration that in his discussions with the reporter from
the Times, Don Van Natta Jr., he ``refused to confirm or comment on
what Judge Starr or the Office of Independent Counsel was thinking
or doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Starr ordered an investigation by the FBI of any
leaks even if they were not illegal. After that investigation,
Starr's office withdrew its earlier assertion that it was not the
source of any information in the Times article. Bakaly resigned
shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Editors at the Times have said that they do not and will not
discuss the sources for the article.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was unclear how the appeals court ruling would affect an
earlier decision by Johnson in which she held that 24 other news
articles and broadcasts appeared on their face to show that
prosecutors in Starr's office had leaked grand jury material.
</P>
<P>
   Those 24 news accounts include articles from the Times as well
as Newsweek, Brill's Content, The Washington Post and The Boston
Globe and broadcasts from ABC, NBC, CBS, CNN and the Fox network.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, in a ruling last Oct. 30 said the articles demonstrated
``serious and repetitive'' violations of the law against disclosing
grand jury secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office has appealed Johnson's ruling on the other
articles. The case has not yet been decided on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Times article concerning Clinton's possible
indictment by Starr's office, three appeals court judges, Patricia
M. Wald, Laurence Silberman and Karen LeCraft Henderson, ruled in
their unsigned opinion that the appeals court had never meant that
a ``veil of secrecy be drawn over all matters occurring in the
world that happens to be investigated by a grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said prosecutors' statements about their
investigations are only a problem when ``they directly reveal grand
jury matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1144 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-PHILLIES-ASTROS-H     09-14 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PHILLIES-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
A decade passed between the Astros' last two 20-game winners. Now,
they have two in three days.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Hampton joined the 20-win fraternity Monday night as the
Astros won their club-record 11th straight 13-2 over the
Philadelphia Phillies before a crowd of 44,399 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros remained three games ahead of second-place Cincinnati
in the National League Central. The Reds have won 10 of their last
11 to remain close to the division lead _ but have failed to gain
any ground since Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise that could boast of only five 20-game winners in
37 previous seasons has added two to the club since Saturday.
Hampton (20-3) followed teammate Jose Lima (20-7), who earned his
20th win Saturday against Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   They are the only NL pitchers to reach 20 wins this season. And
like so many of his previous 19 wins, Hampton's conquest Monday was
predictable.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched. He hit. The Astros won.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hampton has had a fabulous year and has a chance to make it
even better,'' manager Larry Dierker said. ``He did it in his own
style, getting the double play when he got in trouble, helped with
his bat and running the bases.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton held the Phillies to six hits and two runs and struck
out six over seven innings to extend his personal winning streak to
11 games, longest in the majors this season, and chipped in an RBI
single in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The last time teammates won 20 in the same season was in 1993,
when Atlanta's Greg Maddux (20-10) and Tom Glavine (22-6) did it,
as did San Francisco's John Burkett (22-7) and Bill Swift (21-8).
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who tipped his hat to a standing ovation following the
game and blew kisses to wife, Kautia, and oldest child, Gage, said
he never puts any preseason expectations on himself for victories.
Instead, he aims at reaching 200 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never try to set too many goals,'' Hampton said. ``I always
want to pitch at least 200 innings, because by doing that you're
pitching late in the game and giving the team a chance to win. This
has been my most consistent year, and that's what you shoot for _
consistency. So far I've been able to do that, and I want it to
continue for another two months.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies custom-delivered the Astros' latest victory with 11
walks, three hit batters and two errors, which resulted in eight
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are too good to get that much help,'' said Phillies
manager Terry Francona, whose club has dropped 10 straight games
and 17 of 18.
</P>
<P>
   Tied 1-1, the Astros took the lead for good with two runs in the
third. Bill Spiers led off with a double, and Jeff Bagwell was hit
by a pitch by Phillies starter Joe Grahe (0-3). Carl Everett drove
in a run when Ron Gant misplayed a ball near the left-field warning
track for an error, and Ken Caminiti followed with a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored at least one run in every inning except the
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took advantage of the Phillies' wildness,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio's major-league-leading 54th double in the fourth
inning drove in a run, and Hampton added a run-scoring single in
the fifth. For the season, Hampton is hitting .288 with nine RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past eight days, the Astros have outscored the Phillies
39-16 in five games. Hampton has been the beneficiary of 23 of
those runs.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing a first-inning run, Hampton was in virtual
control. When it seemed the Phillies might make a move in the early
innings, Hampton relied on his defense to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton induced three double-play grounders, including one in
the seventh after the Phillies opened with two singles.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have lost only four of Hampton's 30 starts this
season. ``His last five or six starts, he has been untouchable,''
catcher Tony Eusebio said.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton passed around cups of champagne to teammates after the
game and plans to send the game ball to his father, Mike Sr., in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very special, actually remarkable, how the whole team
has stepped it up, from Shane (Reynolds) to the bullpen,'' Hampton
said. ``Everybody has been consistent at times when we need it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 0130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
