<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANNER-ORDER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. CITY COUNCIL MAY LEAVE DODGERS, LAKERS BLOWING IN THE WIND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles city officials said on Monday they had
made a mistake in letting the ABC network hang street-pole banners
for its fall TV season.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Los Angeles City Council is scheduled to consider
limiting street banners to only those publicizing community,
charitable or nonprofit events. The policy would ban banners for
the Dodgers, Lakers and any other for-profit business.
</P>
<P>
   That means no more banners every spring urging people to ``think
Dodger blue.'' Gone would be those for the MTA's bus service or the
Northridge Fashion Center farmers' market.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We advertise a wholesome family product, and the fact we were
able to feature our players means we could entice people to come to
the games,'' said Dodgers Vice President Tommy Hawkins. ``That
creates jobs, entertainment taxes, parking taxes and other revenue
for the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey Char, director of marketing for the Northridge Fashion
Center was also upset about the possible policy change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't understand this,'' Char said. ``Right now, we just
advertise on the perimeter of our shopping center. We think most
people don't mind the banners. In fact, it's become an accepted
form of mass communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``By allowing them, it would give the city a guaranteed stream
of revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with ABC did not return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The city waives permit fees for charitable and nonprofit
organizations and the banners have not generated enough money to
cover the costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate that it costs us about $1.6 million a year,'' said
Jim Washington, chief inspector of the city's street use inspection
division. The money covers putting up the banners and taking them
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're asking for is a clear city policy on what's allowed
and what isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the use of street poles for the colorful
banners developed this summer when the City Council allowed ABC to
hang its yellow and brown banners on about 1,000 poles. ABC paid
$46,000 to have the banners up for two months.
</P>
<P>
   While the City Council develops the new policy, it ordered a
two-month moratorium on all banners, which ends this week.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, no commercial advertising will be allowed
with the exception of corporate sponsors for charitable or
community events. And then, the corporate logos can only take up a
small portion of the banner.
</P>
<P>
   The city is also looking at changing how banners are approved.
</P>
<P>
   The current system provides for banner companies _ the two main
ones are AAA Banners in West Los Angeles and Gold's Graphics in
suburban Pacoima _ to take out the permits and put up the banners.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Furst, vice president of AAA Banners, said it shouldn't
have a major effect on his business but acknowledged he would like
to see a two-tiered approach where private firms pay a higher
permit fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proponents of any way we can get people's names out to
the public,'' Furst said. ``This is a big business. If this goes
through, you could see a 25 percent drop in the number of
banners.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan has not taken a formal position on the
matter but would be interested in seeing if the program could
generate revenue for the city without resulting in visual blight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people like the banners as long as they are done
tastefully,'' an aide said. ``The mayor doesn't see any reason to
stop those.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
