<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1147 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BOS &LR;      09-14 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
BUMP IN THS ROAD FOR SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-RED SOX-INDIANS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Road warriors for the past 10 days, the Red Sox
finally showed signs of hitting the wall Monday night in Jacobs
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, they still had enough in reserve to offer a belated
challenge to the Cleveland Indians, who were served Tomokazu Ohka
by the fifth inning after driving Tim Wakefield from the mound but
were forced to hang on for an 11-7 win before a full house of
43,264.
</P>
<P>
   If the season ended today, these teams would be meeting in the
first round of the playoffs in a reprise of last year's October
matchup. That Division Series was won by the Indians, just as they
ended Boston's postseason flirtation in 1995, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, honored before the game for winning their fifth
straight AL Central Division title, are assured again of a place at
the postseason table, while the Sox could still have their chairs
pulled out from under them by the unsinkable Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   The A's won their fifth straight game Monday night, completing a
four-game sweep of the Tampa Bay Devil Rays and drawing within two
games of the Sox in the wild-card race with 18 games left. When the
Sox began this 13-day, 12-game excursion, they were two games ahead
of the A's. That hasn't changed, even though they've won 7 of 10,
with back-to-back outings by the Martinez brothers yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez will be starting Tuesday night in place of Pat
Rapp, who left the team for a third time to be with his wife,
Rebecca, who is going through a difficult pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oakland's playing some good baseball, too,'' rookie Trot Nixon
said. ``Sure, we're not too far behind the Yankees, but we're just
worried about going out and playing good baseball. We want to get
to the postseason, and we don't care how we do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon drove in three runs with his 12th home run, a single, and
an infield out but berated himself afterward for not making a
better throw to the plate during the Indians' five-run fourth
inning, when David Justice's single came just before Richie Sexson
unloaded a three-run home run off Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I make a better throw to the plate on (Kenny) Lofton, I
might have gotten Wakefield out of that jam, the way Tek (catcher
Jason Varitek) blocks the plate,'' Nixon said. ``Sexson comes up
and hits that home run. A better throw, and he doesn't get that
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eastern Division-leading Yankees, meanwhile, fell to the
Toronto Blue Jays, but any designs the Sox have of overtaking the
Bombers went as flat as Wakefield's knuckleball Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield was clobbered for eight runs on nine hits and four
walks, including home runs by Lofton and Sexson, in his worst
outing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched like (fermented compost), basically,'' Wakefield
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox rebounded with a four-run sixth, touched off by Nixon's
home run, but the Indians put it away with a three-spot in the
eighth, when ancient Harold Baines hit his first home run as an
Indian, a three-run blast into the tree nursery beyond the
center-field fence. Baines, a trading-deadline acquisition from
Baltimore, connected off Bryce Florie, who has been used almost as
seldom as Ohka.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton, who had missed the last eight games and played just
twice since July 27 because of a strained hamstring and an
irritated sciatic nerve, celebrated his return by leading off the
first with a home run, just as Chuck Knoblauch of the Yankees had
given Bret Saberhagen a similar initiation a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But while Saberhagen closed down the Yankees thereafter, the
Indians were just getting started. Of the 24 batters who faced
Wakefield in the first four innings, 13 reached base.
</P>
<P>
   An infield hit and two walks loaded the bases after Lofton's
homer in the first, and a second run scored when Sexson hit into a
double play.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton, who had three hits, doubled home Jim Thome in the second
when the Indians left the bases loaded. Cleveland teed off again in
the fourth. That man Lofton singled home another run, as did
Justice, before Sexson unloaded his 428-foot home run.
</P>
<P>
   That was No. 30 for Sexson, two more than Thome but nine behind
Manny Ramirez, the major leagues' RBI leader (144) who sat out the
game with a sore right knee. Ramirez was hit by a pitch Saturday by
Jim Parque of the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a very explosive ball club, as we all know,'' manager
Jimy Williams said. ``When you have people like Thome hitting
seventh and Baines hitting sixth, that tells you what kind of
lineup they have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox scored in the second off Charles Nagy (of the Fairfield,
Conn., Nagys) when Varitek doubled and Nixon singled him home.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's home run in the sixth was followed by a double by Jose
Offerman and a two-out single by Nomar Garciaparra. Troy O'Leary
doubled home Offerman, and Mike Stanley followed with a two-run
single to make it 8-5.
</P>
<P>
   That was all for Nagy, but it was also all for the Sox' offense
until the ninth, when they scored twice against Paul Shuey. There
were two runners on base when pinch hitter Brian Daubach lined out
to end it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they're a good team,'' said Nixon, staring solemnly from
behind the glasses he wears when he's not playing. ``But they've
still got to put their jerseys on, hit the ball, and play defense.
We think we can play with anybody. We know we can play with
anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
