u s BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT &LR;      09-14 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DEFEAT ROCKIES, 6-5 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The New York Mets and Bobby Valentine were stepping
gingerly toward uncharted territory _ their 89th victory of the
season, a number the Mets had not reached since 1990 and one
Valentine had never achieved as a manager.
</P>
<P>
   They would not make the move easily, but they eventually
defeated the Colorado Rockies, 6-5, to earn that victory and slip
in just one game behind Atlanta in the National League East.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets grasped leads, then let them slip away, moved in front
with the help of a rare pinch-hit by Bobby Bonilla, only to stumble
again _ much the way the pennant race itself is going.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the lapses were a result of fatigue _ the Mets had not
arrived from Los Angeles until 4 a.m. _ but one runner, Roger
Cedeno, was picked off first with the score tied to start the
eighth inning and another, Melvin Mora, was thrown out trying to
score from second with none out in the ninth by right fielder Larry
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have won several games recently despite themselves,
doing just enough to win. And they did it again on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   With Darryl Hamilton at bat and the score tied, 5-5, in the
ninth with Mike Piazza on third, Colorado's Dave Veres threw a 1-2
pitch way inside, almost hitting Hamilton. The ball instead rolled
to the backstop. Piazza, who had advanced to third with sharp
base-running when Walker threw Mora out at the plate, came charging
home. He slid headfirst _ a move Valentine said he would prefer
never to see _ to score the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets had that milestone 89th victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good until we win 90,'' Valentine said. ``We have a
couple of long weeks left and I think we'll win more than 89. We
said we'll be better than we were last year. If you go by the
record, I guess it means we're better, but right now, that doesn't
mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Valentine, in summing up this game, also gave an identity
to the season. ``This is one of those games when we didn't
particularly take advantage of all our situations,'' he said. ``But
you make your own breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Turk Wendell was lucky he did not break something when he
punched his mitt so hard in frustration after taking a loss six
days ago that he bruised a knuckle. He was not available again
until Monday night, when heaving the rosin bag to the mound as if
he was at home, Wendell returned to stanch the Rockies' offense
after Pat Mahomes briefly faltered in the seventh and eighth
innings. Wendell got the victory and even made a cameo appearance
on the bases _ he did not reach base last season _ walking and
advancing to second when Rickey Henderson walked.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine left him in to bat and run the bases _ Wendell shunned
a jacket, fearing that if he was involved in a collision at the
plate, the catcher could get caught on the fabric _ not wanting to
waste Wendell's superb pitching effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was subconsciously conscious,'' Wendell said. ``I've pitched
some of my best games when I'm sick. When you're sick, your power
level goes down so you don't try to do too much. When you haven't
pitched in a while, you have too good stuff and you try to do too
much and you get tattooed. Tonight, I was just concerned with how
my finger felt.''
</P>
<P>
   It felt just fine, no doubt better than Rick Reed was feeling.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' coaching staff will meet Thursday to discuss what to
do with their six-man rotation. Reed, making his second start since
coming off the disabled list, once would have been a lock for a
spot. But Valentine sounded none too enthusiastic about Reed's
performance on Monday night in which he allowed four runs on nine
hits in six innings. Valentine thought Reed had left too many
pitches up in the strike zone _ including one that Walker, who went
4 for 5, lofted for a home run that would barely have reached the
warning track at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Reed was all right,'' Valentine said. ``He got too many
up tonight to say he's absolutely in the saddle.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed saw it differently. Saying he was annoyed by non-baseball
matters on his mind, Reed bit on his words to keep from saying
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to know what I think,'' he said. ``I think I threw
the ball well, maybe a couple were up but that's it. I'm not even
going to start. I'll wind up saying something I don't want to say
and I'll regret it. I thought I had pretty good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had plenty of other good things to carry them through.
Bonilla, who had swung at the first pitch in all three of his
recent pinch-hitting appearances, this time waited for the second.
He had not had a hit since June 23 and had spent considerable time
on the disabled list. But in the seventh, batting for Reed, he
belted a line drive that just missed clearing the right-field wall
and wound up with a double. Henderson followed with a home run that
gave the Mets a 5-4 lead. Bonilla, who had put off some of the Mets
with his feud with Valentine, was greeted exuberantly in the dugout
when he was replaced by a pinch-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good to get the knock and what was better was
everybody was there to greet me,'' Bonilla said. ``I've got guys
pulling for me and that made me feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of good feeling to spare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
