<HEADER>
A1150 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BBA-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-14 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
ROTATION? IT WILL MAKE YOUR SPIN
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-RYAN COLUMN-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ When you're sitting in the visiting dugout at Jacobs
Field, it's pretty hard to miss the scoreboard staring at you from
the left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   So no one had to tell Jimy Williams that the irritating Oakland
A's had picked up a game on both the Red Sox and Yankees Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I use glasses to read, I guess I'm what you call
farsighted,'' reported the skipper. ``I can see the scoreboard. I
can even see that guy banging the drum.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly for the Red Sox, those were happy bangs on John Adams's
famed kettle drum. The Indians had beaten the Red Sox, 11-7. The
Blue Jays, behind the spurned David Wells, had beaten the Yankees.
And the A's, now winners of five straight, had once again beaten
the Devil Rays. It almost felt as if that glorious weekend in the
Bronx had never happened. Forget the Yankees. The A's are just two
games behind the Red Sox, and they aren't going anywhere. They also
have a schedule that includes 10 games with Kansas City, Minnesota,
and Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The harsh reality for the Red Sox is that they are the only
major league baseball team contending for anything that has
absolutely no semblance of an orderly pitching rotation.
Spahn/Sain/Pray For Rain? How about Pedro and Pray for Helpo?
</P>
<P>
   Guess who goes to the mound Tuesday night? Big brother, that's
who. Pat Rapp was supposed to pitch, but he's back in Louisiana
with his pregnant wife, and so Williams has little choice but to
entrust the game to the patched-up Ramon Martinez, who will be
coming off 11 days' rest, every one of which he probably needs.
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't be wallowing in self-pity if he were placed in
Jimy's shoes? The answer, of course, is Jimy Williams himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go with the people we've got,'' he said after watching Tim
Wakefield get blasted for nine hits and eight earned runs in four
dreadful innings. ``No excuses. We're a team. Ramon will pitch
(tonight), and I feel all right. He can go pitch good.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry, but you've got to laugh. The Mets' Bobby Valentine
has an orderly six-man rotation in place. Jimy's current rotation
really does consist of Pedro Martinez and Whoever Can Give Him Five
Innings. Rotation? He doesn't have Kent Mercker, who spent some
time Monday in the ever-present MRI tube, trying to find out what
ails his ribs, side, or whatever. He doesn't have Rapp, whose
bedridden wife is undergoing a very difficult pregnancy. He does
have Mark Portugal, who hasn't won since Aug. 4 and who, frankly,
scares you.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he's got me, once every 25 days,'' reminded Bret
Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   And he has Tim Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we all know how valuable Wakefield has been to the staff,
not just this year but for the past five seasons. He can start. He
can relieve. No one else in baseball has started 15 games while
moonlighting in the bullpen long enough to rack up 14 saves.
</P>
<P>
   However . . .
</P>
<P>
   There are nights _ and Monday night was most certainly one of
them _ when a manager has to wish that Wakefield had decided on
some other way to make a living. When he is bad, he is really,
really, really bad. He got ahead of Kenny Lofton, 0 and 2, but
Lofton hit the next pitch over the right-field fence for his fifth
leadoff home run of the season. He walked two men as the Indians
pushed across another first-inning run. He walked the leadoff man
in the second, and he wound up scoring. He looked sharp in the
third, which was only a tease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought when he got through the third he was gonna settle
in,'' observed Williams. ``Unfortunately, it just didn't work out.
It was just one of them nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Well put. Singles by Lofton, Roberto Alomar, and David Justice
produced another run in the fourth. That brought up Richie Sexson,
the best-kept 107-ribbie secret in baseball. The elongated left
fielder sent a non-knuckling knuckler to downtown Ashtabula.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can have a bad night, but when Wakefield is like this,
you almost have to go back to the microfilm to verify that the
months of May, June, July, and August really happened. It's been
said before, but it always bears repeating: What Tim Wakefield did
in going 14-1 to start his Red Sox career was the greatest
sustained spurt of knuckleball pitching that has ever been seen in
the history of the sport. It made no sense then, and it makes no
sense now. It is never, ever going to happen again, not by
Wakefield, and not by any other knuckleballer, alive or unborn.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield has since settled back into classic knuckleballer's
groove. He will always have his moments, but he will never inspire
true confidence. But he'll be out there as a Red Sox starter this
season, again and again and again. Williams has no choice.
</P>
<P>
   It's nights like this when you must step back and marvel at what
the Red Sox have done this season. Mike Hargrove did not have the
services of 144-RBI man Manny Ramirez, and yet he was able to write
out a lineup card on which the very dangerous Jim Thome was batting
seventh. For a DH he was able to call upon the wily Harold Baines,
the 40-year-old wonder who would put the game out of reach with his
25th home run, a monster three-run shot to straightaway center off
Bryce Florie in the eighth. When the playoffs do arrive, Thome will
be playing first base, which means that either Sexson, Justice (20
homers, 85 RBI), or Baines (25 homers, 95 RBIs) will not be in the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   That's without even talking about the pitching. Hargrove has his
own worries (Jaret Wright, Doc Gooden, etc.) but he's still going
to have Bartolo Colon, Charles Nagy, and Dave Burba. Williams _ if
he can even get there _ will have Pedro Martinez and, um, er, ah .
. .
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 0141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
