<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSE ANSWERS THE CALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chan Ho Park lasted six innings, allowed four runs
and left with a one-run lead that was later increased to three runs
by the time reliever Alan Mills took the mound.
</P>
<P>
   In the simplest analysis, it's considered a success. Park, one
of the many poster boys for what hasn't transpired this season for
the Dodgers, was en route to his fourth straight win.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers beat Montreal 12-4 in the first of a three-game
series Monday at Dodger Stadium. The 12 runs is the most the
Dodgers have scored since Aug. 8. But apart from the win, much of
what's been wrong with Park for much of the season was on display.
</P>
<P>
   He got behind too often. He was hurt by errors but also appeared
to lose concentration at times. The Dodgers gave him a lead and he
gave it back.
</P>
<P>
   Park, hurt by the long ball since April, allowed two more
homers, the 28th and 29th of the season. He trails Ismael Valdes by
one for most allowed on the Dodgers and is tied for sixth in the
National League in homers allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Light-hitting Geoff Blum, who had a .220 average, gave the Expos
a 1-0 lead with a homer in the third. The second homer was more
disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   It came from Vladimir Guerrero, who was down two strikes with
two outs and one on in the fifth. But rather than wasting a pitch
in the dirt, which Park did in striking out Guerrero with the bases
loaded in the third, he challenged Guerrero. A few seconds later
Guerrero was circling the bases with his 36th homer and the Expos
had a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Park's final pitching line was typical. He pitched six innings,
gave up eight hits and four runs. He threw 94 pitches and his ERA
rose .01 to 5.69.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, as in two of Park's previous four starts, the
Dodgers scored a bundle of runs to make him a winner. Though he
entered the game with three wins and a no-decision in his last four
starts, Park had a 5.09 ERA. That included a six-inning, six-walk
9-7 win against Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also beat Chicago 8-6 during Park's run back to
.500. He improved to 10-10.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the offense that gave Park success, rather than his
pitching against a mediocre offensive club.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers right-fielder Raul Mondesi had four hits (two doubles)
and stole a pair of bases. Even in a tumultuous season in which his
average has lingered in the .240s for most of the summer, Mondesi
is one homer and one stolen base from the second 30-30 season in
Dodgers' history. Mondesi also owns the first record; he hit 30
homers and stole 32 bases in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Todd Hundley hit his 23rd homer of the season, a line
drive into the right-field seats. That number is the most homers by
a Dodgers lefty since Darryl Strawberry hit 28 in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's RBI-single in the fifth scored Gary Sheffield, who hit
a two-run homer in the third to tie the game 4-4. Mondesi then
stole second and Todd Hollandsworth scored without a throw on the
back end of a double steal to give the Dodgers a 5-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Expos starter Dan Smith (4-9) left after yielding five runs on
seven hits in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley increased the Dodgers' lead to 6-4 when he led off the
sixth with a homer against reliever Miguel Batista.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Alex Cora, whom Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
wants to look at so he knows where the slick-fielding infielder
fits into the picture, then atoned for a pair of errors with a
two-run double down the right field line as the Dodgers went ahead
8-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
