<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1152 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN     09-14 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, OSUNA MEETS TOMMY JOHN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Antonio Osuna wanted to pitch through his elbow
injury so he would have leverage when it came to his contract after
the season. The strategy backfired and now the injured Los Angeles
Dodgers right-hander doesn't have an elbow to lean on.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna finally gave into the pain Monday and agreed to have
``Tommy John'' surgery on his right elbow Thursday at Centinela
Hospital Medical Center. The 1{-hour procedure to replace a
partially torn ligament in his elbow will be done by Dodgers
physician Dr. Frank Jobe.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers officials insist Osuna will go through with the surgery
this time. He postponed the same surgery the first week of August.
Earlier in the season Osuna put off surgery to remove bone spurs
from his elbow, only to have it done a month later.
</P>
<P>
   Jobe said the recovery time of the ``Tommy John'' surgery is one
year, which puts Osuna's 2000 season in serious jeopardy. It also
leaves Osuna without a contract after the season. The Dodgers hold
a pair of $1.5 million options for the next two seasons, but they
won't be exercised.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers must rehab Osuna, but they are under no financial
obligation to him next season. If they chose, they can sign him to
a contract, or Osuna can sign with another team. But finding
another team to take a pitcher for the last few weeks of the season
is nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we'll deal with at the end of the season,''
Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said of Osuna's contract
status.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna ticked off Dodgers management with his refusal to have the
surgery in early August. If he had done it then, he could have been
available for two months next season and raised his value. Now his
nine-year affiliation with the club could be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna decided to the have the surgery after experiencing pain
following a rehab appearance Sunday for Class-A San Bernardino.
He's 0-0 with a 7.71 ERA in five games with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started hurting again,'' Jobe said. ``This is sort of what
we expected, but we had to do a rehab and try to let him pitch as
hard as he could. He came in and said, `I guess the time has come.'
It's about a year before you can pitch 95 mph in a game.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Running on Hundley: Even though catcher Todd Hundley has
thrown better since being shut down for nine games in mid-June, the
results are only marginally better.
</P>
<P>
   Before spending time with bullpen coach Rick Dempsey to relearn
the mechanics of throwing, Hundley threw out seven of 60 would-be
base stealers (11.7 percent). Since the aggressive work schedule,
Hundley has thrown out nine of 58 (15.5 percent) of the runners
trying to steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we need to improve the delivery time of the pitchers,''
Dempsey said. ``When it's 1.5, 1.6 (seconds) to the plate, it's
impossible for him to throw guys out. Todd's got to work in the
offseason and get his legs in shape. There's got to be a huge
improvement going into next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers catchers have thrown out 18.2 percent of runners trying
to steal, well under the NL average of 29.4 percent. Hundley has
thrown out 13.6 percent, Paul LoDuca has caught 22.7 percent and
Angel Pena nailed 27.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   __ FYI: Dodgers right-hander Mike Judd is most likely done for
the season because of tendinitis in his pitching shoulder. He was
3-1 with a 5.46 ERA in seven games but is expected to pitch in the
Arizona Fall League. . . . Dodgers minor-league field coordinator
Rick Sofield (Jupiter, Fla.) and Expos bench coach Luis Pujols
(Boynton Beach, Fla.) both went to their homes to help their
families evacuate because of Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
