</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-DOLPHINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS BEAT BRONCOS, 38-21 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ This was supposed to be a night for the Denver
quarterbacks. John Elway would have his No. 7 retired during
halftime. Brian Griese, Elway's successor, would enter the National
Football League on a high note.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Marino was supposed to be old news. Wait, check that. Old
Man Marino and his bum legs were the best combination on the Mile
High field Monday night. Elway is gone, Griese is promising, but
Marino may still be king.
</P>
<P>
   Marino showed his highly accurate passing arm is still capable
of devastating a defense and thanks to some nifty running by Karim
Abdul-Jabbar and good special teams play, the Dolphins showed they
might be the team to beat in the American Football Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Miami beat Denver, 38-21, before a crowd of 75,623, ending the
defending Super Bowl champions' regular season 24-game home winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we lacked intensity,'' Denver linebacker Bill
Romanowski said. ``We just didn't execute. I thought Brian played
well, and basically we all let him down.''
</P>
<P>
   After Denver took a 7-0 lead, Miami scored the next 24 points.
The Dolphins took a 24-7 third-quarter lead after a J.J. Johnson
1-yard touchdown run. Denver scored on Ed McCaffrey's 11-yard
touchdown catch and was threatening to score again when it faced a
fourth down and one at the Miami 40-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Miami's defense came up with one of many big
plays. As Griese dropped back, linebacker Zach Thomas blitzed and
it happened so fast that Griese seemed to be caught by surprise.
Thomas crushed Griese and the Dolphins took possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried a lot of different things to confuse me,'' said
Griese. ``I'd like to think I held up pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami followed that sack with a four-yard touchdown pass from
Marino to wide receiver O.J. McDuffie that concluded a 55-yard,
eight-play drive and gave Miami a 31-14 lead with under 10 minutes
left. Again, Marino threw nothing but precision passes on the
drive.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins added their final score with 3 minutes 56 seconds
remaining after Griese was sacked by Thomas, and the defensive end
Jason Taylor picked up the loose ball and ran in from from the
four-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Denver tried to come back and Elway _ oops _ he retired. There
would be no Elway-led Broncos comeback this time.
</P>
<P>
   Marino, playing in his 17th season, passed for 215 yards and two
touchdowns. Griese was 24 of 40 for 270 yards and three touchdown
passes, all to McCaffrey.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to tell which was a bigger deal in Denver: the end
of one career or the virtual beginning of another. Elway had his
number retired in the team's hall of fame in what was a grand
halftime ceremony. The Broncos know how to throw a party.
</P>
<P>
   But what matters in the National Football League is the here and
now. Elway was officially gone and the Griese era was beginning. It
was the Bubby Brister era until Coach Mike Shanahan yanked the
carpet from under him in preseason and inserted Griese in the
starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Going back to when he played at the University of Michigan,
Griese has always been cocky, and if he was nervous the last week
it did not show.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan showed confidence in his young quarterback by having
him throw on six of the first eight plays. Griese had a few drops
by receivers on his opening series, but each throw was a bullet as
he went 4 for 6.
</P>
<P>
   Griese could not have tossed a better ball than the one he threw
to McCaffrey, whose speed continues to be underestimated by
defensive backs. McCaffrey split safeties Brock Marion and Shawn
Wooden while running a seam route down the middle of the field. The
ball landed perfectly on his chest, and the Broncos were up 7-0 on
the 61-yard pass play less than four minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Griese also showed he could take a pounding. Many times after
just getting a pass off, he was smashed by a Miami player. Griese
would simply get up, dust himself off and walk back to the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   As smooth as Griese was, he still had problems moving the ball
consistently. That could indicate a big difference between Miami's
defense last season and this year. Last year, Miami was often
unable to get a crucial stop when needed. That was not the case
against Denver tonight as the Dolphins continually made big plays
on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Marino set up both of Miami's first-half touchdowns. The first
was a 28-yard pass to McDuffie that set up a 1-yard run by
Abdul-Jabbar. The second was for 40 yards to speedster Tony Martin.
That play led to a 12-yard touchdown catch by the rookie fullback
Rob Konrad.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams also helped Miami. Denver's Jason Elam had a
44-yard field-goal attempt blocked by Lorenzo Bromell, and Terrell
Buckley returned it 43 yards. That set up the Dolphins' first
touchdown. Later, Miami's Greg Jeffries deflected Tom Rouen's punt
with 1:37 left, leading to Olindo Mare's 37-yard field goal and a
17-7 lead at halftime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
