<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1155 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-BRONCOS-     09-14 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-BRONCOS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DENVER _ On a night when John Elway's famous No. 7 was retired in
an elaborate halftime ceremony, the Denver Broncos lost the Mile
High magic he concocted for 16 years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elway's close friend, Miami quarterback Dan Marino, guided the
Dolphins to a 38-21 victory over the Broncos, the two-time
defending Super Bowl champions, before a crowd of 75,623 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody let everybody down, and we didn't match the
intensity of last year,'' Broncos coach Mike Shanahan said. ``We
had a chance to take control early, but they didn't let us. Miami
was excellent in all three phases.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Dolphins ruin Elway's induction into the
Broncos' Ring of Fame, they spoiled second-year quarterback Brian
Griese's starting debut.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be inaccurate to blame this defeat on Griese, whose
father, Pro Football Hall of Fame quarterback Bob Griese, was
watching from a luxury suite. Brian Griese completed 24 of 40
passes for 270 yards and three touchdowns, all to Ed McCaffrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed that we lost, and I'm disappointed in the way
we played,'' Griese said. ``There are some things I could have done
to help us, but I know that I left it all on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miami's got a great defense. They blitzed from all over the
field, but everyone in the building knew they were going to do
that. We had a game plan for it, but we just didn't have enough for
them tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan knew it wasn't Griese's fault the Broncos dropped too
many passes, committed too many penalties and got dominated up
front on both sides of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody had played like Brian, there's no question, we
would have won the game,'' Shanahan said. ``They threw everything
at him, but he kept his poise and showed a lot of composure. I
thought he ran our offense very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins dominated the Broncos' offensive line and kept
running back Terrell Davis under control for the most part. Mainly,
they kept Davis out of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a great scheme,'' said Davis, who was limited to 61
yards on 19 carries. ``They were aggressive up front. Their
linebackers filled the gaps, and the secondary forced the run.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins were so good, nothing short of tear gas and mounted
police could have kept them from the decisive victory that ended
Denver's string of 24 consecutive regular-season victories at Mile
High Stadium. Miami thus protected the NFL record of 27 home wins
in a row set by the 1971-74 Dolphins at the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's victory also avenged the Dolphins' loss to Denver in
last year's AFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos looked like anything but a defending Super Bowl
champion. The Dolphins spotted them a 7-0 lead, then took advantage
of breakdowns by the Denver special teams to lead 17-7 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   On the first series of the game, the Broncos dropped two passes.
But on a third-down blitz, McCaffrey got behind safeties Brock
Marion and Shawn Wooden to catch a 67-yard touchdown pass from
Griese. Jason Elam added the extra point for a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second quarter, the Broncos were driving from their
20 to the Dolphins' 24. After Davis rushed for nine yards on second
down, they faced third-and-one. Davis was stopped for a two-yard
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Denver was within field-goal range and about to boost the
lead to 10 points, but Dolphins defensive tackle Lorenzo Bromell
blocked Elam's 44-yard field-goal attempt, and cornerback Terrell
Buckley returned it 43 yards to the Denver 36.
</P>
<P>
   Four plays later, Dolphins halfback Karim Abdul-Jabbar scored on
a two-yard run, and Olindo Mare kicked the extra point. Rather than
Denver having a 10-0 lead, the score was 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   The next time the Dolphins got the ball, they covered 80 yards
in seven plays. Marino was perfect on four passes for 64 yards,
including a 40-yarder to Tony Martin to the Denver 25.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Marino threw a short swing pass to rookie
fullback Rob Konrad, who had a wide-open path to the end zone
because of a mix-up in the Broncos' coverage. Konrad's 12-yard
touchdown gave the Dolphins a 14-7 lead with 3:02 left in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins weren't done, either. Thanks to another bad play by
the Broncos' special teams, Miami got excellent field position.
</P>
<P>
   After McCaffrey let a long pass slip through his hands, Tom
Rouen's punt was deflected and ended up going 15 yards, giving the
Dolphins the ball at the Denver 43.
</P>
<P>
   With one second left before halftime, Miami had to settle for
Mare's 37-yard field goal and a 17-7 advantage at the break.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, the Dolphins picked up where they left
off. On their first possession, they shoved the ball down the
Broncos' throats. The key play was Marino's 25-yard pass to Martin.
Another 15 yards were tacked on when cornerback Ray Crockett hit
Martin out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   After Abdul-Jabbar's 11-yard run to the one-yard line, it took
Miami three plays to score. Rookie running back James Johnson
scored the touchdown to give the Dolphins a 24-7 lead with 10:02
left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up 24 unanswered points, the Broncos finally
responded. They drove 54 yards in 13 plays and scored their second
touchdown. On third-and-eight from the Miami 11, Griese thought
about running but pulled up and threw to McCaffrey in the end zone.
Elam's extra point left Denver behind 24-14 with 3:42 left in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos seemed to be getting some momentum when they had the
ball at midfield. But third-string tight end Byron Chamberlain
dropped a long pass down the right side. Then, on fourth-and-10,
Griese was sacked by blitzing linebacker Zach Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins capitalized when Marino threw a four-yard touchdown
pass to O.J. McDuffie, giving Miami a 31-14 lead with 9:31 left.
Marino finished 15-of-23 through the air for 215 yards and two
touchdowns, with no interceptions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
