<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1158 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-14 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MIKE Hampton was the starter, so you knew there would be a pitching
clinic at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   What you didn't know was that while Hampton did all the pitching
Monday night, Phillies pitchers were apparently more intent on
sending Astros sluggers to a clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Stick and move, Astros. Stick and move.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were having some trouble throwing strikes,'' Astros
manager Larry Dierker said of Philly's pitchers. ``They couldn't
find the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   They did, however, find lots of flesh and bone.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in this season of Astrodome nostalgia and 35 years of
memories, you'd probably have to go back to Muhammad Ali-Ernie
Terrell to find another day when the old place saw anyone have to
stand there and take such a pummeling.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell got smacked in the biceps by Phillies starter Joe
Grahe, who came to Philadelphia this season by way of Scranton,
which also seemed to be how his errant pitches arrived at home
plate. By way of Scranton.
</P>
<P>
   Grahe walked the first two batters he faced, then another in the
second inning, then gave up a couple of runs and hit Bagwell in the
third. By the end of the third, Grahe already had thrown 71 pitches
and was pulled because of a blister.
</P>
<P>
   We can only assume the blister was on his hand.
</P>
<P>
   But Grahe's adventures were only the beginning of a miserable
night for Phillies pitchers. Altogether, five Phillies scattered
shrapnel in the general direction of the plate through eight
innings, sending Astros batters scurrying for cover and making this
13-2 hammering look easy.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio was hit by a pitch in the seventh. Bagwell was hit
again, this time in the belt, also in the seventh. And there were
so many other near misses on the way to 11 walks by Philadelphia
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   One fastball sizzled under Tony Eusebio's chin. Another sent
Ricky Gutierrez sprawling. Another spun Carl Everett around.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much a batter's box the Astros were diving into
Monday night as much as it was a bunker.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter if 11 walks and three hit batsmen said it all
about why the Phillies lost this game, it also said something about
why Hampton might win the Cy Young Award.
</P>
<P>
   Phillies pitchers looked awful. Hampton made it look easy.
</P>
<P>
   Phillies pitchers couldn't work their way out of trouble if you
gave them the keys to the cell. Hampton handcuffed Philadelphia's
bats all night when things were tight, three times forcing
inning-ending double plays.
</P>
<P>
   Phillies pitchers showed just how difficult it is to pitch in
the big leagues, where batters crowd the plate and umpires shrink
the strike zone even more. Hampton showed just how refined and
polished an ace he has become.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won this game in his own style,'' Dierker said of Hampton,
``getting double plays, helping himself with the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton won this one by bearing down with runners in scoring
position, mixing speeds, nipping at the corners and keeping the
ball down.
</P>
<P>
   He said the most important thing was simply trying to keep the
Astros' franchise-record win streak alive. He called 20 wins
``special'' but said his spring goal was to pitch 200 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you (pitch 200 innings), it means you're keeping your team
in games, staying in the game,'' Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   He drove to the Dome quietly and went through the opponent's
lineup in his head, as always. He put on his serious face, his eyes
burning holes in the catcher's mitt. He made the ball move, slide
and break in all the right ways.
</P>
<P>
   And then he celebrated quietly, as always. He smiled, stood in
front of the Astros' dugout and doffed his cap to the crowd only
after teammates encouraged him to do so. Later, he gathered
pitchers and catchers together in the Astros' weight room and
conducted a champagne toast out of Styrofoam cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll celebrate a little more at the end of the year,'' Hampton
said. ``That's when it will be real special.''
</P>
<P>
   At 20-3, it's already special for Hampton. A Cy Young Award is a
legitimate possibility, but he's thinking bigger than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll trade the Cy Young for the World Series MVP,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the difference between Hampton and most other pitchers.
It was as clear as Monday night's pitching performances: Hampton
looks like he'll make a difference in the postseason. The Phillies
look like they can't wait for the offseason to start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
