<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1159 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     09-14 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ It's over. We won. We won! No, check that. We probably
won.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday afternoon, the race for that 32nd NFL franchise
was, for all practical purposes, down to a single horse, the one
ridden by Houstonian Bob McNair. The three nags from the West Coast
left the league's swank inner sanctum on Park Avenue bound for the
nearest glue factory. There wasn't a single Mr. Ed among them,
either, including Ed Roski. All of the Los Angeles factions fled
for their waiting limos without comment.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what could they say? Since March, when the NFL
conditionally chose LA over Houston for the final new branch office
in our lifetime, none of the groups has made an iota of progress
toward proving it can give the league what it wants _ a viable
venture housed in a palatial, revenue-spewing stadium paid for
mostly by public funds.
</P>
<P>
   Not Roski, the real estate mogul who was pushing for a revamped
Coliseum. Not Michael Ovitz, the Disney defector who proposed
setting up shop on an old dump site in Carson, no relation to
Johnny. And not Marvin Davis, the billionaire financier who has
land next to Hollywood Park in Inglewood but lacks a fire in his
belly for returning pro ball to LA.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who suspect Davis, represented in the building
Monday by his son, Gregg, is less a real candidate than a
dredged-up last-ditch hope for the NFL to salvage its Los Angeles
plans. He has the cash and the clout to do a deal, even at this
late date and with virtually no help from the city of Los Angeles
or the state of California, but it appears unlikely to happen.
Which leaves McNair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me,'' he said, ``I don't object to a one-horse race.''
</P>
<P>
   The analogy is somewhat ill-timed, alas. McNair's real
thoroughbreds, the four-legged variety, had a rough afternoon in
the Garden State Handicap at Belmont Park on Sunday. So if you
believe in bad omens Just because McNair stands somewhere between
being the runaway leader in the clubhouse and the only player on
the course doesn't mean the NFL is dedicated to doing a deal with
him that works for him. ``Remember,'' he said, ``they don't have to
expand.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one teams does not an even number make, causing obvious
scheduling problems. San Diego had a bye Sunday before it had
played a game, something that hadn't happened in the NFL since the
time of the Decatur Staleys.
</P>
<P>
   But financially, expansion means an extra mouth to feed from the
TV revenues, and the 31 rich guys who are already chowing down at
the trough didn't get there by giving stuff away.
</P>
<P>
   It has already been established that McNair will have to pay
through the nose for the privilege of replacing Bud Adams in
Houston. The figures bandied about during what amounted to the
first official, exploratory negotiations were said by one
participant to be ``staggering.''
</P>
<P>
   Staggering? Yeah, as in somewhere well north of the paltry $466
million Cleveland had to cough up to rejoin the party. And look
what the Browns' Al Lerner got for his bucks. He got a 43-0 licking
courtesy of the Steelers on Sunday night, that's what.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the NFL, Al.
</P>
<P>
   McNair admitted he watched the game. And he's still interested
in pursuing this? Amazingly, it didn't dim his enthusiasm in the
least. ``The town went crazy,'' McNair said. ``That was fun to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who really know McNair believe he will stay the course as
long as the NFL treats him fairly. Or, in his words, if ``they
negotiate in a businesslike manner and don't just start pulling
numbers out of the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Numbers like $1 billion. Al Davis and a couple of his usurious
cronies actually think that should be the asking price. But then
Davis, who continues to believe he's a genius, lost touch with
reality years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Only McNair can be sure where he'll draw the line. He doesn't
have to do anything here, either, no matter how badly he may want
to. It's clear he won't be easily deterred, and if he has to take
on a full complement of 24 minor partners _ the league's limit _ to
ease his personal burden, he will. He claims folks are lined up to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   But he won't be taken for a chump.
</P>
<P>
   McNair hopes the details can be hammered out by the Oct. 5-6
meetings in Atlanta and that his bid will go to a vote of the NFL's
full membership there. Chances are, however, the November confab in
Chicago is the best-case scenario for a resolution, and it may drag
into the March 2000 meetings, although commissioner Paul Tagliabue
is said to be tiring of the expansion question and wants it
resolved yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Since McNair intends to be up and running by the 2002 season,
comfortably ensconced in his new retractable-roof stadium, he's
anxious for a reply, but only one tethered to reality. Otherwise,
he'll take his horse and go home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
