<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1161 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     09-14 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THIS is the way they would have us remember them: Emmitt Smith
slashing through holes, Michael Irvin pulling in balls from out of
the crowds inside the end zone, Troy Aikman confidently leading the
orchestra as if he were a Leonard Bernstein in shoulder pads and a
helmet.
</P>
<P>
   For a sun-splashed afternoon on another dramatic opening day of
the regular season in the NFL, we were all strapped into a time
machine and transported back to the days when the Cowboys' offense
was the hottest ride this side of Marty McFly's souped-up DeLorean.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 frantic minutes at the end of regulation and in one cool
bolt of inspiration and execution on third-and-two in overtime, you
could close your eyes and see piles of Dallas touchdowns and a
41-35 win over the hated Redskins and a road of promise that leads
all the way to Atlanta and the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But when you open those eyes, what stares back at you in the
face is the harsh reality of a defensive effort on the outskirts of
the nation's capital that was as clueless as the Justice
Department. Which in the aftermath of a gripping comeback makes any
fantasy of long-range success, at this point, just that.
</P>
<P>
   Buried in the glow of the three-touchdown fourth-quarter rally
was the ugly fact that the Cowboys were still pushed around to the
tune of 504 yards of total offense by a Washington team that has
not made the playoffs in the past six seasons and shows no
indication of being able to find its way with a map and a
flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins may have a new owner in computer-geek boy wonder
Daniel Snyder and a new name on their suburban stadium, but they
are still the very same team under former genius Norv Turner that
couldn't escape from a closet if you pointed at the doorknob.
</P>
<P>
   This is supposed to be a younger, more active, somewhat improved
Cowboys defense from a year ago, yet it was bullied by Stephen
Davis for 109 yards and picked apart by quarterback Brad Johnson
for 382 yards on 20-for-33 passing.
</P>
<P>
   That means the toughest decision facing upcoming opponents is
this: Should we run or throw on the Cowboys?
</P>
<P>
   The response from the chorus, of course, is that the Cowboys
were playing without regular starting cornerbacks Deion Sanders and
Kevin Smith and without their best defensive lineman in Leon Lett.
</P>
<P>
   However, that is not a situation that would appear to be
changing any time soon. Sanders was not at all up to going through
a full workout last week, and nobody knows whether the pain from
offseason surgery on a severe case of turf toe will allow him to be
anything close to his All-Pro best when he does make it back.
Smith's status is up in the air as well. Which means Cowboys fans
could be treated to a good deal more of Kevin Mathis and Charlie
Williams looking as helpless as a pair of turtles turned on their
backs in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And the word circulating around the NFL concerning Lett, who
again violated the league's substance-abuse policy, is that
commissioner Paul Tagliabue plans to keep him on the sidelines for
roughly eight games. Which means Alonzo Spellman, Chad Hennings and
the rest of the defensive front had better find a way to close the
holes and stop the run in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Cowboys start to make too much out of this so-called
``character'' win in Week 1 of the long march, they have to
remember that the Redskins did just about everything except carry
them across the street at busy intersections to make the win
possible. Even before the Dan Turk-to-Matt Turk bad-snap-and-bobble
on the would-be winning field goal at the end of regulation, the
Redskins coughed up two fumbles inside the Dallas 10-yard line,
aborting drives that could have made the score look like one of
those old Nebraska-vs.-East Somebody State whuppings.
</P>
<P>
   Even on the Cowboys' 90-yard drive for the touchdown that tied
it at 35, they were helped along by the blundering Redskins, who
committed four penalties, three for jumping offside.
</P>
<P>
   What it all means is that if the Redskins were anybody but the
Redskins _ or maybe the expansionist Cleveland Browns _ then the
door to the triumphant comeback would have been slammed shut long
before the Cowboys ever got to stick a foot in it.
</P>
<P>
   If Norv's gang had taken care of business, the buzz surrounding
the Cowboys as they head into Week 2 against Atlanta would be less
about the supernatural fourth quarter and more about the miracle
it's going to take to prop up the defense.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe it still should.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
