<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1182 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-LA-HOME-MARKET-LADN     09-14 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-HOME-MARKET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FERNANDO VALLEY'S HOUSE, CONDO SALES HOT AS LAST YEAR'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The San Fernando Valley's real estate market
dodged summer's dog days during August as home sales kept pace with
last year's decade-best level and prices continued climbing, a
trade group said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Escrow closed last month on 1,487 houses and condominium homes,
only nine fewer than in August 1998, said a report from the
Southland Regional Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   ``While sales counts are flat, they are flat at high levels,''
said John Karevoll, an analyst at Acxiom/Dataquick, a market
research firm, who noted that a strong local economy continues to
help drive sales.
</P>
<P>
   As is typical, single-family houses accounted for most of the
Valley's action during August with sales of 1,131, a decline of 76
or 6.3 percent, on an annual basis. The median price of $212,000
was 8.7 percent higher than in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the smaller condominium market turned in an especially
robust performance as buyers looked for bargains.
</P>
<P>
   During August, sales of condos spiked up 23.2 percent to 356
units on an annual basis. And the median price climbed $5,500 to
$122,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first-time buyers' chief market,'' Beth Summer,
president of the Realtors group, said of the condominium market.
</P>
<P>
   Rising prices, slightly higher interest rates and a tight
inventory of single-family homes on the market is helping to fuel
condominium sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take all the forces coming together today, and that translates
into renewed emphasis on condominiums by first-time buyers,'' said
Jim Link, executive vice president of the Realtors group.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers are also feeling pressure from a tight inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, there were 5,972 properties listed for sale
throughout the Valley, only 6 percent more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the number of pending escrows _ sales that
will close this month or next _ jumped 20 percent on an annual
basis. They also increased 1percent on a monthly basis, indicating
that a drop-off on sales is not likely for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Karevoll said that while interest rates have been
bouncing around a bit this summer the jumps have not been enough to
cool off the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither sales counts nor prices are going up so fast that
there is danger on the horizon,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
