<HEADLINE>
SANDPIPER TO PROVIDE AOL WITH AUDIO, VIDEO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON Z. COHEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. _ Sandpiper Networks is expected to
announce Tuesday that it has signed an agreement with America
Online to be the conduit for delivering audio and video broadcasts
to the service's 18 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the result of a relationship begun earlier this
year, when America Online was the largest investor in a $21.5
million round of venture funding for Sandpiper, based in Thousand
Oaks northwest of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Yara, Sandpiper's vice president of marketing, said the
agreement is the latest in a series of deals in which Sandpiper
becomes the means for distributing content to large Internet
service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Sandpiper also has alliances with Inktomi, RealNetworks and Sun
Microsystems, Yara said.
</P>
<P>
   Sandpiper provides Internet sites with a network of servers that
duplicate content on multiple servers in order to speed access to
information, Yara said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real key to getting true quality performance is to avoid
all of the net congestion that occurs,'' Yara said. ``To bring true
broadcast quality, you need to serve the content as close to the
edge of the media network as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandpiper's Footprint service delivers streaming audio and video
to online customers. It allows for the live broadcasts of concerts
and other events, Yara said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're effectively building the broadcast networks of the
Internet,'' Yara said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements with various content providers has created
explosive growth for the Thousand Oaks-based company, he said. It
has gone from 30 employees a year ago to about 90 now, with plans
to grow to 100 by the end of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
