A1186 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BOX-BIGCATWILLIAMS-OB     09-14 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BIGCATWILLIAMS-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Big Cat' Williams dies after car accident &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RICHARD DEAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HOUSTON _ Cleveland ``Big Cat'' Williams, who fought world
heavyweight champion Muhammad Ali at the Astrodome in 1966 at the
pinnacle of his boxing career, has died from injuries sufferred in
an auto-pedestrian accident Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 66, who battled a kidney problem and diabetes for
years, died Friday afternoon at Ben Taub Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was crossing the 7300 block of Fannin from east to west
at 6:35 a.m. Sept. 3 when he was struck by a 1989 silver Nissan
Maxima, according to police reports. No charges were filed against
the driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good man,'' Williams' son, Reuben, said of his
father. ``Loved people, loved children and loved to fish. And loved
the sport of boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Reuben was the only child of Williams and his wife, Irene, whom
he married in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great man,'' said Irene Williams. ``Was loved by a
lot of people. Children and old people were his thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Griffin, Ga., but raised in Houston, Williams was an
accomplished boxer who made a name for himself locally before
embarking on a professional career. In 1997, Williams was inducted
into the World Boxing Hall of Fame in Commerce, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Williams reached the national spotlight in November 1966 with
his heavyweight fight against Ali. He lost to Ali in a three-round
knockout and was never a serious contender again.
</P>
<P>
   Some consider it a miracle that Williams had the opportunity to
fight Ali at all since Williams had been shot in the midsection by
a state trooper a year and a half earlier.
</P>
<P>
   On a dark night along a stretch of highway north of Houston,
Williams was stopped by a Texas state trooper for an alleged
violation. According to reports, words were exchanged, and moments
later Williams lay on the roadside wounded by a bullet from a .357.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had kidney problems as a result of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he was the champion before he got in the ring,''
Irene Williams said, referring to the Ali fight. ``That was a fight
we didn't think would ever happen. He fought Ali with one kidney
and only half of his intestines. He was the people's champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams fought professionally only a couple of more years after
the Ali fight, and then the boxer who fought Sonny Liston twice
called it quits.
</P>
<P>
   Three times a week, Williams underwent dialysis treatments at a
hospital in the Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   It was on his way back from dialysis that Williams was hit by
the automobile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragedy we had to lose him,'' said Irene Williams.
``It's hard to take. The shooting couldn't take him. Diabetes. None
of that took him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Memorial services will be Friday from 7-9 p.m. at Eternal Rest
Funeral Home, 4610 S. Wayside at Loop 610 South. Burial will be
Saturday at 11 a.m. at Paradise North Cemetery, 9235 West
Montgomery Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was well-loved,'' said Reuben Williams. ``We've been
getting a lot of condolences. Daddy didn't have much money, but he
gave a lot to Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial donations to help pay for funeral expenses can be made
to Eternal Rest Funeral Home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
