<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS2-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
 WRITETHROUGH... 
WALK A MILE IN SIZE 11s 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's gotta be the shoes.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago Raul Mondesi wore a pair of Gary Sheffield's
shoes and hit a pair of homers.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of Sheffield on Monday, Mondesi slid on a pair of
Sheffield's size 11s, partially as a reminder to do the little
things. Mondesi promptly had four hits, two stolen bases and an RBI
in the Los Angeles Dodgers' 12-4 thrashing of Montreal at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   That's the type of havoc the Dodgers hope Mondesi creates each
night. His talent matches or exceeds anyone's in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the last few months of a tumultuous season in which his
average has lingered in the .240s, Mondesi is one homer and one
stolen base from the second 30-30 season in Dodgers history.
Mondesi already owns the record; he hit 30 homers and stole 32
bases in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him if he wore my shoes, he's going to get four hits
and he put on my shoes and got four hits,'' Sheffield said. ``It's
just a little reminder for him to do the little things.''
</P>
<P>
   The little things don't include swinging for the fences, which
is how Mondesi got into his horrendous post-May slump.
</P>
<P>
   The difference was the spikes. Mondesi usually wears metal
spikes. On the advice of Sheffield, he wore plastic against the
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't try to hit the ball nine miles . . . this is
what I want from him,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``Hit
the ball up the middle, take the extra base. If he tries to be
(Sammy) Sosa or (Mark) McGwire, that's another story all together.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can hit the ball as hard as both of them, but they can't do
the things he can do. He should hit for a better average, stolen
bases, better defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after Mondesi's tirade in mid-August, and even though there
have been disciplinary problems, Johnson has told people within the
organization that he likes Mondesi, both as a player and a person.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who has taken the leadership role and tried to help
Mondesi through what has been a difficult month, has had increased
conversations with Mondesi about maturing as a ballplayer and not
taking everything to heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player just on his ability,'' said Sheffield, who
moved from right to left field this season to suit Mondesi. ``He
can be a great player every day if he remembers to do the little
things. I think (the outburst) was a wake-up call. `Do you want to
be here?' Don't take everything personally, but take it and make
yourself better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mondy's is a great player and you hate to give up on a guy
that like. He's going to have one of those seasons where he's the
best player and has the best numbers in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Mondesi's second four-hit game of the season were a pair
of doubles. He scored on Devon White's single in the third to give
the Dodgers a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dodgers trailing 4-3 in the fifth, Mondesi singled to
score Sheffield with the tying run. He then stole second and Todd
Hollandsworth stole home on the back end of a double-steal to give
the Dodgers a 5-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It helped starter Chan Ho Park (10-10) win his fourth straight
despite allowing his 28th and 29th homers of the season in six
innings of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheff told me to wear them,'' Mondesi said. ``It's one of
those things to make me remember the little things to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So what will Mondesi do today?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll wear them again,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 0245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
