<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE WILL HIT THE GROUND RUNNING IN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Vice President Al Gore heads to California this
week for a highly visible endorsement tour with the popular Gov.
Gray Davis. But even as the Democratic presidential hopeful tries
to showcase his strength in the nation's most populous state, he
must fight a growing perception that he is playing catch-up on his
most crucial battlefield.
<P>
   ``It is a dogfight,'' said political analyst Sherry Bebitch
Jeffe. ``It is now a battle joined _ and it's one Gore has to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's two-day trip, which begins Thursday, will culminate in a
state tour at the side of Democrat Davis _ who battered the GOP
last November with a landslide victory.
</P>
<P>
   But his 59th visit to the state comes at a time when Republicans
claim that, compared with Texas Gov. George W. Bush, Gore is thin
on endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush has appeared to upstage the vice president on a few
other fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will travel to San Diego, Los Angeles, Fresno and San
Francisco on a trip that will include outreach to Latino business
groups and talk about education. Bush, for his part, hit California
two weeks ago to deliver a major policy address on education _ the
state's top issue _ to the Latin Business Association, representing
the state's most hotly contested voter group.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will return at the end of the month to collect checks from
supporters in Silicon Valley _ another group Gore has long
cultivated in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some extent, it does look as though George W. is shaping
the political game plan here,'' said Bebitch Jeffe.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the Democratic side, Bill Bradley is breathing
down Gore's neck. That means ``Gore has got to pay attention to
California ... not only as part of the general election strategy,''
Bebitch Jeffe said, ``but to keep it in line for the laundry list
of the (March 2000) primary.''
</P>
<P>
   With six months to go before that crucial vote, Democratic
insiders and strategists for rival campaigns in the state say the
vice president's effort to win his party's nomination is entering a
critical phase. Among the tough questions he faces: Does he have
the stuff to make his case to state voters? Or is he too boring,
too battered by ``Clinton fatigue'' to win the primary?
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show that Gore remains in a virtual dead heat with
Bush on the open primary ballot _ even though he isn't facing the
crowded field of competition from his own party that the Texas
governor does.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say those polls, though early, are harbingers of bad
times ahead for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has proven that Woody Allen was wrong: Ninety percent
of life isn't just showing up,'' said Dan Schnur, communications
director for GOP hopeful U.S. Sen. John McCain, who will cross
paths with Gore in California while promoting a new best-selling
memoir, ``Faith of My Fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The twin pillars of Bill Clinton's California support have
been the entertainment community and the high-tech industries,''
said Schnur, whose candidate hits Silicon Valley again next month.
``Both of those groups have pretty significant policy differences
with Gore, so they're taking a look at their other options.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran political strategists say that  &LR; Gore's fortunes in
Silicon Valley _ and beyond _ reflect a shift that has been
occurring for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look back six months, what you saw (was) that he had
been here 54, 56 times. ... The presumption was that the state was
locked up,'' said Gale Kaufman, the Sacramento-based political
consultant who is now a strategist for Bradley's California
campaign. ``That was then; this is now. It's a very different set
of circumstances. He came as vice president. He's now a candidate
for president.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign, however, insists the vice president's current
trip isn't about reacting to other candidates _ or other
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues that are important to the working families of
California is what drives Al Gore's schedules,'' said Gore 2000
spokesman Roger Salazar Monday. ``He has fought for them throughout
his career, and the people of California know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent media reports may ``have an impact on the perception _
but only the insiders are paying attention right now,'' said Julie
Buckner, the former spokeswoman for the successful Clinton-Gore
statewide operation in 1996. ``The Gore operation here is taking
shape and moving forward. They're touching all the base groups,
they're raising the money. ... They have smart people on board, and
they will do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic insiders _ even longtime friends of Clinton's _
insist Gore can and will match the president's legendary ability to
connect with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched Al Gore hundreds of times ... and what is
frustrating for me is to hear people say he's not interesting and
doesn't have charisma,'' said Martha Whetstone, a college friend of
Clinton's and a major Democratic mover in San Francisco. ``I've
watched him give speeches equal to any Bill Clinton has given as
far as being exciting and generating enthusiasm. He's totally
capable of doing that. He's funny and personable. And it's the
biggest misconception about Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   But Garry South, the Democratic adviser who masterminded the
victory of underdog Davis _ another candidate tagged as too boring
to win _ acknowledges a potentially bigger problem, what he calls
``a lack of traction'' in the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   South said that given the administration's strong economic
record in California _ and voters' positions here on such issues as
abortion and guns _ Gore has the credentials he needs against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've tried to approach California as an underdog campaign
for the presidency ... small announcements with the vice
presidential seal hung on the podium,'' said South, who has
consulted for the Gore campaign. ``(Gore) has to approach it like
an underrated underdog. He has to adopt the mentality and fighting
posture of an underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   South insists that California voters _ whose winning campaign
for Davis cited his long government experience _ will balk at a
candidate, however magnetic, who is perceived as ``not ready for
prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is starting to sound a lot like William Jefferson
Clinton, parsing words,'' said South. ``He's a charming rogue _ but
that's what we have in the White House. Do we want a replay?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 0311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 03:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1195 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     09-14 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOMELESS IS WHERE THE HEARTLESS IS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the heart of Richmond, Calif. _ if Richmond has a heart _ is
a big empty building.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, the owners of the building offered it to the
city, free, as a temporary homeless shelter.
</P>
<P>
   And after months of effort by the owners, after volunteer
offers, bureaucratic red tape, bureaucratic red quicksand,
meetings, inspections, pleas and hopes _ it has happened.
</P>
<P>
   The empty building has been converted to ... an empty building.
</P>
<P>
   And just in time, since we're approaching the cold and flu and
freeze-to-death-in-the-gutter season.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, the city of Richmond and Contra Costa County issued
a plea: Will anyone offer two-year use of a 3,000-square-foot
building for a temp homeless shelter for families, while permanent
shelters are being built? Please?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard to believe,'' said Bruce Borjesson when I
told him of the plea.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce and his wife Theresa's building is 6,000 square feet, with
four bathrooms, and they offered it for three years.
</P>
<P>
   They planned to hang onto the building for about five years as
an investment but had no immediate plans for it. They were moved to
make their offer after hearing of a homeless woman and her three
kids being evicted from a Richmond church.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began the saga, reported here a couple times, of the Little
Homeless Shelter That Couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the free building, the Borjessons had elicited
promises from local carpenters' and pipefitters' unions to do any
needed prep work and to pay for shelter insurance, and friends said
they'd pay utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Cost to county and city for a shelter: Fifty cents less than you
invested in this fine newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   No dice.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond Mayor Rosemary Corbin told me the building, according
to her city inspector, needed way too much work. When I asked if I
could see the inspection report, she said she'd never seen one, but
``The building inspector said it needed a lot of work.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Mayor Corbin tell it, the building would never pass the
Big Bad Wolf Huff-Puff Test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The county said (the Borjessons) weren't offering it for long
enough and there were too many strings attached,'' Corbin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Borjessons say: Three years, no strings.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad the Borjessons didn't decide to start a garden for
the homeless, because there's no shortage of fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   Contra Costa County Supe John Gioia, who comes across to me as a
guy interested in helping the homeless, toured the building and
told the Borjessons it would be fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   Gioia says the plan stalled because he could never get a written
report or waiver from the Richmond building department, despite his
multiple requests.
</P>
<P>
   Gioia says a county official finally told him that Richmond was
nixing the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not our program,'' Mayor Corbin told me Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But it's her city, according to Gioia, that provided the final
roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   Follow the bouncing buck.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Borjesson was knocked out by the excitement and enthusiasm
from everyone who toured and inspected the building. He wonders
what happened. Nobody bothered to call and explain. His calls
weren't returned.
</P>
<P>
   Now he hears of the public plea for a building from the same
people who rejected his offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politicians and bureaucrats aren't going to let anything
happen,'' he says. ``They're not looking for (a building).''
</P>
<P>
   What are they looking for? Well, maybe votes. It looks
compassionate to say, ``Please, we need a shelter.'' It gives the
appearance that you care, maybe in lieu of actually caring.
</P>
<P>
   Also, that plea might help with government fund-raising, though
it's worth noting that a civil grand jury four months ago found
that in CC County, ``homeless officials were unable to provide a
mission statement or written report on how money and time were
spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hurdles, the building actually is a homeless
shelter. When it rains, folks often huddle in its doorways.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, when Bruce sensed that his offer was being beaten
to death with a b.s. stick, he said to a couple county officials,
``The first time it gets real cold, what if I just unlock the doors
and people come in? Would you arrest me?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be rash, Bruce. You wouldn't want homeless people in an
unsafe building. Better they camp under freeway bridges, which we
know are 100 percent quakeproof, and in buildings that have been
abandoned because they're so darned safe and nice.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Homeless folks won't have to worry about having to
huddle inside the unsafe building at 332 Harbour Way in Richmond.
The Borjessons, jacked around for months, recently gave up.
</P>
<P>
   I called Bruce on Sunday when I read of the county's new plea,
asked if his building was still available.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold it,'' he said. ``We got discouraged. I signed the
papers yesterday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
