<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 03:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1196 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-MEMORY-LOSS-SFCHRON &LR;      09-14 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMORY-LOSS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FINDINGS OFFER HOPE OF PREVENTING MEMORY LOSS  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fading memory and a steady decline in mental agility have long
been considered hallmarks of aging. Now, brain experts claim to
have found the source of the cerebral cobwebs _ and how to clear
them out.
</P>
<P>
   A team of California researchers traced the phenomenon of
age-related cognitive loss to a small cluster of atrophied nerve
cells buried deep in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are located below the cerebral cortex, these
neurons rarely get much attention. But they make up the active
elements of a vital subcortical system that choreographs activity
throughout the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a series of laboratory experiments, scientists reported
Monday that the key brain cells seem to have plenty of firepower
left even after they appear to quit working. The results were
detailed in the latest issue of the Proceedings of the National
Academy of Science.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all hear this dogma that from the age of 20 we lose 10,000
neurons a day, but that's just not true,'' said lead researcher
Mark Tuszynski, a neuroscientist at the University of California at
San Diego. ``These cells are degenerating, they're dysfunctional,
but they're not dead. And the atrophy can be reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   If your thoughts can be likened to jets landing and taking off
in your head, the subcortical system _ a tiny cluster of so-called
cholinergic neurons sandwiched between your ears _ would be the
air-traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
   They send neurotransmitters into the cerebral cortex and to a
vital region for memory known as the hippocampus. By regulating
memory and attention, the cells enable the higher regions of the
brain to function smoothly. Extensive decline in the same area is
among the signs of Alzheimer's disease and of less pronounced forms
of age-related memory loss.
</P>
<P>
   The system provides a way to ``pay attention to the relevant
things and filter out the irrelevant things,'' Tuszynski explained.
</P>
<P>
   Experiments in aged rhesus monkeys housed at the University of
California at Davis produced evidence that these low-profile brain
cells can shrivel and eventually stop functioning with advancing
years. One possible reason appears to be loss of a protective
factor produced elsewhere in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Previous studies of age-associated mental decline turned up
little sign of neuron loss, although some preliminary studies in
rodents had implicated the same region Tusczynsi studied.
</P>
<P>
   The aged monkeys, however, showed a dramatic 43 percent loss in
the number of full-functioning subcortical neurons compared with
young monkeys. Even the cells that remained active were about 10
percent smaller than their youthful counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers also were astonished to find that the inactive cells
could be brought back to full flower.
</P>
<P>
   In the monkeys, whose brains grow old in a process remarkably
similar to human aging, recovery was achieved by surgically
implanting cells that had been genetically modified to secrete a
rescue protein known as human nerve growth factor.
</P>
<P>
   About 92 percent of the target neurons in the treated animals
once again showed full production of neurotransmitters and other
vital brain-signaling substances. Cell size returned to within 3
percent of normal.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Tuszynski, the study authors included Jeff Roberts at
the UC Davis California Regional Primate Research Center and Fred
Gage at the Salk Institute for Biological Studies in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Other leading brain experts said the experiments were
intriguing, but that it would take more study to prove just how the
activity in the subcortical system affects brain function and just
how big a role the system plays in human cognitive function.
</P>
<P>
   Even if further studies confirm that the aging process is
essentially the same in humans as in monkeys, the implications for
humans are ``not clear at all,'' said Ron McKay, a neuroscientist
at the National Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an interesting finding that suggests a lot of the
stuff we know from rodent models can be applied in primates,'' he
said. ``It certainly should provoke some discussion about how this
is really going to matter to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Many researchers looking into aging and the brain have focused
on genetic approaches. McKay said the new study is part of ``an
important transition'' in the field, where the goal is to more
directly unmask anatomical changes linked to mental processes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One doesn't want to say this is the answer in any sense, but
it does represent a new ability to focus on the problem in a
detailed way,'' McKay said. ``We're beginning to see our way
forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
