<HEADER>
A1300 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-PUERTORICO-BOX-$ADV18     09-14 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-BOX-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``IF YOU GO'' TO OLD SAN JUAN
 &HT;    With PUERTORICO-TRAVEL-$ADV18.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Sept. 18 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIPS FOR TRAVELERS TO PUERTO RICO:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  GETTING THERE: Air connections are good to Luis Munoz Marin
International Airport in San Juan, with American Airlines the
dominant carrier from the U.S. Delta, TWA and United also fly
there. Cruise ships also dock in San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  GETTING AROUND: Puerto Rico is served by all the major
American car rental companies, which have desks at the
international airport. Rates are comparable to within the U.S.,
with a full-size car going for about $50 a day. Taxis are numerous,
but can get expensive if you move around much. Driving a rental car
isn't a problem _ roads are well-marked with good signals, although
parking can be tough to find in San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MONEY: Puerto Rico is a commonwealth of the U.S. and uses
American dollars, making things very easy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TRAVEL DOCUMENTS: None required for U.S. citizens entering
from the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  LANGUAGE _ Spanish is most common, of course, but nearly
everyone, it seems, speaks English, especially if they work in the
tourism industry. In the countryside a phrasebook would be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  CLIMATE _ Tropical, but surprisingly mild. The seabreeze keeps
things relatively cool, although be prepared with plenty of
sunscreen if you plan a beach visit. Average daily high
temperatures in San Juan are a mild 81 degrees in August, a
pleasant 75 degrees in January.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SECURITY _ Like most states with a significant population of
poor, petty theft is present. Use common sense and don't leave bags
unattended at the beach or airport. Don't flash big wads of cash in
public places and don't leave items inside a parked car; lock them
in the trunk or leave them at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WHERE TO STAY _ For beachtime, Isla Verde near the airport has
plenty of new, modern hotels, some with casinos. This is about 10
miles from the historic Old San Juan district. The Condado is
another beach district closer to Old San Juan, but many of the
properties here are in the midst of remodeling. Old San Juan
features a few hotels, including a new, upscale Wyndham; a charming
converted nunnery called El Convento and a few smaller properties.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  OLD SAN JUAN TIPS _ If you drive in, park in one of the
municipal parking garages noted on most tourist maps. The streets
are too narrow and maze-like and parking is too much of a hassle
otherwise. Walking the district is a delight and not too taxing,
but wear comfortable shoes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  EATING OUT _ Puerto Rican food is a delightful mix of
Caribbean, European and Creole, and is served at fine restaurants,
many of which are in hotels. Every conceivable variety of American
fast-food is also available _ and ubiquitous.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  OTHER ACTIVITIES _ Scuba diving and snorkeling are excellent
and can be arranged through travel agents. Touring the small island
in a car can take a day or more, but will give you the flavor of
the old Puerto Rico of small farms and villages. Sidetrips to El
Yunque, a mountainous tropical rainforest, and the Arecibo
Observatory, a giant radio telescope where NASA searches for
extra-terrestrial life, are highly recommended.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
