<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1301 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-PUERTORICO-TRAVEL-$AD     09-14 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-TRAVEL-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PUERTO RICO'S HISTORIC OLD SAN JUAN AN ARCHITECTURAL DELIGHT
 &HT;    With PUERTORICO-BOX-$ADV18.
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Sept. 18 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ You sort of feel sorry for them.
Pasty-white tourists who arrive at Luis Munoz Marin International
Airport and go straight by shuttle bus to the shadowy confines of
the opulent casino-hotels that line large sections of the
waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Days later they stagger back on the bus, pockets either bulging
with winnings or more likely picked clean by the ubiquitous slot
machines, and jet away back home, their Puerto Rican vacation a
cloistered, gambler's binge.
</P>
<P>
   You even feel a bit sorry for the ones who venture outside but
go no farther than the gorgeous _ but building-lined _ beaches of
Isla Verde or Condado, San Juan's two thriving beach districts.
</P>
<P>
   Because if beaches and blackjack are all you get out of a Puerto
Rican vacation, you're missing some of the most intriguing,
picturesque history this hemisphere has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Old San Juan _ a 20-square-block district of cozy streets, shady
plazas and Spanish colonial architectural gems _ beckons with
Caribbean lore and legend, a window into the fascinating early
years of European discovery and conquest.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't always a pretty history, what with massacres of native
Indians, vicious battles among warring empires and centuries of
exploitation. But the setting couldn't be more eye-grabbing.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1521, the city perches atop a narrow, rocky island
guarding the mouth of San Juan Bay. Look inland and the vast bay
spreads out like a tableau, the modern San Juan suburbs rising in
the middle ground and Puerto Rico's green, forested mountains
towering in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Look seaward and the Atlantic Ocean crashes into the rocky coast
at the city's feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish were master fort-builders, and their handiwork
abounds in San Juan. Most of the island is ringed by a massive,
20-foot-thick wall, in places topped by streets, parks and plazas,
or dramatic buildings like La Fortaleza.
</P>
<P>
   Built in the 1830s to defend the bay, it was transformed over
the years into the residence and offices of the island's governor,
and now holds the distinction as the oldest continuously-occupied
executive mansion in the New World. Daily tours offer a peek into
non-working parts of the mansion, including the stunningly tiled
courtyard surrounded by arched-and-columned walkways.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks up the hill from La Fortaleza, through a small
plaza and up a shaded street with dramatic views of the bay,
visitors suddenly find a broad grassy field that leads to Castillo
San Felipe del Morro, a massive fort dominating the bay's entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Known simply as ``El Morro,'' this huge fort has six levels of
gun decks and monstrous walls broken by battlements and turrets.
Built over several decades in the mid-1500s, it towers 140 feet
above the Atlantic. Through the years, Spanish soldiers used it to
repel attacks by competing empires, repulsing such luminaries as
Britain's Sir Francis Drake.
</P>
<P>
   The view from El Morro's battlements down San Juan's Atlantic
waterfront is breath-taking, with white-capped waves crashing on
the rocky shore. San Juan Cemetery, featuring elaborate statuary
and bone-white crosses, dominates the foreground, hugging a rocky
cliff. The city's wall stretches into the distance, leading to El
Castillo de San Cristobal, yet another fort built to protect the
island's eastern fringes.
</P>
<P>
   Along with their war-making, the Spanish thrived at
cathedral-building, too, and San Juan Cathedral is a shining
example of their New World handiwork. Plain stucco walls on the
outside give way to a vaulted, tiled interior where religious icons
and statues line the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish explorer Juan Ponce de Leon _ discoverer of Florida but
also Puerto Rico's first governor _ lies interred here, his remains
guarded by a virgin warrior. He may have needed her help when he
was alive: de Leon had running political battles with Christopher
Columbus' son, Diego, who felt his father's discovery of the place
on his second voyage in 1493 entitled him to rule Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   If 500-year-old politics gives you a headache, you can find
respite only a block away from de Leon's grave at El Convento. No
vows required for entry today, the place was built as a Carmelite
nunnery in 1651 but was converted this century into one of the
district's finest hotels. Dinner and drinks in the courtyard
restaurant are a treat, with formally-dressed waiters who give the
best in European-style service.
</P>
<P>
   But Old San Juan offers more than just history.
</P>
<P>
   Art-lovers will find numerous small galleries and antique shops,
often tucked into the courtyards of buildings with gorgeous iron
balconies and weathered wooden shutters. There is also upscale
shopping, with boutiques offering fine clothing and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   You can even bird-watch in Old San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   Parque de las Palomas _ Pigeon Park _ offers close encounters of
the feathered kind, as hundreds of pigeons wait each day for
tourist hand-outs, often flocking all over the people feeding them.
If Alfred Hitchcock's ``The Birds'' gave you shivers, keep your
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing to avoid is driving inside the district. The
narrow streets can turn into a maze best left to locals. If you're
staying at the beach, taxi in or take a rental car and park it in
one of the several municipal parking garages on the district's
fringes.
</P>
<P>
   The area is a delight to walk, even on hot summer days, as the
seabreeze keeps San Juan several degrees cooler than spots like
Miami or Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   So even if gambling or beach-combing is the main aim of your
Puerto Rican sojourn, consider at least a daytrip to Historic Old
San Juan. The jackpots may be of a different variety, but the odds
are better that you'll go home with something to show from your
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
