<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A lovely affair, nevermind the hat
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ It was a lovely wedding. The bride was
breathtakingly beautiful, and the groom, heartbreak handsome. The
garden was picture-perfect and the rain clouds held.
</P>
<P>
   Violinists seated behind a border of late-summer blooms, drew
family and friends to the grass, two steps beneath the rock-edged
terrace where the minister waited, book in hand, ready to ask the
questions and say the words that would change the bride's name and
two people's lives forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time,'' the bride's mother whispered, shaking me out of
my reverie. Time, I recalled, for the two of us to be claimed by
the young gentlemen who had been charged with walking us to our
places of honor in the garden, among the rose petals at the foot of
the terrace steps. Time to smile. Time to remember.
</P>
<P>
   The young man standing beside Pastor Dan never looked so tall or
handsome before. He is my son. The gentleman to his left, his best
man, used to be my husband. I've known both of them a very long
time. I couldn't help remembering that.
</P>
<P>
   The three of us had grown up together.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the violins eased into a Pachebel Canon, the signal for
the processional to begin. The groom turned, straightened himself,
and focused expectantly on the opening in the tall hedge at the
back of the garden. That's where he would catch the first glimpse
of the lovely lady in white who would soon be his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The one he'd hoped for and waited for all of these years.
</P>
<P>
   Family and friends moved slightly aside to form the aisle the
bride would follow as she walked with measured steps from the
backyard of her childhood, on the arm of her father, to the hand of
her husband-to-be. I couldn't help wondering if ever in her
small-girl imagination she had pictured such a summer's evening
while playing hide-and-seek with her friends _ on the same grass,
around the same bushes.
</P>
<P>
   The tall young man with the rose in his buttonhole (the one
whose stem I'd broken trying to pin in place), watched as his
bride-to-be made her way to him. He looked at her the way all women
would like to be looked at at least once in their lifetimes. A tear
welled in his eye and he left it there. The bride beamed.
</P>
<P>
   Grandma Butler sang the wedding prayer, as she had for the
bride's sister a few years before.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Dan asked who was giving this woman in marriage and the
bride's father answered: ``Her mother and I do.''
</P>
<P>
   For just a moment my mind wandered to thoughts of how it must
feel for a father to place his daughter's hand into the hand of
another man _ a man who had never dried her baby tears or bandaged
her skinned knees. A man who couldn't yet know those special
feelings between a father and his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe one day he would.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Dan spoke words that most of us there had heard before _
well before these children were born. He reminded them always to be
fair and honest, and to stand by one another when times were tough.
They did solemnly promise.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Dan pronounced they were husband and wife.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday afternoon, August 14, 1999, Amy and Kristofor were
married.
</P>
<P>
   I wore a silly hat.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431. E-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
