<HEADER>
A1349 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-AQUA-TAEBO15-COX     09-14 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AQUA-TAEBO15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tae-Bo in water proves powerful workout
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ They're all breathing hard by now, halfway
through their nonstop 45-minute workout. Some weigh more than 300
pounds and some weigh less than 200, but none of the 15 women are
letting up noticeably. Most of them look downright happy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they're singing. As they begin ``Joy to the World,''
they punch an imaginary speed bag rapid-fire and sing about
Jeremiah's mighty fine wine. After that, they kick to the front
with one leg, then to the back with the other. By the time they
finish offering ``joy to the fishes in the deep blue sea,'' they
have added a sharp punch to each kick.
</P>
<P>
   There's no singing in aerobics, you say? No smiling in exercise
workouts? Don't tell anyone at the aqua kickboxing classes that
meet four times a week in the swimming pool at Franciscan Medical
Center's Sports Medicine Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't have fun, they're never going to come back,''
says Cea Cohen-Elliott, the instructor. ``One of the biggest
reasons people don't exercise is because they don't enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   She has been teaching aerobics since 1983 and started shifting
to water aerobics seven or eight years ago. She replaced the basic
water aerobics with kickboxing in January after seeing Billy
Blanks' popular Tae-Bo video. In the water, she decided, kickboxing
was something people could do regardless of their size and at any
pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are ladies who have struggled because they can't
exercise on land,'' Cohen-Elliott says. ``But in the water, the
buoyancy supports them, and it doesn't matter what they look
like.'' They go to these classes comfortable that there will be no
snickering or staring, and they come out of them with more
confidence and better fitness, less stress and fewer pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We full-figured women have discovered that water aerobics
gives us a measure of freedom afforded to those who are agile on
the tennis courts or the jogging paths,'' says Joan Padgett. She
doesn't expect to be enlisted for diet cola commercials, but she
now fits her shrinking hips, thighs, arms and abdomen comfortably
into her business clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Although nominally coed, the class doesn't often have men in it,
but it has women from 24 to 78 years old. Rhoann Carlin is a
50-year-old dental hygienist who started six weeks ago and is
halfway from a size 16 to her size 12 goal. Robin Harris is a 911
operator who has lost 36 pounds in a little more than a year and
calls the aquatic classes ``a way of life.'' And Violet Moster is a
diabetic whose doctor had begged her to exercise for two years
before she gave it a try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared I was going to be intimidated,'' Moster says. ``I
thought everybody was going to weigh 110 pounds. I always thought:
`Exercise? Oh, come on! ' But this is so much fun, it's, `Wow! I
can't wait for the next one.' ``
</P>
<P>
   When she started in mid-April, Moster's doctor was about to
hospitalize her with a blood sugar level above 500. Since mid-May,
it hasn't been over 80. She says she's more ambitious, with more
energy. She has even started working out on dry floors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed my life,'' Moster says. She used to get tired
just going to work, ``and forget about going up a flight of
stairs.'' She needed an electric cart to keep up with her kids in a
shopping mall. She didn't bother getting her nails done or her hair
styled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they just get discouraged about everything,''
Cohen-Elliott says of large, sedentary women. ``But these women are
so proud of themselves. Did Violet tell you about her vacation?''
</P>
<P>
   It was just last month, Moster offers without prompting. ``For
the first time in 13 years, I put on a suit and went swimming with
my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Lori Kelley has been taking Cohen-Elliott's aquatic classes for
seven years, so reluctant to miss even one that she showed up three
days before giving birth last year. Like many in the class, she had
tried a variety of exercise programs. ``On land, it was hard to get
motivated to get back,'' she says. ``Plus there was a little bit of
nonacceptance.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley sometimes sees joggers whose faces ``are in excruciating
pain'' and wonders why they put themselves through it. ``This is
hard work, too, but it's a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Kickboxing alone is a good cardiovascular workout that burns 350
to 450 calories an hour, the American Council on Exercise says.
That's comparable to a brisk walk or slow jog, but ACE points out
that kickboxing has added benefits for strength, flexibility,
coordination and reflexes.
</P>
<P>
   It can be dangerous, though. ACE warns against overextending
kicks, locking joints and exercising beyond fatigue. But the water
not only cushions some of that stress on the joints, it also adds
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't feel like exercise,'' Padgett says. ``I'm light as
a feather in water. I have greater flexibility and enjoy the
stretch just a little further without gravity taking its toll.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never would have thought you could get such a great workout
in water,'' says Cohen-Elliott, who considered stress fractures
just part of the job when she was a dry-floor aerobics teacher. As
a conflict-resolution counselor and motivational speaker on health,
humor and healing, she also understands the water workouts' mental
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stress buster,'' Padgett calls her after-work workouts that
enable her family to share the evening with someone who's not
dragging. Kelley says after she missed a session last week, she was
tired the whole next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come in half dead,'' Joni Kakatolis says after drying off
and dressing. ``And now I have a second wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
