<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1351 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN15-CO     09-14 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Advice for ministers is good for all
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Building a budget and saving some money are just the
beginning for recent college graduates, newlyweds and others who
yearn to secure their futures.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is considerably more complex: turning those
savings into investments that do what you want and don't worry you
to death.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Hamilton, a certified financial planner who counsels
Baptist ministers on retirement and other money matters, has given
a lot of thought to the challenge of setting up a long-term
investment plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all starts with defining what's important to you,'' he
said. ``What do I want in my future, and what will it take to get
it?''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, a 42-year-old who works for the Georgia Baptist
Convention, suggests a three-step process.
</P>
<P>
   The first is setting up an emergency savings account and putting
in enough money to cover three to six months of basic expenses.
This doesn't actually move you ahead, but it protects your savings
if things go bad. Hamilton suggests putting the money into a
readily available money market account.
</P>
<P>
   Step two is organizational _ writing down your goals and what
they will demand of you.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way is a do-it-yourself worksheet. You need to fill
out four columns of information: each goal, what you think it will
cost, when you need the money and how much you need to save each
payday. It's best to start with goals for the next year. Further
down the page, record goals that are one to five years away, then
the really long-term ones.
</P>
<P>
   The tough part, especially for faraway goals, is guessing the
cost. That involves a number of uncertain factors, such as
inflation and the returns you will actually get from your
investments. You may need to read a good book, such as Jane Bryant
Quinn's ``Making the Most of Your Money,'' or hire a financial
planner for a one-time consultation.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton recommends careful attention to near-term spending
plans, such as Christmas gifts and buying a new car. In his family,
a short-term goal is saving enough to celebrate his 20th wedding
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you plan for expenses like this, they don't become a
crisis,'' he observed. ``They don't impinge on your longer-term
savings plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Step three is the big one: Picking the investments that will get
you to each of those goals. It's either the scariest step or the
most rewarding one, depending on how you look at it.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton believes it's best to sort out your investments the
same way you did the worksheet, matching your choices to how soon
you need the money. His investment advice:
</P>
<P>
   _ For the next year's needs, put the money into money market
mutual funds. Another possibility is certificates of deposit that
will mature before you expect to need the cash.
</P>
<P>
   These are best because they are the least volatile. The stock
market might sink in the next year but not a money market or CD.
</P>
<P>
   _ For one- to five-year goals, Hamilton recommends slightly
higher-yielding but still conservative investments. He has in mind
government-backed securities, such as Treasury bills, or mutual
funds that invest in high-quality corporate bonds. For the more
adventurous, he would consider mutual funds specializing in utility
companies.
</P>
<P>
   _ For the long-term goals, Harrison is ready to move to the
stock market and its usually higher returns. Volatility also is up,
but you can reasonably expect to have time to wait out any market
declines.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton tells his clients to stick with mutual funds rather
than trying to be your own stock picker. The first one should be an
index fund that tracks the S&AMP;P 500 index. ``That's your
foundation,'' he said. ``Then you move on from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton does not recommend particular funds. But he favors
certain families of mutual funds, including Putnam, T. Rowe Price,
Vanguard and USAA.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that beginners need to search out mutual funds
that will open an account with a small initial investment.
</P>
<P>
   You will have more choices if you set up an automatic investment
plan, meaning that you authorize your bank to send along a given
amount every payday.
</P>
<P>
   T. Rowe Price's Equity Index 500 fund will open such an account
with a $50 investment. Other fund families will do the same, but
they charge higher fees for their services.
</P>
<P>
   Note that Vanguard and USAA have index funds with substantially
lower expenses, which is a considerable advantage if you expect to
leave your investments alone for many years.
</P>
<P>
   But their cheaper alternatives require an initial purchase of
$1,000 or more for retirement plans, or $3,000 for regular
accounts. That may be something you'll move up to later on.
</P>
<P>
   As you accumulate more savings, Hamilton suggests diversifying
into mutual funds with different investment goals, including growth
or income funds and those that specialize in either small or large
companies.
</P>
<P>
   How do you pick funds? Hamilton recommends starting with the
research reports issued by Morningstar, one of the best-known
mutual fund trackers. You can find Morningstar information at most
libraries or on the Internet at www.morningstar.com.
</P>
<P>
   He tells minister-clients to limit their searches to funds that
have earned four- or five-star ratings. He would steer away from
funds that charge a load, or sales fee, and would favor funds that
have been around at least 10 years. He also suggests comparing the
annual expense ratios of your nominees and looking back to see how
well they performed during market declines.
</P>
<P>
   But don't think the selection will be easy. You will probably
have to balance the good and the bad aspects of each mutual fund
you study. For example, among the index funds mentioned above, only
Vanguard's has been around for longer than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   That means you'll have to make some judgment calls. Your faith
may also come into play. More than half of Americans said in recent
survey that they pray before making major financial decisions. One
in four said they talk to clergy _ perhaps including the ministers
Hamilton counsels.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
