<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1352 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SKOLS-DIVERSITY15-COX     09-14 1445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKOLS-DIVERSITY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feelings of unity ties that bind at high school where no one is
minority
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Up to the ceiling, at least, the student center of
Meadowcreek High School looks like Anyschool, U.S.A. Clean brick
walls and orange molded-plastic chairs lined up neatly at lunch
tables fit the archetype of a middle-class, Gwinnett County school.
On one wall, between Fruitopia vending machines, 10-foot-high,
hand-lettered signs give the rosters of the Mustangs football team
and cheerleading squads.
</P>
<P>
   But above these familiar landmarks, the flags of 60 nations hang
from the ceiling. They mean more to the students than an exercise
in geography. For each flag, at least a few students can point and
say, ``That's where I was born.'' Which makes Meadowbrook one of
the two or three most diverse schools in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother keeps telling me I need to see other countries,''
says Sergio Lozano, 16, a native of Colombia. ``And I tell her, all
I have to do is go to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Meadowcreek is 26 percent white, 35 percent black, 20 percent
Hispanic and 16 percent Asian. But those cold stats don't really
describe the school's diversity; there are scores of students of
Indian, Pakistani and Saudi Arabian backgrounds, for example, who
list themselves as white. Taking in a Meadowcreek hallway between
classes is a bit like strolling through a cheerful port city on
market day. You see clusters of chattering friends where three or
even all four of those major racial groups are represented.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers also don't capture the extra patriotic shiver that
one feels _ at the jam-packed open house for parents the other
night _ when a school choir of every shade of skin color sings the
national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is a minority here,'' says Ronni Ford, the warm but
no-nonsense Anglo principal. ``I honestly think that's the key to
the feeling of unity.''
</P>
<P>
   The students, too, are aware _ in their unassuming,
did-you-see-``Dawson's Creek''-last-night? way _ that they're a
vanguard, that Meadowcreeks will eventually be more the norm than
the exception across the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just by walking around this school we're learning to deal with
what America is going to be later in our lives,'' says Charlie
Charoenlap, an American-born 17-year-old of Thai, Vietnamese and
Anglo heritage. ``We're not even conscious that we're absorbing the
social skills, but we are. Future leaders will come from places
like Meadowcreek because we've dealt with diversity and learned the
skills.''
</P>
<P>
   The look, though, is all-American. Foreign costume, as well as
food, are rare at Meadowcreek, except at the school's well-attended
annual International Festival. ``The whole world copies the
American teenagers they see on TV,'' says a smiling Muhammed
Saleem, a Pakistani accountant accompanying his son to open house.
There's one outward sign of diversity, however: The school has made
one exception to its no-hat rule, permitting turbans, which have
cultural significance for some Muslim males.
</P>
<P>
   Meadowcreek may also be a model for the future in that it draws
families that are themselves multi-ethnic. Roger Flot, who
describes himself as ``Louisiana mix: French, black, creole,'' and
his Anglo wife, Bonnie Flot, say they could have moved into other
metro-area school districts but, ``We chose Meadowcreek's because
it's so multicultural, like where we used to live in Southern
California.''
</P>
<P>
   Meadowcreek does not simply have many-colored threads; it
appears to be tightly woven. Visiting the school is like seeing the
dollar-bill motto _ ``E pluribus unum,'' or ``from the many, one''
_ in action. Soon after Meadowcreek opened in 1987, the
administration set up a mediation group of diverse students to open
up communication, and perhaps because of that foresight, serious
conflicts have not materialized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diversity is never negative for us,'' claims Lauren Bellamy,
the 17-year-old African-American student-body president. Laughing,
she adds that the mediation group ``deals more with typical
problems like, `I heard a rumor that she said something bad about
me because another girl thought I was looking at the boy that this
other girl used to date!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of dating, it's another phenomenon that appears to
cross ethnic and racial lines with relative ease. Lauren Hadden, an
Anglo 17-year-old raised in Georgia, says, ``My parents pick on me
because I've gone out with Italian, Spanish and Russian guys, but
to me it's such a non-issue. I didn't even know he was Russian till
the second date!''
</P>
<P>
   If it all sounds a little too sweet, a little too
We-Are-The-World _ there's more to the story. There are huge
challenges to educating such a diverse population of 2,100, where a
quarter of the students grew up speaking one of 35 languages other
than English. The school's average SAT score this year was 940,
lowest in Gwinnett and lower than the state average of 969.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Yoo, who moved from Korea a year ago, and Darya Sofiyeva,
from Ukraine three years ago, find the Meadowcreek curiculum easier
than that of their native countries, but they are still among the
hundreds at the school who must work even harder than American-born
peers to master the English language. In Darya's words, ``I learned
English in Ukraine, but it's not the same as American!''
</P>
<P>
   Drop-in classroom visits reveal that immigrant students murmur
among themselves in their native tongues even while the teacher is
speaking _ ``I'm hearing a lot of Spanish back there!'' warns one
teacher, without much effect _ creating a kind of underground
classroom from which other students are excluded. When one Korean
boy arrives late for his first class in English for Speakers of
Other Languages, he not only fails to sit down when a teacher asks
him twice to do so (he may not have understood her) but won't even
acknowledge her. It is soon discovered he is in the wrong class and
he's ushered out, so it's unclear how his rudeness would be
disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are no numbers to measure the spontaneous cultural
education of Meadowcreek's halls, lunch tables and playing fields:
``You don't just talk about tolerance here, you learn it,'' says
Pakistani-born Sajid Saleem. Of the conflicts in the school, ``The
few that occur are not about diversity,'' maintains Assistant
Principal Jane Moser.
</P>
<P>
   Parents at the open house agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my daughter first came to this school 10 years ago, I
thought, `Oh no _ the gangs!''' says Efat Ghalagol, a housewife
from Iran whose son is a sophomore. ``But there are no gangs. This
is the melting pot school _ wonderful experiences for my children!
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the race of the children,'' she adds. ``It's
how they were raised in the home.''
</P>
<P>
   The misperception about gangs is not uncommon. When the
Journal-Constitution convenes a panel of eight students to discuss
the school, the subject that aroused the fiercest passions is
Meadowcreek's reputation among other schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call us `Ghettocreek,' '' declares Sergio. He tries to
laugh in a casual way, but one can sense the hurt underneath. The
feeling of being misunderstood, put down, is echoed all around the
conference table. Dhruv Parekh, a 15-year-old of Indian parentage,
says that he's been asked by an adult professional in his
neighborhood ``if it's wise to go to such a rough school'' _ a
notion that becomes almost laughable as one drives onto the
well-tended Meadowcreek campus and sees the playful ``Mustang
Trail,'' blue horseshoe prints on the sidewalks, leading to the
playing fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``It irritates me to hear those comments,'' Dhruv says,
``because I take a lot of pride in my school.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, an us-against-the-world spirit seems to be one of the
glues binding Meadowcreek together. It's a palpably happy school
whose identity is more than the sum of its ethnic parts: in a word,
American. There are cliques, of course, the students say, but the
so-called preppies, jocks and other upper castes do not have the
intimidating power seen at more typical high schools, that has
lately led to despair and violence among alienated students.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Mullins _ accompanied at the open house by his
African-American father and Sicilian-Mohawk mother _ name two
mostly Anglo high schools nearby and declares, ``They think they're
higher than us.'' Then, letting his emotions get the better of his
grammar, he adds, ``At Meadowcreek, ain't nobody higher than
nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
