<HEADER>
A1355 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-DION15-COX     09-14 2623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DION15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Faith, family sustain Dion's joy, talent
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``I wanna play you something,'' Dion
says, making his way down the staircase of his Boca Raton home,
speaking in a heavy New York accent. He's the same pop legend seen
in countless photographs _ the cocky born-in-the-Bronx stride, the
trademark cap covering his jet-black hair.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a difference: He's gentler than one might imagine, a
Rock and Roll Hall of Famer who's got the measured demeanor of a
street-corner philosopher. And he's got a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   First, however, comes the song. From a corner of his study, the
stereo blasts a sweet slice of '50s rock 'n' roll:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tearin' down the highway, look at all that ice and
snow/Headin' for that next town, gettin' ready for another show/I'm
gonna hug my radiator when I hit my hotel room . . .''
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds dated, that's because it is. ``Hug My Radiator''
was written during a 1959 winter tour, when Dion DiMucci was a New
York kid climbing the charts with his group, Dion and the Belmonts.
A couple of other budding rockers _ Ritchie Valens, Buddy Holly _
were part of the show. For them, the Midwest cold proved too much
and they chartered a flight. Dion stuck with the highway and the
bus, saving himself the $35 air fare _ and his life.
</P>
<P>
   On that night the music died _ the plane crashed en route to
North Dakota, leaving no survivors _ Dion was given a second
chance. There would be more revelations in the years ahead _ and
more brushes with death. But it's only now that he's reached 60 and
built a new life in this pretty-in-pink city that Dion is willing
to revisit the past and celebrate the future. ``Hug My Radiator''
is featured on an album he's just finished. It's also part of the
soundtrack to a film that actor-screenwriter Chazz Palminteri (``A
Bronx Tale'') wants to make about Dion's life. And there's a boxed
set due from Capitol that will trace Dion's 40-year career.
</P>
<P>
   The Wanderer has found a home at last.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last 11 years in Boca, they have been the greatest years
in my life,'' he says during a conversation in his kitchen,
surrounded by a close circle of pals munching on slices of pizza.
``I developed friendships that have kept me full of life, kept my
spirit young.''
</P>
<P>
   The rock legend _ a father of three and grandfather of two _
looks remarkably young. His buddies may kid him about the hair _ or
possible lack thereof _ under that trademark cap, but the body is
trim and toned, the result of regular workouts in a local gym. More
importantly, the Bronx hoodlum who knew all the angles still knows
them. But the angles have changed. Now, Dion's life isn't about
talking tough, scoring drugs or even making hit records. It's about
friends and family _ and an abiding faith in a higher power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the thing that defines Dion today beyond a shadow of a
doubt is his relationship with God,'' says Ben Troxell, a Deerfield
Beach financial consultant who met the singer-songwriter on a
spiritual retreat more than 15 years ago and has remained a friend.
Not that Troxell sees any diminishing of Dion's talent. ``He's
probably at least as creative as he was in his 20s and maybe even
more so. There's a richness and a texture to his experience that he
brings to bear along with the fertility of his imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   A great white blues singer
</P>
<P>
   Dave Marsh, one of America's foremost rock critics and a diehard
Dion fan, offers even higher praise. Noting how most '50s rockers
either died or dried up creatively, he says the voice behind such
doo-wop classics as ``A Teenager in Love,'' ``Runaround Sue'' and,
of course, ``The Wanderer,'' is the true exception _ a pop pioneer
who grows with the times. ``He's one of the few great white blues
singers,'' he says. ``He completely understands that music from its
emotional insides.''
</P>
<P>
   And what does the man who wedded a black beat to a Bronx
attitude have to say on the subject? For him, music is an extension
of a search for knowledge. ``I know a lot of guys who sing about
wonderful, beautiful things and they don't even get their own
message,'' he explains during lunch at a Mizner Park eatery. ``But
I wanted to know what the truth was and how you apply it to your
life. Not just talk about it, but live it. That's what I'm about.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty heady stuff for a guy who grew up on the rough streets of
New York, became a millionaire at 21, then nearly threw it all away
on drugs and booze. But that's part of Dion's journey, the road
that's led him to his semi-anonymous, spiritual life in Boca today.
He still gets recognized occasionally on the street _ and the
neighbors in his relatively posh gated community surely know who he
is. And he has something of an ego: His wife of 36 years, Susan,
teases him about the ``store'' he keeps in the trunk of his Jeep
Cherokee, which holds boxes of his CDs that he passes on to curious
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   But otherwise it's a quiet existence. Dion's daily routine might
consist of a visit to St. Jude's Catholic Church in Boca, where he
regularly attends Mass and leads recovery programs for substance
abusers. ``It's kind of the center of my life,'' he explains. From
there, it's lunch or dinner at a local restaurant _ he can name
practically every red-sauce joint between Fort Lauderdale and West
Palm Beach _ with one of his friends, most of whom are
nonmusicians. They joke that he's so discreet about his identity,
it's hard for people to believe he's really Dion. ``He called up my
office a couple of weeks ago and one of the girls hung up on him.
She just thought it was a crank call,'' says Mike Apter, a Boca
business owner.
</P>
<P>
   Dion also spends plenty of time with family members, whom he
prefers to keep out of the spotlight. Wife Susan runs the business
side of his musical affairs. His two older daughters live in South
Florida _ Tane is a teacher, Lark is a homemaker. The youngest,
August, just finished a master's degree in art in Baltimore. The
family gets together for holidays, cruises and, most recently,
August's graduation. ``We caused quite a racket,'' Dion says with
pride.
</P>
<P>
   Between everything else, Dion makes music in his tastefully
decorated but hardly ostentatious home, where figures of Christ
hang next to photos of grandchildren. The closest thing you'll find
to a piece of priceless artwork is his own painting of blues great
Robert Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   He leads a visitor to his ``studio,'' a small room on the second
floor decorated with bits of memorabilia _ Lou Reed's speech
inducting him into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame, an autographed
chart for a Bruce Springsteen song he once sang in concert with The
Boss, even an original poster for the ill-fated 1959 ``Winter Dance
Party'' tour with Holly and Valens. There's also a mixing board and
a microphone. ``If I get really inspired, I turn the chair around,
turn the equipment on and go,'' Dion explains.
</P>
<P>
   Comeback? He never stopped
</P>
<P>
   He's been inspired lately. Although he's continued to record
since his late 1950s-early '60s heyday _ ``I don't think in Dion's
mind he ever made a comeback album because he never stopped,'' says
Marsh _ he's clearly approaching his art with a newfound
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this album,'' Dion says of his newest effort, which
he's just begun shopping to record labels. It's self-consciously
retro, recorded with a single microphone in the style of the old
days. And musically, it brings Dion back to his doo-wop roots. ``My
wife keeps saying, `Dion, this is a work of art.' She feels like
it's full circle.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, from the mid-'60s to the late '80s, Dion really was a
musical wanderer: He traded in his early pop success for a
quasi-beatnik life, singing the blues and folk ballads in Greenwich
Village coffee houses and all but abandoning his five-year
recording contract with Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   He did have one hit as a folkie, ``Abraham, Martin and John,''
an ode to fallen heroes recorded in the aftermath of Bobby
Kennedy's 1968 assassination. But that was followed by a long dry
spell, during which he recorded a fair bit of Christian music,
played more coffee houses, reunited briefly with the Belmonts and
made what even he admits was a terrible album with legendary
producer Phil Spector.
</P>
<P>
   The sign that Dion wasn't finished musically came in 1989, with
the release of ``Yo Frankie'' on Arista. Although hardly a
commercial success, it signaled a new beginning: Here was the
culmination of a lifetime of roots influences, from country (Dion's
childhood idol was Hank Williams) to rock to blues to folk.
</P>
<P>
   Biopic in the planning stages
</P>
<P>
   The new album is even rootsier _ with a sound that takes you
directly back to the '50s. The idea came from the movie that
Palminteri is planning. Actually, it's the second attempt at a Dion
picture. Around the release of Dion's 1988 autobiography, ``The
Wanderer: Dion's Story,'' director Barry Levinson (``Rain Man,''
``Diner'') expressed interest and a script was developed. But the
focus remained on Dion's early years in the Bronx, when he emerged
from the confines of a tough-love Italian family _ his parents now
reside in Broward County _ and became a gang member and finally a
recording star.
</P>
<P>
   To Dion, however, the real story was what followed _ how he was
given a second chance after declining to fly with Valens and Holly.
Not that he couldn't afford the $35 fare. But the sum equaled what
his parents paid for rent each month on their tenement apartment.
``My head just hadn't stretched on spending a whole month's rent on
a 45-minute flight. So, I said no,'' he recalls. When he got to the
next town and heard the news, ``Reality started trickling down in
my head, my heart, my soul. You start thinking, `Who am I? Where am
I? What's life about?' ''
</P>
<P>
   By the time his career peaked in 1963, when he had six Top 40
singles as a solo artist, he still hadn't found the answers.
Walking away from his success, he became a junkie and alcoholic.
``It was like the prodigal son thinking he found heaven when he
found hell,'' he says. In his book, he describes harrowing scenes
of throwing his pregnant wife out of a car, shooting heroin in the
garage of his ritzy Manhattan apartment building and nearly
attempting suicide.
</P>
<P>
   His redemption came in 1968, after he moved to Miami to escape
the mess of his life. At first, little changed. ``I was looking for
a geographic miracle and I found out I brought myself with me,''
Dion says. But then his father-in-law, a recovered alcoholic,
forced Dion to face the truth: On April 1 of that year, he started
a new life, one firmly committed to God and free of drugs or
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had it backwards, now I'm home,'' Dion says, recalling how
all the fame and fortune led to his despair. ``It used to be that
what I did determined who I was. Now, it's who I am that determines
what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Dion's spirituality is something he doesn't hide. In his book,
he relates how during a morning jog in 1979, he experienced the
divine revelation _ a visit from Jesus. At the same time, he
doesn't force his views on other people _ nor does he expect them
to take his words as the gospel truth.
</P>
<P>
   But his friend Ben Troxell, a devout Christian, says that Dion
will gladly tell his story to those inclined to listen. ``First, he
wants to be a friend. Then, if you're interested, he will share . .
. He's so disarming that by the time you have a relationship with
him, you are at least receptive to what he has to say and aren't
the least offended if your beliefs don't line up with his.''
</P>
<P>
   It's this rocker-turned-gentle philosopher's story that
Palminteri, another Italian Bronx native, is determined to capture.
``It's a story of personal triumph with music as a background,'' he
explains. The actor-turned-director _ this will be his first
feature-length directing job _ doesn't hide his admiration for
Dion. ``He's like a great soul,'' he says. ``His story has to be
told.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the most imaginative filmmaker might have trouble
finding much excitement in Dion's life today. Since moving to Boca
Raton 11 years ago _ he wanted to escape the crime of Miami and
find a better place to raise his three daughters _ he has led that
fairly mundane existence described above. He still plays an
occasional concert locally or out-of-town; he did a church benefit
earlier this year at the Eissey Campus Theatre in Palm Beach
Gardens. He also released a second book last year, collaborating
with Andi Litt Wiener on a self-help title, ``Chapters: Writing the
Adventure of Your Life.''
</P>
<P>
   But the only time he really steps into the spotlight is when
he's asked by other rock legends. Bob Dylan and Paul Simon, for
example, saluted him during their recent performance at Coral Sky
Amphitheatre by singing ``The Wanderer,'' pointing him out in the
crowd and inviting him backstage.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't even bother attending the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame
ceremonies, even though he's been invited annually since his
induction in 1989. The one exception was last year, when he took
his close friend, Ric Newman, a Boca commercial real-estate
developer, as a special gift. Newman, the only local buddy who's a
real rock buff, says he was amazed to see the respect Dion was
accorded.
</P>
<P>
   ``When somebody like Billy Joel walks into the room and they see
him, they make a beeline for him. They hold him in very high esteem
as a pioneer of rock 'n' roll,'' Newman explains. ``I think he
(Dion) is starting to appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   `You can make a niche hit'
</P>
<P>
   But the question is whether Dion can have another hit.
Certainly, in a music scene dominated by fashion-conscious
hip-hoppers and angry alt-rockers, it seems unlikely. Dave Marsh
doesn't write off the possibility, though. ``I don't think it's
inconceivable. Circumstances can conspire. And these days, there
are different kinds of hits. . . . You can make a niche hit,'' he
explains, noting the many radio formats. But Marsh's faith is based
on something deeper. ``God knows, Dion has talent. One of the
things that struck me about this new group of songs is that his
singing is so strong and sooner or later, people are going to get
interested in strong singing again.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Dion, he's not holding his breath. ``I guess it would be
nice, but it's something I certainly don't focus on. If I really
look at it, I have had much more than my share. I have a lot to be
thankful for.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Dion seems more interested in connecting with an
audience than on selling them something. His belief is that rock is
simply the great communication medium of popular culture _ and that
anyone can qualify as a rocker, even a classical violinist he
caught on television the other night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `This guy is a rock and roller,' '' he recalls.
``There was a sound coming out that had nothing to do with the
violin under his chin. He played with such passion, it stirred
me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that same passion with which Dion approaches the nonmusical
part of his life. During a two-hour lunch, he answers most
career-related questions politely, but seems far more interested in
offering child-raising advice. ``That's the real important stuff,''
he explains, relating a conversation he once had with Springsteen
during a 1997 concert stop in Sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nobody backstage, just him and a guitar. I said to
him at one point, `Bruce, life is the art,' '' Dion recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Springsteen's response? ``I know, and it's rough.''
</P>
<P>
   At 60, Dion has finally made it look easy.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Passy writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
