   PERSONAL FINANCE
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ ATLANTA _ Building a budget and saving some money
are just the beginning for recent college graduates, newlyweds and
others who yearn to secure their futures. The next step is
considerably more complex: turning those savings into investments
that do what you want and don't worry you to death. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   AQUA-TAEBO _ DAYTON, Ohio _ They're all breathing hard by now,
halfway through their nonstop 45-minute workout. Some weigh more
than 300 pounds and some weigh less than 200, but none of the 15
women are letting up noticeably. Most of them look downright happy.
In fact, they're singing. As they begin ``Joy to the World,'' they
punch an imaginary speed bag rapid-fire and sing about Jeremiah's
mighty fine wine. After that, they kick to the front with one leg,
then to the back with the other. By the time they finish offering
``joy to the fishes in the deep blue sea,'' they have added a sharp
punch to each kick. There's no singing in aerobics, you say? No
smiling in exercise workouts? Don't tell anyone at the aqua
kickboxing classes that meet four times a week in the swimming pool
at Franciscan Medical Center's Sports Medicine Center. (Lamb,
Dayton Daily News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SKOLS-DIVERSITY _ Where Cultures Converge: A visit to
Meadowcreek High School in metro Atlanta's Gwinnett County. With a
quarter of its 2,000 students born outside the U.S., this is one of
the most diverse schools in Georgia and a lab for the multicultural
America of the future. (Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
