<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The ups and downs of home parties
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Imagine: Making money while you have
fun!
</P>
<P>
   That's at least part of the idea behind home party sales, a
subset of the growing home-based sales industry.
</P>
<P>
   Working at home has some obvious ups and downs: Everybody likes
the idea of flexible hours, but most people like the idea of a firm
payday even more.
</P>
<P>
   The upside is strong enough to draw nearly 10 million Americans
into sell-from-home businesses, a number that nearly doubled in the
past decade, according to the Direct Selling Association trade
group. More than 60 percent are women; most work part time.
</P>
<P>
   With a wide range of home care products, cookware and cosmetics
leading the way _ and big-name companies such as Avon, Amway and
Mary Kay _ total sales topped $23 billion last year. More than a
quarter of that was sold through home parties.
</P>
<P>
   While most companies encourage home-based sellers to use
traditional one-on-one sales techniques, a growing number are
following the Tupperware path. The World Wide Web glitters with
prospects for profit-minded hosts, such as:
</P>
<P>
   Pampered Chef kitchen tools. (``If you would like to Host a
Pampered Chef show to see what Pampered Chef has to offer, you will
receive at NO cost to you a wonderful Hostess Gift chosen by
yourself. Whichever you decide you can't lose!'')
</P>
<P>
   Fun-Zee's Funwear clothing (``As a new Sales Rep you can earn
free clothes from Fun-Zee's by conducting 7 presentations within
the first 30 days after receiving your clothes.'')
</P>
<P>
   PartyLite candles (``We're ready to help you enrich your life
with candles, friends, and additional income.'')
</P>
<P>
   Jewels by Park Lane (``A Park Lane show held in the home or
office: Brings friends and co-workers together. Is fun,
interesting, and exciting . . . Offers tremendous free credit,
gifts, discounts, and exciting specials for our hostesses and
guests.'')
</P>
<P>
   Mosley's Home Sales Network, including home decor and
collectibles. (``Our party plan is phenomenal . . . As an MWN Home
Party Sales Representative you can make $125 and more with a 1
1/2-2-hour party!'')
</P>
<P>
   The first step to reward, of course, is investment. Most
party-sales companies require a seller to buy a demonstration kit,
typically $25 to $100. Some, like Tupperware, don't charge
anything.
</P>
<P>
   A high initial fee may be cause for hesitation, but a low
initial fee doesn't necessarily mean a good deal. The Direct
Selling Association advises prospective sellers to find out whether
they'll be required to buy more inventory later, and whether the
company will buy back unsold merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The association offers other tips at its Internet site,
www.dsa.org.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Kalajian writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
