<HEADER>
A1376 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TUPPERWARE-WOMAN15-CO     09-14 1832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUPPERWARE-WOMAN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's no trick to selling Tupperware, consultant says
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jo-Ann DiLorenzo received her Tupperware
calling 27 years ago this Oct. 2. There's no other way to put it.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since she threw her first party, Tupperware has come to
fill her life. And her house. Not merely the kitchen cabinets,
freezer and pantry, but darn-near every bit of her three Boynton
Beach bedrooms, two baths, living and family rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of what you see were Tupperware earnings,'' says
DiLorenzo, who ranks among the top 10 percent of Tupperware sales
managers nationally. ``The linens, the TV, the mirror, the
pillows.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus the dark-wood credenza, the crystal that lines its shelves,
the dining room set, the kitchen set, the end tables and the
minivan in her driveway.
</P>
<P>
   And those are just the inanimate rewards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my best friends, I've met through Tupperware,'' she
adds. ``My children's godparents I met through Tupperware.''
</P>
<P>
   It is almost as though her entire world whooshed out of a giant
plastic tub with one pop of Earl S. Tupper's ingenious, airtight
lid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, it took a lot of hard work,'' says DiLorenzo. ``You
get out what you put in.'' DiLorenzo, 50, expected to be putting
her efforts into something a little more concrete than plastic. She
started out as an architectural draftsman in New York City, working
on urban renewal projects. Then she got pregnant and asked for some
time off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told I had to make a choice between a family and my
job,'' she says. ``But the choice was already made. I said it was
nice knowing them and left.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband chose to live on one income until she found
a job that gave her enough flexibility to care for her family. Her
daughter was 2 years old when a friend of a friend invited
DiLorenzo to a Tupperware party.
</P>
<P>
   At evening's end, the guests were told that any of them could
earn $25 to $30 by giving a Tupperware demonstration. DiLorenzo
signed up for a kit and began planning a party of her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother told me not to invite the relatives because it was a
disgrace,'' she says. She scraped up a few friends and managed to
sell $47 worth of Tupperware.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early '70s, it sold for less than half what it does
today,'' she says. ``It was probably $7 to $8 for an average
container.''
</P>
<P>
   With the standard Tupperware commission of 35 percent, she kept
$16.55 _ not quite what she expected. Her second party was slightly
more profitable, but the third was her breakthrough: $550 in sales,
plus five recruits who agreed to host parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were all women who had never been to a Tupperware
party,'' she says. ``They all brought their moms, and none of them
could get enough Tupperware.''
</P>
<P>
   Product sells itself, she says
</P>
<P>
   There's really no trick to getting people excited about plastic
kitchenware, DiLorenzo insists, as she slaps, taps and bumps a few
bowls to show how rugged they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tupperware is the premier food storage system,'' she declares.
``They're all dishwasher safe. A large variety go into the
microwave. Did you know we now have Tupperware you can put in a
conventional oven?''
</P>
<P>
   DiLorenzo reaches into a cupboard and produces a deep, tan bowl
that looks vaguely like a German army helmet. ``This is called Oven
Works,'' she says. ``It goes into the oven up to 450 degrees. If
it's burnt black from baking, you can wash it right off.``
</P>
<P>
   By the time she's done explaining how Tupperware Oven Works can
cut cooking time (``Remember, it costs 75 cents an hour to run a
conventional oven, and you're paying Mr. FPL even more while you
turn up the air conditioning''), $45.50 sounds downright cheap for
a plastic casserole dish.
</P>
<P>
   DiLorenzo's Tuppermania is so deep, so infectious, that
customers from her early parties are still sending business her way
27 years later. Many of the party-goers she's met since have also
remained loyal, despite the profusion of burp-alike food systems
available everywhere at discount prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give people service,'' she says. ``I call them. I send them
recipes. If they want a little gadget, I just send it to them. I do
what it takes to make the customer feel appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   DiLorenzo sees just about everyone as a potential customer and
rarely misses the opportunity to explain how much better life can
be with Tupperware. (``You can bang on it, step on it, throw it.
You get lifetime replacement.'')
</P>
<P>
   Still, she says, the neighbors don't run when they see her
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never pushy,'' she says. ``I'm informative. There are
many, many customers out there looking for Tupperware
consultants,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message DiLorenzo has been most successful at getting
across. She attracts her own faithful following of ``consultants''
(Tuppertalk for sales people) who can work their way up to being
managers like her by recruiting others. She has 32 of them,
including two former teachers and other professionals who found
Tupperware more lucrative than their previous jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a career choice, not something you do because you
can't find a real job,''
</P>
<P>
   Associates, consultants profit
</P>
<P>
   DiLorenzo and her consultants persuade friends and, sometimes,
strangers to host parties. DiLorenzo or one of her associates does
the selling; the host gets a gift, usually Tupperware. The more
Tupperware guests buy, the more expensive the gift.
</P>
<P>
   Her consultants make commissions on their sales, and so does
DiLorenzo. She also gets a bonus for each recruit she brings in.
When her team meets its sales goal _ which it almost always does _
she gets a little something on top of that. The credenza, for
example, was a bonus for a team sales total of $90,000 in just four
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This jewelry is all from some sort of bonus,'' she says,
showing off several gold-and-diamond bracelets, earrings, rings and
a gold watch with her name engraved in it.
</P>
<P>
   Cars, minivans, lots of trips
</P>
<P>
   She does well with her own parties, too, selling about $50,000
worth of Tupperware last year: $17,500 in base commissions before
all those bonuses. Her sales have been consistently high enough
since her second year on the job to qualify for a company-leased
car or minivan: more than 20 of them, including her current Dodge
Caravan, so far.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, she gets free trips to sales conventions. She came back
from the recent national meeting in Las Vegas with several awards,
including a $400 credit at Sears. The rewards more than make up for
the nights and weekends given to parties and sales meetings in
addition to days devoted to making and taking calls and filling
orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband is retired on Social Security,'' she says. ``Other
than that, the only money coming into this house is from my
Tupperware business. We take plenty of vacations every year. We
just married off my daughter with a very nice wedding. I'd say you
can do very nicely.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Joe, was not a Tupperware bonus, but (unlike her
first husband) he is a Tupperware enthusiast. He helps with the
mailing , the paperwork, the parties. He understands that his
wife's dedication is as emotional as it is financial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hit the lottery tomorrow, she'll still sell Tupperware,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   She nods in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do this as long as I can walk,'' she says. ``A friend of
mine used to say, 'Let me know when there's a Tupperware coffin.
Then I know they'll preserve me forever.' ''
</P>
<P>
   TUPPERFACTS
</P>
<P>
   _ About 950,000 people sell Tupperware around the world.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Tupperware party starts every 2.2 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   _ About 105 million people attended Tupperware parties last
year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Total purchases: more than $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IS TUPPERWARE?
</P>
<P>
   Tupperware started as a line of food storage containers made of
nonporous plastic and covered by a lid that makes a distinctive
sound when opened. (Most call it a burp; Jo-Ann DiLorenzo prefers
``whisper.'') The brand now includes a range of mostly kitchen
products, including cooking pans and utensils. The company is based
in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   WHY THE FUNNY NAME?
</P>
<P>
   Tupperware was invented by Earl Silas Tupper, a New Hampshire
scientist, tree farmer and tinkerer who became fascinated with a
newfangled petroleum derivative called plastic while working for
DuPont in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Tupper struck out on his own, making plastic gas masks and other
military supplies during World War II. After the war, he became a
consumer plastics pioneer. Plastic tumblers and plastic toothpicks
were among his innovations.
</P>
<P>
   He not only made plastic accessible, he made it respectable.
Before Tupper, plastic was synonymous with junk: Brittle, oily,
ugly and smelly. Tupper developed a method of transforming
oil-refining waste into clean, flexible, translucent sheets.
</P>
<P>
   His second breakthrough was the plastic Tupper lid, an air-tight
seal modeled on the metal lids used for paint containers. Tupper
used them on his early food storage containers in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   WHO CAME UP WITH THE IDEA OF A TUPPERWARE PARTY?
</P>
<P>
   Tupper tried to sell his containers in stores, but he had little
success. Who could stomach the thought of food stored in plastic,
much less figure out how to work that crazy lid?
</P>
<P>
   A divorced mother named Brownie Wise discovered that lots of
people could, once they'd seen a proper demonstration. She added
Tupper's wares to the Stanley Home Products line that she was
already selling at gatherings in customers' homes. Tupper was so
impressed by her success that he adopted the home-party idea as his
exclusive sales outlet and made her vice president for sales in
1951.
</P>
<P>
   Tupper, who sold his company to Rexall in 1958 for $16 million,
is regarded as a brilliant inventor and businessman. He died in
1983. His papers are archived at the Smithsonian Institution. The
collection's introduction acknowledges Wise, who died in 1992, as
co-genius for creating and nurturing her army of party throwers.
</P>
<P>
   WHY HOST ONE?
</P>
<P>
   The host gets a gift worth $8.50, even if no one at the party
buys anything. The more people buy, the more you get, especially if
guests agree to host their own parties. If, for example, the guests
spend $300 and agree to host two parties, the host gets a $67.50
Tupperware picnic set, including bowls and utensils. For $450 in
sales and two parties, the hosts gets the picnic set plus an
insulated bag and other containers.
</P>
<P>
   HOW LONG WILL TUPPERWARE PARTY ON?
</P>
<P>
   Indefinitely, the company says, even though it shattered
tradition Aug. 10 when it started selling some of its products
directly through its Internet site (www.tupperware.com). Also new:
mall kiosks and infomercials. But Tupperware says these new sales
outlets will augment, not replace, the traditional parties.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Kalajian writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
