<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ We've been hearing lately just what a tin ear
some over-eager religionists have for the harmonies that are
necessary to keep this religiously diverse nation humming.
Especially egregious is the declaration of a proselytizing war by
Southern Baptists on Jews during this season of the Jewish high
holy days. (Teepen, Cox Newspapers.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Some Cuban exiles like to boast that Miami
was a sleepy little town until they got here beginning in 1960 _ it
was far more advanced than they like to think _ but what has
happened in the last three decades is that Miami's politics has
fallen under the control of a cabal, elected and self-appointed.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ I never understood why the cotton swabs
were in the top of the aspirin bottle, except as little symbols of
stability in a changing world. I felt care was being taken for a
good cause I could not fathom. Such steps will no longer be taken.
I'm on my own now, a little lonelier, a little more frightened.
Progress. (Rosenfeld, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The young man standing
beside Pastor Dan never looked so tall or handsome before. He is my
son. The gentleman to his left, his best man, used to be my
husband. I've known both of them a very long time. I couldn't help
remembering that. The three of us had grown up together. (Schuett,
Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
