   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   DION _ A profile of the singer at 60 and at home in Boca Raton,
his rock 'n' roll memories, the movie Chazz Palmintieri is trying
to make of his life story, his belief in God, etc. (Passy, Palm
Beach Post) with art. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-GARDENS _ ATLANTA _ Public gardens around the country are
taking out life insurance policies _ in the form of activities and
exhibits designed to attract families. Children's gardens, such as
the one the Atlanta Botanical Garden unveils today, are aimed not
only at generating new revenue but at ensuring future generations
of gardeners will visit. To do that, gardens know they need more
than seeds and trowels to compete with computer games and MTV.
High-tech interactive exhibits designed to raise awareness about
the environment have become one strategy, and each children's
garden to open in the past few years has targeted its own niche. In
Atlanta, it's all about wellness, aimed at teaching children's how
plants affect their every day lives. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Includes a list of other new children's gardens.
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ A gardening column by Lee May. (May, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN-GALLERY _ You expect a children's garden to be over-run
with neon-colored displays and wacky sculptures. But a closer look
at the Atlanta Biotanical Garden's new two-acre kiddie attraction
reveals some sophisticated artwork crafted by area artisans using
forged steel, stainless steel and limestone. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) with PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-THEATER _ If you've been thinking of shelling out $10,000
on a new home theater system you're not alone. Home theaters, once
limited to mansions of the well-to-do, are now appearing in homes
near you _ those of middle-class consumers spending anywhere from
$2,000 for a simple 27-inch TV, VCR and recliner to $300,000 for a
state-of-the-art system with 9-foot screen, Dolby sound, DVD player
and theater-style seating. Some consumers say in the end it's worth
it considering all the distractions and hassel of actual
moviegoing. Find out what systems people are buying and why.
(Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) with COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
