<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH EDUCATION PROPOSAL RAISES QUESTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush has done as much as anyone
to make ``accountability'' the dominant education buzzword. And he
proposed raising the stakes with his plan, recently unveiled, to
take federal money from failing public schools.
</P>
<P>
   It is Bush's version, although the Republican presidential
front-runner is reluctant to admit it, of the federal government's
favorite tool for forcing state and local governments to comply
with its will: attach strings to federal dollars and threaten to
cut off the money if certain federally dictated conditions aren't
met.
</P>
<P>
   It has worked on numerous policies, from environmental
protection to highway speed limits and drunken-driving enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan is somewhat different because he wouldn't keep the
forfeited education Title I funds in Washington or transfer them to
another state.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he would let the parents of students in schools that
have been judged low-performing for three years in a row to use the
federal money to educate their children elsewhere, including at
charter or private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Political opponents, of course, immediately started taking shots
at the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused Bush of trying to establish a national voucher
system for private schools, and Republican detractors said Bush was
trying to do a very un-Republican thing _ promote Big Government
intrusion into the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   The latter criticism was of more immediate concern to Bush, and
it obviously was on his mind last week in a campaign swing through
southern New Hampshire, where he courted votes for that state's
crucial Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   At every stop, he took pains to reassure voters that he was
firmly for ``local control'' of public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``My education policy is, first and foremost, trust the people
of New Hampshire to make the right decisions (for their schools),''
he told a crowd at the Milford fire station.
</P>
<P>
   Even a group of fifth-graders in nearby Bedford heard the
``local control'' mantra at least twice during a brief visit by the
Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   If the youngsters didn't understand what their visitor was
talking about, Bush was confident that their teachers _ and media
covering the event _ did.
</P>
<P>
   Bush insisted that he wasn't dancing a sidestep from local
control with his proposed, new federal hammer over the public
schools. He said that was because he would have each state _ not
the federal government _ design its own student test to determine
which of its schools were passing or failing.
</P>
<P>
   But there are, nevertheless, some potential conflicts with local
control whenever the federal government intervenes in local or
state policies, even if the intervention is proposed by a strong
advocate of local control.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal, for one thing, would force some states to begin
evaluating the performances of their public schools. Although that
would be a good thing and serve to boost public accountability of
education tax dollars and maybe improve their schools, it would
remove some local control.
</P>
<P>
   And if states, influenced by their own political considerations,
set widely different standards for assessing the quality of their
local schools, pressure would inevitably increase for the federal
government to set a uniform standard. What would happen to local
control then?
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to vouchers _ which remains strong across the
country, including in Texas _ also may affect standards in some
states. So could concerns over higher taxes and any number of other
political and pocketbook factors.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that the educational failures that Bush and other
reformers are so strongly criticizing were, for the most part,
produced by educational systems designed, administered and funded
at the state and local levels.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean that the federal government could do a better
job. Far from it. But the very fact that Bush is proposing federal
intervention raises questions about his own confidence in the
accountability of local control.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Robison is chief of the Houston Chronicle's Austin Bureau and can
be reached at clay.robison(at)chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
