<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1431 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-TV-BARNHART16-KANSAS-     09-14 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BARNHART16-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEDIES ARE RISQUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON BARNHART  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Is it possible to describe even one scene from
this fall's hottest new comedy in a family newspaper?
</P>
<P>
   We're going to try.
</P>
<P>
   When comedian Jay Mohr first read through the script for
``Action''_ a raucous sitcom about life behind the scenes in
Hollywood _ he loved it. Then he called up Joel Silver, who as
executive producer of ``Action'' had offered Mohr the lead role,
and turned him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Joel, there's no way that what I read is going to be
on television,' '' said Mohr, a former ``Saturday Night Live''
player best known for playing Tom Cruise's nemesis in the film
``Jerry Maguire.''
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, Silver assured Mohr; Fox had already agreed to
green-light the script, even though it was full of obscenities. The
plan was to film the scenes, then simply bleep out any
objectionable words and use different camera angles so viewers
couldn't read the actors' lips.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like this had been tried before on network TV _ yet sure
enough, a second, Fox-approved script soon arrived, dirty words and
all. Mohr took the part.
</P>
<P>
   Though it is an extreme case, ``Action,'' which premieres
tonight, is not the only new sitcom this fall willing to risk the
wrath of viewers, and family-values watchdogs, in order to stand
out.
</P>
<P>
   Thus in CBS's ``Ladies' Man'' (premiering Sept. 20), also from
the creator of ``Action,'' an obnoxious Stephen Root declares his
envy of gay men because ``they have the best clothes ... and the
sex! The sex is phenomenal!''
</P>
<P>
   The ABC comedy ``Oh Grow Up'' (Sept. 22) features two straight
men living with a male friend who's recently come out of the closet
and is divorcing his wife. It's a premise the show's creator admits
would not have gotten on TV even five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The fall's only new animated series, ``Mission Hill'' on the WB
(Sept. 21), also promises to test the limits of broadcast
acceptability by exploring the sex lives of its post-college-aged
characters. The group's next-door neighbors, a gay couple in their
60's, may also raise some eyebrows; in their very first appearance,
they are seen making out in an elevator.
</P>
<P>
   No network, however, is pushing the envelope harder than Fox.
Doug Herzog, Fox's head of entertainment, was an executive at
Comedy Central for four years, where he was best known for
shepherding ``South Park,'' the raunchy cartoon that was the first
weekly series to earn a TV-MA rating (adults only). Like
``Action,'' ``South Park'' avoided the censor's pen by bleeping out
foul language.
</P>
<P>
   But for sheer sexual aggressiveness, nothing on ``South Park''
comes close to the dialogue of ``Action.''
</P>
<P>
   In it, Mohr plays an arrogant, hotheaded movie producer; Illeana
Douglas (``Grace of My Heart'') plays his current love interest and
a script-reader in Mohr's office; and Cindy Ambuehl plays Mohr's
ex-wife who happens to be married to his boss.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to watch a scene from ``Action'' filmed, as I
did last month, with the knowledge that viewers would hear none of
the choicer exchanges nor even see them mouthed. This is a point
Mohr likes to make with the show's critics: ``How do you know I'm
not just saying `biscuits and flapjacks'?''
</P>
<P>
   Trust me _ they don't say ``flapjacks.''
</P>
<P>
   In this scene, filmed for the second episode of ``Action,''
Douglas and Ambuehl are meeting for the first time:
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be difficult to work with such a small staff,''
Ambuehl says, using a thinly-veiled sexual metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas replies in kind. ``He tells me I'm the best he's ever
had in that position,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   You want insults? Ambuehl calls Douglas, in one word, a loose
woman. Douglas fires back, calling Ambuehl a ``skank.'' Ambuehl
calls Douglas, in one word, a female dog.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas looks at Ambuehl's cleavage and says: ``Who did your
(bleeps), Jack the Ripper?''
</P>
<P>
   Another line in the same scene would become a bone of contention
between Mohr and the episode's director, Byron Gordon. Mohr's line
was, ``Where the (bleep) am I supposed to come up with $50
million?''
</P>
<P>
   After several takes, in which Mohr varied the tone and ad lib of
the line, Gordon asked Mohr for one more take _ this time without
the curse word. Mohr refused and walked off the set.
</P>
<P>
   Back in his trailer, Mohr said he knew this was all part of an
elaborately silly tango with the network's word police.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game you play with censors. You have 18 four-letter
words but you really only need three. And you drop so many of them
that, hopefully, you take their attention away from the ones you
really need. I learned that at `Saturday Night Live.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But for some reason, omitting this one word stuck in Mohr's
craw.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the one percent chance that (scene) got in without the
swear word, and I saw it, I'd throw my TV set out the window and
probably walk off the show,'' said Mohr, adding, ``Then realize
what I was getting paid and come back.''
</P>
<P>
   But why so bothered over a line that won't be heard or (after
editing) seen? To Mohr, it's a creative issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm talking with my friends, I don't say, `Kiss my
behind, you doodyhead,' '' Mohr said. ``We want this show to
represent reality the way it really is.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's creator, Chris Thompson, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with doing a story about show business or rock and
roll is they always sound too phony because the meaty stuff is
always too wild for television,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   He should know. Thompson, a veteran producer who got his start
writing for the 1976 sitcom ``Sirota's Court,'' created ``Bosom
Buddies'' in 1980, a show best remembered for the unknown cast as
Peter Scolari's sidekick _ Tom Hanks.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson wrote the pilot of ``Action'' for HBO, since he assumed
no broadcast network would touch it. But when HBO hesitated over
money, Herzog told the producers he'd like to put it on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   As Thompson recalled it, ``Joel and I actually went to him and
said, `We don't think you can.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Herzog proved them wrong. Thompson is convinced that the
networks are embracing concepts like his because it's the only way
to keep up with cable, which continues to siphon viewers from the
broadcast side and is known for being more permissive on content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether this show succeeds or fails, it represents a pylon in
the bridge between broadcast and cable television,'' said Thompson.
``I imagine in 10 years you won't be able to tell the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay characters
</P>
<P>
   One of the most noticeable changes in TV comedy this season is
the predominance of gay characters _ the Gay and Lesbian Alliance
Against Defamation counted 28 of them _ and the acceptability of
gay storylines.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Ball, who created ``Oh Grow Up'' for ABC, said the industry
has two shows to thank for that: ``Ellen,'' which recreated its
star's real-life coming-out in an episode; and ``Will &AMP; Grace,''
last year's sitcom sensation, featuring two gay men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay characters have become less threatening, and I'm glad,''
said Ball, ``because otherwise it would be three guys living
together and dating three different women every week and it would
be boring. The house I lived in was a mixture of gay men and
straight men and you never see anything like that on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball based ``Oh Grow Up'' on his own shared-living experience
seven years ago while writing plays in Brooklyn, N.Y., as well as
on his own coming-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television has always changed, in what you're able to do and
what you're able to say,'' said Thompson. ``I watched that Olsen
Twins show (last season on ABC) and there were jokes on there we
couldn't have done on `Laverne &AMP; Shirley' when I was producing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the foreign sales of ``Action'' are any indication,
American TV has just begun to shock its audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've asked me to shoot more European versions,'' said
Thompson. ``We're literally being asked to spice it up for France
and the Balkan nations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
