<HEADER>
A1441 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-14 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POVERTY IN THE LAND OF PLENTY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The economy is booming. Jobs are everywhere.
Everybody's income is rising. So why do we feel so poor?
</P>
<P>
   Some statistics: In the San Francisco Bay Area, families earn 33
percent more than families in other parts of the country, but homes
cost four times the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Coming soon: Designer cardboard boxes for the middle-class
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Some feelings: A 30-year-old woman I know feels trapped in the
apartment she's rented for five years with two roommates. She hates
living like a college kid, but she pays only $500 a month and can't
afford to live alone with studios going for $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   The only way she can quit living with roommates and their
irritating habits is to get married to someone with a good income.
If they managed to buy a house, they wouldn't be able to fill it
with kids _ or even the standard Bay Area allotment of one kid _
because they'd both have to keep working to pay the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   This is an educated woman with a good income, yet she feels as
trapped in that apartment as any sharecropper ever did in the old
South.
</P>
<P>
   OK, she has one heck of a sharecropper's cabin, with hardwood
floors and a view of the Bay. But she has to share that view with
two roommates and whomever they invite over to drink all her wine.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal says that the Bay Area, with its
technology-driven economy, may be the leading edge of a national
trend. The Journal quoted Cornell economist Robert Frank, who said,
``Extra spending at the top raises the price of admission.''
</P>
<P>
   The price of admission around here is very steep. And man, is
there a lot of extra money to spend for those at the top.
</P>
<P>
   More statistics: Last year, the average corporate chief
executive made 419 times the earnings of the average worker. A
century ago the big boss made only 19 times as much as a worker,
and as recently as 1990 chief executive officers made ``only'' 85
times as much as workers.
</P>
<P>
   Even those of us who were lucky enough to buy a house 10 or 15
years ago _ when we thought they were overpriced at, say, $150,000
_ could sell those houses and make four times what we paid for
them. But we'd have to leave the Bay Area to find another home.
</P>
<P>
   There's no way we want to get into the Bay Area housing market
and have to bid against newly minted millionaires at Internet
companies. No stock options equals no options.
</P>
<P>
   We may look rich by the standards of the rest of America, but
we're just the new Bay Area proletariat.
</P>
<P>
   Workers in this world are chained to two incomes and homes and
apartments they can't afford to leave _ if they managed to get one
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Who ever thought class warfare would look like this? In West
Virginia and Illinois, there are plenty of thin, grimy coal miners
who have faced down fat, unscrupulous mine operators. There is
gritty old-fashioned exploitation in the Bay Area, too, but we also
have the peculiarly intense class warfare between those who drive
Honda Accords and those who drive BMW 7-series.
</P>
<P>
   Workers making 50 grand a year put on ties and go to their
neatly appointed cubicles (which may be bigger than their
apartments) and face inscrutable interoffice e-mail from the
28-year-old company president who says ``cool'' too much.
</P>
<P>
   Who ever thought a ruling class would look like this? Rich
people, the chief executives of Internet companies and their
investors, wear jeans and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   While the middle class tries to keep its homes neat, the upper
class is putting outhouses in front of their homes. The latest
status symbol is a Port-a-Potty for contractors building additions
to the family manse.
</P>
<P>
   The rich people, driven from their homes by contractors (the
rich's particular tormentors), are trying to run us off the road
with their $50,000 SUVs while they're on the car phone making a
reservation to eat a $26 piece of fish.
</P>
<P>
   The class warfare is intense, and the only way Bay Area workers
without stock options can cast off their chains is if they arise
and move to El Paso, Iowa City or Providence.
</P>
<P>
   No, forget Providence. Even my pleasantly seedy hometown in
Rhode Island is getting too expensive, and now has its own TV shows
and movies, just like San Francisco. Some parts of Providence even
have yuppies sitting on the sidewalk drinking caffe lattes.
</P>
<P>
   You can't go home again, contrary to what they say on
``Providence,'' the show.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, who'd want to leave a region with our sense of art and
partying, anyway? ``Party Down,'' a sculpture made partly from a
12-pack of empty Corona bottles, was part of an exhibition at the
California College of Arts and Crafts _ until last weekend, when a
janitor took the bottles to a recycling center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a drag,'' said artist L.G. Williams, ``because it took me
a whole afternoon last week to empty all those bottles.''
</P>
<P>
   The coordinator of the exhibition rushed out to a liquor store,
and the artist went back to work.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
