<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
Sept. 15. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   LEAD: Lead poisoning of children always has been a problem in
Kansas City, but it's only been in the past couple of years that
health authorities have taken a really aggressive approach to
prevention. Armed with federal grant money, new equipment and
tougher laws, hundreds more children now are being tested, and
dozens of homes are being cleaned of lead. Health authorities have
had to work at changing attitudes of doctors, who didn't think lead
was still a problem. And they have had to seek out and train
contractors to do the remediation work. In some Kansas City zip
codes, as many as 26 percent of kids tested have high blood lead
levels, which can reduce IQ and cause learning disabilities, high
blood pressure and kidney damage. Graphics. Photos. Alan Bavley.
44.
</P>
<P>
   ABORT: If this year's abortion debate in Missouri has left you
mystified, you're not alone: The two sides seem to talk past each
other, claiming hidden meanings, evil agendas and tortured
reasoning behind the wording of House Bill 427. The bill, the focal
point of the legislature's annual veto session that begins
Wednesday, bans a procedure known as partial-birth abortion by
defining it as child-killing. But that is the only point of
agreement between supporters of the bill, led by the Missouri
Catholic Conference, and Gov. Mel Carnahan, who vetoed it in July.
Kit Wagar. 25. Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EVE (with ABORT): Last-minute maneuverings in Jefferson City
have lawmakers talking about working through the weekend on the
veto session and a special session to consider an alternative
abortion bill. Meanwhile, both sides are scrambling for votes at
the last minute. Will Sentell. 15.
</P>
<P>
   FAR: We are looking for Missouri officials' reaction to the
Michael L. Farris case. State probabtion officers knew Farris had
cut his electronic monitor on Aug. 9, but it took nearly a month
for them to ask for an arrest warrant. During that time, Farris
allegedly murdered an elderly KC woman. We're talking to the
governor, attorney general and state representatives. Matt Campbell
and Will Sentell. 15.
</P>
<P>
   TEN. Those wacky Kansans just can't get through the day without
arguing about religion, it seems; in Manhattan, Kan., the debate
has gone on for months over the Ten Commandments, specifically as
inscribed on a five-foot-tall piece of granite that once stood
outside City Hall; the City Commission has re-inflamed passions by
agreeing to settle a lawsuit challenging display of the
commandments; the council has promised to never again place them on
public property and will pay $12,000 in legal costs for two
out-of-town activist organizations; now the issue may be headed for
a special election; ``We just can't keep talking about this,''
laments Mayor Roger Reitz, who voted for the settlement. John A.
Dvorak. 27.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   AGA _ The American Gaming Association opens its annual
convention. The association releases a new study that profiles
demographics and attitudes of the American gambler. By Rick Alm
</P>
<P>
   GLEN _ A rural Missouri banker who had a longrunning battle with
the FDIC has sued a UMB affiliate in Springfield that started it
all. But the real battle, once again, is between the banker and the
FDIC. By Charles R.T. Crumpley
</P>
<P>
   HEASTER _ Jerry Heaster column on the overworked,
underappreciated American worker.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   CARVER: More and more, the most important question in boxing
these days is, how can referees and ringside doctors tell when a
fighter is in trouble. Too many boxers have died recently after
appearing to be fine only moments before. Are fights being watched
closely enough and are enough of them getting stopped? David Boyce.
25-30.
</P>
<P>
   WHIT. Jason Whitlock column: Who's at fault in the Carver
tragedy?
</P>
<P>
   POZ. Joe Posnanski column: Why doesn't boxing ever get the
blame?
</P>
<P>
   CHIEFS. After the Chiefs' season-opening loss to Chicago,
Gunther Cunningham promised to get more involved in coaching. Does
that mean he's disappointed in Kurt Schottenheimer and his old
buddies on defense? Randy Covitz. 16-18.
</P>
<P>
   GYMFEAT. Feature on Wednesday's beginning to the World Team
Trials in gymnastics. Howard Richman. Photos
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. Anaheim at Kansas City, 7:05 p.m. Dick Kaegel. 16-18.
</P>
<P>
   MUFT. Julian Jones will get, on average, about two hours of
sleep per night this week. That's normal, for Jones, who has been a
chronic insomiac for years. But although just a junior, he is the
guy who has to call the formations for the secondary and in Western
Michigan's passing attack faces the ultimate test of his MU career.
18-22. Mike DeArmond. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   TV-BARNHART16-KANSAS (LOS ANGELES) _ Is it possible to describe
even one scene from this fall's hottest new comedy in a family
newspaper?
</P>
<P>
   We're going to try.
</P>
<P>
   When comedian Jay Mohr first read through the script for
``Action''_ a raucous sitcom about life behind the scenes in
Hollywood _ he loved it. Then he called up Joel Silver, who as
executive producer of ``Action'' had offered Mohr the lead role,
and turned him down. 1300 words. By AARON BARNHART. Story will move
in the ``e'' category. RELEASE DATE THURSDAY, SEPT. 16
</P>
<P>
   TV-BARNHART12-KANSAS _ The new fall TV shows are here. It's the
moment you've all been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   Well, most of you have been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   Some of you?
</P>
<P>
   Sitting down to sample the new network offerings used to be a
September ritual in most American homes. But the multiple-TV home,
and cable television, may have put an end to that. According to
research from USA Networks, the combined audience for the six
broadcast networks during ``premiere week'' has been falling
steadily and will dip below 50 percent in 2000 or 2001. 1300 words.
By AARON BARNHART. Story will move in the ``e'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
