<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT 3COM FACES A TOUGH NEW COMPETITOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While the 3Com Corp. spins off its popular Palm
handheld computer division, it will be fighting off a challenge
from an upstart portable computing manufacturer, headed by the same
people who invented the Palm technology.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara-based 3Com announced Monday that it was spinning off
the division that manufactures the Palm line of small hand-held
organizers, called Personal Digital Assistants, or PDAs. Meanwhile,
Handspring Inc. of Mountain View is unveiling its ``Visor'' line of
PDAs.
</P>
<P>
   The Visor is based on the 3Com software that powers the original
Palm PDAs. It easily lets a user handle a digital phone book,
expense records, calendar and the like.
</P>
<P>
   That software, called an operating system or OS, is responsible
for the success of the Palm, 3Com's ubiquitous gray handheld
organizer that dominates the portable computing market.
</P>
<P>
   There have been more than 5 million Palm devices sold to date, a
number that accounts for 70 percent of the hand-held computer
market.
</P>
<P>
   3Com, in an effort to become the Microsoft of portable
computing, has licensed the Palm OS to rival makers of personal
organizers.
</P>
<P>
   The first serious challenge to the Palm's dominance using that
Palm OS is Handspring, which was founded by the creators of the
PalmPilot, the original Palm PDA model.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a competitor and a partner,'' said Donna Dubinsky, the
chief executive of Handspring. Dubinsky and Handspring Chairman
Jeff Hawkins invented and marketed the first Palm Pilot in 1996 for
U.S. Robotics, which was later acquired by 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our use of the Palm OS is very supportive of 3Com,'' she said.
``We could've gone ahead and used someone else's software.''
</P>
<P>
   The Visor is a formidable Palm rival. It is lighter and slightly
more compact than the Palm IIIs, though it is bulkier than the
sleek, brushed-aluminum Palm V.
</P>
<P>
   The device is available in a range of translucent candy colors,
like the popular iMac manufactured by Apple Computer Inc. of
Cupertino.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the Visor will be significantly less than the Palm
series. Handspring says the new device will retail for $149 to
$249, while the 3Com units cost from $229 for the Palm IIIe to $449
for the Palm V. 3Com's newest PDA, the Palm VII, costs $599 but is
only available in limited markets.
</P>
<P>
   What sets the Visor apart from its Palm competitors is its
so-called ``Springboard'' slot that will allow the device to hook
into two-way pagers, cell phones or digital-music MP3 players. The
Visor will only be available on the company's Web site, and will be
available on store shelves early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing remotely similar,'' said Dubinsky, who added
that the development of the device began in October 1998. ``That's
extremely fast for something that's never been built before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Visor challenge won't go unmet. 3Com is expected to
introduce a new and inexpensive line of Palm PDAs later this year,
offering a translucent candy-colored iMac shell similar to the
iMac.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
