<HEADLINE>
A HUGE SPLASH IN THE DESERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ruling family of Dubai certainly thinks big. Last Wednesday,
the sheiks not only made the world's richest race richer by raising
the purse of the Dubai World Cup from $4 million to $6 million, but
also added an undercard for the March 25 event worth another $6
million. The Emirates Racing Association, headed by defense
minister Sheik Mohammad al-Maktoum, has, in effect, inaugurated its
own Breeders' Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The Breeders' Cup card, which will be held at Gulfstream Park
Nov. 6, offers eight races worth a total of $13 million, with the
$4 million Classic anchoring the program. Dubai World Cup Day now
offers seven races worth $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Dubai Duty Free, previously run at 1 1/4 miles on the dirt
(as are both the Cup and the Classic), has been switched to 1 1/8
miles on the turf, and the purse was raised from $500,000 to $2
million. The Dubai Turf Classic, raced at 1 1/2 miles, has been
renamed the Dubai Sheema Classic, and its purse raised from
$500,000 to $2 million. The Nad al-Sheba Sprint has been renamed
the Dubai Golden Shaheen, and is up from $250,000 to $1 million.
Added to the program are the $500,000 United Arab Emirates Derby,
on the dirt for 3-year-olds at 1 1/8 miles; the $250,000 Godolphin
Mile, on the dirt; and the $250,000 Dub Kahayla Classic, which is
for Arabian horses over a mile and one-16th.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the fifth running of the Dubai World Cup. The big
race has been the sole major attraction, and only the connections
of handicap horses who could handle dirt were interested in
shipping over. Now, turf horses will be enticed by both the Duty
Free and Sheema Classic; while sprinters, who usually run for
relatively short money, will be scrambling to enter the Golden
Shaheen. Now that Sheik Mohammad's Godolphin Stable is interested
in the Kentucky Derby (they took their first shot this year with
Worldly Manner, who finished seventh), the UAE Derby will serve as
a major prep for the Godolphin Triple Crown hopefuls, plus anyone
else who cares to participate.
</P>
<P>
   What Sheik Mohammad has done is take a one-race wonder _ The Cup
_ and turn it into an international day of racing, second (?) only
to the Breeders' Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mission given to us by His Highness Sheik Mohammad bin
Rashid al-Maktoum and his brothers is one of excellence,'' said Les
Benton, chief executive of the Emirates Racing Association. ``Our
intention is not only to create one of the most significant days of
racing anywhere in the world, but also to make this highly
competitive range of championship races appealing to racing
enthusiasts and viewers around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words: ``Think big.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Run, `Forest,' run
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? Trainer Bob Baffert has another star on his hands.
As if Baffert's barn, which includes such standouts as
Silverbulletday, General Challenge, and Forrestry, isn't powerful
enough, Forest Camp emerged to capture the Grade II $250,000 Del
Mar Futurity in a dazzling performance last Wednesday. Baffert was
so strong at Del Mar that he became the first trainer to sweep all
five Grade I races during the meeting, and he conditioned three of
the five starters in the Futurity. But it was Forest Camp, a son of
Deputy Minister, who came through with flying colors. Now 2 for 2,
Forest Camp took the lead passing the three-eighths pole, and drew
away to a victory of nearly 6 lengths in the time of 1:21 3/5 for 7
furlongs. ``He improved a whole bunch,'' said rider David Flores.
``We wanted to get him to relax and he did. He could be any kind.
He's amazing.'' Baffert has now won the Del Mar Futurity four
consecutive years, and he pronounced Forest Camp his ``most
impressive winner.'' Baffert said he will mull over where the
promising juvenile will start next . . . Saratoga, which closed a
36-day stand last week, had another sensational meeting. The
average on-track handle was $3,110,265, up 5.4 percent, and the
average attendance was 25,562, up 3.7 percent. Jerry Bailey won the
riding title with 47 winners, while Bill Mott led the trainers with
16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pitching in for Baez
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox and Boston radio station WEEI will sponsor a
luncheon Friday to benefit the Rudy Baez Assistance Fund. Baez,
long the top jockey in New England, was paralyzed from the waist
down when he was thrown from his mount in a race at Rockingham Park
Aug. 4. He is undergoing rehabilitation at a clinic in New Jersey.
The luncheon will be held at 12:30 p.m. at the 600 Club at Fenway
Park, and is being billed as ``Lunch with Pedro.'' Ace hurler Pedro
Martinez is from the Dominican Republic, as is Baez, and he is
pitching in to help out. Tickets, which are limited to 50, cost
$1,000 each. They can be obtained by calling Eddie Andelman, the
WEEI talk-show host who is a racing fan and originated the idea, at
617-375-8065, or John Ramsay, marketing director at Suffolk Downs,
at 617-568-3313. Baez lives in Wakefield, Mass. with his wife,
Judy, and he has three children, Camilla, Jessica, and Christopher.
Funds are needed to remodel his house to accommodate his condition.
Donations of any amount can be sent to: Rudy Baez Assistance Fund
c/o Eastern Bank. Attn: Rachael Sosnowski, 125 Washington St., Box
309, Salem 01970 . . . Suffolk will show the Oscar De La Hoya-Felix
Trinidad bout from Las Vegas Saturday. The card starts at 9 p.m.
and will be offered free on the second floor of the clubhouse. For
real boxing buffs, there will be a buffet dinner in the Turf Club
prior to De La Hoya-Trinidad honoring two top fighters of
yesteryear, Carmen Basilio and Tony DeMarco. In 1955, Basilio
stopped DeMarco, who is from the North End, in the 12th round of
two title bouts. Basilio and DeMarco will be on hand to comment on
the film of their battles. Tickets for the Basilio-De Marco dinner
are $60 and are available from the Valenti Ticket Agency at
617-227-9332 or from Suffolk at 617-567-3900.
</P>
