<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS MAKE FORTUNE-TELLING WORTHLESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ OK, here's my official 12-day notice: I'm
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. I'm done. There will be no more New England pro
sports predictions from me. I've even shredded my registered
Prediction Card. Making predictions here was always tricky, but
this year it has become impossible. Michael Jordan retired (the
first time) because he said he had nothing to prove; I am retiring
because the more I predict, the more I prove . . . nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Want to do me a favor? Please send all miscellaneous items _
including shuffleboard instructions and the famous ``DEWEY DEFEATS
TRUMAN'' headline _ to my new Florida residence. It is obvious that
the pro prediction game has passed me by.
</P>
<P>
   I know I am not alone. If you listened to people in March, you
would have thought the Red Sox were the 1990s version of the '62
Mets. And if you were listening three days ago, the Patriots and
Pete Carroll were going to have to play their best to beat up on
(St.) Bill Parcells and the Jets. In fact, the Jets of three days
ago were the first team in pro football history to secure a spot in
the conference championship game by September.
</P>
<P>
   All of that is understandable. The local sports prediction
business has become craftier and developed a wicked sense of humor.
So what appears to be obvious really is not. You look at a Red Sox
team that has lost Mo Vaughn and figure there is no way the team
will be able to compete for the top spot in the American League
East. You see the Pats lose two of their starting linebackers from
last season and guess that Parcells will target that area to gain a
Week 1 win.
</P>
<P>
   I'm afraid to guess what's next. Antoine Walker, Rick Pitino,
and David Stern hoisting a championship banner to the ceiling of
the FleetCenter next spring?
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the previous statement was not a prediction. I am
retired. After Sept. 26 _ the date the Pats play the Giants at
Foxboro Stadium _ there will be no more local predictions from me.
Ask me how many games the Carolina Panthers will win this season
and I will answer, ``Six.'' Ask me what the Sox will be doing in
late October and I'll shrug, ``I don't know. What? Celebrating
their World Series win?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I'm going to enjoy retirement. I may even watch some of
those pregame shows where people sit around and predict the future.
I'll turn to my Shuffleboard Rotisserie League buddies and say, ``I
used to do that before I retired.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Patriots tackle Bruce Armstrong explained how
non-retirees get into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pregame shows have gone from 30 minutes, to 60 minutes, to 90
minutes,'' he said. ``We only play once a week, but there are five
or six days when people are analyzing football. That's good, but
there was a lot of talk about what we were going to do before we
even played a game. How many of those people watched us practice?
Nobody really knows what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   That is certainly the case with the Pats, on the field and off.
Really, who could have predicted that Carroll would have a better
coaching day than Parcells? Not only did Parcells lift a slightly
effective Tom Tupa for an ineffective Rick Mirer in the fourth
quarter, he endorsed his offensive coordinator's call to pass late
in the fourth quarter when he should have been running out the
clock. He pays Curtis Martin $6 million a season to run in
situations such as those, but he strangely put the game in the
hands of a shaky, seven-year backup.
</P>
<P>
   Since I am on my way to retirement, I won't tell you what fans
here would have said if Carroll had done what Parcells did.
</P>
<P>
   There had also been talk that Parcells knew a secret that
allowed him entry to Drew Bledsoe's psyche. That theory also joins
me in retirement, especially after Bledsoe's 21-of-30, 340-yard
performance. And don't forget the chatter that Carroll's poor
offseason conditioning program in '98 partly exlained his team's
rampant injuries. One week into the season, Parcells is now missing
his second-best receiver, lead kickoff returner, and starting
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't even the most puzzling aspect to Sunday's game.
The Jets rely on a solid zone defense, but the feeling on Sunday
was that the Pats could score any time they wanted. And, as
cornerback Steve Israel mentioned after the team's meetings Monday,
``We made a lot of mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this was not a case of a team playing far over
its head to get a win. The Pats did not look at themselves as
descendants of Joe Namath's Jets, shocking the sports world with a
win in Super Bowl III. They simply played a good game _ certainly
not great _ and won.
</P>
<P>
   And that brings us back to the predicting business. It is so
deceiving that it makes you forget what is in front of you. It
baits you into thinking exclusively about all the holes the Pats
have and distracts you from the man they didn't have in their final
three games last season: Bledsoe. As you know by now, I am retired.
But before I retired I realized that Bledsoe and Pedro Martinez
have a lot in common. You have either of them on your team and you
feel a lot better about yourself.
</P>
<P>
   More important for the Pats, the only player talking about Tuna
today will be Shawn Jefferson. Monday, the receiver held a fishing
pole near his locker. Tuesday morning, he was expecting to fish 25
miles outside of Provincetown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going tuna fishing,'' he said. He was not joking and did
not see the irony when someone tried to coax a quip out of him. Who
could have guessed that Jefferson would go tuna fishing after Tuna
Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   This business is crazy. So crazy that I would like to tell you
that the Bruins will be in trouble if they don't get Byron Dafoe
into camp soon. But, again, I'm retired. All I do now is watch the
games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0076 </DOCNO>
