</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FOLIAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT SHOULD BE A LOVELY SHOW IN NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let the show begin.
</P>
<P>
   Despite earlier gloomy reports on New England's annual foliage
show, it appears it will be colorful after all.
</P>
<P>
   Foliage is just part of the show. The season is perfect for
fairs, festivals, apple and pumpkin picking, hikes, white-water
rafting, canoe rides, and bicycle excursions.
</P>
<P>
   The fear this year was that the summerlong drought could cause a
more subdued color or the leaves peaking earlier and falling
faster. However, there is optimism for leaf peepers. While some
areas have been hit hard by the drought, the top foliage
destinations in New England _northern Vermont, New Hampshire, and
Maine _ have had enough rain to keep the leaves in good shape or
color.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forests in Maine are green, and from all indications, we
will have a beautiful fall foliage season,'' said Tom Doak, Maine
State Forest Service director. ``Crews did detect pockets of color
and that may indicate early color statewide. What that tells us is
that Maine trees will display fall color as expected,'' Doak said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mount Washington Valley in New Hampshire is reporting
above-average rainfall for the year, and is predicting brilliant
foliage hues through late October. ``We expect the full spectacle
of fall colors to delight us through a long and on-schedule fall
foliage season this year,'' said Janice Crawford, executive
director of the Mount Washington Valley Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The most frequently asked question at this time of year is,
``What day will the leaves turn color?'' ``We try not to predict
when the colors will be at their peak because Mother Nature has
ideas of her own,'' said Mary Jane McKenna, executive director of
the Massachusetts Office of Travel and Tourism. She adds,
``Visitors to Massachusetts should be less concerned about just how
spectular the leaves will be, and more concerned about getting a
(lodging) reservation.'' That advice is good throughout New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, though, Mother Nature does have a plan. Fall
colors begin in northern New England in mid-September, then slowly
head south, with the colors peaking in southern New Hampshire,
Maine, Vermont, the Berkshires and elsewhere in Massachusetts, and
the Connecticut border the first weeks of October.
</P>
<P>
   And, traditionally, the long Columbus Day weekend has been peak
viewing time throughout New England. The ``show,'' however, does
extend to the beginning of November. Connecticut likes to boast
that its geography makes it a perfect foliage destination. ``Just
as northern New England's fall foliage is winding down,
Connecticut's colors are getting ready for their big burst of
color,'' said Don Smith, Connecticut's Bureau of Forestry chief.
Smith adds that the show may be earlier because of the summer
drought. ``Columbus Day weekend is my recommendation for a foliage
outing _ I don't think you'll go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason New England's display of color is so good is that the
region is blessed with an abundance of deciduous forests, ample
rainfall, and favorable weather. Connecticut's Smith notes that,
according to Native American legend, ``Celestial hunters slew the
Great Bear autumn, and the spilled blood turned the leaves red. The
yellow of fall came from the fat splattering out of the kettle as
the hunters cooked their prize.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today how fall colors occur is often misunderstood. ``Many
people who call for foliage information believe trees start
producing different colors in the fall,'' said Susan Benson,
director of information for the Maine Department of Conservation.
``Perhaps that's why folks though the drought would devastate the
foliage color, and that just is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson, who is known in Maine as the ``leaf lady,'' said the
factors that influence autumn color include wind, rainfall, sugar
accumulations in the trees, and prolonged periods of cool, bright,
sunny fall weather without a killing frost. In summertime, the
leaves of Maine hardwoods _ such as white birch, red oak, and sugar
maple trees _ contain green, yellow, orange, and red pigments.
Chlorophyll produced during photosynthesis gives leaves their green
color and masks the red, yellow, and orange pigments. When the days
get shorter, chlorophyll production declines. The red, yellow, and
orange pigments begin to show and, eventually, become dominant.
Purple and red shades result from the autumn production of another
group of pigments.
</P>
<P>
   Red leaves appear on red and white oak; yellow only _ quaking
aspen, birch, hickory, Norway maple, tulip tree; red or yellow _
cherry, red maple; brown or yellow _ silver maple; bronze _ beech;
bronze or red _ sugar maple and scarlet oak; purple or red _
dogwood; purple, red, or yellow _ ash; purple, red, yellow, or
orange _ sassafras and sumac.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is making it easier to see the foliage show without
leaving home. In Maine, those visiting the www.state.me.us foliage
site can view actual photos taken by parks staff as the color
blankets the hills and mountains of the state. The Foliage Photo
Gallery is updated on the Web every three to five days.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where you head this foliage season, you'll find lots
to do. Fairs and harvest festivals are everywhere, especially
Columbus Day weekend. Here is just a sampling of ideas:
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, take in the Oktoberfest and Food Festival with
microbrewers and international food vendors in Southwest Harbor on
Mount Desert Island Oct. 9; the Historical Society of Wells and
Ogunquit is having its 25th annual Antique Show and Sale Sept.
18-19 at the S. Judson Dunaway Center in Qgunquit; there's still
some great white-water rafting adventures to take in _ Dead River
water releases are set for Sept. 18 and Oct. 2 (call Raft Maine,
800-723-8633); World Puppets Portland, an international festival of
puppet theater, will be Oct. 1-3 (call 207-772-3952); Fall Living
History Days, Oct. 2-3, celebrating the lifestyles and crafts of
the 19th century, will be at the Maine Forest and Logging Museum in
Orono; the Fryeburg Fair, the largest agricultural fair in Maine,
runs Oct. 3-10; the seventh annual ``Chowdah'' Challenge will be
held Oct. 9 on the Town Hall lawn in Freeport.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, enjoy the Historic Tub Parade in Lenox on
Sept. 18; the event features carriages decorated with flowers and
harvest vegetables. The Taste of the Hills festival will be held
Sept. 24-25 by the Glacial Potholes in Shelburne Falls; The Norman
Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge opens an exhibition of contemporary
editorial illustrations Sept. 18 through Jan. 23, 2000; the 37th
annual Petersham Antiques Show &AMP; Sale is Oct. 9-10; enjoy some
guided walks through the Mohawk Trail State Forest the first two
weekends in October (call Zoar Outdoors at 800-532-7483, and ask
also about kayak, white-water rafting, and rock climbing); Hancock
Shaker Village will hold its Country Fair and Crafts Festival Sept.
25-26 in Pittsfield; and to prove you don't have to go far to enjoy
a fall treat, the Harvest Moon Celebration shines on Cambridge Oct.
3 with foods, farmers, storytelling and more, all at the Charles
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In Rhode Island, the Newport Harvest-by-the-Sea Festival offers
lots of family fun Oct. 1-31; Oktoberfest takes over the East
Providence City Hall Grounds Oct. 2; Plantation Days offers a
weekend of celebrations of Colonial times at the state's most
significant historic site, Smith's Castle in North Kingston Oct.
2-3; and the 23d Annual Harvest Festival and Apple Pie Contest,
complete with jonnycakes and clamcakes, will be Oct. 3 at South
County Museum in Narragansett.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, the World's Fair returns to Tunbridge Sept. 16-19,
while in Stowe, it's the 9th annual British Invasion (car show);
Sept. 16-20; Vermont Archaeology Week is Sept. 19-25 (for details,
call 802-656-4310).
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, take in the Oct. 9-11 Walking Weekend where you
can choose from 50 roads in the northeastern part of the state
(call 888-628-1228); the Great Teddy Bear Jamboree, the largest on
the East Coast, runs Oct. 16-17 in Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, the Settlers' Green Outlet Village is having
its third annual Fall Festival with music, contests, and 50
life-sized scarecrows Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   A luxurious way to view the trees and take in a great rail
experience is aboard the Great Train Escapes foliage tour via rail
and motorcoach traveling from Boston to Maine, through New
Hampshire, Vermont, down to Connecticut, and to Cape Cod. For
information, call 888-544-RAIL. Prices begin at $1,999 a person.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHERE TO FIND THE LEAVES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's where to call for the latest foliage reports. Most
foliage reports are updated at least twice weekly.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire _ 800-258-3608 or 800-262-6660; on the Web,
www.visitnh.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont _ 802-828-3239; www.1-800-vermont.com.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts _ 800-227-MASS; www.massvacation.com.
</P>
<P>
   Maine _ 800-777-0317; www.state.me.us or www.visitmaine.com.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut _ 800-282-6863, ext. 88; www.ctbound.org.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee magazine offers a ``one-stop'' viewing of foliage around
New England as well as driving and walking tours and more. Visit
www.NewEngland.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
