<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1499 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HIGH-SPEED-TRAIN-BOS &LR;      09-14 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-SPEED-TRAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIL LOVERS WANT HIGH-SPEED TRAIN _ FAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Dukakis, the former Massachusetts governor and longtime
rail junkie, knew all about Amtrak's reputation for sluggishness,
but he swore this time it would be different. As much as anyone, he
wanted to take a train to New York City and Washington rather than
an airplane shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a satisfying trip to Washington in my last nine
trips,'' Dukakis, who is on Amtrak's board of directors, told a
transportation group in May. And he delighted in the idea that he
wouldn't have to wait much longer for high-speed service. ``The
Northeast Corridor will begin this fall, no foolin,' '' he pledged.
``October or November.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was then.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers in Pueblo, Colo., testing the first of 20 new Acela
high-speed trains, this summer discovered excessive wear on the new
wheels after the train went around curves. Ten days ago, they
reluctantly postponed the debut of long-awaited, 150-mile-per-hour
service to New York until spring _ maybe longer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, skeptics have begun the chorus of ``I told you so'' and are
questioning whether revitalized Northeast Corridor service,
whenever it happens, will live up to its billing, including
providing the revenue that will help Amtrak avoid bankruptcy and
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Amtrak's promises, many had suspected the nation's
largest passenger rail company, a debt-ridden, 29-year-old business
with a can't-do-anything-right reputation, wouldn't be ready with
high-speed rail by the end of 1999. A firm date won't be announced
until early November.
</P>
<P>
   The delay disappointed Dukakis and thousands of others who are
eager to trade driving, parking, riding a bus, flying, and long,
costly cab rides from the airport for a nostalgic mode of travel
whose time, they hope, has returned in America.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a fast train with comfortable seats, decent food,
and spacious, office-like work areas, one that runs on time and
arrives in the middle of its destination cities _ not a 45-minute
traffic jam away.
</P>
<P>
   Although it will cost a good deal more than the current $100
round-trip fare for a five-hour ride from Boston to New York,
frequent reliable service between the two cities is expected to cut
seriously into the airline industry's share of the Boston/New York
commuter market.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of rail advocacy groups interviewed last week
were universally sympathetic to Amtrak, and understanding of the
decision to put off the debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the right call,'' said John Haley, ex-general
manager of the MBTA who is now New Jersey transportation
undersecretary. ``No question, this is such a huge undertaking it's
got to be done right.''
</P>
<P>
   That means at least several more months of tweaking and
replacing parts in the so-called trucks, the steel frames that hold
the wheels of the new Acela (pronounced ah-CELL-ah) coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The all-new train, originally designated the Metroliner but
given a new name to connote excellence and acceleration, was
designed by the French company Alstom and built by the Canada-based
Bombardier.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that the trucks, rigid enough to allow a smooth
ride on long, straight stretches at up to 150 miles per hour, were
too stiff for the give-and-take necessary on curved portions of the
track.
</P>
<P>
   Gaetan Roy, manager of truck systems for Bombardier, said the
wheels presented a ``little more serious problem'' than anything
expected in the trial period, which began in May. They had thought
May through December would be long enough to resolve any problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking at fine-tuning the elements of the suspension
system,'' Roy said. Amtrak and Acela's designer and manufacturer
will battle it out later who is responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem, apparently discovered during the assembly
process, is that clearance distances between tracks on curves will
not allow the train's ``tilting'' mechanism to move to its full
5.6-degree position.
</P>
<P>
   The tilt gives passengers a comfortable ride even around curves
at high speeds. Bombardier officials said that, while the tilt
restriction will mean people will feel more centrifugal force, it
won't keep the trains from meeting their three-hour goal between
Boston and New York.
</P>
<P>
   James RePass, president of the National Corridors Initiative
(formerly the Northeast Corridor Initiative), gives Amtrak high
marks for having the guts to postpone. ``In the past, Amtrak would
have one train in December, a Potemkin train,'' RePass said.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak president George D. Warrington, RePass said, ``showed
real leadership'' by taking time to make sure things work. ``The
bottom line is they didn't anticipate every problem, because no one
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Davis, who is on the board of the National Association of
Rail Passengers and also president of Train Riders Northeast, said,
``I'm glad they found the problem out during testing rather than
having to take it out of service _ but what an embarrassing thing
for Amtrak.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis toured the first new train ``sets,'' as they're called, at
a plant in New York. He called them ``exciting, luxurious.'' And he
is looking forward eagerly to 2000, as the Amtrak high-speed
service begins and, later in the year, intercity service is
extended from Boston to Portland, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year will really be the year of the train,'' he said,
though Davis has had numerous disappointments as Portland service
has been delayed and re-delayed. As one New Hampshire official
said, ``It's been two years away for 12 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak says in its promotional material that the Acela train
will ``change the face of travel in the Northeast United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of high-speed rail in the corridor is so important
that, to a large extent, the future of Amtrak rests on it. Amtrak
has estimated a positive impact of $400 million from new Northeast
Corridor service through 2002. Dukakis said Amtrak's estimate of
profits may even be conservative.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has a goal of weaning itself from government
subsidies by the year 2002, despite recent annual losses of $800
million, so it has a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   According to a July General Accounting Office report,
``uncertainty surrounds Amtrak's ability to achieve this.'' It said
much of the rail company's future is ``based on critical
assumptions . . . that have yet to be tested in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   All major intercity rail services in the world are subsidized.
Amtrak has received nearly $23 billion since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   If the Acela flies, and rail becomes the accepted way to go _ or
even just a popular alternative _ in the Northeast Corridor, other
regions of the country could follow along rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Two corridors in California and others in the Midwest, Pacific
Northwest, Southeast, and Gulf Coast are in planning stages or
early development.
</P>
<P>
   The Acela will offer two classes of express service between
Boston and Washington, with stops in Providence, New Haven, New
York, Philadelphia, and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   It will also operate slower service to Buffalo and Albany, N.Y.,
and Harrisburg, Pa.; between Springfield, Mass., and New Haven; and
from Washington to Richmond and Newport News, Va.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
