<HEADER>
A1508 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-SAID-SIDE-BOS &LR;      09-14 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-SAID-SIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE EXAGGERATION, BUT FORTHRIGHTNESS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Justus Reid Weiner's `` `My Beautiful Old House' and
Other Fabrications by Edward Said,'' the lead article in the
September issue of Commentary magazine, has been making news on
four continents.
</P>
<P>
   Said, a Columbia University literature professor, is the leading
spokesman for the Palestinian cause in the United States. The Wall
Street Journal printed a lengthy excerpt from the Weiner article on
its op-ed page. The Daily Telegraph of London ran a Page 1 news
story. Two op-ed columns have appeared in the Globe. A rebuttal
from Said has had a wide circulation in the Arab press.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy concerns how much of the first 12 years of his
life Said spent in Palestine (the region of the Middle East that
comprises what is now Israel, Gaza, and the West Bank) and the
extent to which he may have misrepresented his upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   Two facts are not in dispute. Said was born in Jerusalem on Nov.
1, 1935, and his family left there late in 1947, several months
before Palestine was partitioned to produce Israel and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Weiner, a specialist in international law who is a scholar in
residence at the Jerusalem Center for Public Affairs, clearly shows
that Said and his family spent most of his boyhood in Cairo. (An
article in the Jan. 16, 1998, issue of The Jerusalem Post Magazine
made similar allegations.)
</P>
<P>
   An examination of Said's writings indicates, however, that he
has never concealed his background. Such a statement as ``I was
born in Jerusalem and spent most of my formative years there,''
from a 1998 London Review of Books article, is clearly an
exaggeration. But he details his Cairo upbringing in his
just-published memoir, ``Out of Place,'' as well as in a 1987 House
and Garden article and refers to it in a 1992 interview published
in ``Edward Said: A Critical Reader.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiner also calls into question a number of statements Said has
made concerning his time in Jerusalem, such as having attended St.
George's, an Anglican preparatory school. Haig Boyadjian, who
attended the school at the time Said says he did, confirmed in a
recent telephone interview from his New Jersey home that Said was a
classmate. ``He was the brightest boy in the class, several classes
running,'' said Boyadjian.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is libel,'' Said said of the article during a recent
interview at his Columbia office. ``(Weiner) got everything wrong.
Basic things: He didn't know the relationships between various
members of my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiner, speaking in a telephone interview from Jerusalem,
dismissed Said's rebuttal. ``First, he says all of his childhood,
now it's 50-50 between Jerusalem and Cairo. It reminds me of
Filene's Basement: You go down there and there's a coat you want,
so you wait two weeks and it gets marked down 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Said supporters nor detractors are likely to feel
satisfied by the debate. They can look forward to its continuation.
Weiner said he has three other articles on Said in the works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1510 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-STEWART-BOS     09-14 1731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-STEWART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYNE HAS MADE GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Start with the knickers. They're such a
glaring part of his persona, where else to begin with Payne
Stewart?
</P>
<P>
   As the story goes, early in his career, Stewart was on the
practice range when he looked around and saw players all dressed
the way he was. That bothered him, and he wanted a look that would
make him stand out from his colleagues, one that would give him an
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Consider him easily identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of his mystique,'' says Mark Lye, a former PGA Tour
player who now is part of the television team at The Golf Channel.
``But the funny part is, when he takes them off and puts on jeans
and a hat, no one recognizes him. So they don't piss him off when
he goes out and has dinner. I think he likes that.''
</P>
<P>
   But as much as he enjoys dining in peace, Stewart craves
attention on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he didn't want to be noticed, why would he wear the
plus-fours? Why would he want to be on the Ryder Cup team?'' says
Lye. ``You have to want the attention to be in the arena he's in.''
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight follows those in pursuit of golf championships,
and it intensifies greatly when the events are majors. Very few
players in our time have stood on this stage as frequently as
Stewart, now in its 18th year on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   He has succeeded gloriously on a few occasions. He has failed
miserably in many more. That is the harsh reality about pro golf,
though Stewart _ 11 times a winner _ has had to deal with more
scrutiny than most because of the numbers that sit on his resume:
25 times a runner-up, 19 times third, 130 times Top 10. The US
Opens of 1986 (he melted when Ray Floyd fixed the stare), 1993 (he
couldn't overcome Lee Janzen's good fortune), and 1998 (he lost his
swing over the weekend) are the tournaments his critics will point
to quickly, but Stewart has survived and through it all one thing
has stood out about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never met anyone more honest, I can tell you that about
Payne Stewart,'' says Chuck Cook, Stewart's swing coach. ``He'll
tell you exactly what he's thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   A sports columnist discovered this during a visit to ``Golf Talk
Live'' on The Golf Channel last winter. It seems the columnist had
written a critical piece about Stewart following the 1998 US Open,
and now the golfer had a chance for rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   So Stewart dialed. And he asked, ``Do you know me? Have you ever
met me?''
</P>
<P>
   What followed were a few icy moments, though Stewart never lost
his composure and eventually got the reporter to agree it was a
hastily written column that never should have been filed. Stewart
had made his point, and a short time later the two met face-to-face
and made peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all fine after that,'' says Stewart. ``I just felt he
should have talked to me before writing what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stewart played on Ryder Cup teams in 1987, '89, '91, and '93. He
loved every second of it, embraced the team concept, and would have
waved pompoms if they were in his golf bag.
</P>
<P>
   Then the show went on without him in 1995. And 1997, too. Both
times he felt he could have been a captain's selection, but he was
in front of his TV instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you, it wasn't a lot of fun,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Not only wasn't he playing, but the team was losing, and a
nation's pride was taking a beating. Stewart is a guy who puts his
hand over his heart and belts out the national anthem, so you could
say he takes this red-white-and-blue stuff seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such an honor to play for your country,'' he says. ``It's
a passion with me. It's the most intense golf I've ever played.''
</P>
<P>
   Hokey, you say? Stewart doesn't care. He was raised in America's
heartland _ Springfield, Mo. _ and his pursuit of a pro golf career
took him to corners of the globe you probably did not know existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have played all over the world and seen awful living
conditions,'' he says. ``I am thankful for what we have in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   What he now has is something he covets _ another spot on the
Ryder Cup team. It's a chance to help the US win for the first time
since 1993, which happens to be the last time he played.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm a rah-rah person,'' says Stewart. ``If I'm
teamed up in whatever I'm playing in and I have a partner, boy, I'm
going to be in his ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people ask me what my record is, I say it's 2-1-1. That's
my record. As a team we've won twice, lost once, tied once.
Individual records don't matter. It's a team effort. Players and
people have to understand that. That's what a veteran like myself
can bring to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   If that indeed is what he's bringing, he's doing so for one
reason _ he earned it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't rely on (US captain Ben) Crenshaw to pick me, so
that's been the driving force for me,'' says Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   He knew that what probably worked against him in 1995 and 1997
was his reputation for not getting the job done. The '86 and '93
Opens. The double-bogey at the final hole of the 1985 Byron Nelson
that dropped him into a playoff, which he lost to Bob Eastwood.
Shots into the water late in singles losses in the 1989 and 1991
Ryder Cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning golf is an out-of-body experience,'' says Lye, who has
known Stewart since the early 1980s. ``If you're not able to stay
in the zone, it's hard to hang on. Payne had trouble staying in the
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   No argument, says Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne is a feel player, 100 percent feel,'' says Cook. ``But
he always lacked structure. Dick Coop gave him some structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart began working with Coop, a sports psychologist, in the
late 1980s, and it was Coop who suggested Cook as a swing coach.
They made for a pretty good team as Stewart posted two wins in
1989, including his first major (the PGA), two more in 1990, and
one in 1991 _ the US Open.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the critics attacked. Mike Reid blew the PGA, they said,
and Scott Simpson handed Stewart the US Open.
</P>
<P>
   A morsel of truth was in there, perhaps, though the gleam of his
championship hardware was what most people saw. That is, until he
changed equipment and began chasing appearance money all over the
golfing world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went to the wrong ball and the wrong equipment,'' says
Cook.
</P>
<P>
   After switching from a wound ball to a solid ball, Stewart went
winless in 1992-94 and plummeted to 123d on the money list. Though
Scott Hoch gift-wrapped a victory for Stewart at the 1995 Houston
Open, golf was not fun.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart didn't want to practice, barely wanted to compete, and
couldn't for the life of him figure out what was going on when he
hit the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Kemper one week, he had 180 yards and a 6-iron,'' says
Cook, ``He hit it 60 yards over the green. 240 yards! Then he goes
to the British Open and has 135 yards to go and he hits 6-iron into
the wind and barely hits 110 yards into the burn.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a feel player, he had to be asking, `Why?' But the ball
spun too much and the club spun too much.''
</P>
<P>
   And Stewart's career spiraled downward.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Start with the knickers if you like, but Lye also remembers
Stewart for the needles in the ears. A hypnotist had suggested them
to calm Stewart during pressure situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ironic,'' says Lye, ``because you could say his game has been
held together by pins and needles.''
</P>
<P>
   He means this in a flattering way, for Lye admires Stewart for
doing so much in a sport that features more gifted players.
</P>
<P>
   ``A classic overachiever, I think,'' says Lye, who not only
competed against Stewart but shared the stage with him, too. They
and Peter Jacobsen formed ``Jake Trout and the Flounders,'' a
for-fun rock band that cut an album.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne played the harmonica,'' says Lye. ``At first he was
reluctant because he didn't want it to interfere with his golf
game. But he liked it. We all did.''
</P>
<P>
   Lye and Stewart were also on the Titleist staff in the early
1980s, along with Hal Sutton and Donnie Hammond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne always said that Hal Sutton was the best player,'' says
Lye, ``but (Titleist's) Joe Turnesa would then tell us that Payne
told him he was going to win the British Open that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he had it in his mind that he would win a major
championship and he conned himself into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Three times now, thanks to his second US Open triumph, this past
June at Pinehurst No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   It was an epic performance for two reasons: It came after his
heartache at The Olympic Club in 1998, when Stewart squandered a
four-shot lead through 54 holes and finished second, and it
culminated his oft-stated goal of returning to the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   At an age (42) when most of his colleagues were content to slide
into a more comfortable lifestyle and avoid the grind, Stewart in
1999 had done the opposite _ he had put himself in the pressure
cooker. He wanted on the Ryder Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   The victory at Pinehurst may have sealed his Top 10 spot, but
two contributing factors paved the way, says Cook:
</P>
<P>
   ``His kids (Chelsea, 13; Aaron, 10) introduced him to religion.
They are raising him religously. And his faith definitely had
something to do with his win.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the dress rehearsal at Pinehurst that Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked the course and marked it (in our minds),'' says
Cook. ``Payne said, `Let's mark it in red,' but I said, `I don't
want to scare you,' so we marked it in blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``And do you know that he hit into that blue area only once all
week _ when he was short right on No. 2 Sunday. Other than that he
never missed it in the wrong place.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was an Open he was poised to give away. His one-shot
lead to start the round had disappeared and Stewart trailed Phil
Mickelson through 15 holes. Then came arguably the greatest putting
performance under US Open pressure: a 25-footer to save par at 16,
a short birdie putt at 17 to regain the lead, then a gut-wrenching
20-footer to save par at 18 and win the US Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must have practiced that putt 150 times during the week,''
says Cook. ``He said to me, `They're gonna have the pin back there
one of these days.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So he practiced that putt. It looked like it would break left,
but it didn't. Payne knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Payne. The one who had the faith in himself to finish
the job.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing the old knickers, of course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1512 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-14 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POET OF MULTI-TASKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; You can't complain that journalists are ignoring the business
world these days.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Post columnist David Ignatius has published ``The Sun
King,'' a novel about a commodity trader who buys a newspaper quite
a lot like the old Washington Star in order to romance his college
sweetheart.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lewis next month will lead a trio of writers on Silicon
Valley with his ``The New New Thing: A Silicon Valley Story,''
about the adventures of entrepreneur Jim Clark. Po Bronson (``The
Nudist on the Late Shift'') and David Kaplan (``The Silicon Boys
and Their Valley of Dreams'') are the others.
</P>
<P>
   Buyout king Bruce Wasserstein, surely the most financially
successful reporter the University of Michigan's Michigan Daily
ever produced, Wednesday in New York will roll out the first
edition of his Daily Deal, with Robert Teitelman, formerly of
Institutional Investor, as editor _ $750 a year unless you're on
the carefully controlled list of those who get it delivered first
thing in the morning for free.
</P>
<P>
   None of these is more interesting, however, than former New York
Times science reporter James Gleick. He shares with Michael Herr
(``Dispatches'') and Tom Wolfe (``Bonfire of the Vanities'') the
distinction of having captured between hard covers, at least for a
time, the pretensions of an age.
</P>
<P>
   Gleick started in the early 1980s with a famous magazine profile
of philosopher Douglas Hofstadter. He wrote (in four months) his
1987 bestseller ``Chaos: Making a New Science,'' about esoteric new
work by a community of physicists and mathematicians, then put the
physicist Richard Feynman on the cultural map in 1993 with an
artful biography, ``Genius.''
</P>
<P>
   Gleick then cofounded the Manhattan Internet service provider
Pipeline, later sold it for something like $10 million, and built a
fancy house on the Hudson River an hour north of Manhattan. In 1997
the ultralight airplane he was piloting crashed. His 8-year-old son
was killed and Gleick lost a leg.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gleick is back with ``Faster: The Acceleration of Just About
Everything.''
</P>
<P>
   (The book has surged to sixth place on The Boston Globe
bestseller list; Gleick is scheduled to speak at MIT Thursday at 7
p.m. in building 26-100.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Faster'' is no milky bromide on seeking the Centered life.
Instead, it is a self-conscious paean to multitasking, a meditation
in 38 lapidary chapters on the various forces, mostly
technological, that have led to the compression of time. Much of it
takes the form of reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Gleick visits the Directorate of Time at the Naval Observatory
in Washington, D.C., where the Master Clock is kept _ an atomic
timepiece whose signal governs the synchronization of computers,
satellites, and television transmissions. He recounts the history
of stop-motion photography. He reflects on the significance of
all-night banking _ and on the moment at 7 a.m. on the last Monday
in February when callers throughout the United States bombard the
Woods Hole, Martha's Vineyard, and Nantucket Steamship Authority
with calls seeking to reserve ferry tickets for their summer
vacation, only to wind up in what he calls a ``telephone lottery.''
He describes the rise of the ``new accelerators'': caffeine in
drinks like Jolt and Surge, not to mention amphetamines known as
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Gleick told one interviewer: ``The dirty little secret of my
book is that I don't think there is any such thing (as hurry
sickness.) Except that we all think there is and that we've got a
terminal case. Some of our fears of hurry sickness show up in the
whole type A idea _ the notion that people who drive in the fast
lane and pound the Close Door button on elevators are heading for
heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't really turn out to be true, or at least no one
has ever proved it. But we do feel that we are more time-driven and
time-obsessed and generally rushed than ever before, and that is
true, and if it's a kind of disease, it's a social disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he says, for the hard drivers among us, time has
become a ``negative status good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
