u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     09-14 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSING A JOB CAN BE VERY LUCRATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In our continuing quest to get rich, we have explored a variety
of schemes.
</P>
<P>
   We've considered going public to take advantage of the hot
market for initial public offerings. We've also toyed with the idea
of selling ourselves to a big technology company _ a Lucent
Technologies or a Cisco Systems _ to get a piece of the billions of
dollars they have spent acquiring small Massachusetts firms.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have a new plan: We want to lose our jobs _ just like
Philippe Dauman and Thomas Dooley. The pair were key lieutenants to
Sumner Redstone, the chairman of Viacom. They helped Redstone
negotiate last week's blockbuster merger with CBS. But in the
course of the talks they realized there would be no place for them
in the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley told the press he and his partner had no choice but to
depart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was important to the deal,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   But don't hang down your head for this Tom Dooley. He and Dauman
aren't going away empty-handed. According to documents filed with
the Securities and Exchange Commission, each man will get a $29
million lump-sum settlement, a $5 million transaction bonus, a
regular bonus of at least $6.6 million plus existing stock options
worth a minimum of $50 million. By our math that comes to $90
million plus per executive.
</P>
<P>
   Beats working, huh?
</P>
<P>
   Dauman and Dooley are only the latest in a long line of
high-profile executives who've managed to turn losing a job into a
high-paying occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Superagent Michael Ovitz was dumped by Walt Disney Co. several
years ago after only 14 months on the job. He and his boss Michael
Eisner couldn't get along. For his troubles Ovitz got a severance
package estimated at $76 million at the time of his departure; the
value of the deal grew to $187 million as Disney's stock
appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   No discussion of executive firing would be complete without
mentioning Frank Biondi, the Michael Jordan of this field. Biondi
has been canned twice in recent years, and each time he walked away
with a major settlement.
</P>
<P>
   He was dismissed first by Viacom and got $15 million to leave.
Two years later he lost his job at Universal Studios and pocketed
$30 million on his way out the door. On top of that he got to keep
an $8 million movie theater Universal built in his home. Do you
think he had to pay for the popcorn?
</P>
<P>
   The sports world has also been known to compensate failed
executives handsomely. When coach John Calipari lost his job as
coach of basketball's New Jersey Nets this year, he still had two
years and $6 million left on his contract. Calipari will get the
money, even though he led the team to a dismal record of 72 wins
and 112 losses as coach _ a curious twist on the notion of pay for
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The departing executives leave under a variety of circumstances.
Dauman and Dooley are credited with building up Viacom and both
remain on good terms with the company. Redstone reportedly
``begged'' the pair to stay. At the other end of the spectrum, J.R.
Bolduc, chief executive of W.R. Grace &AMP; Co., was forced out in 1995
after he was accused of sexual harassment, a charge he denied.
Bolduc got $43 million to disappear.
</P>
<P>
   There are some who find this whole practice distasteful. They
object to the fact that ousted executives are paid enormous sums at
a time when many people don't have enough to eat.
</P>
<P>
   The Ovitz deal struck many as particularly egregious. Steven
Friedlander, an actor, put it this way in 1996 when the news came
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates extreme division in our country between these
people who get paid unbelievable amounts for producing nothing and
regular people who barely get paid enough to survive,'' he told the
Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Several institutional investors also objected to the Ovitz
package as a poor use of shareholders money. As a general rule,
however, investors don't pay much attention to this subject. Tens
of millions of dollars may seem like a lot of money, but in the
context of a multibillion-dollar deal, the numbers don't seem so
big.
</P>
<P>
   The standard defense of huge severance packages _ frequently
offered by those receiving them _ goes something like this:
Executive salaries (and severance packages) are determined by the
free market, and if you want to attract top talent you have to pay
the price. Beyond that, by making it easy for unwanted executives
to leave, severance money contributes to smooth transitions and
avoids messy protracted litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Where do we fit into all this?
</P>
<P>
   While it is true we are not exactly high-profile executives, we
do hold the number one and two spots at this column. And like Frank
Biondi, Michael Ovitz, Philppe Dauman, and Tom Dooley, we are in
the media business.
</P>
<P>
   Like Dooley, who worked for Sumner Redstone for 20 years, we are
long-serving loyal employees. We like what we do. But if the powers
that be decide we have to go for the good of the company, we
wouldn't stand in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Our demands wouldn't be outrageous. We'd take half of what
Dooley and Dauman got _ $45 million each. It may sound like a lot
of money, but remember: It would contribute to a smooth transition
and avoid messy protacted litigation.
</P>
<P>
   With our $45 million in hand, we'd leave, but we wouldn't be
happy about it. And if you believe that, we've got some stock you
can buy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Term life insurance, which is already pretty cheap, is getting
still cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Savings Bank Life Insurance, a Woburn company that provides life
insurance to about 400,000 people in Massachusetts, Monday
announced a rate cut of 10 to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   SBLI is responding to a rate war in term life that has cut the
price of a typical policy by about 60 percent over the past decade.
Recently the prospect of new rules that might raise rates next year
has touched off a frenzy of rate cutting that SBLI president Robert
Sheridan has likened to a ``two-minute drill.''
</P>
<P>
   Term insurance is a plain vanilla product. Term policies provide
insurance for a set period of time without the investment features
common in other types of life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``SBLI's new rates are excellent,'' says Milton Brown, head of
Insurance Information Inc. in Dennis, Mass., who tracks insurance
prices nationally.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
