available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of this article. The art can
be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please specify that you want the
art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``f'' business news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By DEIRDRE MENDOZA 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   As Hollywood continues its romance with the fashion industry, a
marketing alliance of film and fashion is forming that may one day
herald the era of ``designer movies.''
</P>
<P>
   After two decades during which fashion houses and powerhouse
brands from Armani and Tommy Hilfiger to Nike and Levi's shared
screen credit and heady close-ups with America's biggest stars,
product placement has become a key avenue for global exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Lower-budget independent films might rely on the kindness of
emerging designers to provide wardrobing gratis or at cost, while
companies devoted to securing product placement may strike
million-dollar deals with major studios for their notable clients.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of the day, it's all about leveraged
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran marketers say the concept behind product placement may
date back to when men's undershirt sales sagged after Clark Gable
appeared bare-chested in the 1934 movie, ``It Happened One Night.''
This was followed decades later by the rush on Ace pocket combs
immortalized by James Dean in ``Rebel Without a Cause.''
</P>
<P>
   During the '60a and '70a, fashion trends in mainstream movies
proved aspirational. Look at what Audrey Hepburn in ``Breakfast at
Tiffany's'' did for the Little Black Dress; how John Travolta sent
``disco'' shirts flying in ``Saturday Night Fever''; and the
style-setting power of Diane Keaton's whole layered look _ complete
with granny glasses _ in ``Annie Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until the late '70s/early '80s that Seventh Avenue
really started to make a calculated impact on film.
</P>
<P>
   The gold standard of this phenomenon was released in 1980:
``American Gigolo.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers took notice of a handsome young hustler played by
Richard Gere who seduced Lauren Hutton in an impeccable wardrobe by
Giorgio Armani.
</P>
<P>
   Gere laid out piles of clothes on his bed with the Armani label
showing prominently.
</P>
<P>
   For about 20 years, Armani has been among a handful of
sought-after designers whose signature collections and individual
pieces have starred in a range of feature films.
</P>
<P>
   Armani lent his support to the Paramount film ``Double
Jeopardy'' starring Ashley Judd, which highlights an in-store
Armani boutique.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan's collections have also been integrated into
high-profile films. The company takes a team approach to its
product placement, employing designers, public-relations people,
advertising staff and salespeople to determine which projects are
potential props.
</P>
<P>
   One of Karan's big tie ins was Twentieth Century Fox's remake of
``Great Expectations,'' which premiered in 1997, starring Gwyneth
Paltrow.
</P>
<P>
   Karan's sporty and sophisticated looks added realism to
Paltrow's complex character.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Hilfiger is making aggressive strides to target its core
audience by moving forward with wardrobe tie-ins for feature films
and concert tours.
</P>
<P>
   The company blurred marketing lines when it launched an
unprecedented print and TV campaign that tied its jeans directly to
the 1999 teen horror Miramax release, ``The Faculty.''
</P>
<P>
   Movie projects slated to have a Tommy Hilfiger presence include
``Boiler Room,'' a New Line Cinema release starring Ben Affleck and
Nia Long, and ``Keeping the Faith'' (summer 2000), starring Ben
Stiller, Ed Norton and Jenna Elfman.
</P>
<P>
   Powering its presence among concert-aged consumers, Hilfiger
counts Jewel, Britney Spears, Sheryl Crow and the Rolling Stones
among the artists it will present on tour.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's also broke new ground with its promotional efforts on the
1999 release of ``The Mod Squad.''
</P>
<P>
   The brand collaborated with the film's costume designer, Arianne
Phillips, to both create the authentic look of the movie targeted
to a youth audience and to extend the film's impact with the launch
of Levi's Mod 1 line.
</P>
<P>
   Screened during fashion week for the New York press last March,
``The Mod Squad's'' neo-retro look was noted by many of the
country's hip young editors.
</P>
<P>
   Though the film was not a financial success, the Levi's
contemporary ``Mod 1'' look gained tremendous exposure with its
targeted demographic.
</P>
<P>
   For sports companies like Nike and Reebok, product placement has
been a continuous part of the overall marketing strategy. By using
in-house people and outside agencies on retainer, these companies
guarantee a steady stream of placements per year. But both
companies are careful to participate in projects that further an
athletic-driven message.
</P>
<P>
   Nike's consistent placement on Tom Hanks' feet throughout
``Forrest Gump'' (1994) was an example of a marketer's dream.
</P>
<P>
   As Hollywood continues to draw from the best of Seventh Avenue
in stories of action, adventure, comedy and romance, and Madison
Avenue readies a new slate of promotional tie-ins, moviegoers might
soon spend a day at the matinee trend-spotting on the big screen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Deirdre Mendoza is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
