<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW COMMISSIONER GETS HIS FEET WET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK-DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Don Garber has been getting a grass-roots
introduction to soccer. Garber was named commissioner of Major
League Soccer in early August, but he has kept a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   And he has capitalized on his anonymity to explore the problems
of MLS _ by mingling with fans.
</P>
<P>
   His conclusions? Nothing definite yet, but expect to see the
demise of some American-style gimmicks _ e.g. the shootout, the
clock running backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been kind of undercover,'' Garber said Monday after a
press conference to unveil the trophy for the MLS Cup, to be played
at Foxboro Stadium Nov. 21. ``I think the best way to understand
things is to go out and try to be a fan. I start at the airport
when I'm walking through the gate. I've been sitting and talking
with fans, mostly in New York, where you have passionate fans who
went to see the Cosmos and now go to see the MetroStars.''
</P>
<P>
   But instead of being a strength of the MLS, the MetroStars have
become one of the league's many problems. MLS used the 1994 World
Cup as a springboard and started strongly two years later, but
attendance has declined and there is skepticism about the quality
of play.
</P>
<P>
   Garber worked for the National Football League for 15 years and
was hand-picked as Doug Logan's successor by Lamar Hunt and the
Kraft family, MLS's NFL contingent. He is expected to reinvigorate
the league's relationship with the media and sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Though Garber has no background in the game, he clearly
appreciates some of the traditions of soccer and the value of
``hard-core'' supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the shootout tiebreaker, which certainly damaged the
credibility of the league during the Revolution's game at Miami
Saturday night, Garber said, ``The shootout has been our biggest
controversy. Every meeting we have always comes back to it. We are
going to have to make a decision on it, a difficult decision, based
on bringing the game closer to the hard-core fan.''
</P>
<P>
   MLS rules are determined by a competition committee, composed
mostly of owners and their representatives. The shootout was
developed as a desperate attempt to attract attention by the North
American Soccer League, but it faded away along with the league in
1984, only to be revived by MLS. Shootout advocates claim it
discourages teams from cynically collaborating to produce dull tie
games. But at its worst, the shootout can reduce soccer to farce,
as when Revolution goalkeeper Jeff Causey was ejected Saturday,
leaving the position to striker Joe-Max Moore as the Revolution
lost in Miami. Further confusing the issue is the points system,
which breaks from the worldwide norm of 3 for a victory, 1 for a
draw.
</P>
<P>
   But Garber seems to realize that soccer's most dedicated and
sophisticated fans, along with coaches and players, have become
disgruntled with gimmicks. And, unlike the NASL days, high-level
international soccer is easily accessible via satellite, with
advanced production values, on a regular basis. MLS simply has to
improve its standard, and the standard of its presentation, in a
substantive manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is putting the best possible product on the
field, developing the quality of play within our budget, and being
able to compete globally with a marketing plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Garber, 41, is two weeks into Spanish lessons and plans to hire
a senior executive to deal with Hispanic affairs. Garber will not
be able to match Logan's Spanish, but this should at least help him
better understand the game's varied constituency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of work to do,'' Garber said. ``I am encouraged
by the enormous desire of all our constituents, from sponsors to
fans. There is no shortage of interest in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 MLS Cup was played in a torrential downpour at Foxboro
Stadium, witnessed by 34,643 of those dedicated spectators. MLS
will be tempting the weather again this year, but the subsequent
MLS Cup will be held in October 2000, hopefully in a warmer
climate.
</P>
<P>
   The '96 MLS Cup helped lend an identity to the league and to
Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought nobody would show up,'' said Revolution midfielder
John Harkes, who helped D.C. United defeat Los Angeles, 3-2, in
overtime that year. ``The biggest thrill for the players was seeing
more than 30,000 people wearing ponchos and cheering us to the end
of the game. The passion overflowed, and when you can feel that on
the field, it's something special.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first sign for me that soccer was going to make
it in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   About 57,000 tickets will go on sale today (Sept. 14) for this
year's game, according to Revolution general manager Brian
O'Donovan. There have been several 50,000-plus crowds for soccer
games at Foxboro Stadium. But unless the Revolution can recover for
a successful playoff run, and the weather is reasonable, this game
will not likely match the stadium record for a soccer match of
57,407 for a US-Mexico World Cup qualifier/Revolution-Tampa Bay
doubleheader April 20, 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
