<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG EAST PUTS ITS NAME ON THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it Statement Week. At least in terms of reputation. The Big
East can make huge strides _ in either direction _ in terms of its
image this week.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: Penn State at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: Michigan at Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Both are Top 10 opponents. Both are on national television, with
the Syracuse-Michigan game on CBS in prime time Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   In these days of the Bowl Championship Series, when polls,
computerized rankings, and perception can affect not only
postseason matchups but also the status of a conference, it is
vital for the Big East to have a strong showing this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 has taken the pounding in the early going, with
Arizona's first-week rout at Penn State and subsequent struggle
against TCU, as well as UCLA's loss to Ohio State (although the
Bruins were shorthanded).
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, the Big East has taken most of the heat
from the critics, so much in fact that new minimum standards are
being considered for the conference to retain its automatic BCS
slot. The stakes are obvious: two blowouts in these marquee games
and the reputation of the Big East suffers; two wins and the Big
East can strut with any league in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can do nothing but help the conference,'' said Syracuse
coach Paul Pasqualoni, who is hoping his team can repeat last
year's win over the Wolverines. ``Certainly, games like this
receive a lot of attention. We went through the same thing last
year. Did it help? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Even bigger in magnitude is the Penn State-Miami game, with the
winner moving into the high-speed lane for the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   For Penn State, coming off a tough 20-17 win over Pittsburgh, it
is an obstacle that must be cleared before the rigors of the Big
Ten schedule. But the Lions' reputation as a national power is not
being questioned.
</P>
<P>
   For Miami, this is a Back to the Future type game. The
Hurricanes are again in the top 10, with wins over Ohio State and
Florida A&AMP;M as a prelude. Still ahead is the Big East schedule and
its annual game against No. 1 Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Before the season, Miami coach Butch Davis looked at the
nonconference schedule and said that if the Hurricanes could win
two of the three games against Ohio State, Penn State, and Florida
State, they would be back as prime time players.
</P>
<P>
   Davis says he relishes such games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players were excited about the chance to play Ohio
State,'' said Davis Monday. ``And they are excited about a game
like this. It's a chance for people around the country to look at
you and find out what your program is about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Naval battle ahead
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston College had the week off, and coach Tom O'Brien said
Monday that his team is ready to resume its season Saturday against
Navy, which happens to be O'Brien's alma mater. Despite beating
Baylor in the opener, O'Brien said his team is hardly cocky,
particularly since the Middies beat the Eagles at Alumni Stadium
last season. ``This is a great game for our mental toughness.''
said O'Brien. ``We have to play 60 minutes against a team who beat
us last year because they were mentally tougher than us.'' . . .
West Virginia coach Don Nehlen didn't give a ringing endorsement to
quarterback Marc Bulger's selection as the Big East Offensive
Player of the Week. ``We know he is the Big East Player of the
Week, but he didn't have a very good game,'' said Nehlen. Bulger
threw for 226 yards and three touchdowns in a 43-27 win over Miami
of Ohio . . . Virginia Tech coach Frank Beamer said redshirt
freshman quarterback Michael Vick, who missed last week's game
against Alabama-Birmingham with an ankle injury, is ready to begin
full-scale preparation for the Hokies' game against Clemson a week
from Thursday . . . With Miami (8) and Virginia Tech (10), the Big
East has two teams in the top 10 for the first time since Oct. 30,
1994, when Miami (6) and Syracuse (10) made it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
