<HEADLINE>
ZAMPESE'S OFFENSE WAS IN STEP FOR OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The running game still isn't in perfect form
(maybe it never will be in New England), but Patriots offensive
coordinator Ernie Zampese painted a pretty explosive picture of the
team's offense in a 30-28 victory over the Jets at Giants Stadium
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Zampese will never consider this offense on the level of the
ones he had in San Diego with Hall of Famers Dan Fouts, Charlie
Joiner, and Kellen Winslow but there are reasonable facsimiles in
Drew Bledsoe, Terry Glenn, and Ben Coates _ when all are healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Zampese raved about Bledsoe's play, calling it ``beautiful _ he
made great throws all day,'' and credited Glenn with making a key
adjustment on his route running in the second half that allowed him
to make two big catches while he was being double-teamed.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe (21 for 30, 340 yards) completed passes to nine
receivers, which is not the way Zampese drew it up at the
chalkboard, but is something that makes the quarterback and the
coaching staff look good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to get it that way, but you just don't know from
game to game how it comes up,'' said Zampese. ``I hear things like,
you don't throw it to this guy and you don't throw it to that guy.
Well, you're usually trying to get it to your top two guys, but at
times you have to spread it and we have guys you can get it to.
We're just trying to use the personnel we've got and we're trying
to use some formations to get the guys to make plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an awful lot of double coverage on Terry and it
helped the other side. We even got the ball to Terry within the
double coverage a couple of times. Then at halftime Terry had a
hell of a suggestion and we ended up getting him twice. It was a
good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Zampese was a tad surprised that he was able to spring big plays
on the Jets _ a 58-yarder to Tony Simmons for a touchdown and a
45-yarder to Glenn, in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get the big stuff a lot on them,'' said Zampese.
``We did a pretty good job. Drew completed a lot of balls and they
weren't just the little dink things. We got the ball up the field.
He threw the ball really well. Did he look good. His accuracy is so
good. He made nice decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Zampese isn't abandoning the running game; the Patriots passed
30 times and ran 27 times, as even a run/pass ratio as they've had
in some time. Last season, they had more rushes than passes three
times in 16 regular-season games and won all three.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some good movement,'' said Zampese. ``We had some nice
pushes. I think it's coming along, I really do. I think we're
really going to improve it. I had no idea Terry (Allen) had more
carries (15) than Kevin (Faulk, 10). It just happened where we had
some short-yardage situations, two-tight-end situations, and he
carried it more.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing Terry understands is third and 1: get the first
down, and whatever happens after that is gravy. He's back there to
run and he's a fine runner and he'll be better as he gets into game
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Zampese lauded the play of Bruce Armstrong and the offensive
line in general, but he was especially pleased with Damien Woody's
debut at center.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played very well, surprisingly well for a kid in his first
game,'' said Zampese. ``He had one breakdown and that was about it.
It looks like he's going to be a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   So the offense in Year 2 of the Zampese regime is off to a good
start. That was the case in Dallas, too, as Troy Aikman began
lighting it up in Zampese's second year as offensive coordinator
after struggling the first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you change an offense, you struggle,'' said Zampese.
``Then, once they become comfortable _ if the players are good
enough, and I think we have good players _ you'll see some
improvement. There's quite a bit of ability here. This is the best
group of wide receivers I've ever been around.''
</P>
<P>
   You can see where this is heading. Zampese wants to get the ball
to the fast guys. If Glenn is double-covered, he feels he has
enough in Shawn Jefferson, Troy Brown, and Simmons to get the job
done on the other side of the field.
</P>
<P>
   He'd like to even off the run/pass ratio, certainly, but what he
wants more than anything is to exploit the big-play capabilities he
feels this team has.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
