<HEADLINE>
HOW ABOUT AN AUTUMNAL STROLL BY THE SEA? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People who like to walk have a treat in store. The Boston
Harborwalk is a scenic and nautical self-guided stroll from behind
the John F. Kennedy Library and Museum in Dorchester to Castle
Island in South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   There is no need to enter the museum (although it's a great
place to visit) and no charge for the walk. You may not want to go
the entire distance, though. The sign says it's 3 1/2 miles each
way, but to my tired feet it felt even longer, perhaps because the
final 40 percent of the walk hasn't been completed.
</P>
<P>
   The first part takes you along the ocean's edge, with several
resting stops and interesting and entertaining information
presented on granite plaques. Here is some of what you learn:
</P>
<P>
   --A Brothers Grimm fairy tale of a talking flounder, a timid
fisherman, and a greedy wife.
</P>
<P>
   --Information about the humble flounder: It is tasty, requires
the simplest kind of tackle, and is called the ``clown of the sea''
because in adulthood it swims flat along the ocean floor with both
eyes facing up.
</P>
<P>
   --The story of the Flying Cloud. Built in East Boston in 1851,
the clipper was the fastest vessel sailing from New York to San
Francisco via Cape Horn. It set a record by traveling that
notorious passage in a mere 89 days.
</P>
<P>
   --The tale of the wreck of the Magnifique in 1782 on a sandbar
near Lovells Island, one of the Boston Harbor Islands, while being
piloted by a Bostonian. The ship was France's finest, a 74-gun
man-of-war on loan to help in the fight for independence. America
felt compelled to replace the Magnifique with a ship that was just
being completed in Portsmouth, N.H. Appropriately enough, that ship
was named America.
</P>
<P>
   --The history of the siege of Dorchester Heights, with the
neighborhood visible across the water during the walk. On March 4,
1776, the continental army, led by George Washington, fired on the
British occupying Boston and Castle Island, forcing them to
evacuate the city and eventually relinquish the island, which then
acquired the name Fort Independence.
</P>
<P>
   (The walk is part of Harborpark Boston, which encompasses 43
miles of walks, some of them guided, and involves various public
and private groups. A shorter seaside stroll takes you from the
start of the University of Massachusetts harbor campus to the JFK
Library. For more information, call the Boston Harbor Association
at 617-482-1722.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: A few weeks ago we asked which US states were named
for women _ and heard from a lot of readers because we omitted
Maryland. Undaunted, we ask this week which states were named for
men. (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``In . . . the fall the whole country goes to glory.'' _
Frances Trollope, writing about America in 1832. &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: A drink that's popular in Japan and Korea is called
Pocari Sweat. It's a Gatorade-style beverage, so the ``sweat''
refers to the drinker, not the contents. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Autumnal Web site: Www.4autumn.com offers an overview of autumnal
activities across the nation. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: In Connecticut, it is illegal to cross a street
while walking on your hands. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sign of the times: On the side of the trash truck in Ketchikan,
Alaska: ``Your satisfaction guaranteed or double your garbage
back.'' (With thanks to Nancy Ovitt of Chelmsford.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Delaware (for Lord De La Warr, a Virginia
governor), Georgia (King George II of England), Louisiana (Louis
XIV of France), New York (the Duke of York and Albany), North and
South Carolina (Charles I), Pennsylvania (William Penn), and
Washington (George). The District of Columbia, meanwhile, was named
for Christopher Columbus. And you could always argue
(unsuccessfully, in our opinion) that since Oklahoma is Choctaw for
``red man,'' the state was also named for a man. (We thank Tom
Tuttle of Newtonville, Mass. for the idea.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
