<SLUG> BC-EBAY-BLACKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIAL ITEMS ON INTERNET AUCTION SITE RAISE QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EMILY GURNON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ First it was live body parts listed for sale,
then babies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the latest category of disputed items on the on-line
auction service eBay is black memorabilia, seen by some buyers as
collectibles, by others as patently racist.
</P>
<P>
   The memorabilia consist of books, toys, comics and ceramic
figurines from the 19th and 20th centuries that depict blacks in
the stereotypical, often negative ways they were seen by whites.
Examples include ``mammy'' cookie jars, mechanical banks, and
porcelain figurines of black children sitting in outhouses.
</P>
<P>
   Until late last week, eBay shoppers could purchase myriad Nazi
and Ku Klux Klan items, such as KKK knives, belt buckles and a
Christmas ornament of a robed Klan member whose hood, when raised,
reveals a kindly Santa Claus face.
</P>
<P>
   The items are nothing new to collectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are offended by the word `slavery,' but it was
reality, and we have to deal with that,'' said Sam Dyke, the owner
of People's Bazaar, an antiques store in Berkeley, Calif., that
sells black memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a horrible scenario, and by no means am I applauding it,
but you have to know your history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some people see a difference between viewing such items
in an antiques store and seeing them listed, complete with
offending terminology, on the Internet. In some cases, the
descriptions offered by sellers lack sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Faulkner, a collector of black memorabilia in Berkeley, said
he believed that ``eBay needs to exercise some editorial control on
how things appear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Collectors' magazines and newsletters do exercise that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   One item for sale was described by the seller as a ``black
nigger boy eating watermelon figurine.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Oliver, 40, a part-time antiques dealer in
McMinnville, Tenn., said she listed the figurine using the
offensive word because she thought it would attract more potential
buyers. Some people will search on the word to find related items,
such as books that use it in the title, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with prejudice,'' she said. ``I did
hesitate to do it, but I think it has drawn more attention to the
auction.''
</P>
<P>
   EBay spokeswoman Kristin Seuell said the on-line service
generally relies on its buyers and sellers to follow guidelines and
police themselves. ``It's very much like a neighborhood watch,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the company's policy is to allow the use of offensive
words if they are part of a title. But the word is used in an
offensive or vulgar way, ``we will end the auction,'' Seuell said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Ku Klux Klan items, Seuell said such things may be
offensive, but they are legal to sell and therefore would not be
removed from eBay.
</P>
<P>
   The company does stop auctions of items that may not be sold by
law, such as body parts, babies and counterfeit items. EBay pulled
listings earlier this month that featured babies and kidneys from
live donors, saying it believed the listings were hoaxes. It also
restricts sales of firearms, stock and stock certificates,
surveillance equipment, cable-TV descramblers, animals and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Dyke said he understands that some of his fellow
African-Americans are offended by artifacts that portray blacks in
a negative light or glorify racism.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he would not restrict sales of memorabilia. ``I
wouldn't trample on their rights to do what they want. They're
entitled to their opinion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
