<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMUS BROTHERS HOPE RANCH WILL BRING JOY TO SICK KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIBERA, N.M. _ Jack, an orphan of distinguished heritage, is
``still trying to find himself,'' says his ``psychiatrist.'' ``He
was very lonely and depressed when we brought him here. He didn't
know who he was. He thought he was a horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have gotten better. Now Jack thinks he's a donkey.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because he rooms with a couple of them named Gene and
Roy, and maybe donkeys have more fun. At least their hilarious
quotes _ ``Hee-haw!'' in varied tones _ sound as if they do.
Whatever, the living is good in their pen-with-a-view, way out in
the wide open spaces of New Mexico. And there's plenty of food.
This is important for Jack, a shaggy young-and-growing American
buffalo of 1,200 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's starting to feel secure here,'' says Fred Imus,
patting Jack on the withers.
</P>
<P>
   Fred, the dumb-animal psychiatrist, rag peddler, and cosmetic
surgeon to auto bodies, also plays dumb as himself on his big
brother's morning radio show. Scraggly as ever in a half-hearted
beard, weary jeans, and T-shirt, plus cowboy boots and tattoos,
Fred may seem worn and brainless on the airwaves. However, it turns
out it's all a front for a very worthy heart.
</P>
<P>
   Currently he is wholeheartedly involved in fleshing out the
brothers Imus's missionary work: namely this 3,100-acre ranch that
is designed to convert painful days of seriously sick kids to a
stretch of fun. Their belief: Put kids amid the beasts such as
buffalo Jack and the quarter horses, in a setting of grassy
prairie, cactus, mountains, mesas, and sagebrushed rangeland of the
reasonably wild wild West and they'll have the time of their lives.
Lives that may be very short.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you've heard the other Imus _ Don, the raunchy rancher _
babbling about their $4 million spread (plus undetermined millions
in operating costs)? Located about an hour southeast of Santa Fe,
the ranch has been underwritten largely by the contributions of
listeners. But with Imus, who knew? Possibly it existed only in the
creative minds of McCord, Lou and Bernard, Breen or Rob Bartlett?
</P>
<P>
   But no. What was but a beautiful dream does exist beautifully.
The longhorns are on the way. Those acres, at $5,000 a pop that so
many Imusiacs sprang for, materialize immediately as you enter the
iron gate. None of them are underwater, either. The acre of a
Boston friend, the late Keith Brodkin, is a neat rise covered with
rocky outcroppings and juniper trees. Keith would like it. Anybody
would.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to be ready for the first kids on a regular basis in
January of 2000,'' says Fred, who gets a nod from the construction
supervisor, Chaz Schleeter. Swarming carpenters are completing two
huge barns and starting the main building, an adobe hacienda to
house the youngsters and staff. Already up are a couple of
guesthouses, Indian tepees, a greenhouse, windmill, a horse corral,
another for the odd trio: Jack and the donkeys Roy and Gene, named
for film cowboys Rogers and Autry.
</P>
<P>
   The pride of Imus territory is also standing: Downtown, the
one-block main street of a 19th-century adobe-and-wood Western
town, a movie lot Dodge City. Great place for kids to play ``High
Noon,'' to push through the saloon's swinging doors and find an ice
cream parlor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, they'll love it,'' says Fred. ``They'll think they're John
Wayne or Gary Cooper. Maybe Calamity Jane. They'll hear the coyotes
at night, roosters in the morning, and if they feel like it, they
can chase the goats, deer, and jackrabbits. There are cougars and
bears up on that mesa, Rowe Mesa, that runs all the way to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll bring in 10 kids at a time for 10 days. We don't want a
mob scene. They'll get full attention by the staff that will
include medical personnel at the infirmary in Downtown. And they'll
have responsibilities, like with the animals. Over a few years
that'll be quite a few kids. What we want is to see that light in
their eyes. The light of happiness. Just that'll be enough to make
it all worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same sentiment that propelled ex-tennis champ Andrea
Jaeger to found a similar retreat, Silver Lining Ranch in Aspen,
Colo., for kids with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Striding across the crimson earth toward the corrals, Fred says,
``Don and I grew up on a ranch, and we think it's a great
experience for a kid. I think he'd like to do more of his shows
here. There'll be a studio in Downtown. Maybe he'll retire here. I
wouldn't mind, myself.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend, painter Lynn Wade, says she wouldn't mind, either.
She says it was love at first sound bite when she heard Fred on the
radio. It must be love, all right.
</P>
<P>
   But will Jack, the confused buffalo, find love or only become
the butt of Fred's shaggy buffalo stories?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sort of,'' says Fred. ``Poor orphan, he was raised by a mare
and fed with a bottle by her owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack needs a pedicure to be sexier,'' says Lynn, observing
that Fred also gets along with these donkeys fine.
</P>
<P>
   Fred says, ``You'd have to anesthetize Jack to get it done. Say,
notice the cross marks on the donkeys' backs? The story is that
since Mary rode into Bethlehem on a donkey they have these cross
birthmarks. Looks that way, don't it?'' Curiously, it does.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we all have our crosses to bear, don't we?'' says Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   Fred says, ``The donkeys love Jack. But I'm gonna bring in a
female buffalo named Virginia, from a rancher down the road, for
Jack to pal around with. Then maybe he'll get the idea who he is.''
Astute psychiatry that Dr. Freud would applaud.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he says with a sigh familiar to listeners of his
Imusings, ``Jack was, you know, fixed before we got him. He'll have
to settle for platonic romance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
