<HEADLINE>
BICYCLISTS'S ESSAYS TEACH LESSONS OF THE BACKROADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE DANIEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
METAL COWBOY 
Tales from the Road Less Pedaled 
By Joe Kurmaskie 
Breakaway Books, $23, 304 pp. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you had to guess where Joe Kurmaskie grew up, you'd probably
pick the heart of the heartland. The actual answer is Pennsylvania
and Florida, but Kurmaskie's down-home, aw-shucks outlook on life
is decidedly Midwestern, or perhaps ``Mayberry, R.F.D.'' His
``Metal Cowboy'' contains 40 essays covering the ups, downs, and
everything-in-between of riding a bicycle all over America, with a
few foreign lands sprinkled in. Mostly, it's an infectious
celebration of life, a sort of two-wheeled version of ``Chicken
Soup for the Soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurmaskie does what's called loaded touring, which means
carrying all your gear _ food, clothing, and shelter _ on your
bike. I went on my first loaded-touring trip the same week I
started reading ``Metal Cowboy,'' figuring it would be a fun thing
to read by flashlight beam in my tent. I think I stayed awake for a
few sentences a night, and it wasn't the book's fault. Let's just
say that not only do I admire the author's cheery outlook on life,
I gained a newfound respect for the stamina required for daily
bicycle touring.
</P>
<P>
   From the time he was 5 and rode his sister's bicycle, Kurmaskie
fell in love with bikes. ``Just a collection of metal, rubber,
grease and gears to the untrained eye, to me that two-wheeled
contraption has always represented something more. It has to do
with possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I love the wind in my face, the sound of my beating
heart as I work up a hill, but the simple, clean rush of freedom
was what hooked me.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 20s, the author took that freedom seriously, going on
numerous cycling adventures around North America and an odyssey
across Australia and New Zealand. It's America that he is most
interested in, and he takes a Charles Kuralt approach to finding
the quirky but very real people that dot the landscape far from any
Wal-Mart. Seldom does he poke fun at them, and often he learns from
them.
</P>
<P>
   It was an old, blind rancher in Idaho who dubbed Kurmaskie
``metal cowboy'' before tapping the back of his bike in a fond
farewell. ``Though I looked more like a surfer, or a guy on a
fool's journey, to him I felt like a metal cowboy, the bike my
horse, and the asphalt my trail.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other characters he meets up with include a pack of
guard geese, a roving band of Elvis impersonators, and a
78-year-old cyclist he had to struggle to keep up with.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Touched by an Angel'' fashion, the intrepid traveler allows
a retired Italian barber to relive his glory days by cutting
Kurmaskie's hair; accompanies a girl forced to drop out of high
school to her senior prom; and agrees to be the ceremonial
scarecrow _ on bicycle _ in a small-town parade down South.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of this last essay, ``The Next Parade,'' were endearing
and and even hilarious, especially when Kurmaskie is observing such
things as the Lions refusing to follow the Rotarians because of a
feud at last summer's softball tournament. But it also has one of
Kurmaskie's too-frequent treacly endings: ``Handing over the
scarecrow costume, I realized I too was going to be all right in
this world, as long as I remembered to stop every now and then, to
let the good stories just under the surface happen _ and to keep an
eye out for the next parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurmaskie readily and refreshingly admits his foibles and
occasional loss of common sense, and he holds back not a whit when
waxing poetic about his wife, whom he met while cycling. Unlike so
many purveyors of irony and sarcasm, Kurmaskie uncovers what is
sweet and good among people. Truth is, while my eyes sometimes
rolled at the cornball passages, they'd also fill up with tears.
</P>
<P>
   The author, who now lives in Portland, Ore., recently became a
columnist for Bicycling magazine and hosts a busy Web site
(www.metalcowboy.com). Here's hoping he doesn't become a franchise
of the sort he avoided on his many excellent adventures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
