<HEADLINE>
`STIGMATA' BEARS THE MARKS OF BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When William Donohue, president of the ultraconservative,
easily-agitated Catholic League for Religious and Civil Rights,
issued a statement earlier this month denouncing the new thriller
``Stigmata,'' it wasn't difficult to assume he was just up to his
old attention-grabbing tricks again.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Donohue has found small fame by condemning any
movie or television show presenting a challenging view of
Catholicism or the clergy. He has fired unholy words at such
worthwhile fare as ABC's brave and too-quickly-cancelled ``Nothing
Sacred,'' which starred Kevin Anderson as an inner-city priest, and
the 1994 independent film ``Priest,'' with Linus Roache as a young
cleric struggling with his vows and his homosexuality. Even more
irritating, Donohue often slammed his targets before viewing them
in their entirety, if he even bothered to view them at all.
</P>
<P>
   So when Donohue passed judgment on ``Stigmata'' _ calling it
``outlandishly gory and insidious,'' based only on the film's
three-minute trailer _ it landed on many ears as just the same old
sound bite. The film, which opened last week, stars Patricia
Arquette as a young woman mysteriously inflicted with the wounds of
the crucified Christ, and Gabriel Byrne as a priest sent to
investigate. Then there's Jonathan Pryce as a Roman Catholic Church
biggie willing to employ any means necessary to suppress a lost
gospel, written by Christ, that could undermine the power and
validity of the church.
</P>
<P>
   Well, imagine my slack-jawed amazement now that I find myself
agreeing with Donohue's assessment of this dreadful film as
``insidious.'' And, having sat through the whole bloody mess, let
me add repellent, hateful, loathsome and vile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stigmata'' is a deplorable anti-Catholic rant trying to pass
itself off as a provocative thriller about the true nature of
faith, and where faith resides within humankind. Though widely
panned by most critics, the film still garnered $19.3 million in
its opening weekend, booting ``The Sixth Sense'' out of the top
spot for the first time in weeks. So much for Donohue's statement
that ``The good news is that there exists a small audience for such
an exploitative film, and all the hype and technical effects in the
world can do nothing to redeem this bomb of a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   My status as a one-time altar girl notwithstanding, I found the
film offensive, but was hardly surprised by this latest hint of
Hollywood's attitude regarding priests. Along with lawyers and
psychologists, priests have become one of the most maligned groups
on the big screen. Reel-for-reel, even serial killers are presented
as more cuddly and charming than anyone wearing a cassock and a
collar.
</P>
<P>
   Things have certainly changed. We're a long way from Pat O'Brien
getting Jimmy Cagney to turn chicken to save the Dead End kids from
a life of crime in ``Angels in Dirty Faces,'' Spencer Tracy's
tough-but-tender Father Flanagan in ``Boys Town,'' Montogomery
Clift's willingness to take a murder rap rather than break the
sancitity of a parishioner's confession in ``I Confess,'' or Bing
Crosby's too-ra-loo-ra-loo-a-ing to save failing St. Dominic's in
``Going My Way.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, more often than not, we get the tried, tested, and tired
variations of priests who are far more sinners than saints. There's
the bad priest like ``Stigmata's'' Pryce, who obviously has quite a
few melodramatic scowls left over from his villainous turn in the
James Bond flick, ``Tomorrow Never Dies.'' He's a conniving
cardinal willing to break every commandment to preserve the
church's lofty perch as the house of God. Other examples of the bad
priest are Robert De Niro's double-dealing monsignor in ``True
Confessions,'' and Stanley Anderson's corrupt and sexually deviant
archbishop in ``Primal Fear.''
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of sexual deviancy, then there's all those
celluloid clerics who surrender to sins of the flesh. Byrne, as a
priest-scientist who has trouble resisting the oh-so-resistible
Arquette in ``Stigmata,'' joins a long line of picture-show priests
who give new meaning to the term ``hot under the collar.'' The
worst of the lot is Tom Berenger in the abysmal ``Last Rites,'' in
which his hunky holy man actually moves a young woman into his
quarters in St. Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows there are some priests out there who misuse their
position and status for personal gain. And there is certainly a
place for well-made, thoughtful films _ such as the devastating
``Boys of St. Vincent'' _ which explore the darker sides and
motivations of the clergy. But there has to be something better
than films like ``Stigmata,'' which offer nothing more than cheap
titillation, religious mumbo-jumbo, and all the depth of Madonna in
her crucifixes a-plenty stage.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's time for priests to form some kind of
anti-defamation league or association for the advancement of
clerical people. To borrow a line from the eels's ``Novocaine for
the Soul,'' ``Jesus and his lawyer are coming back'' _ and not a
moment too soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
