<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES A MISTAKE IS JUST A MISTAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For readers who care deeply about language, every dumb usage
error that shows up in print can be a sign of declining literacy,
proof that today's journalists, like their less hurried colleagues
in other branches of the writing trade, are more careless and less
well educated than previous generations.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to sympathize, sometimes, with the pessimists.
When beg the question and comprise are used incorrectly _ by
traditional standards _ nine times out of 10, the original meanings
are probably doomed, and the long battle to save them can make even
a dispassionate usagist suspect that instruction may be futile.
</P>
<P>
   But some mistakes are just mistakes, not early warning signs of
trends, welcome or otherwise. Take tenderhooks, for instance _ a
misspelling that horrified Richard Morris of Wellesley when he
found it in The Wall Street Journal last month. Tenderhooks _ it
sounds like the equipment a seductress would have used, back when
there were seductresses _ ought to have been tenterhooks, the
spikes or nails that hold fabric stretched on a frame, or tenter,
to dry. Tentering (from the Latin for ``to stretch'') is associated
mostly with cloth weaving, but, says Morris, ``When I was a
youngster, my mother used a tenter to dry window curtains.'' He
blames sloppiness and ``a not surprising ignorance'' of tenterhooks
for the rising tide of tenders.
</P>
<P>
   But are the waves really lapping at our ankles? In fact, The
Wall Street Journal, which quickly printed a letter correcting its
error, has printed tenderhooks only one other time in 17 years. In
the Globe, tenderhooks appears only twice in the 20 years spanned
by our computer records. The entire Lexis/Nexis news archive coughs
up only about 80 examples of the accidental tenderhooks _ and less
than a third of those are in US publications. London, Glasgow,
Toronto, Singapore _ anywhere English is printed, tenderhooks
appears sooner or later. It doesn't appear to be gaining ground,
though, probably because it's relatively rare even in its correct
form; the people who spell it right are more than a match for those
who spell it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   So let's cross that off the list of worries and turn to
sticks-in-the-mud, which set off alarm bells for Mary Anne
McQuillan, of Freetown, when she spotted it in the Globe last
month. ``Shouldn't it be stick-in-the-muds?'' she asks. ``My image
of that was always of a person mired in a mudhole . . . not of a
twig stuck in mud.'' Exactly so: A stick-in-the-mud is neither a
kind of stick nor a kind of mud, but a person stuck in the mud, set
in his ways, resistant to change. So the word is a unit, and like
will-o'-the-wisps, jack-in-the-pulpits, and Scotch and sodas, it
has the regular, s-at-the-end plural form.
</P>
<P>
   But again, is it a problem? The Globe's files show six
sticks-in-the-mud to seven stick-in-the-muds _ hardly a comfortable
margin for the good guys. A closer look, though, offers some
grounds for optimism: The wrong plural has appeared only twice in
the '90s, while the right one has made five appearances in this
decade. Stick-in-the-muds bears watching, but for the moment, the
proper plural is gaining on the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Another sneaky mistake may be more of a threat, if only because
it seems to be flying below the radar, including mine. A few months
ago, David Tuggy e-mailed from Mexico to ask if I'd really meant to
write that there might be ``a trend underfoot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a blooper I've recorded repeatedly,'' he wrote. ``To
me it is still a rather funny blend of afoot with underway . . .
with perhaps resonances of secrecy and illegitimacy from
underhanded, underground . . . and so forth.'' But Tuggy,
generously doing the research for me, found that half the people he
asked ``think it's perfectly straightforward English; the other
half think it's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that I look at it, I think it's funny, too. As Tuggy
suggests, using underfoot in that way gives it a sense of the
sinister, even of the ground shifting under our feet; afoot doesn't
necessarily have that connotation, despite Shakespeare's
``Mischief, thou art afoot.'' But underfoot has useful meanings
already _ ``How can I work with these children underfoot?'' _ and
if I'd noticed my nonstandard usage, I would have chosen a
different word.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tuggy is the only reader who challenged underfoot, which
suggests that its new meaning may well be afoot _ if not underway,
under way, or under weigh. So if you don't like it, get out your
binoculars; it's not an easy invader to spot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com, or write to
her at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Please
include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 1414EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
