<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY'S PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEVITTOWN, N.Y. _ The steep hill that Hillary Rodham Clinton
faces in her almost-adopted state is not theoretical; nor is it the
product of extrapolated polling numbers.It's very real and very
personal.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Gail Lacks, a bookkeeper at a company in the Long Island
town of Syosset. She's an Independent who follows politics and
tends to vote in Democratic primaries. She's for Al Gore for
president, but her second choice is George Bush, and Elizabeth Dole
is her third.
</P>
<P>
   More important, she was solid for President Clinton's reelection
three years ago; and most important, she has a visceral dislike for
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any really strong feelings against her until she
put out this stuff that she had a Jewish relative,'' said Lacks,
herself Jewish and 53. ``I just deeply resented that, because it
wasn't a matter of truth; she was just using it as a ploy. That did
it. I just don't like Hillary; I really don't want her to be a
senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. So let's try another Clinton '96 female voter _
Trudy Strober, 55 and retired. She considers herself Independent,
not that political, and tends toward Republican primaries. She's
for Elizabeth Dole right now, with Bill Bradley the only Democrat
she could imagine being for later.
</P>
<P>
   To Strober, Mrs. Clinton's sin is that she comes across to this
Long Islander as pure pol.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all this double-talk all the time,'' she said the other
evening. ``No matter what it is, I get the impressing that all
she's doing is playing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not the impression she has of New York City's loudmouth
mayor, Rudolph Giuliani, Mrs. Clinton's likely opponent. To her,
Giuliana represents that precious commodity in these exasperating
times _ authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Rudy says it's Thursday, it's Thursday all day,'' Strober
said. ``There's never any hidden agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail Lacks and Trudy Strober were among 14 female voters who sat
down for a structured discussion in this congested suburban town.
Under the aegis of a national housing and community investment
organization, Republican pollster Frank Luntz led them through
their political paces. They were narrowly for Clinton, and narrowly
for loser Al D'Amato in last year's Senate war _ about what you'd
expect from a middle-class, largely white slice of suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   The group was also solidly for Mayor Giuliani, but what was
interesting about their division was the source of Giuliani's
advantage, women who had picked the president over Bob Dole. There
was nothing in the group discussion that precluded a Hillary
Clinton victory eventually, as a moderate Democrat in a heavily
Democratic state. But the length of the journey she clearly must
still make is considerable.
</P>
<P>
   There was not, for what it's worth, much talk about her
out-of-state life, and none at all about recent Clinton headlines
like the family's decision to buy a home in Westchester County and
the string of communication goofs that added fuel to the fire of
Bill Clinton's decision to offer conditional clemency to more than
a dozen Puerto Rican nationalists convicted of serious weapons and
conspiracy charges in the 1970s and '80s. Instead the talk was
mostly about the kinds of would-be leaders they tend to trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's reaching,'' said Laurie Sheridan, another Bill Clinton
voter, and a part-time teacher and Independent with Democratic
leanings who's for Bradley. ``More than that, she's an
opportunist.''
</P>
<P>
   The outnumbered supporters were not shy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a strong woman,'' said a 25-year-old English teacher,
Roseanne Merell, hinting at the Clintons' private lives. ``I mean
what about Jackie Kennedy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's much the better candidate,'' insisted Gloria Klayman, 58
and retired. ``Giuliani is arrogant, and that means he just can't
work with others, which is what you have to do as a senator.
Hillary is just brilliant, and she'll stand up for kids and women.
All this reminds me of what it was life all those years ago when
Robert Kennedy ran here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joanne Lewis, 37 and a homemaker, countered with the
pro-Giuliani side of that case, that ``a good politician will stick
to his guns and go along his line and persuade others to go along
with them.'' And she voted for the president three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Generalizations are always dangerous in these settings, but the
loss (at least for now) of voters who helped create the Clinton
landlside here three years ago is what makes Clinton-Giuliani a
horse race today. In addition, there is more to all this than just
polarized opinion about Mrs. Clinton; suburban support for Giuliani
is also personal and goes deeper than mere relief at the Big
Apple's lower crime rate.
</P>
<P>
   But down the road, the way the two divide on issues that matter
to people here will be critical. Giuliani, the Republican, against
Clinton, the Democrat, is the campaign that favors the first lady,
which is probably why so much of the GOP babble about her has been
so personal. As I could tell out here last week, the voters are
still seeing this in personal terms as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
