<SLUG> BC-DYING-MALLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALL MANIA SLOWLY TURNS TO MALAISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HADLEY, Mass. _ There was a time when men worked together to
give this mall the look of an alpine village, but that time is 30
years past.
</P>
<P>
   The water wheel has been dismantled and the banks of
spathiphyllum left to die. At the end of an echoing, concrete-lined
hallway a Batman Forever video game asks, over and over, if you
have a thing for bats.
</P>
<P>
   And you get the feeling it's been a long time since the mall's
hopeful, original name, ``Mountain Farms,'' crossed anyone's lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what they call it? They call it the Dead Mall,'' said
Bill Cooley, who works in a computer store that is one of the
mall's few tenants. ``Go into town, ask anyone about the Dead Mall,
and they'll know exactly what you're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, in the retail-saturated Connecticut Valley, Mountain
Farms is being dismantled to make way for a Wal-Mart. Fairfield
Mall, in Chicopee, has stocked emptying storefronts with
religious-themed holograms and scented candles. Eastfield Mall, in
Springfield, has added a multiplex to stave off its decline.
</P>
<P>
   Every neighborhood has its own sad example, but the problem is
not local. Across the country, enclosed malls are spending their
third decades in a slow slide toward obsolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Now the same urbanists who rallied to protect dying downtowns
are working on solutions to a new crisis: What do you do with a
dying mall?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known about dying cities for a long time,'' said Shelley
Peticha, director of the San Francisco-based Congress for the New
Urbanism, an urban planning think tank that focuses on combating
suburban sprawl. ``But now we're starting to hit this wave where
this whole inventory of '60s and '70s malls basically don't work
anymore. . . . This is on the radar of so many communities right
now it's just something you can't ignore.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems like only yesterday that social critics were bemoaning
the mall's success in colonizing America; no one foresaw the
problem of mall failure. Yet PricewaterhouseCoopers predicted
recently that 15 to 20 percent of existing malls are likely to fail
over the next decade, and the Congress for the New Urbanism puts
the number of malls standing empty now at 3,800 _ about 2 billion
square feet of empty space, radiating their air of stagnation into
the neighborhoods around them.
</P>
<P>
   The mall life cycle is a personal issue to Al St. Denis, whose
bookstore has a five-year lease at the ailing Fairfield Mall in
Chicopee. Next to his cash register hangs a 1989 ``Manager of the
Year'' plaque that he says reminds him of better days, before the
Gap and Caldor's left, and before Friendly's gave way to businesses
on short-term leases selling Pokemon cards and workout tapes.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the mall's clients are mostly elderly, and St. Denis
does much of his business in scratch tickets; as he speaks, a
woman's walker scrapes across the floor. St. Denis gives a
prominent display spot to a book called ``Alzheimer's Disease:
Accepting the Loss with Dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't see an end to it any time soon. ``I'll tell you, it
takes forever to close a mall,'' St. Denis said. ``I've been to
malls in Florida that only have one or two tenants left, but they
stay open.''
</P>
<P>
   The simplest explanation for the regional mall's predicament is
market saturation. The amount of retail space per person in this
country has increased by 30 percent since the mid-1980s, with each
new, glossy mall drawing customers from the form that preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, new enclosed malls continue to go up at a rate of
almost 10 per year, according to the International Council of
Shopping Centers _ below the 19 that were built in 1990, but up
from the average of four a year in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Ask anyone in the Connecticut Valley malls that have been
competing for business for 20 years and they'll tell you the market
is already crowded.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time there are enough malls there may be too many
malls,'' said Jerry Rosenswaike, 53, who runs a Beanie Baby kiosk
at Auburn Mall, which has covered a vacant anchor spot with posters
announcing $5 million in free prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Others draw a broader conclusion, saying Americans have actually
lost their taste for the mall experience. The length of the average
mall visit has been dwindling since the 1980s, according to
statistics from the International Council of Shopping Centers, as
time-starved working women cut down on all-day browsing. It's also
an aesthetic choice, some say, pointing out that the great asset
that malls had to offer in the 1960s and 1970s was a completely
artificial environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when we try to manufacture these false environments,
they're sort of thin,'' said Mark Falcone, a Colorado developer
whose father developed malls, and who has now turned his attention
to recycling malls. ``People got the sense that this is costumery,
and you get sick of a costume much quicker than the real thing.
People are thirsting for more real, substantive kinds of places.''
</P>
<P>
   Some _ especially those who hated malls in the first place _ say
it's not too early to render a verdict on the entire mall era.
That's a point of view that has caught on in Western Europe, where
Norway this year put a five-year ban on construction of new malls,
and Britain's top environmental official issued an edict in 1995
strongly discouraging suburban mall construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mall was a kind of experiment that doesn't work,'' Peticha
said. ``It's failed.''
</P>
<P>
   But spending at malls rose 13 percent between 1995 and 1997,
according to the International Council of Shopping Centers.And the
question of why some malls have failed is less urgent than the
question of what to do with their carcasses.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Peticha recalled, ``We realized, `Oh my God,
this is happening all over the country,' '' and the Council for the
New Urbanism teamed up with the International Council of Shopping
Centers on a study of how a failing mall drags down the community.
</P>
<P>
   One planning commentator proposed that corporations who put up
big box stores pledge to finance their demolition once they outlive
their usefulness. In a study for the Council for the New Urbanism,
Falcone recommends that the government forgive outstanding
mortgages for the owners of doomed regional malls, who could, in
turn, release tenants from their leases and turn slow decline into
speedy redevelopment for other uses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout the country, you're talking about literally
hundreds of thousands of acres that could be put back into public
use,'' said Falcone, whose firm, Continuum Partners, is working on
mixed-use renovation of struggling shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
   Empty malls have been successfully transformed into office
buildings, schools, and churches, and one Virginia developer has
looked into reusing malls as jails. More commonly, though, malls
are being reworked as a more modern retail space by removing the
structure's roof and creating a pedestrian walkway. Mashpee
Commons, on Cape Cod, comes up frequently as a model for the
revised mall style.
</P>
<P>
   The aim, consistently, is to make the space less mall-like _ a
considerable challenge in the asphalt-flanked suburban expanses
that appealed to mall developers 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much easier to adaptively reuse an older building in a
downtown that has other things going on around it, as opposed to a
free-standing structure in a cornfield,'' said Constance Beaumont,
who has researched the problem of abandoned big box stores for the
National Trust for Historic Preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, America's malls continue to guard against the voodoo
that makes an atmosphere go bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is an intangible,'' Beaumont said. ``They
probably reach a tipping point at some point, where you go to a
mall and there are just too many empty storefronts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
