r a BC-YOUR-BRAIN'S-BETTER-H     09-14 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUR-BRAIN'S-BETTER-HALF-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAIN WORKS: YOUR BETTER HALF  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 By ERIC HASELTINE  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   You probably write with a particular hand, kick with a
particular foot, peer through a telescope with a particular eye and
raise the telephone receiver to a particular ear.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these habits says more about your brain than it does
about your body parts, because handedness, footedness, eyedness and
earedness (actual neurological terms) are different manifestations
of what brain researchers call hemispheric lateralization.
</P>
<P>
   Hemispheric refers to the division of the brain into left and
right halves, and lateralization describes the brain's tendency to
make the two halves specialize in controlling different functions.
</P>
<P>
   Most people favor their right hands and feet, for example,
because the left halves of their brains, which control the right
sides of their bodies, are better suited for fine movements.
</P>
<P>
   The left hemisphere also supports speech in the vast majority of
people, and there is growing evidence that the left brain is
superior when it comes to analyzing fine details in vision,
audition and touch.
</P>
<P>
   The right cerebral hemisphere, by contrast, does a better job
than the left in reading facial expressions, decoding tone of voice
in speech and comprehending the big picture in visual, auditory and
tactile stimuli.
</P>
<P>
   Lateralization is a hot area of research because cognitive and
behavioral differences between the hemispheres can be correlated
with corresponding differences in size, weight, cell density,
neurochemistry and physiology to help understand how the brain
encodes information and performs tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Although neuroscientists use sophisticated measures (for
example, carefully isolating different kinds of stimuli in the left
and right visual fields) to tease out subtle hemispheric
differences, you can perform a couple of simple experiments to
discover how your own brain has organized itself.
</P>
<P>
   EXPERIMENT 1: With both eyes open, hold up our right thumb at
arm's length under an object across the room directly ahead of you.
Now alternately close your left and right eyes, and see if your
thumb appears to jump to the right or left with respect to the
distant object.
</P>
<P>
   If you are right-eyed like 54 percent of the population, your
thumb will jump to the right when you close your right eye but stay
put when you close your left eye.
</P>
<P>
   The opposite will occur if you are left-eyed like 5 percent of
the population.
</P>
<P>
   If you see little or no jumping, you are among the 41 percent of
the population who are neither strongly left-eyed or right-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   EXPERIMENT 2: Memorize the first paragraph of this article, then
go find a broom, a clock with a second hand, a pencil and a pad of
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Time how long you can balance the end of the broom on the tip of
your right index finger while standing on your right foot, then on
your left index finger while standing on your left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat the test while reciting the paragraph you have memorized.
Speech will be localized on the side of your brain opposite the
hand that is most affected by recital of the paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   By closely observing how people use the different halves of
their bodies, you can see the power of brain specialization at work
_ string musicians finger notes with their left hands, field goal
kickers usually score with their right feet, and it's a good bet
that about 35 percent of eavesdroppers consistently listen through
walls with their right ears.
</P>
<P>
   Look for smaller details too, like which eye your friend uses to
thread a needle.
</P>
<P>
   Nature doesn't shout these secrets, it whispers them.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Haseltine is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
