<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-U.N. (United Nations) _ Developments on the East Timor
peacekeeping force. A Security Council resolution may be approved
Tuesday. Complicating matters, U.N. officials think that the
Indonesian military had a role in wrecking U.N. compound in Dili.
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-REFUGEES (Darwin, Australia) _ Haunted and huddling, more
than 1,500 East Timorese refugees arrived here on military
evacuation planes Tuesday after the United Nations left its
compound, which was wrecked by the militias (and perhaps the
Indonesian military). The militias had laid siege to the compound
from the day after East Timor voted for independence. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   Others as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-UNREST (Moscow) _ Police make an ethnic sweep through
Moscow, checking and rousting people from the Caucasus after
bombings attributed to rebels from the region. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SLOGANS (Beijing) _ Just in case any of the 1.3 billion
Chinese people were having trouble imagining what to chant or
inscribe for the nation's 50th birthday blowout on Oct. 1, the
Communist Party on Tuesday issued a list of approved slogans for
the occasion. Fifty of them, to be exact. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HURRICANE FLOYD &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-FLOYD (Orlando, Fla.) _ Authorities urged nearly 2
million people to evacuate coastal areas stretching from Florida to
North Carolina on Tuesday as Hurricane Floyd, one of the most
powerful storms to ever threaten the United States, roared through
the Bahamas. Floyd's eye was expected to pass within 90 miles of
southern Florida, and perhaps come within 50 miles of north
Florida's coast by Wednesday morning, before striking land
somewhere farther north, perhaps near Cape Canaveral. By Rick
Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Why Floyd is such a big storm, how
it is different from other hurricanes, and what forces are
determining its course. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Others as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FUNDRASING (Washington) _ The House is to consider the
Shays-Meehan campaign finance overhaul bill. By Alison Mitchell.
(1300 words; Eds, final vote may be after 9 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ The Senate continues to wrangle
over a $14 billion Interior Department spending bill, rife with
special favors for the oil, timber and mining industries. By Tim
Weiner. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-WAGE (Washington) _ Senate Democrats push for an
increase in the minimum wage. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLLUTION-SUIT (New York) _ After a series of setbacks
against efforts by Northeastern states and Federal environmental
officials to limit pollution blowing from coal-fired power plants
in the Midwest, New York state is opening up a new legal front,
announcing its intention today to file suit against specific power
plants in Ohio and other upwind states to force them to clean up.
By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   MISS-AMERICA (Atlantic City, N.J.) _ Checking what Atlantic
City, where the Miss America pageant takes place this Saturday,
thinks of the news that the pageant will no longer require
contestants to sign a document saying they've never been married or
pregnant. By Maria Newman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE-MAYORAL (Baltimore) _ Baltimore voters pick their next
mayor in today's primary in this Democratic city. No clear
front-runner is apparent in the three-way competition. By Francis
X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEM-CELLS (Undated) _ The National Bioethics Advisory
Commission recommends that the government allow federal funds to be
used to support scientists who want to harvest embryonic stem cells
from human embryos. The research with the cells, which can give
rise to any kind of cell in the body, shows too much promise for
treating a range of diseases to hold it up, the commission says in
its report to the president. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CELL-PHONE-DEAL (Undated) _ Looking at what a joint-venture deal
between Bell Atlantic and Vodafone Airtouch would mean to their
cellular rivals. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Japanese authorities seem more alarmed by
the speed of the yen's appreciation _ more than 4.5 percent over
the last week _ than the appreciation itself, even as economists
began wondering aloud whether a stronger yen might stifle the
little vitality the long-moribund Japanese economy is starting to
exhibit. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   ORACLE-EARNINGS (San Francisco) _ Oracle is expected to report
fiscal first-quarter earnings after the close. The forecast is for
16 cents a share. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-INSURE (Rome) _ Assicurazioni Generali SpA, Italy's
biggest financial company, has made an unsolicited offer to buy
Istituto Nazionale delle Assicurazioni, the nation's No. 3 insurer,
for $12.8 billion, thwarting INA's plans for a friendly merger with
San Paolo-IMI SpA, Italy's top bank. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-PUBS (London) _ Accelerating a consolidation of
Britain's pub chains, the brewer Scottish &AMP; Newcastle has agreed to
buy 765 pubs and restaurants from Greenalls for $1.8 billion. By
Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS-KINGS (London) _ Marks &AMP; Spencer, Britain's biggest
clothing retailer, plans to sell Kings Super Markets of New Jersey
and focus its expansion efforts in the United States on clothing
retailer Brooks Brothers. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 2:10 p.m., stocks were mixed. The Dow
Jones industrial average was down 90 points, but the Nasdaq index
was up 11 points. The 30-year bond was yielding 6.11 percent. In
Europe, stocks were lower, with London down 0.60 percent and
Frankfurt down 0.68 percent. In Tokyo, the Nikkei closed down 0.74
percent, and the Hang Seng index closed down 0.41 percent. By
Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
