<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURIST PARK COULD ENRICH AMARILLO AREA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of us who live in Texas don't think of Amarillo as the
tourist center of the state. Actually, we don't think of Amarillo
as the center of anything. It has to do with geography.
</P>
<P>
   It is an extremity, to be frank. It is the part of the state
that map makers cut off. You can get El Paso, or you can get
Amarillo; but generally you can't get both.
</P>
<P>
   What we forget is that Amarillo is all some visitors see of
Texas. Traveling from the Northeast or the Midwest, millions of
motorists take Interstate 40 across Oklahoma, and through the Texas
Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   They like to stop in Amarillo. They have to stop in Amarillo. It
breaks the monotony of wheat fields and windmills. It offers
several entertaining opportunities. It has bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the year, visitors can drop down to the Palo Duro
Canyon for the musical pageant Texas, where flag-carrying horsemen
ride to the rim of the canyon while lightning flashes overhead and
thunder rolls through the valley.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the American Quarter Horse Association Museum and
Headquarters, the Panhandle Plains Historical Museum in Canyon, and
a cowboy breakfast on the canyon rim every morning.
</P>
<P>
   But those are things to see and do while passing through, and,
as good as they might be, they aren't what people in the travel
industry call ``destination sites.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, travelers see Amarillo on the way to somewhere
else.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Hess wants to change that. He envisions a cultural heritage
center in the Palo Duro Canyon that will be both a resort and an
entertainment center. A place where visitors will come and stay for
days at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have produced Texas for 34 years,'' said Hess, director of
the musical drama. ``We are the official play of Texas, and we have
people from all over the world come to see it. They often say,
`This is a magnificent place, what else is there to do?'''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Hess said, there have been no answers for them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, armed with optimistic feasibility studies, Hess and other
Amarillo promoters are ready to build a giant tourist park on the
edge of Palo Duro Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe strongly in cultural tourism,'' he explains. ``We
want to unite the area history, culture and natural wonders. We
want to bring them together in a concept that will be appealing to
visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Hess and his group want to showcase the authentic
cowboy, Native American and Spanish-Mexican cultures that are a
part of the Texas Panhandle heritage.
</P>
<P>
   It will be done primarily through the performing arts, he said.
It will be something of a theme resort, but without rides.
</P>
<P>
   All Hess needs now is funding. He said it would take about $25
million to get the first phase up and running. If he had the money
now, it would take 18 months to get started.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hefty price tag, but Hess isn't worried. He thinks the
project is worth the worry, the effort, the years of planning. He
is looking for investors now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't chart a course into the future without understanding
where we came from,'' he said. ``It is important to our young
people.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)Nstar-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
