<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-INTERESTS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    SPECIAL INTERESTS LOOKING FOR WAYS TO SALVAGE TAX CUTS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The American public, which greeted the $792 billion
Republican tax cut with a yawn, may hardly notice when the bill is
sent to President Clinton for his promised veto later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Republican rallies and town hall meetings, constituents
have not caught the tax-cutting fever. In fact, some lawmakers
found more enthusiasm for using future surplus funds for paying off
the still growing federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   But for dozens of special interests and their lobbyists, the big
10-year tax cut bill is still the opportunity of a decade.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 10 percent of the tax breaks are custom-built for
businesses of all sizes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Defense contractors, and multinational insurance companies and
oil companies won breaks for overseas operations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chicken farmers in the Mid-Atlantic states won credits for
burning poultry waste to produce electricity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Boat captains in Alaska would be allowed $7,500 deductions for
taking Eskimos out for their ritual whale hunts.
</P>
<P>
   _ A manufacturer in Illinois convinced Congress to drop an
excise tax on fishing tackle-boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the tax cuts can be traced to political clout.
</P>
<P>
   In the case Plano Molding Company, said to be the largest
tackle-box maker in the country, it didn't hurt that it was located
in Plano, Ill., in the home district of the Republican House
Speaker Dennis J. Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Money was a key indicator, according to a study made by Common
Cause, a private group that criticizes the role of money in
politics. The study noted that nine industry groups that scooped up
$60 billion in tax cuts also had contributed $180 million in
unregulated ``soft'' money to the two parties over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Groups that won tax breaks also tended to spend heavily on
lobbying. The Center for Responsive Politics, a non-partisan
research group calculated that last year insurance companies spent
$77 million on lobbying, the oil and gas industry spent $58
million, the computer industry $39 million and the defense industry
$28 million.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the expected failure of the initial tax bill, these
groups could have a stronger hand as they plot their salvage
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not prepared to wait till next year,'' said Lonnie
Taylor, chief lobbyist for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, who is
pushing forward for business tax cuts, even if the final compromise
bill is less than half the size of the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a tough job, but we've met tough challenges
before,'' Taylor said. His organization has already sent out an
``urgent action call'' for members around the country to contact
their lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the breaks are considered a shoo-in, even if the final
tax cut bill is scaled down to a bare minimum.
</P>
<P>
   So-called ``must pass'' provisions include research and
development tax credits, which expired last June. These credits are
a top priority for pharmaceutical and high tech companies, that are
also a major source of funding for the political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Finding room for brand-new provisions on a slimmed down tax bill
of no more than $300 billion could be more difficult, but not
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Lockheed Martin led a coalition of defense
contractors in obtaining tax credits for overseas arms sales,
similar to those given other types of manufacturers for their
exports. For defense industries, the long-sought credits would save
$1.1 billion over the projected 10-year life of the proposed tax
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in limbo, waiting to see what happens,'' said Alexis
Allen, spokeswoman for the Aerospace Industries Association that is
lobbying for the tax credits. If this effort fails, she said, there
will be other tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, winning approval is often much easier after a tax break
has been around the track once.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an item is included in a tax bill that passes the Congress,
it's easier for the proponent to go back to Capitol Hill,'' said
Evan Liddiard, a former aide for the Senate Finance Committee, who
is now a partner at KPMG accounting firm. ``It puts it higher on
the priority list.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled lobbyists coming to him to urge a provision by
saying, ``If it was a good idea then, why isn't it a good idea
now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very powerful argument,'' Liddiard said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the explosion of special interest items on the current
tax bill has dampened support, even among some of the staunchest
proponents of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing more special about these than any of the
dozens of other (special tax breaks),'' said Pete Sepp, spokesman
for the National Taxpayers Union. ``They're the direct result of
applying the right pressure in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Taxpayers Union, which never saw a tax cut it didn't like,
supports the bill ``warts and all,'' Sepp said. ``But we would hope
that Congress would pass cuts that are across the board for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
