<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANK-WILLIAMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLUB PLANS MUSICAL CELEBRATION FOR HANK WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The idea of a Hank Williams karaoke may find
some people shaking their heads, but others can't wait to get on
stage and break into ``Jambalaya'' or ``Settin' the Woods on Fire''
or ``I Can't Help It If I'm Still in Love With You.'' For those
folks, the Elbo Room in San Francisco is hosting a sing-along
Wednesday night in honor of Hank Williams' 76th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a sign-up sheet for singers who can take the stage
one by one to launch into their favorites, with the Rounders band
rushing to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have songbooks people can go through, sheets of
lyrics,'' said Rick Quisol, drummer for the Rounders. ``When they
come up on stage we'll figure out what key they want to sing in, on
the spot, and away we go.''
</P>
<P>
   Quisol has been the guiding spirit behind the Williams birthday
party, going into its ninth year, as it has moved from club to club
in San Francisco. The party was held last year at Marco's 23 Club,
and before that it was hosted by Cafe du Nord, the Ace Cafe, Bottom
of the Hill, Club Paradise and the Hi-Ball Lounge.
</P>
<P>
   A Williams memory from the Hi-Ball night is one of his best,
said Quisol: ``Someone came up from Japan, could barely speak
English, and he wanted to do a Hank Williams classic, `Lovesick
Blues.' We didn't know what to expect ... kind of prepared for the
worst ... but this guy hit the microphone and nailed it. He just
nailed it, yodeling and everything. He had it completely down.
Everybody in the band, their jaws just dropped, and the people in
the club were yelling and applauding ...''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who died of a drug overdose in the back of a Cadillac
on New Year's Eve 1952, would have been 76 years old on Sept. 17.
From almost the day he turned to music, Quisol has made it a point
of marking Williams' birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized a lot of songs I kept hearing in my childhood _
Rosemary Clooney doing `Cold, Cold Heart,' other pop songs _
belonged to Hank Williams,'' Quisol said. ``To me, his music speaks
to everyone, from all different walks of life, and that's who comes
to these things.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got so many people who know Hank Williams songs,
without really realizing it. It's not just for people who are
country music fans. ... So many different kinds of people come to
this, you don't know what to expect. The spirit of celebration is
what counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Nowicki, steel guitar player for the Rounders, said people
can't get enough of a Williams song, even if it is played over and
over. ``You'll play the same song two, three times in a row and it
won't matter to the next person,'' he said. ``It's their favorite
Williams tune, too, so you just change the key and go at it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admission to Williams night, which starts at 9:30 p.m., is $5.
For more information, call the Elbo Room, 647 Valencia St. in San
Francisco, at 415-552-7788, or 415-468-4454.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
