<HEADER>
A1651 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-ALMODOVAR-WOMEN-NYTSF     09-14 1739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALMODOVAR-WOMEN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 ALMODOVAR and HIS WOMEN  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.  By JONATHAN VAN METER  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    When Pedro Almodovar learned that the Hollywood Madam, Heidi
Fleiss, once employed a prostitute who went by the name of Norma
Jean Almodovar, he was tickled no end. ``This is really
something,'' he says, in his amusing, broken English. ``And she was
police before she decided to become prostitute. This is very
interesting and very honest.''
 &HT;    Only in Almodovar's strangely ordered universe would a
cop-turned-whore seem honest. Almodovar's 13th film, ''All About My
Mother,'' which opens the New York Film Festival on Sept. 24,
features Sister Rosa, a nun who contracts AIDS from a drag queen _
who, as it happens, is also the father of Rosa's baby.
 &HT;    Nearly all of Almodovar's films since his 1980 feature debut are
populated with transsexuals, porn stars, drag queens,
sadomasochists and drug addicts.
 &HT;    But simply to list these character types is to give the wrong
impression.
 &HT;    ``Never has sex looked more appealing,'' says John Waters, the
Baltimore director who is often grouped with Almodovar.
 &HT;    His films are ``gay and straight and all sexualities put
together in the best possible way,'' Waters adds. ``Even the
strangest sexuality in his films is always joyous and funny.''
 &HT;    Oddly enough, it's the unconventional subject matter _ freaky
characters, sex, drugs _ that has helped insure the success of his
movies in the United States.
 &HT;    ``One of the glories of his work,'' says Richard Pena, the
programming director of the New York Film Festival, ``has been the
fact that all of these issues can be handled, not only in comedy,
but with a kind of subtlety and generosity. These are relationships
that people have: you deal with the transvestite who used to be
your boyfriend.''
 &HT;    But, to borrow the phrase that his most successful film made
clichi, Almodovar seems to be on the verge of something different.
His two most recent films, ``The Flower of My Secret'' and ``Live
Flesh,'' showed signs of maturation and newfound writing skill that
are even more evident in ``All About My Mother,'' which caused a
sensation at Cannes earlier this year.
 &HT;    The film tells the story of Manuela, whose teen-age son is
killed by a car; she goes in search of her son's father, who is now
named Lola.
 &HT;    While the so-called freaks and junkies are firmly in place,
``All About My Mother'' is really a film about women _ mothers,
nuns, actresses and, yes, transsexuals and drag queens.
 &HT;    The film draws from a variety of legendary femalecentric sources
_ ``All About Eve,'' ``A Steetcar Named Desire,'' John Cassavetes's
``Opening Night'' and Truman Capote's ``Music for Chameleons,'' to
name a few.
 &HT;    However, this is not, as Almodovar says, ``passive tribute,''
but rather, wholesale sampling. It's as if all of his influences
and ideas about women have finally jelled into something profound.
 &HT;    Indeed, professionally, Almodovar seems pleased and relieved to
have arrived at a more mature vision. Personally, though, he is
having a much tougher time.
 &HT;    Almodovar talks endlessly and with great intensity _ in both
Spanish and English _ sometimes switching language midsentence. In
conversation, he displays a spectacular confidence that
occasionally veers toward arrogance. Utterances like, ``The decade
of the 80's, absolutely I'm the owner of that decade,'' roll
effortlessly off his tongue.
 &HT;    It's not hard to imagine that he might be difficult to work
with. He himself admits to having ``burned up'' relationships with
longtime friends; of the actresses that he's famous for working
with _ and famous for falling out with _ he says: ``I have problems
with all of them. My relations with them are so intense, sometimes
it's very similar to the worst part of love and sex
relationships.''
 &HT;    Cecilia Roth, who appeared in Almodovar's first four films and
returns after 14 years in ``All About My Mother,'' says: ``He is
like a lover! He asks everything about you! He needs everything!
He's curious and intense and possessive, like a boy.''
 &HT;    Seeming younger than his actual age is clearly something that he
works at: he sometimes dresses like a teen-ager, dyes his hair dark
brown, wears trendy long sideburns and lies about his age (which
falls somewhere between 48 and 52).
 &HT;    Once notorious for his late-night club crawling, Almodovar
insists that he no longer goes out.
 &HT;    ``In the last two years,'' he says, ``I've isolated myself a
lot. I can't continue to lead the same life I led 20 years ago in
Madrid. Aside from the fact that I would die, I would be very
bored.''
 &HT;    Almodovar says he ``did a lot of cocaine in the 80's,'' and just
four years ago stopped ``experimenting'' with drugs.
 &HT;    ``In my 40's, something changed,'' he says. ``You can't be out
the whole night and pretend to have a clear brain to write
wonderful lines. No wonderful lines at all. It's a pity, because,
at 40-something, I've got the same needs as when I was 20.''
 &HT;    One of the most popular foreign-language directors in America
(all of his films since 1980 have been released here and all have
made a profit), Almodovar is something of a national hero in Spain.
 &HT;    ``People on the street go up and embrace him as if he were a
member of their family,'' says Marisa Paredes, who has starred in
several of his films.
 &HT;    Says Henny Garfunkel, a New York photographer and friend of
Almodovar's, ``He's the Andy Warhol of Spain.''
 &HT;    Like Warhol, and like John Waters, Almodovar is known for
putting hard-to-believe characters, especially women, in his films.
 &HT;    ``All the freaks look up to me,'' he says. ``I remember in Rome,
the most incredible fat girls that you can imagine came to my
hotel. I've become sort of like the Saint of the Freaks.''
 &HT;    Waters recalls being at a film festival with Almodovar in Italy:
``We were constantly fleeing drag queens, running up those little
streets trying to escape. Pedro and I have laughed about that,
because who else are they gonna go to?''
 &HT;    But Almodovar says he has come to hate the attention. ``I feel
more alone all the time,'' he says. ``I've never really had the
vanity to enjoy those sorts of things.''
 &HT;    Worse yet, he has become sick of himself and the very style that
he has created: ``Before making 'The Flower of My Secret,' I felt,
like, saturated to be Almodovar. Many times I hate my name. I
became commonplace. They made me an adjective: This is
Almodovarian. Which is the worst that can happen to you. I'm sure
that Fellini felt very bad about it.''
 &HT;    In ``All about My Mother,'' Antonia San Juan, a transsexual who
plays a transsexual named La Agrado, delivers an anti-drag-queen
manifesto.
 &HT;    ``It cost me a lot to be authentic,'' she says, proud of the
commitment to sex change. ``But we must not be cheap in regard to
the way we look. Because a woman is more authentic the more she
looks like what she has dreamed for herself.''
 &HT;    It's an idea that Almodovar has been exploring for some time,
that the very definition of ``woman'' is up for grabs. The major
conceit of the film is that all women are actors _ that the state
of being female is a state of constant performance. Therefore, men
who pass for women, who engage in the drama and costume of the
feminine, are on the same plane as women.
 &HT;    While Almodovar is widely _ and duly _ admired for his
portrayals of strong female characters, he is not entirely free
from the taint of misogyny.
 &HT;    ``Federico Garcia Lorca said 60 years ago that Spain was a
country of actresses,'' Almodovar says. ``Not a country of actors.
And he was right. Even now. I think there's something about the
Mediterranean male that makes him less interesting than the
Mediterranean female. Particularly coming from a machista culture.
Men there seem to be made of almost one piece, or two at the most.
 &HT;    ``And yet women seem to be made of many more pieces. They have a
greater capacity to surprise. Their suffering is more spectacular
than that of a man. Their reactions are usually more active, more
interesting and better to narrate.
 &HT;    ``And I think 'All About My Mother' deals with that _ with this
great capacity that women have to act or to fake. Which is not
exactly to lie. Because I think to lie is more in the kingdom of
men.''
 &HT;    A decade ago, with the success of ``Women on the Verge of a
Nervous Breakdown'' _ which was in many ways also about women as
actors _ Hollywood beat a path to Almodovar's door; at the time, he
was in no hurry to go to America.
 &HT;    ``When I discover the story I want to tell in English,'' he told
Time magazine then, ``I will do so.''
 &HT;    Now he has finally found his story: ``The Paper Boy,'' based on
the 1992 novel by Pete Dexter. As Almodovar describes his version,
it will be a dark and offbeat boy-comes-of-age story set in the
swamps near Jacksonville, Fla.
 &HT;    Michel Ruben _ Almodovar's associate producer and translator _
told me that Hollywood executives are a bit mystified as to why
Almodovar chose ``The Paper Boy,'' a story that's about as far as
you could possibly get from the demimonde of Madrid.
 &HT;    Says Ruben, ``There's nothing in it that screams 'Almodovar.''
 &HT;    But, of course, that's precisely what Almodovar wants: to get
away from his adjectival self.
 &HT;    ``Madrid is the cradle where I've been raised,'' he says. ``But
I need to make a change _ like the language, like the culture that
I belong to.''
 &HT;    And in the end, Almodovar isn't really coming to America _ he's
coming to Florida. And Florida, with its baroque characters and
exaggerated colors, is, in the end, very Almodovarian.
 &HT;     c.1999 Jonathan Van Meter  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jonathan Van Meter is a New York-based entertainment writer.) &LR;
