<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-JOURNAL-0915-CO     09-14 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-JOURNAL-0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: HURRICANE PREPAREDNESS CAN MAKE YOU SWEAT THE LITTLE
THINGS
 &HT;    With Photo Mug of Williams available.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COCOA BEACH, Fla. _ It's the little things that drive you nuts.
</P>
<P>
   A massive, killer hurricane is bearing down on our fair
community, the Weather Channel guys are showing grim faces, the
Governor's trying to sound upbeat _ and I'm burning up my fingers
on a three-inch sheet metal screw I unwisely tried to drive through
our stucco wall and into a wooden stud.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this French door doesn't need a sheet of plywood over it
after all.
</P>
<P>
   As much as you plan, as much as you think you know what to do
because you're a journalist and have been covering hurricanes and
their aftermath for years, it's all a different story when the
storm is bearing down on your own home.
</P>
<P>
   Evacuation is a flat-out stress monster. You make a list and
lose it. You grab the insurance papers, put them on the kitchen
counter to toss in with the other items you absolutely have to
take. Then, they get chewed up by the cat and lost under a pile of
canned food.
</P>
<P>
   Michele, my wife, put up the hurricane shutters Monday while I
was frantically trying to get home from an assignment in South
America, but there are still a million little things to do.
</P>
<P>
   You walk around trying to think of that one little thing that if
you leave undone will allow Floyd a tiny fingerhold into the
fortress you're trying to make your home into.
</P>
<P>
   Is the garage door secure? Jeff across the street is bracing his
with two-by-fours from inside, and his doesn't even face the ocean.
Ours faces due east _ about 300 feet away is the Atlantic, and in a
few hours Floyd could be smacking it dead-on with 125 to 150 mph
winds.
</P>
<P>
   After my experience covering Hurricane Andrew, we spent more
than a thousand bucks buying a heavy-duty, hurricane-rated garage
door complete with thick metal braces and extra-heavy hardware.
</P>
<P>
   I was a little embarrassed when we had it installed.
Embarrassed, too, when I sweated for days the first August we moved
in here, putting up the hardware that holds the hurricane shutters
in place. Neighbors stopped by and nodded as I worked. Their
non-committal comments left me thinking I was a paranoid
preparation-junky.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, a half-dozen people stopped as Michele bolted the
shutters into place, telling her, ``Man, I wish we had those for
our house.''
</P>
<P>
   But I'm still worried about the garage door. For all its
impressive bulk, sometimes when I'm in the driveway at night I see
a sliver of light coming from the inside near a seam at the top
right corner. Will Floyd get in there, pry open that tiny sliver
and then rip off our roof?
</P>
<P>
   Will we spend the next six months sweating in a tent in the
yard, slapping mosquitoes and kicking ourselves for not adding a
brace here, an extra stud there?
</P>
<P>
   Too late now. Nothing I can do.
</P>
<P>
   But even losing our house pales when we think about loved ones
at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Michele's sister is married to a Bahamian. They live on Great
Abaco in a tiny village called Cherokee. All day Monday Michele
gently tried to convince her sister Maria to leave with their three
children.
</P>
<P>
   But Bahamians are tough, maybe even a little stubborn.
Traditionally, they have not been able to flee because they didn't
have the means or early enough warning. Maria and her family are
staying, boarding up their home, which is on a small rise about 300
yards from the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's starting to get a little wild,'' she said when she called
about 6:30 a.m. (EDT) Tuesday. ``We just boarded up the door. We'll
try to call you later.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, we have no children to worry about, but another of
Michele's sisters who lives nearby in Merritt Island has three
little ones under the age of five. Michele spent all day Monday
trying to figure out the best direction to run. She could've headed
south toward West Palm Beach, where much of her family lives, but
that didn't look too safe. She has a sister in Tallahassee, but
that seemed too far away.
</P>
<P>
   She finally settled on a cut-rate motel in downtown Orlando,
picking it from a list she compiled off the Internet of motels that
allow pets.
</P>
<P>
   Another big evacuation problem: we have two dogs and two cats,
and most evacuation shelters don't allow pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should board them at an approved kennel,'' one hoarse
radio announcer droned on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance. The only kennels around here are likely to be
underwater, and who could bear the thought of a beloved pet left in
such a place on a night of such terror?
</P>
<P>
   It's the cheap motel. We'll run from there to a shelter if we
have to, and just take the animals and hope for the best.
</P>
<P>
   Michele pulled out at mid-morning (Tuesday). We have been
ordered off this barrier island by 4 p.m. (EDT). I'm finishing up
the last touches on trying to save the house, trying to do a little
reporting, and getting more nervous by the minute as the
neighborhood gets more ghostly and empty.
</P>
<P>
   Michele just called on her cell-phone. She's in bumper-to-bumper
traffic on the Bee-line Expressway, which is normally a
traffic-free breeze of one hour's drive to Orlando. Michele thinks
it may take three hours or more to drive the 60 miles to the motel.
</P>
<P>
   ``And one of the cats just pooped ,'' she said. ``He pooped in
the little carrier I put him in, and I don't have anything to clean
it up with. It really stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, hurricanes and all the fun little things they bring.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd may level our house, but he's going to put us through
plenty of misery before delivering the final coup-de-grace.
</P>
<P>
   And where do they get these names? I hear Floyd and I think of
the smiling avuncular barber on the Andy Griffith Show.
</P>
<P>
   I probably won't think that way after tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams is Cox Newspapers Caribbean/Latin America
correspondent. His home is in Cocoa Beach, Fla.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
