<SLUG> BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OVERTIME LOOK AT A WACKY SUNDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The National Football League got a liftoff like
never before. Four games decided in the final 15 seconds on Opening
Day, another forced into overtime. That's a record, an all-timer
for the league. But let's not confuse it with a crystal ball.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Buffalo last year? The Bills were 0-3 before the San
Francisco 49ers pulled into town. By the end, they were high on
Doug Flutie's pixie dust and bound for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the New York Jets' opener against the Niners in 1998?
They could have had visions of Garrison Hearst dancing on their
heads for the rest of the season. They went to the AFC title game
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the New Orleans Saints last year? They were undefeated
when the Niners showed up in early October, for Steve Young's 37th
birthday. He left the Superdome feeling like a teen-ager. The
Saints left feeling like a Pop Warner team.
</P>
<P>
   But without measuring long-term implications, or seeking major
historical themes, we can pluck a lot of lessons from Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   Keyshawn Johnson threw the best tantrum of his career. Upset
over Vinny Testaverde's season-ending injury in the Jets' loss to
New England, Johnson stormed off the press-conference podium, near
tears. For the author of ``Give Me the Damn Ball,'' this was a
revelation. The young receiver showed how desperately he wants to
win, and that he knows he can't do it alone.
</P>
<P>
   If Rick Mirer, a three-time castoff, flourishes with the Jets in
Testaverde's absence, Johnson and coach Bill Parcells will build
newer, higher pedestals for themselves. And rightly so.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five former Niners coordinators now in charge elsewhere,
three lost and two won. The three losers all have Super Bowl rings
as head coaches _ George Seifert, Mike Holmgren and Mike Shanahan.
The winners, Ray Rhodes and Pete Carroll, have never reached a
conference championship as head coaches. Both work under immense
shadows, Rhodes as Holmgren's replacement in Green Bay, Carroll as
the man who can never escape Parcells' legacy at the New England
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's Pats beat Parcells' Jets on a last-second field goal,
but they almost lost to a team that was using a punter at
quarterback. If Tom Tupa had won that game, Carroll would have been
ripped apart in Boston. As it is, the Pats slew Tupa and the Tuna,
while the Red Sox finished sweeping another nasty bunch of New
Yawkers. That should keep the bloodhounds at bay for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as good as the NFL openers: The five-set,
double-tiebreaker final at the U.S. Open between Andre Agassi and
Todd Martin. The score from that match looked like an international
phone number.
</P>
<P>
   Seen in the waiting room for the Green Bay Packers' relatives at
Lambeau field: A large-screen television tuned to a late game. But
the family members weren't watching their NFC Central rivals, the
Minnesota Vikings, taking on the Atlanta Falcons in a rematch of
the conference title game.
</P>
<P>
   They were checking out the Seattle Seahawks vs. the Detroit
Lions. Was it because the Packers play the Lions next week, or
because Holmgren, Green Bay's coaching expatriate, was taking a
beating from a Lions team without Barry Sanders?
</P>
<P>
   Who are these guys? Bill Schroeder, Corey Bradford, Jeff
Thomason? They caught Brett Favre's last three passes in the
comeback win over the Raiders. Schroeder and Bradford each played
only one year of college football. They are converted track stars.
Thomason is a third-string tight end who had caught a total of 28
NFL passes in six seasons before Sunday. In other words, they are
the football equivalent of the San Antonio Spurs' backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks on the horizon: McNair, McNown and McNabb. Or, on a
first-name basis, the all-Harlequin Romance QB squad: Donovan,
Cade, Peyton, Duante, Kerry, Ryan, Brett, Trent and Trent. If you
like this trend, root for Heath Shuler to make it someday. If you
don't, pull for Gus (Frerotte) and Charlie (Batch).
</P>
<P>
   Michael Irvin's end-zone pose should have put him in traction.
Richie Cunningham's PAT at the end of regulation could have put
half of Texas in traction. It hit the left upright as it went
through for the tie and a victorious trip into overtime for the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Favre and Jake Plummer both had bum thumbs on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   They both led their teams to stunning comebacks. Next, they'll
try a patch over one eye and itching powder in their helmets.
They're just evening things out for Kurt Warner and Shane Matthews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 1535EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
