<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAMESE-STYLE PORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was sitting in a Vietnamese restaurant a couple of years ago,
when a beguiling aroma wafted by. The source was a plate of pork
chops, which I immediately ordered. Some of the smells and flavors
were fairly easy to identify: garlic, lots of it, and lime and nuoc
mam, the Vietnamese fish sauce known more commonly by its Thai
name, nam pla.
</P>
<P>
   But it tasted more complex and challenging than that, and I was
determined to decipher it and then translate it into an easy dish
at home. The pork had a burned sweetness that seemed like
caramelized sugar. It also had another kind of mild acidity in
addition to the lime and an uncommon heat, not fiery but familiar
and piercing.
</P>
<P>
   Only after visiting Vietnam a few months later did I learn that
caramelized sugar is a fairly common ingredient in the cooking,
that the milder acidity was from the lemongrass used there as often
as garlic and that black pepper was added in quantities most
Americans would consider huge.
</P>
<P>
   Once the puzzle was solved, recreating the dish was not
difficult: I caramelized sugar with lime, added the other
ingredients, marinated the pork and then grilled it.
</P>
<P>
   Making caramel, however, would prevent this from being a simple
preparation, so I substituted honey. This might come at the cost of
complexity, because caramel is bitter as well as sweet, but the
intense heat of the grill caramelizes the honey to create that
effect. And that shortcut means the marinade can be assembled in 10
minutes. With the grill preheated in another 10 and the pork
grilled in 10 more, this is a great, intensely flavored, 30-minute
dish.
</P>
<P>
   You can use pork chops, but country-style ribs _ actually the
shoulder end of the pork loin _ remain moister during grilling. And
if you can find these so-called ribs with the bone out, so much the
better; you'll essentially have a one-inch-thick pork loin steak
that grills beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   As for lemongrass, this is the time of year to cook with it.
Peel it like a scallion, and virtually the entire inner core will
be tender enough to mince. (In the winter, when the stalks have
been in storage, you have to peel off layer after layer to find the
edible center.) Figure a yield of about a tablespoon of minced
lemongrass a stalk.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAMESE-STYLE PORK
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced lemongrass
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon nam pla, or to taste, or soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds boneless pork chops or country-style ribs
</P>
<P>
   1 lime, quartered
</P>
<P>
   Chopped Thai basil or cilantro for garnish (optional). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Whisk lemongrass, garlic, honey and nam pla in large bowl.
Add lime juice and pepper. Place pork in the bowl, turning to coat;
let stand while you preheat grill or broiler.
</P>
<P>
   2. Grill or broil pork, spooning marinade over as it cooks,
until nicely done, about 10 minutes. Turn only once so that each
side browns nicely. Serve with remaining lime and, if you like, the
herb garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
