<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Champagne Montaudon Brut, nonvintage, Rheims, France. About $30.
</P>
<P>
   You are going to be seeing some unfamiliar Champagne labels over
the next few months. In anticipation of millennium-driven demand,
some Champagne makers have widened their distribution in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Champagne Montaudon, a house that's been around
since 1891, first in Epernay, now in Rheims. If the other newcomers
here are as good as this one, we can all relax and go back to
worrying about the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   This is a medium-bodied wine, half pinot noir and half
chardonnay, with plenty of flavor, good acidity and the
unmistakable nutlike aroma of a classy Champagne. There is a
vintage version (1995), and also a blanc de blanc and a rose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
