<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ISRAEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL LURES MANY WHO WANT TO EXPERIENCE THE PLACE `WHERE IT ALL
BEGAN' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CECILE S. HOLMES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Nothing quite prepares first-time visitors for this
bustling country of contrasts and its ancient yet modern capital
city.
</P>
<P>
   From the bright beaches of Tel Aviv to the dismal poverty of
Palestinian communities on the West Bank, the Holy Land beguiles
and perplexes, defying definition.
</P>
<P>
   Half of all Israeli citizens are either immigrants or descended
from them. With them came bits of Poland, France, Russia, Italy,
Romania and other nations. Many cultures and customs wove into the
Middle Eastern world of late-1940s Palestine, as the region was
known before Israel became a nation in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Today, native-born Israelis are called ``sabra.'' They live in a
country still troubled by political and religious tensions. But
despite violent stumbles in the process toward lasting peace,
Israel is progressing. Visitors are in some ways safer in Israel
than in the United States, Israelis insist. People stroll streets
at night. Government security at airports and roadside checkpoints
is tight.
</P>
<P>
   Travel to Israel right now promises a wealth of memories _ and
perhaps a number of headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Many feel a tug toward this ancient land as the new millennium
dawns. Some come as pilgrims, remembering the words of the prophet
Isaiah: ``O, Jerusalem, the holy city.'' Nobel Peace Prize winner
Elie Wiesel, a Holocaust survivor, calls Jerusalem ``the city which
miraculously transforms man into pilgrim; no one can enter it and
remain unchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   Others come thousands of miles for less lofty reasons. Perhaps
they realize Jerusalem was a zenith for the ancient world; it
remains a touchstone for the modern one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically this is where it all began,'' said Pini Shani, new
head of the Israeli Ministry of Tourism's southern U.S. office in
Dallas. ``Going to Israel is kind of a circle, going back to the
beginning. I believe it would be more unusual than having a
(millennium) party anywhere else in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Many tour groups will visit late this year and early in 2000. An
estimated 4 million to 6 million visitors, double the usual number,
are expected. About 1.5 million will be pilgrims. Church groups,
especially evangelical congregations, want to visit the land where
they believe Jesus Christ lived, died and rose from the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they believe Jesus wasn't actually born 2,000 years ago
(scholars say the dating is off by several years), many Christian
pilgrims view 2000 as the year to visit the land of their savior's
birth. The date holds no special significance for Jews or Muslims,
but Jerusalem and Israel are sacred to each of the world's three
great monotheistic faiths and significant to other religions as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's capital, situated in the Judean hills, has been a
national center for the Jewish people since their charismatic
poet-warrior, King David, ordained the city his kingdom's capital
3,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was from here that Muslims believe Muhammad ascended to
heaven. Herod ruled here, at the behest of Rome, during the time of
the birth of Jesus. Here Christian Crusaders fought to recover
control of a city they held holy, massacring Jerusalem's entire
Jewish population in 1099.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic forces recaptured the city in 1187, after 88 years of
Crusader rule. About 400 years later, the Ottoman Turks conquered
Jerusalem. The city went to the British at the close of World War
I. Thirty years of British rule ended with the establishment of
Israel, though the bloodshed has continued between Jews and Arabs.
Just this month, Israel seemed closer to peacefully settling its
long-standing differences with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing months of this century, Israel is doing all it
can to promote itself as a travel destination.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the holy city of David, of Jesus and of Sultan
Saladin can add a guest spot at the Magic Kingdom to its rapidly
growing list of international credits.
</P>
<P>
   Come Sept. 30, Israel will be showcased at the new Disney
Millennium Village at Epcot in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Hosts at the Israel Pavilion will include a King David character
charged with greeting visitors before they tread a path made from
Jerusalem stone through the village. There will be a replica of the
Tower of David in Jerusalem, even an electronic Western Wall. (Both
the tower and the wall are landmarks in Jerusalem.)
</P>
<P>
   During the Disney Millennium Village's 15 months of life, 33
Israelis will run the pavilion. Its existence is yet another
example of Israel's determination to put its best foot forward
during a pivotal period for building international goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has been preparing for an increase in visitors for
several years, though government officials and tourism insiders,
from guides to hotel executives, differ on how crowded a country
tourists should expect.
</P>
<P>
   The government says it has spent $90 million to restore the
country's infrastructure. Last spring, parking lots, hotels,
bridges, even centuries-old biblical sites were under construction
or renovation. Israel spent $5 million on a U.S. advertising
campaign that used direct mail and ads in local newspapers to
attract Christians to the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first year of the millennium draws to a close,
millions are expected to respond, determined to ``walk where Jesus
walked.''
</P>
<P>
   There is Bethlehem, the city of Jesus' birth, with the Church of
the Nativity, the oldest church in the country. For the millennium,
the Bethlehem 2000 project _ largely a Palestinian Christian
enterprise _ is working to restore related sites and to improve
services for travelers.
</P>
<P>
   There is Nazareth, where Jesus grew up. Visitors should make
their way to Casa Nova Street and the Basilica of the Annunciation,
built on the spot where Christian tradition holds that the Angel
Gabriel appeared to tell Mary she would bear the Christ child.
</P>
<P>
   The present church, completed in 1966, was built over earlier
ones. Its modern design includes murals in the nave created by
artists from around the world. The more archaeologically oriented
should take the time to visit Nazareth Village, a restoration of a
village believed to be much like the one where Jesus grew up. The
interdenominational project is occurring on a grassy knoll in the
shadow of Nazareth Hospital, with financing coming from the Miracle
of Nazareth Foundation, which has a number of American donors.
</P>
<P>
   Because Israel is small (about the size of New Jersey),
travelers can see many of the country's landmarks during a 10-day
journey. Christian pilgrims should make time for Galilee, Jericho
and Caesarea, among other significant biblical sites. Travelers
also likely will want to spend time in Tel Aviv and make stops at
the Dead Sea and in Haifa.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Jerusalem, which is really two cities _ the walled
city that dates back 3,000 years and the modern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Because of crowds and reconstruction, the experience of
Jerusalem comes with a little dust, a lot of noise and a feeling
that the traveler is part of history in the making.
</P>
<P>
   For it is impossible to visit Israel without thinking about its
past. And, especially in Jerusalem, that means understanding that
the ancient and modern live side by side.
</P>
<P>
   On one corner you may find a traditionally dressed Bedouin
sitting and waiting patiently for a tourist to cough up a few
dollars for a camel ride. In the next block, you may have to step
aside for an Israeli on a cell phone (something of a national
obsession) striding rapidly on his way to work.
</P>
<P>
   The streets of the Old City are a mesmerizing blend. No visit is
complete without seeing its markets and Jewish Quarter, the Western
Wall, the Temple Mount and the Church of the Holy Sepulcher. Walk
the Via Dolorosa, the journey Jesus took on the way to his death.
To understand modern Israel, be certain to visit the Yad Vashem
Holocaust Memorial and the Children's Holocaust Memorial. Arts
events _ from museums to music, theater and dance _ are popular as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers will find an alluring blend of clothing, handmade
silver serving pieces and jewelry, pottery and an assortment of
souvenirs. Evenings call for a stroll down Ben-Yehuda Street to
watch and be watched. Pause for a cup of strong coffee or a glass
of cool juice or a drink at an outdoor cafe.
</P>
<P>
   At the millennium, there are tours led by Catholic priests,
tours led by politicians, tours planned by local and regional
church groups. Many pilgrims made their plans months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But one Catholic tour guide based in Jerusalem is so worried
about water shortages and crowds at the city's holiest shrines _
such as the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, traditionally considered
the site of Jesus Christ's burial _ that he urges people to stay
home. Savvy Israeli hoteliers say that's ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem is a great location for a vacation,'' said Leanne
Ziderman, room-division manager for the Laromme Hotel in central
Jerusalem. ``The great weather, interesting sights and hotel
accommodations are suitable for families and singles.''
</P>
<P>
   She predicted an increase of 10 percent to 15 percent in
room-occupancy rates during millennium celebrations. While many
hotels expect to be fully booked in December and January, rooms are
available at other times, she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
