<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-VIEQUES (Washington) _ The struggle over a U.S.
military target range on Puerto Rico's Vieques island turns into
political hardball. Sen. James M. Inhofe, chairman of the Senate
Armed Services panel on military readiness, threatens to dismantle
a huge U.S. naval station there unless the Puerto Ricans allow the
U.S. Navy and Marines to resume target practice on Vieques. By
STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FINANCE (Washington) _ The House of Representatives
begins to debate the divisive issue of overhauling the way
political campaigns are financed. Lawmakers are expected to vote on
an overhaul proposal tonight. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-THREAT (Melbourne, Fla.) _ Nearly 2 million people
begin evacuating from coastal areas stretching from Florida to
North Carolina as Hurricane Floyd, one of the most powerful storms
to ever threaten the United States, roars through the Bahamas. By
TONY FREEMANTLE.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-FOLKS (Palm Bay, Fla.) _ Hurricane Floyd may be
dangerously powerful, but then some people are just powerfully
stubborn. Some residents of Palm Bay, just south of Melbourne, say
they aren't going anywhere. By LISA TEACHEY.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-EVACUATION (Melbourne, Fla.) _ We talk to Florida
residents and tourists as they settle into shelters and head to
inland hotels and homes of relatives to escape a potential hit by
Hurricane Floyd. By TERRY KLIEWER.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Bryan, Texas) _ Prosecutors present more evidence
in the capital murder trial of Russell Brewer, who is being tried
in the dragging death of a black man. Brewer, 32, is the second of
three white men accused of killing James Byrd Jr., 49, of Jasper.
By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   BEEF-RECALL (San Antonio) _ The H-E-B Grocery Co. recalls 20,000
pounds of ground beef sold in the San Antonio-Austin area over the
weekend. Company officials say a sample was tainted with the
potentially deadly E.coli bacteria. Earlier this month, two people
died and 771 people became ill in an E.coli outbreak in upstate New
York. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TRIP (Queenstown, New Zealand) _ President Clinton
discusses the environmental health of Antarctica on the final day
of a five-day visit to New Zealand. On the first leg of his trip,
the president spent three days in Auckland for meetings with Asian
leaders and the annual summit of the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation forum. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ The Houston Astros put their
franchise-record 11-game winning streak on the line tonight at the
Astrodome against the Philadelphia Phillies. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Right-wing media motormouth Patrick
Buchanan is always spoiling for a good political fight. A
presidential bid on the Reform Party ticket would make him just a
spoiler. But he's generated little support for his current GOP
presidential campaign. How much damage to the major parties would
he really do? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
