A1737 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-COPS-INTELLIGENCE-HNS     09-14 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPS-INTELLIGENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT MAN `TOO SMART' FOR POLICE WORK ASKED TO APPLY IN SAN
FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RYAN KIM  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A man who was judged too intelligent to be an
officer for the police in New London, Conn., has been invited to
apply for a job in San Francisco, where Police Chief Fred Lau said
smart applicants should be welcomed, not discouraged from joining
the force.
</P>
<P>
   Lau extended the invitation Monday to Robert Jordan, 48, after a
U.S. District Court recently ruled that New London officials were
justified in rejecting Jordan based on the results of an
intelligence screening test. He scored a 33 out of 50 points, well
above the 20 to 27-point range that is recommended for potential
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this story is true of rejecting someone for their
intelligence, that just baffles me,'' Lau said. ``We should be
encouraging anyone that is intelligent, enthusiastic or caring to
submit an application with the San Francisco Police Department.''
</P>
<P>
   Lau said turning down police applicants because they may be too
smart only perpetuates an image of dim-witted, keystone cops in an
era when police work is increasingly more complex and demanding. He
said the Police Department, which numbers more than 2,000 sworn
officers, includes at least 10 officers with law degrees and a
handful of others with doctorates.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers are expected to be better versed in the
intricacies of the law and are called upon to work closely with
residents to solve problems, Lau said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to need people who could physically break up a
fight,'' he said. ``Now, we need people who can talk you out of a
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Lau said he is not guaranteeing a job to Jordan or anyone else
who applies with similar qualifications. But Lau said the
department, which is poised to hire another 200 officers in the
coming months, could do well with people like Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, a former insurance salesman who lives in Waterford,
Conn., applied for the job on the New London police force three
years ago. As part of the process, he took a 12-minute test
produced by Wonderlic Inc., an Illinois- based testing company.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderlic has been publishing screening tests for 62 years and
has helped close to 50,000 companies screen more than 120 million
applicants. Several months after taking the test, Jordan found out
that his scores were deemed too high and in 1997 he sued the
department.
</P>
<P>
   New London Police Chief Bruce Rinehart said that applicants who
score above the average may later become bored with the job or
frustrated by their inability to quickly advance in the department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
