<HEADER>
A1779 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-NURSING-HOME15-COX     09-14 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-HOME15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAWMAKERS URGED TO STRENGTHEN NURSING HOME REGULATIONS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Vulnerable nursing home patients are frequently the
victims of abuse and neglect that can lead to injury or death, an
organization that advocates tougher nursing home monitoring said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition to Protect America's Elders, a Tallahassee-based
organization, urged federal and state lawmakers to strengthen
regulations and adopt stricter enforcement of existing policies to
protect nursing home residents.
</P>
<P>
   Among the policies the coalition would like to see enacted
nationwide would be permission for families to use video
surveillance cameras to monitor the treatment given to their loved
ones during non-visiting hours.
</P>
<P>
   The American Health Care Association, an organization of
for-profit nursing homes, accused the coalition of being a front
for Tallahassee trial attorney Jim Wilkes. The association quoted a
recent Wall Street Journal article which noted that the coalition
receives most of its money from Wilkes, whose practice involves
suing nursing homes. The association also noted that the St.
Petersburg Times had referred to Wilkes as ``the suing machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Keegan, the association's vice president, said federal law
does not prohibit nursing home residents from installing cameras in
their rooms, but suggested that ``24-hour video surveillance will
not help seniors and families feel secure. In fact, it's hard to
imagine a greater invasion of privacy or dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Keegan argued that rather than protecting residents, the cameras
would be used to gather evidence for potential lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition issued an 18-page report highlighting instances of
abuse and neglect. Among its findings were that one-fourth of
nursing homes in America continue to operate despite violations of
federal, state or local regulations. It also said spot checks found
that one-fifth of nursing home workers who have direct contact with
patients may have a criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Severe injuries, infections, amputations and even death are
the shameful and direct results of corporate greed, uncaring
employees, lax regulation and weak enforcement,'' said Barbara
Hengstebeck, the coalition's executive director, at a news
conference here. ``It's time to put nursing homes on notice:
America's taxpayers demand zero-tolerance for abuse, neglect and
fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Andrew D. Weinberg, associate professor of medicine at Emory
University School of Medicine, said that while there are good
nursing homes and dedicated staffers, one problem is that quality
care is not given on every shift every day.
</P>
<P>
   Often, abuse and neglect happen on late-night shifts which may
not have as many top supervisors on duty, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such problems led Gale Sweeney to hide a video camera to capture
the mistreatment given to her mother, Katheryn Baker, in a Houston,
Texas, nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said her mother repeatedly was ignored when she needed
assistance, and sometimes her mother's call bell was moved out of
reach. When her mother yelled for help, Sweeney said the elderly
woman was warned that she would be left outside in a wheelchair in
the rain if she didn't stop calling.
</P>
<P>
   Although federal and state agencies routinely threaten nursing
homes for violations, coalition members said stiff penalties are
rarely enforced and the pattern of abuse quickly returns after an
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition concluded that ``lax regulators err on the side of
protecting nursing homes instead of the helpless elder residents.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
