<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-NY-BOULEY-RESTAURANT-     09-14 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOULEY-RESTAURANT-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REINVENTION OF BOULEY BAKERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Bouley has always been a man with a plan. Too
many plans, it sometimes seems. When he closed the four-star Bouley
in 1996, he spoke of imperial ambitions that verged on the
Napoleonic, right down to the wholesale conquest of Russia and
Austria-Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   In partnership with Warner LeRoy, he planned to resuscitate the
Russian Tea Room. He also envisioned a restaurant devoted to the
cuisine of the Hapsburg Empire, a cooking school and other
ventures. And, oh yes, while these schemes unfolded, he would keep
busy with a little place called Bouley Bakery.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership with LeRoy blew up. The Austron-Hungarian
restaurant opens next week. The school lies a couple of years down
the road. But a funny thing happened to Bouley Bakery. The little
cafe with the bakery attached, intended as a place holder, became
the anchor of the operation.
</P>
<P>
   And now, after an expansion and a slick renovation, it has
quietly re-emerged as a resplendent, reinvented, finer version of
its former self. The restaurant crackles with a new energy, and
Bouley, as though responding to his new jewel box of a theater, is
turning out food that is nothing less than inspired.
</P>
<P>
   The new Bouley Bakery still occupies one of the ugliest
buildings in lower Manhattan, a squat rectangle with two grossly
disproportional windows shaped like half-moons. But the interior
has undergone a makeover that has solved several problems. The
walls and vaulted ceilings have been treated with a rose-salmon
glaze that warms up the room, for one thing, and there is now more
space.
</P>
<P>
   The bicycle shop that was next door has been turned into a twin
of the former dining room, allowing for 15 tables to be added to
the 12 of the original room. The redesign has relieved the sense of
claustrophobia while retaining the old intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, the bakery is now sealed off from the
restaurant, removing an annoying distraction and eliminating those
sad little tables near the bakery counter where hapless couples
would attempt to eat while arriving diners milled around them,
occasionally dragging a raincoat across the appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   Anything that distracts from the food at Bouley Bakery should be
considered a capital offense. It is stunningly good, and
consistently ascends to the highest level.
</P>
<P>
   As a chef, Bouley has it all _ elegance, finesse and flair. His
flavors are extraordinarily clear and exquisitely balanced; his use
of seasoning is so deft as to be insidious. Even his most complex
creations have a classical simplicity to them.
</P>
<P>
   Bouley cooks the way Racine wrote and Descartes thought. At the
same time, although French to his fingertips, he has also been
traveling, thinking and assimilating foreign influences. In the
most considered way, he has become a more daring chef, and a more
exciting one.
</P>
<P>
   A zap of citrus and a touch of saffron transform a deep,
intensely flavored seafood stock bobbing with littleneck clams and
trumpet-shape Canadian chanterelles. A lump of Japanese yellowtail,
braised to the point of melting tenderness, comes with a simple
accompaniment of shiitake mushrooms and glazed scallions, but an
ethereal, perfumed ginger sauce, barely touched with orange and
lemon, lifts the dish right off the table.
</P>
<P>
   When Bouley works foreign influences into his dishes, he does so
with impeccable taste and a light Gallic touch. A gently applied
dose of Thai curry, for example, permeates a meaty, full-flavored
lobster with citric spice, redoubling the richness of the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   For professional musicians, the real test is maintaining tonal
purity and expressive power at the softest volumes. The analogy
holds in cooking. Bouley thrives on bold flavors. His rack of lamb
with glazed salsify and chanterelles is potent, with an
intoxicating overlay of sage, but he can communicate in the merest
whisper. His cod with broccoli puree seems almost like a bad bet.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Can anyone hold an audience with ingredients this simple and
sparely presented? The answer is yes, and yes again. For textural
interest, he sprinkles the dish with minuscule cubes of roasted
potato and crunchy grains of gray Breton salt.
</P>
<P>
   Even roast chicken, a boring blur on most menus, takes flight in
Bouley's hands. It comes with an opulent Madeira sauce that enfolds
nicoise olives and organic tomatoes like a silken cloak.
</P>
<P>
   Bouley has found his match in Bill Yosses, the pastry chef,
whose creations are unfailingly elegant, restrained and
imaginative. The calorie-shy will pounce on pineapple carpaccio,
with its cool, eye-catching overlay of frostlike crystallized
coriander and lime sorbet, but Yosses can cater to the unleashed id
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Diners who demand the full monty when it comes to desserts will
not be disappointed by ``sweet pleasures,'' a multilayer affair of
thin milk-chocolate leaves separating layers of milk-chocolate
ganache and chantilly cream, all of it sitting on a toasted
hazelnut dacquoise.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its expansion and the fireworks in the kitchen, Bouley
Bakery retains the feel of a small neighborhood restaurant. Diners
feel comfortable showing up in shirtsleeves, and the staff shrewdly
maintains a delicate balance between informality and the more
disciplined level of service implicit in the food and decor.
</P>
<P>
   The key that winds this mechanism is Dominique Simon, the maitre
d'hotel, who may be as important as Bouley to the dining
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Simon, recognizable by his slightly hunched shoulders and bow
tie, paces the restaurant like an NBA coach whose team is ahead by
20 points but cannot stop himself. When new diners enter, he is
there to greet them. If a waiter somehow neglects to remove an
empty wine glass from a table, Simon appears and snatches it away.
When reading a customer from across the room, he seems to know the
differences among frowns of concentration, confusion and distress.
</P>
<P>
   There is an intensity to the service at Bouley Bakery that is
remarkable in New York. The waiters seem passionate about the food
and deeply concerned that diners enjoy it to the full.
</P>
<P>
   This goes right down the chain of command to the bread waiter,
Zahangir Khan, who plies his trade with gentle zeal. Rare is the
diner who does not subscribe to at least three or four of the
half-dozen breads on offer. And really, there is no point in saying
no to anything at Bouley Bakery. Wiser heads have arranged matters
so that the only possible answer to any question is yes.
</P>
<P>
   Bouley Bakery
</P>
<P>
   4 Stars
</P>
<P>
   120 West Broadway (at Duane Street); (212) 964-2525
</P>
<P>
   ATMOSPHERE: Elegant and intimate, with a slightly casual,
neighborhood feel.
</P>
<P>
   SOUND LEVEL: Quiet but not subdued.
</P>
<P>
   RECOMMENDED DISHES: Crab soup, roast chicken, codfish with
broccoli puree, yellowtail with ginger sauce, ``sweet pleasures''
chocolate dessert.
</P>
<P>
   SERVICE: Attentive and professional.
</P>
<P>
   WINE LIST: An imaginative bistro list of about 90 wines, with a
dozen wines by the glass and a reserve list of 30 wines.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE RANGE: Lunch, appetizers, $7.50 to $12; entrees, $24 to
$32; desserts, $7 to $9.50; three-course prix fixe, $35. Dinner,
appetizers, $7.50 to $18; entrees, $26 to $32; desserts, $7.50 to
$9; six-course tasting menu, $68.
</P>
<P>
   HOURS: Lunch, daily, 11:30 a.m. to 3 p.m. Dinner, daily, 5:30 to
11:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT CARDS: All major cards.
</P>
<P>
   WHEELCHAIR ACCESS: The dining room and restrooms are on street
level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
