<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-OILY-FISH-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      09-14 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OILY-FISH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARK-FLESHED FISH: A TASTE WORTH ACQUIRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN WILLOUGHBY and CHRIS SCHLESINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eating certain foods can be a gustatory badge of courage. Liver,
for example, or sweetbreads or even some bitter Asian greens cause
many diners to just say, ``Yuck!''
</P>
<P>
   High on this list are the so-called oily fish, like mackerel,
bluefish, pompano and sardines. These dark-fleshed fish are
routinely passed over in favor of their milder white-fleshed
cousins. But for anyone who appreciates real flavor, this is a
serious error, because these fish have what those ubiquitous white
fish do not: rich, distinctive taste.
</P>
<P>
   So why does it take courage to face these fish? Perhaps the dark
color is a bit daunting to neophytes. But mostly the same high oil
content that makes these fish so flavorful also makes them very
perishable. Many an unsuspecting diner has bought or been served a
less-than-fresh version and was left to believe that that was the
way the fish was supposed to taste. End of experiment.
</P>
<P>
   This problem should be a thing of the past. With improved
methods of bringing fish to market, it is not that difficult to
find very fresh bluefish, mackerel, sardines, pompano or their
highly popular colleagues in this group, tuna and salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Once a food has a tarnished reputation, though, it can be hard
to rehabilitate it. So perhaps a bit of attitude adjustment is in
order. Instead of thinking of these fish as oily, consider them
rich-fleshed, and health-enhancing, too.
</P>
<P>
   Making this mental change-over can bring great rewards. Stronger
flavors are intrinsically more interesting to the adventurous
palate and can also hold their own with aggressive ingredients like
hot chilies, tangy citrus and briny olives. This allows the cook a
much wider latitude in creating bold dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Rich-fleshed fish also have an advantage when it comes to
cooking methods. Because their high oil content keeps them moist
and helps prevent their sticking to cooking surfaces, they lend
themselves well to grilling or broiling. For the same reason, they
are ideally suited to smoking, a technique that imparts deep, rich
flavors to seafood.
</P>
<P>
   And in a deliciously paradoxical twist, the health benefits of
these fish come from that bad boy of nutritional policy, fat.
Called omega-3 fatty acids, the fats in these fish are thought to
have many benefits, the best-established being the prevention of
heart problems. Omega-3's have been repeatedly shown to help
prevent heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts, including researchers at the Jonsson Comprehensive
Cancer Center at the University of California at Los Angeles,
believe that these fats may also help reduce the risk of breast
cancer. In some patients, omega-3's have also been able to reduce
the painful symptoms of autoimmune diseases like rheumatoid
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest _ and most surprising _ word on omega-3's is that
they may help make people not only healthier but happier. This is
the opinion of Dr. Joseph Hibbeln, the chief of the outpatient
clinic at the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism,
part of the National Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   After correlating immense amounts of data on diets and the
incidence of clinical depression in various countries, Hibbeln
found that the more fish people eat, the less they seem to suffer
from depression.
</P>
<P>
   This theory was bolstered earlier this year when scientists in
England found that individuals suffering from clinical depression
had significantly lower levels of docosahexaenoic acid, a primary
component of omega-3's, in their blood cells.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there are many fish to choose from if you want to
get the flavor and health advantages of omega-3's. While very
dark-fleshed fish like mackerel, sardines and herring are the
highest in oil content, rainbow trout, lake trout and the
ever-popular salmon are also prime examples.
</P>
<P>
   A single serving of Atlantic salmon, for instance, contains 18
times as much omega-3 as the same-size piece of cod or mahi-mahi.
Whichever of these fish you choose, buy only the very freshest.
They are almost always sold as whole fish, which you can then ask
to be filleted.
</P>
<P>
   Apply the usual visual tests: the eyes of the fish should look
bright rather than dull, and its surface should be bright and
glistening, with a clear, almost translucent quality. The flesh
should be firm and unbruised.
</P>
<P>
   But the surest test is to sniff the specimen you are considering
buying. It should smell like fresh sea water, not ``fishy'' or
tinged with ammonia. If in doubt, go to the next fish.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find fresh mackerel, bluefish or sardines for the
recipes here, you can always substitute salmon, which is available
in good quality year-round because it is so widely farmed. And
fortunately, there seems to be little difference in omega-3 content
between farmed and wild fish.
</P>
<P>
   If you give these rich-fleshed fish a try, you may discover to
your delight that there was nothing to be afraid of in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   (RECIPES FOLLOW IN 2nd TAKE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BROILED BLUEFISH WITH GREEN OLIVE RELISH  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   { cup pitted, brine-cured green olives
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   { medium red onion, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   \ cup roughly chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 8-ounce bluefish fillets, each about 1{ inches thick
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons ground cumin.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a bowl, combine olives, garlic, red onion, parsley, olive
oil, lemon juice and salt and pepper to taste. Mix well, and set
aside. (May be refrigerated up to 4 days; bring to room temperature
before using.)
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat broiler. Rub bluefish lightly with vegetable oil, and
sprinkle with cumin and salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place the fish on a broiler pan, and broil until the flesh is
completely opaque throughout, about 5 to 8 minutes a side,
depending upon thickness. To check for doneness, slide a sharp,
thin knife into one piece, and peek inside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Put several tablespoons of relish on each plate, place fish
on top, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   LIME-MARINATED MACKEREL WITH ORANGE-CUCUMBER RELISH
</P>
<P>
   Time: 35 minutes plus 2 hours for marinating  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 8-ounce mackerel fillets (or substitute kingfish, pompano or
salmon)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 navel oranges, peeled, seeded and chopped into bite-size
pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 large cucumber, peeled, cut in half lengthwise and sliced into
quarter-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   { small red onion, halved and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons red-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon red pepper flakes (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place fillets skin side down in a small, flat plastic
container or baking pan in which they fit snugly. Sprinkle
generously with salt and pepper, and pour lime juice on top. Cover,
and place in the refrigerator for 2 to 4 hours (no more than 2
hours for salmon).
</P>
<P>
   2. Make the relish: In a small bowl, combine oranges, cucumber,
red onion, vegetable oil, vinegar, orange juice, pepper flakes,
mint, and salt and pepper to taste. Mix well, cover, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Preheat broiler. Remove fillets from lime juice, pat dry,
brush with olive oil and sprinkle generously with salt and pepper.
Place skin side up on a broiler pan, and broil until opaque
throughout, about 5 to 7 minutes total. Do not turn. To check for
doneness, slide a sharp, thin knife into one piece, and peek
inside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Remove from broiler, and serve, accompanied by relish.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SARDINES WITH CHIPOTLE VINAIGRETTE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   \ cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grainy mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon pureed chipotle pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon roughly chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   { cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   12 large sardines, about 1 pound total, gutted (or substitute
bluefish or mackerel)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat broiler. In a small bowl, whisk together the vinegar,
mustard, chipotle, cilantro, lime juice and sugar. Whisking
constantly, add extra virgin olive oil in a thin stream. Whisk in
salt and pepper to taste, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Season sardines with salt and pepper, and rub them inside and
out with olive oil. Place in a flameproof baking dish, and broil,
turning once, until they are well browned on both sides and opaque
throughout, about 6 to 8 minutes total.
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove from broiler, drizzle generously with vinaigrette, and
serve hot. Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
