<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BECKETT-FESTIVAL-NYT &LR;      09-14 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BECKETT-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: PUZZLING THEN, POIGNANT NOW: A BECKETTIAN
FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Wherever one turns at the Barbican Center, there is
Samuel Beckett's eaglelike image: in posters, programs and in an
exhibition of John Haynes' striking photographs of the writer and
actors in memorable past productions of his plays. In the two
theaters at the Barbican, the home of the Royal Shakespeare Company
in season, all 19 of Beckett's stage plays are being performed,
offering theatergoers the equivalent of a retrospective of a
painter's body of work.
</P>
<P>
   The Beckett Festival, which Dublin's Gate Theater brought to
Lincoln Center in 1996, has arrived in London in an expanded
version. In addition to the plays (the long and the short ones),
there are screenings of films by and about Beckett, broadcasts of
his radio plays and talks and panel discussions by a diverse range
of scholars, critics and biographers as well as the playwright's
nephew and literary executor, Edward Beckett. The festival, which
is being presented by Michael Colgan, the director of the Gate,
continues through Sept. 18. It is as much about Beckett the icon as
Beckett the artist.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, Beckett was greeted with skepticism and, in
some cases, negativism. Now he is generally accepted as the
playwright who altered the course of 20th century theater. One sign
of the security of his stature was the welcoming speech of Mary
McAleese, the president of Ireland, who expressed in dramatic terms
her commitment to the arts.
</P>
<P>
   While extolling Ireland's Nobel laureates in literature _ Yeats,
Shaw, Seamus Heaney and Beckett _ she acknowledged that Beckett
``like the other great Irish writer of this century, James Joyce,
consciously rejected the cultural environment of the Ireland of his
era, that proud yet sometimes narrow and burdensome legacy, and
chose to live and work on the Continent.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that Beckett's work ``confronts us with the stark moral
and spiritual dilemmas of our age, sometimes with savage humor,
sometimes, it seems, with bleak despair, but never without a deep
humanity and concern for the human condition.'' As ``heir to a
glorious intellectual and literary tradition in the English
language,'' Beckett strove to reduce and distill that language to
the essential. She commented that because of such contradictions he
was ``at once the most Irish of writers and the most international
of writers.''
</P>
<P>
   Proof of that point was offered in performance, as Irish actors
(Barry McGovern, Niall Buggy, Rosaleen Linehan and others) gave an
Irish tinge to the plays while allowing the work to be approached
as generic. One change from the Gate ensemble that visited New York
was the casting of John Hurt in ``Krapp's Last Tape.'' With his
hair cropped short and a look of grave intensity, he resembled the
playwright. In this melancholic memory play, his sepulchral voice
seemed as appropriate as his shoes, which squeaked loudly and
humorously as he paced the stage and roamed through his life.
</P>
<P>
   Krapp is as close as Beckett came to writing an autobiographical
character, with his remembrance of having an epiphany standing
alone on the jetty at Dun Laoghaire and of sharing a rare romantic
interlude in a small boat. Krapp also stands in for his author when
he confronts his early, troubled days as a writer: ``Seventeen
copies sold, of which 11 at trade price to free circulating
libraries beyond the seas,'' followed by those two poignant words,
``Getting known.''
</P>
<P>
   During the festival, discussions deal with Beckett's life and
his legacy. I gave a talk on ``Beckett and His Critics'' and was
the moderator of a panel discussion in which Tom Stoppard, Edward
Albee and Jim Sheridan (the film director and writer) spoke about
``Beckett the Playwright.'' Each panelist comes from a different
country and theatrical tradition, but all bear the influence of
Beckett.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his first encounter with Beckett, Albee looked back
to 1959 when his play, ``The Zoo Story,'' had its world premiere in
Berlin on a double bill with ``Krapp's Last Tape.'' It was the
first time he had seen either play onstage and, he said, ``both
impressed me greatly.'' He added that he was puzzled that initially
theatergoers had been confused by Beckett. It was his belief that
the plays were straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   Stoppard said that he saw ``Waiting for Godot'' in the late
1950s in Bristol in a production starring Peter O'Toole. He was
transfixed, but, he said, he did not find the writing
straightforward and he still did not understand all of Lucky's
monologue. In contrast, Sheridan said that after he saw his first
Beckett, he ran home and wrote a Beckett play. It may be, he said,
``how I learned not to write a play.''
</P>
<P>
   From Stoppard's perspective, Beckett's genius was in
``redefining the minima of what theater could be.'' He said that
Beckett was so explicit in his stage directions as to lock the
actors into a performance that would conform to the playwright's
prescription.
</P>
<P>
   When Albee countered with the fact that Beckett continually
revised his plays, Stoppard suggested that the actors were then
locked into the new stage directions. He added that, compared with
the later plays, ``Waiting for Godot'' has relatively few
directorial notes from the author in the text, simply occasional
words like ``shouting'' and ``winsomely.'' Or, as Albee said,
``shouting winsomely.''
</P>
<P>
   This American playwright compared Beckett's plays to musical
compositions. They are, he said, like string quartets, which can be
played differently by different instrumentalists but remain
essentially the same. In answer to those who would say that Beckett
repeated himself, Sheridan said: ``After all, in his first two
plays, he wrote about the end of God and the end of the world. It's
hard to get past that.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that he might be sounding like a devil's advocate in
matters Beckettian, Stoppard made it clear that he was ``our writer
for our times,'' an assessment that seemed very much in keeping
with the celebratory nature of the festival.
</P>
<P>
   Coincident with the Barbican series, a new Irish play, Marie
Jones' ``Stones in His Pockets,'' opened at the Tricycle Theater in
London (after being presented at the Edinburgh Festival). In this
vibrant comedy about the shooting of a movie in a small Irish
village, two actors, Conleth Hill and Sean Campion, play extras and
everyone else, including the director, leading lady and a man proud
of his status as the last surviving extra from ``The Quiet Man.''
</P>
<P>
   What begins as a sharply satiric spoof about filmmaking on
location evolves into a full portrait of the people in this one
colorful corner of Ireland. The actors will soon work together in
``Waiting for Godot'' at the Lyric Theater in Belfast, a natural
next step for these kinsmen of Beckett.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BEAUTY-FILM-REVIEW-NY     09-14 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAUTY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN BEAUTY': DAD'S DEAD, AND HE'S STILL A FUNNY GUY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lester Burnham, played with heavenly finesse by Kevin Spacey in
his wittiest and most agile screen performance yet, is a
buttoned-down 42-year-old who desperately needs to stop and smell
the roses. But he won't get much joy from the ones in his suburban
yard.
</P>
<P>
   These fussed-over specimens are the handiwork of Lester's wife,
Carolyn (Annette Bening), whom Lester introduces at the start of
``American Beauty'' with the same devilish acuity that keeps the
rest of this satire so scalding. ``See the way the handle on those
pruning shears matches her gardening clogs? That's (italics)not(end
italics) an accident,'' Lester remarks.
</P>
<P>
   That Lester happens to be dead when he says this contributes
significantly to the film's darker side. ``American Beauty,''
directed with terrific visual flair by the English stage director
Sam Mendes (``Cabaret'') and replete with the kinds of delicate,
eroticized power-playing vignettes found in his production of ``The
Blue Room,'' strikes an unusually successful balance between the
mordant and bright.
</P>
<P>
   Its vision of curdled suburbia, where Lester's marriage is ``a
commercial for how normal we are when we're anything but,'' is also
somehow embraced with unlikely affection. And it manages to end on
a note of acceptance, even in the wake of its forced yet
brilliantly staged, devastating climax.
</P>
<P>
   As written crisply by Alan Ball (who, like Mendes, makes a most
attention-getting film debut), ``American Beauty'' takes aim at
targets that are none too fresh. His Lester is not the first
super-bland suburban paragon to drop out with a vengeance, nor does
Carolyn amount to a new take on the ambitious, frigid wife.
</P>
<P>
   But as in bourgeoisie-barbecuing movies from ``The Graduate'' to
``Election,'' it's the little things that turn the stereotype into
something memorable, from the sugary sound of ``Bali H'ai'' at an
otherwise glum Burnham family dinner to the father-daughter
give-and-take between Lester and teen-age Jane (Thora Birch, in a
veritable Christina Ricci role). ``So Janie, how was school?'' he
asks, to which the sarcastic reply is: ``It was
(italics)spectacular,(end italics) Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is set in motion when Lester, also none too originally,
goes ape for a nubile blond cheerleader (Mena Suvari, lately seen
in ``American Pie''). That she happens to be Jane's friend doesn't
stop Lester from imagining red rose petals floating out of her open
sweater. (Mendes' rueful, cleanly minimalist camera style often
gives way to such eloquent flights of fancy.) She is stimulus
enough for him to wake up out of a marriage-long coma and start
considering life's livelier possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red 1970 Firebird, the car I always wanted and now I have
it,'' says Lester of his new vehicle, the one that suits his new
career at a fast food restaurant. ``I (italics)rule!''(end italics)
Spacey's way of wringing every bit of nasty hilarity out of a line
like that is itself worth the price of admission. (His enunciation
of ``Don't interrupt me, honey'' is on an evil par with Jack
Nicholson ``Heeere's Johnny!'')
</P>
<P>
   But ``American Beauty'' is also loaded with equally colorful
supporting characters who seem to drift casually through the film
until all their fates converge.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-age voyeur next door is Ricky Fitts (Wes Bentley),
whose mother (Allison Janney) is as wordlessly miserable as Carolyn
is pert. (Ms. Bening is scathingly funny, and also quite graceful,
as a walking monument to despicable values.) Meanwhile, Ricky's
ramrod father (Chris Cooper, doing a wonderful deadpan) is a
military man notably out of touch with everyone around him.
</P>
<P>
   When two neighbors who cohabit and are both named Jim describe
themselves as partners, Ricky's father wants to know what business
they're in. (Tax attorney and anesthesiologist.)
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' hammers heavily on the notion that
nonconformity is needed here. That thought is repeated frequently
and never carries a whit of surprise. But scene by scene, the film
is full of its own brand of corrosive novelty, from the way Lester
transforms himself in hopes of attracting the cheerleader to the
revitalizing effects of Carolyn's acrobatic affair with a fellow
real estate agent (a very smooth Peter Gallagher).
</P>
<P>
   As these characters struggle viciously _ and hilariously _ to
escape the middle-class doldrums, the film also evinces a real and
ever more stirring compassion. As it detects increasingly vital
signs of life behind the absurd surfaces that Mendes presents so
beautifully, the film takes on a gravity to match its evil zest.
</P>
<P>
   There's a haunting power to Lester's last narrative note to the
viewer: that if you don't share the film's piercing vision of what
really matters, someday you will.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity, nudity,
masturbation and less solitary sexual situations, some real and
some imagined.
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN BEAUTY'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sam Mendes; written by Alan Ball; director of
photography, Conrad L. Hall; edited by Tariq Anwar and Chris
Greenbury; music by Thomas Newman; production designer, Naomi
Shohan; produced by Bruce Cohen and Dan Jinks; released by
Dreamworks Pictures. Running time: 115 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Kevin Spacey (Lester Burnham), Annette Bening (Carolyn
Burnham), Thora Birch (Jane Burnham), Wes Bentley (Ricky Fitts),
Mena Suvari (Angela Hayes), Peter Gallagher (Buddy Kane), Allison
Janney (Barbara Fitts), Chris Cooper (Colonel Fitts), Scott Bakula
(Jim No. 1) and Sam Robards (Jim No. 2). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
