A1879 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-NOTES-NYT &LR;      09-14 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: `GOOD MORNING,' UH ... `TODAY'; ABC SCHEDULE SWITCH;
`20/20' SHUFFLE; `ACTION' DENOUNCED; V-CHIP SPOKESFROG 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the unveiling of its new Times Square studio,
and with as much promotion as ABC could put behind it, ``Good
Morning America'' did stir up some reaction in its first edition
from that studio on Monday morning. The program's ratings were up
about 15 percent from the usual level, a solid indication that the
network got the extra attention it was hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the biggest stir, or at least the most noticeable,
probably came from the time period's big shot, NBC's ``Today,''
which staged a little stunt of its own in Times Square on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The moment the new ``Good Morning America'' came on the air,
NBC, which owns the rights to the large video screen on 1 Times
Square down the street, switched from its usual morning format of
NBC promotions and paid advertisements and displayed the live
picture from the ``Today'' program. That meant that NBC's morning
stars, Katie Couric and Matt Lauer, were being displayed right
outside ABC's big new picture window.
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives said they did not even notice what NBC was doing
because their main view looks north, and the giant video screen is
just to the south. But it certainly did mean that any of the fans
of ``Good Morning America'' who were enticed to line up outside the
new studio were treated to big pictures of ``Today'' to remind them
who is still No. 1 in the morning. And it will continue to mean
that, because NBC will display ``Today'' every morning on that big
screen indefinitely, said Jeff Zucker, the executive producer of
``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he made the decision to requisition the Times Square
video screen from CNBC, the business-news cable channel owned by
NBC, and the network's promotion department. He said it involved
``no revenue loss at all'' to the network.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Zucker did it: ``It was totally for fun,'' he said
Tuesday. ``What can I say? I get bored.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'' has been No. 1 in the morning for five years. The
ratings boost for ``Good Morning America'' on Monday, at least,
looks to be no threat to that dominance. The ratings for ``Today''
were unaffected.
</P>
<P>
   CBS will unveil its revamped morning program in November, with
Bryant Gumbel and the newcomer Jane Clayson as hosts. It will have
a Manhattan street view, too, in the plaza overlooking the entrance
to Central Park at Fifth Avenue and 59th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker did not say if he had any plans for that premiere, like
displaying ``Today'' on televisions in the windows of the Plaza
Hotel across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard people saying it's a war in the morning,'' Zucker
said. ``It's not a war. It's television. This was just a little
tweak.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter
</P>
<P>
   Whose Time Is It?
</P>
<P>
   When one of the season's new shows gets yanked off the air
before the television season even starts, it usually means that the
network thought the show was so awful it engaged in a mercy
killing.
</P>
<P>
   But ABC executives swear that is not the case with ``Then Came
You,'' a new comedy that had been scheduled for Thursday nights at
8:30, starting on Oct. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has pulled it off the air, but more to protect the show than
the viewers, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   The series, which is about a woman in her mid-30s living in a
hotel and having a romance with a room-service waiter in his 20s,
was promising, an ABC executive said, but the network schedulers
had rethought Thursdays, having seen how well back-to-back episodes
of the improvisational sketch series ``Whose Line Is It Anyway?''
were doing on that night this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose Line,'' which stars Drew Carey, is apparently able to
produce as many episodes as ABC wants, and at a price far lower
than that of a sitcom, which requires sets and writers. So ABC
decided to stick with double runs of ``Whose Line'' on Thursdays,
shelving ``Then Came You'' until mid-season.
</P>
<P>
   Another executive close to the production of the sitcom said ABC
was also concerned about the comedies, like ``Oh Grow Up'' and
``It's Like You Know,'' that it has scheduled between hit shows on
Tuesday and Wednesday. The network may need a comedy to go into one
of those spots, the executive said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter
</P>
<P>
   First-Person Plural
</P>
<P>
   All four nights of ABC's news magazine ``20/20'' will look
different this fall, but the biggest change will be seen on
Thursdays. On that night, dominated in recent years by NBC's
``ER''-anchored lineup, the program will be called ``20/20
Downtown'' and will feature correspondents roving far afield to
tell first-person stories. To conjure up an imaginary example: John
Miller, well known for reports on organized crime, might take
viewers to the scenes of some of his reporting and recount how he
learned what he did.
</P>
<P>
   An example has to be imagined because Victor Neufeld, the
executive producer, is not yet ready to say what sorts of reports
or even what locations are being pursued, except that they will be
outside the studio and often outside New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `downtown' element is more a state of mind,'' he said
Tuesday, ``a getting away from the traditional places. It's based
on a desire to try something a little different, a little more
distinctive.''
</P>
<P>
   The other editions of ``20/20'' will still originate in the
studio, but all the anchor assignments have changed. Jack Ford,
newly hired from NBC, will join Connie Chung on Mondays. Charles
Gibson (who had been paired with Ms. Chung) will take over Sam
Donaldson's chair on Wednesdays with Diane Sawyer. And now that
Hugh Downs has retired, Barbara Walters will go it alone on
Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   What of Donaldson? He will remain a correspondent and substitute
anchor for ``20/20,'' will keep his co-host role with Cokie Roberts
on the Sunday morning interview program ``This Week'' and will be
ABC News' chief national correspondent (no longer chief White House
correspondent).
</P>
<P>
   He is also adding a new role: three days a week he will
broadcast a live 15-minute news report on the Internet
(SamDonaldson(AT)abcnews.com), at 12:30 p.m. Eastern time on
Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays. It will be available as streamed
video, for those whose computers have that option, as well as audio
and text.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawrie Mifflin
</P>
<P>
   Shocked and Appalled
</P>
<P>
   William Bennett, the former U.S. education secretary who has
become a self-appointed pollution monitor for the nation's movie,
music and television industries, and Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn., held a news conference in Washington Tuesday to express
their outrage over two new Fox series, ``Action'' and ``Get Real.''
They gave their third Silver Sewer Award, a laurel they invented to
dishonor people whom Bennett and Lieberman perceive as purveyors of
cultural filth, to Rupert Murdoch, chairman of News Corp., which
owns Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Already the most talked-about new show of the fall season for
its sexual subject matter and bleep-mouthed dialogue, ``Action''
has its premiere Thursday night at 9:30. A cynic would have to
surmise that the cast, producers, studio and network were privately
delighted about the timing of Bennett and Lieberman. What better
way to whip up curiosity about a show _ especially among the young
adult viewers Fox desires _ than to proclaim the show vulgar,
shocking and bordering on indecent?
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawrie Mifflin
</P>
<P>
   Not Easy Being Clean
</P>
<P>
   Odyssey Channel has only 29 million subscribers, but one of its
owners, Jim Henson Co., has a famous child-friendly celebrity,
Kermit the Frog. Concerned that parents do not know how to use the
V-chip blocking devices now being added as required equipment on
all new televisions, Henson and Odyssey have made Kermit the
national spokes-frog for a V-chip awareness campaign of public
service announcements, which Odyssey will permit all cable system
operators to use.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawrie Mifflin
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
