<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1894 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-DEPRESSION14-COX     09-14 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPRESSION14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buchwald goes public about depression
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pulitzer Prize-winning humorist Art Buchwald endured
two major depressions, in 1963 and 1987. Both times, he was
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Both times, he recovered to go on being funny.
</P>
<P>
   Buchwald, 73, now speaks publicly about his past depression, to
encourage others going through mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   As the featured speaker of the Rosalynn Carter Distinguished
Lecture in Mental Health Journalism, Buchwald will discuss his
ordeal tonight (WEDNESDAY) at the Carter Center in Atlanta. The
lecture is open to the public, but seats are no longer available.
For more information, call 404-614-3765.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Lillian Lee Kim spoke
earlier this week with Buchwald.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Why did you decide to talk publicly about your depression, a
subject many people consider taboo?
</P>
<P>
   A:I went on the Larry King show and talked about depression,
along with Mike Wallace. It was the most successful reaction
Larry's ever had to a show. It turns out so many people have had
depression, and were so happy to hear about it from someone who
isn't a doctor. They're grateful I've talked about it.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Carters asked me to do (the lecture) and I'm big
admirers of theirs, so I agreed to do it.
</P>
<P>
   People are worried about the stigma involved with depression.
Let's say someone's up for promotion, and it comes up that they had
a depression.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Have you ever personally encountered that stigma?
</P>
<P>
   A:I haven't, because I managed to turn whatever was going on
with me into humor. And I've never been up for promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Did you ever seriously consider suicide?
</P>
<P>
   A:Oh, sure. I didn't do it because I was afraid I wouldn't get
in The New York Times obituaries. With my luck, General de Gaulle
would die that day.
</P>
<P>
   See, there's humor in everything.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What advice would you give those now battling depression?
</P>
<P>
   A:My message is that you do get over it. You get over it, and
you're a better person. You go through an awful lot very fast. It
would take you 10 years, if you didn't have a depression, to go
through all the skeletons in your closet.
</P>
<P>
   But don't fight it alone. There now are many, many organizations
where you can get help. You have to get help. Because you can't
make it alone, I don't think.
</P>
<P>
   You can't be afraid to admit to people that you have depression.
This is the part that is tough on people. We've come a long way
with that. We're not there yet, though.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Are you worried your depression might return someday?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. I think I'm prepared for it. I sure as hell don't want to
go there again.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
