<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1896 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CHILDREN-GALLERY16-CO     09-14 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-GALLERY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Artists find gallery in new children's garden
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Sept. 16.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You expect a children's garden to be overrun with
neon-colored displays and wacky sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   But a closer look at the Atlanta Botanical Garden's new two-acre
kiddie attraction reveals some sophisticated artwork, crafted by
area artisans using forged steel, stainless steel and limestone.
The $3 million Children's Heathcare of Atlanta Children's Garden,
which opens to the public Friday, features sculptural pieces by
three artists:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Andrew Crawford, entry gates:
</P>
<P>
   Here's one artist who knows how to sell his work.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Crawford designed a steel gate containing images
of gardening tools and was later asked to show it at the
Southeastern Flower Show. The piece caught the eye of botanical
garden staff members, who asked him to suggest a piece for the
garden's entry. ``I came back with an 8-foot drawing,'' Crawford
said. ``The presentation cost me a bunch of money, but I felt it
was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Crawford, 29, the forged-steel gates, 27 feet wide by 12
feet tall, would become his most important project to date. It took
the artist more than four months to craft the 6-ton piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought a lot about how I wanted the gates to be seen now as
well as down the road,'' he said. ``What I didn't want was for my
first public installation to be fashionable. I wanted it to be
ambiguous.''
</P>
<P>
   He came up with a design influenced by forms in nature but
without being specific to flowers, leaves and other trendy garden
elements. ``I feel it hit the nail on the head,'' said the native
Atlantan, who studied sculpture at the Rhode Island School of
Design.
</P>
<P>
   For Crawford, a professional artist for seven years, the project
became more than just another commission, especially the day he
installed it. ``To be honest, at that moment I felt I would have
done those gates for free,'' he said. ``There was so much
involvement from the community. I'm out there sweating and tired,
having been up all night the night before worrying about it, and
the people got me so fired up. Everybody seemed really proud.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  David Landis, Butterfly Pavilion:
</P>
<P>
   Who says butterflies are dainty little creatures? Atlanta
sculptor David Landis, 34, turned to stainless steel when he was
selected to design a butterfly pavilion for the garden.
</P>
<P>
   The piece, a steel pergola with a stainless steel butterfly
sculpture perched on its roof and comparable butterflies for gates,
is part of an exhibit on the life cycle of the butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   The project took Landis 10 months to complete. ``The butterfly
is all fabricated, as opposed to being cast and all stainless,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Its 10-foot wingspan changes color depending on the light
reflecting on the stainless steel.
</P>
<P>
   The award-winning artist, who teaches sculpture at Georgia State
University, had done large pieces for the 1996 Summer Olympics but
never for a public garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, I had this naive notion that the botanical garden
was one of those places you just kind of go out and see,'' Landis
said. ``Now to see it expanding into a garden that children can
actually experience, it's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Christopher Condon, the Green Man:
</P>
<P>
   Chris Condon knows how to make an entrance. The artist, known
for his whimsical pieces, was commissioned to design a wall
sculpture from Indiana limestone of the Green Man, the mythological
guardian of gardens.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of creating a realistic depiction of the legendary
figure, Condon _ remembering his audience _ crafted a playful face
that beckons children across the bridge and into the garden.
</P>
<P>
   And, with water spewing from its face, this Green Man draws a
crowd. The face contains not only leaves but also a bird and bird's
nest perched on its head.
</P>
<P>
   Condon, who moved to Atlanta from Massachusetts four years ago,
earned a degree in sculpture from the Rhode Island School of Design
and studied in Rome for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved down (Atlanta) here because I knew the garden industry
was bigger here because of the climate,'' said Condon, 26.
</P>
<P>
   The children's garden provided him with further evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The children's garden grand opening is 9 a.m.-7 p.m. today for
members, Friday-Sunday for the public. Free with regular garden
admission: $7 adults; $5 seniors; $4 children 3 and older. Parking:
Only at Ansley Mall for shuttles. 404-876-5859.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
