NYT-09-14-99 1759EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1899 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-KIDS-GARDENS15-COX     09-14 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-GARDENS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gardens plot their future with children
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some childhood experiences you don't forget _ catching
fireflies and putting them in a jar, popping a muscadine in your
mouth and sucking the pulp from its skin.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the closest many children come to experiencing nature is
what they read in their science textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   That's changing, though, as public gardens around the country
develop programs that not only expose future generations to the
joys of plants but, on a more practical level, to generate more
income from admissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If children have no appreciation for nature, public gardens
won't be around one day,'' said Jane Taylor, former curator of
Michigan State University's 4-H Children's Garden, the first of its
kind when it opened in East Lansing in 1992. ``Gardens are finally
realizing they need to cater to a broader audience. Until now,
children have been bored with what they see there because there's
been nothing to relate the plants to their everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting kids interested in nature takes more than showing them
how to plant seeds, so gardens are turning to fun, interactive
themed exhibits. At the Atlanta Botanical Garden, which opens its
$3 million children's garden this week, the message is wellness, or
how humans depend on plants for improving their mind, body and
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children's gardening is no longer just activities. There's a
lot of art involved and obviously a lot of science, as well as
music, meteorology, bird watching, literature,'' said Sharon
Lovejoy, a nationally acclaimed children's gardening author and
consultant. ``Atlanta is definitely cutting edge in doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Children's Healthcare of Atlanta Children's Garden also
is unique in its genesis. The former Egleston Scottish Rite Health
Care System was seeking a means to take its wellness message to the
community. At the same time, the Atlanta Botanical Garden was
searching for new sources of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a match meant to be,'' said Tracey Atwater, special
projects director for Children's Healthcare's fund-raising
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Tough rows to hoe
</P>
<P>
   The children's hospital initially was concerned that a
fund-raising campaign for a garden might dilute community support.
``But we had an amazing response,'' Atwater said. ``Eight
individuals literally funded the entire garden.''
</P>
<P>
   And that support couldn't have come at a better time for the
botanical garden, as it launched a five-year $15 million expansion.
A children's garden topped its list of priorities because of the
potential to increase the nonprofit organization's membership _ its
bread and butter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is designed to help get entire families into the garden
because you're hitting a larger audience with teachers,
grandparents _ not just children,'' said Cindy Tyler of
Environmental Planning and Design, the Pittsburgh landscape
architecture firm that designed the garden.
</P>
<P>
   The garden's wellness theme, believed the only one of its kind
in the country, proved a real challenge. ``We had to think
carefully how children would get that message in a way that's fun
and makes them want to come back repeatedly,'' Tyler said.
</P>
<P>
   Using a time line of how plants, from the prehistoric age to the
present, contribute to good health, designers created a series of
exhibits that teach pre-schoolers to children age 11, how plants
help them ``live, laugh and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   The pathway to the garden wasn't without its obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   The first was safety. The 2-acre site, fronting Piedmont Road,
was separated from the main garden by the entry road. Architect Jim
Winer of Menefee &AMP; Winer came up with an arbored ``Flower Bridge,''
lined with planters spilling with annuals, as a smooth transition
between the two gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another challenge was keeping the botanical garden open during
construction,'' Tyler said.
</P>
<P>
   Construction delays postponed the garden's spring planting until
June and July, when the weather is hot. ``It was tough planting at
that time of year,'' said grounds supervisor Tom Harvey, who
suffered heat stroke during the project. ``But having a wet June
really saved our lives,'' given that a drought followed.
</P>
<P>
   And there was a tree dilemma. A large treehouse was planned for
a pair of 130-year-old red oaks, but some feared construction would
harm the trees. So the Woodland Treehouse was reduced to a
free-standing structure in the shadow of the stately oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the next challenge could be maintenance. Garden
horticulturist Mildred Pinnell said the staff chose ``tough
plants'' that not only feature brightly colored flowers, ideal for
attracting butterflies, but also hold up well to the rigors of
little feet prone to wander.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know which direction kids will take,'' Harvey said.
``But we can't be as strict as we are in the (main) garden about
staying on the pathways and picking flowers. This needs to be
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding a lucrative niche. Fun is what a children's garden is
all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key ingredients are that it be interactive and small
scale,'' said Cindy Reittinger, the garden's education director.
</P>
<P>
   Once hooked, children are more eager to learn about nature.
``People across the country are really concerned how out of touch
kids are with the earth. They're saying we've got to do something
to fuel their interest,'' said Lovejoy, who, in her latest book,
``Roots, Shoots, Buckets and Boots'' (Workman Publishing, $13.95),
advocates gardening as an experience to be shared by parents,
grandparents and children.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, parents say, Atlanta is short on outdoor sites
for family outings. ``There's a huge need for small-scale
activities that younger kids and parents can share,'' said Jennifer
Spring, touring the garden with 2-year-old Anna during last month's
member preview.
</P>
<P>
   Public gardens are responding by zeroing in on a lucrative niche
that not only boosts attendance but memberships.
</P>
<P>
   Just one year after opening its Discovery Garden in 1995, the
Phipps Conservatory and Botanical Gardens in Pittsburgh increased
its attendance some 150 percent, Tyler said.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, it's up an average 3 percent weekly, which it
attributes to posting staff in the garden to answer visitors'
questions. ``We found that the more interactive things we did, the
more people came,'' education director Robert Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   Docents and some staff will be on hand at Atlanta children's
garden, said Julie Herron Carson, marketing director for the
botanical garden. There, attendance has held steady the past three
years at about 200,000, So has membership, at 10,000, ``but we're
really expecting that to jump with the opening of the children's
garden.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, however, the garden recently raised its
admission prices for both children and adults by $1. Supporters
contend the increase, the first in eight years, is a small price to
pay for giving children a foundation for an appreciating nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we get them drawn in here, we can tell them why we're so
concerned about the environment,'' said Reittinger, pausing by the
Soggy Bog, an exhibit that emphasizes conservation. ``So many kids
learn about the rain forest in school, but they don't even realize
there are endangered plants right here in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing is believing.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   GRAND OPENING, Children's Healthcare of Atlanta Children's
Garden
</P>
