<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release WEDNESDAY AMs, September 15, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-SPIES (London) _ Mushrooming revelations from KGB
operative's upcoming book raise anew questions of whether Britain's
secret services are under any effective civilian political control.
By Kevin Cullen. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BOMBINGS (Moscow) _ Russian police attribute bombings to
Dagestani leader Shamil Basayev, announce seizure of TNT and fuses
at another apartment building. By Brian Whitmore. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-TROOPS (Jakarta) _ Nationalist backlash mounts, with
political leaders and the public asking why Western nations are
being summoned to solve Indonesia's problems. By Indira A.R.
Lakshmanan. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-JERUSALEM (Jerusalem) _ Only in the Middle East could
Burger King's Whopper end up in a brush with international law and
Walt Disney Co. find itself clashing with the real world politics
of the Israeli-Palestinian peace process. By Charles M. Sennott.
800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ In a debate filled with
implications for the 2000 campaign, the House moves toward a vote
on overhauling the campaign finance system and banning unlimited
``soft money'' in the upcoming election. By Michael Kranish. 800
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
