<HEADLINE>
SENATOR TIES FATE OF PUERTO RICO NAVY BASE TO REOPENING VIEQUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The struggle over a U.S. military target range in
Puerto Rico turned into political hardball Tuesday when a member of
the Senate Armed Services Committee threatened to eliminate a $300
million-a-year Navy base in Puerto Rico unless local authorities
allow resumption of target practice on the nearby island of
Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. James M. Inhofe, R-Okla., chairman of the Senate Armed
Services Committee's panel on military readiness, said would push
to shift duties from the Roosevelt Roads Naval Station in Puerto
Rico to military bases on the U.S. mainland unless Puerto Rico's
political leaders permit the Navy and the Marine Corps to resume
combat training on a 58-year-old training range on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The Roosevelt Roads base is a cherished ``crown jewel'' in the
Puerto Rican economy and is widely supported by local political
leaders, Inhofe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they don't want to lose that,'' Inhofe said. ``But
we're looking at a package deal: If the Navy loses the target range
on Vieques, Puerto Rico would lose Roosevelt Roads.''
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe said other locations in the United States would be glad
to take on functions currently handled at Roosevelt Roads, adding:
``We're working to break down the functions carried out at
Roosevelt Roads and finding logical homes for those functions back
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe has scheduled a hearing of his Senate subcommittee for
next Wednesday to explore his proposal. Rep. Herbert Bateman,
R-Va., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee's panel on
military readiness, has also scheduled a hearing on the military
impact of suspended combat training on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings will be the first full-blown congressional
inquiries into a politically charged dispute over the island of
Vieques that involves the White House, Congress, the Pentagon and
the political fortunes of candidates courting Hispanic political
support, including First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton in her
exploratory U.S. Senate campaign from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt Roads, a sprawling 8,600-acre installation with nine
piers and an 11,000-foot runway, devotes 85 percent of its annual
workload to supporting Navy and Marine Corps training operations on
Vieques and in adjacent waters.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.2 billion base employs almost 5,000 personnel, including
2,500 civilians. Roberto C. Nelson, a base spokesman, said the
installation pumps $300 million a year into the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   But operations at Roosevelt Roads have been reduced since the
Navy suspended combat-style training on Vieques in April after a
Marine Corps' pilot mistakenly dropped two 500-pound bombs more
than a mile off target at the Vieques range, killing a Puerto Rican
security guard and injuring four others.
</P>
<P>
   With Puerto Rican public opinion strongly opposed to continued
U.S. use of the Vieques target range, President Clinton has ordered
a high-level Pentagon search for options that would address Puerto
Rican opposition to live-fire training and, at the same time,
enable the Navy and Marines to continue to have an Atlantic-coast
site to carry out land, sea and air combat training.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Lt. Cdr. Herman Phillips, a spokesman at Navy headquarters
at the Pentagon, said the Navy has not determined the impact on
operations at Roosevelt Roads if Clinton orders a permanent halt to
target practice at Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Before training was suspended in April, the military used a
899-acre bombing range, an 11,000-acre maneuver range and an 8,000
acre ammunition depot on the island. Some 9,300 civilians live on
the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still hopeful for a mutually agreeable resolution to
the situation,'' Phillips said. If the president permanently ends
military training on Vieques, the Navy would then review operations
at Roosevelt Roads, Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders in Puerto Rico, led by Gov. Pedro Rossello,
and allies in Congress led by Rep. Jose Serrano, D-N.Y., are
demanding a permanent end to military training on Vieques and the
phased Navy withdrawal from the island.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe said he has discussed his plan with key Republican
lawmakers whose congressional districts already host major Navy and
Marine Corps installations.
</P>
<P>
   Those consulted include Bateman, whose congressional district
includes the Atlantic Fleet headquarters at Norfolk, Va; Rep. Randy
Cunningham, R-Calif., whose district includes the Miramar Naval Air
Station; and Rep. Tilly Fowler, R-Fla., whose district includes
constituents at the Naval Air Station at Jacksonville, Fla., and
the Navy port at Mayport, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're excited about the possibility of their bases taking on
more responsibilities,'' Inhofe said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bateman said if Navy and Marine Corps training ends on Vieques,
``it would affect in a very vital way the principal activity and
reason for being at Roosevelt Roads.''
</P>
<P>
   Bateman said he would await congressional hearings and a
Pentagon decision before endorsing the closure of Roosevelt Roads.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the other lawmakers contacted by Inhofe said the
members of Congress were receptive.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Pope, a spokeswoman for Cunningham, said that while
``dismantling Roosevelt Roads would not be our first choice, if the
people of Puerto Rico indicate hostility to the Navy, we need to
look at all the options and that certainly includes taking a look
at dismantling Roosevelt Roads.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Klein, who serves as Fowler's legislative director, said
the congresswoman would support efforts to move some of Roosevelt
Roads' functions to installations in the United States, if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roosevelt Roads is a staging and support facility for training
on Vieques,'' Klein said. ``If Roosevelt Roads doesn't have a
reason to exist, I'm sure the congresswoman would sign up 100
percent to move those assets back here where they would be
appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
