<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1924 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GIANT-SCREEN-FILMS-AR     09-14 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIANT-SCREEN-FILMS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING BEYOND THE `WOW' FACTOR ON GIANT SCREENS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shot with a 70-millimeter camera and chockablock with
spectacular adventure and nature scenes, the giant-screen movie has
become a hugely popular fixture at 300 specially equipped theaters
worldwide, but it is experiencing an identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Should the films be devoted only to outsize visual effects or
should they also be built around story lines?
</P>
<P>
   Can the entertainment values of the commercially shown giant
films be retained in educational films shown in museums and other
institutions?
</P>
<P>
   These are among the issues being discussed this week at one of
the more sedate movie conventions of the year, one held by the
international Giant Screen Theater Association around Manhattan and
at the Liberty Science Center in Jersey City, a major site for
showing large-format movies. The convention, which ends Wednesday,
has attracted 1,000 delegates, conservatively dressed, eminently
civil and concerned about the future of a medium that has recently
taken off commercially.
</P>
<P>
   Movies like ``Everest,'' which has earned $91 million, an
unprecedented amount for a giant-screen film, have put a Hollywood
spin on a field that has always enjoyed a rather documentary-like
gentility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's great growth in the commercial area and also in the
institutional, though that's a bit slower,'' said Jim Marchbank,
the association's president and chief executive of Science North, a
science center in Sudbury, Ontario. ``Many more films are being
made for both segments, and more films will cross over.''
</P>
<P>
   Giant-screen movies, like those shown at the Sony Imax theater
in Manhattan, have been around for about 30 years. Traditionally
they have been designed for either commercial or institutional
audiences, although the occasional film appeals to both. Each year
about 20 films are released, all running 40 to 45 minutes for fast
audience turnover.
</P>
<P>
   The large screen, which can be six stories high, lends itself to
spectacle, which in turn calls for dazzling clarity and stupendous
sound. Many films have nature motifs: ``Africa: The Serengeti,''
``The Living Sea,'' ``Island of the Sharks.'' Others are about
adventure and sports: ``Everest,'' ``Olympic Glory,'' ``Extreme''
(about extreme sports). But filmmakers are wondering if they should
be delivering more narrative with the grand sights.
</P>
<P>
   The conference has attracted producers, distributors and
representatives of museums, science centers and theater chains.
While they are a far cry from their hard-partying, rabidly
self-promoting counterparts at standard festivals, their goals are
similar. They have come to discuss and pitch projects, attend
screenings of a dozen films, take part in workshops, and schmooze
about the complications of making movies, sometimes in 3-D, for
soaring vertical or domed screens in auditoriums so steeply pitched
that viewers can get vertigo.
</P>
<P>
   Producers of such movies earn much less from box office revenues
than do conventional filmmakers. Institutions use the films as
fund-raisers and keep much of the proceeds. And while directors are
not working with stars like Tom Cruise, costs are high. ``Prints
are about $100,000 U.S. a minute,'' said Marchbank.
</P>
<P>
   Being in the field with a 70-millimeter camera is not a relaxing
experience. ``I'm daunted by the difficulties,'' said Tim
Liversedge, whose production company is close to the Okavango
swamps in Maun, Botswana. He has made standard wildlife films for
the BBC and National Geographic, and now, attracted by the growing
audience for giant-screen movies, he is trying the 70-millimeter
format. In keeping with the trend, he would like to stir some
dramatic narrative into the action. ``I want to tell the story of
the region,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One problem faced by filmmakers like Liversedge is the camera,
which weighs almost 90 pounds and is not exactly geared for quick
strikes in the bush. Also, there is only one camera, not three as
there are on many wildlife shoots. A film cartridge lasts only
three minutes, making it tricky to reload at a crucial moment. On
top of this, the camera sounds like a small motor, thereby
announcing itself to wary beasts. Finally, filming doesn't begin
until eight seconds after the camera has been rolling, by which
time the animal could be in the next game park.
</P>
<P>
   Working with conventional equipment, Liversedge said, it takes
years to complete a nature film, mainly because of uncooperative
animals. He hesitated to guess how long it would take with a
70-millimeter camera.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they took a camera up Mount Everest, didn't they?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everest doesn't move,'' Liversedge said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Large-screen movies experience their identity crisis most when
visual spectacle meets story line. As productions grow more
ambitious, they run the risk of overstepping themselves. Dramatic
scenarios often are not effective with audiences conditioned to
seeing roller-coaster rides, bounding lions, 40-foot waves and
crashing avalanches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary aspect has to be entertainment,'' said Greg
MacGillivray of MacGillivray Freeman Films, which made ``Everest''
and other films. ``The audience pays a lot of money for their
tickets and for a short amount of time they want a unique
entertainment they can't get elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment factor is important to museums, as well. The
institutions charge a healthy admission fee for giant-screen
movies, deriving important revenue from them and raising money that
often helps finance new films. ``It's possible for films to have
high educational and entertainment value,'' said Marchbank of
Science North. ``If people aren't having fun, they aren't
learning.''
</P>
<P>
   In museums, a film must both entertain and educate. For example,
Science North was the co-producer of ``Gold Fever,'' which
chronicles the Klondike gold rush and examines the cultural and
economic significance of gold. A film like that is not likely to
show in a commercial theater. But often the distinction is not so
clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these films are neither fish nor foul. They don't
fulfill either market,'' said Truett Latimer, president of the
Houston Museum of Natural Science.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Museum produced ``Alaska: The Spirit of the Wild,''
which was nominated for an Academy Award in 1998. Latimer is a keen
appraiser of the emerging scene in giant movies. ``You see the
Hollywood types drawn by the grosses `Everest' makes, not realizing
what the economics are,'' he said. Or that lions don't like
multiple takes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
