<HEADER>
A1930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SACKLER-ASSESS-ART-2T     09-14 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SACKLER-ASSESS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT SACKLER GALLERY, A GIFT SHINES LIGHT UPON ANCIENT CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo (NYT14)is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the Smithsonian Institution announced this
month that a trove of Chinese art amassed over nearly 60 years by
an American collector, Dr. Paul Singer (1904-1997), had been given
to the Arthur M. Sackler Gallery here, the details were rather
staggering.
</P>
<P>
   It amounts to more than 5,000 objects, with a value estimated at
$60 million, though, in fact, an item-by-item assessment of the
material is only just beginning. The gift more than doubles the
existing collection of the Sackler Gallery, which was established
in 1987 and constitutes, with the neighboring Freer Gallery, the
national museum of Asian art in the United States. And in a stroke
it transforms the Freer and the Sackler into the largest repository
for Chinese archaeological material in North America.
</P>
<P>
   With numbers like these, one might expect to find items of
unusual heft and grandeur in the Singer hoard. On the whole,
though, that is not the case. The collection certainly has its
share of show stoppers, among them a superb 3,000-year-old bronze
bell over two feet high and an exquisite third- or second-century
B.C. carved wooden horse, its lacquer-painted harness still intact.
But most of the work is low-key in appearance and small, even
diminutive, in size.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the entire collection was housed in Singer's modest
two-bedroom apartment in Summit, N.J. At the Sackler, it occupies
drawers and cabinets, not rooms. And a distinctive portion of the
material consists of ancient miniatures, many of them versions of
full-size objects and probably made to be placed in children's
tombs.
</P>
<P>
   One of these is a replica, dating from around the second century
B.C., of a classic type of ritual bronze food vessel, which can be
massive. Here it has been cast with painstaking precision, but at
less than two inches high, it looks as if it had been plucked from
a Victorian doll house. (An example of an ``adult'' version of the
vessel can be found in the Sackler collection.)
</P>
<P>
   Singer, who was a practicing psychiatrist, was well known in New
York's Asian art circles for making eccentric, seemingly whimsical
selections that turned out to be treasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made collecting fun,'' said Jenny So, the curator of
Chinese art at the Freer and the Sackler, who will oversee the
process of examining and cataloguing the Singer objects. Some of
Singer's offbeat choices were determined by finances; he never had
substantial personal wealth. Others reflect the impulses of an
inquiring, chance-taking temperament.
</P>
<P>
   He was attracted, for example, to art that was understudied and
undervalued, including regional work of a kind that has only fairly
recently been awarded full scholarly attention. ``The joint Freer
and Sackler collection was very focused on art from elite and
metropolitan cultures,'' Ms. So said. ``But Singer collected art
from the provinces, with strong local characteristics. Now we can
show these cultures together.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer was especially taken with the art of the southern state
of Chu, which flourished between the eighth and third centuries
B.C. No one in the West knew quite what to make of this
exotic-looking material when he was first buying it. Today,
however, it one of the hottest topics in the field of Chinese art
history. And, thanks to Singer, the Sackler has overnight become
the epicenter of Chu research outside China.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, perhaps because he was trained in investigating
behavior and emotions, Singer seems to have been attracted to art
less for its virtuosic dazzle than for the stories it tells. A
lacquerware cosmetics case brought out from a Chu tomb, for
example, is battered and crushed. But its contents _ combs, silk
ribbons, a hairpiece _ survive intact and bring an everyday world
of human activity vividly to life.
</P>
<P>
   Singer's life began in Europe. He was born in Hungary and grew
up in Vienna, where he studied medicine. In 1938, along with many
other Jews, he left for the United States. And although he had been
acquiring art in Europe since his teens, most of what is now at the
Sackler dates from after his arrival in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He was a classic example of the self-taught connoisseur, a
species often lamented today as a vanishing breed. He neither read
nor spoke Chinese, and visited China for the first time when he was
in his late 70s. He learned about the art close to home, tirelessly
seeking it out, looking at it, handling it, living with it.
</P>
<P>
   His art reconnaissance missions from New Jersey to Manhattan
were so regular and frequent that the staff at the Metropolitan
Museum of Art parking lot reserved a space for him at specific
times, knowing he would fill it. He was a ubiquitous presence in
museums, auction houses and galleries, and regularly spoke with art
professionals, though he had a reputation for being highly
opinionated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the crusty type, set in his ideas,'' said Thomas
Lawton, director emeritus of the Freer and the Sackler, and a
friend of Singer. ``But if you were firm, he would accept what you
said.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1957 he met Dr. Arthur Sackler (1903-1987), whose collection
would later form the basis of the museum in Washington. The men,
both psychiatrists and devotees of Asian culture, became close
friends, but they acquired art in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Sackler had money, and he often bought entire collections at a
shot. Singer tended to buy a few pieces at a time, often selling
previous acquisitions to finance new ones. Because his tastes were
idiosyncratic, he could get top-notch works, often at bargain
prices, that had been dismissed by other collectors for being of
doubtful authenticity or just plain weird.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton remembers that a New York dealer once offered Singer a
small Cubistic-looking marble bear for $150, insisting it was
nothing more than a charming modern fake. Singer knew otherwise,
but said he would buy it at a knockdown price of $125 for use as a
paperweight. The sculpture, from the late Shang dynasty, is now in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Sackler quickly came to value Singer's expertise, and though he
was, like most serious collectors, intensely territorial, he saw
that Singer's interests complemented rather than duplicated his
own. Soon after they met, he began to give Singer, who had little
cash to work with, lump sums of money on a quarterly basis to buy
art.
</P>
<P>
   The funds came with no stipulation as to what kind of art it
should be used for, and there is little question that the Singer
collection as it exists is very much a product of its creator's
eye. But Milo Beach, director of the Freer and the Sackler
galleries, said that the financial arrangement did require that
when Singer (who had no children) died, his art would go to either
to a Sackler-named museum or to the Arthur M. Sackler foundation.
</P>
<P>
   This agreement explains the somewhat complicated credit line
that will accompany all the Singer items in the Sackler Gallery
collection, and it leaves Singer's connoisseurial role understated:
``Joint gift by the Arthur M. Sackler Foundation; Paul Singer; the
AMS Foundation for Arts, Sciences and Humanities; and the children
of Arthur M. Sackler.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sackler curators are sorting through the Singer material to
determine which of the thousands of pieces will be officially
brought into the gallery's collection. (Not everything necessarily
will.) But 18 works have already been put on public view in the
museum's entrance pavilion, and they give some sense of the breadth
of the holdings.)
</P>
<P>
   They include a small bronze bell of extreme rarity (it is among
the earliest known in the West) and a gorgeous jade ritual disk
with striated patterns that almost exactly match those of a disk
that has long been at the Freer. (It is possible that they may even
have been cut from the same block.) Also on hand are the marble
bear ``paperweight'' and a cluster of ceramic jars with
naturalistic motifs that span centuries but together form a winsome
community of turrets, temples and granaries.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the Singer material, however, remains in storage
and, apart from small rotating displays, probably always will.
Although a full-scale exhibition and catalog are in the planning
stages, the Sackler does not have the space to put more than a
fraction of the objects on view at a time.
</P>
<P>
   At least some of them are probably best off left in their
drawers, either because of fragility, because they are closer to
being artifacts than showpieces, or because their once-startling
uniqueness has been superseded by the flood of archaeological
material that has emerged from China in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even the briefest glance at the collection, which is
chronologically comprehensive but has areas of exceptional depth,
is enough to suggest the contributions it might make to the
rethinking of Chinese art history that is now under way. One
intriguing item, for example, is a woven-gold necklace dating from
the fourth or third century B.C. and adorned with two carved jade
spools and two plump amber beads.
</P>
<P>
   The jadework is Chinese. But gold was imported from western Asia
(it is not indigenous to China), and the most common source of
amber was the Baltic region. So it is possible to read in this one
object the picture of a multicultural China, very different from
the monolithic and hermetic model long in place.
</P>
<P>
   Another piece, far less glamorous, tells no less absorbing a
tale. It is a lacquered wood stick with a dove, perky but homely,
carved on the top of the handle. The cane, which appears to have
been much handled, is of a type once traditionally awarded in China
to octogenarians as a sign of their well-earned status as elders in
the community. This example, from around the first century B.C.,
accompanied its owner to the grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sort of work isn't collected often,'' Ms. So said. ``It's
a document, not a thing of beauty. But objects like these humanize
a culture. Through them we can picture people's lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
