<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY CENTER LAUDS 5 IN THE PERFORMING ARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts
announced the names of the recipients of its annual honors Tuesday.
One, Victor Borge, received the official word while rehearsing for
a performance with the Houston Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't sound like it, but I'm speechless,'' said Borge,
the comical pianist and serious comedian, who admits to having
slowed down just a bit due to his age, which he said was 90, but
only 58 in American years. ``It is tough to do a phone interview
when you're speechless,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The other recipients are the actor Sean Connery, the dancer and
choreographer Judith Jamison, the actor Jason Robards and the
singer and songwriter Stevie Wonder.
</P>
<P>
   After rehearsing with the Houston musicians (``Some music from
`La Boheme' and parts of the Concertos No. 1 and No. 2 by
Rachmaninoff, and then I talk in between, and, yes, they will
laugh,'' he said), Borge told why his age was sometimes at variance
with the indisputable fact that he was born 90 years ago in
Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   He had fled from the Nazis, who occupied Denmark during World
War II and, he added: ``In America I am not that old because I came
here when I was 31, and I took a couple of years to learn English,
so I am only about 58 years old. But I don't look it.''
</P>
<P>
   Borge is one of two foreign-born recipients of this year's
honors. The other is Connery, the urbane Scot known for the James
Bond movies as well as such films as ``The Untouchables'' (1987),
for which he won the Academy Award for best supporting actor, and
``The Russia House'' (1990).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jamison, 56, who was born in Philadelphia, danced with the
Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater and took over the company in
1989 upon the death of Ailey, who won a Kennedy Center honor in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   She said in a statement from Brazil: ``When I realized that I
was going to receive the Kennedy Center honors, I was in tears
looking at Alvin's picture. I think he would have been extremely
proud.''
</P>
<P>
   At 49, Stevie Wonder is relatively young to be receiving the
award, but he has been singing ballads and pop songs since he was
7. Wonder was born in Saginaw, Mich. His songs have included both
straight pop, like ``You Are the Sunshine of My Life,'' and those
associated with his social activism, like the plea to fight world
hunger in ``We Are the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Robards, 77, who was born in Chicago, has acted in movies and on
television but is best known for his stage work. He is the nation's
pre-eminent interpreter of the plays of Eugene O'Neill, and he said
that he was pleased by the recent renewal of interest in those
works, although ``O'Neill really has never ceased being done.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his home in Southport, Conn., Robards was asked
whether he might return to Broadway, where he has performed in
virtually every theater, to play in an O'Neill work again. ``I'd
love to, but I'm getting so long in the tooth now,'' he said.
``It's too late. It brings back all the old memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of his O'Neill collaborators, like the director Jose
Quintero and his frequent co-star Colleen Dewhurst, are dead. He
said he fondly remembers touring with them for years at a time in
such O'Neill plays as ``The Iceman Cometh,'' ``A Moon for the
Misbegotten'' and ``Long Day's Journey Into Night.''
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, he said, there is an O'Neill play he could
perform: ```Desire Under the Elms' I could probably do. There's an
old man in that that I could do, a very good part. But I'm not
contemplating that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy Center Honors are the center's principal
fund-raising event. The recipients are to receive their awards from
President Clinton at the White House on Dec. 5 and then be honored
at a performance at the center.
</P>
<P>
   The performance will be broadcast on CBS television later in
December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
