<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-RESTAURANT-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SPAIN, A CHEF TO RIVAL DALI 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: recipe in 3rd take) 
 (bl)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSAS, Spain _ Some say it is the best restaurant in Europe,
possibly the world. No one mentioned that it is also so remote. A
friend and I sped around hairpin curves on a pitted, single-lane
mountain road northeast of Barcelona, with nothing above us and the
Mediterranean a sharp descent below.
</P>
<P>
   The road snaked around the mountain and eventually delivered us
at the base of a sunny, narrow cove. There was an empty beach, a
rundown shack and a small villa wedged into the hillside. This was
El Bulli.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Michelin three-star restaurant everyone was talking
about. The one that six top American chefs _ Charlie Trotter, Todd
English, Norman Van Aken, Roberto Donna, Jean-Louis Palladin and
Douglas Rodriguez _ would all flock to this same week and the next,
not for an event but on a pilgrimage. The one where the chef,
Ferran Adria, is rarely referred to as a chef, but as a mad
scientist, a genius, a Dali of the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   When we entered, he sat hunched over the reservation desk, head
in his hands, like a schoolboy struggling with a math problem. A
stocky man with curly black hair and a Mediterranean tan, he smiled
widely and shook my hand vigorously. He wore no toque, no expensive
shoes, no airs of a god in his temple. He pointed us to our table
where we were meeting some friends.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to get down to business.
</P>
<P>
   A waiter set down a plate of lollipops. They were flat,
caramel-colored translucent wafers on a stick. I placed one in my
mouth. A salted peanut-honey brittle melted on my tongue like a
rice cracker. A flurry of tapas arrived, including Adria's version
of a tomato-and-bread salad _ a crisp, hollow sphere of bread
concealed a burst of olive oil. It rested on top of a cool puff of
white foam _ an intense froth of tomato water in disguise. The
stream of surprises never let up.
</P>
<P>
   El Bulli got its third star in 1997. ``It was the quietest
three-star ever,'' said Michael Ginor, an owner of Hudson Valley
Foie Gras on New York's Long Island. But then again, it was in
Spain, and three-star restaurants outside France simply do not
attract the same volume of attention. But among chefs and insiders,
it was a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Robuchon, the former chef of the three-star Robuchon in
Paris, visited a few years ago and went back to France telling
everyone that Adria was the best chef in the world. That's a bit
like Picasso coming to see your paintings, then declaring that
you're the best artist in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Attention reached an apex this year, when the standing of El
Bulli changed from professional touting to required eating.
American chefs and foodies flooded it this summer for Adria's
parade of tiny courses, his clever riffs on tapas and his
outrageous pairings like bone marrow and caviar.
</P>
<P>
   Many chefs have sought time in Adria's kitchen. Jeffrey
Cerciello, the chef at Thomas Keller's Bouchon, in the Napa Valley,
interned there for a year. Jose Andres, the chef at Cafe Atlantico
and Jaleo, in Washington, worked for Adria for a few years and has
returned numerous times since. Many of Andres' dishes, like his
mango anchovy ravioli foam, echo Adria's style: _ they experiment
not just with new tastes but with temperatures, textures, aromas
and appearance as well.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Andres, are clear disciples. But Adria is also
influencing American cooking in more subtle ways. So many chefs are
visiting El Bulli, and Adria is clearly inspiring them as he
strikes out in new directions.
</P>
<P>
   Adria gained most of his fame, though, for a specific technique
he developed. A few years ago, he received a gift from friends in
Madrid. It was a nitrous oxide canister meant to be used for making
whipped cream. Most people would accept such an odd gift and
promptly deposit it in the closet, but Adria put it to work. He
filled it with various liquids, and his ethereal ``foams,'' as they
are called, were born. Soon, he was making tomato foams, shellfish
foams and potato foams, and chefs from around the world were coming
to taste _ and copy _ them.
</P>
<P>
   It is just this kind of creativity and risk taking that defines
Adria's style. He takes classic dishes and deconstructs them,
disregarding familiar contexts in an effort to form new ones. A
tortilla de patata, which in every other Spanish restaurant is a
potato and onion omelet, is served at El Bulli in a martini glass
and is liquid and foam. You are handed a spoon and told to dip it
all the way to the bottom with each bite. You plunge through a
white potato foam into a soft pudding of egg and caramelized onion.
In his chicken curry, the curry is the solid, the chicken is
liquid.
</P>
<P>
   His cooking follows no patterns. It has been described as
everything from surrealist to techno. It is not especially French
and not especially Spanish. Global, perhaps. The only element you
can depend on finding is seafood, which is spectacular and
abundant, not surprisingly, given the location of the restaurant.
(A former pupil of his said fishermen would drive boats up to the
shore and deliver mussels and sea urchins in their dive suits.) His
curve balls are easily missed. Some diners, for instance, will have
a 12-course meal without noticing that just two courses were hot.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures can even change through the course of a single
dish. After the tapas, the waiters returned with shot glasses
filled with a grass-green liquid. We waited for our instructions.
``Pea and mint soup _ drink all at once,'' the waiter said.
Diligently, we all lifted the glasses to our mouths and tilted our
heads back. It was a tasty, slightly coarse pea and mint soup. It
began hot, but as you drank it, a stream of cold soup slid under
the layer of hot soup on your tongue. It ended completely cold.
</P>
<P>
   Adria's latest breakthrough is finding a way to serve gelatins
hot. His tagliatelle carbonara is witty and brilliant. There is
tagliatelle, but it is not pasta. It is a chicken consomme jelled
with agar-agar and cut into long, brown translucent ribbons. A
tangle of them lie in a sauce of egg, cream, Parmesan cheese and
diced ham. The warm jelled tagliatelle feel like pasta in the mouth
and dissolve slightly to meld with the rich, eggy sauce. It's as
good as it is perplexing.
</P>
<P>
   And just as you are moved by such creativity, he stops you with
a dish of baby shrimp sauteed in their juices and nothing else _ no
jell, no foam, no garnish.
</P>
<P>
   These innovations are what American chefs visiting El Bulli come
looking for. Kenneth Oringer, the chef at Clio in Boston, spent
three days in the kitchen last year. ``His approach left a mark on
me,'' Oringer said. And on his menu. Dishes like a black truffle
fondue served in a coffee cup, covered with a celery root foam,
shavings of black truffle and a dusting of bitter cocoa powder, are
clearly influenced by Adria.
</P>
<P>
   English, the chef at Olives and Figs in Boston, was inspired by
Adria's creative freedom. ``It made me think, `Why are you
stopping?''' he said, ``That was the inspiration I got: Don't hold
back.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Adria, 37, has had no formal training. Most of his career, in
fact, has been spent at El Bulli. He began working in a small
restaurant in Barcelona when he was 17, washing dishes to earn
money to go on vacation. ``I started washing dishes the same way I
could have been a car mechanic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Being there in the kitchen, he became interested in cooking.
Soon, he made the leap. After four years there, he got a job at El
Bulli, where he has been for 17 years. The restaurant, now 45 years
old, has always had a reputation for good cooking. When Adria was
hired as a cook at El Bulli _ named ``the bulldog'' by the first
owner, who was fond of French bulldogs _ the restaurant had two
stars. He became the chef after two years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, he went to a class given by Jacques Maximum, then the
chef of the two-star Chantecler at the Hotel Negresco in Nice.
Someone in the audience asked what it meant to create. ``Not to
copy,'' responded Maximum. That moment, that simple definition,
Adria said, was transcendent. It has informed his cooking ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   El Bulli is open just six months of the year, from April 1 to
Oct. 1. During the season, the restaurant serves about 45 people at
each meal. A team of 35 to 40 cooks turns out menus that range from
about 12 courses to as many as 35.
</P>
<P>
   Adria spends the other six months in Barcelona, working with his
brother, Alberto, developing recipes. Alberto had been the pastry
chef but has recently turned his attention to the direction of the
restaurant's cooking. They call the Barcelona kitchen their
laboratory and run it very much like one, using controls and
experimenting with countless variables until they get a combination
like potato and coffee to work.
</P>
<P>
   Astonishingly, they managed to. And they serve it as if it were
a jewel. At lunch, a troupe of waiters passed around large spoons.
``Eat in one bite,'' one said. The soft cylinder of potato perched
on the end of the spoon was filled with an intense, viscous coffee
sauce. It was rich, earthy, strangely delicious.
</P>
<P>
   There is a difference, Adria said, between having to create food
because you have a restaurant and needing to have a restaurant
because you create food. Because he experiments with food, he said,
he needs the restaurant to show it. It is his gallery.
</P>
<P>
   As with any exhibition of challenging artwork, not all diners
leave El Bulli feeling sure that they love it. But they know that
they are astonished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I wasn't dining or eating,'' English said, ``I
felt I was being experimented with. I never felt satisfied with
every dish that I ate. It wasn't like I ate something. It was like
`Wow, that was wild.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clara Maria G. de Amezua, a food historian and lecturer in
Madrid, said Adria was widely respected in Spain but not always
adored. ``When they say they don't like,'' Ms. de Amezua said, ``I
think, They don't understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He remains controversial,'' said Victor de la Serna, a
restaurant critic and a deputy editor of El Mundo, the Madrid
daily, ``because in his constant search for new things, new
textures, new combinations, sometimes he misses the mark, which is
the risk. I've never had a meal cooked by him that didn't have
something that didn't miss the mark. But I've never had a meal
cooked by him where there weren't several things that were
sensational.''
</P>
<P>
   At lunch, a dish of frozen polenta illustrated just how his
experiments, his risk taking, sometimes fall short. It was salty,
grainy, cold and simply unpleasant to eat. Another dish featuring
duck seemed like nothing other than a mediocre version of egg foo
yung. But after so many extraordinary dishes it was difficult to
see it as much of a flaw. Who cannot applaud a chef with such
bravery?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's maybe more of a chefs' restaurant,'' said Trotter, the
chef at Charlie Trotter's in Chicago. ``It's certainly more of an
eager enthusiastic gourmand's restaurant than an enthusiastic
diner's restaurant. You appreciate it more if you have more
experience at the table.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest surprise supporter of all has been the historically
stuffy Michelin guide. For years, chefs have complained that
Michelin's judgment of china, artwork and service in addition to
the food has forced them into bankruptcy and corrupted the
definition of dining. Michelin maintains that the food is the only
criterion for stars, and that inspectors in Spain are Spanish, not
French. Alain Arnaud, the director of communications for the
Michelin guide in Paris, said: ``It is difficult to say you can eat
the meal of your life on a paper plate. You need a minimum of
decor.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what you get at El Bulli. There are cobwebs in the
bathroom, dust on the copper pots hanging from the walls, and _ mon
dieu! _ unfluffed seat cushions. There is no expensive artwork
(though you couldn't put a price on the ocean view). And for a
restaurant that, according to Michelin, is ``worth the detour,'' a
detour it certainly is.
</P>
<P>
   Even Adria seems mystified by the inspectors' decision to give
him three stars. They made a bet on the future of restaurants and
food, he said, because they based it on creativity.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the meal, the plate of petit fours, which he calls
``pequenas locuras,'' or ``little crazies,'' seemed to bring it all
together. Lollipops appeared once more, only this time they were
lemonade and as they melted in your mouth, they fizzed. From the
solid substance, bubbles formed, lifting off the tongue like
champagne. His chocolate mint is a fresh mint leaf framed in flat
chip of chocolate. The chocolate was lean and bittersweet, the mint
tasted of the outdoors. His thin flat tuiles, all fanned out on a
modern silver rack, had mottled surfaces that were cream, yellow
and pink and tasted of coconut, pistachio and beet. There were
chocolate caramel tuiles seasoned with pink peppercorn and, for
anyone who was beginning to take this all too seriously,
chocolate-covered salted corn nuts.
</P>
<P>
   By the end we were laughing, slouching in our chairs as the sun
descended toward the horizon. We visited the kitchen, a high-tech
lab compared with the homey dining room. Adria did not rush us
along. He chatted, one eye on us, one eye on the young men wrapping
plump coral mussels in a clear sea-water jelly _ the production
line for post-modern food. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (RECIPE FOLLOWS IN 3rd TAKE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   PARMESAN ICE CREAM SANDWICH
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from El Bulli, Roses, Spain
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours, plus 6 hours freezing time  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the ice cream:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   { pound finely grated Parmesan cheese For the marmalade:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5 lemons
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar For the cookie:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5 large egg whites
</P>
<P>
   { pound finely grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick cooking spray.
</P>
<P>
   1. To prepare the ice cream: Place a fine strainer over a medium
bowl, and set aside. In a medium saucepan over medium heat, bring
cream to a simmer. While stirring with a wooden spoon, gradually
add Parmesan. Stir constantly until mixture is smooth, about 10
minutes. Pour mixture into strainer, and press on any solids to
extract as much liquid as possible. Allow to cool to room
temperature. Pour mixture into a 9-by-12-inch baking dish, and
cover with plastic wrap. Freeze until solid, about 6 hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. To prepare the marmalade: Using a sharp knife, cut all peel
(including white pith) from lemons. Dice lemons into {-inch cubes,
and transfer to a small saucepan. Add sugar, and bring to a simmer
over medium-low heat. Cook, stirring occasionally, until mixture is
thick, about 1 hour. (While marmalade is simmering, prepare
Parmesan cookies.) Remove from heat, and let cool to room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   3. To prepare the Parmesan cookies: Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
In a mixing bowl, combine egg whites and grated cheese. Spray two
10-by-15-inch nonstick baking sheets with nonstick cooking spray.
Spread half of mixture in center of each sheet. Top with a sheet of
wax paper, and use a rolling pin to press mixture evenly across
each pan. Remove and discard wax paper. Bake mixture until lightly
browned, about 7 minutes. Remove pans from oven, and trim dark
edges. Cut remaining mixture in in each pan into 12 3-inch squares
to make a total of 24. Using a spatula, turn the squares over, and
return pan to oven. Bake an additional 5 minutes, and remove pan
from heat.
</P>
<P>
   4. To assemble: Remove pan of ice cream from freezer, and place
on top of a warm damp cloth for about 5 minutes. Using a knife
dipped in hot water, cut ice cream into 12 3-inch squares. Place a
square of ice cream on a Parmesan cookie, top with a spoonful of
marmalade, and top with another Parmesan cookie. Serve immediately,
or place in freezer until serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 12 ice cream sandwiches.
</P>
</TEXT>
