<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1945 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     09-14 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT FACES TRIALS OF HOMEOWNERSHIP
</HEADLINE>
   (lh) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton and his wife, Senator Clinton, recently bought
a $1.7 million house in Chappaqua, N.Y., but it's what happens next
that has me worried.
</P>
<P>
   Wisely heeding the financial advice I gave them in an earlier
column, the Clintons, who are reportedly $5.5 million in debt,
bought a house that was way more than they could afford. This will
give Bill and Hillary something to fight about every month when the
mortgage payment comes due, reminding them of the good old days in
the White House when they were fighting all the time.
</P>
<P>
   I can only assume that the Clintons heeded my other advice and
checked to make sure none of their neighbors were stock-car
enthusiasts who liked to fire up their engines late at night or
early on Sunday mornings, and that they also checked for rats in
their orange trees, assuming there are any orange trees in
Chappaqua, N.Y., which I doubt.
</P>
<P>
   What has me worried now is how Bill plans to maintain his new
home, which was built in 1889. The Clintons, after all, have spent
most of the past 20 years living as guests in executive mansions in
Little Rock, Ark., and Washington, D.C., where they have not had to
wrestle with the endless chores that make the average suburban
homeowner old, or dead, before his time.
</P>
<P>
   From what I've read in the paper, Bill Clinton is even more of a
home-repair boob than I am, which is extremely alarming given that
I am the kind of person who has been known to have trouble
operating a shower curtain.
</P>
<P>
   While visiting a school in Norfolk, Va., the other day, Clinton
drove a screw with a cordless electric drill, a tool he said he had
never seen before. I don't know if Clinton poked his eye out with
the unfamiliar tool or somehow managed to burn the school down, but
I assume he didn't or we probably would have heard about it by now.
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of bipartisanship, I should point out that some
of our previous presidents were also deeply out of touch. President
Bush, for example, had never seen an electronic grocery scanner
before. The difference, however, is that you're a lot less likely
to ruin a wall with an electronic grocery scanner than you are with
a cordless drill.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how Clinton got roped into buying a 110-year-old
house. Maybe Hillary bullied him into it or maybe it was a slick
real-estate agent who used the sales pitch, ``They don't make 'em
like this anymore,'' which Bill will find to be irrefutably true
every time he tries to find a part at the hardware or
building-supply store.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton will quickly find that, in an old house, even the
simplest tasks are recipes for disaster. Take hanging a picture,
for instance. He will start by gently tapping a nail into the
smooth, plaster wall. (Let us give the man credit and assume he
uses a hammer for this job, not the butt-end of his new cordless
drill.) It doesn't look bad at first, but as soon as he hangs the
picture, the nail falls out. The picture drops on the original
hardwood floor, sending shards of glass everywhere. Worse, when the
nail came out it gouges a huge hole in the plaster.
</P>
<P>
   So what does America's most famous new homeowner do now? Find a
bigger nail, I'm guessing. This allows him to destroy another
picture frame, create an even bigger hole and, if he's especially
lucky, maybe hit an electrical conduit and short out the house.
</P>
<P>
   But even a man with the energy and perseverance of Bill Clinton
will eventually grow tired of shocking himself while at the same
time creating holes in the living-room wall big enough for Socks
the cat to jump through and will turn his attention to bathroom
repairs. This will be a great opportunity for the president because
he will get to acquaint himself with a bunch of unfamiliar tools,
such as a screwdriver, wrench and bucket. In the end, every
homeowner has to learn how to do things the hard way, by trial and
error and, of course, by writing large checks to professionals to
come in and clean up your mess.
</P>
<P>
   So I'll just leave Clinton alone to sort things out for himself.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he's an intelligent man and I'm sure he wouldn't
begin any bathroom-repair project without turning the water off
first.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
