<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BAD-LANGUAGE-NYTR &LR;      09-14 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAD-LANGUAGE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOWADAYS, PEOPLE ARE CURSING LOUDLY AND PROUDLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BEN STEELMAN   
 The Morning Star, Wilmington, N.C.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ When Lenny Bruce wrote ``How to Talk Dirty
and Influence People'' in 1963, the standup comic was in
near-constant hot water with police for his profanity-laced
monologues.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 40 years later, dozens of comedians have made a living,
and occasionally a fortune, using almost the same language that he
did.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, comedian George Carlin performed a sketch called
``Seven Dirty Words,'' based on _ and using as often as possible _
the seven words specifically banned from broadcast in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Pacifica Radio of San Francisco ran afoul of the Federal
Communications Commission for playing ``Seven Dirty Words'' over
the air.
</P>
<P>
   The case made it to the U.S. Supreme Court in 1978. Justices
upheld the ban while adding, in the majority opinion, ``We have not
decided that an occasional expletive...would justify any sanction
or, indeed, that this broadcast would justify a criminal
prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   What a difference 20 years make.
</P>
<P>
   While the Seven Dirties are still banned, network TV situation
comedies routinely slip in references to ``boobs'' when the
characters are not talking about idiotic guys, or the technical
term for a female dog as applied to naughty ladies.
</P>
<P>
   The language gets even raunchier on cable, where the little boys
of South Park get away with remarks once used in public only by
drill sergeants and sailors. On radio, Howard Stern still boldly
goes where no disc jockey ever talked before.
</P>
<P>
   And if you still haven't had an earful, buy a ticket at the
local movie house. This was the summer when South Park went to the
Big Screen, when Cartman, Kyle and Stan got to use even more foul
language.
</P>
<P>
   Blair Witch Project, one of 1999's ``sleeper'' movie hits, drew
less controversy for its horror plot and improvised acting than for
its stars' frequent use of words beginning with ``f'' and ``s.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders responded that the Blair Witch kids simply talked like
most ordinary college students.
</P>
<P>
   They may have a point. Based on field studies of language use,
women and children are swearing more often in public, according to
Timothy Jay, a psychologist and author of the book ``Cursing in
America.'' In a 1992 poll by Teenage Research Unlimited, 52 percent
of the 2,000 teens questioned said they thought cursing is cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's one more example of the decline of civility,''
said Connie Eble, a professor of English at the University of North
Carolina at Chapel Hill, who researches contemporary slang and
young people's speech patterns.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it sometimes seemed (to paraphrase an innocent heroine
of another summer movie, Dick) that everyone was talking
``potty-mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The age of euphemism is over,'' said sociologist John Shelton
Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the front-runner in the race for the
Republican presidential nomination, drew flak from some other
Republicans for using profanity in an interview with Talk magazine.
</P>
<P>
   And Timothy Boomer gained notoriety last summer when he fell out
of a canoe in a river near Standish, Mich. A policeman ticketed the
25-year-old under an 1897 Michigan law that forbids ``indecent,
immoral, obscene, vulgar or insulting language'' where women or
children might hear it.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a state District Court judge in Standish sentenced
Boomer to four days of community service and a $75 fine. The
American Civil Liberties Union has announced that it will help him
appeal the decision.
</P>
<P>
   All societies have language taboos, said Eble, but in America,
those taboos have shifted in recent years. Taboos against racial
epithets have grown stronger, to the point that some people feel
pressured by ``political correctness.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet taboos against other words for sexuality and body functions
_ once used only among close friends or outside the earshot of
members of the opposite sex _have eroded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blame it on the '60s,'' said Reed, a professor of sociology
at UNC-Chapel Hill and a social conservative who was appointed by
President Reagan to the board of the National Endowment for the
Humanities. ``But then, I blame everything on the '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay said that exposure to swear words in movies, on TV and in
music expands the use of profanity. School-age youngsters pick up
the habit from their peers.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Steinberg, executive director of the Penn National
Commission of Society, Culture and Community at the University of
Pennsylvania, also cited increased personal anonymity in society,
especially with the Internet. People are more likely to ``flame''
faceless strangers on the Web, with language they'd never use
against a neighbor in the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the taboos have eroded. Eble said that, personally, she
is still extremely bothered by the use of the names of God and
Jesus Christ as epithets.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, regard the issue as hopeless but not serious.
``I think there are worse things than language to worry about,''
Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
