<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1949 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV21-     09-14 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV21-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING EYE CONTACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, Sept. 21)  
(lh) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the list of Two Kinds of People, there are those who make eye
contact and listen up and those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   For example, each individual has to decide his or her personal
response policy regarding the wait persons at a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose you could rationalize that you walk in, in a definite
pork chop mood and don't want to be dissuaded. But the recitation
of daily specials has been part of the dining experience for some
time now. What does it take to listen to what's in tonight's
special calzone?
</P>
<P>
   My foodie friend Alison and I got to talking about this at lunch
after I noted how attentive she was to the waitress. Not only did
she halt in mid-conversation when the woman approached our table &UR; , &LR; 
but she said ``Hi'' in a truly friendly manner and murmured
encouragingly over each special, cocking an eyebrow as if she had
never thought to team mussels with baby corn. I think she even
asked about the type of lettuce it would be bedded on.
</P>
<P>
   I gave her high marks for going way beyond the smile and a
``thank you'' I consider appropriate, and she said that she had
just been in New York at a restaurant where the entire table not
only avoided eye contact with the waiter but continued talking over
his greeting, the part where he shares his name and the entire list
of very tricky specials.
</P>
<P>
   She felt as if she had to hurry back to California and make up
for their abuse.
</P>
<P>
   I know the type. I've dined with people so dismissive of servers
that I feel compelled to order the special couscous just so they
will know that someone was listening.
</P>
<P>
   We asked our waitress that day about customers' listening
manners, and she said that most people at least pretend to pay
attention but there are those who act as if she's invisible or an
annoyance, which would be like forever being the mother of
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that we are just overloaded with information and
strangers yapping in our ear and simply need to select out. But is
this the place to take a stand?
</P>
<P>
   What about flight attendants? Does anybody listen to their
takeoff rundown anymore? I looked around a flight and hardly anyone
even glanced toward the front of the plane. They were talking and
flipping through magazines as if they had been through this a
million times and knew exactly where the exits were. But I think a
lot of fliers just want to look cool and world-weary. To pay
attention might have people wondering how they got so old and never
flew before.
</P>
<P>
   But this could be risky. Snub the wrong flight attendant, and
she may someday be standing over you saying, ``What did I tell you
about your flotation cushion?''
</P>
<P>
   No one likes to be ignored, although there are some people who
probably get used to it. Telephone solicitors must endure daily
abuse from people shouting that they don't want more credit cards
or they want to eat their dinner. And yet, someone must engage with
them, or they wouldn't keep calling back.
</P>
<P>
   How about toll takers? Do you say hello when you pay your money
to cross the bridge? OK, some toll takers act as if they don't want
to be bothered either, but have you ever tried forcing them to at
least grunt?
</P>
<P>
   Drive-through parking lot attendants are generally amiable and
certainly deserve more than asking for a receipt. Same with airport
shuttle drivers. Someone has to laugh at their banter.
</P>
<P>
   Strolling violinists? People selling roses at your table? You
can't keep looking into your soup.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, we were in an Italian restaurant, and without
warning the waiters started passing out song sheets. There was no
time to look to the beautiful people and figure out the coolness
rule.
</P>
<P>
   I chose to sing, because how often do you get to sing ``When the
moon hits your eye like a big pizza pie'' with two guys who look
like Al Pacino? You can always be cool tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
