<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley slams Gore's environment record
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Harshly criticizing Vice President Gore's record on
the environment, Friends of the Earth on Tuesday endorsed Bill
Bradley, Gore's rival for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental group praised Bradley's leadership on the
environment when he was a senator from New Jersey and called Gore's
record, both in Congress and in the White House, disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore did an enormous service by raising issues such as ozone
depletion and global warming,'' said Mark Whiteis-Helm, spokesman
for Friends of the Earth political action committee. ``The fact
that he has done little to follow up on that is very disappointing.
We are not happy about having to inform the American public that Al
Gore is not as strong an environmentalist as the public
perception.''
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement is mainly a symbolic victory for Bradley. With
about 20,000 members, Friends of the Earth is one of the smaller
environmental groups. The 30-year-old organization tends to
concentrate on international issues more than other environmental
groups do.
</P>
<P>
   The two largest environmental organizations, the League of
Conservation Voters and the Sierra Club, both called the Friends of
the Earth endorsement of Bradley ``premature,'' and said they may
or may not offer endorsements of their own. LCV is the political
arm of the entire environmental movement, representing some 9
million people. The Sierra Club has about 500,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a lot of information to hear from these
candidates,'' said LCV president Deb Callahan. ``Al Gore and Bill
Bradley have both been friends of the environmental community.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Weiss, the Sierra Club's political director and a former
activist in Democratic politics, said the Friends of the Earth
endorsement wouldn't change how people feel about Gore because
``there are many people across the country, environmentalists,
working on the Gore campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me this is as if the mayor of a small town in New Jersey
endorsed Gore,'' said Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the endorsement demonstrates that Gore, who has built
much of his reputation around his concern for the environment,
can't take the votes of the environmental community for granted.
</P>
<P>
   As vice president, Gore has been the administration's point
person on the environment and he represented the United States in
signing the global warming treaty in Kyoto, Japan. The treaty
hasn't yet been presented to the Senate for ratification because of
stiff opposition from Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the Earth based its endorsement of Bradley partly on
Gore's failure to seek more aggressive ozone protections in the
Kyoto treaty. The group also noted that Gore's voting record on the
environment in Congress, as compiled by LCV, was some 20 points
lower than Bradley's.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of protecting the ozone layer to prevent global
warming, the central purpose of the Kyoto treaty, Friends of the
Earth grades the Clinton/Gore administration a ``D.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore's been anointed the point person on the environment for
this administration,'' said Whiteis-Helm. ``If you want to paint
yourself as the enviro-man then you have a responsibility to live
up to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the Earth praised Bradley for his role in reforming
California water management in 1992, ending some government
subsidies and improving the ecology of California waterways. The
group noted that Bradley also led a 1996 filibuster against a plan
to open 20,000 acres of Utah wilderness for coal mining and oil
drilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will help remind people that Bradley not only had a good
environmental record, but that he was focused on it over a long
period of time,'' said Eric Hauser, Bradley's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Kiki Moore, Gore's spokeswoman, said Gore would continue to
fight for a ``balanced approach'' to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president is going to fight to make sure there's a
clean and healthy environment,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
