<HEADLINE>
CEO OF DAIMLERCHRYLSYER'S SMART CAR UNT WILL RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Lars Brorsen, the chief executive of
DaimlerChrysler AG's struggling Smart car business, will resign at
the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise resignation, which Daimler executives disclosed
here Tuesday at the Frankfurt international automobile show, came
just as sales of the quirky two-seater ``city car'' finally
appeared to be picking up.
</P>
<P>
   The Smart, a snub-nosed car with plastic body parts, began as a
joint venture between Daimler and the founder of Swatch watches.
But it had a horrendous start after it went on the market in the
fall of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Though Daimler built a factory able to turn out 200,000 cars a
year and projected first-year sales of 150,000, only 70,000 have
been sold so far, and sales were almost nonexistent in the first
three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the results improved in recent months after the company
reduced prices and added safety features. The company said it sold
9,500 Smart cars in June, 10,000 in July and 7,500 in August, a
month when many Europeans go on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear why Brorsen quit. Daimler executives said
Brorsen cited ``differences'' over business strategy after a recent
board meeting. The company has not named a successor, which
suggests that the resignation was unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   News of Brorsen's resignation overshadowed the introduction of
two new Smart models in Europe: a diesel-powered version that gets
90 miles to the gallon and a sporty convertible that will cost
about $11,000.
</P>
<P>
   The company also introduced a racy ``concept car'' that looks
like a cross between a sports car and a dune buggy but uses much of
the same basic components as the standard Smart.
</P>
<P>
   Juergen Hubbert, a DaimlerChrysler board member who substituted
for Brorsen at the car show Tuesday, acknowledged that initial
sales had fallen far below expectations. But he said Smart had
``achieved a turnover that is quite unique'' and praised the Smart
management team for ``an exceptional job under difficult
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The brand has polarized'' people ever since its inception,
Hubbert added, generating both vehement criticism and praise
because of its wildly unusual design.
</P>
<P>
   Daimler executives now predict sales of 80,000 Smart cars this
year and more than 100,000 next year.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Smart, DaimlerChrysler's automotive lines are all
growing at good rates. Robert Eaton, co-chairman of the company,
said it would roll out 64 new car and truck models by 2004 and
invest $47 billion in development over the next three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
