</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-PUBS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER BIG DEAL IN BRITAIN'S VOLATILE PUB INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Seized by the ferment in Britain's pub industry,
Scottish &AMP; Newcastle PLC, the country's dominant brewer, said
Tuesday that it had agreed to buy 868 pubs, restaurants and budget
hotels from the ailing Greenalls Group PLC for $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal came just days after Allied Domecq PLC completed a $4.4
billion sale of 3,500 pubs to the privately held Punch Taverns
Group Ltd. That deal left Punch Taverns and Nomura International
PLC as Britain's biggest bar owners. Smaller rivals like Bass PLC,
Whitbread PLC and Scottish &AMP; Newcastle must expand to compete more
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement brought an immediate rise in the value of
Scottish &AMP; Newcastle's shares, which finished the day up 3.2
percent at 612 pence ($9.88) on the London Stock Exchange.
Greenalls stock fell nearly 2 percent, to 361 pence ($5.83).
Scottish &AMP; Newcastle said it would finance the purchase through
increased debt.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish &AMP; Newcastle, Britain's biggest brewer by market share,
has beer brands including Courage and Newcastle Brown Ale, and it
specializes in branded, managed pubs with names like the Rat and
Parrot.
</P>
<P>
   Like other brewers, it faces legal restriction under the
so-called Beer Orders _ a set of government rules implemented a
decade ago _ on the number of pubs and licensed premises it may
own. Scottish &AMP; Newcastle's limit is 2,937 outlets; the acquisition
would put it over that limit.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would therefore dispose of some of the 664
pubs it leases to independent managers and move toward a goal of
having most of its outlets under its own management. According to
the company, managed outlets yield more than 20 percent return on
investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal provides a strong platform for us to outperform the
growth sectors on which we are now focused,'' said chief executive
Brian Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition includes 531 managed pubs, 234 pub-restaurants,
61 budget hotels and 42 other pubs. Scottish &AMP; Newcastle, based in
Edinburgh, said it would rename some of the pubs and restaurants
with its own brand names and use them as outlets for beers it brews
under license, including Foster's and Kronenbourg. Scottish &AMP;
Newcastle finance director Derek Wilkinson said the deal would
bring annual savings of $40 million by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Greenalls issued a profit warning in July because of what it
called ``challenging conditions'' for its pubs, restaurants and
drinks-wholesaling businesses. The company has said that it wants
to focus on health and fitness clubs and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's announcement, Greenalls said it would use the
proceeds from the deal to return $688 million to shareholders and
reduce debt.
</P>
<P>
   Recent sales in the pubs business have set the stage for what
analysts expect to be consolidation in the spirits industry as
smaller players maneuver to compete with the giant Diageo PLC, the
world's leading maker of alcoholic beverages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
