<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1962 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-14 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN, AGAIN. SIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Patrick Buchanan, the obnoxious right-wing media
motormouth, is happy. Hardly anybody else is.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Buchanan is getting what he craves _ public attention
for his narrow-minded, white-male-supremacist, backward-looking,
isolationist political ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Voter interest has been in short supply during his campaign for
the Republican presidential nomination this year. His favorable
ratings have never risen higher than 5 percent and his negatives
have frozen at about 33 percent. The proportion of voters who say
they would never consider voting for him is about the same as those
who feel that way about Sen. Edward Kennedy, his philosophical
counterpart on the left.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan came in only fifth with 7 percent in the August
Republican presidential straw poll in Iowa despite his famous
television face and a vigorous campaign to stir up blue-collar
workers who had backed his 1996 presidential drive. His candidacy
was over.
</P>
<P>
   It took a spot of political blackmail to get back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   When Buchanan began openly flirting with the idea of quitting
the GOP and running for the Reform Party presidential nomination,
Republican leaders suddenly discovered what a big deal he was. The
more the GOP panicked, the more interested Buchanan got in
deserting a party that has studiously ignored him since his
hard-nosed, disastrous 1992 GOP convention speech contributed to
President George Bush's defeat for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who at 60 is still living in the political and
cultural past, is having a lot of fun with this. But it's not a
done deal.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, who recently seized control of the
Reform Party from its founder Ross Perot, opposes Buchanan's
harshly judgmental views on social issues, which run counter to the
party's traditional tolerant stands. Ventura is searching elsewhere
for a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But the Reform Party is not organized in the ordinary sense.
It's a loose collection of similar-minded folks who have no
coherent agenda or hierarchy. No one is quite sure how to create a
logical nomination process.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the party's presidential nod could bring Buchanan $12
million in federal funds for a campaign he could not otherwise
finance. But Buchanan could bring the party something, too. He is
more likely than lesser-known fellows also suggested for the role
to attract the 5 percent minimum of the total turnout required to
keep qualifying for federal campaign funds. It would be a political
marriage of convenience, principles be damned.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes that's not such a bad thing. But it could artificially
warp the outcome of the 2000 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Assume that Buchanan, running on a third party ticket, gets
roughly 8 percent of votes cast, Perot's score last time.
</P>
<P>
   His votes would come largely from Republicans. Most Democrats do
not agree with Buchanan's agenda, particularly his insistence on
banning abortion without exception.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by GOP pollster Frank Luntz showed Buchanan
getting 6.5 percent of the total vote in a three-way trial heat
with Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore. That
seems in line with what we already know. Buchanan is an ideologue
with a tiny but noisy following, not a serious presidential
contender.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago his pitch for international trade limitations
appealed to blue-collar workers who used to vote for Ronald Reagan.
But that appeal largely vanished with the booming economy. His
ultraconservative take on cultural issues has never resonated with
Democrats or moderate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   If the race between Bush and Gore, John McCain and Bill Bradley
_ or whomever _ is close, a GOP loss of even 2 percentage points
could toss the nomination to the Democrat. History is replete with
spoilers who ran to satisfy their own ambitions and destroyed their
party's prospects in the process. In the most famous example,
Theodore Roosevelt split the Republican vote with his Bull Moose
Party in 1912, allowing Democrat Woodrow Wilson to defeat GOP
President William Howard Taft.
</P>
<P>
   Would Taft have avoided World War I and made a better, more
permanent peace? We'll never know.
</P>
<P>
   But if the 2000 race is not close, Buchanan cannot make much of
a difference. He can, however, make a great fool of himself, either
reaching unsuccessfully for the $12 million or spending it. His
egocentric notion that he can actually win the White House with his
nutty ideas is strictly delusional.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign will not be pretty. It will not be enlightening. It
will probably not be good for the country. But it's the American
way.
</P>
<P>
   And Buchanan will have a good time back in the spotlight. At
least he isn't boring. Remember when he said that women who wanted
equal rights reminded him of the freaks in the bar scene of ``Star
Wars?'' This guy is pathetically easy to detest.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1963 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-MEXICO-BEACHES-2700(3     09-14 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BEACHES-2700(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN BEACHES FROM A (ACAPULCO) TO Z (ZIHUATANEJO)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All coasts are not created equal.
</P>
<P>
   Especially in Mexico, the land of a thousand (or so) beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Some are better for surfing, some for sunning, some for
snorkeling. The one you take the kids to might not be the best one
for your second honeymoon. And it's far too easy to end up as the
only older couple in a sea of college-kid revelers, or a would-be
swinging single in family land.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you know where to go?
</P>
<P>
   Easy. We've been to each of these resorts (yeah, tough job, but
we take our work seriously) and our studied sunning has produced
this guide to 10 popular Mexican resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Read on. And then go buy some sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   ACAPULCO
</P>
<P>
   WHERE AND WHAT: The original glamour girl of Mexican resorts,
Acapulco is situated dramatically in the mountains on the edge of
the Pacific. It's where jet-setters headed in the '50s and '60s
(and where, according to a legend almost nobody believes, the
margarita was invented).
</P>
<P>
   WHO GOES: Families, singles, anyone seeking old-fashioned
glamour.
</P>
<P>
   STAR ATTRACTIONS: Acapulco is home to some of the most beautiful
and luxurious hotels in Mexico, including the famous Las Brisas,
with its private pools attached to some rooms. The night life is
lively and upscale, the dining continental, the shopping plentiful.
(In a welcome move, beach vendors have been relocated to a separate
shopping area, so you can sun without being approached by hawkers.)
You can't go home without seeing the famed cliff divers, who do
their thing daily at La Quebrada, and have since 1934.
</P>
<P>
   DRAWBACKS: Tourism officials say the beach and bay have been all
cleaned up, but it's still not as pristine and dazzling as those on
the Gulf of Mexico side. It can be expensive. And if you don't
venture far from your high-rise hotel, you'll never realize you
went to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   NEW: The CICI water park, which offers seal and dolphin shows
and water slides and rides, was recently renovated. And in the
Acapulco Diamante area, the latest area of development, the new
Vidafel Mayan Palace is spectacular, with grounds filled with
reflecting pools, waterfalls, giant Mayan statues and canals plied
by flower-filled boats.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: The Acapulco Convention and Visitors Bureau Web
site is at www.acapulco-cvb.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BAJA
</P>
<P>
   WHERE AND WHAT: The desert tip of the Baja California peninsula
has developed into a busy resort area with two distinctly different
towns. San Jose del Cabo is quieter, more traditional, with a
traditional downtown plaza. Cabo San Lucas, pegged Cabo San Loco by
some visitors, is the party town. And hotels and resorts stretch
nearly all the distance in between.
</P>
<P>
   WHO GOES: Golfers, fishing enthusiasts, whale watchers; singles
and young couples flock to the party atmosphere of Cabo San Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   STAR ATTRACTIONS: Sport fishing for marlin, sailfish and
swordfish is a big activity, on anything from a posh cruiser to a
simple ``panga'' owned by a local. Golf is popular, too, especially
at the new Jack Nicklaus-designed course. Beachgoers might see
migrating gray whales off the coast, particularly between January
and March.
</P>
<P>
   DRAWBACKS: Cabo San Lucas is packed with American-style spots
like Planet Hollywood, often at the expense of locally flavored
hangouts. The luxury of many of the resorts doesn't come cheap.
</P>
<P>
   NEW: Las Ventanas al Paraiso _ managed by the Rosewood Hotel
folk who also maintain Dallas' Mansion on Turtle Creek _ is a hot
new luxury hotel. It claims the largest suites in Mexico (nearly
1,000 square feet), a restaurant managed by a former Mansion chef,
a high-end spa and perhaps the world's fanciest tequila bar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CANCUN
</P>
<P>
   WHERE AND WHAT: Located on the Yucatan Peninsula, which juts
into the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean, Cancun was largely a
stretch of empty beach until it opened for business in 1972. An
easy jaunt from Texas, it has also become Mexico's most popular
beach resort, with more than 25,000 hotel rooms, many of them in
huge, elaborate beach-side high-rises, and a seemingly endless
supply of restaurants and shops.
</P>
<P>
   WHO GOES: High school and college kids on spring break or
graduation trips; conventioneers; families.
</P>
<P>
   STAR ATTRACTIONS: It's the beach, stupid; this site was selected
for development by data-crunching tourism experts, and they got
that part right. Cancun is situated on a truly beautiful stretch of
beach, with white sand and sparkling turquoise water.
</P>
<P>
   The explosive development means there's plenty to do, from water
parks to shopping to restaurants to water sports like parasailing
and snorkeling. The bar and club scene is lively, varied and can go
late into the night. And it's a good ``starter vacation'' for
travelers new to Mexico; no Spanish is really necessary.
</P>
<P>
   DRAWBACKS: And that, for others, is the chief gripe about
Cancun: It's possible to spend a week here and never realize you're
in Mexico. The joint is packed with U.S. restaurants (Tony Roma's!
T.G.I. Friday's!) and retailers (The Gap!). Everybody speaks
English. Some of your fellow vacationers may be largely focused on
seeing just how much tequila they can put away. And though you can
get good deals on package trips, food and beverage and cab fares
here can cost more than nearly anywhere in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   NEW: Within the last year, three nature parks have opened within
an hour of Cancun. The closest, Tres Rios, is just 30 minutes away
and offers horseback riding on the beach, walking and bicycle tours
of the jungle, and swimming in ``cenotes,'' places where
underground rivers break through to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour away is Xpu-ha, featuring nature trails and a bird
sanctuary. About the same distance away is Actun Chen, where
vacationers can explore caves in a jungle setting, in close range
to spider monkeys and iguanas.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: Cancun Convention and Visitor Bureau, (800)
CANCUN8, or www.gocancun.com.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COZUMEL
</P>
<P>
   WHERE AND WHAT: This small island in the Caribbean, just off the
coast between Cancun and Playa del Carmen, has long been known as a
diver's destination. No wonder; its clear water hosts the
second-largest reef in the world.
</P>
<P>
   WHO GOES: Divers. And snorkelers.
</P>
<P>
   STAR ATTRACTIONS: The diving and snorkeling really can be as
spectacular as advertised. The friendly town of San Miguel, the
island's ``only'' town, has decent shopping and dining. And there's
a good range of hotels, from clean budget operations to luxury
resorts.
</P>
<P>
   DRAWBACKS: The beach isn't as good as the other Mexican
Caribbean coasts. Though there's good dining and some night life,
revelers expecting Cancun-style liveliness will be disappointed;
divers tend to go to bed relatively early.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HUATULCO
</P>
<P>
   WHERE AND WHAT: One of Mexico's newest developments, hotels
started opening in this Pacific resort only in the late '80s. A
series of nine bays stretches along the coast, providing beautiful
settings for luxury hotels and all-inclusive resorts.
</P>
<P>
   WHO GOES: Beach lovers; couples and honeymooners; those looking
for a newer, quieter resort.
</P>
<P>
   STAR ATTRACTIONS: Secluded and small, this full-service resort
offers privacy that others don't, with boats available to take you
to the nearly private, sandy coves. All-inclusive resorts are
popular here.
</P>
<P>
   DRAWBACKS: It might be ``too'' secluded for some; development
has outpaced the tourists, and a number of retail spots haven't yet
been occupied, making parts of the resort seem almost abandoned.
Guests can't easily walk from hotel to hotel, and those staying at
the beach will need a car or taxi to get to the small but pleasant
downtown area of shops and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAZATLAN
</P>
<P>
   WHERE AND WHAT: This is the northernmost of the large Pacific
resorts, and has been attracting water sports lovers since the
first tourist fishing expeditions in the '40s.
</P>
<P>
   WHO GOES: Families, fishing enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   STAR ATTRACTIONS: Sport fishing, boating and other water sports,
such as windsurfing and parasailing. The night life, especially in
the beach zone, can approach Acapulco's for liveliness, though it
doesn't seem as upscale. Mazatlan's downtown, like that of Acapulco
and Puerto Vallarta, is a vibrant place, full of shops and market
areas, and interesting architecture and a fun place to wander. The
resort attracts a larger number of Mexican tourists than some
others, so it has less of an overt U.S. flavor and, often, lower
prices.
</P>
<P>
   DRAWBACKS: The so-called golden zone on the beach, site of most
large tourist hotels, still strikes some as overly glitzy. The
beach, though pleasant, isn't as beautiful as the ones on the
Caribbean coast, and the diving and snorkeling aren't as enticing,
either.
</P>
<P>
   NEW: Two marinas are under construction on the north end of the
beach, and when they open, they'll give Mazatlan the largest such
operation in Mexico. More luxury hotels and condos are planned for
this area as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAYAN RIVIERA
</P>
<P>
   WHERE AND WHAT: Stretching more than 60 miles, from south of
Cancun to the archaeological site of Tulum, this newly christened
strip of beaches includes the relaxed beach town of Playa del
Carmen, the diver's dream of Akumal, and newer resorts such as
Puerto Aventuras.
</P>
<P>
   WHO GOES: Beach fans looking for a more laid-back, authentically
Mexican vacation; independent travelers; veteran Mexican
vacationers who've seen everything else.
</P>
<P>
   STAR ATTRACTIONS: The soft white-sand beaches and azure water
are at least the equal of Cancun's, and possibly even more
beautiful. Even better, it's relatively easy to get a stretch of
beach to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   DRAWBACKS: If you're looking for rollicking night life, keep
looking. In Playa, for instance, the streets start rolling up about
midnight; most vacationers head for the hotel after dinner and
drinks and, on a big night, listening to a live band. And after a
few days, you may feel you've seen every restaurant and shop each
of these relatively small resorts has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   NEW: This section of Mexico's Caribbean is growing faster than
any other; a new resort, restaurant or major shop opens almost
every month.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE: Unlike most of the other destinations we
profiled, there is no major aiport here. Fly into Cancun and rent a
car or take a taxi. (If you're at one of the pricier hotels, they
might arrange transport.) Or fly into Cozumel, and you can get a
high-speed ferry over to Playa for less than $10.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUERTO ANGEL/PUERTO ESCONDIDO
</P>
<P>
   WHERE AND WHAT: These like-minded neighboring beach towns on the
Pacific Coast, about 250 miles from Acapulco and 75 miles from
Huatulco, aren't resorts of the type many U.S. travelers expect
from Mexico. They're filled with small, basic (occasionally even
grungy) hotels and inexpensive restaurants serving fresh seafood.
</P>
<P>
   WHO GOES: Surfers, hippies, backpackers, budget travelers.
</P>
<P>
   STAR ATTRACTIONS: The surf here is so good, athletes flock here
from all over the world; even if you don't surf, it's fun to watch.
Much less expensive than the shinier, newer resorts, both towns
give off a laid-back, friendly vibe that tends to attract a younger
crowd, plus backpacking Europeans. If you want to settle in for a
month or two on a budget, this is the place.
</P>
<P>
   DRAWBACKS: If you're into creature comforts and upscale resorts,
this isn't the spot for you; lodging and dining spots tend toward
the rustic. There's little to do beyond sit on the beach or surf,
and the night life is largely nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   NEW: Nothing much. Which, of course, is part of the charm.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE: There's actually a small airport at Puerto
Escondido, with connecting flights from Mexico City, Huatulco and
Oaxaca. More likely, fly into Huatulco on a charter and rent a car
for the scenic coastline drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUERTO VALLARTA
</P>
<P>
   WHERE AND WHAT: Spreading along mountain cliffs and
champagne-colored beaches midway down the Pacific coast, just below
the point where the Sea of Cortez spills into the vast Pacific,
this Mexican jewel has aged gracefully. Touted in the 1950s as a
``little Acapulco,'' tiny little PV (as regulars call it) changed
forever when movie director John Huston chose to film his classic
``The Night of the Iguana'' here. Once the Hollywood press and the
world learned that Liz Taylor was hanging out here with new lover
Richard Burton, growth exploded.
</P>
<P>
   WHO GOES: Spring breakers and party hounds are drawn to the new
half, south of downtown; lovers of all ages seek the romantic
environs of the cobblestone village and the jungle-shadowed beaches
to the north.
</P>
<P>
   STAR ATTRACTIONS: A delightful sense of place is found in the
simple, old-world town bisected by the Rio Cuale, where village
women still scrub their wash and where donkeys still climb the
steep, narrow streets; right in town is an inexpensive enclave of
older, rustic cottages called Molino de Agua. Up the coastal road
are charming beaches and boat rides to distant, secluded pieces of
paradise.
</P>
<P>
   DRAWBACKS: The larger hotels and resorts are almost too perfect
and pretty, and they're removed from the essence of PV.
</P>
<P>
   NEW: La Jolla de Mismaloya is a glorious resort overlooking the
beach where ``Iguana'' was filmed. New restaurant choices include
Le Bistro Jazz Cafe, where you can skip the Mexican and have crab
sashimi or steak in brandy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ZIHUATANEJO/IXTAPA
</P>
<P>
   WHERE AND WHAT: Along the extensive and very generous Pacific
coast of Mexico _ roughly 130 miles north of Acapulco and a little
more than 200 miles south of Puerto Vallarta _ are a pair of sister
towns that are anything but twins.
</P>
<P>
   Zihuatanejo, which is pronounced ``zee-what-tah-NAY-hoe'' but
usually just called ``zee-whah,'' is said to have been discovered
by Cortez and company in 1524. John Wayne brought his buddies
fishing here in the 1940s _ and it was the destination for Tim
Robbins' escaped convict in ``The Shawshank Redemption.'' Still a
pleasant, quiet fishing village, it was joined in the late 1960s by
the resort town called Ixtapa (''ees-TAH-pah''), created five miles
north by the Mexican government tourism arm.
</P>
<P>
   WHO GOES: Honeymooners and other lovers seeking old-fashioned,
often luxurious escape.
</P>
<P>
   STAR ATTRACTIONS: A wonderful, authentic fishing village with a
delightful marketplace offering bargains on everything from leather
to baskets, textiles and flowers, lavish meals at modest prices,
beautiful lodgings that don't break the bank and a series of
beaches where you can sun, eat, drink or buy freshly caught snapper
from fishermen who bring in the day's catches.
</P>
<P>
   DRAWBACKS: A pronounced lack of Mexico is felt in Ixtapa, which
is a sterile arrangement of large, modern hotels, shopping centers
and overpriced restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   (Star-Telegram writer June Naylor Rodriguez contributed to this
report.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (General information on Mexico: Try the Ministry of Tourism of
Mexico at (800) 44MEXICO (446-3942) or on the Internet at
mexico-travel.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
