<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1969 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-INJURIES-COX     09-14 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-INJURIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL brass won't admit playing on turf harmful; survey shows
players prefer grassBy Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Clark Gaines watched replays of New York Jets
quarterback Vinny Testaverde rupturing his left Achilles' tendon
Sunday, he shook his head in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Nine days before, Jets wide receiver Wayne Chrebet had broken
his foot playing in an exhibition game on the artificial turf of
Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Gaines, a regional director for the NFL Players Association,
blames artificial turf.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries have devastated the Jets, who were a popular
favorite to return to their first Super Bowl since the 1968 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Testaverde's injury and Chrebet's injury were
probably two of the most most ridiculous injuries I've seen, and
they could have been avoided,'' Gaines said. ``When you look at the
non-contact injuries that occur on grass versus the non-contact
injuries that occur on artificial turf, it's no contest. It's
probably two or three times higher on turf.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chrebet broke his foot jogging. How can you break your foot
jogging? He was going across the field in motion and turned up
field and broke his foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde is only one player on a long list of star players,
including teammate Leon Johnson, who were hurt in Week 1 of the
1999 NFL season.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit wide receiver Herman Moore will miss at least a month
after spraining his left knee. Rookie running back Ricky Williams
of New Orleans is hobbling with a sprained left ankle, and
Tennessee Titans cornerback Charles Fisher's career might be over
because of a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   The players association has conducted surveys of its members
every two years since 1994, Gaines said. In last season's survey,
the players named Giants Stadium as the fourth-worst playing
surface in the NFL, he said. The artificial turf in Philadelphia's
Veterans Stadium, Cincinnati's Riverfront Stadium and Pittsburgh's
Three Rivers Stadium were considered the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-seven percent of the players indicated they prefer to
play on natural grass over artificial turf, as opposed to 5 percent
who favor fake grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, the players made no beefs about it in terms
of how they feel,'' Gaines said. ``The league knows how the players
feel. But the league has decided to do nothing about it. The teams
have consistently let their investment _ the players _ play on an
unsafe surface. The players don't want to, but they're forced to
play on turf in games.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Aiello, vice president of public relations for the NFL,
said the league has conducted scientific studies ``for decades
since artificial turf was first introduced.'' Dr. John Powell, an
athletic trainer in Michigan and Iowa, conducted a
league-sanctioned study in the 1980s that found little difference
between the severity and number of injuries on turf and grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, injuries occur on both surfaces,'' Aiello said.
``The scientific research we've done over the years has shown one
thing _ there's not a significant increase in injuries when playing
on turf. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``What about (Miami quarterback) Dan Marino tearing his
Achilles' in 1993 on grass in Cleveland?'' he asked. ``Why don't
people say that grass caused his leg injury? We recognize that
players prefer to play on grass, but let's stick to the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Medlin, head trainer of the Atlanta Falcons, says
Testaverde's injury probably wasn't caused by playing on artificial
turf. ``If it's going to go, it's going to go,'' Medlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Medlin said the Falcons, who play on artificial turf in the
Georgia Dome, suffer the same amount of injuries on turf and grass,
but he said the injuries on the artificial stuff tend to be more
severe.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler, recovering from a pulled
right hamstring he suffered in the fourth quarter of Sunday's 17-14
loss to Minnesota, has suffered numerous concussions when his head
hits the artificial turf, which is put down over concrete.
</P>
<P>
   ``That surface isn't going to give,'' Medlin said.
</P>
<P>
   The municipalities that control the stadiums often are reluctant
to replace the turf, Gaines said. The stadiums also are used for
music concerts and other events, which could destroy a grass
surface. Gaines estimated the cost of installing grass at $1.5
million. The Jets signed Testaverde to a $19.5 million extension
before this season.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Jets and Giants lease Giants Stadium from the New
Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority, which has experimented with
grass each of the past two preseasons. Aiello said the group is
considering installing grass permanently next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say to the teams, 'If you're going to make a
multi-million-dollar investment in a player, when are you going to
put him on a safe surface?'' Gaines said. ``It's a bad business
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
