<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN-FLA-RUN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis may be key to Tennessee redemption
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Jamal Lewis is a laid-back guy. Likes to have
fun. Doesn't sweat the small stuff. Doesn't have the word
``nervous'' in his vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   But not this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee running back performed his required duty during
media day Tuesday, but his mind was somewhere else. He already was
focusing on Gainesville, Fla., and Saturday night's big showdown
between No. 2 Tennessee and No. 4 Florida.
</P>
<P>
   For Tennessee, it is a chance to win two in a row over Florida.
The Vols also will be trying to win in Gainesville for the first
time in the '90s. For Lewis, however, the game represents a shot at
redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, from Atlanta's Douglass High, was a highly regarded
freshman when Tennessee last visited the Swamp in 1997. The
coaching staff knew Lewis could run. But it didn't know whether he
learned enough to pick up the complicated blitzes of the Florida
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than risk the health of quarterback Peyton Manning in the
third game of the season, Lewis carried only five times against the
Gators, and the Vols gained just 45 yards on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee lost the game 33-20 and critics said Lewis should have
been used more. Lewis went on to be the nation's top freshman
running back with 1,364 yards rushing for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I would have liked to have gotten a few more snaps,''
Lewis said, ``because I just wanted to help make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamal got only got a few carries in that gam,'' quarterback
Tee Martin said, ``but he wanted lot more, I can tell you that. You
have no idea how hungry he is to go down to Gainesville.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis might have to be the difference if Tennessee is going to
break its six-game losing streak at Florida:
</P>
<P>
   _ The team that has gained the most yards rushing in the game
each year in the '90s has won.
</P>
<P>
   _ When a Tennessee runner exceeds 100 yards, the Vols have won
33 games in a row.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 10 of Phillip Fulmer's 11 losses, no Tennessee back reached
100 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any big game, it's important that you can run the
football,'' Fulmer said. ``With those guys, you really want to stay
ahead in down and distance. So, sometimes a 2- or 3-yard run is not
a bad play.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has gone over 100 yards in 11 of his last 14 starts. He
had 159 yards on 25 carries in Tennessee's opener against Wyoming.
The Volunteers' offensive line could be the school's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that to win we have to run the ball,'' Lewis said. ``I
feel really good about my offensive line and the other backs we
have. I think we'll do okay.''
</P>
<P>
   No Tennessee back has rushed for more than 100 yards against
Florida since Tony Thompson in 1990, but chances of breaking 100
look pretty good for Lewis. Last year in Knoxville, he had 82 yards
on 21 carries against a Florida defense that led the SEC in every
statistical category. Florida coach Steve Spurrier also knows what
being able to run the ball means in this game. His Florida teams
are is 52-1 when a back goes over 100 yards. The Gators had
minus-13 yards rushing in last year's loss to Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing 95th in the nation in rushing last season,
Florida has recommitted itself to the running game. Redshirt
freshman Earnest Graham has 223 yards on 30 carries in the Gators'
first two wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get back to the line of scrimmage last year,''
Spurrier said. ``If we can't run a little bit, we'll be in for a
long night, I would imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TO VICTORY
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Florida-Tennessee game in the '90s has been
the team most successful running the ball.
</P>
<P>
   YEAR WINNER SCORE RUSHING ADVANTAGE
</P>
<P>
   1990 Tennessee 45-3 228-64 +164
</P>
<P>
   1991 Florida 35-18 114-49 +65
</P>
<P>
   1992 Tennessee 31-14 250-68 +182
</P>
<P>
   1993 Florida 41-34 156-76 +80
</P>
<P>
   1994 Florida 31-0 136-68 +68
</P>
<P>
   1995 Florida 62-37 203-124 +79
</P>
<P>
   1996 Florida 35-29 149-9 +140
</P>
<P>
   1997 Florida 33-20 95-45 +50
</P>
<P>
   1998 Tennessee 20-17 (OT) 171-(-13) +184
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
