<SLUG> BC-MARKS-KINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S MARKS &AMP; SPENCER TO OVERHAUL U.S. OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Marks &AMP; Spencer PLC, the once-expansive British
retailer, announced a major overhaul of its U.S. operations
Tuesday, saying it would sell the Kings supermarkets in New Jersey
while promoting Brooks Brothers menswear stores in an effort to
bolster brands with international allure.
</P>
<P>
   The august store chain, which is still Britain's biggest
clothing retailer, has been under siege at home from rivals
clambering into the market for young adult clothing, leaving Marks
&AMP; Spencer stores looking under-inspired and overpriced. At the same
time, it has pared back overseas operations, closing stores in
Canada, France and Germany since last April. There had been
speculation among analysts that Brooks Brothers might be among the
next to be sold.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday, Marks &AMP; Spencer said, however, that
Brooks Brothers' 148 stores in the United States, along with 71
stores in Japan and six franchise operations in Hong Kong and
Taiwan had ``the potential for growth both in the United States and
internationally.'' Brooks Brothers sales in fiscal 1999 totaled
$550 million.
</P>
<P>
   Marks &AMP; Spencer bought Brooks Brothers in 1987 for $770 million
and paid $110 million for Kings one year later. With annual sales
of $400 million, Kings' 25 stores in New Jersey are currently
valued in the region of $190 million. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
has been appointed to handle the sale. Mark Ashman, a Marks &AMP;
Spencer spokesman, said no specific talks with buyers were under
way. ``It's an open field,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sale represents a remarkable shift for the British company,
one of the first to venture beyond national frontiers for new
business. Now, it is reining in its U.S. operations at just the
moment when Wal-Mart Inc., the biggest U.S. retail chain, is making
forays into Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Marks &AMP; Spencer said it would seek to promote Brooks Brothers
and planned to introduce the store to Europe, starting in Britain.
``We believe it has got quite a lot of legs and London would be our
first target,'' said finance director Robert Colville.
</P>
<P>
   The company's pullback from the United States is the latest of
many indications that the British retailer is trying to escape the
problems that led to a major management shake-up late last year as
both profits and share-price tumbled. But the announcement Tuesday
did nothing to help the shares, which fell 2.5 pence, or nearly 1
percent, to 373.5 pence, or about $6. The shares are down about 16
percent since last November's management crisis. Last May, the
company said its profits for fiscal 1999 were down by half to $596
million.
</P>
<P>
   Ashman, the spokesman, said the company's new strategy meant
developing subsidiaries with ``international appeal'' while
shedding those without an international brand.
</P>
<P>
   The changes reflect efforts by Peter Salsbury, who took over as
chief executive earlier this year, to lower costs and lure
customers back to Marks &AMP; Spencer's stores, once regarded as models
of high quality and good value.
</P>
<P>
   Ashman said the company is close to completing a refurbishment
of 100 Main Street stores, has introduced a new fall fashion line
and plans to introduce more innovative food lines. In October,
Marks &AMP; Spencer plans to take an unusually bold step into the
technological future: as of October, Ashman said, Marks &AMP; Spencer
will begin selling cellular phones alongside its clothing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
