<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-OAKLAND-A's-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAKLAND A'S WAIT FOR D-DAY ON SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DWIGHT CHAPIN and MATTHEW YI  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In baseball terms, the bottom of the ninth
inning is almost here for the investment group that is hoping to
buy the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 major-league team owners are expected to vote Thursday
during meetings in Cooperstown, N.Y., on whether to accept a $122.4
million offer from 16 investors headed by supermarket mogul Bob
Piccinini _ a deal that would guarantee that the A's stay in
Oakland until 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely on the agenda,'' said Andy Dolich, the former
A's executive who put together the investment group and would serve
as team president. ``Absolutely, we're optimistic about a positive
outcome. We believe we've done everything asked of us to prove our
worth, with all the various bodies. We are as enthusiastic as we've
ever been. But we don't cast a vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolich said he and the other investors have been given no
indication what the often capricious owners will do. But it will
take a yes vote by three-quarters of the 14 American League owners
and a simple majority of 16 National League owners for the sale to
be approved.
</P>
<P>
   The final report by the Major League Baseball staff on the
proposed deal went out to the owners last week.
</P>
<P>
   Before going to the full ownerships group, the sale will be
considered along with three other ownership transfer proposals _
Cincinnati, Kansas City and Montreal _ by baseball's ownership
committee. The panel is made up of commissioner Bud Selig and
representatives from 10 of the teams.
</P>
<P>
   Public officials in Oakland say the wait and the uncertainty
have been like sitting on pins and needles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely pulling for the home team; there's no
question about that,'' said Oakland City Manager Robert Bobb,
referring to the local investment group.
</P>
<P>
   Bobb and Oakland Mayor Jerry Brown have been lobbying Major
League Baseball to approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   When developers Steve Schott and Ken Hofmann purchased the A's
from the Walter Haas family in 1995, they signed a lease agreement
that would keep the ballclub in Oakland until 2004, with an option
to terminate the contract at the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Schott and Hofmann announced last year they would be exercising
that option, causing Oakland and Alameda County officials to
scramble to find a new owner who would keep the franchise in
Oakland at least through the length of the current lease.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving bids from two sets of investors, the city and
county officials decided on the Piccinini/Dolich group, which also
includes baseball Hall of Famer Reggie Jackson, the Oakland
Tribune, Men's Wearhouse president and founder George Zimmer,
advertising executive Jeff Goodby, attorney Guy Saperstein and Wind
River Systems chairman Jerry Fiddler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that (Dolich) has assembled, clearly, an all-star
cast to revive and continue the excitement for baseball here in
Oakland,'' Bobb said.
</P>
<P>
   Alameda County Supervisor Mary King said the only thing clear is
that the investors' group has met all the financial criteria set by
Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the objective thing and there's no guessing in that,''
King said. ``However, whatever subjectivity (the owners) bring into
the vote, that is hard for me to predict. Because I have no
intimate familiarity of how the team owners think, I can never
guess that. As far as I know, these guys are very independent
thinkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Vataha, president of a Boston-based investment banking
firm Game Plan LLC, hired as consultants by the city of Oakland and
Alameda County, sounded much the same theme as King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm highly optimistic,'' he said. ``I believe we've done
everything that we can do. I don't see any negatives out there, But
you have the vote of 30 owners, and that's hard to predict.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a clear need for urgency.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is not approved by Monday _ the date the sale
agreement expires _ Schott and Hofmann can consider other offers.
</P>
<P>
   They would retain ownership of the team with an obligation to
stay in Oakland only until 2001, with a year-to-year lease
arrangement at the Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding a possible delay in a vote by the baseball owners,
Dolich said, ``I've been told that they understand the unique
timing of our circumstances. Our group has flexibility (in the
timing), but we've always gone with the concept that the date is
the date, and we haven't requested an extension.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
