<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDIA-SINGH-NYT &LR;      09-14 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-SINGH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULAR INDIAN WRITER PREFERS LUST TO LOVE, TO CRITICS' CHAGRIN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ ``With lust, you go kaput at a certain age,''
said Khushwant Singh, one of India's most popular writers and
eccentric characters, who, at 84, has just written a sexy potboiler
that he said could have been called ``The Fantasies of an
Octogenarian.''
</P>
<P>
   His publisher, Viking, preferred to title it with the more
marketable ``The Company of Women.'' Some of his critics describe
the novel, which details a divorced man's sexual escapades with a
series of beautiful women, as yet more second-rate frivolity from a
writer who should be cultivating a sober, statesman-like posture in
his old age.
</P>
<P>
   But Singh, author of weighty works of history and fiction, as
well as raunchy joke books and an unending stream of newspaper
columns, exults in his continuing ability to provoke. To those who
say he has squandered his reputation, Singh tartly retorts, ``I
honestly couldn't give a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   One recent evening, he shambled from his armchair to a small
side table and poured himself a Scotch, briefly interrupting a
discourse on the advantages of what he called earthy lust over
``airy-fairy'' love, as Kaval, his frail, ailing wife of 60 years,
listened impassively from a couch on the other side of the living
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in lust because I know what it is,'' Singh said.
``Love I find a very elusive concept.''
</P>
<P>
   But in old age, it seems, even lust can be a shifty friend. The
desire remains, he said, but the ability to fulfill it diminishes.
He mentioned the pathos of a scene in a Muriel Spark novel in which
an old man calls on a woman and pays for the pleasure of watching
as she bares the full length of her leg.
</P>
<P>
   He got the idea for his latest book, he said, when a friend told
him about her father, who had divorced her mother and gone on to
have a series of affairs. ``I think he advertised,'' Singh said.
``I thought he was a wonderful unusual character.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh wrote what a reviewer called his ``rollicking sexual
romp'' in seclusion. He took his cook of 40 years to the family
villa in a hill station in Himachal Pradesh. There, he sat in the
garden under a spreading tree and filled yellow legal pads with his
small longhand script.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the lust I can't spend on people, I spend on paper,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to name his greatest pleasures in life, his wife, who
had said almost nothing up till then, replied for him: ``Crossword
puzzles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he agreed, ``crossword puzzles in the morning and good
Scotch in the evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh has for many years had a wide appeal built on his
unpretentious mixture of seriousness, silliness and sex. In his
mid-30s, he abandoned the solid, respectable fields of law and
diplomacy for the chancier work of a scribbler.
</P>
<P>
   He could have just played golf. He came from a wealthy family of
Sikh entrepreneurs _ his father was the contractor who built India
Gate, the grand archway that is Delhi's version of the Arc de
Triomphe _ but Singh had no interest in either business or leisure.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he has kept up a grueling schedule of writing _ one that
has left him no time for the drunkenness and debauchery that some
have thought were his metier. His reputation as the dirty old man
of Delhi is undeserved, his friends say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a myth, a great big lie,'' said his fellow
best-selling author Shobha De. ``He's just a party flirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh, a workaholic by his own description, has now written so
many books he has lost count, and he continues to churn out two
syndicated newspaper columns a week. His son, Rahul, said his
father has sometimes been gullible in politics _ for example,
supporting Prime Minister Indira Gandhi for some months after she
suspended civil liberties in 1975 _ but has always been honest.
</P>
<P>
   And at crucial junctures, he has stood up for his beliefs,
opposing the Hindu fundamentalism that led to the destruction of a
mosque in 1992 and denouncing the leader of a Sikh separatist
insurgency in his native Punjab as a ``homicidal maniac.'' From the
early 1980s until just a few months ago, he lived under constant
police guard to protect him from Sikh militants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to kill me anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His words, however, can still sting like a bee. In the current
election, he campaigned for Manmohan Singh, a fellow Sikh who was
the principal architect of India's economic reforms in the early
1990s and is a man with a reputation for rectitude who would never
tell an off-color joke, much less laugh at one.
</P>
<P>
   With an impish glint in his eye, Khushwant Singh waited for his
chance to speak at a recent rally in a predominantly Sikh
neighborhood, while the boring political speeches droned on.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Kumar Malhotra, the candidate of the Hindu nationalist
Bharatiya Janata Party, had been accused of challenging Manmohan
Singh's credentials as a Sikh because his daughters had married
Hindus and suggesting that Singh's turban be removed to see if he
really had unshorn hair like a true Sikh. (Malhotra has denied
making those statements.)
</P>
<P>
   Other speakers had expressed umbrage at so grave an ethnic
insult, but Khushwant Singh replied with a bawdy one-liner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why doesn't the BJP man drop his trousers so we can see if
he's a Hindu or a Muslim?'' he asked to the howls of the crowd.
(Muslims are circumcised; Hindus are not.)
</P>
<P>
   As the rally dragged on, with flies buzzing around in the
oppressive heat, Khushwant Singh's high spirits began to fade. He
yawned and his shoulders drooped. Reeta Devi, the neighbor and
friend who had protectively accompanied him, began to fret.
``They're squishing Mr. Singh,'' she told one of the rally's
organizers, her voice rising. ``If people push him like that, we
can't go to these meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he escaped the dais, he and Mrs. Devi hurried to the car.
``Don't stop,'' he urged, ``or they won't let me get away.''
</P>
<P>
   As the car slowly made its way through the rush hour traffic,
Mrs. Devi worried that Mrs. Singh would be angry because they were
late. ``I promised her I'd have you home by 6:30,'' she said,
joking nervously, ``I think I won't come in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 7 after 7,'' Singh observed. A man who pours the first of
his three Scotches at 7 p.m. sharp and shuts the bar at 8, he was
anxious to get home to his armchair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
