<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOMBINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SEIZE EXPLOSIVES IN APARTMENT BUILDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In the wake of two bombings here that claimed at least
210 lives, Russian police say they have prevented a third blast by
seizing as much as 2 tons of explosives in yet another apartment
building.
</P>
<P>
   The explosives and a 70-yard fuse were discovered in a 12-story
residential building housing 260 apartments in southeastern Moscow,
police said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the death toll for Monday's blast has risen to
118, as rescue workers completed their work digging through the
smoldering remains of Moscow's worst explosion since World War II.
Monday's pre-dawn explosion came just four days after a blast at
another apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials also said they have evidence linking
the explosions to Chechen field commander Shaimil Basayev and the
Jordanian-born Islamic rebel leader Khattab. Since last month,
Basayev and Khattab have led an insurgency in the Muslim-dominated
republic of Dagestan in southern Russia. The two seek to create an
Islamic state in the Caucasus region free from Moscow's grip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can now say that these blasts are tied to Basayev and
Khattab,'' said Igor Zubov, deputy head of Russia's Interior
Ministry, which runs the nation's police force. Zubov said that
Russia's police have in their possession recordings of telephone
conversations that implicate Basayev and Khattab in the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Basayev and Khattab have repeatedly denied responsibility for
the blasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are carrying out an open war with the Russian armed forces
and have never even considered killing sleeping, peaceful citizens
with bombs and shells,'' Khattab said Tuesday in a statement from
Chechnya's capital, Grozny. ``Our fight is against the Russian army
and not against women and children.''
</P>
<P>
   Police also say they have detained a third suspect in the
bombings. Two arrests were announced Monday. Police gave no details
but the Interfax news agency reported that the suspects were tied
to a business that had rented commercial space on the first floor
of both apartment buildings. Police released sketches of three
other men suspected of being involved in the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, meanwhile, has proposed sealing
off Russia's border with the breakaway republic of Chechnya. In
1994-96, Moscow fought a 20-month war with Chechnya in an
unsuccessful attempt to prevent that republic's bid for
independence. Although Chechnya tecnically remains part of Russia,
authorities in Moscow have no control over events there.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to Russia's parliament Tuesday, Putin called Chechnya
a ``huge terrorist camp.'' The prime minister demanded that the
republic's leadership turn over suspected terrorists to Moscow.
``Otherwise we will ruthlessly eliminate them every time they cross
the border,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya's Foreign Ministry released a statement Tuesday
condemning terrorism and expressing sympathy for the victims of the
two Moscow blasts.
</P>
<P>
   Putin also told lawmakers that he opposed the declaration of a
state of emergency in Russia, a move that could put parliamentary
elections scheduled here for December in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Police have, however, announced a major ``anti-terrorism''
campaign in which the attics and basements of Moscow's 30,000
apartment buildings would be checked for explosives and suspicious
residents. As of Tuesday, police claimed to have checked 26,000
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Police in bulletproof vests combed Moscow's streets, parks,
markets and subway stations demanding that anybody they deemed
suspicious show identity documents prving that they have a right to
be in the capital. Moscow's strict registration law requires all
visitors to the capital to register with police within three days
of arriving.
</P>
<P>
   And with suspicion for the bombings falling on Chechens and
others from the Caucasus region, dark-skinned people were the most
vulnerable. Riot police also manned checkpoints and searched
vehicles on higways in and out of Moscow. Hundreds of people
lacking proper registration have reportedly been detained.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Iskandaryan, a Moscow-based specialist of the Caucasus
region said the measures would do little to stop terrorism and only
harm Russia's already strained relations with its Moslem
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any terrorist could easily pay a completely Russian-looking
Muscovite to plant a bomb,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
