<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2004 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-FALN-CLEMENCY-RENO-HN     09-14 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALN-CLEMENCY-RENO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS AND ADMINISTRATION COLLIDE OVER CLEMENCY OFFERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Angry congressional Republicans charged the White
House with ``stonewalling'' about President Clinton's decision to
grant clemency to 14 Puerto Rican militants and accused the
administration of silencing an FBI official who had planned to
testify at a Senate hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., called on
Attorney General Janet Reno to come before Congress and explain
Clinton's clemency decision, but she rejected the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   The senators asked for Reno after the Justice Department ordered
Neil Gallagher, assistant director for the FBI's National Security
Division, not to testify at a Tuesday hearing of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee's terrorism subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell and Helms accused the White House of pressuring the
Justice Department into making the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty clear that the White House is behind
this,'' Coverdell said. ``You've got to wonder what would cause the
White House to bypass a chance to explain themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter, the two senators called on Reno to appear before
the Foreign Relations Committee to explain the Justice Department's
and the FBI's positions on the president's offer of clemency to 16
Puerto Rican militants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people have a right to know why and how this
decision was made ... and your department has an obligation to
provide answers on this issue,'' Coverdell said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining its decision not to allow Gallagher to appear before
the committee, the Justice Department said in a statement that
there were constitutional questions about whether it would be
appropriate for FBI officials to testify because the power to grant
clemency is the president's exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate statement, the Justice Department said Reno
declined the senators' offer, saying the attorney general could not
testify for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   But Coverdell and Helms said the reason was that ``the White
House pulled the plug on the FBI ... is obviously stonewalling
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's explanation also was criticized by
several experts on constitutional law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI or the Justice Department may not want to talk about
how the decision was made, but there's absolutely no legal or
constitutional reason why they can't talk to Congress about it,''
said Louis Seidman, a law professor at Georgetown University here.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's order also prompted the House
Government Reform Committee, which is scheduled to hold hearings on
Thursday on the issue, to subpoena many of the witnesses who had
previously been invited to appear at the Senate hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Gallagher, the House committee subpoenaed acting
Assistant General Jon P. Jennings and White House counsel Beth
Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Reno, we expected something like this to happen, so we
were prepared to send out the subpoenas even before this morning,''
said Mark Corallo, spokesman for the House panel.
</P>
<P>
   Corallo said those subpoenaed officials must attend the hearing
but that they can refuse to testify by invoking executive privilege
_ which is a claim that their testimony would hamper their ability
to give the president candid advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I don't see how telling the American people why the
president did something that he is supposedly proud of doing can
have anything to do with executive privilege,'' Corello said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokeswoman Chris Watney said the agency had
not received the subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's hearing before the Senate terrorism panel was
designed to explore whether the president's grant of clemency may
have undermined the government's strict anti-terrorism policy.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing came as the Senate approved a Republican-sponsored
resolution condemning clemency for the Puerto Ricans. The
resolution passed 95-2. The House adopted a similar resolution last
week, 311-41.
</P>
<P>
   Although Coverdell's hearing was to focus on terrorism, it
relied primarily on the emotional testimony of victims of bombings
by Puerto Rican militants and by Rep. Vito Fossella, R-N.Y., a
harsh critic of the clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ``My speech comes from my heart as an American citizen who has
been betrayed by his president,'' former New York City Police
Detective Richard Pastorella said. He lost his sight, much of his
hearing and all the fingers on his right hand in a 1982 FALN
bombing in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ignited a firestorm of criticism when he announced last
month that he would commute the sentences of 16 militants not
directly involved in planting bombs if they renounced violence and
met other conditions of parole. Fourteen of them accepted the offer
and 11 were freed from federal prison Friday. One prisoner must
serve five more years before he is released under the clemency deal
and the remaining two, who were already out of prison, had their
fines of $100,000 and $50,000 eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and some members of the law enforcement community
had accused Clinton of offering clemency to help his wife's
all-but-announced Senate candidacy from New York, home to some 1.3
million Puerto Ricans.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue has turned into more of a headache for the first
lady than a help. Mrs. Clinton first came out against the clemency
offer, angering many of New York's Puerto Rican leaders. Then last
week she explained that she should have consulted more with Latino
leaders before reaching a decision.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
