<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-INSURE-255&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY'S BIGGEST INSURER MAKES HOSTILE BID FOR COMPETITOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ In a move to further consolidate Italy's financial
industries, the nation's largest insurer, Assicurazioni Generali
SpA, announced a hostile $12.8 billion bid Tuesday for its domestic
rival, Istituto Nazionale delle Assicurazioni SpA.
</P>
<P>
   Generali, which is based in Trieste, said it was offering 3.067
euros, or $3.18, in cash and stock for each share of its rival,
which represents a 19 percent premium over Istituto Nazionale's
share price Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The move is the latest in a series of deals intended to
reorganize Italy's fragmented financial services industries. If it
succeeds, it would undo plans for a friendly merger between
Istituto Nazionale _ known here as INA _ and San Paolo-IMI SpA, one
of Italy's largest banks. Just last week, San Paolo and INA
announced that they were discussing a merger. It would also have
major implications for the reorganization of Italy's banks.
</P>
<P>
   INA president Sergio Siglienti said Generali's bid was ``neither
announced nor agreed upon'' with his company's management.
</P>
<P>
   San Paolo said in a statement that it would study Generali's
move at a board meeting next Tuesday. It remained unclear whether
San Paolo would make a counteroffer.
</P>
<P>
   Umberto Agnelli, the president of Ifil, an investment company
that has a big stake in Fiat and is also one of San Paolo's biggest
shareholders, said San Paolo's talks with INA were intended to
create ``a bank-insurance industrial project that reinforces the
financial structures of the country.'' He described Generali's bid
as arrogant.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Italian banks and insurance companies have come under increasing
pressure to shake out their industries after the conclusion in
August of a three-way bank brawl in France, in which Banque
Nationale de Paris failed in an effort to acquire Societe Generale
but succeeded in buying the financial services giant Paribas to
form one of Europe's biggest banks. In Germany, too, rumblings have
grown as the nation's big banks study ways to merge and make their
retail and investment banking operations more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, the most recent move came in June, when the boards of
Banca Intesa, the nation's second largest, and Banca Commerciale
Italiana, the No. 4, approved a $15 billion merger to create what
will be Italy's largest banking group. San Paolo is now the
largest.
</P>
<P>
   For Generali, the consequences of the bid, if successful, would
be to broaden its capital base and to make it a harder target for
some other company's hostile-takeover attempt. Through the summer,
speculation has abounded that the No. 1 European insurer, AXA of
France, would try to buy Generali, though AXA officials have denied
the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Generali's bid would create an insurance giant with a market
value of roughly $45 billion and annual revenue of more than $46
billion. The combined companies would rank behind only AXA and
Allianz of Germany in the European insurance industry. Insurance
analysts say the bid makes sense, given Generali's strong position
in life insurance, while Istituto Nazionale's main operating
company, Assitalia, is a leader in both life insurance and in
businesses like property and casualty insurance.
</P>
<P>
   As to the effects of Generali's bid for Italian banking, the
idea behind the move, people close to the matter said, is to
propose dividing up Istituto Nazionale's assets _ giving that
company's insurance business to Generali and its banking assets to
San Paolo. Istituto Nazionale has 51 percent of Banco di Napoli
Holding, which controls the largest commercial bank in southern
Italy, and a 7.5 percent stake in Banca Nazionale del Lavoro,
another leading commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
   But a first sign that such a compromise might fail came Tuesday
morning, when a planned meeting between Generali president Alfonso
Desiata and Luigi San Paolo head Arcuti was canceled. San Paolo's
idea has been to merge its banking interests with the insurance
business of INA, creating a banking and insurance giant.
</P>
<P>
   INA has hired as advisers Credit Suisse First Boston, whose
parent Credit Suisse Group holds a 3.4 percent INA stake. Credit
Suisse chairman Lukas Muehlemann, who headed Switzerland's big
Winterthur insurance group before taking over at Credit Suisse, is
among Europe's principal proponents of banking and insurance
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   UBS AG, the Swiss banking giant that competes with Credit
Suisse, is advising Generali through its Warburg Dillon Read
investment banking unit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
