<SLUG> BC-PRISON-GUARDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS DROPS MONEY FOR UNION LEGAL FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The Davis administration quietly tried to
give the union for state prison guards $4 million in public money
for its legal defense fund, a highly unusual concession for a major
political donor.
</P>
<P>
   Exposed and excoriated by fellow Democrats, Gov. Gray Davis
agreed to remove the provision last week, moments before the
Legislature approved a pay raise and other perks for the
25,000-member California Correctional Peace Officers Association.
</P>
<P>
   The union was one of Davis' strongest supporters during his 1998
campaign. It supplied him with $2 million in campaign contributions
and television advertising and provided critical cover against
Republican accusations that Davis was soft on crime.
</P>
<P>
   If the defense fund had been included in the legislative action,
taxpayers would have been in the extraordinary position of paying
to both defend and prosecute guards.
</P>
<P>
   Several Corcoran State Prison guards have been accused of
arranging the rape of one prisoner and staging illegal,
gladiator-style fights among other inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The $4 million for the defense fund was removed from the
agreement late Thursday as the Legislature was ending its 1999
session. A few Democratic lawmakers who have sparred with the union
noticed the money and complained loudly to officials who negotiated
the deal for Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `What is this about? How could you be doing this? How
could you be placing the administration in such an embarrassing
situation?''' said Sen. Richard Polanco, D-Los Angeles, a frequent
critic of the union and the Davis administration's prison policies.
</P>
<P>
   Polanco said Davis's union negotiators ``got it'' when he
spelled out an imaginary newspaper headline about taxpayers being
asked to pay for defending prison guards accused of horrible
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was a real slap to the Legislature, to the
governor, to the people of California, to be using taxes to defend
prison guards against alleged criminal wrongdoing,'' Polanco said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement approved by the Legislature, the guards
still secured an immediate 4 percent pay raise, retroactive to July
1, and another 4 percent on Sept. 1, 2000, as well as increases in
health and retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Most other state employee unions negotiated similar contracts
with the Davis administration. Prison guards, however, already are
some of the highest paid workers in California government, earning
$47,800 a year _ without overtime _ after seven years of work.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Morgenstern, the governor's chief negotiator on state
employee issues, said the legal defense money for the union of
prison guards was taken out because it became too controversial.
</P>
<P>
   The prison guards have had a legal defense account since 1991,
but it has relied mostly on union dues and private donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have money for a variety of things people wanted,''
Morgenstern said. ``Firefighters got money for boots and money for
their health fund. The Highway Patrol wanted money (put) into a
health fund. That's what collective bargaining is.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the legal defense fund for the prison guards, Morgenstern
said: ``Nobody wanted to deal with the controversy, so we took it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The union and the Davis administration now have 90 days to
negotiate how to spend the $4 million on other benefits,
Morgenstern said. The same is true for the California Highway
Patrol union, which got $3 million to spread around on benefits,
education, uniforms or whatever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
