<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-TROOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN OPPOSITION TO OUTSIDE PEACE FORCE GROWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A nationalist backlash is mounting against
plans to send an international peacekeeping force to quell the
violence in East Timor, as Indonesians object to summoning outside
nations to solve what they call an internal problem.
</P>
<P>
   In street protests and in interviews, many Indonesians make
clear that they see the international effort in East Timor as a
throwback to the era of European colonialism, a latter-day case of
picking up the ``white man's burden,'' the attitude that white
nations had an obligation to show third-world countries how things
should be done.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, some 200 demonstrators shouted and burned effigies in
front of the United Nations office and the US Embassy, one day
after 1,000 protesters were allowed by security guards to vandalize
the US Consulate and the Western Australia trade office in
Surabaya, Indonesia's second-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters decried what they called foreign meddling in
Indonesian affairs and President B.J. Habibie's weakness in the
face of outside pressure, even as the United Nations announced that
a peacekeeping force would be deployed within days.
</P>
<P>
   The West has condemned Indonesia's military for sponsoring an
orgy of killing, burning and looting that has claimed hundreds, if
not thousands, of lives and displaced much of East Timor's
population. The violence followed a landslide referendum vote in
favor of independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The roots of Indonesians' sensitivity to foreign intervention
run deep. For centuries, this archipelago of 13,000 islands and
hundreds of ethnic groups chafed under harsh colonial rule by the
Dutch, and it won independence only 54 years ago in a bloody war.
Then in 1958, the United States supported rebellious army units in
a civil war on the island of Sumatra, an event that older
Indonesian nationalists have never forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Indonesia has gladly accepted decades of military
and economic assistance from the West, and arguably behaved like a
colonial power itself in East Timor, a tiny territory on the
southeastern end of the Indonesian archipelago that Indonesia
invaded in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Few Indonesians bring up the fact that their government imposed
24 years of repressive rule and military-sponsored abuses on the
former Portuguese colony after the invasion. Many ordinary citizens
accept the government line that Indonesia gave East Timor roads,
schools and electricity. Most have never heard of the military
oppression that claimed 200,000 lives, a quarter of East Timor's
population, through war, starvation and disease in the five years
after Jakarta invaded.
</P>
<P>
   If there must be peacekeepers at all, Jarkarta would prefer an
Asian-led force. Indonesia's neighbors traditionally refrain from
criticizing or policing fellow members of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
   At a protest at the Australian Embassy Monday, 21-year-old
student Eko Sulistio Santosa declared, ``We don't need
international peacekeeping forces there. Indonesia can take care of
it alone. . . . Habibie was premature in giving East Timorese a
vote for independence. They obviously weren't ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe the media reports about the killings'' in East
Timor, said Bambang Nurbianto, 24, a street vendor, as he sold
snacks Tuesday. ``Indonesia gave East Timor a lot, and these people
don't show gratitude. . . . I also fear that if East Timor goes,
many other provinces will go, and Indonesia will not be Indonesia
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Others note that Australia and the United States openly or
tacitly supported Indonesia's invasion of East Timor in 1975, at a
time when Cold War politics stoked fears of a Marxist, independent
East Timor _ a ``Cuba in southeast Asia,'' as it was called at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Australia is very hypocritical,'' said Salvador
Soares, the pro-Indonesia editor of East Timor's daily newspaper,
Suara Timor Timur (``The Voice of East Timor.'') ``Western
countries encouraged Indonesia to come to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting Australia as the lead nation in the peacekeeping force
could delay deployment, something hundreds of thousands of
displaced East Timorese without food, water and medicine cannot
afford. But ignoring Indonesia's concerns could usher in other
problems _ diplomatic strains and even physical danger to Western
troops deployed in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   An American serving as a UN police officer said he was shot in
East Timor last week because gunmen believed he was Australian.
</P>
<P>
   An Indonesian government source said that contrary to Western
assertions that Australia is the only country ready and able to
lead an East Timor peacekeeping force, Malaysia has privately said
its own troops could be ready in 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a large country with a complex history. . . . It has
experienced many foreign interventions,'' said Sabam Siagian, a
former Indonesian Ambassador to Australia, in an interview. ``With
that background, the world should be wise and tactful'' in
selecting a force to restore order in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Siagian criticized Australia for acting ``macho'' and being
``noisy about being ready with thousands of troops.'' He said
Australian politicians are trying to win points at home ahead of
upcoming elections, and might even be trying to ``establish a
strategic beachhead in marine southeast Asia'' by sending troops to
East Timor, 400 miles north of Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
