<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Losing an unusual feeling for Falcons
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Falcons had not lost a regular-season game in
nearly 11 months and a home game in almost two years. But after
last week's gut-wrenching 17-14 loss to Minnesota in the Georgia
Dome, the Falcons find themselves in unfamiliar territory _
recovering from a defeat. They will have a few extra days to repair
their psyches before Monday night's nationally televised game at
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way you find out about the character of your
football team,'' Falcons coach Dan Reeves said. ``The (losses) that
we had last year, we reacted very well. We went out to San
Francisco and got beat badly (31-20 on Sept. 27), and we came back
and played well after that. We went up and got beat by the Jets
(28-3 on Oct. 25), and we bounced back from that one. You really
learn a lot more about your team through adversity. It wasn't like
we played a poor football team (in the Vikings).''
</P>
<P>
   But the loss to Minnesota, in which the Falcons turned the ball
over three times, missed two field goals and committed two costly
pass-interference penalties, might be more difficult to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sticks with you a little bit longer,'' running back Jamal
Anderson said. ``I had like 'road rage' going home (Sunday). I was
mad. I was really, really frustrated with a lot of things _ the way
I played and with the way things went down. It's not necessarily a
moral victory, but you want to beat a team like that, and I know
how important it was to the 70,000 people who were there. It's a
tough pill to swallow, but we'll try to rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss was different because Atlanta didn't have an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Against the 49ers in Week 3 last season, the Falcons were still
relatively unknown and weren't considered playoff contenders.
Atlanta also hasn't won in San Francisco since 1991, so nobody
really expected them to win in 3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Jets, Atlanta played without starting quarterback
Chris Chandler, who missed the game with a sprained left shoulder
and bruised ribs suffered the previous week in a 31-23 victory over
New Orleans. Starting defensive tackle Travis Hall also was hurt
and did not play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough because we're not accustomed to losing now,''
Anderson said. ``These things stick with you, especially when you
lose by three points and you have a chance to win. We did all the
things that we did wrong, giving them good field position every
time we turned the ball over. We've just got to buckle down and get
it together. We've got to pray Chris is healthy enough to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons might be forced to play without Chandler again. He
is doubtful for the Cowboys game after pulling his right hamstring
in the fourth quarter of the opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was evident last year, and it was evident (Sunday, that)
we've been faced with a lot of adverse situations,'' linebacker
Keith Brooking said. ``We fought through them, so we're definitely
going to find out what this team is made of. After a disappointing
loss like that, you've got to bounce back the following week. This
is a big test for us, but there's no doubt in my mind that we're
going to step up to the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
