<HEADER>
A2015 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-SPIES-BOS &LR;      09-14 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-SPIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S CONTROLLING SPYING? BRITONS WONDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As Soviet spies go, Merlita Norwood is a media darling.
She's an 87-year-old great-grandmother, a frail but unrepentant
communist.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, when she appeared in the front yard of her modest
home in the south London suburb of Bexleyheath, holding in her
trembling hand a brief statement that acknowledged her role as a
spy dating back to the 1940s, she touched off a heated debate over
whether she should be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   But as the days wear on, the debate is shifting to why it took
so long for the public and, even more, the government to learn that
Norwood and her accuser existed. Her unmasking and that of about a
dozen other British-based Soviet spies was meant to trumpet one of
the British intelligence services' greatest coups. Instead it may
serve as a catalyst for bringing secret agents here under greater
scrutiny. Because of the controversy, a parliamentary committee
will hold an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   While many Britons have long followed the fictional exploits of
James Bond, the quintessential British secret agent, they know far
less about their real secret services, which remain shrouded in
official secrecy. The existence of MI6, the foreign intelligence
service, was not even officially acknowledged by the government
until 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Two laws passed in 1994 and 1996 were meant to make the secret
services more accountable. But while the leaders of the secret
services can now be called to face parliamentary questioning, it is
done in private.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of a freedom-of-information law, meanwhile, inhibits
journalists from getting official, objective information. That
means that most public knowledge about the secret services has been
informed by disgruntled former agents, who typically paint the
services as ghastly organizations peopled by paranoid incompetents,
or by journalists and authors who are given access and information
by the secret services in exchange for favorable coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The method and timing of the disclosures about Norwood and other
spies operating in Britain, which have been made as part of a
coordinated public relations campaign to promote a book that is
published Wednesday (Sept. 15), have raised eyebrows and prompted
questions about how seriously the secret services take their duty
to keep their political masters informed.
</P>
<P>
   The book, ``The Sword and the Shield,'' by Christopher Andrew, a
professor at Cambridge University, analyzes handwritten copies of
KGB documents made by a KGB archivist, Vasili Mitrokhin, who
defected to Britain in 1992. Besides exposing Norwood, it details
some of the more sensational attempts by the KGB to discredit
American figures from J. Edgar Hoover to Martin Luther King Jr.,
and of the KGB effort to bury arms caches throughout the West for
an invasion that never came.
</P>
<P>
   But some here find it unsettling that Prime Minister Tony Blair
didn't find out about Mitrokhin's archives until last Thursday,
three years after Andrew was authorized by MI5, the domestic
intelligence service, to meet Mitrokhin to begin preparing the
book, and weeks after journalists got access to some of the
information to prepare stories and a television documentary that
will be broadcast Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Andrew acknowledged that he was stunned
to learn that he knew the intimate details of Mitrokhin's archives
before senior cabinet members and the prime minister. While
believing there was no intent by the secret services to avoid or
mislead the politicians, he agrees there is a need for an
investigation to clear the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a cock-up, not a conspiracy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been legislative efforts in recent years to make
Britain's domestic and foreign secret services more accountable to
the government, but as the author and journalist Hugo Young
concluded Tuesday, ``Any belief that this has brought with it more
respect for ministerial supremacy, let alone democratic
accountability, is an illusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy is more than a Cold War hangover. It also
exposes the ideological divide in Britain that many say has
narrowed since 1997 when Blair moved the traditionally left-wing
Labor Party to the center and won the biggest parliamentary
majority in two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the Conservative Party say it is outrageously
hypocritical for the Blair government to insist on holding
83-year-old Augusto Pinochet, Chile's former dictator, for
extradition to Spain to face charges on human rights abuses that
occurred in the 1970s while giving a free pass to a little old lady
who betrayed her country for much of the last half-century.
</P>
<P>
   Leftists argue that there is no moral comparison between what
Pinochet stands accused of and Norwood's use of her secretarial job
_ in a metals research laboratory that developed Britain's atomic
bomb _ to pass secrets to the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   Many legal observers say that the evidence against Norwood,
despite her public admissions, amounts to handwritten notes by
Mitrokhin that would not be admissible in court.
</P>
<P>
   While the controversy over prosecution seems likely to pass, a
more lasting debate appears to be opening up on whether the
democratically elected leaders of the British people need to have
more control over the secret agents entrusted with looking out for
national security, both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The ideological divide is obvious again, with many conservatives
arguing that the secret services cannot operate effectively under
the glare of public scrutiny, and many liberals contending that the
secret services have made a mockery of efforts to make them more
accountable.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Britain's home secretary, Jack Straw, who is in
charge of law enforcement, called for more governmental oversight
of MI5, which handles domestic intelligence, and MI6, which does
foreign spying. Straw acknowledged that he had been briefed on
Mitrokhin's archives after taking up his post in 1997, but didn't
learn of Norwood until last December.
</P>
<P>
   Mitrokhin's treasure trove of KGB secrets, smuggled out in a
half-dozen trunks, was so voluminous that British intelligence
agents and their Western allies, including those in the CIA, spent
four years poring over his notes and debriefing him. In 1996,
Malcolm Rifkind, then foreign secretary, approved the idea of
having Andrew write a book that would put Mitrokhin's archive into
the public domain.
</P>
<P>
   David Shayler, a former MI5 agent who faces arrest here for
disclosing some of the agency's secrets, says the way MI5 handled
the Mitrokhin archives shows that there needs to be more
parliamentary oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``MI5 is not accountable,'' Shayler said from exile in France.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, suggest that the British people are widely in
favor of leaving the murky world of espionage to professionals, not
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   D. Cameron Watt, professor emeritus of international history at
the London School of Economics, said he is skeptical that Norwood
was as important a spy as some are making her out to be, but he is
not troubled by the secret services' decisions to analyze
Mitrokhin's information for years before notifying their political
masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had many leads to follow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some have criticized the handpicking of Andrew, who wrote a
history of MI6, as a way to ensure that the secret services are
cast in the best possible light. But Watt believes it is more an
illustration of a lack of historians within the secret services who
could put the information into proper perspective.
</P>
<P>
   He said the information will be of ``more interest to historians
than prosecutors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
