<SLUG> BC-CAR-PETIT-LEMANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Petit Le Mans: Defending champ skeptical
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In last year's inaugural Petit Le Mans, Wayne Taylor
and teammates scored an upset when they drove a 4-year-old Ferrari
333SP to victory at Road Atlanta, beating faster, newer cars.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 39, a two-time World Sports Car champion and the only
driver to win the prototype class at the 24 Hours of Le Mans, the
Petit Le Mans, the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring,
faces greater odds this year. The car, co-sponsored by
Atlanta-based Lease Plan, is a year older, and the competition is
even tougher.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who was in a tight battle for the American Le Mans
Series points championship last year, is a distant eighth this year
with 55 points, 40 behind leader Elliott Forbes-Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two of the exotic prototypes are entered in this
weekend's race, including the BMW V12 LMR that won Le Mans and
Sebring; three Panoz LMP-1 Roadster Ss, two with Team Panoz and one
with J&AMP;P Motorsports; the Team Rafanelli Riley &AMP; Scott Judd that
won the spring ALMS race here; and a Champion Porsche 911 GT1 EVO.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he isn't thinking about it, but his car might not
make the field. Seven cars must be eliminated to bring the field to
50.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll run two cars, rather than one like last year,'' Taylor
said. ``We'll run as hard as we can. We have very good tires and a
very good reliability record.''
</P>
<P>
   His Doyle-Risi team hasn't heard any news of an upgrade from
Ferrari. Taylor was bumped from the 24 Hours of Le Mans field
because of a paperwork error. But he is upbeat because of the
success of the American Le Mans Series, although he was skeptical
when the ALMS was announced last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know from one year to the next if we'd have a series
or not,'' Taylor said. ``Everyone had great ideas; no one followed
through. Then Don Panoz came in, said what he'd do and did it. ...
I think we're on our way up.''
</P>
<P>
   And that means the dream lives for the kid from Port Elizabeth,
South Africa, who lives in Altamonte Springs, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far back as I can remember, the only thing I ever had in my
head was being a race car driver,'' Taylor said. ``I was absolutely
adamant that that was what I wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's every kid's dream to drive a race car, so I'm living my
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   PETIT LE MANS
</P>
<P>
   _ When: Thursday-Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Road Atlanta, Braselton, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tickets: $45 and up, 800-849-7223 or 770-967-6143.
</P>
<P>
   _ Info: 770-967-6143; www.petitlemans.comKent Mitchell writes
for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
