   &UR; FOLD: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-FLOYD (Orlando, Fla.) _ Authorities urged nearly 2
million people to evacuate coastal areas stretching from Florida to
North Carolina on Tuesday as Hurricane Floyd, one of the most
powerful storms to ever threaten the United States, roared through
the Bahamas. Floyd's eye was expected to pass within 90 miles of
southern Florida, and perhaps come within 50 miles of north
Florida's coast by Wednesday morning, before striking land
somewhere farther north, perhaps near Cape Canaveral. By Rick
Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   4-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 8:30 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SCHOOLTEST-ERROR (New York) _It was one of the most momentous
tests in New York City history. School Chancellor Rudy Crew imposed
new standards public schools _ declaring an end to social promotion
_ and sent 21,000 students to summer school, then announced that
14,000 had failed. But on Tuesday, Crew said that the high-stakes
test given last spring to determine who would be assigned to s}mmer
school was deeply flawed, and that that thousands of students had
been assigned to summer school by mistake. Aides estimated that
2,000 to 3,000 children had been assigned to the classes who did
not deserve to be there. By Anemona Hartocollis.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 8:30 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-U.N. (United Nations) _ A multinational force of up to
7,000 troops could begin landing in East Timor by the weekend,
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said on Tuesday, as the Security
Council prepared to vote on the resolution creating the military
mission. Pressure was intense to complete work on the resolution
Tuesday night, in the light of reports of continuing violence in
the territory. ``Lives are leaking away in East Timor while they
wait for the Council,'' said Sir Jeremy Greenstock, the British
representative, who introduced the resolution. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-COMPLAINTS (New York) _ Hundreds of police officers
found to have engaged in misconduct by an independent review board
escaped punishment when their cases were summarily dismissed by the
Police Department without any further investigation, according to a
report by the Office of the Public Advocate. The report is based on
an examination of police misconduct files that the Public Advocate,
Mark Green, obtained after suing the city. The report accuses the
department of routinely dropping civilian complaint cases, citing a
lack of evidence, without ever re-interviewing victims or
witnesses, or making any other efforts to examine the strength of
the evidence it discounted. By Laurie Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-UNREST (Moscow) _ Police make an ethnic sweep through
Moscow, checking and rousting people from the Caucasus after
bombings attributed to rebels from the region. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   2-column photo with story.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 8:30 p.m. ET in `i' news file.)
