<P>
   &UR; INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FUELREGS-SUVS (Detroit) _ After heavy lobbying by the auto
industry, the Senate is expected on Wednesday to extend a
four-year-old ban preventing the Clinton administration from
reviewing a two-tier system of fuel economy regulations that allow
auto makers to produce large numbers of big, gas-guzzling sport
utility vehicles. Auto makers are moving forward with preparations
to take advantage of this system by introducing as many as two
dozen small and medium-sized car-based vehicles in the next few
years. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `f' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SACKLER-ASSESS (Washington) _ When the Smithsonian Institution
announced this month that a trove of Chinese art amassed over
nearly 60 years by an American collector, Dr. Paul Singer
(1904-1997), had been given to the Arthur M. Sackler Gallery here,
the details were rather staggering. It amounts to more than 5,000
objects, with a value estimated at $60 million, though, in fact, an
item-by-item assessment of the material is only just beginning. The
gift more than doubles the existing collection of the Sackler
Gallery, which was established in 1987 and constitutes, with the
neighboring Freer Gallery, the national museum of Asian art in the
United States. And in a stroke it transforms the Freer and the
Sackler into the largest repository for Chinese archaeological
material in North America. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `e' category.)
