<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2023 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-NYSHOWS15-COX     09-14 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-NYSHOWS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ellen Tracy wraps up by playing with fire
 &HT;    By Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service'
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the spring/summer 2000 womenswear she previewed
Monday morning, Ellen Tracy design chief Linda Allard indicated
just how wrapped up she is in her work.
</P>
<P>
   String-back halters, belted raincoats, scarf-tied tops and
flappy wrap skirts were the hallmarks of the collection. From top
(gold cord necklaces) to bottom (strappy stilettos), all 68
ensembles shown seemed to have strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   And prior to her runway presentation, Allard announced the
launching of a new Web site, ellentracy.com . Within a week, Allard
said, the site will feature video clips of the collection that
stressed relaxed shapes and styles that are nonetheless fun to wear
and precious to own.
</P>
<P>
   The key accent color was fire-engine red. Allard rendered it in
a resined silk raincoat with a thin belt that fastened just under
the breasts, a stretch top with a revealing neckline and tails that
knotted in the back, a stretch silk bustier and a collarless glazed
gauze jacket. Allard also liked to use lemon yellow: It showed up
in striking ensembles featuring tight blouses with rolled,
three-quarter length sleeves and seductive, round-edged ``petal''
skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the clothes came in subdued shades of khaki, blue,
purple and pink. But Allard juiced up her show at the end with an
array of fruit-colored eveningwear separates that were frosted with
crystal beading.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Allard played with casual luxury motifs: cropped and
cuffed linen khakis, a short-skirted blue, white and brown gingham
business suit, tank tops and tunics and cardigans in cushy shaker
knit, and tie-dyed shantung suits.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar de la Renta
</P>
<P>
   Only at an Oscar de la Renta show could an invited guest _
albeit a very wealthy and well-connected guest _ arrive so late
that models literally had to dodge her as she dashed to her seat.
Normally, such a dramatic entrance would cause an uproar; in the
photographers' pit especially. But this was the philanthropist Nan
Kempner barging in; and to Manhattan socialites like her, viewing
de la Renta's runway previews from a front-row seat is one of
life's necessities. The designer earned the blue bloods' devotion
once again with 69 outfits that were opulent, playful, contemporary
and somewhat sexy.
</P>
<P>
   De la Renta's slim, A-line shapes catered to the ladies who
lunch, but only on watercress sandwiches. His show started with a
series of punch-hole embroidered leather skirts, pants, coats and
dresses. Next came dark denim suits and separates that looked
anything but casual. His beaded cocktail dresses were surprisingly
sheer and his flower-powered resortwear was fiercely festive. As is
the trend, his hemlines hovered around the knee and featured
asymmetrical flair and ruffled finishes. Cashmere sweater sets were
key to the collection, as were ``khaki'' looks in luxe fabrics like
silk chiffon.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Miller
</P>
<P>
   In the literal and figurative senses, Tuesday's collection
preview by Nicole Miller was vintage her. She described much of her
collection was inspired by the sort of thrift store clothes ``you
wish you'd held onto.'' And she designed with that whimsy,
modernity, femininity and delight in color that makes her
collections joys to behold.
</P>
<P>
   Her hemlines hit the knee or lower; many skirts and dresses
featured the undeniably trendy ruffles and asymmetrical wrap
styling. The detailing _ glossy linens, delicate embroidery and
beading, laser cut-outs, and tulle trimming _ were exquisite.
Miller's floral patterns ranged from big, outdated upholstery-style
prints to minuscule sprays of thistle on hand-painted dresses. And
she made denim pieces look dressy by rendering them in stretch
linen.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
