u a BC-NC-FLOYD-PREP-COX     09-14 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-FLOYD-PREP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Back-to-back storms send N.C. sound residents scrambling
 &HT;    By T. Scott Batchelor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Residents around Pamlico Sound are cleaning
up from Tropical Storm Dennis with one hand while they prepare for
Hurricane Floyd with the other.
</P>
<P>
   Axson Smith, manager of River Forest Manor Marina and Shipyard
in Belhaven, spent part of Tuesday reserving trucks to remove
debris if Floyd visits the eastern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not fully repaired from Dennis,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The marina lost decking on both piers. The decking has been
replaced, Smith said, ``but there's a lot of problems with rental
houses and other parts of the property.''
</P>
<P>
   Boats at the mercy of waves and wind are the first order of
business when a tropical cyclone such as Floyd threatens the
marina.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best place is to haul them out of the water for storage on
land,'' Smith said. Anchoring them in side creeks and canals is the
second best thing.
</P>
<P>
   River Forest has a boatyard on Tom's Creek in the northeastern
part of town where boats can be secured, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the National Hurricane Center's forecast on Tuesday
put the hurricane's eye in the vicinity of Raleigh, employees at
Robb's Boatyard and Marina on Pungo Creek are making storm
preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now they're hauling all the boats to the back of the
yard and getting them out of the water,'' said Kristy Clayton,
assistant office manager of the Belhaven business.
</P>
<P>
   They had stored about 10 boats by late morning, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton said the one-two punch of Dennis and Floyd has kept the
boatyard busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our docks were messed up, and they just got them back together
when they predicted Floyd,'' Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   Workers there are expecting Hurricane Floyd to make matters even
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water comes up in our (boat) shops usually about 1 or 2
feet. The water's supposed to come up higher this time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said one couple sailing down to Florida via the Intracoastal
Waterway wisely chose to stop at Robb's.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to Greenville and see if they can wait it out,''
Clayton reported.
</P>
<P>
   Belhaven's mayor, Charles O. Boyette, said, ``We've had high
water ever since Dennis came.'' More than 60 percent of the town's
businesses and residences sustained flood damage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just haven't had a chance to dry out,'' Boyette said.
</P>
<P>
   Belhaven residents are accustomed to storms, Boyette said. But
Floyd is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurricane Floyd is a monster,'' he said. ``They are nothing to
play with. We're moving right along (with preparations) again, just
as if Floyd is going to be on our back doorstep.''
</P>
<P>
   Town officials will meet today to decide whether to issue
evacuation orders. They're ready to start electrical generators and
move the command station from the police department to higher
eleveation in the municipal building, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the electrical department and other utilities were in
good shape, having trimmed back trees during the summer in
preparation for the tropical storm season.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 miles west of Belhaven, McCotter's Marina on Broad
Creek just east of Washington was gearing up for Floyd's impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are taking their boats and anchoring them (in
the Pamlico River), said Susan Boone, an office worker at the
marina.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have not brought their boats back in from the
last one,'' Boone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a dock that is somewhat tore up, with no
electricity on that particular dock,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gibb Chauncey, Pitt County Schools director of student
information and assignments, drives 50 miles to his home on the
Pamlico River each work day.
</P>
<P>
   Chauncey lives on the river about 10 miles east of Bath in
Beaufort County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to react to this one,'' Chauncey said of
Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boat's on the trailer in the yard,'' he said. ``It's about
as good a shape as it's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Pamlico crawled up his lawn and threatened to
overtake his home's foundation during Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It already washed away my pier,'' he said of Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   The good thing about the two storms hitting so close together,
he joked, is that anything that can be washed away has already done
so.
</P>
<P>
   T. Scott Batchelor writes for The Greenville Daily Reflector,
Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
