<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL SOCIETY'S PUBLISHING CHIEF RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Continuing the turmoil at the Massachusetts Medical
Society that began in July, the group's publishing chief, Joel H.
Baron, has announced his departure after two years of aggressively
expanding the organization's lucrative publishing division.
</P>
<P>
   The division, which publishes the New England Journal of
Medicine and a dozen other publications, brought in 87 percent of
the medical society's $84.1 million revenues in fiscal 1998, the
last year for which public figures are available.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors recently have questioned whether the nonprofit
medical society's priorities are being distorted by its growing
publishing activities. Medical societies should not ``allow
economic considerations to dominate their policies,'' Dr. Arnold S.
Relman and Dr. Edmund Pellegrino wrote last week in the Journal of
the American Medical Association. Relman is editor emeritus of the
New England Journal and Pellegrino is from Georgetown University
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Baron, the medical society's vice president for publishing, said
Tuesday his resignation was voluntary. Its timing, he said, had
nothing to do with the well-publicized clashes he had with Dr.
Jerome P. Kassirer that led to Kassirer's forced departure this
summer as New England Journal editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no asking me to leave, it's me resigning,'' Baron
said, adding that he will continue to represent the Bay State
physician group on publishing-related matters.
</P>
<P>
   Baron said he decided to leave because the medical society is
entering ``a quiet period'' in which it will not be launching or
acquiring new publications at its previous pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to enter a period of probably a year in which we
sort of hunker down until there's a new editor (of the New England
Journal) on board and that editor is up to speed,'' Baron said in
an interview. ``It's time for me to move on and find another place
where I can make a strategic contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Kassirer, he and Baron disagreed repeatedly over
Baron's plans to exploit the New England Journal's prestigious
brand name to market other medical society publications that
Kassirer and his staff considered less rigorously edited.
</P>
<P>
   Baron has denied such disagreements, but Kassirer has said they
were frequent, and escalated in intensity this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thwarted many attempts to use the name of the New England
Journal of Medicine on various Massachusetts Medical Society
products,'' Kassirer wrote in a letter to the British medical
journal The Lancet published Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week, Kassirer said Baron had been carrying
out the wishes of medical society leaders intent on expanding the
nonprofit group's publishing domain and revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my judgment, Joel wasn't acquiring properties that were
good ones,'' Kassirer said. ``I had serious questions about his
judgment, but he was simply doing what he was expected to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marcia Angell, who succeeded Kassirer as interim
editor-in-chief of the New England Journal after lengthy
negotiations, wished Baron well but expressed relief at his
departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret the other editors and I were concerned about
the use of the journal's name to promote unrelated products, and
that many of those concerns centered on Joel Baron's activities,''
Angell said. ``My personal relations with Joel have always been
good and I wish him well in the future. I think he might be happier
in a situation in which his entrepreneurial talents could have
freer scope.''
</P>
<P>
   Baron dismissed the importance of a set of principles governing
the New England Journal's independence that Angell insisted on
before taking over as interim editor. Those principles, announced
by the medical society in July, give control over the New England
Journal's name, logo, and content to the journal's editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing people don't understand is that the agreement
reached with Marcia is no different from the agreement we had with
Jerry,'' Baron said. ``I'm telling you a fact. There's no
difference, but people have been making like there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Baron said he does not have any immediate job prospects.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter announcing his resignation to medical society staff,
Baron reviewed his accomplishments since joining the organization
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Those include acquiring a magazine called Hippocrates from Time
Inc.; launching three new publications called Journal Watch that
summarize medical journals' content; starting a new consumer
newsletter called Heart Watch; and making the New England Journal's
contents available on the Internet and computerizing that journal's
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Baron boasted that the medical society's publications exceeded
profit expectations in the past two years and ``with a few breaks
we'll beat them this year as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
