<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2030 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TIMOR-U.N.-(TRIMS)-NY     09-14 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-U.N.-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. THRASHES OUT DETAILS OF MILITARY MISSION TO EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A multinational force of up to 7,000 troops
could begin landing in East Timor by the weekend, Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said Tuesday, as the Security Council prepared to vote
on the resolution creating the military mission.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure was intense to complete work on the resolution Tuesday
night, in the light of reports of continuing violence in the
territory. ``Lives are leaking away in East Timor while they wait
for the council,'' said Jeremy Greenstock, the British
representative, who introduced the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   A direct reference to Australia as the designated leader of the
international force was dropped from the wording of the resolution,
but Indonesia will not oppose an Australian commander, Foreign
Minister Ali Alatas said Tuesday. Indonesian and Australian
military officials met Tuesday afternoon to begin discussing how
the force will be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer met with Alatas and
told reporters later that he had assured his Indonesian counterpart
that the force would be truly international, with significant
participation by Asian nations in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sensitive issue for Indonesia, and we understand
that,'' Downer said. ``This is not an Australian force.''
</P>
<P>
   A more fundamental long-term question that is still unresolved
concerns the role of the Indonesian army. For the next four months
_ the proposed term of the interim force now being created _ the
Indonesians say they expect to work with the international force,
and Tuesday's Security Council resolution demands their
cooperation. But how many Indonesians, and for how long, remains
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of the withdrawal of Indonesian troops from East
Timor is a matter which is not resolved,'' Downer said Tuesday.
``Indonesian troops will certainly be there in the initial stages
of the deployment of the multinational force. There will have to be
a mechanism for cooperation between the multinational force and
Indonesian military. There are, after all, quite a large number of
Indonesian troops in East Timor.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Downer said that some ideas were being discussed by Indonesia
and the Australians, but he did not elaborate. Under the May 5
agreement that led to the referendum on East Timor's future last
month, Indonesian troops would be gone by the end of the year, when
the United Nations would move in with its own peacekeeping force
and administration to run the new country until its first election.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some diplomats and officials here say they no longer trust
Indonesian pledges, because of the failure of the Indonesian army
to stop attacks on East Timorese and international aid workers over
the last two weeks, when, under the May agreement, they were
responsible for law and order. Had they performed that duty, there
would be no need for the international force now being created.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, no one is certain whether the Indonesian army chief,
Gen. Wiranto, is in full control of his troops, or, conversely,
whether he had a hand in fomenting recent violence.
</P>
<P>
   There is also concern that soldiers from this very nationalistic
army, which prides itself on having brought Indonesia independence
from Dutch colonialists, will protect the militias or even side
with them against a foreign force.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Political pressures continue to mount on President B.J. Habibie
as the deployment of an international force gets closer. In Jakarta
Tuesday, hundreds of students tried to march on parliament to
demand his resignation. He is already under fire from within his
own party, Golkar, for allowing the East Timorese to vote on their
future and then conceding he needs international military
assistance to end the violence that followed their choice of a
clean break with Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Evidence has piled up of Indonesian military complicity in the
violence in East Timor, where Lt. Gen. Prabowo Subianto, a former
special forces commander and son-in-law of the deposed president,
Suharto, has considerable influence among troops. He is considered
by some experts to be a foe and a threat to Wiranto.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials said Tuesday that Indonesian army regulars were
seen looting the deserted compound of the U.N. mission in East
Timor Monday night and Tuesday morning after staff members and
refugees taking shelter there were evacuated. Soldiers in uniform
appear to have stolen or destroyed about $10 million in computers,
photocopiers, office equipment and vehicles, according to reports
from the remaining handful of U.N. security officers, now in the
Australian consulate.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There is also some debate over whether or not the resolution
will carry authorization for the use of military force beyond
routine self-defense and the protection of refugees. Such
essentially war-making powers fall under Chapter VII of the U.N.
Charter, which some Security Council members seemed reluctant to
approve. Several diplomats said that they thought these
reservations had been overcome by midday Tuesday after a meeting of
experts from Security Council member countries.
</P>
<P>
   It is apparent to military planners that even refugee aid could
require a considerable use of force, since pro-Indonesian militias
rampaging through the territory will have to be disarmed at some
point. Looting of aid goods will have to be prevented.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Relief experts believe that several hundred thousand East
Timorese may have been driven from their homes. The United Nations
says that 600,000 of the territory's 870,000 people are in need of
some kind of emergency aid. Australia is awaiting permission to
begin airdrops of food and other supplies, which are being
stockpiled in the northern port city of Darwin.
</P>
<P>
   Violence is continuing on the ground in both East Timor and West
Timor, where there were reports Tuesday that some displaced people
were being singled out and taken away in boats to an unknown fate.
No one has a firm estimate of how many people have already died,
but at least one U.N. agency, the Food and Agricultural
Organization in Rome, puts the figure at 7,000. The agency does not
say how it arrived at that number.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees said Tuesday that ``an
atmosphere of total intimidation'' prevails in the East Timorese
capital of Dili. ``UNHCR is gravely alarmed by persistent reports
and indeed mounting evidence of deportation of East Timorese to
West Timor and cases of separation of men from women and
children,'' the refugee agency spokesman, Kris Janowski, said in
Geneva.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
