<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-PUERTO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL SEEKS TESTIMONY IN NATIONALIST CLEMENCY OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Angry over the Clinton administration's reluctance
to discuss the clemency offer to members of a Puerto Rican
nationalist group, a House committee Tuesday sent three subpoenas
to White House and Justice Department officials, demanding that
they appear Thursday to state their case.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth subpoena is to go out Wednesday, escalating an
already-politically charged fight between the White House and its
opponents on Capitol Hill and in law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Several congressional committees are holding oversight hearings
on President Clinton's sharply criticized decision to offer
clemency to 16 members of the Armed Forces of National Liberation,
known by the Spanish abbreviation FALN.
</P>
<P>
   The group, defended as freedom-fighters by their supporters and
derided as terrorists by law enforcement and prosecution officials,
was linked to a series of bombings, murders and robberies during
the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 16 offered clemency was convicted of any specific
act of violence, but the FALN as an organization claimed
responsibility for the crimes. Fourteen of the FALN members
accepted the offer last week.
</P>
<P>
   Practically, there is nothing Congress can do to reverse
Clinton's clemency offer, and the congressional talk on the issue
has served more as a vehicle for members of Congress to say Clinton
is soft on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have also accused Clinton of making the gesture to
assist his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, in her potential bid for
New York's US Senate seat, a charge the White House has denied.
</P>
<P>
   But even if they can't undo the clemency, members have a right
to know why Clinton made the offer despite the strenuous objections
of prosecutors and law enforcement officials, said Mark Corallo,
spokesman for the House Committee on Government Reform.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``is not a king. He is the representative of the people.
We want to know what the reasoning was, exactly,'' Corallo said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI at the last minute backed out of a scheduled appearance
Tuesday before a subcommittee of the Senate Foreign Relatoins
Committee. The move infuriated the chairman of the subcommittee on
terrorism, Senator Paul Coverdell, a Georgia Republican who accused
the White House of pressuring the FBI not to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty clear the White House is behind this,''
Coverdell said. The administration is ``trying to build a fortress
around their decision'' to offer clemency, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do want to provide Congress with information to satisfy its
oversight needs to the fullest extent possible,'' explained Justice
Department spokeswoman Chris Watney. But because of the
``constitutional and institutional'' concerns, and the fact that
the hearing might delve into matters protected by executive
privilege, the agency needed to consider the request further before
sending officials to testify.
</P>
<P>
   The House subpoenas _ issued Tuesday to Beth Nolan of the White
House counsel's office, Neil Gallagher of the FBI, and Michael B.
Cooksey of the Bureau of Prisons _ will be ``reviewed,'' said Jim
Kennedy, spokesman for the White House counsel. The fourth subpoena
is to acting Assistant Attorney General John Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   The four could be held in contempt of Congress if they fail to
appear, though Corallo said that wasn't likely.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional question of which takes precedence _ the
right of the president to executive privilege vs. the right of
Congress to investigate _ is not clear, Kennedy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 1941EDT &QL; 
