<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     09-14 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HOW TORRE DEALS WITH THE BOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the New York Yankees squirm, George Steinbrenner
is strangely silent, at least publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not getting involved,'' the principal owner professed in a
statement Monday after the lost weekend with the Boston Red Sox had
reduced the Yankees' lead in the American League East to three and
a half games. ``I'm not sticking my nose in.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware of his boss' nasal prudence, Joe Torre phoned him Tuesday
and, the Yankee manager reported, discussed the slump
goodnaturedly. Quite a contrast to Torre's memory of 1996 when a
12-game lead dwindled to eight games and his phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you blow this thing, I'll never let you forget it,''
Steinbrenner told him. ``You'll have to live with this for the rest
of your life. You'll be another Ralph Branca.''
</P>
<P>
   Branca, of course, was the Brooklyn Dodgers right-hander who
gave up Bobby Thomson's pennant-winning home run for the New York
Giants in 1951 after the Dodgers had blown a 13-game lead.
</P>
<P>
   Those 1996 Yankees went on to win the World Series, but when
Steinbrenner phoned to congratulate Torre on clinching the
division, the manager said, ``Hello, this is Bobby Thomson.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the manager's disclosure of those 1996
conversations in his book ``Joe Torre's Ground Rules for Winners''
(Hyperion, $23.95), written in collaboration with Henry Dreher,
arrived just when Steinbrenner's nose must be itchy.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Torre analyzes ``12 keys that have worked for me''
that he believes will work for any executive or manager in the
corporate world.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the Yankee manager's relatively peaceful
relationship with Steinbrenner, three chapters on ``Dealing With
Tough Bosses'' are the most revealing in how Torre has coexisted
with the principal owner, notably his reaction to the ``Branca''
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were strong words from the Boss,'' Torre writes, ``and I
made a point of not dwelling on them. I was not about to let myself
get undone by the comparison. Don't overreact to your boss'
behavior. Don't let negative comments get under your skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre has also managed the New York Mets, the Atlanta Braves and
the St. Louis Cardinals, but surprisingly he writes that
Steinbrenner has been ``the easiest'' to work for.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first key to dealing with a tough boss,'' Torre suggests,
``is to develop mutual respect and trust. When you put out trust
and loyalty, you're more likely to get trust and loyalty in return.
Don't allow your boss' negative side to bring out your negative
side.''
</P>
<P>
   To Torre, Steinbrenner's negatives are outweighed by his pluses,
especially the owner's commitment to winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``George was willing to spend his money to get the best players
available,'' he writes. ``He was giving me something I never had
before: the horses to ride to the finish line. Having never been to
the World Series in my three decades in baseball, that was worth
everything. In my previous experience, upper management of both the
Braves and Cardinals never made good on their promises to get the
best players available.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre mentions that Ted Turner, the Braves' owner, ``was more
meddlesome'' than Steinbrenner has ever been, a factor that wrecked
their mutual respect in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning,'' Torre writes, ``I let George know that
as far as I am concerned, he's the boss. He's the owner, he pays my
salary, he built the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Likewise, from day one George understood that I run the team
on the field. I'll listen to his suggestions, but the final call is
always up to me. I've never gotten a mandate from George about what
to do on the field. I don't expect I'll ever get one.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner's day-to-day involvement tortured other Yankee
managers, especially Billy Martin, but to Torre, it's a plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the fact that I could talk to George, that he made
himself available, made it possible for us to develop mutual
respect,'' he writes. ``I liked both Ted Turner and August Busch
III, but neither of them was very accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Joe Torre has kept his sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   While appealing for more funds for prostate cancer research at a
Senate committee hearing last June, the Yankee manager told the
committee members, ``I'm a cancer survivor.'' Then he added with a
smile, ``I'm also a survivor of George Steinbrenner for four
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Yankees blow it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
