<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2035 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-WOMAN-ENTREPRENEUR-18     09-14 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMAN-ENTREPRENEUR-1800(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HER FATHER TOLD HER SHE'D NEVER SUCCEED IN A MAN'S WORLD. HE WAS
WRONG.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRANBURY, Texas _ Her father used to tell her that she should've
been born a man; that a woman's place was in the living room,
kitchen and bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been an unconscionable thing for a dad to say to a
little girl with big dreams, but Mary Lou Wilson says she can't
help but thank him.
</P>
<P>
   The memory, she says, feeds her drive to succeed, playing like a
broken record every time anyone suggests _ directly or indirectly _
that she might fail.
</P>
<P>
   That's what came to mind that day in June 1995, when the
chairman of Enrich International, a network marketing company that
makes and sells herbal nutrition and beauty products, asked his top
distributors, including Wilson, to choose a country where they
would like to open a business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other distributors chose countries like Korea, Australia,
Malaysia and New Zealand,'' Wilson said. ``I said, `Japan,' and
they said there was no way an American woman could succeed in a
male-dominated country.''
</P>
<P>
   The men punctuated their assessment with laughs. But all Wilson
heard was her father's words playing in her head, and she
remembered how they had sustained her all these years as she worked
to prove him wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought to myself, `I will make this work no matter what,'
'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly five years later, Wilson, 62, runs a network of 100,000
individual distributors in Japan, which Enrich International says
produces gross revenues of more than $10 million a month. That's
twice as much as the $1.5 billion Venetian, the new Las Vegas
casino and hotel complex, is reported to be making each month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basically a housewife, and I'm doing over $10 million a
month in sales,'' she said. ``There was never a question in my mind
I would pull it off. But I didn't think in my wildest stretch of
the imagination that I would be as successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Clad in a signature red dress, Wilson sits on her living-room
sofa facing a picturesque view of Lake Granbury in North Central
Texas. Around her are mementos that she and her husband, Bob, have
collected over the years.
</P>
<P>
   On a brass coffee table is a globe made of jade, mother of
pearl, lapis and amethyst, etched with lines of gold. She purchased
it in Singapore during a cruise that she sponsored to thank the
Japanese leaders who have supported her business.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, a white Rolls-Royce bought in mid-August sits in the
driveway. The license plates read: M LOU W.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a '97 Mercedes, but my Japanese customers have been
after me to get rid of it,'' Wilson said. ``It's an image-driven
country, and anybody that earns a certain amount of money can get a
Mercedes, but only the successful can get a Rolls.''
</P>
<P>
   The car, the lakeside home, the globe and even the red dress
that she is wearing are symbols of her success, and are closely
linked with the growth of her distributorship, now known as Wilson
International Networking: WIN. They embody the kind of
rags-to-riches lifestyle that for many years was just a dream for
this grandmother of three.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't supposed to happen to Mary Lou Wilson. Her father
told her as much. Then he left when she was 6 years old, leaving
behind his wife, daughter and three sons.
</P>
<P>
   He paid for his sons' college educations. But not for Mary
Lou's. His words kept playing in her mind: ``A woman's place was in
the living room, kitchen and bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think deep down I became successful to prove to my father
that a woman can be successful,'' Wilson said with sadness in her
eyes. ``We all have something that drives us, something that makes
us hungry for success. For me, this was it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the process of proving her father wrong, Wilson said, ``I
proved it to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many people who may identify with Wilson, although few
have had her success. She said that she worked from the time she
was 9 years old because she wanted to make life easier for her
mother.
</P>
<P>
   She paid her way through night school, but didn't stay long
enough to get a degree from the business college she attended. To
make a living, she worked as a financial adviser, and then as owner
and operator of a Saint Bernard show-dog kennel.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1991, Wilson said, she became interested in herbs _
plants she always thought were just for cooking _ as a way to lose
weight and treat health problems that she was having.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea,'' she said, still astounded at where her
new-found interest would take her.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to obtain the product wholesale, Wilson became a
distributor with Enrich International. When people started
inquiring about her weight loss, they, too, wanted to try the
products.
</P>
<P>
   Before she knew it, Wilson's inventory of herbal products grew
from filling a few shelves in her laundry room to filling her
garage.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Today, she is perhaps the best-known distributor for Enrich
International and the most successful. She is a presidential
director of the 22-year-old company, a member of the President's
Club, and a former chairwoman of the company's International
Advisory Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Lou is one of the most dynamic ladies I've ever met, and
quite a mentor for me,'' said Beverly Hollister, vice president of
worldwide marketing at Enrich. ``She is a great leader, a great
strength, but most of all has great dignity and love.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollister said that she has traveled throughout Japan with
Wilson and has seen her ``take off a beautiful mink coat and give
it to one of the leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   That leader was Yasuko Takezaki of Honolulu. Takezaki, a single
mother and Wilson's top distributor, had complained of being cold.
</P>
<P>
   Hollister said that she was not on the Enrich team when Wilson's
fellow distributors laughed at her for wanting to sell the
company's products in Japan. But she added that is not something
that would happen today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our management goal is to always give opportunity to everyone
so that there isn't unfair competition,'' Hollister said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson exudes confidence, but not in an intimidating,
condescending way. She is eager to help fellow distributors, to
share the secret of her success. In her case, Wilson's secret might
be as simple as being prepared.
</P>
<P>
   She said that she found out a few days in advance that Enrich
International would ask its distributors the million-dollar
question about which country they would choose as a new market for
the company's products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the library,'' she said. ``I looked at countries,
and (Japan) said it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said she and her husband, a retired airline captain, read
every book they could find on the Japanese people and their
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned all their customs. We learned when to have tea and
how to have it,'' she said. ``We learned red was the color of
success. I bought a lot of red. I have more red in my closet than
Santa Claus.''
</P>
<P>
   The laughter from her male colleagues only added to Wilson's
motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of going into a corner and crying, I went out and
proved them wrong,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Wilson immediately contacted the 10 people in
her North American network of distributors who were
Japanese-American. Two of them, she said, wrote to family, friends
and other acquaintances back home to gauge their interest in Enrich
International's herbal products.
</P>
<P>
   During this time, the company was being bought by a group of
private investors. The new CEO and board said no to Japan. That
broken record playing more loudly now, Wilson became even more
determined.
</P>
<P>
   After six months of being bombarded with Wilson's sales pitches,
officials agreed to a less risky approach that would allow her to
sell to Japanese customers for their personal use only. People
could receive cash bonuses for new customer referrals, but they
could not set up any network-retailing organization.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing left to do was prove there was enough interest
for a viable business. ``I worked hard,'' she said. ``There was no
stone unturned.''
</P>
<P>
   With a $160,000 loan from her husband, Wilson rented a
convention hall in May 1998 in Yokohama and invited Enrich's new
CEO to a meeting. She also invited 379 Japanese people who'd
expressed an interest in the herbal products and asked them to
bring others. More than 3,000 people showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lou was wearing her red silk suit, red blouse and red
shoes. The company decided to go forward with the ``not for
resale'' plan. If Wilson were able to reach $3 million in monthly
sales, they told her, they might open an office in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In March of this year, Wilson reached that goal. And on June 28,
an office opened in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything worked,'' Wilson said. ``I did a lot of groundwork,
behind-the-scenes work, fighting custom. I ran into detours,
potholes, but I never lost sight of the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, she credits much of her success to her father, who
died 15 years ago. She describes him as an astute businessman and
said that while working at his various retail and wholesale
businesses, she watched his every move, his style, the way he spoke
to his customers, how he figured profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked all the good out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When it's time to go to sleep after another long day, Wilson
said, she never forgets to thank her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell him thank you all the time in my prayers,'' she said,
as a big smile creased her face. ``You were a miserable son of a
sea cook but I thank you for making me reach my full potential.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
