<SLUG> BC-GORE-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC OFFICIALS BACK GORE, TAKE SWIPE AT BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore picked up endorsements from
Hispanic elected officeholders Tuesday as his campaign launched the
``Ganamos con Gore'' (We Win with Gore) outreach effort to woo the
growing number of Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore used his limited Spanish to win over a crowd of Democrats
who gathered at a Washington hotel where the Congressional Hispanic
Caucus Institute is holding an issues summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am honored to have the support of so many outstanding Latino
leaders from across the country,'' Gore said. ``We share the same
values: familia, educacion, amor de patria, communidad y Dios''
(family, education, love of country and belief in God).
</P>
<P>
   The event was designed to distinguish Gore's support in the
Hispanic community from that of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the
front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination who also
speaks Spanish on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Gore attacked the popularity of Bush, who so far
has the edge over the vice president in national public opinion
polls, more than a year before the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats are very worried that the governor is going to
be the next president of the United States,'' Bush campaign
spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said from Austin. She said Bush enjoys
strong support among Hispanics in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Gore supporters unleashed a barrage of attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is known to our community, and his interests in us are
not new found,'' said Rep. Robert Menendez, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the streets of Los Angeles and New York to the piers of
New Jersey to the valley in Texas, Al Gore stood by our side _ not
with compassion, but with empowerment,'' said Menendez, taking aim
at Bush's campaign slogan of ``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante of California tried to douse the
perception that Bush's popularity rivaled that of Puerto Rican
singer and heartthrob Ricky Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody thinks George Bush is good for the Latino
community, they are `Livin' La Vida Loca,''' Bustamante said,
referring to Martin's hit single.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the state's four Hispanic Democrats in Congress and
numerous local Hispanic officeholders have endorsed Gore. Those
officials said Gore's party primary opponent, former Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey, has struggled to make inroads with Hispanics
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Gonzalez, D-Texas, said Gore was committed to
Hispanics. ``I think he has always demonstrated that,'' the
congressman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has Bradley had the occasion or opportunity to address that in
the past? Maybe not. But I now where Gore has been,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning Bush by name, Gore criticized the Texas
governor's education proposals as a scheme that would take federal
money away from public schools and funnel it to private
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposals would allow parents to take use federal
education funds to enroll their children in private or charter
schools, if public schools fail.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, has promised pre-school education for every
child by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   He also said more needs to be done to improve high school
graduation rates among Hispanics; improve Medicare for the nation's
elderly; and make health care affordable for working families.
</P>
<P>
   He called for a ``fair and accurate census,'' an issue of
concern in the Hispanic community where an undercount of the
minorities in 2000 could lead to weakened political influence in
Congress and other elective offices.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing contrast to support for Bush, the Gore campaign released
a list of nearly 700 Hispanic officials nationwide who have
endorsed the vice president for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
