<HEADER>
A2040 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FLOYD-EYE-BOS &LR;      09-14 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-EYE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DEVICE HELPS HURRICANE HUNTERS MEASURE FLOYD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While nearly everyone else is fleeing Hurricane Floyd, Jim
Carswell of the University of Massachusetts will fly into the eye
of the storm for the third time Wednesday, measuring its ferocious
winds with a new device that gives forecasters unprecedented
accuracy in gauging the storm's power and direction.
</P>
<P>
   Carswell, part of a team of hurricane hunters who criss-cross
storms in a Navy P-3 ``Orion'' airplane, gets a very different view
of Floyd than the coastal Florida residents boarding up their homes
and heading inland. Dangerous as it is, Carswell said, Floyd is
also quite beautiful in its calm center, and he described it as
being in a cathedral of swirling clouds above water turned a
surreal green.
</P>
<P>
   But the ride to work is singularly hazardous as the specially
reinforced P-3 penetrates Floyd's winds of up to 150 mile an hour
that buffet the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a while to get your flight legs,'' admitted Carswell,
a research professor at UMass-Amherst's Microwave Remote Sensing
Laboratory. ``You always expect to make it home, although sometimes
your heart races a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Floyd, one of the strongest ever known in the
Atlantic, slammed into the Bahamas Tuesday and sparked an exodus of
2 million people from parts of Florida and Georgia, where
catastrophic damage was feared. Georgia emergency officials
predicted Floyd would rake Savannah and other coastal cities with
winds of 125 miles per hour late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane-hunting flights, run by the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, provide vital, inside-the-hurricane
information that help forecasters decide where a hurricane will
reach land and how strong its winds will be. As Floyd draws closer
to the coast, the flights become even more important because the
National Hurricane Center needs around-the-clock updates.
</P>
<P>
   Carswell, who has already flown into Floyd twice, tracks the
wind speeds at the surface of the ocean, the speeds most important
for predicting coastal impacts. Using a high-tech device called a
microwave radiometer, Carswell can calculate wind velocity
thousands of feet below the plane based largely on the amount of
foam churned up in the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, hurricane hunters had to estimate surface winds based
partly on the wind outside the aircraft because older model
radiometers couldn't provide enough readings from the sea surface.
But Carswell's radiometer, built by the University of Massachusetts
and Quadrant Engineering of Amherst, Mass., provides surface
readings 12 times more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The microwave radiometer gives us much more complete storm
coverage at the surface . . . and at a fraction of the cost,'' said
Peter Black of NOAA's Hurricane Research Division, one of the
radiometer's designers. ``Eventually, we hope to see this
instrument on all hurricane-hunter aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Carswell, who has been chasing hurricanes since 1991, said Floyd
is the biggest hurricane he has ever seen, with gusts of wind of up
to 140 miles per hour that last for 10 minutes. The winds are so
strong that they strip the top off the waves, creating `streamers'
of water that fly parallel to the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night Carswell and the rest of the 16 to 18 person
crew will get an even closer look at Floyd's power as they track
its approach to land at just 5,000 feet elevation, instead of the
normal 14,000 feet. Eric Knapp, the University of Massachusetts
engineer who led the radiometer design team, said the device gives
more detailed readings at lower altitudes, though the flight may be
rougher as well.
</P>
<P>
   However, NOAA officials say the Lockheed P-3 planes are well
equipped to withstand hurricane-force winds. Mainly, the pilots fly
in a straight line across the storms, constantly compensating for
the winds that blow them off course. The main hazard are the abrupt
up and down drafts, which tend to be strongest just outside the
eye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2041 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-FLA-EVACUATIONS     09-14 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-FLA-EVACUATIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurricane-wary residents heed Floyd's wrath
 &HT;    By Stephanie Desmon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Tuesday morning, the roads through Palm
Beach County were almost deserted, a sort of anti-rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   People who were going to leave did _ off to standing-room-only
Red Cross shelters, to hotel rooms in Tampa or Orlando, to friends
or relatives a few miles inland. The rest put the finishing touches
on plywood improvements to their homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic is very, very light,'' said Florida Highway Patrol Lt.
Pembrook Burrows.
</P>
<P>
   It was too late to head north, where the brunt of the storm was
expected anyway. Bumper-to-bumper traffic snarled northbound
Interstate-95 through northern Florida, westbound Interstate-10
toward Tallahassee was congested and State Road 60 west of Vero
Beach was jammed as people tried to get a little more distance
between themselves and the expected fury of Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County sheriff's spokesman Paul Miller said the Palm
Beach County Sheriff's Office planned to have 500 deputies on the
road Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic was moving smoothly through St. Lucie, Martin and
Okeechobee counties on Tuesday, though in some spots it was heavier
than normal. But officials expected people off the roads by the
time the storm came through, said Okeechobee County Sheriff's Capt.
Gary Hargraves.
</P>
<P>
   The car was the only option. Train service was suspended Monday;
Palm Beach International Airport was closed at noon Tuesday (doors
locked, sandbags out) and jets were flown out of the region. The
airport should re-open today, though travelers should call their
carriers for information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going north,'' said Mike Deoreo, as he boarded up his
Flamingo Park home Tuesday around lunchtime. ``If anything, I'd go
south.''
</P>
<P>
   At daybreak Tuesday, Palm Beach was nearly deserted except for
police patrols, a few sightseers and a lone jogger hoofing along
Seaspray Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury cars that normally park at the curbsides were nowhere to
be found and mansions and condos were masked with color-coordinated
shutters and panels of plywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people have left,'' said Sigrid Kumpe, as she
loaded belongings into a car on Seaspray a block from the ocean.
``I think I need to get out, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the rows of mobile homes at Briny Breezes, there were few
signs of life except for Rhea Weber trimming a flowering bush with
her clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other fools have stayed,'' joked Weber, who was making
final preparations to leave herself.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Tim, said they would be out by noon to spend the
night with relatives in Boca Raton. A wind gauge whirling above his
mobile home registered a gust of 36 miles an hour at 8 a.m., he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, when we come back Wednesday this will be just as it
is now,'' he said. ``If not, we have three different insurance
policies for wind, flood and property damage.''
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach also resembled a ghost town. The stores that
opened were, for the most part, closed by noon. Most fast-food
restaurants were closed; it was even hard to find a gas station
open in the afternoon. Those who were out on Clematis Street
downtown were putting up shutters and plywood.
</P>
<P>
   Along I-75 north of Central Florida, evacuees flooded tourist
offices with questions: Where to stable a horse? Find a hotel that
takes pets? Find enough rooms for 100 people?
</P>
<P>
   By 10 a.m. Tuesday, the staff at the Gainesville Holiday Inn was
</P>
<P>
   advising them to look for hotel rooms in Atlanta. By 11:30 a.m.,
the word
</P>
<P>
   at the Georgia welcome center, just north of the Florida border
on I-75,
</P>
<P>
   was that there were no rooms south of Calhoun, 80 miles north of
Atlanta _ and 320 miles from the border. Four hours later, the
Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau was suggesting Chattanooga,
Tenn. A hotel in Birmingham, Ala., was offering rooms, convention
bureau spokeswoman Brandy O'Quinn mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Flores of Belle Glade took a break at the welcome center,
after
</P>
<P>
   driving through Monday night. After Palm Beach County officials
ordered
</P>
<P>
   mobile home residents to evacuate Monday evening, ``I closed my
trailer, got my clothes and my family, and hit the road,'' he said.
In a caravan of four cars and 20 relatives, he was heading for his
brother's home in Macon, Ga. _ the same place he waited out
Hurricane Andrew seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many east-coasters could be found at the Hyatt
Regency Tampa, which General Manager Tom Smith boasts has never had
water in the lobby. ``I've got all your residents over here,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's hovering around the television at the bar and
watching the storm updates,'' Smith said. ``It's kind of a festive
atmosphere. They're just a little worried about their homes,
whether they'll be gone when they get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, some residents who evacuated from barrier
islands didn't travel that far. The Doubletree Hotel In Palm Beach
Gardens put its overflow guests in the ballroom. The Omni Hotel in
West Palm Beach booked up early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're coming from all over,'' said the Omni's Lori Keil. ``I
just saw a whole group of people come in with their paintings to
protect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything I'd save.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Desmon writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. Sanjay Bhatt, Bill Douthat and Michael Van Sickler
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
