<HEADER>
A2056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-STANFORD-RESIGN(TRIMS     09-14 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STANFORD-RESIGN(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASPER TO STEP DOWN AS STANFORD'S PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanford University president Gerhard Casper announced Tuesday
that he would resign at the end of August 2000, citing the
perpetual need for fresh perspectives on campus and his desire to
focus on teaching undergraduates.
</P>
<P>
   Casper, 61, became president at the elite West Coast campus in
1992, as it was recovering from revelations that the university had
overcharged the federal government millions of dollars in indirect
research costs, and as it was trying to rebuild after the 1989 Loma
Prieta earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, Casper launched several initiatives to
improve education during students' first two years; led a merger of
the hospitals at Stanford and the University of California-San
Francisco; boosted fund raising to more than $300 million annually,
and started a $200 million endowment campaign to support graduate
students independent of research grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a university, no time is ever an appropriate one to claim
that tasks have been completed,'' Casper told a regularly scheduled
meeting of deans and department heads on the Palo Alto, Calif.,
campus Tuesday afternoon, according to the prepared text of his
remarks. ``All days of a university need to be first days. The work
of the university is work that cannot be done unless it is
continuously reconsidered.''
</P>
<P>
   Quoting from Ecclesiastes, ``To every thing there is a season,''
Casper noted that he had spent two decades in top administrative
posts, starting as dean of the law school and then provost at the
University of Chicago. Of his seven years at Stanford, he joked,
``Ten years at least is the way it feels.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nestled in the heart of the booming Silicon Valley, Stanford has
become among the hottest names in higher education during Casper's
tenure, rivaling Ivy League institutions in competitiveness,
prestige and fund-raising prowess. Faculty members who have watched
the international reputation of the 14,000-student campus soar said
they were stunned by the resignation, and praised their president
for unifying the university and refocusing it on academics.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``His dedication to and love of teaching undergraduates
permeated everything,'' said Lucy Shapiro, a professor of
developmental biology at the Stanford Medical School. ``He's almost
unique in his desire to learn in depth how different schools work,
how different disciplines work, and how to put a research
university like Stanford squarely in the center of training the
next generation.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Key elements of Casper's legacy will be Stanford Introductory
Studies, a series of small seminars for first- and second-year
students, and Sophomore College, a two-week program in which
students take one intensive course before classes begin in the
fall. On the graduate level, he founded the fellowship program to
support up to 300 science students free of sponsored research, and
another initiative that brings graduate students from Asia for a
year-long seminar on politics and economics.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``He convinced the faculty that it was very possible, indeed it
was necessary, for a research-intensive university such as Stanford
also to focus on undergraduate education, from the first days
students step on campus,'' said Ramon Saldivar, a professor of
English who recently finished a five-year stint as vice provost.
Noting that Casper taught undergraduate courses, Saldivar added:
``Gerhard didn't just talk about undergraduate education, he
provided the immense resources necessary for undergraduate
education to flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   Casper also oversaw restoration of earthquake-damaged landmarks
and construction of a new science and engineering quadrangle, and
graduate residences.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done just a marvelous job of rebuilding and expanding the
campus, not just for the buildings themselves, but for the strength
that he's given the institution,'' said Yale University president
Richard Levin, who is a Stanford alumnus. ``He is a true scholar, a
person of really wide learning and wide tastes. It's a great loss
for Stanford, and a great loss for higher education.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Hamburg, Germany, and having spent a quarter-century at
the University of Chicago, Casper at first struggled to adjust to
the laid-back life on the sun-dappled campus, where he is referred
to by his first name. But he soon donned the T-shirt of the 6th Man
Club and became a staple in the stands during basketball games, and
took roles in the Stanford Gaeities, an annual follies.
</P>
<P>
   Known to whip out the copy of the U.S. Constitution he keeps in
his coat pocket during discussions of affirmative action _ which he
supports _ or gay rights _ which he expanded by giving benefits to
employees' domestic partners _ Casper plans to take a sabbatical
and then return to Stanford to teach constitutional law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
