<SLUG> BC-BEEF-RECALL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ILLNESSES REPORTED FROM POSSIBLY TAINTED BEEF, SAYS H-E-B 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ No known illness has been caused by 10 tons of
possibly tainted beef that was sold at dozens of H-E-B food stores
before a voluntary recall, state health officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But due to an incubation period for E. coli bacteria that can
last several days before intestinal illness strikes, the officials
said some related incidents of diarrhea might be reported later
among people who unwittingly consumed contaminated meat that was
sold Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 20,000 pounds of recalled ground beef was
distributed in the Houston area, officials of the San Antonio-based
grocery chain said. Nor was any of it sold in its 75 smaller H-E-B
Pantry Food outlets around Texas or its three gourmet Central
Market stores in Austin and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Any unsold meat in question has been removed from the shelves in
160 other H-E-B stores in Central, South and North Texas, including
40 in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The recall began after store employees detected the potentially
deadly bacteria while taking routine samples at a company
warehouse, officials said. The bacteria was found only in a
one-ounce sample, but state officials said the grocery company
decided to ``err on the side of caution'' by recalling all 10 tons
of possibly contaminated beef.
</P>
<P>
   The grocery chain said the beef was sold in two types of
packages. Some was packaged on Styrofoam trays and covered in clear
plastic wrap, with ``sell by'' dates of Sept. 13 and 14. Aqua and
green tubes of super lean ground beef, also recalled, displayed a
``sell by'' date of Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get word to people that if they bought ground
beef at H-E-B on Sunday or Monday and it has those sell-by dates on
it, then it may be contaminated. And the key word there is `may,'''
said Texas Department of Health spokesman Doug McBride.
</P>
<P>
   The grocery company has offered full refunds to anyone who
returns one of the suspected meat packages. They also offered to
test packages at the customer's request.
</P>
<P>
   Because so many stores are involved in the recall, health
officials said it's still unclear how much of the beef was sold;
how much was removed from shelves and whether any of it was also
tainted. Health officials also are waiting to see if anyone turns
up sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may take a few days,'' McBride said, adding that distress
usually strikes five to seven days after exposure.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that proper cooking of raw meat can reduce or
eliminate the E. coli danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's cooked like it's supposed to be _ we recommend to 160
degrees internal temperature _ then there shouldn't be a problem,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   E. coli is a large family of bacteria, most of which is harmless
and lives in the intestines of healthy humans and animals. However,
a strain carried by some cattle produces a toxin that can make
humans severely ill.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, two people died and nearly 1,000 became ill
in separate outbreaks of E. coli in New York and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
