<HEADER>
A2059 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FLOYD-PARADISE-BOS &LR;      09-14 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-PARADISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOYD REVEALS THE DARK SIDE OF PARADISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIERA, Fla. _ Carol Ketchum has long had the dream life. A house
six blocks from the ocean. A pool in the backyard. Christmas on the
beach.
</P>
<P>
   Now she wants to move back home.
</P>
<P>
   With Hurricane Floyd and its 145 mile-an-hour winds barreling
toward central Florida Tuesday night, Ketchum and her family left
their home in Satellite Beach and joined nearly 800 others at a
shelter in an elementary school here. Floyd, due to hit overnight,
has them spooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister from Greenville, Rhode Island, called me this
morning, and said, `Please leave there. You're my only sister.
Don't die!' '' said Ketchum, 51, sitting in a beach chair in a
school hallway. ``Well, I'm ready to move back to Rhode Island or
Massachusetts. Enough of this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick of Florida, too,'' said her husband, Charles, 46, a
mailman and a Key West native. ``The fires were terrible last year.
Now this. In the post office, they say we deliver in rain, sleet,
or snow. They didn't say anything about hurricanes.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida is a place of opportunity for some, a last resort for
others, a place of escape, a place of retirement communities, a
place with old cow towns in its middle and concrete canyons along
its sides. And it keeps attracting hundreds of thousands of
newcomers every year because of its climate.
</P>
<P>
   But part of the package is the hurricane season, from June to
November, and for anyone who has lived through a hurricane there is
a feeling of dread whenever one gets close.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't be much closer now. Here, along the so-called Space
Coast, there is the widely expressed belief that this stretch of
Florida coast is safer than any other place because of the
recurrent wind current and wind pressures. NASA conducted in-depth
studies before deciding to build the Kennedy Space Center here.
</P>
<P>
   But Floyd appears bent on breaking the rules. It is too big.
Forecasters late Tuesday predicted that the hurricane's eye may
pass 20 to 25 miles from the coast here, but tropical and
hurricane-force winds could last 20 hours, not ending until 4 p.m.
Wednesday. Tropical winds are over 37 miles an hour, hurricane
winds over 74 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of know when to worry and when not to worry, and I'm
worried now,'' said Karen Smink, who has lived in Florida for 40 of
her 43 years. ``And that's why I'm in the shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   The shelter was in the brand-new Ralph M. Williams Jr.
Elementary School, which is in the brand-new community of Viera,
which is full of brand-new homes with huge picture windows, several
golf courses, and thousands of birds that were madly digging up the
greens in a hunt for worms in the hours before the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Bob and Judy Davis own one of those homes. ``I just had my
windows washed on Sunday, so at least when my glass goes to heaven
tomorrow it will be clean,'' Judy Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd didn't shake their belief in Florida life, but it unnerved
them. ``It scared the hell out of her,'' Bob Davis said, motioning
to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very threatening feeling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many in the shelter, they received phone calls from
relatives up north. Judy Davis's brother called from Boston
Tuesday, where he was on a business trip. ``He wanted to know where
we were going,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Patterson, 42, a Burlington, Mass., native, got an
earful, too. ``I was going to stay in my home and send my wife and
kids to the shelter,'' he said, sitting in a L.L. Bean canvas
chair. ``But this morning, I got, `I want you out of that house, I
want you to drive north,' from my sister-in-law. Then my sister
calls, so here I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really isn't much you can do, is there?'' he asked. ``I
don't miss the snow, and I like it when it's Christmas and you're
outside and it's 72 degrees. But this is part of life here, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
