u a BC-ARYAN-NATION-LAWSUIT-     09-14 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARYAN-NATION-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aryan Nation leader files suit in Ohio over beatings from blacks
 &HT;    By Wes Hills
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The local head of the Aryan Nation charges he was
severely beaten in 1997 at the Montgomery County, Ohio Jail because
he was not properly segregated from black inmates.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed late Friday in U.S. District Court in Dayton,
Morris Lynn Gulett also charges that his jailers waited four to
five weeks after the assault to get him medical attention, further
aggravating his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Defendants in the lawsuit include Sheriff Gary Haines, 10
unnamed jailers and five unnamed inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Donald Sprude, the warden at the jail, said he has not been
served with a copy of the lawsuit and declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit states that Gulett was an inmate at the jail from
March 1, 1997, through March 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Court records show he was awaiting trial on two counts of
felonious assault on a police officer. On Jan. 16, 1998, Gulett
pleaded guilty to a reduced charge of aggravated assault on a
police officer and was released after serving one year.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit states that jailers knew, or should have known that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gulett was the ``head individual of the Aryan Nation in the
metropolitan Dayton'' area, as well as a ``ranking member'' of the
organization for Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Aryan Nation is ``an organization that is known to be
segregationist in its ideology and to be supportive of the belief
of 'white supremacy' and in the inferiority of certain others, in
particular, Afro-Americans, Jews, and Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The population of the jail at that time was ``substantially
Afro-American.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 13, 1997, the lawsuit claims, Gulett was attacked and
beaten when he was left unprotected by the jailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beating was unprovoked by plaintiff and was solely because
such inmates, as Afro-Americans, knew of plaintiff's identity and
his relationship with the Aryan Nation,'' claims the lawsuit, which
seeks millions of dollars in damages.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the beating, Gulett claims he suffered serious
physical injuries, including a broken nose, ruptured eardrum and
lacerated lip.
</P>
<P>
   But as a result of not being provided medical attention for
about four to five weeks after the beating, physicians had to
re-break Gulett's nose in order to properly set it, the lawsuit
claims.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Hills writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
