<HEADER>
A2063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OHIO-TOBACCO-COX     09-14 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-TOBACCO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taft's task force advises giving tobacco money back to
neighborhoods
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Democrats on Gov. Bob Taft's tobacco advisory
task force Tuesday proposed sending some of Ohio's $10.1 billion in
the national tobacco settlement back to local communities, a plan
advocated by Montgomery County Prosecutor Mathias Heck Jr. and
prosecutors from four other large counties.
</P>
<P>
   That and other proposed changes from the spending plan offered
last week by state budget director Tom Johnson, chairman of the
task force, delayed a vote by the 15-member group until its Sept.
29 meeting. Other proposed changes included increased spending for
minority health needs and buying prescription drugs for senior
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco money is to be paid over 26 years with the first two
installments, totaling about $443 million, to arrive by June.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Jo Ann Davidson, R-Reynoldsburg, said the
legislature will need the task force's recommendations by month's
end to have enough time to consider them when the House and Senate
return in October for a fall session. The legislature and Taft will
have final say on how the money is spent.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the task force would consider the proposed changes
but that Taft, who has endorsed Johnson's proposal, will not budge
on the key recommendation to spend $4.5 billion on school
buildings. Johnson also calls for spending an additional $1.2
billion on technology for schools. Overall, education would get
more than 56 percent of the tobacco money under Johnson's plan.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco money is a key part of Taft's 12-year school
building plan, also announced last week, to spend $23.1 billion in
state and local money to build and repair schools, including
vocational schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not willing to bargain on school facilities,'' said
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Eric Fingerhut, D-Cleveland, and Rep. Harold Ford,
D-Toledo, the House minority leader, advocated sending some tobacco
money _ Ford suggested $10 million a year _ directly back to local
communities. Johnson's plan has no money for local communities.
</P>
<P>
   Heck and prosecutors from Summit (Akron), Cuyahoga (Cleveland),
Lucas (Toledo) and Franklin (Columbus) counties contend that local
governments have spent their money, not the state's, for treating
tobacco-related illnesses in public hospitals and in caring for
prisoners, and thus deserve part of the windfall from the tobacco
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   If local governments don't get a portion, the prosecutors have
said they might file their own lawsuits against the tobacco
companies. If they prevailed, their settlements could be taken from
the $10.1 billion because of the way the national tobacco
settlement is structured.
</P>
<P>
   Another Democratic task force member, state Rep. Jerry Krupinski
of Steubenville, called for spending $29 million a year on
prescription drugs and taking the money from what Johnson has
recommended for school buildings. This would be enough to help an
estimated 53,000 senior citizens, said Krupinski.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not make them choose between eating a good meal, eating
any kind of meal and taking medication that is life-sustaining,''
Krupinski said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ford said some money for senior citizens' prescriptions
could come out of a proposal he made to increase the first-year
allotment to a public health priorities health fund from $10
million to $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these extra dollars, however, would be for minority
health needs, said Ford. The added money is needed because tobacco
advertising for years targeted minority customers, resulting in a
disproportionate rise in tobacco-related health problems for
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said that the increase for this trust fund would not have
to be so great if some of the dollars in another trust fund, for
tobacco use prevention and control, were earmarked for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The task force includes lawmakers, members of Taft's Cabinet and
Attorney General Betty Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio is one of 46 states that agreed to the overall $206 billion
settlement with the major tobacco companies last year.
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
