<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2068 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DIRECTOR-AMERICAN-BEA     09-14 1705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRECTOR-AMERICAN-BEAUTY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENDES BRINGS THEATER DIRECTOR'S EYE TO FILM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sam Mendes has been focusing a fresh, imaginative
eye on live theater for some time now. The 36-year-old Englishman
has won raves on both sides of the Atlantic for, among other
things, his audience-involving re-engineering of ``Cabaret,'' and
``The Blue Room'' production that earned oceans of press for Nicole
Kidman's brief nude scene.
</P>
<P>
   Now Mendes has aimed his vision through cameras. And ``American
Beauty,'' his feature directing debut, should stir up as much
praise and hubbub as his stage work.
</P>
<P>
   A comedy of morals that gets deeper as it grows darker,
``Beauty'' dissects the suburban dream with unflinching, often
outrageous precision. It's built around the midlife crisis of
unhappy husband Lester Burnham (Kevin Spacey), his success-crazed,
real-estate agent wife Carolyn (Annette Bening) and their sulky
teen-age daughter, Jane.
</P>
<P>
   Fixated on Angela (``American Pie's'' Mena Suvari), one of
Jane's cheerleading pals, Lester tries to drive every last vestige
of responsible behavior out of his life and act like he's 18 again.
Other main characters include Ricky Fitts (Wes Bentley), the
pot-selling, videotaping voyeur next door, and his father the
Colonel (Chris Cooper), a martinet ex-Marine with a big secret.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes, whose small frame contains a boundless, good-natured
enthusiasm, feels especially well-equipped to examine these
archetypal American souls in minute detail. After all, he hasn't
lived around anyone like them, but he did see them in movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most Englishmen, I grew up on American film, so I felt
very comfortable telling American stories in a way that actually
surprised me when I came to read the script,'' says Mendes, who was
turned on to TV writer Alan Ball's screenplay by none other than
DreamWorks partner Steven Spielberg. ``I never doubted it because I
wasn't American. But I also realized that a lot of the films I've
loved most about this country had been directed by non-Americans _
John Schlesinger's `Midnight Cowboy,' Roman Polanski's `Chinatown,'
Wim Wenders' `Paris, Texas' ...
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an emotional detachment that the outsider can have
that's very difficult to bring to films about their own culture. I
mean, James Ivory, who's an American, makes great movies about
England. If I had to make a film about English suburbia, I'd
probably fail dismally.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as his actors are concerned, Mendes came to the right
place at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam was incredibly well-organized _ and one of those people
who barely lets on that he is so well-organized,'' notes Bening.
``He was really prepared, did storyboards, really knew how he saw
the movie. We rehearsed for two weeks _ very much like a play _ sat
around a table with him and the writer, talked about shared
histories that we should all know about, got to know each other. He
had a way of bringing everybody together so that there was an
intimacy about everything, a feeling of safety and freedom. That
continued onto the set.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very familiar with Sam's work and anticipated reading
this script, because I knew he'd turned down a bunch of films over
the years,'' says Spacey, a Tony Award nominee for his recent
revival of Eugene O'Neill's ``The Iceman Cometh.'' ``I knew that
the acting work and the story arc would probably go very, very well
with Sam. What I couldn't have been prepared for was what a visual
stylist he turned out to be _ without calling attention to himself,
which is a refreshing thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though confident in his vision, the first-time feature director
wisely decided to rely on a real pro to put it on screen. So he
hired director of photography Conrad Hall, lenser of such legendary
'60s movies as ``In Cold Blood,'' ``Cool Hand Luke'' and ``Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'' (for which he won an Oscar).
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the most experienced, most gifted cinematographer I
could find,'' Mendes says. ``And one of the things I loved about
Conrad was that he embraced my storyboards, loved the fact that I'd
lain the film out in my head. Then, he would come to the set, and
we'd often find a better shot. But it was important, as a
first-time director, to have some kind of blueprint as a starting
point.''
</P>
<P>
   While he left the formal, color-rich main compositions to Hall,
Mendes himself shot most of Ricky's handheld, vitally organic video
footage. ``What it needed was an amateur operator; it needed a kind
of wobbly, kinetic energy,'' Mendes says. ``Of course, Conrad lit
it all, so it looked very good.''
</P>
<P>
   As impressive as ``Beauty's'' photographic qualities are, the
film's themes and tone are likely to generate much more discussion.
While many are hailing it as the most insightful American movie of
the year, others are complaining that Mendes is a little too
objective, that his film takes easy shots at middle-class
materialism and condescends to its characters.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, Mendes disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, I wanted to push the envelope comically at the
beginning, so I could reveal that underneath that were genuine,
vulnerable, sympathetic characters,'' he says. ``However, a lot of
the easy laughs ended up on the cutting-room floor. It's very easy
to take potshots at suburban angst, and it's not new. I didn't want
it to be a satire; after all, if you're going to make a satire,
this is the easiest subject to do it on, and by extension the least
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's that climactic moment when Lester's lust for Angela
discomfortingly approaches consummation. Although hardly
``Lolita,'' it places the movie within batting distance of the same
ballpark _ and the last remake of Nabokov's classic sat on a shelf
for years out of fear that its man-girl sex theme would trigger
protests or even charges of kiddie porn (neither happened when the
film finally opened last year).
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you go into it with utter seriousness, the revelation
has no impact,'' Mendes says. ``But I wanted that tension all the
way through. I want people to ask themselves, `Is this right, or is
it wrong?' And if the answer is it's wrong, that's fine. I'm not in
it to make moral judgments _ but at the same time, it's pretty dark
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's this incredibly courageous story that pulls no punches,
doesn't ask anybody to like it, is politically incorrect and has
characters who make wrong choices and right choices,'' Spacey adds.
``But you can't pull scenes out of context. You can't say, `Oh,
here's a ``Lolita''-like scene.' It's not _ I reject it. What those
two characters teach each other is more beautiful and more
interesting than taking that out and waving it around like it's
some hot-button issue. It's unfair to the film; you keep it in
context, and everybody who sees the film will understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether such a defense is even necessary in a year when that
other movie with ``American'' in its title came out (along with a
raft of other outrageously vulgar comedies) remains to be seen.
After all, the explicit details of the Clinton impeachment
proceedings have probably inured Americans to sexual material that,
not too long ago, may have made them queasy.
</P>
<P>
   For that and other reasons, Mendes feels that ``American
Beauty'' is the right film for the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was written and made by people who live in 1999,'' he
asserts. ``So many of our current concerns are dealt with in the
movie, whether they be the possession of guns, what goes on in the
garage right next to you that you don't know about, or the
incredible sexual maturity of young people right now _ `American
Pie' being the classic example of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those things are in the air. And whilst one never thought
about President Clinton while making the movie, it's clearly a
product of the era. Filmmaking _ storytelling _ deals with the
issues of the world you're living in and telling stories back to
the people who also live in that world. There is a debate, and if
this movie becomes the subject of argument and intense discussion,
nothing could please me more.''
</P>
<P>
   If self-proclaimed late-'90s guy Mendes sounds an awful lot like
an artist from the early 1970s there, that's because he is
something of a throwback. Just as his stark, simply staged live
productions run counter to the overproduced effects extravaganzas
that have dominated Broadway and London for much of the decade, his
movie boasts a calm, controlled form that is the polar opposite of
flashy, attention-span-deficient, MTV-inspired movies these days.
</P>
<P>
   The better to tell his story, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing the theater teaches you is how to hold an audience's
attention for two hours without recourse to close-ups,'' he
explains. ``So when you get to the movies, you're used to the
rhythm of storytelling over two hours. You're not a commercial
director, you're not a director of rock videos; you direct two-hour
slabs of time, and you have to hold the audience's attention. If
you do not, you have failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about trying to find a way, if you can, to get
audiences to use their imaginations,'' he adds. ``To not spell
everything out, dot every i and cross all the t's. You have to be
careful not to be rigid about this, though; `The Lion King' (stage
production) is heavily designed, but what a wonderful work of
imagination that is. I think the death of theater is something like
`Beauty and the Beast,' where they just wear the costumes, and
you'd rather see the cartoon.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of his stage accomplishments, Mendes admits that films
are what he's always wanted to make. And now that he's directed his
first feature, he's more convinced of that than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theater works within a tradition of revival and reassessment
of classics,'' Mendes explains. ``I think this is more personal, to
me, than anything I've done on stage, because filmmaking is more
authorial. Which is not to say that Alan's script wasn't always
fantastic, and he was there on the set the whole time. But you
rewrite it in the cutting room, you rewrite it on the mixing stage,
and you rewrite it again. You are constantly refining it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
