<SLUG> BC-WOMENS-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTERNOON TV SHOW IS BY WOMEN, FOR WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Now, something new and different for Southern
California,'' the male announcer intoned before the Monday launch
of KCBS' new 4 p.m. ``women's news'' show, ``Women 2 Women.'' But
rather than something unique, the TV show is actually part of a
larger trend of broadcasters trying to find ways to ``narrowcast''
to specific audiences, especially by combining news with an
entertainment talk-show format to make it more palatable to the
masses.
</P>
<P>
   On the network level, we've seen ABC's ``The View'' and NBC's
``Later Today'' (a women-targeted extension of ``Today'') crop up
lately. On the local level, stations in Los Angeles, San Francisco
and other markets around the country have been adding shows or
segments within existing newscasts that target women with more
personality pieces and features on subjects from fashion to women's
health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women'' is anchored by Ann Martin, Catherine Anaya, Pamela
Wright and former KNBC news anchor Kelly Lange, with the four women
conducting much of the show from a talk show-like set, without a
desk in front of them. The subject matter on Monday's show fell
decidedly on the softer side of the spectrum. Barbara Chacon,
program director for KCBS, said they wanted to keep the launch
simple, to focus on establishing the hosts' personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show what they're about and develop the chemistry
a bit,'' said Chacon, admitting, ``It will take a litle time. But I
think eventually, we will be the kind of show people are talking
about. We're really the only local talk show on the air now. Our
viewers told us they want that, and it's very exciting for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Chacon, who used to produce the local morning show ``A.M. Los
Angeles,'' said though many women obviously are busy with work and
family activities at 4 p.m., ``there really is a high concentration
of women viewers watching at that time, and the L.A. market is a
little different than many. ... There are people at home at all
hours.'' Chacon also said KCBS is specifically targeting new
viewers who are a ``little hipper, a little younger'' than the
current average viewer for KCBS and CBS, which is known for being
the oldest-skewing of the major networks.
</P>
<P>
   KCBS' research indicates that 64 percent of the total news
audience at 4 p.m. is female. Those women weren't demonstrating
loyalty to any one newscast, but were valuable viewers because they
make many household decisions on entertainment, major purchases and
the like. Therefore, it made sense to create a localized program
for women that could highlight such things as shopping, restaurants
and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's segments included a gushy review of fashion from
Sunday's Emmy Awards and a ``behind the scenes'' look at ``The
Price Is Right'' _ not coincidentally, ``Women 2 Women'''s lead-in
on KCBS _ in which host Bob Barker revealed, ``We have the best
stagehands in the world.'' Another spot featured comedy
writer/novelist Gail Parent suggesting ways to ``be with your guy
forever, and never let him see you naked (tips included ``Wear
beach cover-ups'' and ``Never be naked and stand up at the same
time ... the missionary position is very flattering'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Women'' also managed to promote the CBS Evening News with Dan
Rather, whose move to 6:30 from 5:30 p.m. caused the reshuffle of
KCBS' late afternoon lineup. Rather was in town for the week in
part to promote this time slot change; the hosts' attempt to create
a ``female'' angle on Rather's appearance was tenuous. It basically
amounted to Rather crediting his mother, his grandmother, his
second-grade teacher and Barbara Walters with being helpful to him
in his life and his career. The hardest-hitting question the ladies
asked him was, ``How do you keep your hair looking so perfect?''
</P>
<P>
   Chacon admits the show is a work in progress, from its subject
matter to a few technical glitches. On Monday, microphones didn't
always work, a crew member walked in front of the cameras, both
guests and hosts had their awkward moments. But Chacon said the
hosts handled everything in stride, and promised there would be
more substantive pieces mixed with the fluff in the future.
Consumer advocate Mike Boguslawski will be a regular feature, and
there will be segments covering women's health and current issues
mixed in with pieces on hairstyles, restaurants and celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Chacon also insisted that KCBS management is committed to
letting the show find an audience, and that the reshuffling of the
news schedule does not signify that Ann Martin is taking a smaller
role in news. Martin is still co-anchoring the half-hour newscasts
at 6 and 11 p.m. with Jonathan Elias, while Gretchen Carr, the
younger and slightly blonder former KCBS weekend anchor, fills the
seat next to Elias from 5 to 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   As further evidence that ``Women'' is still shaping its
identity, the hosts at the end of Monday's show asked viewers to
share what they think of the show, along with suggestions for show
topics. They encouraged viewers to write to KCBS or to log their
comments on KCBS' Web site,  &UR; www.channel2000.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
