<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2076 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SHABBY-BLACK-DANCE-AR     09-14 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHABBY-BLACK-DANCE-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLOIST WITH A SINGULAR PERSONA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I'm supposed to look like a disheveled, disgruntled
old geisha,'' Beverly Blossom said cheerfully, dressed in a long
golden kimono and top hat and sprawled in a convenient folding
chair in a midtown rehearsal studio.
</P>
<P>
   Next she swept across the floor in a bargain-basement black
satin Balenciaga cloak and thrift-shop gold dress, a toy monkey
drooping from her hand. Then, with the donning of another, slightly
shredded costume, she became both an aging beauty and a
bottom-patting old gigolo drawn together in a bittersweet tango.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who (italics)is(end italics) she?'' a visitor to the studio
whispered, eyes wide, as Ms. Blossom glided through the dizzying
array of characters she will portray in ``Dances in Shabby Black,''
a retrospective program on Friday and Saturday at the Context
Studio, a small black-box theater on the Lower East Side.
</P>
<P>
   A dancer with Alwin Nikolais, Ms. Blossom went on to train with
Mary Wigman. But the greatest creative spur was Nikolais' delight
in his performers' individual visions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Blossom began to choreograph in the 1950s and then joined
the actor Roberts Blossom, her husband at the time, in the theater,
dance and film experiments that thrived in the East Village in the
yeasty 1960s. Creating pieces for her dance students at the
University of Illinois in Champaign-Urbana, she rediscovered the
attraction of solo performing.
</P>
<P>
   Back in New York City since 1990, Ms. Blossom has become an
underground favorite who is known for performances and pieces, set
typically to gooey popular and classical music, that are
simultaneously tragic and hilarious and that evoke surprisingly
complex emotions. ``I always liked the Cubist term
`multidimensional simultaneity,''' she said. ``The duality just
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Her solos are often inspired by odd confluences of random
events. The 1996 ``Dead Monkey'' grew in her mind after she saw a
video on the mistreatment of laboratory monkeys and learned that
she would have to have her hip replaced.
</P>
<P>
   At 73, Ms. Blossom is a large woman with a beautifully ravaged
face. She does not attempt to disguise either attribute, preferring
to make them a comfortable part of her dances through the use of
voluminous cloaks and bright-red hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always have to tell the hairdresser that I (italics)want(end
italics) to look like Bozo the Clown,'' Ms. Blossom said.
</P>
<P>
   She often creates her dances sitting at one end of a room and
``watching myself perform.'' Sometimes she dresses a thick wooden
post in a costume and positions it where the stage might be. ``I
used to think that was pretty crazy. I didn't tell anyone.'' But
then she read that Isadora Duncan would rent an auditorium, hire a
pianist and sit out in the audience to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know now that she was choreographing in her mind's eye. What
is a dance, anyway? It comes from your mind. And there's nothing
like a good idea. Nothing can come up to that.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the first time, Ms. Blossom is allowing other
dancers to perform some of her solos. She has taken a chance on
Cynthia Pipkin-Doyle, Ella Magruder and Betsy Fisher, all of whom
will perform with her at Context.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point to it is that I'm trying to sell my choreography,''
Ms. Blossom said with a quizzical grin. ``What is a dance worth?
$1.99? Get them while the price is right.'' She also coaches
choreographers and performers on her Web site
(http://www/beverlyblossom.com).
</P>
<P>
   The best homes for the solos are with dancers who are ``old
enough, and sophisticated,'' she said. Her signature ``Dad's
Ties,'' for instance, ``must be done by someone who has memories.''
</P>
<P>
   What are the special skills required for solo dancing in
general?
</P>
<P>
   ``Personality,'' Ms. Blossom said, alluding to a comment the
ballerina Natalia Makarova made about great dancers. ``You can't be
a blank-minded ingenue. There must be a dance persona that is rich,
that has layers of interest. A soloist has to have a `voice,' the
way a singer does. And it has to do with _ not exactly beauty, but
something that consumes the whole space. A good soloist has to know
the tricks of the trade, too. How loud to sing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
