<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2078 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JAKOB-THE-LIAR-FILM-$     09-14 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAKOB-THE-LIAR-FILM-$ADV19-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OFT-TOLD TALE? NOT BY HIS LIGHTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Even though the director Peter Kassovitz wore a yellow
star as a child in wartime Budapest, Hungary, and his parents were
Nazi concentration camp survivors, he does not remember growing up
in the shadow of the genocide of European Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly he was not looking for a way to address the Holocaust
on screen when he came across Jurek Becker's 1969 novel, ``Jakob
the Liar,'' which tells of a Jewish cafe owner who uses lies to
bring hope to a Polish wartime ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know directors,'' he said with a smile, recalling his
discovery of the book at his mother's home in Budapest in 1990,
``they are always flicking through books looking for a good subject
for a film.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, the novel had already been widely translated from
German (Plume Books is reissuing it in English this month). It had
even been turned into a small German film in 1974. But the
61-year-old director, who fled to France after the 1956 Hungarian
uprising, wanted to retell it anyway, and he persuaded Becker to
sell the rights for a new English-language version. Kassovitz's
``Jakob the Liar'' finally opens in New York on Friday, with Robin
Williams in the role of the reluctant hero, Jakob Heym.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the nine years between Kassovitz's discovery of
the book and his movie's release, other Holocaust-related feature
films have reached the screen. He was still circulating the
screenplay that he co-wrote with the French novelist Didier Decoin
when Steven Spielberg's ``Schindler's List'' was released in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   And while he finished shooting ``Jakob the Liar'' before Roberto
Benigni had completed ``Life Is Beautiful,'' the Benigni film came
out sooner. Another Holocaust-related movie, Radu Mihaileanu's
``Train of Life,'' which also treats the subject with humor, was
released in Europe last year; it is set to open in New York on Nov.
5.
</P>
<P>
   But Kassovitz, a soft-spoken and good-natured man, seems
unfazed. He believes ``Jakob the Liar'' is different.
</P>
<P>
   Set in an unidentified Polish ghetto under German occupation, it
opens with Jakob ordered to present himself before a Gestapo
officer and, while waiting, hearing a radio report suggesting that
Russian forces have German troops on the defensive. Instructed to
return to the ghetto, he finds its gates closed and, while looking
for a way back in, he bumps into Lina Kronstein, a 10-year-old girl
(Hannah Taylor Gordon) who has escaped a train carrying Jews to a
death camp. The pair slip back into the ghetto, and Jakob hides the
child in his attic.
</P>
<P>
   News of the Russian offensive, though, cheers him. And when a
hot-headed young friend, Mischa (Liev Schreiber), plans a reckless
escape, Jakob urges patience and tells of hearing a radio report
that liberation is near. Soon the entire ghetto believes that Jakob
has a radio hidden in his house. Terrified, Jakob denies it,
knowing that he will be executed if word reaches the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Frankfurter (Alan Arkin), an aging actor, tells him to destroy
it. Kowalsky (Bob Balaban), the suicidal local barber, keeps asking
for more news. Everyone starts treating Jakob with new respect.
</P>
<P>
   Only Dr. Kirschbaum (Armin Mueller-Stahl) realizes that Jakob
has no radio _ but, he points out, there have been no suicides in
the ghetto since Jakob first brought good news. The message is
clear: Jakob has a duty to keep hope alive in the desperate and
starving community, so he should invent news.
</P>
<P>
   With little Lina ailing, he even promises she can hear the radio
if she recovers: he then imitates the voice of Winston Churchill
from behind a screen. Eventually, of course, the Germans hear about
Jakob's radio, but hope somehow wins out.
</P>
<P>
   Kassovitz, whose career to date has focused on television films,
said that above all he wanted to make the movie as realistic as
possible. While interiors and some exteriors were shot in Hungary,
a ghetto was re-created in the Polish town of Piotrkow, which had a
small Jewish ghetto during the war and is near Lodz, which had a
much larger ghetto where Becker himself spent much of the war.
(Becker died in late 1997, just as filming of ``Jakob the Liar''
was about to start.) Much effort also went into making the ghetto
and costumes look authentic. The only concession was that the
Polish Jews were speaking English.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film should have been made in Yiddish,'' Kassovitz said,
sipping water on the terrace of his apartment in eastern Paris,
``but it is better to do it in English than French. First, you have
more money. But that wasn't the reason. We're more used to hearing
English spoken with a Yiddish accent than French. I think it works
better.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As important, in Kassovitz's view, is the Jewish humor in his
film, humor that stems occasionally from absurd situations but is
more often expressed darkly by the residents of the ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had in mind much more humor,'' he said. ``You know the
saying, you can laugh at anything, but not with everybody. The film
became more dramatic and emotional because of the cast. They
brought their own feelings. The way the lines are said, the way
they act, they had more respect for the subject than I had.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Williams said that Kassovitz kept telling him to ``forget
your gentile guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But as an American, you get kind of uncomfortable that humor
in this situation would be taken as disrespectful,'' he said in a
telephone interview from Berlin, where he had just attended a
screening of the film. ``But there was a man on the set, a Jew and
a survivor who said, `You can't be afraid of the humor, it's how
you exist, it keeps your soul alive.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes part of the survival mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   This is also the view of Mihaileanu, whose ``Train of Life''
tells of an Eastern European shtetl that decides to escape by
building its own deportation train, with some villagers dressed as
Nazi officers and the rest locked in wagons as deportees, an idea
as original as it is surreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jewish humor has always been a shield against madness,'' said
the Romanian director, who was himself raised in a shtetl. ``Comedy
is tragedy's balm. We don't laugh (italics)at(end italics) a tragic
event. But we continue to laugh in order to persevere.''
</P>
<P>
   The special quality of Jewish humor was in fact one reason that
Kassovitz sent his screenplay to Williams: he thought the actor was
Jewish. But instead it was the screenplay itself that interested
Williams' wife, Marsha Garces Williams, who runs their Blue Wolf
Productions. And soon the couple were dining in Paris with
Kassovitz and his (more famous) director son, Mathieu (``Cafe au
Lait,'' ``Hate'').
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fairy tale,'' Kassovitz said with a laugh. ``Unknown
director sends script to big star and big star says, `Let's get
married.'''
</P>
<P>
   Well, better, actually. Williams agreed to play Jakob, and Ms.
Williams agreed to produce the $15 million movie through Blue Wolf.
And, with Williams on board, it was easy to recruit other
well-known actors.
</P>
<P>
   Did Williams think he was gambling in joining forces with a
director whose work he had never seen?
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew if he had written this script, he certainly had an
instinct,'' Williams said. ``Then after meeting him and Mathieu in
Paris, his sense of humor, the way he is. It was pretty much an
immediate thing. His being a Hungarian Jew, whose parents were
survivors, gave him a certain sensibility. And remember, three
years ago, no movie had been made that attempted to use humor in
this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, after the success of ``Life Is Beautiful,''
``Jakob the Liar'' is not the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Williams said with undisguised exasperation. ``It's
like you can have 25 buddy movies or guys who are blowing each
other away, but another Jewish film, `Oh God, one a year is enough,
thank you.' PLEASE.''
</P>
<P>
   Kassovitz seems more worried about the Jewish reaction,
particularly that of Claude Lanzmann, the director of ``Shoah,''
the renowned Holocaust testimony film, who criticized both
``Schindler's List'' and ``Life Is Beautiful,'' arguing that the
Holocaust should not be treated as fiction.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Jakob the Liar'' was shown at this month's American Film
Festival in Deauville, France, however, Kassovitz felt more
reassured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was walking along the beach and I heard these two old Jewish
ladies talking about the film,'' he said. ``One said, `Oh, it was
so great, it was exactly like that, but how did they find the
place?' And the other said, `And the little girl, exactly like my
girl.' I think they did not feel betrayed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
