<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2084 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DOWNSIZING-MUSICALS-2     09-14 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNSIZING-MUSICALS-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNSIZING THE BROADWAY MUSICAL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note subslug for BEAUTY-BEAST-THEATER)  
 (af)  
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The dancing corkscrew will still be there, as will
the singing whisk and the graceful cheese grater. But there may be
slightly fewer spinning plates and spatulas when ``Beauty and the
Beast'' reopens on Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   And over at ``The Scarlet Pimpernel,'' which reopened Sept. 10,
there are fewer people waiting to be executed in the guillotine
scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beauty and the Beast'' closed at the Palace Theater on Sept. 5
and is coming back in a slightly smaller version to the
Lunt-Fontanne Theater on Nov. 12; the cast will drop by seven,
including understudies and swings (who fill in for various roles).
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' closed at the Minskoff on
May 30 and reopened at the Neil Simon after several weeks of
touring, having scaled back its cast by 12 and its orchestra by 4.
</P>
<P>
   Musicals are typically made more modest when they leave Broadway
for the road. But it is unusual for a show to close in New York and
then reopen there in reduced form, particularly at a time when the
industry has increased the top ticket price to $80 from $75.
</P>
<P>
   And, taken together, these two examples suggest a potentially
significant rethinking about how to produce shows for less when
musicals increasingly cost more.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' and ``Beauty and the
Beast'' maintain that the changes are imperceptible and the shows
have improved considerably as a result of scaling them down. ``It
plays better in an intimate space,'' said Robert Longbottom, the
director of ``Pimpernel.'' ``This is a story about three people,
and you can touch them at the Neil Simon. It's substantially less
people onstage, but it doesn't feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the scenery has also been simplified. What was
previously a full stage elevator that simulated a ship is now a
scissor lift. ``It's the low-tech version of it,'' Longbottom said.
``But it's absolutely as graceful and as magical.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the downsizing raises questions that some in the
theater industry will have to deal with if this practice gains in
popularity. Might not such reductions ultimately compromise
content? Won't other producers inevitably want to follow suit and
try to sustain a run by revamping shows, conceivably at the expense
of production values? What does this mean for theater audiences?
</P>
<P>
   ``Costs are just as important as quality,'' said Rocco
Landesman, president of Jujamcyn Theaters.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the loss of jobs? The New York musicians union,
Local 802, is contesting the reduction in the number of musicians
in ``Pimpernel'' from 24 to 20, even though the union-set minimum
drops from one theater to another. ``The fact of diminishing the
production and selling it for the same dollars, there is something
wrong with that,'' said William Moriarty, president of the local.
</P>
<P>
   While union rules require the Neil Simon Theater to use four
fewer musicians than the Minskoff does, the union is arguing that
the streamlined ``Pimpernel'' is the same production and therefore
should maintain the same number of musicians. ``Our contract says
the orchestra is hired for the run of the show in New York City,''
Moriarty said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his union had a meeting scheduled later this week with
the grievance committee at the League of American Theaters and
Producers. ``This is a new set of circumstances so far as I'm
aware,'' Moriarty said. ``If it is the wave of the future, now is
the time to address this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Moriarty said he also planned to talk with the producers of
``Beauty and the Beast'' about making sure the orchestra for that
show retains the same musicians from one production to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Eisenberg, executive director of the Actors Equity
Association, the actors union, said he, too, was troubled by the
scaling down of musicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody with a long time on a show can be downsized out with
no kind of compensation for the commitment that they've made,'' he
said. ``There should be some recognition of seniority. Jobs are
hard to come by.'' As it is, he noted that union members work an
average of only 16 weeks a year.
</P>
<P>
   Some producers are skeptical about whether downsizing can work.
Tom Viertel, a Broadway producer, said he tried it unsuccessfully
years ago with a show called ``Sills &AMP; Company,'' moving to a
smaller theater and reducing the cast to five from nine to save
money. ``Whether you can actually turn things around by tightening
up, I don't know,'' Viertel said. ``It didn't work for us. The
audience tightened up too.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say the trend signals a healthy re-examination of how
Broadway plays are produced, an approach that would be best adopted
before a show opens rather than after it is up and running.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this signals a kind of responsible reaction or need to have
these productions come in at figures that can actually be
economically feasible, I think that's terrific,'' said Margo Lion,
a Broadway producer. ``Hopefully, they'll be even better than they
were before.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Schumacher and Peter Schneider of Walt Disney Theatrical
Productions played down the changes to ``Beauty and the Beast'' as
little more than the kind of polishing that is always done with a
show. In fact, they said, a song (``There's Been a Change in Me'')
was recently added, an unusual step four years into a show's run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out there saying simpler, smaller, cheaper,''
Schneider said. ``We're saying it's a move to the Lunt-Fontanne to
keep it running longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the people behind these productions seemed to bristle at
the suggestion that their shows had somehow diminished in quality
because they had decreased in size.
</P>
<P>
   ``The producers had the option to end the run or to rethink it
in a smaller house,'' Longbottom said. ``And I think it has been
overdramatized what that rethinking means. We simply have moved to
a smaller home and in doing that, you sometimes have to throw out
furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Ward Land, who has been in ``Pimpernel'' since the
beginning, said the show had benefited from becoming more compact _
there had previously been people on stage who didn't do much _ but
that it was hard to see some of her colleagues go. ``I think for
the people who stayed, they were glad to have a job,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jed Bernstein, president of the producers league, pointed out
that the reconfiguration of these productions has meant the
preservation of some jobs rather than the elimination of all of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In what other industry is there this notion that there are no
efficiencies to be gained?'' he asked, adding: ``It isn't about the
number of people. It's about what tells the story the best and
that's what should govern, not some antiquated rule. And if you can
save money, great, because it will give the show longer life and
make it better for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a tradition of renovating long-running shows. In an
extreme example, the producer Cameron Mackintosh replaced almost
the entire cast of ``Les Miserables'' after deciding that the
production had grown stale.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospect of slimming down musicals is a new question for
Broadway. Where until just a few years ago the idea of closing,
reworking and reopening a show would have been financially
prohibitive for most producers, corporate deep pockets have now
made it possible to finance such transitions.
</P>
<P>
   But both producers in this case say they did not scale down
their productions mainly for financial reasons. They did it, they
say, because of real estate; their theaters had been promised to
other shows. ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' had to leave the Minskoff
because ``Saturday Night Fever'' was moving in. ``Beauty and the
Beast'' had to leave the Palace for Disney's ``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, economics are part of it _ it's a commercial venture,''
Schumacher said. ``But at the end of the day, it's the quality of
the show that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hawkins, the executive producer of ``The Scarlet
Pimpernel,'' said moving was not a matter of choice or financial
necessity. The show was grossing a respectable average of just
below $500,000 a week before it closed, he said, and ``the move and
adjustments are happening because we're forced to move to a smaller
theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, costs will be about 20 percent lower in the
smaller theater. The Neil Simon not only has fewer seats (1,300
compared to the Minskoff's 1,700), but its total dimensions are
about 60 percent that of the Minskoff, Hawkins said. He said
``Pimpernel'' had to scale down to adapt to that new tighter space.
</P>
<P>
   And while die-hard fans may notice that there is no longer a
crowd scene where there used to be one, Hawkins said: ``We believe
that the perception will be that nothing changed, that the show
delivers now maybe even moreso than than it did in the Minskoff.''
</P>
<P>
   This will mark the third incarnation of ``Pimpernel,'' a version
its creators refer to as Pimpernel 3.0. The first overhaul,
undertaken last year, was prompted by flagging ticket sales.
``Pimpernel'' had some loyal _ and wealthy _ fans in the
Cablevision Systems Corp., which acquired the musical in
partnership with the financier Theodore J. Forstmann, one of the
show's original producers.
</P>
<P>
   After a period of rehearsing the new show during the day while
performing the old version at night, ``Pimpernel'' reopened last
fall with substantial changes: new lines, discarded scenes and
moved songs.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from some new choreography, the current revised
``Pimpernel'' has changed in that the total cast has shrunk from 41
to 29. This reduction has meant more responsibility for each cast
member. ``An ensemble member may go from being a soldier in one
scene to a maid in another scene to someone at the royal ball in
the next scene,'' Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether it was difficult to let some longtime cast members
go, Longbottom said: ``That's never easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast of ``Beauty and Beast'' has dropped from 39 to 32. And
the show's producers said the lighting, sound and sets have been
improved. For the big production number, ``Be Our Guest,'' in which
the kitchen comes to life in inviting Belle (Beauty) to dinner, the
producers said the changes would be minor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some adjustments to the cutlery,'' Schumacher
said. ``But all your feature condiments containers are safe. They
haven't been affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether self-justifying or not, producers say such efforts will
ultimately make their productions measurably better, without making
them perceptibly different. ``It's like honey, I shrank the show,''
Longbottom said. ``But because of the house that it's in, it looks
just as big to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
