<SLUG> BC-DOG-SLEDDING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKI RESORTS LET DOGS LEAD THE WAY TO SNOWY ADVENTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURANGO, Colo. _ Slipping quietly through snow-packed trails cut
by snowmobiles on the highest peaks of the San Juan Mountains,
bundled comfortably on a sled behind a pack of exuberant huskies,
the lure of dog sledding quickly becomes apparent:
</P>
<P>
   Gliding through fresh snow that glistens in the sun like a
glitter-covered white blanket; skipping the lift lines that come
with downhill skiing. None of the huffing and puffing through flat
and uphill spots as you do with cross-country skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Also missing is the loud, banging rattle of a powerful engine
belching smoke from a snowmobile. Instead, you hear the yapping and
barking of dogs, obviously excited about a romp through the snow in
the fresh mountain air.
</P>
<P>
   Our trip with Silver Mountain Sled Dog Tours validated why dog
sledding has become so popular. Such businesses now operate out of
most major ski resort areas in the Western United States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, ancillary activities at ski resorts have grown
immensely in the last 10 years, and dog sledding is among the most
popular,'' said Nancy Pfeiffer, a consultant for InterWest
Adventures, a public relations company in Salt Lake City, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``No longer do you go to Park City or Jackson Hole or Vail and
spend five out of six days skiing. There's snowmobiling, snowshoe
hikes, cross-country skiing, powder cat tours, sleigh rides,
hot-air ballooning and ice climbing. Nearly every ski resort has a
sled-dog operation nowadays,'' Pfeiffer said.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as you begin your trip, you feel the dogs' energy and
enthusiasm and get caught up in it _ that and the beauty of the
frozen glades and forests of what people in Colorado call simply
``the high country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You really can see diamonds in the snow up here,'' my daughter
observed, pointing out the sun glinting on the pure white expanse.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, she fell in love with ``Snowy,'' a pure Siberian husky
with beautiful eyes and an unusually sweet temperament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look for dogs that are agile and athletic, smart and
trainable,'' said Gretchen Dubit, 32, who with her husband, Gregg,
operates Silver Mountain Sled Dog Tours out of Durango. The Dubits
got their first sled dog and began mushing about six years ago.
This will be the third season they have commercially worked the
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The Dubits keep 21 sled dogs at the Durango Dog Ranch, their
40-acre spread near Purgatory Ski Resort. Most of their dogs are
not purebred; some were adopted from animal shelters. They may not
have the credentials to be sled dogs, but they have the heart.
</P>
<P>
   A sled dog's desire to work is the most important thing. Sled
dogs must know the commands to go, turn left, turn right and stop,
and they have to learn to work together. These working dogs also
are cuddly and sweet, an important characteristic for animals that
provide joy rides for strangers all winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We train them to be pets first, but when they are hooked up,
they know what it means and what they should do. They want to run,
they're ready to go. They are as sweet as can be out of the
harness, but so serious and intent on working in harness, they get
aggressive,'' said Gretchen Dubit, a high-school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Dubit, 35, a high-school teacher until about a year ago,
patiently talked my eager 12-year-old through a lesson in mushing.
He made sure she knew how to use the sled's two brakes and
emergency anchor before allowing her to take control.
</P>
<P>
   She learned to say, ``OK, let's go _ Gii!'' rather than
``mush,'' because the dogs respond to the particular and consistent
commands used in training them.
</P>
<P>
   For tourists, Silver Mountain uses small, classic curved ash
sleds with six to eight dogs, depending on the number of
passengers, who nestle up on sleeping bags with faux fur throws
wrapped around them or stand on the back like real mushers to drive
the sled.
</P>
<P>
   A sledding trip is a big adventure. The Dubits, and their
passengers, never know what's going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a sled tips over and dumps passengers in a heap in the
snow, but none of the dog lovers who book a tour seem to mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO:
</P>
<P>
   Silver Mountain Sled Dog Tours, Durango, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Half-day trips with snack and hot drinks _ and hot dogs to feed
the dogs for a treat at the end _ cost $95 per person. Full-day
trips with lunch for you and the sled dogs are $155 per person.
Overnight expeditions to a cabin in the woods also can be arranged.
Trips begin with the start of the ski season.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (970) 259-0694.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
