<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2094 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-SAVANNAH-95     09-14 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-SAVANNAH-950(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE FORCES MASSIVE EVACUATION OF SAVANNAH, COASTAL GEORGIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (With HURRICANE-FLOYD and related stories) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ The evacuation of Savannah began at dawn
Tuesday, an endless motorized march of steaming engines and crying
children fleeing the winds that threatened this old city's historic
buildings and Spanish moss.
</P>
<P>
   More than half a million people were on the move Tuesday away
from the Georgia coast, and most of those were in slow lines of
traffic leading away from Savannah and surrounding Chatham County,
where the evacuation became mandatory at noon. Forecasters said
there was a strong chance the eye of Hurricane Floyd could come
ashore within 20 miles of downtown on Wednesday or Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the weather was clear and hot Tuesday, county officials
decided not to delay the evacuation orders, figuring that it could
take as long as 28 hours to clear the county's 225,500 people.
Surrounded by rivers and inlets, the county is particularly
difficult to evacuate, and it has been 10 years _ since the
abortive strike of Hurricane Hugo _ that officials have even tried.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the main interstates and other arteries out of town
were packed from sunrise until well past nightfall, as residents
headed to fully booked hotels in central Georgia and relatives in
Atlanta. All lanes on Interstate 16, the main route away from the
coast, were made westbound for 90 miles, and on some sections,
walking was faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a good thing we're not in a hurry,'' said one woman
who called from her cell phone to a Savannah radio station Tuesday
afternoon. ``If Floyd were coming today, we'd be killing each other
out here.''
</P>
<P>
   County emergency management officials said the movement was
generally orderly, with a minimum of honking and fender benders.
But there were serious problems moving the poor, the elderly and
the sick, many of whom had no access to transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Those who needed rides were told to come to the Savannah Civic
Center downtown, where buses would take them to shelters farther
inland. But the county could not supply enough buses to move the
thousands of people who came, and there were shoving matches
whenever a bus showed up. Many people wound up waiting most of the
day for a ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was panic, pure and simple,'' said Bert Graitham, a retired
mechanic who uses a wheelchair and was unable to board any of the
school buses the county pressed into service Tuesday afternoon.
``People were pushing past old folks and kids and squeezing on
those buses like their lives depended on it. They told me a van
would be coming with a lift, but I sure haven't seen it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost every business, restaurant and hotel in the region was
closed. Hospitals stayed open, but warned residents not to show up
without a serious emergency.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Tropical storms generally have not been hard on Georgia, which
is protected by its recessed coastline. The last hurricane that
came ashore here was David, which did substantial damage in 1979.
But emergency officials warned that Floyd had far more destructive
potential. If it did make landfall near Savannah, said Gary
McConnell, Georgia's emergency management director, it would be
``the most dangerous storm ever to hit Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The well-publicized warnings persuaded most people to leave the
area, and county officials said they were pleased with a 60 percent
compliance rate by 6 p.m., a rate expected to be higher by
Wednesday morning. Holdouts were particularly few in the low-lying
coastal islands southeast of the city. By 2 p.m., almost everyone
had left Tybee and Talahi Islands, which could well be engulfed by
storm surges on Wednesday or Thursday; even the Tybee Optimists
Club was boarded up. It had been so long since there was a serious
threat, however, that a few residents could barely bring themselves
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll leave in a few hours, once the traffic dies
down,'' said John Wylly III, who grew up on Tybee Island and was
mowing his lawn in the warm afternoon breeze. ``We once found some
letters from 100 years ago by a guy who said the flooding from a
hurricane was so bad they had to swim from house to house. I guess
that's what we're looking at now, so we're all getting out of
here.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Wylly's father, an antique car collector,
drove up in a Model T Ford and laughingly said he wanted to take a
last look at the beaches. He said he would reluctantly have to
change cars before leaving, as the old Ford refused to go faster
than 30 mph.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that only a few people had refused to
comply with the orders in Savannah, where some of the moody old
homes along Victory Drive were boarded up; most were dark and
abandoned. Since many of the homes are huddled around downtown
squares, some residents felt the buildings would be sheltered.
Still, there was concern that winds, debris and heavy rains could
damage the old structures.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many residents said they were afraid their homes would be looted
once they left, but there were scores of police cars cruising the
side streets, and unmarked cars were posted at main intersections
leading to prosperous neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Donnelly, an auctioneer who owns an antique shop, said one
of his employees insisted on staying behind to protect the
inventory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a shotgun and a Bowie knife, and I don't think even a
hurricane can knock him down,'' Donnelly said.
</P>
<P>
   But the prevailing sentiment seemed to be captured by a farewell
message spraypainted on a boarded-up window of Roberts Furniture
Co. downtown: ``This town's only big enough for one Floyd.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
