<HEADLINE>
A BLUE PLATE SPECIAL ON SOUR GRAPES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sad thing about awards shows, wrote  &UR; John Boe &LR;  after
watching this week's Emmys telecast, ``is that not everyone can
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Linz, Austria, where the Prix Ars Electronica &LR; 
cq &LR; , the Oscars of cyberspace, were distributed recently,
old-fashioned sour grapes were served up by high-tech artists.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco filmmaker and video artist  &UR; Lynn Hershman &LR; , who
took home a winged 3-foot-tall solid gold Golden Nica for ``The
Difference Engine 3,'' says she ``clung'' to the bulky prize ``and
carried it home on the airplane for fear it would be lost if I
checked it.''
</P>
<P>
   But when an artist from Digital Domain, which won for special
effects in ``What Dreams May Come,'' set down the award at a
post-ceremony celebration, it disappeared immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The theft was a political act perpetrated by another artists'
group, etoy. The thieves said at a press conference later that they
took the prize because they didn't think Digital Domain deserved
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUCK UP, SAID BILL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bill Clinton &LR;  telephoned  &UR; Katherine Bryan &LR; , the wife of one of
his supporters, to offer condolences when news broke that her
husband,  &UR; Shelby Bryan &LR; , was having a hot and heavy affair with
Vogue editor  &UR; Anna Wintour &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   New York magazine reports that it looked for a while as if
Bryan's affair, much noticed in New York, would put the kibosh on a
planned presidential appointment. Then came the news that Bryan is
divorcing his wife and that Wintour is divorcing her husband,
psychiatrist  &UR; David Shaffer &LR; . And Bryan, a heavy contributor to
Clinton, has been given a seat on an advisory board on foreign
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Said one Vogue editor of the scandal's effect on her hard-edged
boss, ``It's really weird. ... It's kind of chipped away at her
whole persona. Like she's been caught in the act of doing something
... human.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Ken Maley &LR;  was taken by the sign in Benny's in Vancouver:
``We prepare your food as if we had to eat it ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   _ From the man who invented the Internet: In the course of
research for a business matter,  &UR; Len Fisher &LR;  came upon Senate Bill
459, Title 3.5, sponsored by  &UR; Al Gore &LR;  and passed into law in 1990:
``Use of inventions in outer space.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Pamela Anderson Lee &LR;  told Men's Fitness that the weirdest
thing in her refrigerator is her son's placenta, which wasn't all
that weird because holistically minded people know that consuming
the placenta is a tribal ritual. More surprising, however, is her
revelation of plans for the thing, which bears a ``do not eat''
sign: ``We're going to put it in our koi pond once our yard is
finished.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
