</P>
<P>
   _ Mayor  &UR; Ying-jeau Ma &LR;  of Taipei was in San Francisco over the
weekend, and because Taipei has a growing gay-rights movement, he
was particularly interested in taking a look around the Castro,
says Supervisor  &UR; Tom Ammiano &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Thomas Lee &LR; , a Chinese-speaking aide to Ammiano, took Ma
through the neighborhood, where he expressed particular delight at
the Gay Cleaners, a Chinese laundry. Although that Castro Street
establishment was in business long before ``gay'' described the
Castro, Ma perceived it as a perfect melding of Chinese
entrepreneurship and neighborhood lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newly named neighborhood: Residents of that upwardly mobile
piece of Mission Street between Cesar Chavez and Randall streets
(which ``skirts the base of Bernal Heights'') are ``eager to
differentiate this area from its bookends, the Inner and Outer
Mission,'' writes  &UR; John Perry &LR; , who passes along one suggestion:
BeLola, derived from Bernal Lowlands.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bravo to  &UR; Robin Williams &LR; , whose name has been on a freeway
cleanup sign near 3Com Park for many moons, and here's hoping he'll
be on hand to help park cars when PacBell opens.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the ``deep, dark end'' of Sacramento Street, strobe lights
flashed for an hour and a half at the Claire Lilienthal School last
week; during the last half hour, an audible alarm ``shrieked,''
too, reports neighbor  &UR; Fran Johns &LR; . A school official told Johns
that the strobe is for the hearing-impaired, who apparently get
warned of impending disaster well before anyone ``blind or
napping,'' says Johns.
</P>
<P>
