<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2116 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-OHNESORG-MUSIC-ART-2T     09-14 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHNESORG-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN CARNEGIE HALL CALLS, YOU DON'T SAY NO  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ As Americanization proceeds apace, many
things remain different in Germany. Tabloids, for one, and a
refreshingly offbeat notion of what constitutes blockbuster news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ohnesorg Weg aus Koln'' (``Ohnesorg Out of Cologne''), a
banner headline trumpeted in January, when it was announced that
Franz Xaver Ohnesorg was leaving his position as director of the
Cologne Philharmonie, without evident mayhem or murder, to become
the executive and artistic director of Carnegie Hall. A full-color
photograph of the miscreant, looking for all the world like the
teddy bear with which he appears in another well-circulated
photograph, accompanied the headline.
</P>
<P>
   But cultural figures are seen differently in Germany, too. Even
concert-hall managers, and especially this one, can loom larger
than life. In 16 years on the job in this relatively small city,
Ohnesorg, 51, a Bavarian who had held various administrative
positions in Munich, became something of a legend.
</P>
<P>
   He oversaw the planning and construction of the Philharmonie,
one of the finest modern concert halls in Europe, which opened in
1986. Then he installed in it some of the most varied and
adventurous musical programming anywhere, attracting the best
performers on the international scene. And on it all he left the
imprint of an oversize personality, fueled by enormous energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a person you feel neutrally about, and I have nothing
but positive things to say,'' said the American conductor James
Conlon, who, as general music director of the city of Cologne since
1991, has worked closely with Ohnesorg. ``Especially in Europe,
where so much artistic administration has an aura of bureaucracy,
his example has been revelatory. He always puts artists and their
needs first.''
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Stern, who as president of Carnegie Hall played a crucial
role in luring Ohnesorg away from Cologne, spoke similarly of his
qualities, making special note of the fact that he is an
accomplished flutist. ``I was very much impressed that he was a
musician first,'' Stern said. ``He has a great understanding of the
history of music and of the beauty of the history of music.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was another farsighted administrator who first envisioned
Ohnesorg's potential at Carnegie Hall: his predecessor there,
Judith Arron. Over a period of many months, as the cancer that led
to her death last December progressed, Arron tried to persuade
Ohnesorg to join her team, as a ``No. 1 {,'' in Stern's phrase, and
a likely successor. Just days before she died, she was still
courting him from her hospital bed in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   So Stern and Sanford I. Weill, the chairman of Carnegie Hall,
evaluated Ohnesorg along with three or four American candidates
whom Stern called ``extraordinarily qualified'' but refused to
name. In a sort of certification of Arron's judgment, Ohnesorg
became a full-fledged No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Even apart from the devastating loss of his friend Arron, the
timing was less than ideal. Ohnesorg _ Xaver (pronounced ZAH-ver)
to his many friends _ was just finishing work on a home into which
he and his family had moved in Cologne.
</P>
<P>
   And he was looking forward to one of the most exciting periods
at the Philharmonie, including the 2000 edition of the Cologne
Music Triennale, a 20th-century-music festival that he founded in
1994, which is to feature all of the American Big Five orchestras
(those of Boston, Chicago, Cleveland, New York and Philadelphia)
within four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you said no to Carnegie Hall, what else would you do?''
asked Ohnesorg in his Philharmonie office, soon to be vacated.
``Someday perhaps the Salzburg Festival, but a chance like this may
never come again.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Carnegie Hall, too, was anticipating one of its most
exciting seasons in decades, with a vast patchwork survey of
20th-century music variously guided by Maurizio Pollini, Pierre
Boulez and Daniel Barenboim, and placed in a rich historical
context. The culmination of Arron's dozen years of innovative
programming of concerts and workshops, it was also a season after
Ohnesorg's heart: one similar, in fact, to his own Cologne season
in the prominence it gives to Boulez and Barenboim and in its other
emphases.
</P>
<P>
   So Ohnesorg said a long goodbye recently with a gala affair of
which New York has seldom seen the like in recent decades: perhaps
only in the celebrations of James Levine's 25th anniversary at the
Metropolitan Opera and of the renovation and then the centennial of
Carnegie Hall itself. Through five hours at the Philharmonie,
Conlon and Kurt Masur conducted the resident Gurzenich Orchestra;
Juliane Banse, Christine Schafer, Christoph Pregardien, Irwin Gage
and others offered an extended segment of songs, and Frank Peter
Zimmermann, Heinrich Schiff, Olli Mustonen and others played
chamber works.
</P>
<P>
   With a magnanimity said to be characteristic, Ohnesorg
contributed the proceeds (some $80,000, with all the musicians
donating their services) to the Beethoven House in Bonn to aid in
the publication of a facsimile edition of the autograph manuscript
of the ``Pastoral'' Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And in the wee hours after the concert, he treated much of the
assembled throng to a party in the nearby Alter Wartesaal, a
cavernous beer hall, at which a local band ran a gamut from ``Give
My Regards to Broadway'' to ``New York, New York.'' But the
ebullient Ohnesorg himself provided the most riotous entertainment,
extracting a hilariously sappy travesty of the Bach-Gounod ``Ave
Maria'' from an air pump with some ungodly combination of flute and
slide-whistle technique.
</P>
<P>
   American orchestra and concert-hall managers do not generally
put themselves forward to the public in the way Ohnesorg has done
here. ``You learn that in Germany,'' Conlon said. ``Germans expect
it and want it from a music director or a manager.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Conlon added, Ohnesorg's high profile had never
detracted from his considerate relationships with performers and
composers. Indeed, Stern cited the many deep friendships Ohnesorg
had cultivated with artists worldwide as a decisive factor in his
attractiveness to Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by all accounts _ not least, his own _ Ohnesorg will have
much to learn, much to adapt to, in New York. For one thing, he can
hardly expect to achieve the same kind of prominence outside the
classical-music community in a city where that community is _ in
contrast to the situation in Cologne _ dwarfed, jostled and made to
fend for itself. For another, he will have to get used to American
ways, pure and simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not the same recognition of authority here as in
Germany,'' Stern said, noting that even dealing with hall staff and
employees will require a significant adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever problems may arise, Ohnesorg suggests, will not be for
lack of effort on his part. ``I will need 24 hours a day for
Carnegie in the first months,'' he said, with no hint of hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Franziska, and his 3-year-old son, Severin, are
remaining in Cologne until next year, as he installs himself in an
apartment in Carnegie Hall, which Arron had built to ease her
difficult situation in her last years. He expresses relief that for
the moment, at least, he can put off moving his 10,000 books and
5,000 CDs.
</P>
<P>
   For Ohnesorg, New York, which he professes to love, will be the
farthest cry yet from his origins. He was born in 1948 in Weilheim,
a little town in the lovely, undulating countryside south of
Munich. In 1968, he moved to that city, where he studied both
business management and music. His work there included stints as
orchestra manager of the Munich Philharmonic and as a music
journalist.
</P>
<P>
   To judge from a couple of long conversations, Ohnesorg is an
affable man. (``Ohnesorg'' could translate as ``carefree.'') He
cuts a figure both dapper, with bow tie, a trim beard and
wire-rimmed glasses, and jolly, with an eager smile and twinkling
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, one senses steel underneath, and in truth it would
be surprising if Ohnesorg had accomplished so much without that.
Conlon's remark about the impossibility of remaining neutral toward
Ohnesorg undoubtedly cuts both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Be that as it may, Harold Clarkson, a prominent artist and
touring manager based in Hanover, likened Ohnesorg to a magnet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He attracts things,'' Clarkson said. ``He's absolutely
brilliant at getting people to open their purses. What he
accomplished in Cologne is remarkable. Most of the halls in Germany
act as garages. He changed that. He developed a hall with real
character and individuality.''
</P>
<P>
   When a man of such qualities meets an institution of such
tradition and resources as Carnegie, the chemistry is sure to be
volatile and, to say the least, interesting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
