<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ENVIRON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SETBACK FOR GORE, FRIENDS OF EARTH PAC ENDORSES BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley on Tuesday received the
endorsement of a national environmental organization, dealing a
blow to Vice President Al Gore's efforts to cast himself as the
clear choice of environmentally minded voters in the Democratic
presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the group, the Friends of the Earth Political
Action Committee, said they had decided to back Bradley this early
in the campaign _ the Iowa caucuses are still more than four months
away _ largely out of frustration with the environmental policies
of the Clinton administration, particularly on global warming and
international trade issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had very high hopes for Al Gore, and we've been
disappointed,'' said Mark Whiteis-Helm, a spokesman for the group.
``He's talked the talk but he has simply been unable to walk the
walk.''
</P>
<P>
   With 20,000 members in the United States, Friends of the Earth
is significantly smaller than other major environmental groups, and
it lacks the financial resources to provide much campaign help to
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement also appears unlikely to sway the two other
national environmental groups that endorse candidates, the Sierra
Club and the League of Conservation Voters. Officials of both
groups called Tuesday's move premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of these candidates have even outlined their positions or
programs,'' said Deb Callahan, president of the League of
Conservation Voters. She added that both candidates have strong
environmental records.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, the author of a 1992 best-selling book about the
dangers of global warming, ``Earth in the Balance,'' has been
widely viewed as the leading environmental voice in the
administration. So Tuesday's endorsement raises questions about the
depth of his support within an important Democratic constituency
that might have once been safely considered in his camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to remind a lot of people who care about the
environment about how good Bradley's record was,'' said Eric
Hauser, a spokesman for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokeswoman Kiki Moore said, ``Al Gore will continue to
work for a balanced approach and fight for a clean and healthy
environment for America's working families.''
</P>
<P>
   Whiteis-Helm criticized the Clinton administration _ and by
extension Gore _ for not pushing to reduce the use of chemicals
that are believed to contribute to global warming and for
negotiating trade agreements that allowed foreign companies to
skirt U.S. environmental rules.
</P>
<P>
   The League of Conservation Voters, which grades members of
Congress on their environmental votes, has given Bradley a lifetime
score of 84 percent for the 18 years he represented New Jersey in
the Senate. The group has given Gore, who represented Tennessee in
the House and the Senate for 16 years, a 64 percent lifetime score.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0280 </DOCNO>
