<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2120 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-EVACUEES-COX     09-14 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-EVACUEES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southeastern evacuations give new meaning to 'rush hour'
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Long before making landfall, Hurricane Floyd delivered
a strong blow to metro Atlanta: an all-night rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic got so bad that officials worried it would deter some
coastal residents from seeking safety on higher ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to get out of there,'' said Lillian Jackson, a
spokeswoman for the Georgia Department of Transportation. ``While
we want to be able to give them a realistic estimate of how long it
will take them, we really don't want to discourage them from taking
this trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the destination, the trip was long. But with hotels and
motels booked throughout the metro area and as far west as
Anniston, Ala., many evacuees had nowhere to go.
</P>
<P>
   Matters weren't much better along I-16 between Savannah and
Macon, where traffic crawled along at 35 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The highway was heavily congested even after officials closed
its eastbound lanes on an 85-mile stretch between Savannah and the
Swainsboro, Ga., exit just before noon and turned the interstate
into a one-way evacuation route. The eastbound lanes will be closed
``until the determination is made that everybody's out,'' said Ben
Snedeker of the DOT.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Hooker, the wife of a U.S. Army staff sergeant stationed
near Savannah, left home before noon with her two children,
Zachary, who turns 2 today, and Jacob, who turns 7 Sunday. By a
little after 7 p.m., she had gotten only to the small town of
Smarr, about 20 miles north of Macon in central Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm freaked out,'' said Hooker, whose husband was away for
drill-sergeant training. She rested at a BP gas station in Smarr.
``I'm trying to find a place to sleep. I don't want to go to a
shelter with these two kids. I thought I could find a room north of
Atlanta, but I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she planned to drive to her sister's house in
Guntersville, Ala., 65 miles northeast of Birmingham _ at least
another five hours away.
</P>
<P>
   Gas-station parking lots along the interstates were packed with
weary refugees. Families traveled in caravans of two or three
vehicles, and at a Shell station in Smarr, several vehicles with
Florida license tags had mattresses tied to their roofs, with blue
tarpaulins protecting the bedding from the inevitable rain.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people were trying to escape from Florida, where
the storm was expected to strike first. John Joyce, a spokesman for
the Florida Division of Emergency Management, said traffic was
bumper to bumper on I-75 and I-95, with ``a massive amount of cars
on the roads'' heading to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   They shared the roads with 500,000 people from Georgia's six
coastal counties who had been ordered to evacuate, including all
250,000 residents of Savannah and Chatham County.
</P>
<P>
   Savannah resident Mary Cannon, 53, packed her car with
essentials _ blankets, a 2-inch television, a flashlight, clothes
and her two cockatiel birds, Spike and Michelle. The birds rested
in the front passenger seat of her sky-blue Chevy Blazer as she
tried to navigate the traffic heading west on U.S. 80. She had
stopped at a gas station in Bloomingdale, about 20 miles outside of
Savannah, to get water for the birds, but it was closed and the
windows were taped up.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had packed most of her valuables in the Blazer, but
she had to leave something behind. ``You know what I'm worried
about?'' she asked. ``I had three or four thousand dollars' worth
of baseball cards. I had to leave them behind. I had to leave Ken
Griffey and Cal Ripkin, but I brought Mark McGuire and some Sammy
Sosas.''
</P>
<P>
   Some evacuees stopped short of metro Atlanta, spending the night
in makeshift shelters in small-town school gymnasiums and meeting
halls.
</P>
<P>
   At the Douglas Community Service Center in Coffee County, 500
people were expected to spend the night in a facility that had not
been prepared for their arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're overrun,'' said Sarah Paulk, a member of the center's
staff. ``We're needing all the food we can get ahold of. We didn't
know about this situation until this morning. It was just on us
right then.''
</P>
<P>
   Other shelters had radio stations broadcast pleas for bottled
water and mattresses, and two state DOT trucks left a north Atlanta
suburb late Tuesday to deliver 700 cots to shelters in Macon and
Swainsboro.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT trucks got help in quickly reaching their destinations _
a state police escort through crowded highways.
</P>
<P>
   A few coastal residents stayed behind in Savannah, where an
eerie calm settled over the nearly deserted city late Tuesday. The
only people on the streets were police officers and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   At the Beasley home on U.S. 80 heading into town, boards covered
every window and two-by-fours were wedged against the front door.
But as Norma and James Beasley fortified their house Tuesday
morning, Norma's mother had a stroke, and the couple had to rush
her to the hospital, where doctors don't expect her to live.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as they tried to leave town, their truck wouldn't start,
and they were delayed in getting out of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a hell of a day,'' James Beasley said while loading
the couple's other car with their most valuable possessions,
including a framed will from the 1600s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what we'll have when we come back,'' Norma
Beasley said, standing in her driveway, the road in front of her
house jammed with cars moving inch by inch from the coast. ``We may
not have anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Judd writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. David Pendered , Craig Schneider and Brad Schrade contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
