<HEADER>
A2126 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-UNREST-ART-(TR     09-14 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-UNREST-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW SEES BOMBING SCAPEGOAT AS SECURITY SWEEP TARGETS CAUCASIAN
NATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ With two apartment buildings leveled by explosions in
recent days, many Russians are afraid to go into their apartments
at night. But many people from the Caucasus are now afraid to leave
theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Literally overnight, the city's thousands of dark-complexioned
natives of Dagestan, Chechnya, Ingushetia and other regions of the
Caucasus Mountains, Muslim or Christian, have become suspects _ and
potential scapegoats _ in Russia's reaction to the suspected
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of encountering the bullying police or suspicious
neighbors, they only venture outside for quick trips to buy food.
Shut in, they work their phones, talking to other friends,
ferreting out facts and rumors about the authorities' plans to deal
with its undesirables.
</P>
<P>
   But even staying inside is no guarantee of security. Aishat, a
39-year-old Chechen, thought she was safe until a rap on her door
Tuesday morning. A handsome woman with a genial manner, Aishat had
brought her two young sons to Moscow to escape the turmoil in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Moscow police demanded to see her official residency
permit. When she was unable to produce one, they gave her three
days to come up with the documents or leave town.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Chechen would have have carried out these bombings,'' said
Aishat, who allowed only her first name to be used. ``Whoever did
this made our situation much, much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with the death count from the blasts on Monday and last
Thursday at more than 210, people from the Caucasus have plenty of
reason to be worried. When Vremechko, a popular late-night talk
show, asked its viewers Tuesday night what should be done to end
terrorist threats to the capital, more than 1,000 quickly called in
with their recommendation: All people from the Caucasus should be
deported from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Graffiti urging citizens to ``Kill the blacks,'' Russians' slur
for the dark-skinned people from the Caucasus, have turned up in
subway stations and alleyways.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin has urged citizens not to turn the
terrorist attacks into a racist crusade. The enemy, Yeltsin said in
a nationally televised address on Monday, ``has no face,
nationality or faith.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all Russian politicians have been so conscientious.
After blaming Islamic militants for the blast, Moscow's mayor, Yuri
Luzhkov, proclaimed that all visitors to the city would have to
re-register within the next three days.
</P>
<P>
   The move was largely aimed at Caucasians, who number in the
hundreds of thousands and who, more often than not, have lived in
Moscow without residency permits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main threat is coming from Chechnya,'' Luzhkov said.
``Special attention will be paid to visitors from that republic and
to cargo arriving from Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Moscow authorities began to carry out Luzhkov's policy.
More than 4,200 people from the northern Caucasus, including many
from Chechnya, were stopped by the police and asked to show their
official documents. Many did not have any.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the bombings, the police had monitored the major
entry points to the city and stopped people who looked like they
were from the Caucasus for random document checks, which often
turned into little more than an opportunity to extract bribes.
</P>
<P>
   But those inspections were stepped up Tuesday. People were
checked at Moscow's Vnukovo airport, where planes from the northern
Caucasus arrive. At the Paveletsky railway station, the train from
Makhachkala, Dagestan was met by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   One Russian woman who telephoned the host of Vremechko Tuesday
night complained that that the crackdown on Caucasians getting out
of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Moscow, we are considered half-Caucasian,'' she said. ``But
if go to the northern Caucasus they consider us half-Slav. Millions
of people live this kind of life. We are facing a new hatred that
nobody needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Aishat, the woman from Chechnya, does not look remotely like a
terrorist. She had lived in Grozny, the capital of the Chechen
republic, Until her house was leveled in the 1994-96 war between
secessionist rebels and Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   For a while after that, she lived with her parents in a small
village near the town of Urus-Martan. But life there was hard for
her sons, Abubakar and Ilyes.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   School was in session, but little learning went on. Teachers
were not paid and the school had no heat because people were afraid
to venture into the mine-filled forests to look for firewood.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   So Aishat and her sons came to Moscow, moving into a two-room
apartment owned by a close relative. About 30,000 Chechens live in
the Moscow area, according to one local Chechen leader.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Under the Russian Constitution, each citizen is supposed to be
able to live where he wants. But Luzhkov has insisted on a
registration system that is essentially a continuation of the old
Soviet system that required residents to have a permit to live in
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Many Chechens know it is difficult for them to obtain the
documents and so live in Moscow without them. They suffer from a
constant fear of eviction, an anxiety heightened by memories of
Stalin's deportation of the Chechen people from their homeland in
1944.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even before the latest explosions, Aishat said she was harassed
by the police. But the blasts that demolished the apartment
buildings have exacerbated her situation.
</P>
<P>
   Her youngest son was sent home from school Tuesday with a note
from the principal, a kind woman who had been sympathetic in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   With a citywide crackdown under way, the principal warned that
the boy would have to be expelled from school unless Aishat
furnished a residency permit.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday morning, the police came knocking at her door of her
modest fifth-floor walk-up apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to impress the police, Aishat showed a brochure from an
American charitable organization _ the Gift of Life _ which had
arranged for her son to go to New York for heart surgery. Her
family had come to Moscow, she insisted, so that her invalid son
could continue his medical treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The police still demanded that she pay a 10 ruble fine (about 40
cents in U.S. currency) and produce a residency permit within three
days.
</P>
<P>
   With little time, few contacts and no ability to travel freely
within Moscow, Aishat said she had no idea how she might prevail.
Perhaps the police would let her buy some more time by paying yet
another fine. Perhaps they would evict her and all of her Chechen
friends from the city.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Despite her distress, she welcomed a visitor in her apartment,
laid out a table of eggplant, tomatoes and honey from Chechnya and
pulled out a treasured album of photos.
</P>
<P>
   One photograph showed her in front of her parents' home in
Chechnya. The smiling women were wearing colorful scarves.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the custom for Muslim women in the Caucasus,'' she
explained matter-of-factly. ``We can't do it here. It would attract
too much attention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
