<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2127 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-REPUBS-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      09-14 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE GOP COOL ON ITS PATIENTS' RIGHTS PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Ariz., Va., Ga., Mich., Ohio)  (bl) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders, who directed junior
members of the party to draft a bill defining patients' rights just
five weeks ago, criticized the results of that effort Tuesday,
saying the bill could expose health maintenance organizations to
costly lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   If House Republicans have any strategy for dealing with the
volatile issue of patients' rights, it was not evident when they
finished an hourlong meeting Tuesday in the office of Speaker
Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 6, just before lawmakers left for the summer recess,
Hastert said that ``a proposal developed by Congressmen Tom Coburn
and John Shadegg will be considered by the House this September.''
Under the bill, he said then, patients could appeal the denial of
care to an independent panel of medical experts, and ``HMOs can be
taken to court and held accountable when patients are harmed.''
</P>
<P>
   When Coburn, a physician from Oklahoma, and Shadegg, a lawyer
from Arizona, disclosed the text of their bill last Thursday,
Hastert had no comment. Senior House Republicans, including the
chairmen of several committees and subcommittees, expressed grave
reservations about the bill Tuesday as they emerged from a meeting
with Hastert and the sponsors of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Dick Armey described the bill as ``the least
worst way to do the wrong thing.'' Provisions of the bill
authorizing patients to sue HMOs for injuries caused by the
negligence of a health plan ``still bother me,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., chairman of the House Commerce
Committee, said he, too, was reluctant to create a new right to
sue. ``I'm for care, not for court,'' said after Tuesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn said, ``The leadership is divided on what they think
should be in the bill.'' The reason, he said, is a disagreement
over the proper degree of legal liability for HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Health plans, insurance companies, Senate Republicans and
businesses of all sizes oppose any new right for patients to sue.
But Coburn said: ``It's unrealistic to think a bill will pass the
House that doesn't have liability as a mechanism to hold health
plans accountable. Whatever passes the House is going to have some
form of liability.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 40 of the 222 House Republicans and almost all 211
House Democrats favor some form of HMO liability. Republican
leaders acknowledge that they probably need some such provision to
keep Republicans from supporting Democratic bills that impose much
more government regulation than most Republicans want.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't beat something with nothing,'' Shadegg said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who attended Tuesday's meeting said party leaders
did not repudiate the Coburn-Shadegg bill, but intend to keep
working with the sponsors to devise a measure with broader appeal
to House Republicans. ``The feeling in the meeting was that they
should continue to work together and move the process forward,''
said John Feehery, a spokesman for Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   The Coburn-Shadegg bill was conceived as an alternative to a
proposal drafted by Reps. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., and John Dingell,
D-Mich., who have long insisted that patients should be able to sue
their health plans for injuries.
</P>
<P>
   While authorizing lawsuits against HMOs, Coburn and Shadegg are
trying to protect employers, who under their bill could be sued
only if they directly participated in final decisions on claims for
benefits. But Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio, shares the concern of
employers who believe that they would still be exposed to lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   David Schnittger, a spokesman for Boehner, said: ``In practice,
it's very difficult to guarantee that employers would be shielded
from that liability. That's a serious concern because it could
prompt some employers to drop health coverage for their employees
at the very time we're trying to expand access.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-GEORGE-COLUMN-COX     09-14 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GEORGE-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cherish Dan Marino, before it's our turn to bid farewell to
legendary QB
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ All right, so maybe the rain was blowing
sideways in South Florida on Tuesday night with the passing of a
hurricane. It's in Denver that the sky is falling.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this sampling of the mournful Colorado newspaper
coverage from Miami's 38-21 win against the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end is not near. It is here,'' that's how one Denver Post
columnist began his analysis. ``Poof. The magic's gone,'' wrote
another.
</P>
<P>
   One game into the season and the two-time Super Bowl champions
are kaput. From a Rocky Mountain high to a landfill low, and all
because John Elway is pitching beer as a private citizen this
September rather than tossing footballs as a Hall of Fame
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there were a moment to get through to all the Dan Marino
bashers, this is it. What's happening in Denver is a preview of the
daze that will envelop our own community the day the Dolphins say
goodbye to their legendary passer. Only then, after nearly two
decades of certainty at quarterback, will we fully appreciate the
luxury of an old hand in charge of the Miami offense rather than
one of the rookies or retreads most NFL teams depend upon.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the same nagging doubts resurface at the final gun of
every Miami loss.
</P>
<P>
   Could the Dolphins' Super Bowl blueprint be missing a mobile
quarterback and nothing more?
</P>
<P>
   Can any Miami coach, fidgety Jimmy Johnson included, ever fully
commit to a balanced offensive attack as long as Marino looms over
the huddle?
</P>
<P>
   Might the average busload of senior citizens unloading at the
mall yield several candidates capable of handing off a football
with more speed and less deliberation than creaky, old No. 13?
</P>
<P>
   Be honest. In the opening minutes of Monday night's game, with
Brian Griese hitting on a 61-yard touchdown bomb and Marino tossing
ill-advised passes off the fingertips of Denver defenders, many of
you were asking questions much harsher than these.
</P>
<P>
   The kid did look good, far more composed than anyone but proud
papa Bob Griese could have guessed. Without a strong running game,
however, and without a dominating effort by the Denver defense,
Elway himself would have been hard pressed to make a closer game of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone remember how futile Elway's record-breaking efforts
were before Terrell Davis got to Denver? Elway's Broncos lost three
lopsided Super Bowls before the glorious finishing kick of
championship victories against Green Bay and Atlanta changed his
image as a regal runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   Even in last season's humiliating 38-3 loss to Denver in the AFC
playoffs, the quarterbacks were a relatively minor factor. Elway
hit a fourth-quarter touchdown pass, long after the matter was
decided, but it was Davis who set the brutal tone of the game by
rushing for 199 yards, the most allowed by Miami in a post-season
game.
</P>
<P>
   Marino threw two touchdown passes Monday night, neither
particularly spectacular, but what made him an easy winner on John
Elway appreciation night at Mile High Stadium were the
contributions of Jimmy's new offensive components.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk Tony Martin up for 101 yards in receptions, including a
40-yarder, and rookie fullback Ron Konrad for a touchdown catch.
Running back J.J. Johnson, the second-round pick everyone forgot,
ran hard. Cecil Collins, the summer sensation with the dangerous
past, hasn't even suited up.
</P>
<P>
   These are the people Marino will utilize in 1999, and he'll do
it as efficiently as Griese did at the Dolphins' Super Bowl peak.
There is an opening here. The Jets have lost Vinny Testaverde for
the season. Fred Taylor is clopping around the Jaguars' camp with a
cast on his left foot. As for the Broncos, well, according to
published reports the end is here.
</P>
<P>
   Only Marino can make the most of all this. Not Damon Huard, who
has attempted nine NFL passes. Not Craig Erickson, whom Johnson cut
loose in training camp after three seasons of grooming him as
Marino's successor.
</P>
<P>
   Elway's emotional farewell Monday proved the unmatched power of
a truly classic quarterback. One day Marino's retirement will prove
it again, even to those who wonder if he's not already about five
years overdue.
</P>
<P>
   Dave George writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
