<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2131 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-FUNDRAISING-     09-14 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-FUNDRAISING-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE COALITION DEFEATS AMENDMENTS AIMED AT WEAKENING CAMPAIGN
BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defying the Republican leadership, a bipartisan
coalition of House members picked up momentum on Tuesday night in
the drive to overhaul the way the nation's political campaigns are
financed by defeating a series of amendments that they said would
doom the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The votes came as the House engaged in an all-day debate over
the influence of money in politics that pit bipartisan legislation
sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Martin Meehan,
D-Mass., against three rival bills and 10 amendments.
</P>
<P>
   By evening, Shays and Meehan were holding their coalition
together and handily defeated a series of amendments that they had
said were designed to splinter their ranks and weaken their
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The defeated measures would have done things like raise current
contribution limits or exempt from regulation ads on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The House did pass, 261 to 167, an amendment that was aimed
squarely at Hillary Rodham Clinton, but which sponsors did not
consider significant enough to kill their bill. It would require
the first lady to pay the full costs of any governmental travel to
New York during a Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's looking good,'' said Shays, as his supporters grew
optimistic that the House would approve for the second year in a
row legislation to ban the unlimited and unregulated donations to
the national political parties that figured prominently in the
scandals arising out of the 1996 presidential election. These
donations are commonly called ``soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers clashed repeatedly over whether the influx of money
into campaigns was corrupting Congress or whether it was essential
to free political speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reach and influence of special interests have grown out of
control,'' said Rep. Marge Roukema of New Jersey, one of many
Republicans to cross their leadership and support the bipartisan
bill. ``As a consequence, people believe their elected officials
are bought and paid for.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., said that the legislation could not
face constitutional muster. ``It tromps all over people's
individual First Amendment freedoms,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   In the the Senate last year, the Shays-Meehan legislation drew a
majority of 52 votes last year but then died in a Republican-led
filibuster. The opposition has carried over into this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that there are the votes to pass any bill,''
Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the Senate majority whip said, on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue is volatile, and it is not clear whether the
looming 2000 campaigns will cause any change in the dynamics. The
debate comes at a moment when the 2000 races are well underway and
provide a new barometer of how the public will respond to money in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side of the presidential campaign, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, who has amassed a $50 million campaign fund, has
declared that he will not accept federal matching money. Steve
Forbes, the multimillionaire publisher is also forgoing federal
money. Those decisions leave both men unrestricted by a $40 million
spending limit that applies to candidates who accept matching funds
in the primaries, a cap that was a bulwark of the post-Watergate
campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is the chief sponsor of the
Senate legislation to ban soft money, has put his crusade at the
center of his own uphill presidential bid. He has called the
current campaign system ``an elaborate influence peddling scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, former Sen. Bill Bradley, who is seeking the
Democratic nomination, has pledged that he would refuse soft money
in 2000 if the Republicans would also do so, saying big money is at
the root of multiple problems in American politics.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan legislation would ban ``soft money,'' which
both parties have used to circumvent the limits on contributions to
individual candidates that were enacted in the wake of the
Watergate scandal of the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   It would also curb the increasingly popular practice, used by
independent advocacy groups and the the political parties
themselves, of running commercials that purport to explain an issue
but are thinly veiled campaign commercials attacking or supporting
a candidate. The bill would more strictly regulate such ads in the
60 days before an election.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIMS STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The question of how to overhaul the campaign finance system has
dogged Congress for years but became particularly heated after the
1996 campaign, in which President Clinton aggressively used access
to the White House to raise funds. The Democratic National
Committee also gave back several million dollars in campaign funds
after disclosures that they had come from foreign nationals or were
of questionable legality.
</P>
<P>
   But despite holding a series of high-profile hearings into the
1996 campaign, the Republican leaders in Congress have staunchly
opposed the move to ban soft money, arguing publicly it would
weaken political parties and harm free speech.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, in a closed door meeting for House Republicans,
party leaders were more blunt. Republicans said their party
chairman, Jim Nicholson, and Rep. Thomas M. Davis III, who is head
of the House Republicans' re-election effort, told lawmakers their
party held a $39.9 million advantage in soft money in the 1997-1998
election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Through a long day and into the night, House members argued over
the money chase that they have come to know so well. Shays insisted
his legislation would close loopholes that had come over time come
to erode long-standing fund-raising restrictions enacted by
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about ending corrupt politics,'' he said, ''that's what
it's about. It has been against the law since 1907 for corporate
treasury money to be used in campaigns. But it happens. It's been
against the law since 1947 for union dues money to be used in
campaigns. But it's happening. It's been against the law since 1974
for foreign nationals to contribute to campaigns but they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the bill spoke out against regulation and said its
restrictions on issue advocacy infringed on the First Amendment.
``Free speech, particularly free political speech is a cherished
right and shrine in the first amendment to our constitution,'' said
Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif. ``For democracy to flourish a free
people must be able to express their political views without
government restriction.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt, the House minority leader, added a partisan
tone to the debate when he accused the Republican majority of being
in the sway of special interests on issues ranging from health care
to tax cuts to gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all seen what being bound to big money from the
special interests has done to the Republican legislative agenda,''
he said. ``Republican leaders put the needs of powerful lobbyists
ahead of the average family and their needs.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan legislation was only one of several rival
measures under consideration today. Under the established
procedures, passage of any of the other measures would serve to
trump the bipartisan legislation.
</P>
<P>
   One measure sponsored by Rep. Asa Hutchinson, an Arkansas
Republican, would ban soft money donations to the national
political parties but not to the state parties. Another measure
sponsored by Rep. John Doolittle, R-Calif., would eliminate all
current federal contributions limits, eliminate public financing of
campaigns and require immediate disclosure of contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas of California was sponsoring a third, noncontroversial
measure to strengthen and streamline the powers of the Federal
Election Commission. Shays and Meehan were fighting it on grounds
that its passage and would kill their own measure. Thomas argued
that the Shays-Meehan bill would never become law and that his FEC
bill might prevail in the Senate. ``I believe if you take smaller
steps in a cooperative way then you can take bigger ones,'' he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition, the Shays-Meehan supporters faced 10 attempts to
amend their bill. They fought off the seven provisions they
believed would have been deadly to the legislation. But one
amendment that passed was all about the New York Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by Rep. John Sweeney, R-N.Y., with Mrs. Clinton in
mind, it would require ``a candidate for election for Federal
office (other than a candidate who holds Federal office)'' to
reimburse the government for free federal transportation used for
campaign purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said his measure ``remedies an unfair advantage.'' Rep.
Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., called the measure ``a mean-spirited,
petty, politically charged amendment'' and asked why local
officials running for federal office should not also be required to
reimburse states or cities for transportation or for providing
security.
</P>
</TEXT>
