<HEADER>
A2136 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      09-14 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL SHARES DEPRESS DOW; TECHNOLOGY BUOYS NASDAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices were mixed Tuesday, as fears of rising
interest rates continued to deter investors.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was dominated by a government report on retail sales
that showed consumers were much more active buyers last month than
analysts had thought.
</P>
<P>
   The report sent shivers through the bond market, where interest
rates rose, and it further depressed prices of financial services
stocks. Insurance stocks, which are not helped when rates climb,
were weakened further by worries that the advance of Hurricane
Floyd suggested big damage claims in the making.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago these sales figures wouldn't have caused a
ripple,'' said Bill Allyn, head of listed trading at Jefferies &AMP;
Co. ``But it is very difficult to invest more when there is so much
uncertainty about the course of interest rates and the dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Selling Tuesday was most heavily concentrated among blue-chip
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Led by J.P. Morgan, which fell 2 13/16, to 122, the Dow Jones
industrial average lost 120 points, or 1.09 percent, closing at
10,910.33. General Electric, parent company of GE Capital, lost 1
13/16, to 116 3/4. And American Express dropped 7/8, to 139 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   With financial and drug company shares weakened, the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index also lost ground, falling 7.84 points, or
0.58 percent, to 1,336.29.
</P>
<P>
   Worries about an overly vigorous economy and rising rates did
not dampen demand for technology shares, however. The NASDAQ
composite index gained 23.52 points, or 0.83 percent, to 2,868.29,
led by Qualcomm, which gained 17 1/8, to 170 1/2. Qualcomm, which
makes cellular phones, said it would meet or exceed fourth-quarter
profit estimates, reassuring investors, who had sent the company's
shares down sharply on Monday after it pulled out of an investor
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Other technology stalwarts also rose, further lifting the NASDAQ
average. Microsoft was up 1 3/16, to 95 1/16. Intel gained 1 7/16,
to 85 13/16. And Cisco Systems rose 1 1/4, to 71 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   The ferocity of Hurricane Floyd created some anxiety about
insurers. But analysts said that by and large the industry was in
far better shape to handle a disaster than in August 1992, when
Hurricane Andrew ripped through South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowner insurers, which potentially face the biggest claims,
suffered Tuesday. Allstate dropped 1 7/16, to 32 1/8. Hartford
Financial lost 1 5/16, to 46 15/16. And St. Paul Cos. fell 1, to 31
5/8.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market's reaction was rational,'' said Alice Schroeder of
Paine Webber. ``We do expect that the storm will result in reduced
earnings this quarter, but we just don't know by how much. However,
it is a one-time event and will not affect next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Cohen, a Merrill Lynch insurance analyst, said that ``when
Andrew hit, the level of equity capital for the industry was about
$160 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he said, ``that figure is just over $340 billion. Floyd
would have to have an absolutely enormous impact to have an effect
on the industry as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, entertainment analysts said that Walt Disney Co.'s
decision to close Disney World for the first time in 27 years
should not have a tangible financial effect. The company plans to
keep the park closed for the next two days. The Disney World
hotels, which are fully booked, remain open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will be material to earnings,'' said Jill
Krutick of Salomon Smith Barney, although she said her assessment
could change if there was severe hurricane damage to the Orlando,
Fla., property.
</P>
<P>
   Investors did not seem much concerned: Disney shares, which have
been under pressure for about a year, closed at 27 15/16, down 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   And news that airlines were canceling flights in and out of
Miami did not dissuade buyers of airline stocks. AMR, the parent of
American Airlines, gained 1/4, to 55 1/8. Delta Air Lines rose 1/2,
to 50 5/8. And UAL, parent of United Airlines, was up 1 1/4, to 68
1/8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weather hurts the airlines, whether it is a blizzard or a
hurricane,'' said Glenn Engel, an analyst at Goldman, Sachs. ``But
they are vulnerable to everything, from weather to a change in oil
prices to a change in fares.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final analysis, Al Goldman, chief market strategist at
A.G. Edwards in St. Louis, said investors remained more concerned
about a man-made threat _ higher interest rates _ than about a
possible natural disaster. ``Hurricanes come and go, and people
generally look beyond them,'' Goldman said. ``Rising interest rates
hit you right between the eyes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
