<HEADER>
A2139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-PRICING-BOS &LR;      09-14 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PRICING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRONIC PRICING WOULD SAVE MONEY, CONSUMER OFFICIAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Massachusetts' top consumer official says the accuracy
of grocery prices would improve if the Legislature allowed
supermarkets to substitute electronic shelf labels for the
labor-intensive process of stamping prices on individual store
items.
</P>
<P>
   Supermarket industry officials said the recommendation by
consumer affairs director Daniel A. Grabauskas should give a major
boost to their nearly decade-long campaign to eliminate food-store
item pricing, but a key lawmaker predicted changes would probably
be more evolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Peter J. Larkin of Pittsfield, a Democrat who
heads the Legislature's Commerce and Labor Committee, said the
panel sees benefits from item pricing. He said a bill will probably
emerge from committee soon that would exempt far more products from
the item-pricing law if a supermarket installs electronic shelf
labels.
</P>
<P>
   Grabauskas said his recommendation was not easy to make and that
he waffled during the course of the state's year-long study of the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to Larkin and the committee's cochairman, Senator
Stephen F. Lynch of South Boston, Grabauskas said the current law
has been effective but also cumbersome and fraught with human
errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Price accuracy is consumers' No. 1 concern,'' he said in an
interview. ``I think this addresses that No. 1 concern in a way
that really is better than the current system.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates, some of whom participated in the study, said
Tuesday they disagreed with Grabauskas's conclusions and would work
to block passage of any law weakening the item-pricing statute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers potentially will be losing an important tool to help
them shop more wisely,'' said consumer advocate Edgar Dworsky, who
wrote the current law in 1987 when he worked for the state's
consumer affairs office.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is one of five states in the nation with a food
store item-pricing law. Separate regulations promulgated close to
30 years ago by the attorney general's office require item pricing
by other Massachusetts retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the day the food store item-pricing law passed,
supermarket officials have grumbled about the difficulty of trying
to make sure that prices on items, on shelf tags, and at checkout
scanners all match. The officials have said employees who stamp
prices on store items could serve customers better working
elsewhere in the store.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic shelf tags, which cost a supermarket about $125,000
to install, theoretically would eliminate most pricing errors. The
systems allow a supermarket to input prices tied to product bar
codes into a store computer and the computer posts the same price
at the shelf and checkout scanner. The only way a pricing error can
occur is if a price is inputted incorrectly or listed incorrectly
in the store's advertising circular.
</P>
<P>
   The state's study found 100 percent price accuracy for the items
where electronic shelf tags were used. ``This backs up what we've
been saying all along,'' said Christopher Flynn, president of the
Massachusetts Food Association, which represents supermarkets in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   But Dworsky said most supermarkets already achieve 98 percent
price accuracy, so electronic shelf tags represent ``a solution to
a problem that doesn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   A state survey of 556 shoppers found that 47 percent would
approve a change to electronic shelf labels at the expense of
individual price stickers, 27 percent opposed it, 22 percent had no
preference, and 4 percent were unsure.
</P>
<P>
   Dworsky and Deirdre Cummings, consumer program director at the
Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group, said research has
shown that consumers prefer to check prices by looking at stickers
on grocery items rather than hunting for shelf tags with
hard-to-read product abbreviations.
</P>
<P>
   The stickers also make it easy to double-check price accuracy at
the checkout and after leaving the store. They also help consumers
add up the cost of what they have put in their shopping basket and
help build consciousness about what items cost.
</P>
<P>
   Grabauskas, who takes the top job at the Registry of Motor
Vehicles on Monday, urged the Legislature to exempt supermarkets
that install electronic shelf tags from the item-pricing law as
long as a number of safeguards are included. For example, he said
the Legislature should require supermarkets to provide grease
pencils so consumers can mark prices on purchases and make
available aisle scanners enabling consumers to check the price of
an item anywhere in the store.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter Tuesday, Grabauskas also said the supermarkets had
agreed to verify that no employees would lose their jobs because of
electronic shelf tags and to have the state double the penalty for
pricing errors to $200 per violation with a maximum of $5,000 per
inspection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
