<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2141 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SATURDAY-NIGHT-LIVE-3     09-14 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATURDAY-NIGHT-LIVE-3TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMEDY INSTITUTION JUST KEEPS ON GOING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty-Five years used to be considered a long time, the events
of the quarter-century before taking on the sepia tinge of ancient
history.
</P>
<P>
   Children who attended the New York World's Fair in 1964 heard
from their parents about the ``old'' World's Fair, with its
glimpses of all kinds of futuristic inventions, even a thing called
television. That fair took place before Pearl Harbor, even before
the invasion of Poland. It was in 1939, exactly 25 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same in the entertainment world. Twenty-five years
before comics like Jack Benny and Bob Hope were stars of 1950s
television, they were in vaudeville. And 25 years before James Dean
defined a certain kind of hip American culture in ``Rebel Without a
Cause,'' the movies had just stopped being silent. Silent!
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in popular culture can be hip for 25 years. The culture
turns over far too many times. Icons become relics; objects of
obsession become objects of nostalgia. So what are we to make of
``Saturday Night Live''? The one-time groundbreaking,
precedent-setting, establishment-tweaking comedy sketch show begins
a decidedly well-established 25th season on NBC next week, to be
celebrated by a two-and-a-half-hour prime-time special next Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Longevity is certainly not in itself a claim on pop cultural
relevance. Other shows have been on longer but are in no danger of
being labeled hip (e.g., ``The Price Is Right''). But, apparently
in defiance of both time and show business convention, ``SNL''
begins a 25th year still the most pervasive influence on the art of
comedy in contemporary culture.
</P>
<P>
   For proof, look no further than the summer movie grosses. The
dominant stars? Mike Myers, Adam Sandler, Steve Martin and Eddie
Murphy, a collection of comics with roots deep in ``SNL'' soil. In
the wings is what is expected to be one of the year's biggest
movies, ``Man in the Moon,'' starring Jim Carrey as the comic Andy
Kaufman. It contains numerous scenes recreating the early days of
``SNL,'' including Kaufman's memorable ``Mighty Mouse'' performance
on the show's premiere.
</P>
<P>
   Two more movies based on ``SNL'' characters are in the works:
``Superstar,'' featuring the Catholic school girl Mary Katherine
Gallagher (played by Molly Shannon), opens on Oct. 8, and ``The
Ladies' Man'' (Tim Meadows) was filmed over the summer in Canada.
Other ``SNL'' alumni are firmly established stars of movie comedy:
Bill Murray, Chevy Chase, Dan Aykroyd, Billy Crystal. Former
``SNL'' performers like David Spade, Norm Macdonald, Jane Curtin,
Dennis Miller, Martin Short, Julia Louis-Dreyfus, Chris Rock and
Conan O'Brien (he was actually an ``SNL'' writer) are all over
television. You can even get into a New York cab and hear Al
Franken's voice urging you to buckle up.
</P>
<P>
   There is a continuum at work, a comedy continuum that has
consistently defied the sell-by date that eventually undoes even
the hugest television hits.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of this continuum is the creator, first producer,
one-time defector, but forever the man most responsible for the
phenomenon that has been ``Saturday Night Live'': Lorne Michaels.
Michaels still occupies the office in New York City's Rockefeller
Center, nine floors above Studio 8H in what is now the GE Building,
that he first moved into in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Cast members and writers have no trouble identifying Michaels'
central role in the making of this epic. ``Lorne is the
godfather,'' said Chris Rock. ``Like Paulie in `Goodfellas.' You
have to give him respect.'' Which, he said, he is happy to do. ``I
have never been broke a day in my life since I met Lorne
Michaels,'' Rock said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Smigel, one of the show's chief writers in the 1980s,
said: ``Lorne has done the most amazing job. His eye for comedic
actors is just the best anyone has ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels himself, famously nonlinear, has no specific
explanations for how the show has persevered, becoming in the
process a kind of elite university. Indeed, Rock called the show
``the Harvard of comedy.'' It certainly has distinguished alumni,
honored dead and some of the toughest entrance criteria imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels said: ``I was given an opportunity or I took an
opportunity to create a place where a lot of people got to work and
where it was safe to work. The value system here was always about
the work and the writing and performing.'' But there are clearly
some reasons this show, more than any other, has survived the
challenges of time and network programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Topicality is part of it,'' Michaels said. ``Having a
different host every week is part of it.'' A bigger part of the
explanation, perhaps, is what Michaels called ``its complete
unpredictability.''
</P>
<P>
   One evidence of that is the way the entire cast has turned over
several times. Or as Smigel put it, ``Ed Sullivan isn't coming out
there every week introducing the regulars, Harvey Korman and Tim
Conway.'' Instead, a movie star, a political figure, a sports star,
even an occasional television executive turns up and throws himself
or herself into a series of hastily written comedy sketches,
performed by a frequently recast repertory group of comedians. Oh,
and it's all live.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear all these other shows talking about their special
episodes: they're going to do `E.R.' live,'' said Jimmy Fallon, one
of the show's fast-rising new stars. ``We do it every week live!''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Smigel said ``SNL'' had defied the standard exhaustion that
swallows up all other hit shows because ``it's not a show; it's a
format.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All those times it's been written off as `Saturday Night
Dead,' people miss the point,'' he added. ``The format doesn't get
tired. It can be revived.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the history of the show is one of parabolas made up of
surges of popularity and derision. The same is true of almost every
individual show: peaks of hilarity between valleys of near-dead
air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to say that `uneven' should be inscribed on my
tombstone,'' Michaels said. ``Uneven is how the show has been
described consistently. As if 90 minutes of blank page to
on-the-air is going to be seamlessly funny.'' Still, the show has
clearly gone through a number of specific eras, a few of them rocky
enough that contemplating a life span of 25 years would have been
the biggest joke of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The first era remains the most famous, of course, remembered,
like most cultural breakthoughs, with enormous affection and very
selectively. Certainly the show burst onto the television scene
with a creativity and energy that were unlike anything the medium
had previously seen.
</P>
<P>
   In a bit of spectacular prescience, Dick Ebersol, the young NBC
executive in charge of late-night programming, plucked Michaels to
guide the new show. He had an interesting, if not overwhelming,
resume, having produced specials for Lily Tomlin and written for
``Laugh-In.'' He had also been a performer in a comedy team in his
native Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But what mostly qualified Michaels for the job was his hunger to
make a show for an audience like him, one that had never been
served anything truly original that spoke to their taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a moment when I doubted it would be a hit,''
Michaels said. ``If I could just get it on the air. We were the
last period where there was no cable alternative. We were defining
late night as the alternative. And because it was live, when the
audience saw it and the network saw it, it was already formed. We
were from the audience and we were doing a show that we wanted to
watch. We had a unity of taste.''
</P>
<P>
   The show in the early years wasn't just funny; it was
subversive, almost dangerous. Michael O'Donoghue, one of the
best-known early writers, ``thought Dan Aykroyd was like rough
trade; he was afraid of him,'' said Michaels. The subversiveness
was symbolized by Chevy Chase's imitation of President Gerald Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got so used to Chevy not making any attempt to look or sound
like this guy,'' Michaels said. ``That to me seemed so hip and
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The stars of that first era _ Aykroyd, Chase, John Belushi,
Gilda Radner, Bill Murray _ grew so big so fast that it almost
doomed the show. When Michaels and the last of the original cast
members left in 1980 (and he acknowledged that they all wanted
``SNL'' to die right then and there), NBC turned the show over to
Jean Doumanian, a producer now closely associated with Woody Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Her one, turbulent year is remembered mostly as a disaster,
although as Smigel pointed out, ``She brought on Eddie Murphy and
he's probably the biggest star ever to emerge from the show.''
</P>
<P>
   In desperation, NBC turned to Ebersol, the former late-night
executive, who took over as producer in 1981. He shrewdly built a
new edition of the show, principally around Murphy and Joe Piscopo.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years some significant talent slipped through the show
because they never found their own voice. Many were women, who
suffered from the image of the show as, in Piscopo's words, ``a
boy's club.'' That male-centric view of the show held until
recently; Smigel called the three current women _ Molly Shannon,
Cheri Oteri and Ana Gasteyer _ ``surely the three best women the
show has ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   But among the talented women who filtered through the show
making little impression were Joan Cusack, Julia Louis-Dreyfus and
Janeane Garofalo.
</P>
<P>
   Piscopo said Ebersol made another shrewd decision when he
arrived in 1980; he moved away from the subversiveness. ``Dick
would go through the magazines like People and see who was hot,''
Piscopo said. ``Then he'd say we should have Robert Urich on. Or
Robert Blake, who was great. Dick mainstreamed the show. And it
worked.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last year as producer, having lost Murphy and Piscopo,
Ebersol came up with another effective idea. He stocked the cast
with established talents like Billy Crystal, Martin Short and
Christopher Guest. The result was, in Michaels' estimation, ``a
really great year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ebersol was done. Brandon Tartikoff, then running NBC's
programming (and a one-time host of the show himself), told
Michaels he was going to cancel the show unless Michaels took it
over _ but as an overseer, not the hands-on producer. He agreed,
bringing in an all-new cast that included Jon Lovitz, Dennis
Miller, Anthony Michael Hall and Robert Downey Jr. But the season
as a whole ``just didn't gel,'' as Michaels put it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the season Tartikoff again said he was ready to
pull the plug. But ``I fell in love with doing it again,'' said
Michaels. He couldn't let the show die. ``I told Brandon I thought
I could correct it. He said OK, but I couldn't delegate. What a
difference a year made!''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels kept half the cast, including Miller, who had taken
over the ``Weekend Update'' segment and made it the biggest hit
since Chevy Chase had left, and Lovitz, whose liar character had
become so big that it was referenced by politicians. As additions,
Michaels brought in Jan Hooks, Dana Carvey and Phil Hartman. The
show was reborn.
</P>
<P>
   The upward arc only soared further when Michaels added Mike
Myers, Chris Farley, Adam Sandler and David Spade. This time he
remade the show on the fly, adjusting as some of the more
experienced players left.
</P>
<P>
   Now Michaels saw a generational shift. The new performers were
younger and they started pulling in younger viewers. That was ideal
for NBC until the network started to think the show wasn't funny
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   A new barrage of criticism in the press hit the show. In 1995
NBC executives decided Sandler and Spade especially weren't funny,
Michaels said. ``Don Ohlmeyer wanted me just to go back to
basics,'' he said, referring to the president of NBC's West Coast
division at the time. ``Dynamite the thing and start again.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels was reluctant. ``I thought Adam was really, really
funny,'' he said. ``And David Spade. The network thought quite the
reverse. Every note was: `Fire David Spade.' He, of course, wound
up saving their season on `Just Shoot Me.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told to get rid of people,'' Michaels continued. ``Adam
Sandler was let go, and he had two years left on his contract.
Chris Farley had one year. And Chris Rock was in that cast.''
Michaels went back to the drawing board and introduced more than
half a dozen new cast members the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Few shows could survive the potential humiliation of dismissing
a talent like Sandler, who went on to become the hottest comedy
film star in America. ``SNL'' somehow turned this into another
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   The new cast, in the estimation of one of its longest-tenured
staff members, is ``full of outstanding talent, but Lorne doesn't
have the writing talent he needs to go with them.'' To add to the
challenge, Michaels said he would be replacing much of the cast for
the season that begins in fall 2000.
</P>
<P>
   One change that has clearly come over the show as it has aged _
matured might be the appropriate word _ is that it has lost some of
the danger that characterized the early years. Michaels himself has
gone mainstream enough to have been thrilled earlier this year when
he had a star engraved with his name on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   But not all of the old subversive spirit is gone. Last season,
without any advance publicity, ``SNL'' brought on Monica Lewinsky
as a special guest. And that wasn't even as far as Michaels had
wanted to go in stirring up sensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, is there any way to get O.J.? I just wanted to get
the two of them together in a photo because I thought they could
say to the audience, `We just took the last four years of your
lives.'''
</P>
<P>
   He never got as far as asking O.J. Simpson if he wanted to make
the splash. But every former guest host has been invited to return
for next Sunday's anniversary special, and, Michaels noted, Simpson
did serve as a guest host once.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the anniversary special, Michaels is gearing up for
another season, the wall board in his office crowded with index
cards of different colors, indicating confirmed hosts and musical
guests (green) and possibles (blue.) Jerry Seinfeld is green and
ready to be the host of the season-opening show on Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels spends his days much the same as he always has,
supervising writers, preparing shows. Young performers and writers
still hound him everywhere. ``Saturday Night Live'' is, maybe more
than ever, Mount Everest for young comedy talent.
</P>
<P>
   Piscopo said, ``I will always wear being on the show as a badge
of honor.'' Not every performer became a star, he said. Some, like
him, are just working actors today. Some have all but disappeared
from show business. (They're all invited back for the special,
however.)
</P>
<P>
   Chris Rock had similar feelings, though with a twist. ``I
watched the show as a kid and always dreamed of being the black guy
on `Saturday Night Live,''' he said. ``I was so happy when Lorne
told me I was on the show. I haven't been as happy since.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels has his own context for what the show has become, and
it connects to the issue of longevity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something was confirmed for me when I saw `Shakespeare in
Love,' the idea of a writer having a set of actors who did all his
stuff,'' he said. ``You just know Shakespeare had a big guy that
the audience liked. So after he was Falstaff in `Henry IV,'
suddenly he's in `Merry Wives of Windsor,' and you realize he had
to be held over.''
</P>
<P>
   Having once left, only to return to see his creation through to
the new millennium, Michaels now has no intention of ever walking
away from ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the synergy of the thing at its essence, that's the thing
I most love about it,'' Michaels said. ``You have designers,
musicians, directors, writers, all together in this act of putting
on a show. And it all just hurtles toward 11:30. I've said it often
before: It doesn't go on because it's ready. It goes on because
it's 11:30. It is exhilarating. And once you've had that high, it's
sort of hard to live without it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
