<SLUG> BC-FUELREGS-SUVS-ART-890(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR-BASED LIGHT TRUCK   OBEYS FUEL RULES, AND HELPS MAKE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Scheduled to go on sale next spring, the Chrysler PT
Cruiser is not quite a sport utility vehicle and not really a
minivan.
</P>
<P>
   It does not look like a conventional car, either, although it
uses much the same underbody and even a few of the same parts as
the Dodge Neon, which is definitely a car.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at DaimlerChrysler AG have decided that as far as
federal regulations are concerned, their lightweight, fuel-sipping
vehicle is a truck and not a car. ``We certainly are intending to
have this classified as a light truck,'' said Jan Zverina, a
DaimlerChrysler spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler has chosen to call the Cruiser a truck because
of breaks it can get under the complex system of separate federal
fuel economy standards for cars and light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Counting the Cruiser as a light truck stands to improve the
average fuel economy of the entire fleet of DaimlerChrysler's light
trucks, which include sport utility vehicles, minivans and pickups.
The more Cruisers that DaimlerChrysler sells, the more big,
high-profit sport utilities and pickups it can sell while still
meeting the gas mileage averages required by law.
</P>
<P>
   After heavy lobbying by the auto industry, the Senate is
expected on Wednesday to extend a four-year-old ban that prevents
the Clinton administration from studying or changing these
two-decade-old fuel economy regulations. Meanwhile, automakers are
preparing to introduce as many as two dozen vehicles with car-based
designs in the coming years and to ask that many of them to be
certified as light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Two car-based sport utility vehicles, the Toyota RAV-4 and the
Honda CR-V, have been on the market in limited numbers for two
years and are categorized as light trucks. BMW AG will start
selling its car-based sport utility vehicle, the X5, in December
and has asked that it be certified as a light truck. Next spring,
Ford Motor Co. will put on sale the Escape, a small sport utility
vehicle that is based on the Ford Contour compact sedan. And the
Cadillac, Buick, Pontiac, Saturn and Chevrolet divisions of General
Motors Corp. are all developing models that will combine car and
light truck features, although GM has not said when they will go on
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Auto executives say that Americans want automobiles that combine
the rugged appearance of a light truck with the handling and easy
access of a car. The new models are not being created for
fuel-economy reasons, said Lawrence Burns, GM's vice president for
planning, research and development. ``That is not the driving force
behind what we're doing here,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys show that with gasoline prices low, consumers care very
little about fuel economy. Yet as buyers have switched from cars to
light trucks, fuel economy has declined, increasing the nation's
dependence on imported oil and increasing emissions of gases that
many scientists have linked to global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Each automaker is required to produce a fleet of cars with an
average gas mileage of at least 27.5 miles a gallon. But
manufacturers are permitted to sell their fleets of light trucks
with average fuel efficiencies of just 20.7 miles a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The rules that govern whether automobiles are classified as cars
or light trucks have remained virtually unchanged since they were
first written in 1976, and they are riddled with loopholes. Current
and former regulators at the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, the federal agency that administers the
fuel-economy laws, say the agency has never challenged an
automaker's decision on whether to register an automobile as a car
or as a light truck.
</P>
<P>
   When Republicans took control of Congress in 1995 and began
trying to curb what they called regulatory excesses, one of the
first things they did was prohibit the Clinton administration from
spending any money even to study increases in fuel-economy
standards or changes in the fuel-economy rules. The House has
already voted this year to extend the prohibition for another year
as part of the federal budget; the Senate is scheduled to vote
Wednesday on a nonbinding resolution that would urge Senate budget
negotiators to remove the provision during conferences with House
leaders. That vote is expected to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have been lobbying hard for passage of the
Senate resolution, but the auto industry has fought back with
full-page newspaper advertisements and radio spots in nine states
and appears likely to prevail. The administration has sat on the
sidelines during the current debate.
</P>
<P>
   Even some auto executives acknowledge the shortcomings of the
current system. BMW, for example, has sold only cars until now, and
its executives had been very critical of the breaks that are
available for automakers who sell vehicles that qualify as light
trucks. But BMW changed that position when it developed the X5.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Doolan, BMW's president for North American operations
until he was hired by Ford a few weeks ago, said in an interview
early this year that he had decided to submit the X5 to regulators
as a truck primarily because of the preferential treatment afforded
light trucks under fuel-economy rules. ``That's the major reason:
Why should we pay punitive penalties that Mercedes and Lexus do
not'' on their sport utility vehicles? he said. ``It's the rules
that are wrong, not the way we play the game.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
