<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-RULING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING IN MOB IMMUNITY CASE EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Nearly a year after a parade of witnesses unmasked an
unholy alliance between the FBI and two of the region's most
notorious gangsters, a federal judge is expected to rule Wednesday
on whether the FBI promised to protect its prized informants from
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   In an eagerly awaited decision that could dismiss _ or at least
dilute _ criminal charges against organized crime figures, US
District Judge Mark L. Wolf will resolve the issue at the core of
exhaustive hearings held in his courtroom last year: Did the FBI
promise fugitive South Boston crime boss James J. ``Whitey'' Bulger
and his sidekick, Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi, immunity in
exchange for information about their Mafia rivals?
</P>
<P>
   If Wolf accepts Flemmi's claim that the FBI sanctioned his
criminal activities, then he could dismiss the January 1995 federal
racketeering indictment that charged Bulger and Flemmi with
colluding with the Mafia to control bookmaking, loan-sharking and
other rackets throughout New England.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi, reputed New England Mafia boss Francis ``Cadillac
Frank'' Salemme, reputed mob soldier Robert DeLuca and John
Martorano have been jailed since 1995 while awaiting trial. Bulger
remains a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Martorano agreed to plead guilty to the charges
and testify against Bulger and Flemmi if the case ever goes to
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf's voluminous ruling is expected to be a scathing indictment
of the FBI's handling of longtime informants Bulger and Flemmi, who
wined and dined with their FBI handlers while their crimes went
ignored and unpunished for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we proved is the FBI had a relationship with
Bulger and Flemmi that amounted essentially to them supporting an
organized criminal enterprise,'' said Attorney Anthony Cardinale,
who represents Salemme, 66, of Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Martin G. Weinberg, who represented Martorano until he
began cooperating with federal authorities, said: ``I think the
hearings demonstrated that for decades the FBI as an institution
ignored and violated the guidelines which governed their
relationship with high level, top-echelon informants.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, the FBI, rather than the Justice Department,
became the decision-maker as to when their informants should and
should not be prosecuted,'' Weinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers have asked Wolf to dismiss the indictment on the
grounds that the racketeering enterprise alleged in the indictment
doesn't exist because Bulger and Flemmi actually were working for
the government.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney John Mitchell, cocounsel for Salemme, said: ``Under
federal law you can't conspire with someone who doesn't have
bonafide criminal intent. If the guy is an undercover cop or an
informant, you can't conspire with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense also has asked Wolf to suppress FBI tapes of various
Mafia meetings _ including a 1989 Mob induction ceremony _ because
of alleged prosecutorial misconduct in obtaining the bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi, 65, who became an FBI informant in 1965, followed by
Bulger a decade later, testified that he and Bulger were given
permission by former FBI supervisor John Morris to commit any crime
short of murder in exchange for leaking information about the
activities of local Mafiosi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I was performing a service for the US government in
my role as an informant,'' Flemmi testified.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying under a grant of immunity, Morris denied authorizing
Flemmi to commit crimes, but stunned many former colleagues by
revealing that he pocketed $7,000 in payoffs from Bulger and Flemmi
between 1982 and 1988. He also admitted warning the pair that the
FBI had tapped the phone of a Roxbury bookmaker who worked for
them.
</P>
<P>
   In some of his most explosive testimony, Morris said he told
Bulger and Flemmi's handler, FBI Agent John Connolly, that Brian
Halloran, an associate of the pair, was cooperating against them
and had implicated them in several murders _ fully expecting that
Connolly would warn Bulger and Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   When Halloran was murdered, Morris said he suspected Bulger and
Flemmi had killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Morris also claimed that Connolly acted as the middleman, twice
delivering $1,000 from Bulger and Flemmi to Morris. One payment, he
said, was stuffed in the bottom of a case of wine delivered to him
at the Boston FBI office.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly refused to testify at the hearings, citing his Fifth
Amendment right against self-incrimination. But in numerous
interviews, he vehemently denied Morris's claims that he delivered
money to Morris or warned Bulger and Flemmi about Halloran's
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   As for their deal, Connolly said Bulger and Flemmi ``could
operate a gambling and loan-sharking syndicate with impunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors declined to comment Tuesday but have denied
that any valid immunity agreement exists. They said Bulger and
Flemmi were protected by a few rogue agents and not by the FBI as
an institution.
</P>
<P>
   There was evidence during the hearings that Bulger and Flemmi
got away with plenty.
</P>
<P>
   A South Boston realtor testified that he was extorted at
gunpoint by Bulger, who threatened to put him in a body bag.
Although the realtor was interviewed twice by FBI agents, there is
nothing in the FBI files about the case and apparently Bulger was
never questioned about it.
</P>
<P>
   A former agent testified that Connolly confided to him in 1983
that Bulger and Flemmi had extorted as much as $90,000 from a
Charlestown drug dealer who stored marijuana in South Boston
without their permission. Another agent testified that he never
pursued allegations that Bulger was shaking down drug dealers after
Connolly told him the ``street talk'' wasn't true.
</P>
<P>
   Still, like other officials, former FBI supervisor James Ring
testified he knew Bulger and Flemmi were involved in crimes while
working as informants, but never gave them the FBI's permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `If you're doing anything, you're doing it on
your own,' '' Ring testified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
