<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FUELREGS-SUVS-ART-2ND     09-14 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUELREGS-SUVS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DETROIT: the game.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most crossover vehicles ride high off the ground and have
all-wheel drive. Those two features qualify them as ``off road''
vehicles, which the fuel-economy rules classify as light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   But few of these crossover vehicles are ever likely to be driven
up a rocky mountain trail. ``Every crossover vehicle is being
called a sport utility even if they can't go up a wet driveway,''
said Jamie Jameson, the vice president for sales and marketing at
DaimlerChrysler, which takes pride in the off-road capacities of
its Jeeps.
</P>
<P>
   The company does not make such claims for the PT Cruiser, which
has front-wheel drive instead of all-wheel drive. The Cruiser is
being classified as a light truck through an obscure provision of
the fuel-economy rules often applied to minivans. The provision
says that vehicles can be so classified if they have removable back
seats and a flat load floor.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Felrice, a top regulator at the NHTSA for two decades and
now a top lobbyist in DaimlerChrysler's Washington office, said the
provision was written in the 1970s to cover about 12,000 cargo vans
a year. Without the provision, those vans might have been
classified as cars. But since the 1970s, the auto industry has used
the provision to classify the entire minivan market, or 1.2 million
a vehicles a year, as light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The Cruiser is no gas-guzzler. It may even get high enough
mileage to match the mandated average for cars. Indeed, Zverina,
the DaimlerChrysler spokesman, said the vehicle's combined city and
highway gas mileage might reach 30: the Environmental Protection
Agency will issue an official figure when the vehicle goes on sale.
</P>
<P>
   By adding the Cruiser to its light truck offerings,
DaimlerChrysler will improve the overall average fuel economy for
its fleet. This will allow the company to sell more large sport
utility vehicles and pickup trucks, which are the most profitable
models, with margins of up to $15,000, but which also tend to have
thirsty V8 engines.
</P>
<P>
   The Cruiser ``helps us because on the light truck side, there's
very strong demand for V8s,'' Zverina said.
</P>
<P>
   The average fuel economy of new light trucks appeared to improve
slightly in the 1998 model year, the most recent data available.
Automakers acknowledge that this is largely because of anomalies in
the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and DaimlerChrysler, for example, began equipping many of
their minivans and pickups to run on either gasoline or ethanol to
take advantage of federal fuel-economy credits for dual-fuel
vehicles _ even though fewer than 100 service stations in the
country actually sell ethanol. GM redesigned its four-wheel-drive
Suburbans to make them too large to be counted as light trucks;
they ceased to be included in any gas mileage averages at all.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether they are classified as cars or light
trucks, the new, car-based vehicles have a number of advantages.
Dr. Ricardo Martinez, the head of the NHTSA, says they might be
safer than current sport utility vehicles because they will tend to
be lower and less likely to roll over. The new vehicles are also
less likely than sport utility vehicles to kill other motorists in
crashes because they have lighter underbodies that are not as
stiff.
</P>
<P>
   The new automobiles get 20 to 30 miles a gallon, a level several
miles a gallon less than the small and mid-size cars on which they
are based, but far better gas mileage than most current sport
utility vehicles. Overall, the effect of the new vehicles on the
nation's fuel efficiency depends on what kind of vehicles they will
replace. If they attract customers who might otherwise buy big
sport utility vehicles, then the net effect would probably be to
improve fuel efficiency slightly.
</P>
<P>
   But most customers for crossover vehicles seem likely to switch
from cars, hurting the nation's overall fuel efficiency. Except for
a few, low-volume luxury models, like the BMW X5 and the Lexus RX
300, most new crossover vehicles will sell for less than $20,000
and be fairly small. Three-quarters of the sport utility vehicles
now sold cost $26,000 and up, including all of the big gas
guzzlers.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the giant vehicles, despite their price tags, has
put DaimlerChrysler, GM and Ford all perilously close to falling
short of the light truck fuel-economy standard. For each tenth of a
mile per gallon that an automaker falls short of the standard, it
must pay $5.50 for each vehicle sold. This can add up to tens of
millions of dollars for a big automaker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
