<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-REPORT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WARNS OF POTENTIAL FOREIGN `Y2K' PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attempting to consolidate information about the worldwide impact
of the pending Y2K computer bug, the US State Department and
several foreign governments warned of potential problems in
developing countries such as power outages and shipping problems.
</P>
<P>
   While the reports contained little new information, they served
as a reminder of the interconnectedness of many economic sectors.
For example, Venezuela, which exports a great deal of oil to the
United States, was judged to have a ``moderate risk'' of
disruptions in its electrical-power supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The reports also raised objections from some nations that were
cited as problem areas, on grounds that the information in them was
outdated or the perceived threats were overblown.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a spokesman for Pakistan disputed the US State
Department warning of a ``high risk'' of disruptions for electric
power and health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect that any major disruption is going to take
place,'' the spokesman said. ``We are late starters but in order to
cope with the sitaution a high-powered and technically manned
national task force has been entrusted with the tak of dealing with
any problem that might arise.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department also was critical of India, with its report
asserting that parts of the utility and shipping sectors there
``have been slow to address the Y2K issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``Y2K'' problem relates to the practice of many
older computer programs using just two digits to keep track of the
year. Left unfixed, these systems might grow confused by the date
of Jan. 1, 2000 and shut down. That could lead to delivery problems
in computer-controlled systems from air-traffic control networks to
water-supply pipes.
</P>
<P>
   To address the risk, governments and industries worldwide are
spending billions of dollars worldwide to upgrade or fix their
systems. But there seems to be no consensus on the global outlook
except that few observers expect severe problems in developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, developing countries accustomed to water and
power supply disruptions might take less notice of problems related
to the date change, said Leon Kappelman, a professor at the
University of North Texas who advises the United Nations on Y2K
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't apply our expectations to their realities,'' he said.
Kappelman and others also said the reports seemed to reinforce the
criticism that governments have provided relatively little hard
data to pinpoint problem areas.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department declined to issue warnings against
traveling to certain countries specifically because of worries
related to Y2K, saying no single country's problems raised
sufficient concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The British Foreign Office also issued a Y2K report Tuesday but
took a different approach in some cases. In the case of Ukraine,
for example, Britain cited concerns about water and power systems
and wrote: ``We advise against all holiday and other nonessential
travel to the Ukraine over the New Year period and early January
2000 until the situation becomes clearer.''
</P>
<P>
   Some countries disputed the findings of the various reports. In
an e-mail to a popular Y2K discussion group on the Internet, a
member of Uganda's national Y2K task force challenged the British
Government's descriptions and said the report was based on
six-month-old data.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect an apology,'' wrote Elisha Wasukira, the Ugandan
official. Officials at the British Embassy in Washington said they
couldn't immediately respond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
