<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2157 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FLOYD-ANIMALS-BOS &LR;      09-14 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-ANIMALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMALS NERVOUS ABOUT FLOYD, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The tortoises dug holes. The lethal coral snakes,
usually shy, climbed their cages. The rhino iguana paced nervously.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly a day before Hurricane Floyd moved close to the
Florida coast, and the animals knew something was coming.
</P>
<P>
   Before a hurricane, human beings aren't the only ones exhibiting
unusual behavior. Animals, too, sense the falling barometric
pressure. Some mate. Some squawk. Some hunker down, their survival
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   And in Joe Wasilewski's living room Tuesday, even as Floyd
veered north, giving Miami just a glancing blow, a menagerie of
exotic proportions let him know they weren't so happy about the
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Wasilewski, 47, the owner of Natural Selection Productions who
has helped produced animal behavior films for National Geographic
and the Disney Channel among others, moved more than 70 animals
inside his home to protect them, and protect others.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the midst of dog and cat crates that contained Nile
crocodiles, American alligators, monitor lizards, spur-thighed
tortoises, frilled dragon lizards, a kinkajou and a coatimundi,
Wasilewski said that watching the animals prior to a big storm is
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that coral snake,'' he said, as the red, yellow and
black-banded snake slithered around the cage. ``It never moves and
look how agitated it is now.'' The snake's venom, drop for drop, is
the most poisonous in North America.
</P>
<P>
   One of Wasilewski's mentors was the late Cecil Clemons of
Palmdale, Fla., who owned Florida's largest crocodile and alligator
farm. Clemons told him that snakes swarmed on to roads before a
hurricane. ``He said I could go on the road and fill up my pickup
truck with snakes,'' said Wasilewski.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might try that later on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday was taken up mostly with getting the animals inside.
One of the reasons was to protect others. During Hurricane Andrew
in 1992, hundreds of monkeys and other nonnative animals got loose
after the storm destroyed their cages.
</P>
<P>
   Wasilewski spent several weeks then tracking some of the more
dangerous animals. One was a male African lion. ``Some eccentric
guy had it. We didn't believe the reports at first. This woman who
had panthers, mountain lions, said she saw it. One of her females
went in heat and she heard the roar of a lion outside the house. I
went and I saw the track.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' he said, ``we're not kidding around here.''
</P>
<P>
   His house, located in the Redlands section of unincorporated
Dade County, southwest of Miami, gradually took on the feeling of a
zoo Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wasilewski lifted up a lid of a crate and eight alligator babies
tried to break out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, hey, get in there,'' he said, pushing their heads back
inside.
</P>
<P>
   An African bullfrog puffed out his chest nearby. A chameleon
stood perfectly still.
</P>
<P>
   Wasilewski was running around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this storm passes us by,'' he said. Later, Floyd would
move north, sparing South Florida. But Wasilewski won't be moving
the animals out just yet. Another hurricane, Gert, was way out in
Atlantic, looking as if it could be headed his way. The animals
would let him know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
