celing at Meadowcreek High School. For each flag, at least a few
students can point and say, ``That's where I was born,'' which
makes Meadowbrook one of the two or three most diverse schools in
Georgia. (David Tulis/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Sept. 14, 1999 -- AUTHOR-SAID, 09-14 -- Prof.
Edward Said in his office at Columbia University. Said, a
literature professor and leading spokesman for the Palestinian
cause in the United States, sees a single, nonsectarian nation as
the only long-term resolution to the conflict between Israelis and
Palestinians. (Janet Knott/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 14, 1999 -- TIMOR-U.S., 09-13 -- Gen.
Hugh Shelton during his testimony before the Senate Armed Services
Committee last week which was conducting a hearing on his
re-appointment for a new term as chairman of the Joints Chief of
Staff. Even as President Clinton publicly condemned the destruction
of East Timor, it fell on Shelton to deliver a series of tough
messages to the Indonesian government, finally warning that the
U.S. would act to cut off billions of dollars of international aid
unless international peacekeepers were allowed in, according to
senior Administration officials. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. -- Sept. 14, 1999 --
HURRICANE-FLOYD-2, 09-14 -- Near the Main Street pier on Daytona
Beach, Tony Mazzullo (on ladder) and Howard Sears ready the Pitstop
Restaurant and Bar for Hurricane Floyd by covering the windows with
plywood. Authorities urged nearly 2 million people to evacuate
coastal areas stretching from Florida to North Carolina Tuesday as
Hurricane Floyd, one of the most powerful storms to ever threaten
the United States, inched closer. (Timothy O. Davis/The Gainesville
Sun)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. -- Sept. 14, 1999 --
HURRICANE-FLOYD-1, 09-14 -- On Tuesday morning Rodney Ward of
Daytona Beach reads graffiti scrawled on plywood protecting one of
the many stores on city's usually crowded boardwalk. Authorities
urged nearly 2 million people to evacuate coastal areas stretching
from Florida to North Carolina Tuesday as Hurricane Floyd, one of
the most powerful storms to ever threaten the United States, inched
closer. ``It is deserted, like a ghost town,'' said Ward of the
boardwalk. (Timothy O. Davis/The Gainesville Sun)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
