<HEADER>
A2164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-WACO-JUSTICE-NYT &LR;      09-14 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-JUSTICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WACO PROSECUTOR IN TEXAS REMOVES HIS OFFICE FROM CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The top federal prosecutor in Texas responsible for
handling all legal matters related to the FBI tear-gas assault near
Waco, Texas, has asked for and received permission from the Justice
Department to be recused from the case, according to legal papers
disclosed Tuesday in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The recusal request by the U. S. attorney in San Antonio, James
Blagg, also applies to other prosecutors in the Western District of
Texas who have any involvement in the case. That would include Bill
Johnston, a prosecutor who had recently complained to Attorney
General Janet Reno about what he said was a possible coverup
involving the attack on the Branch Davidian compound in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The court papers filed Tuesday, called a notice of recusal, do
not explain why all personnel for the U. S. attorneys' office for
the Western District of Texas, including Johnston, an outspoken
critic of his superiors, were removed from the case.
</P>
<P>
   But law-enforcement officials said Tuesday that Blagg sought the
recusal because he, along with other prosecutors, would be
witnesses in the investigation by former Sen. John Danforth of the
tear-gas assault. Reno has also recused herself from any matters
concerning Waco. The recusal was approved by Eric Holder, the
deputy attorney general and the top Justice Department official
responsible for Waco after Reno's recusal.
</P>
<P>
   The agency transferred all Waco-related matters to J. Michael
Bradford, the U. S. attorney in Beaumont, Texas, who said his goal
will be to ``foster public confidence.'' The main pending legal
action is a wrongful death lawsuit filed by families of Branch
Davidian members who died near Waco.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the action was not intended to silence
Johnston. But he and his superiors had tangled in recent months
over the handling of evidence recovered from the cult compound
after the tear-gassing and the deadly fire that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, in a letter made public by the Texas Rangers on
Monday, wrote to Reno last month warning that her aides were
misleading her about the federal agents' role in the assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have formed the belief that facts may have been kept from
you _ and quite possibly are being kept from you even now _ by
components of the department,'' he wrote in an Aug. 30 letter.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Johnston had angered Justice Department officials in
Washington when he allowed Michael McNulty, a documentary filmmaker
who had long challenged the government's account of the assault, to
examine physical evidence from the compound where about 80 people
died.
</P>
<P>
   It was McNulty who first recognized that a tear-gas cannister
retrieved from the scene was a combustible round, a finding that
seemed to contradict Reno's longstanding statement that nothing the
government did at Waco could have ignited the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of the flammable tear-gas round has created an
outcry in Congress and has forced Reno to appoint Danforth to
re-examine how the fire was started and whether any FBI or Justice
Department officials lied or concealed evidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
