u f BC-GLOBE-EARLY-BOS &LR;      09-14 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-EARLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBE TO PUBLISH EARLY SUNDAY EDITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Seeking to increase circulation and accommodate the
changing lifestyles of its readers, The Boston Globe will begin
publishing an early edition of the Boston Sunday Globe on
Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Oct. 23, the early edition of the paper will be
available on Saturdays at about 2,000 local retail locations
throughout Greater Boston. The early edition will be delivered to
stores between 9 a.m. and 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Globe subscribers will continue to receive home delivery of the
latest edition of the Sunday paper on Sunday morning, the Globe
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant undertaking, one which a team from many
departments within the paper has been working on for months,'' said
Globe publisher Richard H. Gilman Tuesday. ``Our goal is to
increase Sunday circulation by giving consumers more time on the
weekend to spend with the Sunday Globe. It's another way we're
trying to meet the changing needs of our readers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilman said the early edition will contain much of the features
and news from the regular Sunday edition and the color and
supplemental sections such as the Help Wanted, Real Estate, TV
Week, Parade magazine and advertising supplements, allowing readers
to get a look ahead at Sunday retail sales and classified
advertising listings, such as jobs and homes for sale. The main
news, metro news, and sports sections will be updated for the
Sunday final edition.
</P>
<P>
   Initial plans for the early Sunday edition call for a press run
of nearly 40,000 copies, the Globe said.
</P>
<P>
   Like most major metropolitan newspapers, the Globe has
experienced declining Sunday circulation. For the six months ended
in March, the Globe's Sunday circulation was audited at 730,420, a
2.4 percent drop from the comparable six-month period a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers in other big cities, including Chicago, Los Angeles,
and New York, have had success publishing early Sunday editions,
the Globe said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
