<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2176 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WACO-RECUSAL-COX     09-14 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-RECUSAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prosecutor removed from Branch Davidian investigation
 &HT;    By Mark England and Tommy Witherspoon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Federal prosecutor Bill Johnston of Waco and his
boss were removed Tuesday from any dealings with Branch Davidian
matters by Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder.
</P>
<P>
   Those duties were assigned to J. Michael Bradford of Beaumont,
U.S. Attorney for the Eastern District of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   No explanation was given for the recusals of Johnston and James
W. Blagg, United States Attorney for the Western District of Texas,
in documents filed in Waco's federal court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not have a comment on the substance of the recusal,''
said Johnston, an assistant United States attorney, ``but I am
going to continue to do what I think is the right.''
</P>
<P>
   Blagg released a statement noting that his office, based in San
Antonio, advised law enforcement officials before and after the
1993 raid on Mount Carmel, home of the Branch Davidians and their
leader, David Koresh. It also handled the subsequent criminal trial
of 11 Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of their roles in matters that may be under
investigation, my office has been recused from all related matters
to avoid any potential or appearance of a conflict of interest,''
the statement read.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Mike Caddell of Houston, who represents several
Davidians in the upcoming wrongful death lawsuit against the
government, speculated the recusals may relate to concerns that
Blagg, Johnston and others will be targeted in an investigation
into whether they acted improperly five years ago by not telling
defense attorneys for the Davidians that incendiary tear gas was
used at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said the recusals shouldn't have an impact on the
lawsuit, set for trial on Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, the U.S. Attorney's office was not handling anything
related to the civil case,'' Caddell said. ``They had already been
taken out of the loop by the Justice Department. Everything we're
doing, arranging for depositions and document production, is being
handled by the Justice Department.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Tinker, an Austin attorney who defended Davidian Brad
Branch, said the recusal of Johnston ``should have happened a long
time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are documents in the possession of lawyers in the case
where Bill Johnston is saying, 'Let's be careful interviewing these
ATF agents so we do not create any Brady material,''' Tinker said.
``That's material that could prove helpful to the defendants. Now
if he is coming around claiming that he is trying to reveal the
truth, that is outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell, though, said he had mixed emotions about Johnston's
removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``His actions in saying don't create Brady material are not
consistent with a claim to be seeking the truth,'' Caddell said.
``But he gave Mike McNulty access to an evidence locker, which
ended up benefitting us. The Justice Department had been
stonewalling us for six years. I thought Johnston was straight with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Johnston let McNulty, a film producer, view
the Davidian evidence, leading to a series of new allegations
against the government and another Congressional inquiry into what
happened at Mount Carmel. More recently, Johnston wrote a memo to
Attorney General Janet Reno warning that her own department was
possibly misleading her about federal agents' roles in the Branch
Davidian siege.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnston also acknowledged he may have sat in on a meeting
five years ago where members of the FBI's Hostage Rescue Team
admitted using incendiary tear gas at Mount Carmel, firing at a
bunker away from the Davidians' residence. The admission was not
made known to defense attorneys. Johnston said he didn't understand
the terminology used during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford will now handle all Branch Davidian related matters,
including any dealings with appeals related to the 1994 criminal
convictions of seven Davidians; the wrongful death lawsuit next
month; pending or future requests for information under the Freedom
of Information Act; and inquiries into what happened at Mount
Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton appointed Bradford as United States
Attorney for the Eastern District of Texas in 1994. Before that,
Bradford was a Jefferson County district judge and a United States
magistrate. He graduated from the University of Texas Law School in
1978.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Bradford successfully prosecuted Dallas City
Council Member Paul Fielding for mail fraud and conspiracy.
Fielding was accused, among other things, of using minority-owned
front companies to obtain contracts under affirmative action
programs.
</P>
<P>
   His first duty will be to get up to speed on the Branch Davidian
case, Bradford said in a released statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first priority is to familiarize ourselves with the issues
at hand so that we may fully cooperate with all other entities
looking into this matter,'' Bradford said. ``Our main objective is
to assist in providing truthful information in order to foster
public confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark England and Tommy Witherspoon write for The Waco
Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
