<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2182 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-BAYLOR'S-LAMENT-H     09-14 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR'S-LAMENT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
WACO _ It is the talk of college football. The infamous moment that
cost Baylor a victory over Nevada-Las Vegas has been replayed
countless times on ESPN, CNN, Fox and every other major sports
television outlet.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports talk-show hosts on radio stations across America are
blasting Baylor coach Kevin Steele, and callers are making jokes
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baylor needs a Catholic quarterback,'' they say. ``He would
know how to kneel.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just one of the flaming arrows Steele knew would come
because of Saturday night's final play. Baylor, leading 24-21 with
eight seconds left, elected to run the ball up the middle from the
UNLV eight. Darrell Bush fumbled at the one, and UNLV cornerback
Kevin Thomas picked up the ball in the end zone and returned it the
length of the field for the most improbable victory imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor's agony will go down as one of the most incredible
moments in college football history, but it's a moment Steele and
his players would like to forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to rehash this over and over,'' Steele said.
``It happened, and it's over with. I had a press conference to talk
about it, we met as a team and talked about it, and the coaching
staff met and talked about it. That's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, the criticism doesn't affect me. The only thing that
bothers me is these players need a win, and they deserve to win.
There are only so many opportunities in a season. If you spend your
time looking back, before you know it, it's over. This is a lesson
learned, and we have to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably no football player in the country is suffering more
these days than Bush, who had the ball knocked out of his hands
when he was trying to reach the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my job to hold on to the ball, so I really felt like I
let the team down,'' Bush said. ``But there's nothing I can do
about it now. I just have to look forward to Oklahoma.''
</P>
<P>
   The opponent for the Bears this weekend is a Sooners team that
won 49-0 over Indiana State on Saturday in the debut of coach Bob
Stoops. Like everyone else in college football, Stoops has seen
replays of Baylor's shocking loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes fluky or freaky things can happen,'' he said. ``I'm
sure other people will take notice of what happened and be a little
more cautious of what they do. It was unfortunate for Baylor.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele has taken a lot of heat for not having quarterback
Jermaine Alfred take a knee to run out the clock, but other Big 12
coaches have come to Steele's defense. Texas coach Mack Brown said
Steele is taking too much criticism for opting to run the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``A whole lot of coaches around the country would have handed
the ball off and not even thought about it,'' Brown said. ``If you
don't win, people are going to criticize you. If you win, nobody
says anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Vikings coach Dennis Green had his team run two dive
plays in the final seconds Sunday while leading the Atlanta Falcons
17-14. The Vikings won, and no one said a word about why Green
didn't have Randall Cunningham take a knee.
</P>
<P>
   When the Baylor game ended Saturday, UNLV coach John Robinson
had a message for Steele as they shook hands. ``I don't know what
to say,'' Robinson said, ``except you are not the only one this has
happened to.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson knows from experience. While coaching the Los Angeles
Rams, Robinson had a decision to make in a 24-24 game against Green
Bay with 30 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams had a first-and-10 at their 20. Instead of having the
quarterback take a knee, run out the clock and try to win in
overtime, Robinson called for a handoff to Eric Dickerson, who
fumbled. The Packers recovered, took a knee on first down to run
time off the clock, then kicked a field goal on the last play to
win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of thing will happen to all of us sooner or later,
somewhere down the line,'' said Texas Tech coach Spike Dykes.
``People don't understand why you don't go for the score if you're
on the lip of the cup, but that's why. But every once in a while,
you have to go by your gut feel. It's just part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The surprising finish to the UNLV game was the second
consecutive disastrous ending for the Bears. Baylor lost the season
opener at Boston College 30-29 when kicker Kyle Atteberry missed an
extra-point attempt in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   One of those outcomes in a year is bad enough, but back-to-back
heartbreaking losses to start a season could be devastating to a
team's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a family and you have adversity, a lot of times you
come together and become stronger,'' said Baylor cornerback Gary
Baxter. ``I think that's what we will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe they have bonded together because of
this,'' he said. ``We will find out what kind of football team we
are, and we'll find out what kind of head coach we've got.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
