<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAPAN SELLS YEN TO CURB SHARP RISE AGAINST DOLLAR
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese central bank sold yen to curb the currency's recent
heady rise, but the intervention barely managed to nudge the yen
off its three-year high against the dollar. And in New York, the
yen gained again, to 105.79 to the dollar from 106.44 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese authorities seemed more alarmed by the speed of the
yen's appreciation _ nearly 5 percent in the last week _ than in
the rise itself, even as economists began wondering aloud whether a
stronger yen might stifle the little vitality that a long-moribund
Japanese economy is starting to exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   ORACLE SHARES FALL ON PROFIT REPORT
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Oracle dropped sharply in after-hours trading after
the company reported first-quarter earnings that met the consensus
estimate of analysts but fell short of the so-called whisper
number. After closing at $45.4375, shares fell as low as $41.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T TO CUT THOUSANDS OF JOBS
</P>
<P>
   As AT&AMP;T continues to cut costs amid its campaign of cable
television acquisitions, thousands of employees in AT&AMP;T's core
long-distance telephone operation could lose their jobs before the
end of next year, executives close to the company said. Many of
those employees could find jobs in other, faster-growing AT&AMP;T
divisions that will continue to add jobs, but others could be laid
off. Shares of AT&AMP;T fell 62.5 cents, to $44.50.
</P>
<P>
   Seagate Technology, the computer disk-drive maker, said that it
would cut 8,000 jobs, or 10 percent of its workers.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTORS SEE HSBC DEAL IN DANGER
</P>
<P>
   Fears about Republic New York's liability in what prosecutors
are calling a huge fraud dragged down the company's stock 1.6
percent, to $59, for a decline of nearly 15 percent this month.
Investors are concerned that the fraud could derail or alter HSBC
Holdings' planned acquisition of Republic.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ IS UP, BUT DOW DECLINES
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were mixed as robust retail sales heightened fears of
rising interest rates. The Dow Jones industrial average decreased
120 points, to 10,910.33. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
lost 7.84 points, to 1,336.29. The NASDAQ composite index gained
23.52 points, to 2,868.29.
</P>
<P>
   Bond yields climbed to 6.12 percent from 6.05 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   BIG ITALIAN INSURER BIDS FOR RIVAL
</P>
<P>
   In a move to further consolidate Italy's financial industries,
the nation's largest insurer, Assicurazioni Generali, announced a
hostile $12.8 billion bid for its domestic rival, Istituto
Nazionale delle Assicurazioni.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER'S SMART-CAR CHIEF QUITS
</P>
<P>
   Lars Brorsen will resign as chief executive of DaimlerChrysler's
struggling Smart car business at the end of the month. The surprise
resignation, which Daimler executives disclosed at the Frankfurt,
Germany, international automobile show, came as sales of the tiny
two-seater, called a city car, finally appeared to be picking up
after the company reduced prices and added safety features.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH BREWER BUYING 868 PUBS
</P>
<P>
   Scottish &AMP; Newcastle PLC, Britain's dominant brewer, agreed to
buy 868 pubs, restaurants and budget hotels from the ailing
Greenalls Group PLC for $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   EBAY TO BAN ALCOHOL AND TOBACCO
</P>
<P>
   The online auction site Ebay plans to prohibit the sale of
alcohol and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL SALES UP 1.2 PERCENT IN AUGUST
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales surged 1.2 percent last month, to $252.4 billion,
as people bought cars and clothing. The increase was almost double
what analysts had expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
