<SLUG> BC-CELL-PHONE-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T COST CUTS COULD TRIM LONG-DISTANCE JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the AT&AMP;T Corp. continues to cut costs amid its campaign of
cable television acquisitions, thousands of employees in AT&AMP;T's
core long-distance telephone operation could lose their jobs before
the end of next year, executives close to the company said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those employees could find jobs in other, faster-growing
AT&AMP;T divisions that will continue to add jobs, including the cable
operation, the wireless phone unit and the group that serves big
business customers, the executives added. But others could be laid
off.
</P>
<P>
   An AT&AMP;T spokeswoman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of job cuts would come on top of the 14 percent
reduction in work force announced by C. Michael Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's
chairman, last year. Despite the company's success in cutting
workers, the company's overall employee base has grown by almost 40
percent in recent years, to 149,000, with AT&AMP;T's acquisition of
Tele-Communications Inc., the big cable television operator, and
the success of smaller internal units.
</P>
<P>
   When AT&AMP;T announced its $58 billion deal to acquire Mediaone
Group Inc., another cable giant, in May, AT&AMP;T also said it intended
to cut $2 billion in annual costs by the end of next year. The
company said some of that reduction could come in the form of a
smaller work force but declined to specify just how much.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, some AT&AMP;T managers have not been moving quickly
enough. Last month, when AT&AMP;T announced a new long-distance calling
plan that charges 7 cents a minute, the company added that the core
long-distance operation was behind the May schedule in cutting
costs.
</P>
<P>
   So last month, AT&AMP;T instituted a companywide hiring freeze. In
addition, hundreds of senior executives throughout AT&AMP;T have been
instructed to cut costs within their departments, an AT&AMP;T executive
said, speaking on the condition of anonymity. Because of the
decentralized nature of the cost-cutting campaign, the executive
said, it may be difficult to determine just how many jobs will
disappear and where the cuts will be concentrated. New Jersey,
however, may bear the brunt simply because many of the company's
employees are in the state.
</P>
<P>
   What is sure is that the job cuts will come mostly in AT&AMP;T's
core long-distance operation, which is relatively stagnant. An
executive close to AT&AMP;T said that the unit that runs the
long-distance network and the unit that sells long-distance phone
service to business customers would probably be the first to make
cuts, perhaps by Oct. 1. Other cuts, including those in the
consumer long-distance business, might not take place until next
year, the executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, AT&AMP;T said it would build as many as 26 new
Internet data centers to provide services like operating Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AT&AMP;T fell 62.5 cents, to $44.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
