<SLUG> BC-FEES-AD-COLUMN-345(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: P&AMP;G TO TIE AGENCY COMPENSATION TO SALES PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world's largest advertiser, Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. , plans
major changes in how it pays the agencies that create campaigns for
its 300 household brands around the world, which include Cheer,
Crest, Folger's, Ivory, Jif, Noxzema, Pampers, Pringles and Tide.
</P>
<P>
   Effective July 1, 2000, P&AMP;G will no longer pay agencies
commissions based on what is spent to advertise products in
television, magazines, newspapers and other media. From that date,
the company will base compensation on sales objectives, with
agencies being paid more if a brand's sales increase and less if
sales decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in my career we've ever made such a
really big, broad-scale change,'' Robert Wehling, global marketing
officer at Procter in Cincinnati, said Tuesday in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a system that's in our best interests and the best
interests of our agencies as we move forward,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The change has been tested with seven brands since July, and an
announcement of the switch, which will affect some of Madison
Avenue's largest, best-known agencies, is scheduled for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about bringing forth bigger and better ideas
faster,'' said Roy Bostock, chairman and chief executive at
MacManus Group in New York, which owns one Procter agency, D'Arcy
Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all trying to drive top-line sales growth,'' he added,
``and the agencies are going to charge after this in a big, big
way. This is really going to generate some sales increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Many marketers have already replaced the traditional commission
system with performance-based compensation: calculating agency
payments on predetermined, measurable goals like growth in sales,
increased awareness of a brand or gaining broad distribution for a
new product.
</P>
<P>
   But P&AMP;G's decision to join their ranks is likely to accelerate
the shift to performance-based compensation because of the
company's strength and influence among marketers and agencies, as
well as its heritage of innovations like inventing the soap opera.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   P&AMP;G spent an estimated $5.75 billion on worldwide advertising in
1997, the most recent year for which figures are available,
comfortably ahead of No. 2, General Motors Corp., at an estimated
$4 billion. Procter has most recently paid agency commissions of
about 13 to 15 percent of the amount spent on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will give performance-based compensation real critical
mass,'' said Nancy Salz, president at Nancy L. Salz Consulting in
New York, which conducts annual surveys on advertiser-agency
relations, ``and it will now be more considered by every major
advertiser.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``Holding the agency accountable, when it shares the
financial risks and the financial rewards, creates a full business
partnership. That changes attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salz said that her most recent survey found that agencies
and advertisers using performance-based compensation described
their relations as less tense, with more teamwork. ``And 35 percent
of clients using performance-based compensation said they had more
respect for their agencies,'' she added, ``compared with 12 percent
for clients that don't use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Procter is striving to double sales to more than $70 billion in
the next few years and speed the development and introduction of
products with worldwide sales potential like Fabreze, a fabric
deodorizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to create a new and stronger partnership
relationship with our agencies,'' Wehling said. ``We both win if we
figure out how to build sales faster, and we both lose to a degree
if we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If you're an agency and your income growth is tied
to the growth of the brand you're handling, you have an
unbelievable sense of urgency to find solutions to problems and
drive sales forward. Under the commission system, as long as media
billings were holding up, you could take as long as you wanted to
come up with solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   That opinion was echoed by the head of an agency who has
crusaded since 1990 for new compensation plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the old system, you could argue that you make more money
with mediocre advertising because you have to run it more to get
the same result,'' said Keith Reinhard, chairman and chief
executive at the DDB Worldwide Communications Group unit of Omnicom
Group in New York. DDB, which does not work for Procter, has more
than 25 alternative compensation agreements with clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what I call results-based or success-based compensation,
people sit down and do a much better job of really determining a
situation, analyzing a problem or opportunity,'' Reinhard said.
``It has a transforming effect, because you're examining every
possibility, every form of marketing strategy and tactic, to help
you achieve your goal.''
</P>
<P>
   That underlines a significant reason for P&AMP;G's switch. The old
system could tempt agencies to focus their attention on the types
of advertising that cost more to create, produce and run in the
media _ like commercials on prime-time television _ regardless of
whether they were the most appropriate for the task at hand,
because expensive media buys generate higher agency commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Performance-based compensation plans are described as media
neutral, meaning they favor no one medium _ and often eschew
traditional media for unconventional sales tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now what really emerges is a new degree of `holistic
marketing,''' Wehling said, ``looking at all the forms of
communicating, bonding with our customers, whatever it takes:
direct mail, public relations, Internet advertising, new media,
traditional advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   Wehling said that he first heard the term ``holistic marketing''
about 15 years ago, on a trip to visit Dentsu Inc. in Tokyo, which
works for Procter in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said to me, ` Wehling, we are not your advertising
agency,''' he recalled, ``and I said, `Oh, really?' and they said:
`No, we're your total communications agency. If the best way to
sell your brand is images on matchbook covers or street-corner
sampling, that is what we will recommend.' That is a powerful
thought.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G agencies are already working on such multifaceted campaigns
for a variety of brands. For instance, for the Cover Girl line of
cosmetics, units of Grey Advertising Inc. in New York have
developed a Web site, designed packages, created promotional
materials, sponsored events for consumers in stores and organized a
concert tour by the singer Brandy, who also appears in the brand's
commercials and print advertisements produced by Grey.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this new system,'' said Edward H. Meyer, chairman and
chief executive at Grey, ``our rewards will be based not on which
media we use but on successful business-building ideas and
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Grey is one of the four main worldwide agencies for Procter,
along with D'Arcy; Leo Burnett Co. in Chicago, part of Leo Group,
and Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi in New York, part of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC.
The company also has two major regional agencies, Dentsu and Jordan
McGrath Case &AMP; Partners/Euro RSCG in New York, part of the Euro
RSCG Worldwide unit of Havas Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the sales-based compensation plan could reduce the
agencies' revenue and income by generating more use of media that
is less expensive than prime-time TV and national print, Wehling
replied: ``I'd be very surprised if that is the outcome. By working
together with us to grow our sales, the agencies will grow their
income _ and possibly faster than under the traditional system.''
</P>
<P>
   Bostock at MacManus concurred, adding that compensation based on
sales could offer ``a more predictable stream of revenue for the
agencies'' than ``media budgets, which fluctuate so much more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And therefore we can staff more consistently over time,'' he
said. ``That's a huge advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The new compensation system will not be adopted until next July
1 rather than Jan. 1, Wehling said, because ``we still have a lot
of i-dotting and t-crossing to do on issues like taxes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
