<HEADLINE>
OUTCRY OVER MISS AMERICA'S NEW RULES
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Fla., Okla., N.J., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. _ When the Miss America Pageant began
allowing contestants to wear sandals a couple of years ago, few
eyebrows were raised.
</P>
<P>
   When it allowed two-piece bathing suits last year with bottoms
that could be no more than one and a half inches below the navel,
many people thought it was about time.
</P>
<P>
   But when the board of the Miss America Organization adopted new
rules last month that would clear the way for a divorced woman or
one who had had an abortion to compete for the crown, many
supporters and participants in the pageant said they would be
ruining the essence of a contest they hold sacrosanct. The outcry
grew so loud that pageant organizers said Tuesday that they were
reconsidering.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a purity and an integrity and a morality that would be
violated if you let in women who are divorced and had an
abortion,'' said Kathrine Baumann, the Miss America first runner-up
from 1970, whose niece, Tiffany Baumann, is competing in this
year's pageant as Miss Ohio. ``People get divorced. But if that
happens, then let them compete in the Mrs. America pageant.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the changes loomed over the Atlantic City Convention
Center, where the televised pageant is to be held Saturday, even
more ominously than the hurricane whipping up the ocean just beyond
the Boardwalk outside, or the strike by hotel workers that began
Tuesday night and could cripple this gambling mecca.
</P>
<P>
   Many people here had traveled to see the weeklong pageant events
and support candidates from 50 states and the District of Columbia.
To them, the trip is a pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction against the changes has been so furious that the
national organization seemed to reverse its position on the changes
Tuesday. Robert L. Beck, president and chief executive of the Miss
America Organization, said the national board would go back to the
state franchises that run the local contests before it institutes
the new guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Beck said the changes to the qualifications were made to conform
with state anti-discrimination laws. The New Jersey Law Against
Discrimination includes marital status among the 13 categories
protected in areas of employment, housing and public accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Dabreu, the acting director of the N.J. Division on Civil
Rights, said she could not comment on whether the law could be
applied to the pageant or any other contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to do that until we have a case filed in our
office,'' Ms. Dabreu said. ``It's an interesting issue, but we have
to wait until we get to what the issue actually is until we address
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck insisted that the changes in the pageant would not dilute
the nature of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the same values,'' Beck said. But he was hard pressed
to delineate what those values were at a time when the pageant is
trying to attract a wider television audience as well as more
contestants in some parts of the country where pageants are waning
in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The values cut across the United States,'' he said. ``It's not
a cookie-cutter thing. You have 10,000 people competing all across
the country. Each is an individual with all kinds of values and
backgrounds, and we're trying to meld those together.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck is the first chief executive of the organization without a
long history of involvement with pageants. The guideline changes,
he said, were made by the national board, whose 22 members are
almost all from the Atlantic City area.
</P>
<P>
   At the convention center, the reaction to those changes was
mostly negative among the hundreds of supporters and relatives of
contestants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hearts are in Miss America,'' said John Covil, a
telecommunications worker from Jacksonville, Fla. ``I've just had a
lifelong affection for the Miss America pageant.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend Tony Daniels, a music studio owner from Oklahoma
City, also said he did not support the changes. Both men have been
judges in local competitions for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just from the old school,'' said Daniels, who was snapping
pictures of Miss Oklahoma, Daneka Allen, as she walked down the
runway in rehearsals for the talent competition. ``Miss America is
such a tradition. A lot of people think it's tired and old, but I
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Spector, a flight attendant from New York who has judged
local competitions, said they were told earlier in the day by
pageant officials not to talk about the changes. She said past
changes were made to keep the pageant from growing irrelevant and
to keep the support of sponsors. But she said allowing contestants
to wear sandals or go barefoot was different from allowing divorced
women to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel they're losing the younger people,'' she said.
``They're trying to use hipper music. They want the girls to look
more natural. But I think these other changes are too drastic. I
don't know anyone who supports them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
