<SLUG> BC-CNBC-ARCHIPELAGO(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNBC INVESTS IN ELECTRONIC STOCK TRADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CNBC on Tuesday demonstrated the new willingness of media
companies to move out of the meat-and-potatoes business of news and
into the world of finance itself, taking a 12.4 percent equity
stake in Archipelago, the third-largest electronic communications
network for trading stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In making the cash investment in the network _ which amounted to
close to $30 million, according to a person briefed on the deal _
the financial news cable channel, a unit of General Electric Co.,
is lending its imprimatur to one of the contenders in the
free-for-all among the nine electronic communications networks
currently vying to dominate the new electronic marketplace for
stock trading.
</P>
<P>
   Other investors in Archipelago include the Etrade Group Inc.,
Goldman, Sachs, J.P. Morgan and Instinet, which is part of Reuters
Group. Instinet itself, as the largest electronic communications
network in the United States, is also a competitor of Archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, the emergence of the electronic
communications network's has been a news event and an investment
opportunity for media companies interested in electronic commerce.
Most networks are registered with the Securities and Exchange
Commission as broker-dealers, although they function more like
exchanges because they serve as electronic meeting places for other
broker-dealers and thus facilitate the trades. In August,
Archipelago applied to the SEC to be registered as a stock
exchange, the Internet equivalent of the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC is ``just a great name _ that's a wonderful thing for us,''
said Gerald Putnam, the chief executive of Archipelago, which is
currently the third-largest of the electronic communications
networks, after Instinet and The Island ECN Inc., whose majority
owner is the Internet broker Datek Online Holdings Corp.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Putnam said that he hoped the presence of two CNBC executives on
Archipelago's board would help persuade the SEC that his network
was not designed simply to serve institutional investors to the
detriment of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that is really important to us and really
important to the SEC'' in considering whether to register
Archipelago as an exchange is that ``we have representation of
individual investors, not just big guys,'' Putnam said. CNBC, which
for 10 years has covered financial news for lay audiences helps
fill that need, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But the deal raised the issue of whether CNBC could provide
arm's-length coverage of the emerging industry of networks when it
has an investment stake in one of the major players.
</P>
<P>
   Even though other media companies have invested in electronic
networks, they have been, at best, corporate cousins of news
outlets. Dow Jones &AMP; Co., the corporate parent of The Wall Street
Journal, has a stake in Optimark Technologies Inc. Bloomberg LP has
one unit, Bloomberg News, that covers financial news and another,
Tradebook, that functions like a network.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Loeb, the former editor of Columbia Journalism Review,
who is also a columnist for CBS Marketwatch, said, ``This gets to
the whole issue of covering yourself and as media companies grow
bigger, they find themselves more and more in the position where
they will be covering themselves and/or covering their competitors
and this is invariably problematic.''
</P>
<P>
   Loeb also said that, as the crowded field of electronic networks
thins out, the winners are likely to be companies with the largest
trading volume. So, the logic goes, the more often Island or
Archipelago is mentioned in a financial news broadcast, the more
likely the higher profile will give them a competition advantage.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC president Bill Bolster said that CNBC's journalists would
give Archipelago no special treatment. ``We've got to cover them
all equally because our true point is to let everyone know what's
going on everywhere,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
