<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROPRIATIONS CHIEF AIMS TO TAP 2001 SURPLUS NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Idaho)   (ART ADV: Photo (NYT36) is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Draining the budget surplus for 2000 and thirsty
for more money to finance their spending bills, Republicans will
tap the projected surplus for 2001 for $12 billion or more, the
chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman, Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, said ``a tremendous
surge in defense spending,'' along with requirements for a myriad
of health, science, education and agriculture programs, made it
necessary to use ``some of the surplus for the year 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans need roughly $30 billion now to finance spending
bills for the 2000 fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1, at a level
that will win enough votes to gain passage by the House and Senate
and, perhaps, President Clinton's signature.
</P>
<P>
   But ``we have sort of bumped into a wall,'' said House Majority
Leader Dick Armey.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have sworn off the habit of using Social Security
surpluses to help finance the government. And they say they want to
preserve the strict spending limits, or caps, they imposed in 1997.
The caps cut spending on government agencies other than the
Pentagon by $37 billion, down to $246 billion, for the coming year.
That is not enough to satisfy everyone.
</P>
<P>
   So the extra money may come from increasingly creative
accounting techniques, including drawing down a projected surplus
in the budget for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Some are wary. ``We need to be very careful about that,'' said
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott. ``That shouldn't be used as a
way to get more money.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stevens, who as the Senate's appropriations chairman is
probably the most influential member of Congress on spending,
advocates the technique. At the same time, he is swatting down some
of the more enterprising ideas of House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans considered cutting $1 billion or more for
poor and working-class people from the Social Services Block Grant
program, which finances programs like day care and foster care. But
Stevens said these programs had ``been pretty well scrubbed'' and
were unlikely to provide extra billions.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans also considered delaying billions of
dollars in payments to poor and working-class Americans under a
federal tax-credit program. Stevens rejected that idea Tuesday as
``a gimmick.''
</P>
<P>
   Other devices will help Congress cobble together the spending
bills, which is the only job the Constitution requires it to
perform.
</P>
<P>
   One is declaring predictable costs like the 2000 census an
``emergency,'' or creating a kind of escrow account for agriculture
aid. Both techniques take billions off the books. Another is taking
money from the projected surplus for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   There are two kinds of budget surpluses. One is the Social
Security surplus, which is like a retirement account, and Congress
has vowed not to touch it. The other is the so-called ``on-budget''
surplus, which is like a checking account. That account was
overdrafted for 30 years, until this year.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping into the budget for the year after next is a growing
trend. Congress spent $1.9 billion in this fashion in 1996 and
$11.6 billion this year. Stevens said Congress would have to spend
more _ how much, he could not say, though Republican aides said the
sum could reach $20 billion _ to finance the spending bills for the
fiscal year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   With 11 working days before the fiscal year ends, Congress
making slow progress on spending bills, and the president vowing to
veto bills he says have been cut too deeply, it looks like only
``the aroma of turkey'' at Thanksgiving time will compel Congress
to conclude its appropriations work, Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho,
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If the president vetoes spending bills, and no solution is
reached, the government will have to run on stop-gap bills, called
continuing resolutions, until some compromise is found. Last year,
Congress wound up lashing together a last-minute spending bill that
contained $21 billion in cap-busting expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, including Majority Whip Tom DeLay, say they
intend to blame the President this time if the spending bills
eventually bust the spending caps or siphon off Social Security
surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, in a strategic retreat, are now focusing solely
on Social Security. They are no longer talking much about the caps.
</P>
<P>
   In April, House Speaker Dennis Hastert said: ``We intend to stay
within the caps. That was a promise we made to the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Republican leaders like Stevens were repeating, like a
mantra, a different line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is not the caps, the issue is Social Security,'' the
senator said.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that the caps would be broken, and he said a $17
billion increase in military spending would be the battering ram
that broke them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
