<HEADLINE>
NASA WAITS OUT THE STORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (With HURRICANE-FLOYD and related stories) 
(mk) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hurricane Floyd not only threatens the southeastern
coast, but also places the nation's manned space program at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy Space Center at Cape Canaveral, Fla., and nearby
launching pads at Cape Canaveral Air Station at Patrick Air Force
Base were virtually abandoned Monday and Tuesday as authorities
evacuated all but essential personnel.
</P>
<P>
   But left to ride out the storm are the nation's four space
shuttles, valued at $2 billion apiece; billions of dollars worth of
components for the international space station, and launching pads,
control rooms, radar stations and other buildings.
</P>
<P>
   NASA said it had done everything possible to protect the
shuttles and other space hardware in hangars and other buildings,
but that their fate would depend on the strength of the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tied down, covered and secured everything we can, and
now we're just going to ride it out,'' a NASA spokesman, George
Diller, said Tuesday. ``We know we have a lot at risk here.''
</P>
<P>
   Diller is one of 102 volunteers on a skeleton crew the agency
allowed to stay at the Kennedy center for the duration of the
storm.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, NASA ordered most of the center's 12,500 workers to
evacuate until at least Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttles Discovery, Endeavour and Columbia are in the
Orbiter Processing Facility, a building where the spacecraft are
refurbished between missions. The building is designed to withstand
winds of up to 105 mph. The ships, supported by scaffolding, have
their landing gear retracted, payload bay doors closed and
tail-mounted main engines covered with bags to protect against
water and debris.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle Atlantis is in the sturdier Vehicle Assembly
Building, designed to withstand winds of 125 mph. The Atlantis' bay
doors are closed, and the craft is sitting on its wheels, its
landing gear and engines covered with plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
   The space station building contains about 60 percent of the
hardware that will eventually go into the station, a $60 billion
structure that will be assembled above Earth over the next four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Because the space center is only nine feet above sea level,
officials worry about flooding from a storm surge. The two
launching pads for the shuttles are particularly vulnerable,
officials said, as are pads at the Air Force station, where four
multimillion-dollar rockets sit awaiting launching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
