<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL URGES STEPPED-UP ATTENTION TO TIES WITH NORTH KOREA
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A special Clinton administration panel led by
former Defense Secretary William J. Perry has recommended to the
president that the United States step up diplomatic and trade
relations with North Korea at a ``markedly faster rate'' in hopes
of ending the Communist government's program to develop nuclear
weapons, administration officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, the officials said, has tentatively accepted
the findings of the panel, which explains his announcement this
week that he is preparing to lift some of the trade sanctions that
have barred commerce with the North for close to half a century.
</P>
<P>
   While encouraging Clinton to seek closer ties, the committee
recommended that the United States maintain its troop strength in
South Korea and that it remain vigilant to new provocations by the
world's last Stalinist government in the North.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as a few weeks ago, North Korea appeared ready to
test fire a new long-range Taepodong 2 missile that is
theoretically capable of hitting Alaska and Hawaii. Under a
tentative agreement reached this week with the United States at
talks in Berlin, American officials said, North Korea agreed to
hold off on additional missile tests as long as negotiations with
the United States continued.
</P>
<P>
   Senior administration officials were unwilling to release many
of the details of the classified final report prepared by Perry and
his committee and presented to Clinton a few days ago, after eight
months of study.
</P>
<P>
   But the senior officials said the overall conclusion was that it
is better to try to contain North Korea's nuclear ambitions through
negotiation rather than through isolation or confrontation, which
would increase the possibility of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many aspects of North Korea's behavior will remain
reprehensible,'' said a senior American official who agreed to
discuss the report. But the goal, the official said, ``is to end
the nuclear weapons activities and long-range ballistic missile
activities and ultimately to end the Cold War on the Korean
Peninsula.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel, the official said, recommended that the United States
attempt to improve relations with North Korea at ``a markedly
faster rate, but as North Korea takes steps to address our security
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   The report is certain to revive the question, raised by
congressional critics of the administration's policy toward North
Korea, of whether the administration is rewarding North Korea for
defusing a crisis that it created when it test fired a long-range
missile over Japan in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Perry, who left the Defense Department to return
to business, was asked by Clinton to oversee a full review of
policy toward North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials acknowledge that nothing binds the
North to its agreement this week except the fear that whatever
sanctions the United States lifts in coming weeks could be
reimposed.
</P>
<P>
   Perry's brief report _ 18 pages _ recommended that the White
House appoint an ambassador-level senior official to oversee all
aspects of policy toward North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department negotiations with North Korea are being
carried out by Ambassador Charles Kartman, a longtime diplomat. The
new official would apparently have even more senior rank and would
also coordinate policy among the State Department, the Pentagon,
the Treasury Department and other agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
