<HEADER>
A2206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NY-FASHION-I-ART-NYT &LR;      09-14 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION-I-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 MARC JACOBS CAN'T GET ENOUGH OF THE '70s  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)(jt) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a career with more ups and downs than an elevator in the
World Trade Center, Marc Jacobs has been riding high in the last
few years, with a devoted following of young fashion editors and
their friends who look so right in his slick yet youthful clothes.
Those cashmeres in luscious colors. Those simply cut dresses with
pretty details like scalloped hems. And then there's his success in
making Louis Vuitton a name to be reckoned with in ready-to-wear as
well as in handbags.
</P>
<P>
   In his signature collection last season, Jacobs mined the 1970s
with flaring calf-length skirts shown with chunky-heeled boots and
multicolored striped sweaters. For the spring 2000 collection he
showed on Monday night, he gravitated to another aspect of the 70s,
rediscovering denim. But not the decorated kind that Tom Ford
revived for Gucci, setting off a flood of cheap imitations.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs used denim in soft shades of green, pinkish coral and tan
cut into sleek versions of jeans and jeans skirts, sometimes adding
curved yokes or pockets with sunburst seaming. He teamed them with
gauzy cashmere T-shirts and highly styled versions of the jeans
jacket that women have been tossing over just about everything in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   High-heeled sandals added a feminine touch to the denim suits,
which were the most likable styles in the show and the styles
likely to prove the most commercially successful. You could
envision not only fashion editors but also lots of other women
adopting them as a comfortable middle ground between a casual and
an uptight way of dressing for all kinds of occasions.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Jacobs' dresses tended to look old-fashioned, not
only the A-line styles with set-in waistbands but also the
chrysanthemum-patterned waistless shifts and the cotton net dresses
decorated with bands of sequins that ended the show. Let's call the
show a qualified success.
</P>
<P>
   Old-fashioned is a term no one would ever apply to Yeohlee's
clothes, which are as modern as the latest techno fabric yet as
comfortable as a bathrobe. She uses cotton coated with Teflon so it
doesn't stain, and wools and gabardines that are machine washable.
But they would never be mistaken for mass-produced drip-drys, at
least not to anyone who recognizes masterly cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The spring collection she showed Tuesday is in neutral stone,
concrete and teak tones inspired by building materials. (She has
always considered clothing another form of shelter.) Unlined
translucent raincoats and capes are in a lightweight nylon perfect
for travel, whether across town or across a continent. Attached
hoods make umbrellas unnecessary. Even whimsical pockets cut like
mittens are utilitarian.
</P>
<P>
   Yeohlee's cuts are precise and deceptively simple. What looks
like a straight skirt has triangles inserted into the hem for ease
of movement. A boxy vest has an L-shaped pocket. That rounded
collar is really an ellipse. Two curves and a square of fabric are
combined to form a shawl.
</P>
<P>
   The metallic gold silk she uses for evening pieces has a dull
rather than a glittery finish. She combines it with putty-colored
silk Jacquards for tank tops with deep U-necks or V-necks, narrow
trousers and skirts with inset triangles or a soft saronglike fold
on one side.
</P>
<P>
   A Yeohlee collection never sets off fireworks. But the clothes
have gained a cult following among women in the art and fashion
worlds with an eye for subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   The evening wear of Mark Badgley and James Mischka is another
story entirely. There, beading and decoration are the magnets to
women who want to be noticed. But for spring, the lavishness of the
embellishment has been tempered. Instead of all-over beading, most
of the clothes have a light sprinkling of beads or seemingly random
placements of delicately beaded flowers. A few Badgley Mischka
dresses have just one spot of jeweled embroidery.
</P>
<P>
   Fabrics, too, are light, running to georgette, tulle, organza
and lace. And there is an emphasis on separates, usually a beaded
top with a bias-cut satin skirt or narrow taffeta pants. Color, on
the other hand, is used lavishly, from pale tones like melon,
lavender and peach to stronger shades of pink, salmon and
turquoise. Sometimes a pale shade was layered over a deeper tone.
The parade of colors was like a massive bowl of rainbow sugar,
either tempting or cloying, depending on your taste.
</P>
<P>
   Black? Forget it. The fashion world has practically turned its
back on its longtime favorite. Designers may be forgiven for
indulging in prettified colors for spring, as long as they don't
make a habit of it. But what about women who don't want to look
like ingenues? Maybe Badgley Mischka, as well as some other
designers, will go back to thinking about them next season.
</P>
<P>
   Zang Toi always thinks about the women who wear his clothes, who
tend to be the moneyed variety who like a bit of dash as long as it
comes with good fabrics and workmanship. The designer has been
dressing them for a while now in impeccably tailored suits, coats
lined with unusual scarf prints matched to shirts or dresses, and
evening dresses that are slender columns or doorway-filling ball
gowns.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that he seems to have fallen into a rut. About
the only thing in the collection that changes is the pattern of his
scarf prints. This time there are two: one he calls My Dream of
Africa, populated with people and camels, and another is African
Night, which features a tiger with coiling tail. Perhaps he thought
leopards have been overexposed. But tigers in Africa?
</P>
<P>
   Not content with its reputation as an innovative leather-goods
house famous for its woven handbags, Bottega Veneta is trying to
follow the likes of Gucci and Vuitton into the realm of
ready-to-wear. After two seasons of showing in Milan, Laura
Moltedo, the president of the company, brought the collection to
New York this week.
</P>
<P>
   There were some nice things, particularly caviar-beaded
sweaters, buttonless jackets loosely belted over shorts, strapless
tops tied in back like pareos and, as might be expected, leather
jackets. But much of the collection was just uninspired, with
shapeless jumpsuits and hip-slung skirts worn with loose tops that
were unflattering.
</P>
<P>
   Betsey Johnson has always gone her own way, even when it veered
precipitously from the direction fashion was heading. Now that
decoration, color and pattern are back, she would seem to be right
on track. But rather than simply showing her spring line in a way
that might make it look like what some other designers are doing
(heaven forbid!), Ms. Johnson opted for a different approach.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of hiring models, she called on friends and loyal
customers and invited them to style themselves. ``I wanted to show
the clothes on my customers, tall and short, small and big,'' she
said in a chat before the show. ``For three days last week they
came in and picked clothes. I didn't put outfits together. I hung
the tops here and the bottoms there and let them loose. They took
them home, picked their own accessories and are doing their own
hair and makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   And they came out, rock singers, artists, students, employees of
the designer, the shop owner Patricia Field, Steven Tyler's wife
and daughter, and Ms. Johnson's own daughter, sister and niece
wearing floral georgette, embroidered satin, peasant skirts,
bikinis, sarongs, ruffled net coats, patchwork skirts and jeans
with ruffled hems a la Cher.
</P>
<P>
   It was pure Betsey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
