<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-EARNINGS-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORACLE SHARES TUMBLE AFTER DISAPPOINTING EARNINGS REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shares of Oracle Corp. dropped sharply in
after-hours trading Tuesday evening after the company reported
first-quarter earnings that met the published consensus estimate of
analysts but fell short of the so-called whisper number.
</P>
<P>
   Whisper numbers are the last-minute adjustments analysts make to
their forecasts that they informally mention to clients and traders
just before companies report results.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Aug. 31, Oracle reported earnings of
$236.7 million, or 16 cents a diluted share, up 21 percent from
$195 million, or 13 cents a share, in the comparable period a year
ago. Revenue rose 13 percent, to $1.98 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings number matched the consensus estimate as reported
by First Call Corp., which tracks corporate earnings, but the
whisper number had been as much as 19 cents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the company's revenue growth also fell short of
their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle posted its results after the close of the market. Its
shares closed for the day at $45.4375, down 31.25 cents, in NASDAQ
trading. But in after-hours trading, they fell as low as $41.
Analysts predicted a big sell-off on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday's announcement, Oracle's share price had tripled
from a 52-week low of $14.875 hit early last October. In June,
Oracle reported unexpectedly strong results for its fourth quarter
and announced plans to cut $1 billion from operating expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock had traded up very aggressively in advance of this
earnings release on expectations they would at least hit the
whisper number, if not do better,'' said William Epifanio, an
analyst with J.P. Morgan. ``I see unimpressive revenue growth, and
they clearly cut some costs to make the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, Oracle chief financial
officer Jeff Henley said, ``We're glad to get Q-1 behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit slower than we would have liked,'' he
continued, ``but I don't think we have a very different feeling for
the year. Our business is healthy. This is always a seasonally slow
quarter, and we just didn't get quite as many big deals finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Software sales growth slowed significantly from the fourth
quarter. Over all, first-quarter software licenses and other
revenue grew 9 percent from the corresponding period last year,
compared with 22 percent year-over-year growth in the fourth
quarter. Data-base revenue grew by 8 percent to $443 million, and
applications software sales rose 11 percent, to $109 million,
compared with the first quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, data-base revenues grew by 25 percent,
while application sales grew by 28 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Facing a volley of hostile questions from analysts, Oracle
chairman and chief executive Lawrence Ellison said: ``One quarter
does not make a trend. Place your bets, gentlemen.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Oracle historically had weak first quarters and
bounced back in its second quarters. ``It's not a matter of us
asking you to believe we will do something we've never done
before,'' he said. ``We think we're going to have a very strong
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison said that sales of enterprise software, the big packages
made by SAP, Peoplesoft and Baan that companies use to manage
internal business processes, had slowed, and with it the Oracle
data bases that feed such applications. But he said deployment of
Internet-based sales operations had boomed and that Oracle had a 93
percent market share of this business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God for the move to the Internet,'' Ellison said. ``The
growth of the Internet is largely offsetting the slowdown in SAP
installations, Peoplesoft installations, Baan installations. That's
where our growth is coming from.''
</P>
</TEXT>
