<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-EVACUATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCHWORDS FOR MOST FOLKS AROUND FLORIDA: `STAY INSIDE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TERRY KLIEWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Fla. _ A sign in front of a tiny, boarded-up antique
store along all-but-abandoned U.S. 1 just south of here captured
Tuesday's thought for the day for all Floridians and anyone else
passing by:
</P>
<P>
   ``Floyd _ Go Back in the Void,'' it proclaimed to the handful of
drivers headed north along the famous old highway that runs from
Key West to Jacksonville, hugging the Atlantic coastline all the
way.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, Hurricane Floyd did return to the void, at least
as far as South Florida is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon, the storm's northward path toward possible
landfall in South Carolina had convinced many Miami residents to
assume that the worst, such as it was, was over. They weren't
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among signs that folks across South Florida were ready for
life to return to normal was a flood of phone calls to emergency
officials asking if schools would re-open Wednesday. The answer:
Probably not but stand by.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the moderating weather conditions, plywood stayed on
windows and hurricane shutters remained locked down on buildings
and homes across Miami and through the coastal cities trailing off
to the northward.
</P>
<P>
   The watchwords for most folks around here continued to be ``stay
inside.'' Traffic along U.S. 1 and parallel Interstate 95 was
virtually nil all afternoon. A few truckers and the rare state
trooper had the pavement to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Near Melbourne, hotels on the barrier island just offshore were
evacuated as a precaution as winds and squalls picked up. Only a
handful of gas stations were operating. Restaurants and stores were
shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   Told that in Miami, surfers were testing the waves, one local
storeowner just shrugged: ``Well, that's Miami for you. It's not
over for us _ or them.``
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the afternoon turnout of surfers, skaters and
wave-kickers at Miami Beach was troubling to emergency officials,
who again and again used radio and TV time to warn people to stay
put.
</P>
<P>
   But one surfer spoke for all when he was asked about the
still-extant hurricane warning: ``What hurricane? The waves are
good and if it gets worse, I'll leave. It's not often you see waves
like this.``
</P>
<P>
   Others milling along the shoreline said they figured the
occasionally gusty wind and intermittent, spray-like showers were
as bad as it would get.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our vacation and we're going to use it the best we can
within reason,'' said one father, on vacation with his wife and two
children from Illinois, as they stared out into the Atlantic
looking for the elusive hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being careful, but right now it seems OK to walk down to
the beach for a little while.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
