<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CLEC-ACQUIRE-ART(TRIM     09-14 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEC-ACQUIRE-ART(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL, LOCAL PHONE CARRIERS GO IN SEARCH OF BIG SUITORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Psst, wanna buy a phone company?
</P>
<P>
   That is not quite how Wall Street takeover pitches are made, but
it captures the gist of the calls that have gone out across the
telecommunications industry recently as at least a few competitive
local exchange carriers _ young communications companies trying to
compete against the Bells in local phone and data communications
markets _ look to be acquired.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives on Wall Street and in the
telecommunications industry, E.Spire Communications Inc., GST
Telecommunications Inc., ICG Communications Inc. and Intermedia
Communications Inc. are among the competitive local exchange
carriers, (or CLECs, pronounced ``SEE-lecks''), that have recently
canvassed or are currently canvassing for potential acquirers,
generally with the help of big-name investment banks. With an
average market value of $750 million, those four carriers are
fairly representative of the middle of the CLEC industry.
</P>
<P>
   But, so far, there have been no takers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The search for scale and capital happened at this stage of the
game for wireless, at this stage of the game for cable and is
happening now for the CLEC's,'' said Mark Bruneau, president of the
business strategy group at Renaissance Worldwide, a consulting firm
in Boston. ``Some entrepreneurs have done a good job of getting
licenses and growing businesses to a certain scale, and now they're
realizing that they need the kinds of things that large phone
companies are really good at, like scalable customer acquisition
and billing. And those things are generally absent from these
CLECs, and they have grown as much as they can in an
entrepreneurial spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   E.Spire, GST and ICG declined to comment. Intermedia chairman
David Ruberg declined to comment on any potential deals but seemed
to echo Bruneau in saying, ``Cost of capital, cost of customer
acquisition and cost of network are the driving forces in this
industry, and we are in constant discussions about how to reduce
those costs.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The main way to reduce costs is to get bigger, analysts say, and
often the fastest way to get bigger is to merge or be acquired.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the competitive carriers that emerged in the wake of the
deregulatory Telecommunications Act of 1996, hoping for easy
pickings in local communications markets, have found competing
against the regional Bell companies more difficult and expensive
than they expected. Many are laden with debt and need to raise yet
more money _ generally in the high-yield market _ to continue
ripping up streets and building local communications networks. In
addition, the wild gyrations that many CLEC stocks have gone
through over the last year or so may have scared off potential
investors. Some analysts and communications executives have been
predicting a wave of consolidation among the competitive carriers
since last fall. It has not happened.
</P>
<P>
   But if the stock market manages to avoid the paroxysms that have
struck during the last two Octobers, that could change quickly in
the coming weeks and months. For all of their stock volatility,
many CLECs have built valuable fiber optic networks in cities and
towns across the nation and have won many business customers away
from the Bells.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to the (somewhat meager) prospects for consolidation
among the smaller CLECs themselves, there are at least three groups
of communications companies that may find them attractive.
</P>
<P>
   The first group is larger competitive local carriers looking to
expand geographically or expand their menu of services. This group
includes McLeodUSA Inc., Nextlink Communications Inc., Teligent
Inc. and Winstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Teligent and Winstar have almost identical market values of
about $3 billion and both companies generally use advanced wireless
technology to serve business customers rather than traditional
copper or fiber optic links. Nonetheless, both companies could be
interested in expanding their fiber optic offerings, according to
executives close to the companies. Nextlink is backed by Craig
McCaw, the cellular telephone legend. McLeodUSA, one of the oldest
and most-respected CLECs, in August received a $1 billion infusion
from Forstmann Little &AMP; Co. in exchange for a 12 percent equity
stake in the company. McLeod may well use that money to underwrite
new construction, but could also use the cash to buy assets rather
than build them, some Wall Street executives said. (Forstmann was
not alone among buyout shops investing in CLECs this summer; in
July, Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co. agreed to invest up to $110
million in privately-held Birch Telecom Inc.)
</P>
<P>
   The second group of potential CLEC acquirers are the new breed
of long-distance carriers including Qwest Communications, Level 3
Communications and Global Crossing. All three of those companies
have generated market values in the billions as they have built or
agreed to buy advanced new long-distance networks around the nation
and, in Global Crossing's case, under the seas. But each of those
companies may look to extend their networks into cities and office
parks around the nation much as Worldcom did in 1996 by acquiring
MFS Communications, one of the first big CLECs, and as AT&AMP;T did
last year in acquiring Teleport. Qwest has appeared particularly
aggressive in exploring CLEC acquisition possibilities, but for now
may be preoccupied with its pending acquisition of U S West,
according to executives close to Qwest.
</P>
<P>
   The third, and perhaps most intriguing, group of candidates to
acquire some of the lonely-heart CLECs is the regional Bells
themselves, especially SBC Communications Inc. and Bell Atlantic
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its deal with the Federal Communications Commission
to win approval of its pending acquisition of Ameritech Corp., SBC
agreed to expand into 30 local communications markets in which it
is not currently active. As Bell Atlantic seeks approval of its
pending merger with GTE Corp., it seems likely that Bell Atlantic
will have to agree to similar conditions. Faced with the prospect
of having to deploy networks quickly in dozens of new markets,
acquiring a CLEC that already operates in those places could seem
reasonable, according to Wall Street executives. A problem arises,
however, if that CLEC already provides competition in the Bell's
home territory. In that case, such a deal could be seen as
anticompetitive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
