u a BC-HURRICANE-FOLKS-1STLE     09-14 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-FOLKS-1STLEDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FLORIDA RESIDENTS STAYING HOME DESPITE HURRICANE THREAT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to clarify lede) 
 
By LISA TEACHEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIALANTIC, FLA. _ While hundreds of residents along the
eastern Florida coast were packing up valuables and fighting
bumper-to-bumper traffic on their way inland Tuesday, Tony Flohre
had no plans to evacuate despite the threats from Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't here yet,'' Flohre said as he walked toward the beach
of this community on the barrier islands about 60 miles south of
Daytona Beach. He was on his way to visit friends who live only a
block from the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I leave,'' Flohre said. ``It may not even hit
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Flohre was practically a loner in the one-square-mile community
that had become a ghost town by noon Tuesday. Most locals heeded
officials' warnings to flee before the Category 4 hurricane hit.
Shops along the main road were closed and boarded up, including
hotels, restaurants and gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   But Flohre and a handful of other island residents decided to
wait out Floyd's anticipated wrath approached the north-central
Florida coast Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Those choosing to stay either weathered similar storms before,
or they simply want to stay with their property. Many believe if
they leave they won't be able to get back. Some live in concrete
houses and think they will hold up under the torrential winds.
</P>
<P>
   The barrier islands are flanked by the Atlantic Ocean on the
east and the Indian River on the west. While theory holds that if
the storm is big enough, the ocean could surge one side while the
river swells and spills over, virtually drowning the islands from
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   But Flohre doesn't believe the theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens then I guess I'll see what Moses and the
pharaohs saw at the Red Sea,'' Flohre chuckled. ``(Hurricane)
Andrew didn't put the Intercoastal and the Atlantic together. So
I'm not worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Flohre, a painter by trade, has lived on the islands for 14
years. He had already worked several hours Tuesday morning but
decided to go home early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have stayed at work longer, but I was worried they
wouldn't let me back on the island later today,'' he said. ``See
that's the problem. When they evacuate you they don't let you come
back right away.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the biggest concern of Linda Burns and Lynn Pucci who
were on their way to the beach Tuesday to videotape trees and
shrubs gusting in the winds that already had begun to pick up.
</P>
<P>
   The two recently bought a house and wanted to stay with it
through the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to ride it out and protect what we have,''
Burns said. ``If it gets too intense we'll bail, but we don't want
to be stuck off the islands and basically not be able to get
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair spent about a year fixing up the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a lot into it,'' Pucci said. ``Just to leave it? That's
too hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the river about a block back on the mainland, several
residents of Palm Bay were hunkering down for the storm as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This house has solid concrete walls. We've boarded up the
windows. We have a motor home with a generator if the power goes
off,'' said Susan Wendler. ``So we are pretty much
self-contained.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendler and her husband, Mark, moved to the area in 1992 and
live in a small neighborhood off U.S. 1 with their son William. The
highway was littered with downed palm branches and debris but
remained passable Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little nervous,'' Susan Wendler said. ``But I'd be more
nervous trying to get out of here with all that traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   By 10 a.m. EST Tuesday parts of Interstate 95 and Florida 528
were lined with cars for dozens of miles. Most of the traffic had
subsided by 4 p.m. when rain showers began to drench the area.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Wendlers decide to stay, they took precautions
to ensure their safety. They loaded up on supplies and fresh water
Monday, and spent most of Tuesday securing the house with boards,
putting lawn furniture in the swimming pool and moving anything
that might become airborne away from the house.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago when Hurricane Erin ravaged the area, the
Wendlers saw 100 mph winds and lost only a car antenna.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one wasn't too bad,'' Susan Wendler said. ``It just
sounded like wolves and it was like a snow white blizzard even
though it was midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wendlers know about blizzards, having survived one in Ohio
20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd much rather go through one of these,'' Mark Wendler said.
``If I was in a wooden house I might be concerned. But I'll take my
chances here.''
</P>
<P>
   Their next door neighbor Bill Dorman was going to try to weather
the storm in his wooden house. His wife, who recently had surgery,
opted to evacuate while he stayed to protect against looters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just got too much here,'' Dorman said. ``But I am taking
calculated risks. I've been tracking the storm closely.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorman said his house was built in the 1960s and has withstood
many storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty steady house but if I hear the roof creaking and
the walls start to move I'll go to the neighbors,'' Dorman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Wendlers have offered their home to Dorman, even suggesting
they tie a rope from his door to theirs so he can find his way if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In Port Malabar, just south of Palm Bay, Bill and Kathy George
were planning to stay as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to stay _ it's as simple as that,'' said
Kathy George. ``We've never been through one that was too much to
handle.''
</P>
<P>
   During Hurricane Erin, Bill George sat in a chair on the front
porch to watch the winds blow by.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one had 100-mph winds. And it didn't bother me a bit,''
Bill George said. ``But I'm not going to watch this one. This one
is a little too big.``
</P>
<P>
   In New Smyrna Beach, 10 miles south of Daytona Beach, sheriff's
Deputy Bruce Fleischmann told The Assocciated Press: ``We're not
going to arrest people for staying. We just ask for their next of
kin.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
