u f BC-MAYTAG-MARKETPLACE-AR     09-14 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYTAG-MARKETPLACE-ART-890&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: MAYTAG'S DELAY IN DISCLOSURE COSTS IT DEARLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Were some investors lucky or did they know something was awry
last week at Maytag Corp.?
</P>
<P>
   The stock plummeted last Wednesday and Thursday in unusually
heavy trading as big institutions bailed out. When the New York
Stock Exchange asked Maytag on Thursday to issue a statement
indicating whether any corporate developments explained the action,
the company said its policy was not to comment on rumors or unusual
market activity.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts say they spoke that evening with company
officials and were given no indication that there would be any
significant changes to the earnings outlook.
</P>
<P>
   But early Friday, before the markets opened, Maytag issued a
statement saying that earnings for the third and fourth quarters
would fall far short of analyst estimates. Maytag shares plunged
$14.8125, to $41.75, leaving the stock almost 44 percent off its
July 14 high of $74 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, accustomed to gentle guidance from all manner of
companies, were shocked and angry. And some are now asking whether
large institutions knew something in advance. Others wonder when
exactly management knew Maytag's earnings were disappointing.
Furthermore, does management now have a full grasp of the company's
financial situation?
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to the company the night before, and they were
guardedly optimistic,'' said Efraim Levy, an analyst at the S&AMP;P
Equity Group. ``They were looking to give the street some good
news.''
</P>
<P>
   John C. Coffee Jr., a securities law professor at Columbia
University, said two possibilities exist. ``There may have been
some kind of contact between an executive and a group of analysts
or institutions, or it may have been that important information
somehow trickled out,'' perhaps from a supplier or a Maytag
retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the company tipped off big shareholders _ a practice
that Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman Arthur Levitt has
frowned upon as ``selective disclosure'' _ it would still generally
not be illegal or considered insider trading, Coffee said.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts say that the company had been riding a market
boom and may have simply botched its earnings forecast, then
delayed the public statement in hopes that the September numbers
would be strong enough to bolster profits.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Newton, Iowa, also defends its move.
Maytag chief executive Lloyd Ward said in a telephone interview
Tuesday that the company would never engage in selective
disclosures to investors or analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no evidence to suggest there was tipping from anyone at
this corporation,'' he said. ``Frankly, it's illegal. We would
consider that a significant violation for any official at Maytag.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward, who took over in August, said the company simply failed to
meet its forecasts and that officials unfortunately had to keep
those details private from even analysts on Thursday until a public
statement was ready Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult for our investor-relations manager to deal
with this particular issue,'' he said. ``If we had dealt with the
analysts that would have been selective disclosure. We weren't in
the position to give guidance to the analysts because it wasn't
available to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday and Thursday, trading activity in the stock
bulged. Though just 282,000 shares of Maytag traded on Tuesday,
Sept. 7, volume shot up to 1.6 million shares the next day and 3.9
million last Thursday. Average trading volume in the last six
months was about 480,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   Maytag shares fell again Tuesday, Sept. 14, to $37.9375, a
52-week low. Some analysts said Maytag had been a hot stock, always
beating estimates, and investors may have simply gotten nervous.
Few short-sellers were in on the drop, and analysts saw few clues.
</P>
<P>
   But Jay Huck, an analyst at the Center for Financial Research
and Analysis in Rockville, Md., a group that scrutinizes corporate
accounting on behalf of investors, said he was preparing a report
on Maytag that suggested that there were operational difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Inventory had begun to bulge in the second quarter, and cash
flow had dropped to $104 million the last six months from $159
million, even though net income had risen from a year earlier.
There was also a little-noted warning in the second-quarter
statement about a European client that suggested it would not be
buying as many vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were clearly some signs of trouble,'' Huck said. ``You
look at cash flow and you say, `We've got a problem here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Heymann, an analyst at Prudential Securities, has also
found problems. He says Maytag understated its overhead early in
the year and over-projected its unit sales. Instead of conservative
accounting approach, he said, the company took an approach that led
to stronger earnings in the first half of the year and shortfalls
in the second.
</P>
<P>
   It was accounting issues and ``not underlying fundamental
weakness in the company's innovation strategy or its execution,''
he said, which is why he now recommends the stock as a strong buy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Heymann said, the company failed to disclose the earnings
news in a timely manner and before Friday denied that a serious
problem was at hand _ which is why the stock was hammered for an
expected 15 percent shortfall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several analysts said that Maytag executives may have simply
become too optimistic after several years of robust growth. ``I
don't think the company was trying to mislead anyone,'' said Scott
Graham, an analyst at CIBC Oppenheimer. ``The management just made
some guidance mistakes. They let expectations get too high.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts say that some investors were not entirely assured
of coming gains, so they simply sold in a panic, fearing the worst.
</P>
<P>
   In the selloff, smaller investors apparently got hit hardest,
according to Birinyi Associates, a market research firm in
Greenwich, Conn., which said institutions dominated trading. On
Thursday, small investors were actually net buyers of $2.3 million
worth of stock, it said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Ward said that the company acted properly and
simply missed a forecast because it is creating innovative products
that are hard to predict because they are coming to market for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not sure of the value equation or what consumers are
going to pay,'' he said. ``We are not perfect. We do not always get
it right.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there were no accounting irregularities but there were
some ``unfortunate occurrences'' in Maytag's discussions with
analysts. He plans to talk with analysts today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to figure out how to improve the communication
process,'' he said. ``That is on my table and I will address it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
