<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS TO RALLY SUPPORT TO CURB GREENHOUSE GASES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand _ President Clinton, speaking at the
jumping off point to the South Pole, sought Wednesday to rally
international support to curb greenhouse gases that many scientists
blame for a hole in the atmosphere over the Antarctic.
</P>
<P>
   The use of fossil fuels and their role in climate change are
helping create weather extremes, from vicious hurricanes to
droughts, Clinton told 5,000 New Zealanders. School children here
routinely where hats and sunblock to protect themselves from the
excessive ultraviolet rays that pierce the Antarctic's ozone hole
in spring months.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began his remarks by expressing concern for the
Americans who are in the path of Hurricane Floyd. He called it
``one of the most serious hurricanes ever to threaten the United
States if the predictions of its force and scope hold true.'' The
president will fly to Washington following a state dinner Wednesday
night, skipping a day of golf in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God it is no longer necessary to burn up the atmosphere
to create economic opportunity. We have somehow got to convince a
critical mass of decisions makers and ordinary citizens in every
nation of the world that that is true,'' Clinton told New
Zealanders gathered at the International Antarctic Center on a
gray, chilly spring day.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the biggest obstacle to curbing greenhouse gases
was the continued belief by wealthy and developing nations that
they must continue using the same fossil fuel sources to maintain
their economies. He said new technology and alternative energy
makes it possible to curb greenhouse gas use and expand economies.
</P>
<P>
   Before his speech, Clinton toured the International Antarctic
Center, the headquarters and supply depot for the Antarctic
programs operated by New Zealand, the United States and Italy.
Christchurch has long been the jumping off point for South Pole
explorers and scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also was joined by Sir Edmund Hillary, the first man to
scale Mount Everest and who failed in an attempt to traverse the
Antarctic continent, and Prime Minister Jenny Shipley, who is
hosting Clinton to a state visit here.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Antarctic Program is operated by the National Science
Foundation with support from the U.S. Air Force and the New York
Air National Guard. During the summers, the International Antarctic
Center supports 3,000 people, most of them Americans, who work on
the ice cap.
</P>
<P>
   In a gesture of scientific support, Clinton announced the United
States would declassify some secret satellite photographs of
Antarctic's dry valleys to help researchers study the affects of
global warming.
</P>
<P>
   The president's state visit followed a day off in scenic
Queenstown, a South Island village that bills itself as New
Zealand's playground. While the president played golf on a course
framed by a snow-capped mountain range called the Remarkables, his
top aides engaged in extreme sports that have made this area
famous.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gene Sperling, the president's economic adviser, took a
bungee jump off a bridge. Queenstown is the birth place of bungee
jumping. Senior aides such as Doug Sosnik, the first to jump, also
indulged in ``rocket boating'' in which a power boat races down a
canyon gorge and takes high-speed turns just yards from huge rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, accompanied on this trip by daughter Chelsea and
mother-in-law Dorothy Rodham, also dined with actor Chris
O'Donnell, his wife and in-laws. O'Donnell is making a film near
Queenstown. Clinton also was joined by Lucy Lawless, a native New
Zealander who plays television's Xena, the Warrior Princess.
</P>
<P>
   In Christchurch, the president thanked the people of New Zealand
for giving him and his family ``five absolutely glorious days in
one of the most beautiful places on Earth.'' Clinton, the most
traveled president in U.S. history, said his biggest regret was not
making it to the Antarctic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
