<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON CALLS HEALTH CARE VITAL ISSUE FOR SENATE CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREAT NECK, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton said Tuesday that she
would embrace the issue of health care coverage in her probable
race for the U.S. Senate next year, asserting that public concern
about the subject had grown since her campaign to change the system
collapsed in failure six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the issues that I will, if I run, emphasize is health
care,'' Mrs. Clinton declared, expounding on the issue first before
an audience of elderly Long Islanders and then at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be very interested in being part of another effort in
our country to try to address the problems that you so eloquently
put forth,'' the first lady told an audience member who voiced
concerns about health care coverage. ``We are going to have to face
that problem in the next years because the problem in the next few
years will only get more difficult and more expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   With her remarks, the first lady clearly signaled that she did
not consider her close identification with President Clinton's
proposal for universal health care _ which has come to be viewed by
many Democrats and Republicans as perhaps the greatest failure of
his first term _ as a political liability in her expected race for
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   She said her travels through New York had convinced her that
voter concern about the issue was as raw as ever, and she grew
animated as she discussed the future of Medicare programs and the
concerns of uninsured and underinsured Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists have long said that they would use the
issue both in an attempt to portray Mrs. Clinton as ideologically
left-of-center and politically inept. The first lady was faulted at
the time for trying to push health care legislation that many
considered to be too sweeping, and for moving without consulting
with many key members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton acknowledged some of those criticisms Tuesday,
saying that she would move gradually and that she saw her role as
trying to help develop a consensus for change. ``I know in any
great country and democracy, such as ours, we have to persuade
people about what it is we should do and we need to have a national
conversation about that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton used her visit to the Great Neck Senior Center to
offer a tough attack on Republicans for their proposed $792 billion
tax cut. (She did not mention her likely opponent, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, who has said he favors the Republican bill). Mrs. Clinton
asserted that the bill jeopardized the future solvency of Medicare,
the medical insurance program for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said he would veto the tax cut bill as too large.
The president has proposed using 15 percent of a projected surplus
that Republicans are tapping for the tax cut bill to assure the
stability of Social Security through the first quarter of the next
century. Mrs. Clinton supported her husband's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party bill, that they say will be sent to the
president probably tomorrow, would be in effect a statement that
would ask us to cut and run on our obligations to older
Americans,'' she said. ``It would break our faith with the seniors
in New York, and I would fight it, if I were in the Congress now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's remarks on health care came on a day that was
filled with suggestions of the kind of issues that have intrigued
her. It also came amid signs that she was growing more assured
about offering positions: Her news conference was her third in two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, for example, distanced herself from a central
tenet of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the leading candidate in
polls for the Republican presidential nomination, to use
faith-based charities, rather than government programs, to care for
the nation's downtrodden. She said she thought that such
institutions could play a limited role, but added, '`I am concerned
and cautious about how such a program could be constitutionally
devised and implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton spoke in favor of campaign finance restrictions,
even as she prepared to return to Manhattan for two more
fund-raisers. She suggested, though, that one of the reasons that
changes in campaign laws had stalled in Congress was because there
had not been much public interest in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people who care about campaign finance reform in the
public arena get somewhat discouraged because the public doesn't
seem to respond as much as we hoped people would,'' she said, in a
reference to her husband. ``I'm hoping that maybe over the next
year, or as we educate the people of the consequence of all this
money coming in, that more Americans will express your concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton was careful not to offer specifics on how the
health care system should be changed. However, she rejected the
notion that her failure last time was evidence that the public did
not share her concern about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm beginning to hear from people again that the problems
that they were telling me about in '93 and '94 are still with us
and we have to address them and we have to figure out a way to do
that effectively,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want people in public life who are afraid to raise
difficult issues and are afraid to take on the biggest challenges
facing our country,'' she said. ``I believe that if you look at the
problems that we're going to be confronting, what we do about
health care is going to be on the agenda.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
