<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECODING U.S. ENCRYPTION POLICY NOT AN EASY THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Clinton administration will announce its new
policy on the export of encryption software. Commerce
Undersecretary William Reinsch, who administers export controls,
said the change will be ``dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday, Reinsch said the administration seeks
``balance'' between the needs of computer users and the police.
That balance, however, keeps shifting in favor of computer users.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, the administration's idea of balance was
mandatory key escrow. Programs to encode computer text would have a
key deposited with an agent. Upon presentation of a court order,
this agent would hand the key to the cops.
</P>
<P>
   A furious battle ensued over this idea, and mandatory key escrow
lost. Now that a bill in Congress, the SAFE Act, would ban key
escrow, the fallback Clinton position is voluntary key escrow. ``We
don't want to make it mandatory,'' Reinsch said.
</P>
<P>
   Would anyone volunteer? Industry doesn't think so, though
Reinsch thinks some large employers might.
</P>
<P>
   Assume key escrow is dead. What's left? Congress long since
rejected an FBI proposal for domestic controls on encryption. What
remains is controls on exports. Though the administration has
lifted controls for lower-level products, industry keeps creating
new and neater stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators can fall embarrassingly behind. On July 1, the
Commerce Department had to change its definition of an exportable
computer chip because it was at the point of applying export
controls to Sony PlayStations. That would have been a chuckle. It's
already funny enough that Apple is advertising its newest model to
be classified as ``munitions.''
</P>
<P>
   The newest version of Microsoft's Internet Explorer uses 128-bit
encryption, and cannot legally be shipped outside North America,
though Microsoft gives it away free.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Reinsch about Internet Explorer. ``We'll address that
Thursday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government is not about to abandon export controls on
everything. Reinsch offers a hypothetical example: ``If the Iraqis
need 450 centrifuges to make enriched uranium, you probably can't
hold them to zero. Maybe they get 120, and they pay 10 times more.
If that means Iraq's got capability in 2008 instead of 2001, that's
a good thing. Part of the game is buying time.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the post-Cold War world, control is becoming more
difficult. More of the technology is civilian, and fewer nations
are agreeing to control it. An example came in 1997, when it was
discovered that machine tools from a closed McDonnell Douglas B-1
bomber line had been sold to China. The most sensitive tool, a
stretch press, was tracked down and returned. But all that really
meant is that the Chinese bought a new stretch press from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. controls have also given away encryption business. ``I
thought for a long time that these were unsubstantiated
assertions,'' Reinsch said, ``but there's increasing evidence of
lost sales. That matters to us.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the concerns of police? ``Law enforcement wants
everything to be the same as in the wiretap world,'' Reinsch said.
</P>
<P>
   That's no longer possible. But will they get anything? Reinsch
met Monday with representatives of Visio, WRQ, Adobe and Microsoft
_ ``a young crowd,'' he said. ``I asked them, `If we could do
something for you on the export-control side, what should we do on
the law-enforcement side?' They didn't have a lot to say about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement has a legitimate concern. ``I prosecuted a case
that went to trial last year that involved a guy who traded in
child pornography,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Fred Short. He
won a conviction, but without the benefit of certain computer files
on which the encryption was never cracked. Short said flatly that
the more his evidence is encrypted, the more time and money it will
take to convict criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Candy Marshall, vice president and general counsel of WRQ Inc.,
said encryption is essential to WRQ's products, which allow a PC to
connect to a mainframe computer over the Internet. Without strong
encryption the product is not trustworthy. But Marshall said the
amount of paperwork to sell overseas is ``astounding,'' and that
all it does is help WRQ's foreign competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about ``balancing'' these concerns sounds good, but there
is no clear way to do it. Either we have encryption or we don't.
The fact is, we have it; we can have all we want of it. The
question on the table is, how much can we sell to foreigners?
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday there's a new answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
