<SLUG> BC-NY-ENCEPHALITIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM BRITAIN, MOSQUITOES LOOK LIKE SCOURGE OF DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you happened to be tracking New York City's
encephalitis problems from Britain for the last week, you might be
forgiven for recoiling in horror at the Black Death devastating
Gotham.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Plague on New York: Panic as City Is Sprayed to Control
Killer Mosquitoes'' screamed The Daily Mail, a tabloid.
``Helicopters Attack Killer Biting the Big Apple,'' bellowed The
Express, another tabloid, and The Evening Standard, a third
tabloid, warned darkly, ``New York in Fight Against Deadly Brain
Bug.''
</P>
<P>
   If the headlines were not frightening enough, the articles
surely were. ``Panic swept New York last night as a plague of
mosquitoes killed three people and left 57 more fighting for their
lives,'' The Daily Mail wrote breathlessly. ``Helicopters were
weaving in and out of skyscrapers, dousing the city's streets with
powerful insecticide.''
</P>
<P>
   City residents were described as rushing to railroad stations to
get away, or cowering indoors so as not to be infected. Those
unlucky enough to get sick were depicted as keeling over from
seizures, paralysis, fever and brain swelling.
</P>
<P>
   Some papers seemed slightly pleased that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
apparently famous abroad for his quality-of-life crackdowns, had
met a pest he might not be able to lick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tough New York Mayor has beaten crime, squeegee merchants
and, bizarrely, ferret owners who want him to overturn his ban on
keeping them as pets,'' wrote a reporter for The Express. ``Now he
may finally have met his match.'' The mosquitoes, the report went
on to say, have proved ``immune to the zero tolerance he
successfully displays to most other irritants.''
</P>
<P>
   One paper, the sometimes sober, sometimes sensational Times,
even talked as if it were a contest between insects and politics.
``The giant political ambitions of Rudolph Giuliani, the mayor of
New York, are under attack from a swarm of mosquitoes spreading
fear and disease throughout the city,'' its report said.
</P>
<P>
   The articles indicated that no matter where the suffering seven
million went, they could not escape. ``Subway trains are filled
with the smell of insect repellent as New Yorkers generally heed
requests to spray themselves,'' an article in The Express said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some wrote admiringly that New Yorkers were
steely enough to disregard the whole thing. ``Normally neurotic New
Yorkers, who dash to the dermatologists at the slightest sign of a
pimple, largely ignored the goings-on,'' wrote a correspondent for
The Scotsman, adding that the sang-froid in Manhattan probably
stemmed from the fact that the fatalities had occurred in other
boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Just as interesting were the explanations of why New York had
been visited by this plague, perhaps even deserved it. One writer
in The Daily Telegraph said it was because smoking was so commonly
banned in the city. Mosquitoes would stay away, he said, if only
there was more cigarette smoke in the air.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter in The Guardian explained that it all stemmed from
global warming. New York was well on its way to becoming Kuala
Lumpur, the story surmised, because unstable weather in the
northern half of the globe was allowing pests and diseases to
migrate north.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the odd pun or joke about past menaces, real
or imagined. ``The city that thrives on buzz has found a version it
wants to go away fast,'' The Express said. ``At least you could see
Godzilla.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, all the hoopla did not seem to be deterring travel plans.
Both British Airways and Virgin Atlantic Airways said there had
been no perceptible drop in reservations. If the airlines did get
questions about a menace, it was one farther south.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't gotten any calls on the mosquitoes,'' Christine
Pilson of Virgin Atlantic said. ``The issue of the moment seems to
be Hurricane Floyd.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
