<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-SCHOOL-SITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS CRITICIZED FOR SCHOOL BUILDING SITE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Internal investigators for the Los Angeles school
district released a report Tuesday that sharply criticized senior
school officials, consultants and outside lawyers for their roles
in the development of a $200 million high school, built near an
abandoned oilfield, that may never be finished because of
environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   District staff members and outside consultants misled school
board members on ``significant matters of fact, policy and law''
regarding the school, the Belmont Learning Complex, the report by
the Los Angeles Unified School District's Internal Audit and
Special Investigations Unit said. As a result, the report said,
former boards broke several state education, environmental and
hazardous-waste control laws by acquiring the land for the school
despite its hazardous conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommends disciplinary action _ possibly including
dismissal _ for nine officials, including the district's general
counsel, Richard Mason, and the chief administrative officer, David
Koch. It said the board should consider Superintendent Ruben
Zacarias' ``failure to supervise the Belmont project in a diligent,
professional and effective manner'' in his next performance review.
</P>
<P>
   ``The L.A.U.S.D. professional management and staff responsible
for Belmont, both past and present, developed and tolerated a
culture remarkably indifferent to compliance with environmental or
public health and safety standards, as well as a culture where
accountability for these standards was lax,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are certain to become another major embarrassment
for the district, which has been heavily criticized in recent
months for approving construction adjoining an abandoned oil field,
where dangerous concentrations of methane and hydrogen sulfide have
subsequently been found. The Board of Education, which has three
new members since the project was approved, has appointed a panel
to recommend whether to abandon the school altogether, after $125
million has been spent on it.
</P>
<P>
   Mason and Koch referred all questions to the superintendent's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias said in a statement Tuesday that he would ``consider my
full range of options for employee discipline up to and including
termination of employment,'' and would also look for organizational
or procedural changes. He also defended his role, citing several
changes in oversight he instituted, and sharply disagreed with the
report's assertion that he failed to oversee the project
adequately.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The report said companies hired to evaluate environmental
conditions at the school site breached their ``duty of professional
care'' to the district by failing to conduct tests properly.
</P>
<P>
   It also said an architectural firm retained by the district for
design advice, McLarand, Vasquez &AMP; Partners, engaged in a direct
conflict of interest by simultaneously seeking an architecture
contract from Belmont's developer, Temple Beaudry Partners LLC. A
partner with the architecture firm could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   O'Melveny &AMP; Myers LLP, a Los Angeles law firm that served as
outside counsel to the board, was criticized for recommending
Temple Beaudry Partners as an exclusive developer for the project
while it was representing a principal partner in Temple Beaudry,
Kajima Urban Development, on another matter.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, the firm said the report's criticism of
its work is ``unfounded, unfair and badly mistaken.'' It said it
had disclosed any potential conflict to district officials. ``We at
all times represented the L.A.U.S.D. capably and in compliance with
our professional and ethical obligations,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said Temple Beaudry misled city and state regulators
about environmental conditions and management of hazardous wastes
on the site, including failing to disclose its knowledge of methane
to the Los Angeles Fire Department for six months while continuing
construction. A lawyer for Temple Beaudry did not return a
telephone call.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2245 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-VERMONT-COLLEGE-ART-N     09-14 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-COLLEGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CATHOLIC WOMEN'S COLLEGE PRAYS FOR A MIRACLE
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: New England)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MARIALISA CALTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Vt. _ Last year, when reports of financial
instability surfaced at Trinity College of Vermont, a small Roman
Catholic liberal arts institution and the state's only women's
college, people in the academic community gathered occasionally to
pray for the welfare of the college.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the prayer meetings are held weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we've upped the ante,'' said Sister Jacqueline Marie
Kieslich, Trinity's newly appointed president. She began her job
just a few weeks ago, knowing that her task was to close the
college on June 30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been hoping for a miracle,'' said Donna Dalton, vice
president for academic and student affairs. ``A miracle would be
very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, Trinity's board announced that the 74-year-old college,
founded and run by the Sisters of Mercy, could no longer support a
$6 million debt _ due mostly to declining enrollment _ on a $13.2
million operating budget. At the end of the fiscal year, the
trustees declared, Trinity would cease to exist as an independent
institution for its 1,150 students.
</P>
<P>
   American colleges are ``incredibly hardy,'' in the words of
Terry W. Hartle, senior vice president of the American Council on
Education in Washington. Yet every year, two to three of the
country's estimated 3,500 two- and four-year colleges fall victim
to demographics or cultural trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``A school closing affects not only the students, faculty, staff
and alumni, but the community as well,'' Hartle said. ``Our
diversity of choices is diminished. And the community loses an
engine of economic and cultural vitality.''
</P>
<P>
   Next door to the comparatively more sprawling University of
Vermont, Trinity College sits on 28 acres of well-trimmed paths,
maple trees and neat, sensible brick buildings in a corner of
Vermont's largest city. Students stroll the grounds sporting
buttons with quotations from Gandhi (``An eye for an eye makes the
whole world blind''), John Lennon (``You may say I'm a dreamer, but
I'm not the only one'') or the occasional ``I am a sensuous
woman.'' There seem to be fewer body piercings than at most higher
education institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The college, which opened in 1925 to educate what was then an
underserved population _ Vermont women _ has long been a pioneer in
education and community service, with a stated mission to ``promote
social justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Trinity was among the first private colleges to
open its doors to older nontraditional students. In the 1980s, it
began a study program for single mothers. A campus-based child-care
center for the community serves as a laboratory for education
students. The college's education department, which has supplied
the state with an estimated 10 percent of its teachers, sends its
professors to Vermont elementary schools to teach graduate courses
on site. And every year, through a program endowed by a former
trustee, Trinity brings to the community speakers like Elie Wiesel,
Kenzaburo Oe, Maya Angelou, Joyce Carol Oates and Alice Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Students and faculty members are clearly reluctant to let these
programs die. They are, they point out, part of the reason that
U.S. News &AMP; World Report ranked Trinity in the top tier of Regional
Liberal Arts Colleges for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``My overwhelming feeling is of sadness, because no other
students will be able to experience what I have been able to
experience here,'' said Mattie Pontecorvo, a sophomore from
Woodstock, Vt. She described the Trinity experience as one of
empowerment and support.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are a student here, you feel like you can do
anything,'' said Ms. Pontecorvo, who is president of her class,
co-editor of the student newspaper, a member of the student senate,
and a resident assistant, in addition to being active in community
service projects sponsored by the college.
</P>
<P>
   She said the atmosphere at Trinity, ``where women support
women,'' had helped her assume leadership roles. ``I don't think I
would have been doing all these things in my second year at a co-ed
institution. I wouldn't have had the confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tosca Zern, a junior biology major from Shelton, Conn., frowned
over her computer during a physiology laboratory. She is worried,
she said, about her chances of getting into medical school if the
college closes. ``What about recommendations?'' she asked. ``What
about getting a degree from a place that will no longer exist? When
I say I'm going home, I mean I'm coming here. This place is home to
all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Campbell, a sophomore from Portland, Maine, whose
smiling visage graces the Trinity catalog, echoed the feelings of
many when she said she had returned ``determined to have the best
year ever, no matter what happens.'' She added, ``If Trinity
closes, these two years would definitely have been worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such expressions of optimism, using the word ``if,'' are ``what
we all need to be able to get up in the morning,'' said Sister
Kieslich.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Since the trustees' decision, administrators have been trying to
find a sponsoring institution to adopt some of the programs and
enable Trinity students to complete their degrees with as little
disruption as possible. Sister Kieslich said the college was
``exploring new relationships'' with other colleges, like merging,
forming partnerships or collaborating. Many administrators hope
talks with St. Michael's, a Catholic college in nearby Winooski,
will prove fruitful.
</P>
<P>
   But even the most optimistic Trinity booster seems to agree
that, come June 30, the college will cease to exist in its current
form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we were to receive a windfall, we would have to
re-evaluate our structure, concentrate on our strengths, and cull
some of our weaker programs,'' said Sister Kieslich. ``We can't
continue as we are.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While the number of graduate students has hovered at about 550,
the number of traditional-age undergraduates at Trinity fell from
415 in 1989 to 263 this year, and the number of nontraditional
undergraduates, who include older women and men, has dropped to 338
from 659 a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Jarvis, vice president for finance and administration,
said the reasons for the decline were unclear but might include a
turnover in the admissions department, an increase in choices for
nontraditional students and the waning popularity of single-sex
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the number of women's colleges has decreased to 77
from 300 in 1960. While those colleges that have hung on are
``quite competitive'' and are drawing increasing interest in recent
years, said Jadwiga Sebrechts, president of the Women's College
Coalition in Washington, an all-women's college must work
especially hard to ``tell its story'' and attract students.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jarvis said Trinity's financial problems were compounded by
the fact that to remain competitive, the college could not reduce
expenses, particularly in areas like technology, nor raise their
charges (about $21,400 for tuition, room, board and fees). In the
meantime, the relatively small endowment of $2 million has not
substantially increased.
</P>
<P>
   That would change, of course, if Peggy A. McCluskey, the
president of the alumni board, gets her wish. Ms. McCluskey, a 1960
Trinity graduate, has been buying lottery tickets in the hope of
winning money for her alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a miracle,'' she acknowledged. ``But if any school
deserves a miracle, it's Trinity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
