<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION-II-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NOW, A GENTLE NUDGE FROM HERRERA AND DE LA RENTA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Back in the late 1980s, in that opulent birthday cake
known as the Plaza, Oscar de la Renta and Carolina Herrera were
putting on the kind of fashion shows that practically sealed their
fate in swag. They were identified with it. A good-looking model,
coiffed, swathed up to her skinny chin in bows, would come
barreling down the runway, train her eyeballs on the room like a
howitzer and pivot in an insolent rustle of taffeta.
</P>
<P>
   And the funny thing was, Ms. Herrera herself dressed in a black
turtleneck and a smart pair of trousers as if to say, ``I have a
life.'' And de la Renta wasn't much different. He has his social
friends, but even now, when he's up at his place in Connecticut,
he's usually in a pastel polo shirt tooling around in his golf cart
to inspect the chicken coop. (The man has one.)
</P>
<P>
   So they have changed, and they haven't.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Ms. Herrera sent out a collection that was so much
like her personality _ at once practical and lavish _ that it
closed the gap between who she is and what she designs. You could
almost boil down her idea to a pair of pants and a top, except the
pants were in close-fitting shantung and the top was in suede or
maybe embroidered shantung, and fitted, in peony pink.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herrera had other ideas, too. Like a caftan embroidered in
deep pink and beige to resemble the pattern of Moorish tiles, and a
bisque patent-leather skirt with a pink asymmetrical halter. The
clothes were stridently young and sexy _ enough so to cause
whiplash in a client still clinging to her ladylike ideals. And
maybe there is something absurdly hopeful about expecting a woman
to wear a lemon suede bikini or a ball skirt two inches below her
navel. But, sex or swag _ which would you choose?
</P>
<P>
   ``So with the times,'' pronounced Crown Princess Pavlos of
Greece afterward.
</P>
<P>
   And strange as it must seem, these casual, chaotic times need
someone like Ms. Herrera, who lives the life of her customers, to
give modern sportswear a dressy, grown-up edge. Her silk pants may
have looked as casual as khakis, but her tops _ with belled
sleeves, a keyhole or a coy drawstring up one side _ looked like a
million bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, how many more T-shirts are you going to show _ tell
me!'' Ms. Herrera said.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing like an Oscar de la Renta show to bring on an
Edith Wharton moment. All the familiar faces were there _ Brooke
Astor, Mica Ertegun, Blaine Trump, Casey Ribicoff, Barbara Walters,
Kenneth Lane. Between this cheek and that cheek, Lane, the costume
jewelry king, didn't know whom to greet first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you telling everything?'' asked a friend passing through.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm kissing everything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the show started, against a backdrop of blue sky and
clouds. Out came models in lace-cut leather skirts with cashmere
sweaters, all in shades of pink, lemon and aqua, some sparkling
with clear stones. The models were moving along, in sporty denim
pants suits and shirtwaist dresses, when suddenly a lone figure
appeared on the edge of the runway. It was Nan Kempner, running
late. She scooted past the photographers. No one bellowed.
</P>
<P>
   The collection was carefree and summery, with lighthearted
details like rhinestones in a pick-up-sticks pattern on an ice-blue
satin skirt and Carmen Miranda florals that made the models look
like tall fruity drinks. De la Renta didn't push the youthful
message as far as Ms. Herrera, but the collection evoked something
of the life of New York, at least in its upper reaches.
</P>
<P>
   As Lane said on his way out, ``Clothes for the family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
