<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINIDAD COMES OUT OF SECLUSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ It was a historic occasion Tuesday afternoon in the
pre-fight hoopla surrounding the Felix Trinidad-Oscar De La Hoya
showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Trinidad actually opened up his workout session to a few
sportswriters, a few photographers and the usual nauseating gaggle
of hangers-on peculiar to boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Trinidad didn't do much other than shadow box, hit the heavy
bag and make the speed bag sing rhythmically before the viewers
were informed the room had to be cleared.
</P>
<P>
   But the mere fact that outside observers even were given
permission to take a glimpse at Trinidad was startling, since no
one previously had been allowed to enter Pavilion III at the Las
Vegas Hilton to watch Trinidad train since he arrived here from
Puerto Rico on Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tito (Trinidad's nickname) is concentrating solely on this
fight,'' explained his promoter, Don King. ``He's been
concentrating all his energies in getting ready to beat Oscar De La
Hoya. And, believe me , he's ready for it. Oscar De La Hoya is
going to be Cape Canaveral for Tito, his launching pad for
world-wide fame and fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felix's been the Invisible Man up to this fight, but he won't
be after it. After it, he will be known as the greatest fighter in
the world. He's going to knock Oscar De La Hoya out.''
</P>
<P>
   The opinions are divided among fistic scientists on this issue
the odds on the Saturday night match now stand even at 6-5, pick it
but there is no doubt that Trinidad is in peak condition.
</P>
<P>
   The anatomy of the 5-foot-11 IBF welterweight champion looks as
though it has been chiseled by a sculptor, the result of three
punishing months of preparing for De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad exudes an air of confidence, and those in his entourage
insist that he will be too strong and powerful for De La Hoya,
exactly the same sentiments echoed by those in De La Hoya's camp.
</P>
<P>
   During his brief Las Vegas stay, Trinidad already can lay claim
to a unique distinction being the first person to stay in Barron
Hilton's private suite at the Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not even Elvis Presley managed that feat,'' cracked King.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite allowing reporters to watch 30 minutes of his
workout Tuesday, Trinidad did not meet afterward with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll do his talking at the final press conference on
Wednesday,'' said his father, Don Felix Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   You must understand that Don Felix, a former Puerto Rican
featherweight champion and his son's trainer, does most of the
talking for the Trinidads.
</P>
<P>
   He did so again Tuesday, giving reporters an interview as his
son went through his regimen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a more domineering fight father than Felix
Trinidad's father,'' says Bob Arum, De La Hoya's promoter and a
reluctant partner in this promotion with King. ``He won't let Felix
be interviewed. He hasn't allowed anyone to watch his workouts.
Felix Trinidad can't do anything without his father's consent.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Trinidad has raised his son to be a boxer from
childhood, presenting him with a pair of boxing gloves as a
birthday gift when he was a mere five.
</P>
<P>
   At 12, Felix began his boxing career and would win five Puerto
Rican National Amateur championships (100 pounds, 112, 119, 126 and
132).
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, for a guy now celebrated for his power, he didn't
display much of it as a youngster. He had only 12 knockouts in
posting a 51-6 record.
</P>
<P>
   But that would change as soon as he turned professional on March
10, 1990, when he knocked out one Angel Romero in two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   He has been rendering opponents unconscious ever since with his
slashing left hooks and straight right hands on the way to a 35-0
ledger that includes 30 KOs.
</P>
<P>
   He also has become a national hero in his native Puerto Rico,
even surpassing the popularity of guys like Wilfredo Gomez and
Wilfredo Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trinidad can't walk anywhere in Puerto Rico without being
mobbed,'' says Bob Arum. ``There's no one there that's more famous.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Trinidad is so big in Puerto Rico that his fight with De
La Hoya is being piped into its four major prisons because
politicians feared there would be wide-spread rioting among the
inmates if it weren't shown.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran boxing publicist, Bill Caplan, recently took a group
of reporters to Puerto Rico to observe Trinidad none, natch, got to
see him spar and came away with the impression that not one person
on the entire Caribbean island envisions Trinidad losing to De La
Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every person you talk to thinks Trinidad's going to win and
going to win easily,'' says Caplan. ``If he happens to lose, it
will be a shock to the entire country because no one I talked to
thinks that will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an outlook is understandable considering how dominant
Trinidad has been throughout this decade.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't fought a lot of household names, and 24 of his fights
have gone four rounds or less.
</P>
<P>
   He beat both Pernell Whitaker and Hector (Macho) Camacho in 12
round decisions like De La Hoya did. And he knocked out Oba Carr
like De La Hoya did.
</P>
<P>
   Also like De La Hoya, who's been down four times, Trinidad's
chin has proven to be vulnerable, as he's been detached to the mat
six times.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Trinidad hasn't been down in the past four years,'' says
Bobby Goodman, the long-time fight publicist who now works for
King. ``I think he's matured as a fighter and also gotten
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   I saw Trinidad floored by Luis (Yory Boy) Campas in the second
round in a fight five years ago at the MGM Grand Garden, but such a
humiliation seemed to incite Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   He would pummel Campas unmercifully after that indignity,
stopping him in the fourth round after landing 12 unanswered
punches.
</P>
<P>
   He is a brawler who never takes a backward step, and Oscar De La
Hoya has told intimates such an aggressive style is perfect for
him.
</P>
<P>
   It might be, but Felix Trinidad hasn't given the faintest hint
during his remarkable career that he would be an easy opponent for
anyone, even Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
