u a BC-NY-POLLUTION-SUIT-1ST     09-14 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLLUTION-SUIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW ANTI-SMOG TACTIC, NEW YORK TO SUE POWER PLANTS IN OTHER
STATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: W.Va., Va., Ohio, Ind., Va., Ky., N.Y.)   (Subs grafs first, third and original 17th and 19th grafs to fix
time elements _Tuesday should become Wednesday _ and subs 6th graf
to remove incorrect reference to Gavin; subs 8th graf for more
info; subs 12th graf for clarification, then inserts 3 new grafs,
last of which identifies the companies that own the plants; story
is now 2 takes)  
 (bl)  
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York state is opening a new legal front in its
fight against pollution drifting from coal-burning power plants in
upwind states with an announcement Wednesday that it intends to sue
17 power plants to force them to clean up.
</P>
<P>
   This action would be the first by a state directly against
individual companies owning power plants that send pollution in the
air across state lines, according to federal environmental
officials and other experts. The Northeastern states and the
federal government have long battled to force these older plants,
mainly in the Midwest and the Virginias, to reduce their emissions,
but those efforts have faced a series of recent setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   In letters being sent Wednesday to the companies that own the
plants, Attorney General Eliot Spitzer of New York state gave
notice that he intends to sue them for failing to upgrade equipment
that cleans smokestack emissions when they made other big
investments in the plants. Such upgrades are required by the
federal Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, older plants were granted exemptions to the
stricter pollution standards required for newer ones, on the theory
that they would shut down in a few years anyway. But the clean air
law always contained provisions requiring power companies to seek a
permit and install better pollution controls if they substantially
upgraded these aging plants.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Spitzer said he could prove that significant
improvements had been made to equipment at the plants that
increased their lifespan and their output of both electricity and
pollution, but no permits were sought and no new pollution controls
added. The plants are located in West Virginia, Ohio, Indiana,
Virginia and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   They include some of the biggest single sources of air pollution
in the country, with one plant in Ohio emitting more smog-causing
nitrogen oxides than all of the dozen or so coal-burning plants in
New York state, according to federal emissions records.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, New York and other Northeastern states had focused on
direct negotiations with upwind states over cutting smog, on
efforts to pass federal acid rain laws, and suits and petitions
aimed at forcing the federal Environmental Protection Agency to
stop pollution created in one place from adding to problems in
another.
</P>
<P>
   But the last round of state-to-state negotiations broke down two
weeks ago, no new acid rain laws are likely soon, and a round of
maneuvers in federal court by the states hosting the old coal
plants has delayed new EPA action to staunch the pollution flow. In
light of those problems, Spitzer decided to pursue the individual
suits, an approach his staff had been studying for some time. Those
suits would be filed in federal court, but where exactly has not
been decided, Spitzer's staff said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said the new move is based on concrete facts about
changes at the plants, and thus should avoid some of the legal
snags that have delayed other efforts. ``The other actions involve
esoteric legal issues of jurisdiction and power,'' he said. ``We're
enmeshed there too. But this cuts right to the source.''
</P>
<P>
   When told of the impending legal action by New York, officials
at the EPA, which is conducting its own investigation of
investments and pollution at many coal-fired power plants, did
everything but cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, we are absolutely supportive of any state's effort
to secure cleaner for its citizens,'' said EPA spokesman David
Cohen. ``We encourage the use of all legal tools available, and we
at EPA are doing everything possible, given constraints from recent
court decisions brought by polluters that have attempted to
frustrate our work.''
</P>
<P>
   But representatives of the coal-power industry said they were
confident that they would prevail in court against the New York
suits.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Under the Clean Air Act, older plants were granted exemptions to
the stricter pollution standards required for newer ones, on the
theory that they would close in a few years anyway. But the law
requires companies to seek a permit and install better pollution
controls if they substantially upgrade aging plants.
</P>
<P>
   Federal environmental officials said that they had used the same
provisions of the Clean Air Act several years ago to force changes
at large pulp mills that upgraded but did not cut pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The plants are owned by American Electric Power of Columbus,
Ohio; Cinergy Corp. of Cincinnati; Ohio Edison Co.; Northern
Indiana Public Service Co., Virginia Electric Power Co. and
Monongahela Power Co. of Morgantown, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of the 17 plants named in the suit are owned by American
Electric Power of Columbus, Ohio, and officials there, when told of
Spitzer's plans Tuesday, said the investments made at their old
plants were strictly to improve reliability and to keep up with
rising demand for electricity.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of the maintenance work we do,'' said Pat Hemlepp,
a spokesman for American Electric Power. ``We're required by state
regulators to deliver reliable power to our customers. If what they
are questioning is whether we have done maintenance, yes, we have.
Have me made improvements that would increase capacity? No.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's staff contends otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the attorney general built their cases over the past
few months by collecting data from a wide array of federal and
state utility and environmental agencies that track the budgets,
construction projects, and pollution levels at plants, said Peter
Lehner, the top environmental lawyer in Spitzer's office. He said
consultants familiar with the energy industry helped pinpoint
instances where work was not simply done to replace old gear, but
to improve on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of this case is solid and fair,'' Lehner said.
``When an old plant's life is significantly extended, it has to
play closer to the rules of the new plants.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, he provided some details about changes at one
West Virginia plant, which Lehner said he preferred not to identify
until the letters were sent out Wednesday. Records filed with the
Ohio Public Service Commission and federal energy officials show
that from 1988 to 1992, boilers for three generators were virtually
rebuilt, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the years following the work, power generation at the plant
more than doubled, he said, resulting in a corresponding rise in
emissions of nitrogen oxides and sulfur oxides, which contribute to
smog and acid rain, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement may not end up playing out in a court
case, Lehner and others involved in the investigation said. The
plant owners could negotiate a settlement with New York in the
60-day waiting period required before such suits are filed, or they
could negotiate directly with the EPA some agreement to improve
pollution controls at the plants in question, lawyers in the
attorney general's office said.
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible that the EPA could wrap up its own
simultaneous investigation of potential violations of pollution
laws and take one or more of the plant owners to court in the
meantime.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And New York and other Northeastern states still are pursuing
other actions, including petitioning the EPA directly to force
individual power plants to clean up pollution. In New York, the
pressure on the Clinton administration has come not from Spitzer,
who is a Democrat, but from the state Department of Environmental
Conservation, which _ unlike the attorney general's office _
operates at the pleasure of Gov. George Pataki, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Pataki administration officials declined to comment on
Spitzer's initiative, preferring to highlight the work being done
to put pressure on the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   If the lawsuits go to court, they are likely to be hard fought,
said David Flannery, a lawyer and spokesman for the Midwest Ozone
Group, a coalition of coal and power companies.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the action by New York and the ongoing
investigations of work at the old power plants by the EPA would not
change a basic reality _ that much of the pollution in the
Northeast is generated there, not carried on the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There still isn't any good science showing otherwise,''
Flannery said.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said his main goal is to clean the air. He added that
his office was planning similar actions against heavily polluting
power plants in New York state, as well. ``We're looking at
everyone,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 23:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2314 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      09-14 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SISTER TELLS OF LAST VISIT WITH BYRD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRYAN, Texas _ A sister of a black man who was dragged to death
near Jasper last year took the stand Tuesday in white supremacist
Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr.'s capital murder trial to tell jurors
about the last time she saw her brother.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Verrett of Houston identified James Byrd Jr.'s shirt,
shoes, watch and keys, and said that the day before Byrd was
chained to a pickup and dragged down a rural road, she had given
him some new clothes. Byrd, whom she called by his nickname,
``Son,'' had promptly tried them on and modeled for her, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He paraded in front of me and said, `What do you think?''' she
remembered. ``I told him he looked good.''
</P>
<P>
   And when she was shown a baseball cap found at the crime scene
June 7, 1998, Verrett smiled and identified it as a souvenir that
her sister, Mylinda Washington, had given to Byrd after returning
from a family vacation to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``You all loved him very much?'' asked Assistant U.S. Attorney
Johnny Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was part of us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Verrett was among 12 witnesses to take the stand during the
second day of testimony in Brewer's trial, which was moved to
Brazos County at his lawyers' request.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, several law enforcement officers testified
how they had collected evidence, including beer bottles, a can of
black spray paint and cigarette butts from the crime scene and
shoes, pornographic photos and notebooks containing racist
literature from the apartment of Brewer's co-defendant, John
William ``Bill'' King.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors also got their first look at color slides of Brewer's
tattoos, which include an eagle, a pentagram, a burning cross, a
swastika, the words ``death before dishonor'' and the ``patch'' or
symbol of the Confederate Knights of America, a racist prison gang
affiliated with the Ku Klux Klan. Brewer, an ex-con who served time
for burglary and parole violations, was a top official, the
``Exalted Cyclops,'' of the CKA at the Beto I prison unit in
Tennessee Colony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not illegal to have tattoos,'' Jasper County District
Attorney Guy James Gray said after leaving the courtroom for the
day. ``But it's an expression of the degree of their white
supremacy. It's one thing to say white supremacist words. It's
another to belong to a white supremacist gang. It's one step
further when you tattoo that message on your body. That's
permanent.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brewer's attorneys, Doug Barlow and Layne Walker of
Beaumont, downplayed the significance of the tattoos, pointing out
on cross-examination that there could be several interpretations of
their meaning. And they reminded jurors of another tattoo that had
earlier been shown on an overhead projector. That tattoo, an image
of a woman on Brewer's chest, depicted a friend of Brewer's family
whom he knew from his church growing up, Barlow said.
</P>
<P>
   The defense team also picked at the evidence-gathering
techniques of several law officers, criticizing Jasper County
sheriff's office investigator Tommy Robinson because he did not
change his gloves each time he picked up a new piece of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you agree with me that you were in way over your
heads?'' Walker asked him on cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   ``No sir, I wouldn't agree with that,'' Robinson replied.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also showed jurors a color photo of Brewer's toe,
which was bruised and swollen when he was booked into the Jasper
County Jail the day after Byrd's dismembered, decapitated corpse
was found on Huff Creek Road near a black cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors also were told that a shoe with the initials ``L.B.'' on
the tongue and what appeared to be blood on the toe was found at
King's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Gray later indicated that DNA evidence from the shoe would help
link Brewer to the crime. An FBI expert in DNA evidence testified
during King's trial in Jasper last February that Brewer's tennis
shoe was stained with Byrd's blood.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's genetic blueprint, testimony in that trial indicated,
was found on a beer bottle and a cigarette butt found at the crime
scene.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of capital murder, Brewer, 32, would face life in
prison or death by injection.
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, was convicted by a Jasper County jury last February
and was sent to death row. A third defendant, Shawn Allen Berry,
24, will be tried later this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
