<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2361 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-MAIN-1STUPDATE-     09-14 1831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-MAIN-1STUPDATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Floyd packing mighty winds as it threatens Atlantic coast
 &HT;    (EDS: UPDATES; CORRECTS writer's name to Rochell in tagline;
Barnes &AMP; Noble; Chick-fil-A.)
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Florida's day of reckoning starts this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Massive and menacing, Hurricane Floyd began buffeting Florida's
east coast Tuesday afternoon with strong winds and heavy rain. But
the real onslaught should come today.
</P>
<P>
   However, Floyd took a favorable northerly turn Tuesday evening,
perhaps keeping the storm's sustained winds of 140 mph farther
offshore than first thought.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions changed through the night, but it was generally
forecast that the center of Floyd could come within 30 miles of the
central Florida coast. That close brush would leave coastal cities
such as Melbourne and Cape Canaveral exposed to winds of up to 100
mph and a potential storm surge of 15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   While Florida started to feel the punishment from the powerful
storm, the Georgia and South Carolina coasts braced for a possible
landfall by late tonight or early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bahamas felt Floyd's full fury Tuesday as the hurricane
easily uprooted 30-foot trees and sent blinding, horizontal sheets
of rain through deserted streets. The fierce winds shoved autos
around, snapped palm trees and set car alarms screeching throughout
Nassau.
</P>
<P>
   Extensive reports of damage and possible injuries or fatalities
could not be easily determined because most communication to the
islands was lost.
</P>
<P>
   But this much is already known about Floyd: It's one of the
worst storms many longtime weather watchers can remember. By the
time it becomes a whisper, Floyd may go down as one of the largest,
most destructive storms to hit the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very dangerous storm,'' said Jeremy Pennington, a
meteorologist with the National Hurricane Center. ``We don't see
many Category 4 intensity storms striking the U.S. mainland and
certainly not one as large as this.''
</P>
<P>
   A clerk at the Avis rental car counter at Orlando International
Airport summed it up when she told a customer: ``Things that are
standing today aren't going to be standing tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how much is still standing in the Bahamas remains to be
seen, perhaps as early as today.
</P>
<P>
   Bahamian defense officials met Tuesday to plan cleanup and
relief efforts, and all defense personnel were ordered to report to
duty this morning, according to radio reports from the islands.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton did not wait for the storm to hit U.S. soil to
issue a pre-emptive disaster declaration for Florida and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The early declaration ``enables state and local governments to
get equipment and other things ... in place to begin recovery
efforts at the earliest possible moment,'' White House spokesman
Barry Toiv said in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd stranded thousands of travelers throughout the nation
Tuesday as airlines grounded hundreds of flights. Most of the
passengers were headed to or from Florida, where a handful of
airports closed. Some train service on the East Coast also was
suspended.
</P>
<P>
   An indication of how seriously Floyd is being taken could be
found Tuesday at a deserted Disney World, which closed its gates
due to weather for the first time in its 28-year history. Other
Orlando-area resorts such as Universal Studios and SeaWorld also
shut down.
</P>
<P>
   With a storm that is more than 500 miles wide, hurricane-force
winds of at least 74 mph could reach as far inland as Orlando, 60
miles west of Daytona Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Orange County Commission Chairman Mel Martinez, whose community
includes Disney World and other theme parks, urged evacuation _ and
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should call for higher help,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona Beach construction worker Rick Ross placed his faith in
plywood and nails. The 40-year-old lives just west of the Atlantic
Ocean, which crept a block closer to the Daytona Beach shore than
usual by Tuesday afternoon _ and Floyd was still 300 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   From a playground parking lot overlooking the frothing,
white-capped ocean, Ross watched the thundering surf with his black
labrador-chow-shepherd mix, Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live right up the street. Everything I own is there,'' Ross
said. ``I'm not going to leave it.''
</P>
<P>
   On International Speedway Boulevard, a mix of hotels, strip
malls and the home track of the Daytona 500 NASCAR race, most
businesses shut down early Tuesday, if they opened at all. The road
was already littered with broken branches.
</P>
<P>
   Hooters was closed. So was Barnes &AMP; Noble, Chick-fil-A, Sears
and Dillard's. KFC and Wendy's served the lunch crowd before
letting its employees make their storm preparations. Hotel clerks
turned away guests, saying they'd need to drive at least an hour
west to find accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   The big business was at Home Depot, which opened a register
outside to handle demand for 4 X 8 sheets of plywood. Seventeen
minutes before the 2 p.m. closing time Tuesday, the line was 18
deep.
</P>
<P>
   Former Volusia County lifeguard Tim Johnson stood in the middle
of the plywood line. His family lives in Port Orange just west of
the Intracoastal Waterway, less than 1 mile from the beach. Johnson
ordered 14 sheets at $14.97 a piece
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping we get the outskirts,'' Johnson said. ``If it gets
too bad, we'll try and head somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Kmart on Semoran Boulevard in Orlando, residents bought
33-gallon trash cans to store water.
</P>
<P>
   Inland shelters filled up quickly. Even pets sought refuge, and
Osceola County animal shelters filled up with 700 pets by late
afternoon. After 6 p.m., officials in Seminole County urged
residents to boil their drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Along Central Florida's Space Coast, the streets of small beach
towns from Melbourne north to the Kennedy Space Center were empty
of all but the last stragglers, who motored through blustery winds
on their way to bridges leading to the mainland. Mandatory
evacuation orders were issued Monday, and heavy traffic choked
highways leading west toward Orlando all that night and into
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses were boarded up with plywood, along with houses
facing the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   A big worry on the barrier island was storm surge. In Cocoa
Beach, State Road A1A skirts just along the top of the dune line,
with one row of homes perched just over the beach, most about 10 to
15 feet above the waterline.
</P>
<P>
   By midday Tuesday, huge waves were pounding the dune, splashing
foam and sea mist onto the beachfront houses. Chronic erosion
problems have left many homeowners with little more than sea walls
to protect their property.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's breaking a mile out already,'' said Mike Brown, 48, who
runs a small cleaning business in Cocoa Beach and lives one block
from the ocean. ``It's looking like it wants to top the dune.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Kennedy Space Center, 12,500 workers were evacuated,
leaving behind 102 employees who volunteered to ride out Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's four space shuttles _ worth $2 billion each _ were inside
hangars, but officials were worried that the buildings are not
capable of withstanding winds of more than 125 mph. Officials also
were worried about four unmanned rockets already on launch pads
that could not be moved to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Workers placed protective towers around the rockets and secured
them to their pads as best they could.
</P>
<P>
   There were also fears that rising waters from Floyd's storm
surge might inundate the facility. Most of the launch complex and
processing buildings are less than 10 feet above sea level, and
forecasters said Floyd might kick up waves of 20 feet or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a direct hit on us, or even a skirting hit, we could
lose a great deal,'' said NASA spokesman Bruce Buckingham.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 miles up the coast, lifelong St. Simons Island
resident Jamie Gould IV said he will ride out Floyd on the
low-lying barrier island. The Gould family has seen storms: Gould's
great-great grandfather built the island's landmark lighthouse more
than a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gould said he disobeyed a mandatory evacuation order that went
into effect for Glynn County around noon Tuesday because an elderly
neighbor with cancer could not be budged from his home.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't leave Mr. Jimmy,'' Gould said. ''We'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   By late Tuesday, however, most of the Georgia island's 18,000
year-round residents and more than a few late summer vacationers
had crossed the four-mile long causeway to the mainland on the
first leg of what quickly became a crowded trip west.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes declared a state of emergency for the entire
coast Tuesday. Gale-force winds were expected to begin raking St.
Simons around dawn today and winds as high as 125 miles an hour
could hit by this evening, said Ed Abel, Glynn's emergency
management director.
</P>
<P>
   Abel said barrier islands and low-lying areas could be awash and
battered by wind-driven waves if the storm surge reaches its
projected 9 to 15 feet over mean sea level.
</P>
<P>
   During the afternoon Tuesday, most islanders packed their cars,
moved patio furniture indoors, boarded or taped windows and headed
west.
</P>
<P>
   Darlene McCabe, a computer teacher at Glynn Middle School in
Brunswick, finished her packing and played Frisbee at an island
park with friends.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm having to leave all my house plants, my yard sale
treasures and my three cats behind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   McCabe said she fears the hurricane will devastate the island's
magnificent live oak forest.
</P>
<P>
   ''Take a good, long look at these trees,'' she said. ''I just
hope they'll be here when we come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipation also was felt in South Carolina, where Charleston
Mayor Joseph Riley declared a state of emergency. Starting today,
the city will be under curfew from 7 p.m. to 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Riley spent Tuesday warning that Floyd threatens to flood
low-lying areas spared by Hugo in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   If Floyd makes landfall southwest of Charleston, near Beaufort
and Edisto Island, tidal surges of 12 to 18 feet could hit
Charleston, Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   The city's mayor for 23 years, Riley is particularly worried
that some residents don't appreciate the possible danger.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, 56, said Floyd is following a course similar to a
hurricane in 1893 that killed 1,500 to 2,000 people in coastal
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real killer is the surge, the almost instantaneous rush of
water into areas where people do not expect it,'' Riley said.
``They do not call this the low country for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Plywood covered the tall arched windows of Charleston's City
Hall and other historic buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Floyd go back to Mayberry,'' read a message scrawled on a
board over the window of the Four Corners Cafe on Broad Street.
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Mike Williams, Jingle Davis, Chris Burritt, Anne
Rochell Konigsmark and the Associated Press contributed to this
report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
