<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MICH-SYRACUSE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SYRACUSE TRIES 2 UNDERCLASSMEN TO SUCCEED McNABB  
 (bl)  
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Replacing Donovan McNabb as Syracuse quarterback would be
difficult for even a highly touted upperclassman with obvious
talent and impressive size. It would seem harder to replace a
four-year fixture like McNabb with an undersized redshirt freshman
who was lightly recruited at this position outside the Ivy League.
</P>
<P>
   But this could be the case for the Orangemen, who risk their
undefeated record Saturday night against undefeated Michigan in the
Carrier Dome. Once again the Syracuse starter is expected to be
Troy Nunes, now with 182 pounds on his 6-foot frame, up from 163
pounds last season.
</P>
<P>
   Nunes is one of two quarterbacks expected to share the position
for the third consecutive game. The other is Madei Williams, a
sophomore who has not yet conceded the first-string position.
Michigan, which lost at home to Syracuse last season, is also
expected to use two quarterbacks, with fifth-year senior Tom Brady
and sophomore Drew Henson again taking turns.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback rotation seems to be in fashion on many campuses
this season, at least until conference schedules, performance
differences and injuries force coaches to make choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't know if it's a trend,'' said Syracuse coach Paul
Pasqualoni of the two-quarterback system. ``The teams that are
doing it probably have two guys who deserve to play or deserve to
be evaluated. It has worked out for us so we are going to continue
it. We are comfortable with that. It is still early in the year.
They both had a chance to play Saturday and both did some really
nice things.''
</P>
<P>
   In that game, a 47-7 victory over Central Michigan, Nunes
completed 8 of 13 passes, 3 of them for touchdowns, for 170 yards.
Williams was 5 of 6 for 91. Williams was last year's backup to
McNabb, a versatile and charismatic star who was chosen with the
second pick of the National Football League draft by the
Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' chances were hurt this summer in training camp by an
injury to his left hand, although he throws with his right.
Speaking by telephone yesterday, he said the injury ``kind of cut
down on my reps as far as assuming the starting quarterback role,''
as he missed a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to get the opportunity to get out on the field and
make the plays I do make,'' he said. ``Right now I'm just battling
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who dislocated and cut the little finger of his left
hand, said that the first-string job was ``definitely a
possibility'' for him and that he and Nunes had a good
relationship. They played against each other in high school in the
Pittsburgh area.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the outside looking in, it might seem like it would be
hard,'' Williams said. ``But we get along. We get along just fine.
There's no legitimate starter now. Even though he's playing well,
I'm playing well myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Williams improved in Game 2. In the first game, a
35-12 victory over Toledo, Williams fumbled three times, partly a
result of his hand injury. He did not fumble Saturday. ``Madei got
better,'' Pasqualoni said, ``and Troy did also.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer break and again this week, McNabb visited campus
and spoke to both. Nunes said McNabb ``told me and Madei to do what
you can and not put any more pressure on yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to do all the stuff he did,'' Nunes said. ``It
will be difficult. He's one of the best the university has ever
seen. We know what we're following.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is 6 feet 2 inches and 202 pounds. Nunes is
considerably smaller, and the head coach was asked about his size
this week. ``The line and the backs really blocked the blitzes,''
he said. ``I think that is probably the most important factor as
opposed to are you tall or short.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the season began, Nunes spoke of the first-string role.
He said Syracuse followers conceded the job to Madei, and
acknowledged that it was ``hard for me to take.''
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Pasqualoni said: ``If there's one clear
quarterback, nobody in America is a two-quarterback guy. When it's
gray, it's easy to say you're a two-quarterback guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan is also dealing with two quarterbacks, although Brady
is a returning starter. Henson, a Yankees baseball prospect, has
come off the bench in the first half in both Michigan victories,
over Notre Dame and Rice. In a telephone interview from Ann Arbor,
Mich., this week, Brady said: ``We're very solid at the quarterback
position. We both have experience. We've both been in big games.''
He said he was not bothered by having competition for the job.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised interview last week, Henson said, ``We may not be
the best of friends, but we have tremendous respect for each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady said the biggest difference between them is three years in
age. ``We are good friends,'' Brady said. ``You kind of develop
your close relationships with people who are more your age. But,
obviously, I have a great amount of respect for Drew. I'm always
rooting for him just as I'm sure he's always rooting for me. Our
goal is to win football games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
