r s BC-GLF-STOCKTON-SENIORS-     09-14 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-STOCKTON-SENIORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKTON HOPES TO GET BACK INTO SWING OF THINGS ON SENIOR TOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES CLINES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When Dave Stockton awoke Jan. 1, not all of his golf
game entered the new year with him. He just didn't know it at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Bizarre is the only way Stockton can describe his 1999 Senior
PGA Tour season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 16 top 10 finishes last year, and I haven't had a one
this year,'' he said yesterday after playing a practice round at
Bent Tree Country Club, site of this week's Bank One Championship.
</P>
<P>
   With 11 finishes in the top 25 this season, Stockton's game
hasn't been rotten enough to dump into the trash, but it hasn't
satisfied the eight-year Senior Tour veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been by far my worst year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the Senior Tour, he finished in the top 10 at
least nine times (1997) and as many as 24 times (1995) a season.
During that time he has recorded 14 victories, so it's no surprise
his play this season has him concerned.
</P>
<P>
   It got so bad for Stockton that he summoned his son, Ron, from
competing on the mini-tours 21/2 months ago to follow him around
and see if he could help cure his ailing game.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton said he has found the root of his problem, and will tee
off Friday in the first round with more confidence than he has had
all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, I'm fine. I think most of my problems have been
mental,'' he said. ``I've had too many \Rswing\S ideas, and I've
been trying too hard. I have to relax more and just let it
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his play last week at the Comfort Classic in
Indianapolis was solid, and he tied for 19th, which was his third
consecutive tournament to finish in the top 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with Tom Watson two rounds, and I really played
good,'' Stockton said of his pairing with the senior rookie who
finished in a tie for 22nd. ``I'm encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockton said part of the reason for his so-so season could be
attributed to a couple of family situations in the past year that
caused him to miss playing on some of his favorite courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, my older son's wife had a baby that was about 21/2
months premature,'' Stockton said. He curtailed his playing to be
with his son, David, and family as the baby had to undergo stomach
surgery and survive pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baby's fine, now, and just celebrated her first
birthday,'' Stockton said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, this year, his wife's 87-year-old mother was seriously
injured after a fall, and died almost three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent more time at home because of all this,'' said
Stockton, who has played in 19 events this season. ``But I have no
reason to not be playing good now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we're back in Dallas,'' said Stockton, who won the
Muratec Reunion Pro-Am in 1993 at Stonebriar Country Club in
Frisco. ``I like it here and I like the course. I feel like I could
have a good week.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the seniors played at Bent Tree was in 1988 when
the Reunion Pro-Am ended a four-year stay, and that was before
Stockton was old enough to play.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990914.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
