u w BC-TRAVEL-Y2K-NYT &LR;      09-14 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Y2K-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL TIP FOR JAN. 1, 2000: STAY HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The people at the State Department did their best
to be diplomatic Tuesday, but there was no getting away from the
message: Saturday, Jan. 1, 2000, may not be the best day to travel
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The department said it was preparing detailed advisories
covering 194 countries and how they are dealing with the inexorable
approach of the next millennium and the problems that may befall
computers come New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials were cautious in their language,
emphasizing that the advisories in no way constitute warnings not
to go to certain places, but are meant to foster preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of State has no greater responsibility than to
insure to the best of our ability the safety and security of U.S.
citizens traveling around or residing abroad,'' Kevin Herbert, the
director of overseas citizens services in the department's bureau
of consular affairs, told a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, he issued a reminder that whatever computer
complications occur in the switch to the year 2000 just might be
more serious than, say, an annoyance with an airline-reservations
agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``In countries that are not sufficiently prepared,'' Herbert
warned, computer problems could affect vital functions like medical
services, telecommunications, and electricity and water, as well as
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   China, Russia and India are among the biggest countries that may
be susceptible to mixups, the State Department said.
Country-by-country advisories are at the Bureau of Consular Affairs
site: http://travel.state.gov/travelwarnings.html
</P>
<P>
   To assess how other countries are meeting the computer
challenge, the department has been collecting data from American
embassies around the world for nearly a year. It said it will post
updates whenever appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the prognosis all bleak. Australia, for example, is rated
well prepared to deal with any computer problems that may come up,
whether they be in government, industry, transportation or other
services.
</P>
<P>
   While the State Department did not point it out, Australia may
even provide a hint of just how serious the problems will be.
</P>
<P>
   The New Year, and the new millennium, will arrive in Sydney 15
hours before it does in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
