<SLUG> BC-NFL-L.A.-EXPAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. FLAWS PUT NFL EXPANSION IN LIMBO
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas) ( nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In three weeks, the National Football League is supposed to
award its 32nd franchise to Los Angeles or Houston. On further
review, it may defer the choice until November.
</P>
<P>
   Or it could stick with 31 teams.
</P>
<P>
   League officials met Monday with representatives of three Los
Angeles suitors and the prospective Houston owner and decided that
the franchise hunt is still as wide open as the Vikings' passing
attack, and that the owners will vote on Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Any possibility of conferring a franchise on either city
Wednesday is impossible, although Wednesday had originally been
cited as the deadline. The league voted, 29-2, last March that its
expansion committee would recommend making Houston the 32nd team if
Los Angeles did not have a stadium site, a plan to build and
finance a stadium and commitments by the business community to
support a franchise by Wednesday. But it did not specify when the
committee would make its report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL hasn't ruled anyone out, and hasn't ruled anyone in,''
said Gregg Davis, who met with league officials Monday on behalf of
his father, Marvin, the billionaire oilman, to pitch Hollywood
Park, a race track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we have the most plausible site,'' said Davis, a
sensible position given the track's abundant land and parking. The
enormous cost of building garages near the L.A. Memorial Coliseum
led the league last month to end its exclusive focus on the
Raiders' and Rams' former home and widen its vistas to Hollywood
Park and Carson, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's wide open _ and all sites are under active
consideration,'' said Greg Aiello, a spokesman for the league.
``It's a matter of someone stepping up with a plan that can get 24
votes from owners.''
</P>
<P>
   The league wants to return to Los Angeles because it is the
nation's second-largest TV market and to prove that the problems
that sent the Raiders back to Oakland and the Rams to Anaheim and
then St. Louis, were more about ownership than a lack of fan
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion guarantees an infusion of cash; splitting an expansion
fee of perhaps $600 million 31 ways would mean $19.5 million a
team.
</P>
<P>
   Now the expansion process must be crammed into three weeks; it
started Monday with league officials describing the steps it would
take until owners meet Oct. 5 to 6, and asking how much of an
expansion fee the suitors would pay. Last week, NFL Commissioner
Paul Tagliabue said the fee would be more than the $476 million Al
Lerner paid for the Cleveland Browns. Lerner paid $54 million more
to defray the cost of building a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' group did not present a plan to develop land at Hollywood
Park for a stadium on Monday, and there is a suspicion inside the
league that Davis is more a window shopper than a serious buyer.
Davis owns an option to buy land at the race track for $60 million,
but must renew his option by Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is little time to make his case for Hollywood
Park, Gregg Davis said that ``we feel very confident about doing a
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coliseum plan from Ed Roski Jr., a real-estate developer,
and Eli Broad, a financial services magnate, is well known to the
league but no longer tantalizing.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ovitz, the Hollywood talent manager, had once trumpeted
the Carson option, but ``his interest is in being an owner and
operator in Los Angeles and he'll do it wherever it needs to be
done,'' Aiello said.
</P>
<P>
   The league met last week with Carson officials, who would invest
$180 million in a stadium and mall on a former landfill that needs
a $35 million cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our proposal is there,'' said Daryl Sweeney, a Carson City
councilman. ``We don't have to start from scratch like Hollywood
Park. We're cautiously optimistic, but we're not interested in
being dragged around. If we're in play, we can move instantly into
formation.''
</P>
<P>
   The only obstacle-free course for the league is in Houston, the
11th-largest television market, where Robert McNair is ready with a
$310 million stadium plan that has $195 million in public money on
tap. His only problem is that Houston is not Los Angeles, an
entertainment mecca that the league feels incomplete without.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is that Sept. 15 was the deadline and any decision
will be based on where the parties are at that time,'' McNair said.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. The league will accept more information through
Oct. 5 on Hollywood Park and Carson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all need to admit that it's time to bring this thing to a
conclusion,'' McNair said. ``I'm not going to do this for the rest
of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
