<HEADLINE>
SUNDAY'S COMEBACK RANKS HIGH IN COWBOYS LORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Three days have passed since the Cowboys' 41-35
overtime comeback, and I still can't believe the Redskins left
speedy receiver Raghib Ismail that wide open on the clinching
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   That's seemingly as implausible as the Redskins' unthinkable
bobble on their potential game-winning field-goal attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Just ahead of these incidents on the incredulous meter is that
the Cowboys won the game after trailing 35-14 in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Add the memory of receiver Michael Irvin becoming the playmaker
again with two fourth-quarter touchdowns, the fourth-quarter calm
and perfection of quarterback Troy Aikman and running back Emmitt
Smith's ``I want the ball'' intensity, and what you have are
lasting images of one of the greatest games in Cowboys history.
</P>
<P>
   At least so says a certain former baby photographer who served
as the Cowboys' scouting director from 1959-1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the great ones,'' said Gil Brandt, now a
scouting analyst for NFL.com.
</P>
<P>
   So move over, Hail Mary, make room for Double-Dive 132, the play
call on Ismail's dash to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman and Ismail, likewise, achieve places alongside 1974
Thanksgiving Day cult heroes Clint ``The Mad Bomber'' Longley and
receiver Drew Pearson, who also hauled in Roger Staubach's Hail
Mary pass against the Vikings in the 1975 divisional playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Brandt, whose vast experience with the Cowboys has taught him to
never give up, said he wasn't surprised by the comeback, which he
called ``one of the greatest not just in Cowboys history but ever
in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought it was over,'' Brandt said. ``I might have
thought it was over if you were going against a real good defense.
I might have thought it was over if you didn't have so many weapons
on offense. Maybe if you didn't have so many receivers that could
make big plays or a run-of-the-mill running back or some Billy Joe
Tolliver at quarterback, it's over. But with Aikman and those guys,
you have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   What's also certain is that for much of their 40-year history,
the Cowboys have always seemingly made most of their chances,
despite impossible situations.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's outing was just the latest in a long line of great
Cowboys finishes. Here are a few others to jog your memory bank:
</P>
<P>
   Thanksgiving Day in 1974 will be forever remembered for rookie
quarterback Longley and, as teammate Blaine Nye said, ``the triumph
of an uncluttered mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Longley had never thrown a regular-season pass, nor did he have
a good grasp of the Cowboys offense before being forced into action
in the third quarter because of an injury to starter Roger
Staubach.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he rallied the Cowboys from a 16-3 deficit to a 24-23
victory, capped by a 50-yard touchdown pass to Pearson in the final
30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Hail Mary was the proper name for the situation facing the
Cowboys on a bitterly cold December day in Minnesota in 1975.
Trailing 14-10 against the heavily favored Vikings, the Cowboys got
the ball on their own 9-yard-line with less than two minutes to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Staubach threw five passes on the drive _ all to Pearson. The
last one was literally a prayer. Lined up at ]midfield with 24
seconds left, Staubach threw a long pass down the right sideline.
Pearson faked inside then raced to the corner. As the badly
underthrown ball came down, there was contact between Pearson and
Vikings cornerback Nate Wright, who fell down. Pearson caught it on
his hip at the 5-yard line and stepped backward into the end zone
as the Cowboys won, 17-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had more of an eerie sensation on a football field,''
said Staubach, who told news reporters he had said a ``Hail Mary''
before throwing the pass. ``It was as if we were playing in an
empty stadium. The silence was deafening.''
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 16, 1979, Staubach played his final regular-season game.
And the hated Redskins were in town to decide the NFC East title.
</P>
<P>
   If that wasn't motivation enough, then add in the backdrop of a
funeral wreath sent to Cowboys defensive end Harvey Martin earlier
in the week wishing him ``sympathy for an impending loss''.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys fell behind 17-0 in the second quarter and trailed
34-21 late in the fourth. Staubach, however, began to work his
magic again. A 30-yard touchdown pass to Ron Springs cut the score
to 34-28. The game-winner came on a 7-yard pass to Tony Hill in the
final minute.
</P>
<P>
   After the 35-34 victory, Martin marched to the Redskins locker
room and tossed the wreath into the middle of their prayer and told
them to ``take this damn thing back to Washington with you.''
Yardsticks \Nsubheds:Defense anyone?
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys and Redskins combined for 1,045 yards _ 541 Dallas,
504 Washington _ all all-time high for a Cowboys game. After Week
1, the Cowboys are 27th in the league in total defense, and the
Redskins are 30th.
\Nsubheds:Ground control
</P>
<P>
   In Emmitt Smith and Chris Warren, the Cowboys have the No. 1 and
No. 5 leading active rushers in the NFL. Smith has 12,675 career
yards; Warren has 7,055.
\Nsubheds:Third and long
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys defensive end Greg Ellis was criticized last season for
getting only three sacks in 16 games. After getting two in the
season opener against the Redskins, he's on pace for 32 in 1999.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
