<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS HOPE VIKINGS BLUEPRINT STOPS FALCONS' ANDERSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys will attempt to contain Jamal
Anderson on Monday night by duplicating the Minnesota Vikings'
success of stacking eight-man fronts and using more than arms to
make tackles.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys did little of either Sunday against the Washington
Redskins, allowing unheralded running back Stephen Davis to rumble
for 109 yards, more than doubling Anderson's 50-yard output on 16
carries in the Atlanta Falcons' season-opening loss to Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   What was supposed to be a younger, quicker Cowboys defense was
pushed around for three quarters by Davis and quarterback Brad
Johnson, and wound up yielding 504 total yards. Now, the test comes
from a Super Bowl team that boasted the league's second-best rusher
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You better be a good, solid tackler because he can run through
the arm tackle,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said. ``The man is a
big man who can run the football, and he's hard to tackle. He can
make you look bad in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's style is based on spotting a crease in the defense
and attacking it. He uses his muscular, 234-pound physique to
punish would-be-tacklers by dropping a shoulder or stiff-arming
defenders. He often resembles a larger Emmitt Smith, churning out
yards with quick bursts up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   In his second year as a full-time starter, Anderson carried the
Falcons to the Super Bowl last season, rushing for 1,846 yards and
14 touchdowns on an NFL-record 410 attempts. When he carried the
football 20 times or more last season, including the playoffs, the
Falcons went 15-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings limited him to 16 carries, mainly by forging a
17-point lead that forced the Falcons to pass, but also via a
dominating performance by the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used a lot of eight-man fronts to try to stop the run and
force the pass,'' Cowboys defensive coordinator Dave Campo said of
the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys must get improved play from ends Greg Ellis and
Kavika Pittman, and tackles Chad Hennings and Alonzo Spellman. The
foursome applied little pressure to Johnson, giving him time to
pass for 382 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do a good job with the front seven,'' Campo said.
``We didn't tackle very well last week. He's the kind of guy that
can get into a crease and make your secondary get involved as well.
''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
