<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SYDNEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR AUSTRALIA, THE CLOCK IS COUNTING DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN SHAW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ In exactly one year, the largest event in
the history of sports will get under way here in Sydney, where
billions of dollars, national pride and international prestige will
all be at stake at the 2000 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney Olympics, from Sept. 15 through Oct. 1 next year,
will include a record number of sports (28), events (292), sessions
(635) and athletes (10,200). And Stadium Australia, site of the
opening and closing ceremonies and the track and field events, is
also the largest arena in the history of the Olympics, holding
110,000 spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the size of these Games _ and the controversy that
has accompanied them here and the Olympic movement in general _ the
Sydney organizers say they are prepared but not overconfident as
the year counts down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not scared, but we're running scared,'' said Sandy
Hollway, chief executive of the Sydney Organizing Committee for the
Olympic Games. ``There's a strong sense of urgency and not a shred
of complacency.''
</P>
<P>
   All outward indications back him up. In August, Stadium
Australia, located in Homebush Bay, 10 miles west of downtown
Sydney, staged a rugby match attended by 107,042, most of whom got
there by train or bus with minimal delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``That test went smoothly, but I told my people that we'll have
to do that twice a day for eight straight days of track and
field,'' said Jim Brown, who managed Stanford University stadium
during its six World Cup games in 1994 and the baseball stadium in
Atlanta in the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Still, transport planners were recently told to upgrade the
services between the athletes' village and venues.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney organizers are trying to avoid the problems that
befell the Atlanta Games, during which transportation and
technology breakdowns were constant headaches for athletes,
spectators and media alike.
</P>
<P>
   Hollway, 53, an affable and unflappable former diplomat, has
studied Atlanta's difficulties _ and achievements _ and hired key
managers, including Americans like Brown, to apply in Sydney
lessons learned in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Donovan, 32, who was a technical manager in Atlanta and is
senior competitions executive here, said that Sydney is now a year
or more in advance of Atlanta's readiness at this stage.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that Atlanta failed to fully test the computerized
distribution of scores and times. Sydney plans to test that
process, for media and spectators, on Super Sunday, a Sept. 26 test
in which live or simulated results from 21 sites will
simultaneously pour into an information control center.
</P>
<P>
   Test events at national and international levels in 10 Olympic
sports _ and a range of meetings for Olympic back office players,
are also being held here this month as Olympics planners shift
gears up from talks to tryouts.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Super September program involves 10 sports and
competitors from over 50 nations in order to simulate Olympic
conditions. The sports involved are archery, badminton,
canoe/kayak, equestrian, field hockey, handball, pentathlon,
rowing, sailing and water polo. Their sites range from Sydney
Harbor in the city center to a whitewater course in suburban
Penrith, 25 miles west.
</P>
<P>
   Hollway marked the end of the five-year planning stage and the
start of a year of operational testing for the Games by installing
two large clocks to remind his 1,000 staffers how time is running
out.
</P>
<P>
   One clock marks weeks remaining before the opening ceremony. The
other shows how long before the Olympic torch begins its
20,000-mile circuit of Australia, a 100-day, 100,000-runner relay
across the deserts, rain forests, sheep ranches and suburbs of this
island continent of 19 million people.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, one clock will indicate 52 weeks, the other 38
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, we've really got 14 weeks less than a year to go,''
Hollway said as he sat in his modest office, located in a former
newspaper building in a drab side street near Sydney's main
railroad station.
</P>
<P>
   A few issues still need to be settled.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the scandal surrounding the International Olympic
Committee members accused of selling their votes to bid cities, the
Sydney organizing committee has a sponsorship shortfall of about
$65 million. IOC vice president Dick Pound , apologized to Sydney
Games sponsors here Tuesday for negative publicity surrounding the
bribery scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Atlanta's corporate-style, privately-funded organizing
group, the Sydney group is a public body, controlled by the New
South Wales government. Sydney is the state capital. Michael
Knight, a senior politician of the state's ruling Labor Party, is
minister for Olympics, drawing on a $3 billion mix of public
infrastructure funds, private investment in major venues, corporate
sponsorship and ticket and television revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Some 5 million Games tickets, with a total value of $225
million, are on public sale in Australia and about 3 million
available overseas. Prices range from $1,000 for the opening
ceremony to $300 for a front seat at track finals to a $6 pass to
the rowing heats.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the IOC scandal, the Sydney organizers had to
settle a few local issues. Despite neighborhood protests, the beach
volleyball competition will take place at Bondi Beach, a suburban
surf beach. And after Australians said that too many Americans and
Japanese were in the 2,000-member marching band participating in
the opening ceremonies, the committee has decided to form a more
international unit, using musicians from 20 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Some minor complaints surfaced this week. Some news media
officials complained about the quality and cost of accommodation at
the $65 million media village, and Dr. Rick Charlesworth, coach of
Australia's Olympic gold medal women's field hockey team, said the
surface of the new field is not smooth enough.
</P>
<P>
   But one major controversy was solved Tuesday. The IOC announced
that it and the International Amateur Athletic Federation had
solved their differences over the starting times of leading track
events.
</P>
<P>
   While the IAAF had wanted from 10 to 13 changes in six days of
the track schedule, IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch approved
just two. Speaking from Lausanne, Switzerland, Knight said Tuesday
that the final of the women's 5,000 meters and 10,000 meters would
be rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC receives 40 percent of Olympic television royalties _
some 1,600 television cameras will be in use _ and divides them
between international sports federations.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney officials had always been willing to consider some
timetable changes, but not for the women's 400-meter final, planned
for Sept. 25, 2000. This is the hottest Games ticket for
Australians because Cathy Freeman, the current world champion, is
the favorite for the sprint and Australia's best chance for a track
medal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
