r s BC-RODEO-CALF-ROPING-TEX     09-14 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODEO-CALF-ROPING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVISTS AND SOME RODEO FANS DECRY CALF ROPING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When dyed-in-the-leather cowboy Neal Gay watches calf roping, he
sometimes cringes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what they say about an animal's durability; when
they jerk a calf down, it has to hurt,'' said Gay, producer of the
Mesquite Championship Rodeo] the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Gay, however, includes calf roping on his weekly card. After
all, calf roping and saddle-bronc riding are the two original
events of organized rodeo and are among the five mandatory events
in Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association shows.
</P>
<P>
   But the event appalls animal-rights activists and even some
rodeo fans, especially when they see animals stopped in their
tracks and yanked by their necks through the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to seeing calf roping, and it doesn't really bother
me,'' said Garland resident Eddie Hill, a rodeo fan. ``But I've
taken people to the Mesquite Rodeo from Japan, and they are upset
with calf roping.''
</P>
<P>
   Said animal-rights activist Linda Yarbrough of Fort Worth:
``Calf roping is extremely disturbing. In this day and age, it's
abuse of animals. It's pretty black and white.''
</P>
<P>
   No statistics are kept on the number of injuries to calves, but
rodeo officials have been cognizant of criticism. In the past few
years, they've implemented several safety measures, including rules
forcing the use of smaller calves _ less jerking is required to
stop and tie them _ and giving judges the power to disqualify
contestants for jerking calves too hard.
</P>
<P>
   Rodeo officials also say what looks dangerous isn't for a calf,
comparing a calf's protection _ its hide and muscular structure _
to that of a football player wearing pads. Roping and tying a calf
can be compared to a running back being tackled and then popping up
and hustling back to the huddle, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a more urbanized society where people have very
little understanding of how sturdy calves really are,'' said Cindy
Schonholtz, the PRCA's animal-welfare coordinator. ``Instead of
always being on the defensive, we've worked really hard to educate
people and to help all rodeo associations come under compliance
with safety measures.'' SMALLER IS BETTER? Probably the biggest
change in calf roping is the use of smaller animals. The smaller
calves, which weigh 220 to 280 pounds, are about 70 pounds lighter
on average than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rodeo cowboys point out that smaller calves require smoother
handling for fast times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to beat champions like Fred Whitfield and
Cody Ohl if you jerk your calf down and then have to take the time
for it to get back up,'' said Mack Altizer, who supplies livestock
for PRCA shows in Texas and the National Finals.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnny Emmons gained the first of his two National Finals
Rodeos calf-roping berths a decade ago, he earned many paychecks by
jerking a calf down before making the tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calves were bigger then, and I wanted to make sure that it was
on the ground to keep it from running around,'' said Emmons, a
Grandview resident who qualified for the National Finals in 1989
and 1998. ``But if I did that now, I wouldn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, ropers have devised a method called ``switching.'' After
lassoing the calf, ropers tighten the slack on the rope enough to
keep the animal on its feet; when the calf hits the end of the
rope, it turns around and faces the roper.
</P>
<P>
   And if calves are jerked down,, they can be disqualified. In the
past five years, PRCA judges have been allowed to disqualify a
contestant and levy a $100 fine for jerking a calf down; judges
have handed out 228 fines, but have disqualified only five
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I see a guy flank a calf in a way that I think is too
rough, I call him for unnecessary roughness, and he'll
automatically be disqualified and have to pay a fine,'' PRCA rodeo
judge Tommy Keith said. ``And you bet I'll call it. There's not too
many guys willing to risk that with thousands of dollars at
stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock contractors say they are also making stronger efforts to
purchase calves that are physically sound, Altizer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are coaching a soccer team, you're going to go after a
player that can run the length of the field,'' he said. ``We're not
going to buy calves that are short-legged with pot bellies; they
would stand more of a chance of injury. Today, we view the calves
as athletes, and we are more selective and give them better diets,
just like race horses and bucking horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodeo operators also have been encouraged to have smoother arena
surfaces so calves are less likely to suffer leg injuries by
digging in and locking their feet while being roped. CRUEL AT
HEART? None of the precautions are enough to convince Tammy Hawley,
executive director of the Humane Society of North Texas, that rodeo
needs calf roping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen stock contractors take better care of their animals
than children, and I'm aware that rodeo personnel have done a lot
to make calf roping safer for animals,'' Hawley said. ``But I'm
saddened by the fact that I see rodeo fans enjoying watching
animals being put in uncomfortable situations. When you see calves
roped and tied, you can see the fear in their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Calf roping would not be sorely missed in Fort Worth if the
rodeo could be a PRCA-sanctioned show without the event, said Bob
Watt, the Stock Show's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we took out calf roping, only a small percentage of our
fans would be upset, and it wouldn't affect ticket sales that
much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Stock Show assistant general manager Trey Watt said
it is a challenge to sell calf roping to many fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have 300 clean calf-roping runs at our show, but all
that it takes is only one calf being jerked down, which causes a
fan to become upset,'' Trey Watt said. ``If one person calls and
says that they're upset, we've got a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always treated livestock well over the years at the
Stock Show, but within the last 10 years we've had to show proof
that were not abusing animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changing people's perception about calf roping is our big
challenge.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
