<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-LINEBACKERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINEBACKER SHUFFLE NOT A GAMBLE FOR TEXAS A&AMP;M
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ There's always room for another good
linebacker at Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   To create space for a player who might be the latest find, the
Aggies have moved their best linebacker to the position he played
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Say hello to redshirt freshman Brian Gamble, a name that could
become increasingly familiar beginning Saturday when the
seventh-ranked Aggies (1-0) play their home opener against Tulsa
(1-1).
</P>
<P>
   Based on review of the defensive tapes from the 37-17
season-opening victory over Louisiana Tech, A&AMP;M coaches have moved
Cornelius Anthony back to the weakside slot to open the door on the
strong side for Gamble. Gamble played most of the game against the
Ragin' Cajuns in the ``dime'' defensive package and made nine
tackles (six unassisted, two for losses) and recovered a fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony moved to the strong side during two-a-days to fill the
void left by Dat Nguyen, last season's Lombardi Award winner who
plays for the Dallas Cowboys. Coach R.C. Slocum said he doesn't
believe moving Anthony back is _ well _ a gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian is challenging for a starting position,'' Slocum said
yesterday. ``We're really pleased with him. He made some athletic
plays in the \Rlast\S ball game. But that didn't really surprise
me. We felt he'd be a good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble's first-game performance might have nudged that timetable
a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out thinking that Gamble needed more playing time,''
Slocum said. ``We couldn't do that without reducing Cornelius' time
_ and we're not going to do that because he's the best we've got.
Cornelius played weak\Rside\S last year, so it made more sense move
him back over there and leave Gamble where he was.''
</P>
<P>
   This apparently is not an experiment. Asked if he anticipated
moving Anthony back, Slocum replied, ``not any time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble, 6-foot-2, 225 pounds, is from Class 2A Alto in East
Texas. He's a former high school quarterback-linebacker who wanted
to play linebacker in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was recruited at both positions,'' Gamble said. ``But I
wanted to play linebacker, so where else was there to go? A&AMP;M had
the great \Rlinebacking\S tradition and I knew Dat was still going
to be there and I could learn from him. Everything was in my
favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble seems to have picked up Nguyen's aggressive style of play
and his sense of fun. He showed up for an interview yesterday
wearing a teammate's glasses \R''It makes me look educated,''\S and
a cheerleading T-shirt \R''for the irony of it.''\S
</P>
<P>
   But Gamble is not just a kid out on a lark, Anthony said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a young kid who is really good and who really knows the
game of football,'' Anthony said. ``I see a bright future for him.
He did a tremendous job against Louisiana Tech. For a guy to come
off a redshirt year and play like he has _ I'm sure we'll see a lot
more of him.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Briefly Reserve linebacker Chris Thierry is in a
Baytown hospital after undergoing a surgical procedure to
investigate a suspected kidney ailment. ... R.C. Slocum said
fullback D'Andre Hardeman is questionable this week after suffering
an ankle sprain against Louisiana Tech. He did not practice last
week.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
