<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BLOOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENJAMIN BLOOM, 86, A PIONEER OF HEAD START 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Pa.)   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Benjamin S. Bloom, whose path-breaking 1964 research showing
the profound impact of early childhood experience on adult ability
helped lead to the creation of the Head Start program, died Sept.
13 . He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom died at his home in Chicago, said William Harms, a
spokesman for the University of Chicago, where Bloom was professor
emeritus of education.
</P>
<P>
   In the most influential of his 17 books, ``Stability and Change
in Human Characteristics'' (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, 1964), Bloom said
that many physical and mental characteristics of adults could be
predicted through testing while the subjects were still children.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he found that 50 percent of the variations in
intelligence at the age of 17 could be estimated at the age of 4.
He also found that early experiences in the home shaped learning
ability.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom's findings focused the attention of many educators and
psychologists on the importance of early education and the home
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He provided the intellectual and empirical basis for Head
Start,'' said Lorin Anderson, a professor of education at the
University of South Carolina and a former student of Bloom. ``His
timing was impeccable. He had the ability to see beyond where we
are to where the next issue will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloom's discussions of his research with President Lyndon B.
Johnson and his testimony before Congress played a big part in the
1965 establishment of Head Start. The early education and
pre-school program provides education, health, nutrition and other
services to low-income children and their families.
</P>
<P>
   The program became an important part of Johnson's Great Society,
and has enjoyed bipartisan congressional support since then.
</P>
<P>
   Among Bloom's other books, ``Taxonomy of Educational
Objectives'' (David McKay &AMP; Co., 1956), which sets forth a
hierarchy of learning beginning with factual knowledge and leading
through comprehension, application, analysis, synthesis and
evaluation, is still in use today by education scholars in more
than 50 languages.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom also advanced a theory called ``mastery learning,'' the
idea that all students are capable of learning if material is
presented to them in a logical, systematic way.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Samuel Bloom was born on Feb. 21, 1913, in Lansford,
Pa. He received a bachelor's degree from Pennsylvania State
University in 1935 and a master's degree from Penn State, also in
1935. He received a Ph.D. from the University of Chicago in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom joined the Chicago faculty in 1944. He also served as
president of the American Educational Research Association.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom is survived by his wife, Sophie, of Chicago; two sons,
David and Jonathan, both of Chicago; and a brother, George, of Jim
Thorpe, Pa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
