<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-LETT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' LETT SUSPENDED FOR EIGHT GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to second chances, few players get more than
Dallas Cowboys defensive tackle Leon Lett.
</P>
<P>
   Lett failed a drug test for the fifth time during the off season
and could have been suspended for the entire season. (Some Dallas
executives say he should have been.) Instead, the National Football
League announced Tuesday that Lett would be suspended for eight
games.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Cowboys have already played one game, Lett is eligible
to return Nov. 14 against the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed, but I'm glad we have a definitive time we
can expect him back,'' said Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said at a
news conference. ``We're disappointed we don't have him now.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Lett has been suspended since June 4. The NFL
felt that since Lett had fulfilled most of his aftercare
responsibilities, he deserved another opportunity to play. The NFL
also believed that Lett is a good person who is trying to better
himself and can eventually be a productive member of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Lett's suspension is sure to draw criticism from other teams.
Even before the announcement, when it was revealed that Lett had
failed a drug test for the fifth time, several team executives said
that if he was not suspended for the entire season then the drug
program would be a travesty.
</P>
<P>
   There is precedent for the league's ruling, however. The former
Dallas player Clayton Holmes was also a five-time offender of the
drug policy and, like Lett, was suspended for less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said Lett would be suspended for a
year if he fails another drug test.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that does not appease some teams, who ask privately what
it would take for a player to be suspended for an entire season.
</P>
<P>
   Lett has missed playing time because of drug problems in four of
his past five seasons. He missed four games in 1995 after testing
positive for marijuana, and the last three games of 1996 and the
first 13 of 1997 for testing positive for cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   When Lett is playing, he can be one of the most dominant linemen
in the game. His play has declined slightly, but when Lett is in
the game, the Cowboys are an imposing defense against the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not have dependency or addiction,'' Jones said.
``That's not to say they're not issues, but those are not two of
them. That is a meaningful part of why I want him on the team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-99 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
