<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WTO STRUGGLES TO DISEPL MYTHS ABOUT WHAT IT DOES, HOW IT WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RON REDMOND  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ To those who accuse it of everything from spawning El
Nino to being a tool of ruthless multinational corporations bent on
globalization, the World Trade Organization has a ready reply:
Don't blame us, blame your government.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the threat of massive demonstrations at the Nov. 30-Dec.
3 ministerial conference in Seattle, WTO officials in Geneva are
struggling to dispel what they consider numerous fallacies about
the controversial world body.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 5,000 guests from the WTO's 135 member states
expected to attend, the Seattle event will be the largest trade
meeting ever held in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It is also expected to draw an army of public-interest groups
with a multitude of concerns ranging from saving rain forests to
AIDS activism to militant anti-capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   WTO officials believe many of these groups have little or no
understanding of how the organization actually works.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some very strange perceptions out there about the
WTO,'' said David Hartridge, director of the Geneva-based
organization's Trade in Services Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that people have a grossly inflated idea of the
power and influence of the WTO.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps foremost among the misperceptions, according to several
trade officials interviewed in Geneva, is the notion that the WTO
is trying to control world trade by dictating policy to
governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WTO is basically a negotiating forum to help facilitate
the settlement of trade disputes,'' Hartridge said. ``The WTO
itself does not regulate trade. We don't issue licenses or regulate
tariffs. The WTO itself does not take a decision on anything; the
member governments do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartridge and his colleagues said the WTO's staff of more than
500 people, most of them translators and support personnel, simply
provide a neutral secretariat to serve member governments.
</P>
<P>
   And they say complaints about a lack of openness and access to
the decision-making process should be directed at the member
governments, not at the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make an easy target,'' acknowledged Jorge Vigano, counselor
for the WTO's Trade and Environment Division. ``But the decisions
are taken by governments.''
</P>
<P>
   That argument doesn't quite wash with critics like Mike Dolan,
deputy director of Public Citizen's Global Trade Watch, an offshoot
of Ralph Nader's Washington, D.C.-based consumer group. While
recognizing the WTO's function as a legislative forum for
governments, Dolan said the organization also has a direct judicial
role in resolving trade disputes through its Dispute Settlement
Body. The body issues rulings by adopting the findings of a panel
of experts or an appeal report.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, our demands and complaints are not directed at the
WTO functionaries in Geneva, but at the 135 member governments,''
said Dolan, who is helping to organize the so-called ``mobilization
against globalization'' in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a bit disingenuous for the WTO to ignore its judicial
function. They refer to their legislative function, but they also
have a judiciary role that is extremely untransparent and extremely
undemocratic.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, WTO officials acknowledge, the organization is going
to serve as a lightning rod for all kinds of complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been blamed for everything from El Nino to acting as a
tool of powerful multinational corporations,'' said a Geneva-based
trade official who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   He said violent protests in the normally placid streets of
Geneva during the last ministerial conference in May 1998
underscored the public-relations challenge faced by the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Geneva protests, including the overturning of the Jamaican
ambassador's car, was an eye-opener for a lot of us,'' the official
said. ``The passion in the streets was based on ignorance and was
totally misdirected, but it illustrated the need for us to inform
and educate the general public as to what the WTO really does.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous groups, known as non-governmental organizations, or
NGOs, have sought a place at the WTO negotiating table in Seattle,
a demand that has so far been rejected by member states. Dolan said
``the deck is stacked against civil society,'' which may get a seat
``near the table, but not at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, the Seattle conference will provide ``an
opportunity for a historic confrontation'' that will reveal the
``slavish devotion'' of political elites to the ``corporate
agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the kind of talk that makes people in Geneva nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Although Geneva trade officials are ``much impressed'' with
preparations by the Seattle Host Committee, the threat of
disruption remains a very real fear, Hartridge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are worried about the huge presence of NGOs,'' he
said. ``You've got the right wing on one end of the spectrum, then
in the middle are trade unions and environmentalists, then the left
wing. It's impossible to address a single audience because there's
such a large spectrum. It's easy to meet with some of them and
discuss issues with some of them, but you can't provide a sort of
all-inclusive discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though donor governments won't allow them into the
negotiating room, a lot of NGOs are consulted closely by their
respective governments in advance of ministerial meetings, he
added. In a bid to make NGOs feel involved, the WTO secretariat
regularly meets with them and has organized conferences on specific
trade-related issues. In March, for example, about 900
organizations attended a Geneva symposium on trade and the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   But Vigano agreed there is little chance NGOs will be involved
in the decision-making process in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt if any government representative would want NGOs
participating in the official ministerial,'' Vigano said. ``It
would be very difficult. There are those NGOs who work with us and
those who say no to everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartridge dismissed those critics who say the WTO does more harm
than good. ``To say that the WTO is harmful is literally to say
that the world would be better off without a multilateral set of
rules on trade,'' he said. ``It's manifest nonsense. Nobody could
seriously defend that position.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can perfectly well say that some of the individual
rules should be revised. That's OK; that's what rules are for.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Rockwell, the U.S. director of the WTO's Information and
Media Relations Division, said he welcomes the public scrutiny.
``Our main concern is that there not be violence,'' he said. ``But
peaceful protest? I think every American believes it's their right
to express their point of view. In fact, it's a right and a duty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
