<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2413 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-REFUGEES-1STLD-     09-14 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-REFUGEES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1,300 REFUGEES FROM EAST TIMOR FLOWN TO SAFETY IN AUSTRALIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs number of refugees in head and lede)  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARWIN, Australia _ Haunted and huddling, more than 1,300 East
Timorese refugees arrived here Tuesday on military evacuation
planes after the United Nations abandoned its compound to the
militias who had laid siege to it after East Timor voted for
independence.
</P>
<P>
   For two weeks the refugees, many of them women and infants,
cowered behind the walls of the compound as the militias fired
shots over the courtyard and attacked anybody who dared to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conditions were not tenable,'' said Ian Martin, the head of
the mission, who left with refugees on the first flight Tuesday
morning. ``It's crucial there is an international force as soon as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Mission to East Timor left a skeleton staff of 15
people in the territory's capital city, Dili. But they moved from
the compound to more secure quarters at the Australian Consulate.
</P>
<P>
   President B.J. Habibie of Indonesia let the refugees be
evacuated from the compound, along with 45 U.N. staff members.
Officials here said the convoy of refugees was protected by
Indonesian soldiers on the way to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Several reports from Dili said that hours after the last refugee
had left, a pillar of smoke could be seen rising from the compound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It simply is further proof that the militias are still active
in East Timor and are destroying every last remaining building,''
said David Wimhurst, a spokesman for the U.N. mission.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the arriving refugees were closely guarded by the
Australian police and military officials after they landed.
Reporters were kept far away from the East Timorese as they were
put on buses and driven to an encampment of olive-drab tents near
the airport of this dusty outpost on Australia's northern coast,
less than 400 miles from East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Buses could be seen carrying elderly men and young mothers to
the tents. Many of the women were holding babies on their laps.
</P>
<P>
   In the generally bleak atmosphere, there was a bright note. A
woman went into labor as the plane landed and was taken to a
hospital to give birth.
</P>
<P>
   The newborn joined an 8-day-old boy who was born in the compound
on the day of a particularly fierce militia assault. The boy's
parents named him Pedro Unamet Rodrigues, his middle name a nod to
the acronym for the U.N. Mission in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Even as this last group of refugees made its way to safety,
fears were growing for the more than 100,000 East Timorese who had
fled or had been forcibly removed to neighboring West Timor in the
last week. The United Nations said there were unconfirmed reports
of militias attacking pro-independence refugees in camps in two
West Timorese cities, Kupang and Atambua.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to several camps in Kupang on Sunday suggested that the
settlements are largely under the grip of the militias.
</P>
<P>
   While refugees were landing at Darwin's airport, the city's port
was alive with activity as warships from Australia, New Zealand and
the United States bobbed in the harbor or took on supplies at the
wharf.
</P>
<P>
   An officer of the Navy cruiser Mobile Bay declined to comment on
whether his ship was headed to East Timor. He said it was here on
training exercises with the Australian Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of the U.N. talks, Darwin is a city in a
high state of readiness. Witnesses watched trucks and other heavy
vehicles being loaded onto an Australian transport ship Tuesday
morning. And hundreds of Australian and foreign journalists have
descended on this city of 85,000, frantically trying to book
passage on a military ship or plane to East Timor.
</P>
</TEXT>
